<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-EVALUATION-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SELF-EVALUATION, GIULIANI FINDS PLENTY TO CROW ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Continuing one of his favorite traditions, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani produced a stack of charts Thursday that suggested
the city is ever safer, its streets ever cleaner and its citizens
ever healthier under his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In a self-evaluation known as the Mayor's Management Report,
which the City Charter requires to be published every six months,
Giuliani and his administration found that almost every city agency
improved its delivery of services in the last fiscal year, which
ended June 30. In particular, 85 percent of streets were rated as
clean, the number of people who died in fires had dropped
significantly and the infant mortality rate was the lowest since
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find bad news in the report, which is prepared by
Giuliani's staff and has become more upbeat every year since he
took office in 1994. But there was some: police response time to
crimes in progress increased to an average of 9.8 minutes from 9.2,
and the number of children on waiting lists for day care programs
increased to 14,145, from 11,674.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that reported incidents of child abuse and
complaints against police officers had increased, and that the city
had not repaired potholes promptly. But Giuliani did not dwell on
such problems, focusing instead on the drops in crime, traffic
fatalities and the number of people receiving welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this all adds up to is a massive change in the way people
feel about New York City,'' he said, speaking to reporters and
dozens of city employees who came to City Hall for the
presentation. ``All of these things show what most New Yorkers
believe when you poll them, but that people who want to be
consistent critics refuse to accept. Which is that the city of New
York has improved.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked to point out areas of concern in his report,
the mayor declined to mention anything specific. ``There are always
situations in which we could respond better, respond more
quickly,'' Giuliani said. ``The purpose of statistical analysis is
to motivate people to improve as much as possible. But there's not
an area of city government that should feel satisfied that we're
doing the best we can.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The twice-yearly report has traditionally focused on both the
city's accomplishments and problem areas where agencies need to
improve. But under Giuliani, the reports have been increasingly
glowing, with problem areas mentioned only in a separate volume.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the only problems that Giuliani mentioned during
Thursday's presentation was something over which he has minimal
control: the rising cost of auto insurance premiums for city
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Critics noted that the report did not include the total number
of traffic accidents last year, the number of lead poisoning cases
or plans for improving problem areas, like police response time to
crimes in progress. The report would be more balanced if it were
written by an independent agency, said Ludovic Blain, the city
legislative advocate for the New York Public Interest Research
Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``These reports are more and more effective campaign commercials
and ineffective management tools,'' Blain said. ``The mayor uses
them as cheerleading pompoms for his brand of public policy. It
makes people wonder what is being left out.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Council, which has been critical of Giuliani's
management reports in the past, sent out a news release mentioning
several areas of concern, like the day care waiting list and a drop
in the number of window guard inspections. But the tone of the
release was generally positive. Speaker Peter Vallone, a Democrat
who is running for governor, made a point of saying that the
Council was partly responsible for the many improvements listed in
the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that the city is steadily growing safer and that
city government is becoming more fiscally responsible with each
passing year,'' he said in a statement. ``We should all be proud of
what we have accomplished in New York City thus far in securing a
bright and stable future.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was jubilant in his presentation of statistics on
crime, welfare benefits and city responses to medical emergencies,
calling the improvements ``astounding,'' ``tremendous'' and
``remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   But his most chest-pounding moment came with the unveiling of a
new set of statistics: the number of wins by the Yankees and the
Mets, both of which have increased since the baseball-fixated mayor
took office. ``This comes from having the most dedicated and
knowledgeable baseball fan as mayor,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
