<SLUG> BC-EDIT-UN-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TOO LONG TO WAIT AT THE U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, 18 September:
</P>
<P>
   Charges of mixing official and private business have held up
President Clinton's nomination of Richard Holbrooke to be the chief
U.S. representative at the United Nations. That would be a serious
offense, but the merit of the charges has yet to be established.
Formal State and Justice department investigations are now under
way.
</P>
<P>
   These inquiries guarantee a delay of at least four months in
filling the U.N. post. That is too long to leave issues like Iraq,
Libya and the Balkans in the hands of a deputy without cabinet
weight. The administration must quickly name a senior diplomatic or
political figure to fill the job temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations are that in 1996 Holbrooke, then an investment
banker working simultaneously as an executive of the Swiss banking
concern Credit Suisse and as Clinton's envoy on Bosnia and Cyprus,
improperly used his contacts with U.S. diplomatic officials to do
work for the bank. Under federal conflict-of-interest laws,
Holbrooke, as a recent State Department employee, would have been
legally barred from any business contacts with his former
diplomatic associates.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has also raised questions by failing to disclose until
now a gift of free lodging in Washington from M. Larry Lawrence,
the former U.S Ambassador to Switzerland, who was later buried in
Arlington National Cemetery and then exhumed when his right to be
interred there was challenged. Holbrooke supported the waiver that
allowed Lawrence, a non-veteran, to be buried at Arlington.
Holbrooke's defenders say that he kept his Credit Suisse business
and his diplomatic work strictly separate and that his dealings
with Lawrence were entirely correct.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who brokered the Dayton peace agreements on Bosnia,
is experienced and sophisticated enough to know that any blurring
of lines between public and private business is unacceptable. This
page applauded his selection for the U.N. job and we hope it turns
out that his conduct was as careful as he says it was.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Burleigh, the acting representative, has been doing a
decent job since Bill Richardson left for the Energy Department.
But the U.N. post is America's second most important diplomatic
position after the secretary of state. It should be filled by a
weightier figure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
