<HEADER>
A1868 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-LANG-COX     09-18 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-LANG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lang's mix of `beautiful,' `interesting' a winner
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now that Helmut Lang's proved he can make the whole
world of high fashion bow to his demands, it's only fitting that
he's designed a collection for spring/summer '99 that's ideally
suited for his supplicant subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, silk and leather jeans with ridged knee padding made the
most declarative statement in the edgy, innovative assortment of
clothes for men and women that Lang presented Thursday in a
stiflingly hot downtown warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The jeans _ reminiscent of the racing pants high-speed
motorcyclists wear to protect their knees while making hairpin
turns _ were a stark departure from all the frilly, feminine styles
shown repeatedly this week by other designers. And the collection _
which also featured knee-length blazers, tightly tailored slacks
and fuzzy cotton suit separates _ solidifies his reputation as a
designer blessed with enough new ideas of his own to never feel
compelled to mimic others.
</P>
<P>
   Lang, a reclusive man of few words who commonly turns down
requests for his own photograph, has said this collection was
``about being beautiful and interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Any discernible flaws in the clothes he showed derived from the
fact that some of his pieces could be described only as
``beautiful'' or ``interesting'' but not both.
</P>
<P>
   The jeans _ in white, black or a tarnished shade of silver
leather _ were an intriguing alternative to all the Capri pants
derivations his counterparts have shown. But they didn't look
particularly comfortable or attractive on his models.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of his navy and black tailored jackets lay in their
utter lack of detail; their extended length looked rather novel,
but Lang's ``less is better'' attitude toward padding and
embellishment is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   The shimmering, shaggy texture of some of Lang's trim-fitting
skirts, camisoles and jackets was a sight to behold, but these
pieces aren't of the type one gets much wear out of ... and where's
the beauty in that?
</P>
<P>
   To further distinguish himself from all the designers who will
ring in next spring with a flourish of colors and an abundance of
vivid floral prints, Lang stuck to the usual neutrals (white,
black, tan, cream and gray), used hot pink as his only accent shade
and cloaked his muted floral skirts and dresses under layers of
panel-sewn sheers.
</P>
<P>
   And as if that weren't enough, Lang bucked the trend toward
designing ``must have'' handbags by accessorizing his outfits with
side holsters, zip-pocketed elbow pads, shoulder strap packs and
money belts.
</P>
<P>
   The applause for Lang's show was so fervent that he reluctantly
stepped out from his position backstage to give a quick nod of
acknowledgement to the adoring crowd. He's expected to show his
collection for fall/winter '99 around Feb. 14. If so, he'll no
doubt cause a rash of dinner date cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
