<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
RANGERS WIN HARD WAY AFTER hELLING DIGS HOLE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Winning the ``hard'' way has become a way of
survival for the Rangers. As defined back in July by Johnny Oates,
that means overcoming poor work from a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, it wasn't just any starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   After having spent most of this season in a witness protection
program, it had finally become safe for the Rangers' rotation to
mingle once again in public. Even the use of real names was
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Although other malfunctions kept the team in a frustrating flux
over the last month, it was the rotation that allowed a divisional
race to continue. Well, that and the fact the Anaheim Angels had
problems of their own.
</P>
<P>
   A ``quality start'' in baseball is defined as at least six
innings while giving up three earned runs or fewer. The rotation
had reached that level in 13 of the past 17 games going into, yes,
the season's most critical encounter to date last night.
</P>
<P>
   Needed this win badly. Needed Rick Helling to be better than
even ever, which was asking a lot, considering how consistently
good Helling has been. From his April role as fifth man in the
rotation, the right-hander had earned his way to ace status. And
this was a battlefield promotion, too.
</P>
<P>
   With first place at stake, Helling was the logical choice to
nail down the American League West lead. After all, he was most
responsible for preventing the Rangers' staff from falling off
baseball's planet.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, however, it was Helling who took that tumble last
night. A 19-game winner looking for No. 20, his outing resembled a
pitcher who had never won more than five games in a season. Which
until this year, was Helling's story.
</P>
<P>
   The plate must have looked as far away as Fargo, Helling's North
Dakota hometown. The bases looked as busy as midtown Manhattan
streets. Of the 12 batters Helling faced, nine reached and six
scored. Oates usually can't get enough of Helling. By the second
inning, he couldn't stomach any more.
</P>
<P>
   What's that Oates has repeatedly said for weeks, going on
months? Something about, ``if we can just hold 'em to four, maybe
five runs, we'll probably score six.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, six wouldn't win it, not after Helling's
rare poor outing.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with no other option, Oates had to begin an early bullpen
parade while also depending upon the Rangers' No. 1 ally _
ballistic bats. But here's a manager who has had plenty of practice
at trying to survive rotation failure. It has been a major part of
Oates' 1998 life.
</P>
<P>
   And it worked again, with plenty of help from the dark side of
the Rangers' bullpen, meaning long and middle men.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin's eighth-inning run-scoring single capped a
remarkable evening for the Rangers, who won, 7-6, and rolled back
into first place for the first time since Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Ten games to go in the season, and the lead is one over the
Angels with three meetings still to go in Anaheim. But a two-game
swing in the division in two Arlington nights put the Rangers at
the wheel for the flag lap.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim, of course, wanted no part of an offensive shootout.
Against the Rangers, no one does. But since there was no knuckle to
Angels starter Steve Sparks, Anaheim's quick 4-0 lead was gone by
the bottom of the first. And then a 6-4 lead also disappeared on
solo homers by Todd Zeile and Juan Gonzalez, the latter tying the
score in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed that way until Goodwin's hero hit in the eighth. But
also give credit here to Oates. For a man with possible job
security problems if the Rangers don't finish first, Oates went
with percentages instead of panic in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   After a leadoff single by Lee Stevens, Zeile came to the plate.
The temptation was to have him swinging for the big inning, except
Oates stuck to basic baseball. The bunt sign was flashed, and Zeile
laid down a beautiful sacrifice, moving pinch runner Milt Cuyler to
second. That meant, however, Oates had put the game in the hands of
either Royce Clayton or Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton was drilled by a pitch, leaving it up to Goodwin. He
delivered, and Oates looked smart.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said for the manager using the quick hook on
Helling in the second inning. It was questionable to turn a game
over to his bullpen that early, down 6-4. But 21/3 shutout innings
from Al Levine, then a masterful four shutout innings by Tim
Crabtree put the Rangers in a position to eventually win.
</P>
<P>
   Right moves by the manager, and baseball's best offense rescued
another ``hard way'' win. And this time with first place at stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
