<SLUG> BC-FREEMEN-LAWSUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEMEN FOLLOWER SUES GOVERNMENT FOR $300 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN MAESHIRO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANCASTER, Calif. -- The self-described disciple of an
anti-government group is now turning to the government to seek $300
million in damages for what she claims was her wrongful conviction
in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In a civil rights lawsuit filed in Lancaster, Margaret Elizabeth
Broderick and her husband say a search of their home in nearby
Palmdale was improper, that the FBI and other federal agencies have
no authority there, and that the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department and county officials should have protected them from
federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court, where she was sentenced in March 1997
to 16 years in prison for convictions on 26 counts including
conspiracy, fraud and money laundering had no right to try her,
according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to, during and subsequent to this `trial,' (she)
maintained the position that the United States District Court did
not and does not have jurisdiction over the offenses allegedly
committed by her,'' the suit stated.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick was accused of creating bogus checks and staging
seminars to tell people how they could use the forgeries to pay off
debts.
</P>
<P>
   She described herself as a follower of LeRoy Schweitzer, a
leader of the anti-government Freemen group jailed last year in
Montana. The self-styled Freemen say they reject almost all
government authority and insist they have their own laws and
courts.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed Sept. 10 by Broderick's husband, Richard,
in Lancaster Superior Court. He is now serving time in a Texas
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants are Attorney General Janet Reno, U.S. Attorney
Nora Manella, the Internal Revenue Service, Los Angeles County
District Attorney Gil Garcetti, former Lancaster Deputy District
Attorney John Spillane, Sheriff Sherman Block, county supervisors
and various members of the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to respond directly to a lawsuit we have not
seen yet. It is my understanding she has filed several other civil
rights lawsuits in federal court, all of which were summarily
dismissed,'' said Thom Mrozek, a spokesman for the U.S. Attorney's
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Since her incarceration in April 1996, Broderick's health has
been jeopardized because of ``horrendous, subhuman medical
facilities and treatment,'' the lawsuit stated.
</P>
<P>
   The filing said she has been denied access to proper and
necessary medication and was ``forced to consume unnecessary and
mind-numbing/duping medication such as Prozac.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said federal agents ``stormed'' the couple's
Palmdale home March 25, 1996, to conduct a search.
</P>
<P>
   The agents entered the house with weapons, including firearms
and axes, drawn. They then ``began to indiscriminately and
aimlessly search and ransack'' the home, holding Richard Broderick
at gunpoint during the search, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Because the federal court has no jurisdiction over her,
Broderick's conviction should be overturned and the ``sentence
extinguished,'' the suit stated.
</P>
<P>
   Lancaster is about 55 miles north of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
