<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RODRIGUEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK SPASMS FORCE RANGERS' RODRIGUEZ OUT OF GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ All-Star catcher Ivan Rodriguez had to leave
last night's game in the fifth inning with muscle spasms in his
lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez felt the spasms on one particular pitch, an inside
fastball from Tim Crabtree that he had to reach for while Anaheim
Angels hitter Phil Nevin danced out of the way. Rodriguez
immediately left the field and was replaced by reserve catcher Bill
Haselman.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's status is listed as day-to-day, but the Rangers are
hopeful he'll be in the lineup tonight against the Oakland
Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he'll be ready to play tomorrow,'' manager Johnny
Oates said after the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are also concerned about shortstop Royce Clayton,
who was hit in the shoulder in the eighth inning on a pitch from
Angels reliever Rich Delucia.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton stayed in the game for the ninth inning but was feeling
sore afterward. He has started 43 of 44 games since being acquired
from the St. Louis Cardinals on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more worried about Clayton than I am about Pudge,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has started a league-leading 129 games at catcher, and
the Rangers are 11-12 this year in games started by Haselman.
Haselman is hitting .301 but has thrown out just five of 29 base
runners trying to steal off him, including one of the past 18.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, a six-time Gold Glove winner, threw out Jim Edmonds
trying to steal in the first inning and has thrown out 40 of 74
attempting to steal this year. The 54 percent success rate is the
best in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez and Haselman are the only full-time catchers with the
Rangers even though the rosters have been expanded to a maximum of
40 players. The Rangers thought about putting Triple-A catcher Rick
Wrona on the roster for September but instead gave that spot to
pinch-running specialist Milt Cuyler.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers plan to have Triple-A catcher Chris Tremie at the
ballpark tonight. If Rodriguez can't play, Tremie will be placed on
the roster as a backup for Haselman.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile was once a catcher but hasn't gone
behind the plate since 1990. Reserve infielder Scott Sheldon could
catch in an emergency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-WILDCARD-NYT &LR;      09-18 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WILDCARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ANYBODY'S RACE AS METS AND CUBS BATTLE DOWN THE HOMESTRETCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy had to contend with Sammy Sosa the past four days,
but the San Diego Padres manager had to admit that the New York
Mets had his attention, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Mets are doing has to create a lot of interest
there,'' Bochy said Thursday before the Chicago Cubs and Sosa could
plague his National League West champion team one last time.
``We're checking for the scores. The comebacks and the extra
innings _ that was one heck of a series with the Astros. I'm sure
it doesn't get any better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Bochy had something in common this week but no
longer. Bochy doesn't have to deal with Sosa anymore; the Mets have
Sosa to contend with for perhaps the next eight games.
</P>
<P>
   That's how many games both teams have in their duel-to-the-death
race for the National League wild-card spot. Sosa has carried the
Cubs in their quest, epitomizing his role by driving in all six
runs, the last four with his 63d home run, in a 6-3 victory over
the Padres on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, for once, did not power the Cubs on Thursday, but they
nevertheless edged the Padres, 4-3, and increased their lead over
the Mets, who were idle, to one game.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mark McGwire's, the Mets' fortunes could fall or rise with
each Sosa swing. But they have not let themselves be intimidated by
his most valuable player performance. They have staged their own
spine-tingling, heart-stopping style of play, spreading around
their game-winning heroics among players like Mike Piazza, John
Olerud, Brian McRae, Edgardo Alfonzo, Tony Phillips and Todd
Hundley. In their modest way, the Mets have matched Sosa as their
teams have been no further than a game apart since Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have remained in contention to join the Yankees in the
post-season for the first time, a fact that only heightens the
drama surrounding the next 10 days. The Mets have eclipsed the
Yankees in interest, though perhaps only temporarily, because the
Yankees have had a losing record the past month while the Mets have
played exciting baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Mets can join the Yankees in the post-season, they
have to shed Sosa and his supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incredible what he's doing,'' Bochy said by telephone
from San Diego. ``Just like the Mets. This is quite a race here.
Two teams playing great ball, playing with a lot of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has had this kind of effect on the Mets. After they pulled
out yet another come-from-behind victory in Houston on Wednesday
night, John Franco was in the shower when noise from the locker
area of the clubhouse caught his attention. Rushing out of the
shower, the pitcher yelled, ``Who hit that? Who hit that?'' Told
that Sosa had hit a grand slam, Franco hung his head, turned around
and retreated to the shower.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have surely had a similar effect on the Cubs with their
late-inning dramatics. In nine of their last 20 games, dating from
Aug. 28, the Mets have hit home runs in the seventh, eighth or
ninth innings that either won or tied the game or put them ahead.
Four of the games were against the Astros, and two of the home runs
were hit against Billy Wagner, the Astros' closer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Cubs, the Mets have put themselves in position to
reach the playoffs with a versatility that has served them well.
The series in Houston that enthralled Bochy was a microcosm of the
Mets' season.
</P>
<P>
   The first game belonged to McRae. First, he hit a two-run home
run against Wagner in the ninth inning that tied the game, then
drilled a two-run, tie-breaking double in the 13th.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga tied the second game with a two-run home run in the
eighth inning, then combined with Rey Ordonez for consecutive
doubles in the 11th, putting the Mets ahead, albeit temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud socked a three-run home run in the eighth inning of the
third game that gave the Mets a lead they did not relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for the piece de resistance, Piazza cracked a three-run
home run in the ninth inning of the fourth game against Wagner,
putting the Mets in the lead. The Astros tied the game with a home
run of their own, but Hundley won it with a pinch-hit home run in
the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier late-inning comebacks, Alfonzo, Piazza and
Phillips hit pivotal home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets clearly have not warranted inclusion with the division
champions, Atlanta, Houston and San Diego. They do not have the
overall talent those teams have. But they have held firm in the
wild-card race by playing relentlessly, never conceding anything to
the better teams.
</P>
<P>
   Entering this month, the Mets faced a pair of games in San
Diego, four at home and three on the road against Atlanta and four
in Houston. Those were 13 of their final 24 games. With the
season-ending series in Atlanta left, the Mets have a 7-3 record in
those games, splitting two games with the Padres and snatching
three one-run victories from the Braves before outlasting the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have not played as intensely and as dramatically
against weaker teams, evenly dividing six games with Philadelphia
and Montreal. They play the league's weakest team, the Florida
Marlins, three times this weekend and then have two games against
Montreal at Shea Stadium before finishing the season in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   While the hitters have dominated the recent stretch with their
breathtaking hits, one unheralded member of the pitching staff has
begun to exemplify the excitement the Mets have brought to Shea
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell, a 31-year-old right-hander, had been an
underachieving relief pitcher throughout his career, but he has
recently evoked memories of a more successful reliever in Mets
history, Tug McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrative Wendell was effective and indefatigable in
Houston, pitching two shutout innings in the first game, one and
two-thirds shutout innings in the second, two shutout innings in
the third for a save and one shutout inning in the fourth for
another save. He threw 97 pitches, a remarkable number for a relief
pitcher over four consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   When McGraw completed a victory, he hopped off the mound yelling
and slapping his glove against his thigh. When Wendell completed
the last two victories in Houston, he leaped off the mound
screaming and thrusting his arms in the air. He brought back scenes
that the Mets would like to see continued next month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
