<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MOVE INTO FIRST IN AL WEST WITH 7-6 VICTORY AGAINST ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Ten days separate the Rangers from an
American League West title.
</P>
<P>
   It became theirs to lose on an evening in which their players
refused to lose. The Rangers regained possession of first place for
the first time since Aug. 13 with their exhilarating, 7-6 victory
against the Anaheim Angels last night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Tom Goodwin supplied the Rangers their first and
only lead with his one-out, eighth-inning double off right-hander
Rich DeLucia.
</P>
<P>
   That scored Milt Cuyler from second base with what proved to be
the game-winning run, but the Rangers' bullpen made this victory
possible with 72/3 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Tim Crabtree, who threw 46 pitches, surrendered
only one walk during his career-high, four-inning appearance, and
closer John Wetteland recorded his 41st save by retiring the side
in order during the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some high moments, but this was awesome,'' said
Crabtree, who urged those in attendance to their feet after
recording the final outs of the seventh and eighth innings. ``It
was a great night all the way around. We were down four runs and
battled back. The crowd was in the game. It was outstanding. You
can't ask for more from a major-league game than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Lee Stevens opened the bottom of the eighth
inning with a leadoff single off right-hander Pep Harris (3-1), and
manager Johnny Oates summoned Cuyler from the bench as a pinch
runner.
</P>
<P>
   Cuyler advanced to second on the ensuing sacrifice bunt by third
baseman Todd Zeile, and Angels manager Terry Collins went to the
bullpen for right-hander Rich DeLucia.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton reached first after being hit by a
pitch, and that brought Goodwin to the plate for the decisive
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was big, but we still have to come out and focus on
Oakland,'' Goodwin said. ``Obviously, it's good to come in here and
win two games and get into first place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers overcame:
</P>
<P>
   Six runs surrendered by right-hander Rick Helling during a
11/3-inning catastrophe that represented the shortest start of his
career since a one-inning appearance May 11, 1994, against the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   A gaffe on the bases by Goodwin that cost the Rangers one run
and perhaps more by robbing catcher Ivan Rodriguez of a
second-inning at-bat with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Angels center fielder Jim Edmonds, who cannot be described as
Helling-friendly, concluded the pitcher's brief evening and bid to
become the major leagues' first 20-game winner with his two-run,
second-inning home run.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds, whose eight hits in 17 at-bats against Helling include
four home runs, also delivered home the first of the Angels' four
first-inning runs with a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, responded with a four-run first inning of
their own on the strength of a two-run double by left fielder Rusty
Greer and run-scoring singles by first baseman Will Clark and
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Angels right-hander Steve Sparks, who relies on a knuckleball,
did not fare significantly better than Helling and found himself
replaced by right-hander Shigetoshi Hasegawa after recording only
five outs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers eventually tied the score with third- and
fourth-inning solo home runs by third baseman Todd Zeile and right
fielder Juan Gonzalez, respectively, and the contest became a
battle between the bullpens.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Al Levine pitched 21/3 scoreless innings, and
left-hander Greg Cadaret also retired one batter during a
near-perfect evening for the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two nights are big wins playing the team we really
need to play well against,'' Clark said. ``Those are two big wins
this time of the year, but we can't let down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
