<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-VANDAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY HOME TARGET OF FIRECRACKER VANDALISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN and BETH BARRETT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Police stepped up patrols of Monica Lewinsky's
family home in Brentwood after someone pushed a firecracker through
the mail slot, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said there have been mailbox attacks elsewhere in
that neighborhood recently, but neighbors believe Thursday's act
was fallout from the Lewinsky-Clinton affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's all kinds of crazy people out here. It's very sad that
people do those kinds of things. I think they should be left
alone,'' said Terry Klein, who lives a few doors away from the home
of Beverly Hills oncologist Bernard Lewinsky and Barbara Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was injured by the firecracker, which was discovered
Thursday on the wood floor of the living room after the Lewinskys
returned home. Police said it was placed Wednesday in a mail slot
on the front of the home in the 12200 block of Darlington Avenue,
said LAPD Sgt. Willie Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   The firecracker slightly damaged the living-room floor and left
debris. Barbara Lewinsky made the discovery about 9:30 a.m.
Thursday and called police.
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD's bomb squad and detectives from the Criminal
Conspiracy Section responded to the home but determined the
incident appeared to be ``a random act of vandalism,'' Guerrero
said. The incident remains under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinskys immediately altered the metal box so it could only
be opened with a key.
</P>
<P>
   The attack focused unwanted attention from police, TV
helicopters and more than a dozen reporters on the otherwise quiet
street, as nannies strolled babies and homeowners walked their
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents decried the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that it's unfortunate for them to go targeting
the family. It's her father's house,'' said Flora Tangen, 23, of
Brentwood.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including neighbors, said they understand the public's
display of anger over the fallout from Lewinsky's affair with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often wonder how my teen-age children will look back on
their youth, with the Monica Lewinsky scandal and the Simpson
murder case,'' said Sylvia Godwin, noting that Nicole Brown Simpson
and Ronald Goldman were slain just blocks from the Lewinsky home.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the whereabouts of Lewinsky, a former White House
intern, was uncertain Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Told about the firecracker incident, David Wolpe, the rabbi at
Sinai Temple in Los Angeles, which the Lewinsky family attends,
said the topic raises powerful passions in people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex, power, the desire to know the secrets of the rich and
powerful'' are all a part of the equation, Wolpe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all would be a great morality drama, a great lesson for the
nation's soul, if it wasn't so tragic,'' he added. ``But it's
heartbreaking, it's too sad -- there is an overwhelming weight of
real grief about it.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
