<HEADER>
A1908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-WOODWARD-     09-18 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-WOODWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD STAKES HAS A SMALL, BUT POWER-PACKED, FIELD
</HEADLINE>
   (bl) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Sonny Hine got the word Thursday that his Skip
Away had been made the favorite to win the Woodward Stakes at
Belmont Park on Saturday and repeated his old theme with new
emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are finally coming to understand that Skip Away is one
of the greatest horses of all time,'' said Hine, who trains the
5-year-old. ``All I tell people to do is to look at Skip Away's
record. He's never had a break. He's raced in every important race
there is, and he has always run his heart out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like him to win back-to-back Breeders' Cups, go to the
farm as the top money-earner and go with everybody knowing that he
is one of the greatest horses of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away was made the favorite in ``the race of the year'' when
only five horses were entered in the Woodward _ four superstars and
one invader from Europe. That horse is Running Stag, who drew the
rail and was absolutely the long shot at 30-1 odds. But the mighty
four, starting from the No. 2 post position, were Skip Away at 6-5,
Gentlemen at 7-2, Free House at 9-5 and Coronado's Quest at 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away has won eight races in a row, won the Breeders' Cup
Classic last year when Hine risked the supplemental fee of $480,000
to enter him, now has earned a career total of $9.2 million and
needs to win just $793,456 more to pass the record total banked by
Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   On the down side: this will be Skip Away's seventh stakes race
of the year; he was forced to make a last-ditch rally to win the
Iselin Handicap by a nose at Monmouth Park last month and he has
been treated lately for sore feet and he must outrun three of the
best horses in America to keep his streak alive.
</P>
<P>
   The horse with the strongest chance of unseating Skip Away is
Free House, one of the heroes of last year's grinding Triple Crown
series and the freshest competitor in the Woodward. He is a tall,
gray powerhouse from California who built a remarkable record at 3
and has started and won twice at 4. His last race was on Aug. 15,
when he won the Pacific Classic at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   Free House made his bones as a fighter last year when he won the
Santa Anita Derby over Silver Charm, ran third in the Kentucky
Derby behind Silver Charm and Captain Bodgit, ran second in the
Preakness to Silver Charm and ran third in the Belmont behind Touch
Gold and Silver Charm. Then he won the Swaps Stakes, ran third in
the Haskell and sixth in the Super Derby _ and was finished for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   It took nine months to mend Free House's campaign wounds, which
included bleeding and the early signs of a stress fracture in a
foreleg. But he spent much of that time at the California farm of
his breeders and owners, Trudy McCaffery and John Toffan, and in
the watchful care of his trainer, Paco Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in this race because we want to see where we are with
this horse,'' Gonzalez said. ``He has had two good races, but now
he is going to face the very best.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, McCaffery and Toffan would face the same decision that
Sonny Hine faced last year: It would cost them $800,000 to run Free
House in the Breeders' Cup because neither he nor his sire was
registered when he was foaled. ``The Woodward,'' Paco Gonzalez
said, ``is our Breeders' Cup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
