<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-BIZ-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS BUSINESS COLUMN: WHAT IS YANKS' VALUE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Alfred Lerner bought the Cleveland Browns for
$530 million last week, it was a record price for a sports team. A
day later, Rupert Murdoch trumped Lerner by agreeing to pay $1
billion for the Manchester United soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is renewed speculation that Cablevision Systems wants
to acquire the New York Yankees, resurrecting talks that faded
early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Yankees worth more than the Browns or Manchester United
_ even if Hideki Irabu and Andy Pettitte are in pitching slumps?
</P>
<P>
   ``The likely price is close to, at or beyond $1 billion,'' said
Neal Pilson, a sports industry consultant, citing the likelihood
that Cablevision might as well pay $1 billion to buy the team if it
has to spend the same amount to keep the Yankees' television rights
on the MSG Network after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between $500 million and $600 million,'' said Marc Ganis, a
sports finance expert with SportsCorp, who tempered his price tag
because major league baseball lacks a cap on player salaries and
because the Yankees have uncertainty about a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lack two things the Browns, a National Football
League expansion team, have: the guarantee of $70 million a year in
national television money, about five times what baseball teams
reap, and a new stadium with 116 luxury suites that will be a
money-printing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the likelihood that the state and city will finance the
bulk of the cost of a new stadium or a fixed-up Yankee Stadium,
filled with scrumptious, revenue-enhancing features, must play into
the team's future value.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision's continued interest amply displays the intense
focus by media and entertainment companies on sports. Media outfits
such as Time Warner, News Corp., Walt Disney Co. and Comcast are
ravenous for sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of the Yankees to a buyer with media synergy, like
Cablevision, is greater than one without,'' said Paul Much, a
managing director of the Chicago investment banking firm Houlihan
Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin.
</P>
<P>
   And while there have been past offers to buy the Yankees, the
most serious have come from two media companies, Cablevision and
Paramount Communications, which owned Madison Square Garden, now
owned by Cablevision.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning bid for Manchester United by Murdoch's B Sky B
satellite network may look as outlandish as the $1.58 billion he
paid for National Football League television rights for the Fox
Network in 1993. But that investment proved crucial to Fox's
viability. Murdoch owns the satellite television rights to Premier
League soccer games in England. By owning the league's most
profitable team, he has a seat at the table to renegotiate with
himself on future television deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He paid a 50 percent premium on the Manchester United stock
price,'' Much said, ``but he does that to fulfill his master
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   That plan is to use sports to drive his television empire.
Murdoch did not pay $311 million for the Los Angeles Dodgers last
March because he loves the hit-and-run or W.P. Kinsella novels. He
acquired the team to secure the perpetual cable rights on Fox
Sports West, his regional sports channel in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the value of sports as an infinitely renewable resource,
with a new script every day,'' Pilson said. `` `Seinfeld' and `ER'
will wear out. The Yankees never will. In 50 years, it will still
be a storied franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   How much leverage Cablevision chairman Charles Dolan can exert
on George Steinbrenner to sell is questionable. Steinbrenner has
repeatedly said he has no desire to sell. He has loved owning the
Yankees in good times and bad times; he undoubtedly loves it even
more with a first-place, playoff-bound team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision may appear to be the only bidder for the Yankees'
cable rights because it owns the two local regional sports
channels, Fox Sports New York and MSG, which vied for the deal that
MSG won in 1988. Then Cablevision bought the Garden and competition
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dolan can't push George too far,'' Pilson said. ``It wouldn't
take much for George to to go Time Warner or Disney to launch a
regional sports channel with the Yankees. That's the tightrope
Chuck Dolan has to navigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Although an extraordinary bid by Cablevision could tempt
Steinbrenner to sell, why shouldn't he play to Cablevision's
buyer's ardor by selling the company a minority stake that could
painlessly help finance a new stadium?
</P>
<P>
   A new stadium would push the Yankees' value higher, perhaps by
as much as the size of Cablevision's investment. Then, who knows?
Sell the public stock in the team. What fan wouldn't want a piece
of the Yankees? That's the philosophy behind teams like the Boston
Celtics and Cleveland Indians going public.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they sold shares to the public, then you might see a
billion-dollar value of the team,'' Ganis said. ``The Yankees have
a lot of vanity value.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
