<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SHUT OUT DEVIL RAYS, 4-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ A handful of players checked on Joe Torre
in his office on Thursday afternoon, under supposedly innocent
pretenses. Tino Martinez dropped off some cigars, Derek Jeter
grinned his funny grin and called his manager Mr. Torre, and Paul
O'Neill stopped to say hi.
</P>
<P>
   Torre presumed they all made conversation to gauge his mood the
day after he blistered the Yankees in a team meeting for their
recent effort. If any feelings of disgust lingered in the manager,
however, they were chased away by a sharp, 4-0 shutout of Tampa
Bay. Hideki Irabu had to pitch well to keep alive his chances of
being part of the playoff roster, and he did so, allowing two
infield hits in eight innings. The Yankees are 105-46.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played tonight like we're used to playing,''Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   All the regulars were back in the lineup, and the Yankees had
runners on base in every inning, collecting 16 hits. Jorge Posada
slugged a two-run home run in the sixth inning, his 17th homer of
the year, and Bernie Williams banged his 26th home run in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu set the tone _ or, if you will, he reset the tone _
for a team that had lost 16 of its last 28 games coming into
Thursday night's game. Irabu had lost his last four decisions,
allowing 30 runs in 201/3 innings dating to Aug. 15; another poor
outing would have probably meant he would be watching the playoffs
from the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, however, Irabu was able to use mechanical adjustments
that he had successfully implemented in the bullpen. He wanted more
leg drive, to pitch on an aggressive downward plane, and he had
that. He wanted a better breaking ball, and he had that. He wanted
to throw with confidence, and he attacked the Tampa Bay hitters all
evening with fastballs, inside and outside, 90 to 93 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   When Irabu was at his worst earlier this month, Posada said, he
pitched at the same elevation, his fastball, split-fingered
fastball and curveball all crossing the plate thigh high, making it
easy for hitters to look for pitches in one area. On Thursday
night, he went up and down in the strike zone, like an elevator
operator. ``I knew I was doing badly,'' Irabu said, through
interpreter George Rose, ``and I wanted to get better as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's only two hits were flukes. Aaron Ledesma hit a slow
roller to the left side of the infield in the second inning; third
baseman Scott Brosius charged and tried bare-handing the ball and
throwing in one motion, but he couldn't get a grip. The next
inning, Randy Winn bunted to the third-base side, and Brosius
charged again; his former manager, Art Howe, says Brosius makes
this play better than anyone in baseball. But the ball bounced out
of Brosius's hand. Two do-or-die plays, two infield hits. ``We
didn't hit many balls hard,'' said Larry Rothschild, the Tampa Bay
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``He maintained his velocity the whole game and he
got his curveball over. He had the best command he's had all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu struck out five and walked two, his confidence growing
from inning to inning, in the mind of pitching coach Mel
Stottlemyre. When Irabu struggles, he can be restless on the bench
in between innings, his dissatisfaction apparent in his body
language. But on Thursday night, Stottlemyre said, Irabu rested
quietly between innings; only once did Stottlemyre need to call
Rose to discuss a pitching adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel I needed to be confident,'' Irabu said. ``If I
don't have confidence, I'm not going to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won't make up their playoff roster until next week,
and if the votes were tabulated today, Irabu would probably still
not be in the rotation and might not even be part of the 25-man
roster. But he will pitch at least once more during the regular
season and, with another strong outing, could create a dilemma for
Torre and Stottlemyre. If Irabu is pitching well, he can dominate
anybody, and right now, Andy Pettitte is having trouble against
everybody; on the other hand, Irabu has no playoff experience, and
Torre will always remember Pettitte's 1-0 victory in the 1996 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which ever we use him,'' Torre said, referring to Irabu, ``an
outing like tonight's will only help him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stottlemyre: ``We want them to make it tough for us to
decide. We want to see it again in his next start.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada has been a direct and honest pundit on the subject of
Irabu the whole year, praising him when he was throwing well early,
criticizing him when he floundered. Posada began to get a good
feeling about Irabu last Friday, after Toronto's Roger Clemens
drilled Scott Brosius with a fastball. Irabu immediately answered,
beanball for beanball, bouncing a fastball off the first batter he
faced the next inning. ``He showed me a lot there,'' Posada said.
``He showed me a lot of heart and poise.''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu has got to show it again, if he wants to wear pinstripes
in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0040EDT &QL; 
