<SLUG> BC-GLF-SOLHEIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS TURN UP HEAT IN QUEST FOR SOLHEIM CUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ Talking about the pressure of the Solheim Cup,
which begins Friday morning, Laura Davies admitted she was nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes it fun,'' said Davies, the long hitter from
England who will be a key member of the European team. ``You're
scared of losing the point for your team and scared of messing up.
That's the thing that gets you going. That fear inspires you to
play better.''
</P>
<P>
   The nerves, the anticipation and the heated competition are part
of what has made the Solheim Cup one of the most anticipated events
in women's golf. It takes place every two years, and this year's
match between the United States and Europe has all the ingredients
to be memorable.
</P>
<P>
   While the United States has won three of the four Solheim Cups,
including a 17-11 victory in 1996, this weekend's match is
difficult to call. Pia Nilsson, Europe's captain, said this is the
best European team ever assembled, featuring Annika Sorenstam,
perhaps the world's top female player, and with strong support from
Liselotte Neumann and Davies.
</P>
<P>
   With Europe posing a serious threat, the intensity between the
two teams has grown, just as the men's Ryder Cup became more
intense during the 1980s, when Europe began to field teams that
were capable of beating the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the rivalry is getting worse and worse each and every
event,'' Catrin Nilsmark of Sweden said. ``It's fantastic. I want
this to be a good cup, to raise women's golf to higher levels.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will be hard for Europe to win unless Sorenstam plays
well. Look for Nilsson to rely heavily on Sorenstam, Davies and
Neumann, who all played the maximum five matches in 1996. By
contrast, Kelly Robbins was the only United States team member who
played five matches in '96. With more depth on her team, the
American captain, Judy Rankin, may have the luxury of keeping her
players fresher for Sunday's singles matches, where the outcome
will be decided.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam sounded ready for the challenge of playing five
matches in three days at the Muirfield Village course. The first
two days consist of four alternate-shot matches in the morning and
four best-ball matches in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to give this team as many points as I can,'' said
Sorenstam, who has a 4-1-2 Solheim Cup record. ``I know I'm
probably going to play all five matches, which gives me an
opportunity to collect a lot of points.''
</P>
<P>
   Other subplots will make this competition interesting. Charlotta
Sorenstam, Annika's sister, qualified for Europe's team for the
first time this year, but the Sorenstams have a frigid relationship
and Nilsson is expected to avoid pairing them.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson left herself open to criticism by selecting Swedes with
four of her five captain's picks. Six of Europe's 12 players are
from Sweden, but Europe's players said the team was not divided
between Swedish and non-Swedish factions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has got the same shirt that says Europe on it,''
Charlotta Sorenstam said. ``We're a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rankin has her concerns as well. Tammie Green, a key player for
the United States, is expecting a baby Dec. 23. Rankin has said
that Green will not play two matches in the same day, but after
Thursday's practice round, Green said she felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a physical golf course and I do notice my feet hurting
a little bit at the end of 18,'' said Green, whose doctor will be
in the gallery. ``Other than that, I'm striking the ball well and
everything seems like it's all natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's morning matches may set the tone for the weekend. If
either team loses three or four matches in the morning, the
pressure will build immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson made a potentially risky decision, pairing Davies with
Trish Johnson on Friday morning, because Johnson has been bothered
by a neck injury. But after watching her Thursday, Nilsson decided
Johnson was ready.
</P>
<P>
   The 24 players sense that their sport is on an upswing, and a
close match with a dramatic finish would only add to that momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're on that peak,'' Rosie Jones of the United
States said. ``It just feels like there is a lot more energy. I was
at the first Solheim in '90, and there has already been more people
than there were at that one. So we've come a long way baby.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
