<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NEVADA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON PESSIMISTIC AS LICENSE HEARING LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Like a politician who is trailing in a campaign a
few days before an election, Mike Tyson made a public appearance at
a luncheon to honor Nevada Gov. Robert Miller and Dr. Elias Ghanem,
the chairman of the Nevada State Athletic Commission, at Caesars
Palace on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson will appear before the commission Saturday in a public
hearing on his application for the reinstatement of his boxing
license. All the members except Luther Mack were present at the
luncheon. But while Tyson shook hands with the commissioners and
took pictures and signed autographs for fans, he was not optimistic
about his chances to regain his license.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very encouraged,'' Tyson said when asked whether he
thought he would be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson refused to discuss the matter in depth. Two commissioners,
Dr. James Nave and Glen Carano, also refused to discuss it. Nave
said he ``never gave it a thought'' that Tyson appeared at the
luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Nave also said he would question Tyson extensively about an Aug.
31 incident in Gaithersburg, Md., in which two men said Tyson
assaulted them after a minor traffic accident. Tyson has been
charged with two counts of misdemeanor assault, and Nave said the
commission hearing will be very lengthy.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's license was revoked on July 9, 1997, after he bit
Evander Holyfield on both ears during a heavyweight championship
fight in Las Vegas on June 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Finkel, Tyson's adviser, said Tyson did not assault the
two men, aged 50 and 62, after the accident. And the misdemeanor
charges, Finkel said, should have no bearing on the ex-heavyweight
champion's chances of getting his license back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, it's my understanding that you're innocent until
you're proven guilty,'' Finkel said. ``If that was a factor for
some reason for Mike not getting licensed, then you would be
prejudging him as guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Finkel said Tyson will be represented at the hearing by his two
California lawyers _ John Branca and Dale Kisella _ who are
handling his lawsuits against the promoter Don King and his
co-managers, Rory Holloway and John Horne. Finkel also said Tyson
will not use as many character witnesses as he did in New Jersey,
where he first sought reinstatement before withdrawing his
application. Finkel said Tyson was having financial difficulties,
because he has not been able to fight in a year. Finkel estimated
that Tyson has lost between $25 million and $50 million since the
revocation.
</P>
<P>
   In August the Internal Revenue Service placed a $6.3 million
lien against Tyson's 61-room mansion in Farmington, Conn. The
mansion has been for sale for $22 million for more than a year.
Tyson bought it for $2.7 million in 1996. Local realtors estimate
it is worth $4.3 million.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1925 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-3RDL     09-18 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL WRANGLES OVER RELEASE OF VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to recast and rewrite first 5 grafs)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-CONGRESS-SLEAZE,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-ASSESS, CLINTON-EDITORIALS, CLINTON-BOSTON,
CLINTON-RELEASE, CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-MINISTER,
CLINTON-CONGRESS-TV) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Abandoning any pretense of bipartisanship, the
House Judiciary Committee spent Thursday wrangling over whether to
release immediately a videotape of President Clinton's grand jury
testimony in the Monica Lewinsky case and discussing how to edit
reams of pages delivered by the Whitewater independent counsel
Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The panel adjourned late Thursday without taking a vote on
releasing the tape, which put off the anticipated disclosure of the
president's testimony on Friday. Now, on Friday, the panel is
expected to approve making the videotape public. The tape could be
released as early as Saturday, once aides copy and prepare
documents for distribution.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the president's deposition in the Paula Jones
case in January, in which his testimony about Ms. Lewinsky has
become the foundation for Starr's central charges of perjury, may
also be released. The judge in the Jones case granted an unusual
request made this week by the chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., to release that videotape.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong committee meeting was mired in feuding, as
Republicans aggressively pursued procedures that would unseal
mounds of documents that support the impeachment report by the
independent counsel. In a series of 11 votes, Democrats on the
panel pushed unsuccessfully for a delay in releasing both the
videotape and the 2,000-page appendix of information attached to
Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that they should take the time to review all the
materials before releasing any portion, noting that they still have
until Sept. 28 to meet the deadline set by the House to complete a
review of the material. In some cases, they argued that deletions
should be made so that graphic material would never be released.
The Democrats expressed grave concern at the meeting about making
the information public piecemeal and without deletions, calling the
strategy politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, issued a statement
Thursday in which he said he had demanded that Starr destroy the
videotape of Clinton's grand jury testimony. Its continued
existence, he said, ``was to insure its public release and
embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   In a seething response Thursday night, Starr said the
independent counsel's office considered the videotaped testimony to
be ``evidence of a crime.'' The prosecutor is contending that
Clinton lied to the grand jury as well as in his Jones deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape does not cast Clinton in a flattering light,
depicting him as occasionally impatient, and quibbling in his
discussion of his affair with Ms. Lewinsky. Democrats said an
edited transcript of the testimony would have sufficed.
</P>
<P>
   One official familiar with the material and the proceedings said
the videotape showed Clinton repeatedly relying on legalisms and a
narrow definition of sexual relations. He also refused to answer a
series of more prying questions about the sexual nature of the
affair, the official said. Surprisingly, many of the toughest
questions were asked by grand jurors and not prosecutors, the
person added.
</P>
<P>
   While much attention has focused on disputes over the
president's videotaped testimony, the panel spent much of the day
arguing about the supporting documents that Starr sent to Congress
to bolster his case that the president's actions may be cause for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The panel agreed on more than 100 separate edits of the report's
2,000- page appendix, which includes background information, maps
of the West Wing, a table of Ms. Lewinsky's White House visits and
a table of the contacts between the two of them. It also contains
lengthy footnotes and legal references.
</P>
<P>
   The protracted debates mainly involved squabbles over eight
passages containing the most sexually explosive material, officials
familiar with the proceedings said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In their first meeting since Starr delivered his report to
Congress on Sept. 9, the panel's Republicans and Democrats bickered
about the merits of releasing the videotape and zeroed in on the
most sensitive sexual material. They debated, among other things,
the relevance of mentioning sexual props. Both sides said they took
decency into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee aides have spent days poring over documents
in boxes delivered by Starr but Thursday's debate centered only on
the contents of one box, indicating that the process will be long
and slow. They have yet to take up the issue of whether to release
the transcripts of testimony given by Ms. Lewinsky and other
central figures, including Clinton's secretary, Betty Currie, his
friend Vernon Jordan Jr. and Secret Service officers.
</P>
<P>
   In a debate that boomeranged between civility and partisanship,
members accused each other of political motives and questioned each
other's sincerity in pursuing the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to let the public join in the decision making
process,'' said Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., a committee member,
who argued that the committee is searching for a balance between
privacy and decency concerns and the public's right to know. ``The
very fact today is balance. It must be presented in a balanced
fashion so the American people can make their own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson's argument was echoed throughout the day by other
Republicans on the panel, who argued that the public should make
its own determination based on the same evidence handed to
Congress. And they accused Democrats of putting Clinton's concerns
ahead of the country's. The president's testimony, they said, is
vital to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats insisted, as they have all week, that hasty disclosure
of the materials is a strategy that will humiliate Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Republicans are trying to do is get the bad stuff out
about the president, as much as they can, as fast as they can,''
said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., a panel member. Frank added,
``They're frustrated that the president's official standing is as
high as it is, and they're trying to tear it down.''
</P>
<P>
   But some members said the party-line friction in the panel was
predictable. Last week, 11 of the Democrats on the panel voted
against a House-passed resolution to release Starr's report and
many of its accompanying documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe some Democrats would like to thwart the procedures
established under the resolution,'' said Rep. Charles Canady,
R-Fla., a member of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the partisan battle threatened to intensify, the
panel's ranking Democrat, Rep. John Conyers Jr. of Michigan, filed
a letter of protest Thursday with Hyde, over the chairman's request
for the Jones tape without consulting Democrats. ``I have serious
concerns regarding the propriety of your seeking the release of a
videotaped deposition in a private civil case that has now been
dismissed,'' Conyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's meeting also came at a time of ill will between the
parties over an online magazine's disclosure that Hyde had
conducted an extramarital affair 30 years ago. Calling this
disclosure and a few others a smear campaign of intimidation,
Republican leaders blamed the president's allies and asked that the
FBI to look into it. The White House has denied any involvement.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans and Democrats continued to face divisions
within their own ranks about release of the material.
</P>
<P>
   An opening salvo in the Judiciary Committee meeting came when
Democrats asked that the gathering be held in public and not under
the cloak of secrecy. The motion was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have decided that the appropriate way to fight for
openness is in total secrecy,'' Frank said during one of the
committee's sporadic breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats complained that they had not had enough time to
sift through the material and the proposed redactions.
</P>
<P>
   But in an attempt to deflect charges of partisanship, Hyde
allowed members to speak on and on at the debate. After the
meeting, the chairman said: ``There's been lot's of debate. It's
been productive debate, not frivolous debate.'' He added, ``It gets
passionate at times, interesting at times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
