<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN HURT BUT ROOKIES IMPRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There was no shortage of news at Spaulding Field
on Thursday as the Bruins zipped through a light workout in
preparation for Saturday's game at Houston.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 tailback Keith Brown did not practice (turf toe) and will
be evaluated this morning. If he can't play, senior walk-on Mark
Reynosa will travel. And with or without Brown, true freshman
DeShaun Foster will play second string, behind starter Jermaine
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Brown couldn't run (Thursday), it's likely DeShaun will be
the backup,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile two rookie defenders, nose guard Ken Kocher and
linebacker Robert Thomas, continue to impress despite injuries.
Kocher is recovering from a sprained ankle; Thomas has a broken
right hand that requires a cumbersome cast.
</P>
<P>
   Both are expected to play significantly this weekend (``They're
improving every day,'' Toledo said) but manpower concerns make
Kocher's progress essential to UCLA's long-term success.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, defensive line is the Bruins' most troublesome
position. One end, Pete Holland, plays hard but is limited
athletically. The other, Kenyon Coleman, is massive and gifted but
lacks intensity. Nose guard Micah Webb did not record a single
tackle against Texas, not even an assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kocher) is a big, strong guy. He's not as experienced as the
others, but there's no question he's a talented guy,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Kocher, 6-foot-4 and 292 pounds, sprained his right ankle on the
first day of contact and missed the rest of training camp. He
returned in time to play 10 snaps against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has felt a lot better the last couple days,'' he said.
``The day off (Sunday) really helped. I'm almost 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   However, outside linebacker Michael Wiley (sprained back) is
not. Santi Hall will start in Wiley's place.
</P>
<P>
   Backfield bits: Fullback Craig Walendy, who missed four weeks
from an allergic reaction to bug bites, participated in contact
drills this week but is not expected to play extensively. Durell
Price, impressive against Texas, will make his second career start.
</P>
<P>
   Secondary situation: Ryan Roques apparently was going to usurp
Damian Allen as the backup cornerback when Allen quit the team
Monday to concentrate on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, a change was about ready to take place
and everybody knew it,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Whitfield will start at free safety over Jason Stephens. In
passing situations, however, Whitfield may slide to nickel back
(the third cornerback) while Stephens plays free safety.
</P>
<P>
   Tackle tidbits: Tackle Josh Webb, who switched from defense to
offense two weeks ago, has progressed quickly and will play as much
as possible to speed his transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get him in early if we can,'' Toledo said. ``He's
learning it well. He'll spell (starter) Brian Polak. It's hard to
go the whole game if you're 325 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Cougar concerns: Houston's starting cornerbacks, Kenny Hill and
William Fields, are 5-9 and 5-8, respectively. The free safety,
David Williams, also is 5-9. The Bruins will try to exploit their
size advantage with 6-5 split end Brian Poli-Dixon and 6-4 flanker
Danny Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   On the edge: Two true freshmen are straddling the fine line
between playing and redshirting: guard Mike Saffer and defensive
tackle Anthony Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saffer's on the bubble; I don't know what will happen,''
Toledo said. ``(Fletcher) is real close. We'd like to save him a
year if we can with (senior defensive linemen) Vae Tate and Jayson
Brown. Why play a freshman if the seniors can be the backups?''
</P>
<P>
   Back to work: Freshman cornerback Lovell Houston practiced this
week after missing a month with a strained quadricep muscle. He's
so far behind schematically that redshirting seems the most-likely
path, unless a spate of injuries demand otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't play, it's not that big a deal to me,'' Houston
said. ``Whatever's best for the team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
