<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LUNGREN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUNGREN CALLS ON CLINTON TO RESIGN PRESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Saying President Clinton has brought disrepute on
the presidency and embarrassed the country, California Attorney
General Dan Lungren said he believes the president should resign.
</P>
<P>
   In his most detailed remarks to date, Lungren -- the Republican
candidate for governor in the Nov. 3 election -- used a speech
Thursday before the Greater Los Angeles Area Chamber of Commerce to
criticize Clinton and his record. At a news conference afterward,
he said the president should quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be good for the president to step down,''
Lungren said. ``I think he has undermined his own presidency. I
think he undermined the institution of the presidency itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not partisan. That's not hitting someone when they're
down. This is about what's in the best interests of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Lungren said he doesn't believe Clinton can be effective in his
relationship with Congress or in foreign affairs as long as he
remains embroiled in the scandal involving former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lungren said he questioned his opponent,
Democrat Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, for his scheduled appearance at
fund-raisers for Democrats with the president next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not questioning his character, just his judgment,''
Lungren said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Davis said the lieutenant governor has not formally
committed to appearing with Clinton, but will do so if his schedule
permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no problems in appearing with the president,'' said
spokesman Michael Bustamante. ``(Davis) has made it clear that what
the president did was wrong and indefensible and he should be
punished, but that it's up to the Congress of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said Davis also continues to appreciate what Clinton
has done for California during his years as president.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several weeks and as a major part of his campaign,
Lungren has been hitting at the ``character issue'' concerning
public officials.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks to the 40 members of the chamber gathered at the
downtown Marriott Hotel, Lungren again stressed the issue, asking
what the legacy of the present generation would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have had three great generations in our history,''
Lungren said. ``The Founding Fathers, those from the Civil War era,
and our parents, who came out of the Depression and World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legacy of my generation is Bill Clinton, and I don't think
that's the legacy my generation wants to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
