<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ERSTAD FALTERS, ANGELS HAMSTRUNG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Before Thursday's game against the Texas
Rangers, his first start since Sept. 2, the Angels' Darin Erstad
could joke about his strained left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned,'' he said, ``I'm scoring from second
on a base hit, and I'm legging doubles into triples.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, however, didn't make it out of the first inning _ and
barely made it out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the game, he ripped the first pitch into the
left-center field gap. But Erstad hobbled to first and stayed there
with a single.
</P>
<P>
   After Randy Velarde walked, moving Erstad to second, manager
Terry Collins and third-base coach Larry Bowa consulted with
Erstad, then took him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running pretty decent, but the first step out of the
box, that's where you build into your speed, and that's what I'm
having problems with,'' he said. ``I thought I was good enough to
run around the bases tonight. Obviously, that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said it would be a ``best-case scenario'' for Erstad to
miss this weekend's series with Seattle at Anaheim and be ready for
Texas on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another down: Catcher Phil Nevin was on crutches after the game,
his left ankle wrapped. He sprained the ankle in the first inning
when Will Clark slid into him on a play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin said he felt he would be able to play in spite of the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Quick assimilation: It hasn't taken long for Gregg Jefferies to
realize he fits in with the Angels. He was acquired Aug. 28 in a
trade with the Philadelphia Phillies and already performs like most
everybody else in an Angels uniform _ he plays hard, he plays hurt
and he doesn't complain.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why he wants to come back to play for the Angels next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great group,'' said Jefferies, who is hitting .362 (21
for 58) in 14 games for the Angels. ``As long as you want to win, I
don't care if you come to the park with a dress on; what you do off
the field doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to come back here.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the Angels want him back. Jefferies'
contract includes a 1999 club option for $6 million, a steep price
for a 31-year-old player who might not have a place to play if Tim
Salmon is healthy enough to return to the outfield next season.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Troy Glaus got his first start in three games. ``I
thought, `This guy's the future. This is a chance to make him a
better player,''' Collins said of Glaus, who had been struggling at
the plate. ``This is the time of year you make adjustments at-bat
after at-bat.'' ... Pitcher Ken Hill will make his scheduled start
tonight despite an arthritic condition in his right elbow. Hill
will pitch only from the stretch position to help alleviate the
pain ... Omar Olivares will start Sunday's game against Seattle in
place of Jeff Juden.
</P>
</TEXT>
