<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACHON STILL OUT IN THE COLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Kings executive Rogie Vachon was in
his office Wednesday when media-relations director Mike Altieri
delivered the news he'd been hoping not to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Vachon _ a former star goalie with the Kings and
three other NHL teams _ had been denied entrance to the Hockey Hall
of Fame, this time in his final year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old Vachon now must wait to be elected in the
veterans category after he's been retired for 25 years. Vachon,
seventh in NHL history with 355 victories, retired during the
1981-82 season after a 16-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disappointing,'' Vachon said Thursday. ``What
can you say? You're at the mercy of people voting, and somebody
obviously didn't think I did enough to make it. For an athlete,
making the Hall of Fame is icing on the cake. But, hey, life goes
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Players elected Wednesday were former Quebec Nordiques Peter
Stastny and Michel Goulet, and the late Roy Conacher, who played
for four teams in the 1930s, '40s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty proud of what we accomplished here in the 1970s,''
Vachon said. ``We put hockey on the map. Of course, Wayne (Gretzky)
brought it to a different level. But I was proud to be a part of
that era.''
</P>
<P>
   On the outs: As their would-be teammates file onto the ice for
scrimmages each morning, three unsigned Kings quietly exit the
Iceoplex in North Hills after holding their own workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake, Matt Johnson and Jamie Storr can only guess how much
longer they will remain unsigned and out of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen today, it could happen in a week, it could
happen in two months,'' said Blake, voted the NHL's top defenseman
last season. ``I'm going to prepare the way I have to. I'm not
going to let this contract dispute get in my head and throw me off.
I'm going to stay in shape and do what I have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said, ``We've talked a bit. I'm just kind of digesting
what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr, who would be battling No.1 goalie Stephane Fiset for
playing time if he was in camp, sounded a bit more upbeat when
asked when he thought he'd be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a huge gap,'' Storr said. ``It never has been.
Hopefully we can reach an agreement in the next couple of days or a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dave Taylor, however, did not sound as
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say we're close,'' Taylor said. ``But we've had
discussions and we'll continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Contracts, Taylor added, are not the only thing he's focusing on
at the moment. With the Kings expected to send several prospects
back to their junior teams today, a sizable portion of Taylor's
attention is on player evaluation. The Kings also may assign at
least one player today to their IHL affiliate, the Long Beach Ice
Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth unsigned player, defenseman Aki Berg, has returned to
his native Finland and may be close to signing with a team in
Finland or Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Blast from the past: Also skating at Iceoplex has been
unrestricted free agent Marty McSorley, a two-time former King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to compete and get a fair contract,'' said
McSorley, who earned $1.3 million last year with San Jose. ``I'm
not looking to break the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   McSorley, 35, would not say which teams have shown interest in
signing him, but Edmonton and Toronto reportedly are strong
contenders for his services.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative roster: The Kings open exhibition play with games
Saturday and Sunday in Las Vegas against Colorado. Manny Legace is
expected to start in goal Saturday, and the Kings will probably
take a look at some or all of these prospects: defensemen Sean
Blanchard and Peter Hogan, and forwards Olli Jokinen, Matt Zultek,
Scott Barney, Josh Green and Pavel Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   The games in Las Vegas will be played with two referees, as will
20 of the Kings' 82 regular-season games. Such veterans as
defensemen Mattias Norstrom and Sean O'Donnell and forwards Glen
Murray, Yanic Perreault and Ray Ferraro also are expected to play
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
