<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFUSED BY SPORTS STATS? JOIN THE CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As Mariner fans know, Ken Griffey Jr. joined the 50/20
club this week, when he stole his 20th base to go with 53 home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez is on the verge of the 40/40 club, needing one
more homer to go with his 43 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   What I wasn't sure about was when these things became clubs. Is
there an initiation ritual? A secret handshake? A cover charge? Do
the dancers have to stay a minimum distance from the customer?
</P>
<P>
   And who decides what constitutes a club?
</P>
<P>
   An exhaustive P-I search of sports rulebooks discloses no
requirements or policies regarding the creation of these clubs.
Apparently there is no rule against putting together any two stats
to make a club.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, we have discovered numerous clubs worthy of
mention:
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez and the 30/:30 club: The Mariner designated
hitter needs two home runs for a career-high 30, and needed 30
seconds to leg out Thursday's triple against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Davis and the 20/40 club: The Mariner third baseman has 20
home runs and needs just six more errors to reach 40, an amazing
feat considering the eye-hand coordination necessary for both
skills. How is it possible to have it for the top of an inning and
lose it in the bottom?
</P>
<P>
   Mariner management and the 1/0 club: First baseman David Segui
and the number of other new players acquired in the offseason or
from the farm club who made significant contributions to the team
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Ayala and the 10/10 club: 10 losses and 10 blown saves is
a difficult feat because it takes an unusually foolish team to keep
putting him out on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson and the 10/10 club: After 10 losses with the
Mariners, Johnson needs two more wins to get 10 for Houston in less
than two months, providing abysmal evidence for the he's-washed-up
cabal in the Mariner ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Piniella and the 1/300 club: He's about a half-dozen
pitchers short of becoming the first major league manager to go
through what seems like 300 pitchers in his tenure as Mariner
manager, and still doesn't have a complete starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   George Karl and the $5 million/2 club: By the end of the NBA
season _ should one occur _ Karl will join an NBA elite of Rick
Pitino, John Calipari and Larry Brown, who will earn top coaching
salaries but fail to get beyond the second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Kemp and the 0/6 club: With no marriages and six kids, the
ex-Sonic takes a big lead in the Reckless Paternity League,
although competition is heavy and the game is early.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Wrenn and the 10/4 club: In 10 months, the O'Dea High
School basketball star will have committed to four educational
institutions: The University of Washington, two East Coast prep
schools and to the University of Connecticut. He is ahead of the
pace of former Husky running back Corey Dillon, who nodded at
admissions clerks at a half-dozen or so schools before graduating
to the NFL College of Cash.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer and the 1,000/3 club:
Number of tackles the Buckeye All-American needs to make everyone
forget the three classes he passed to stay eligible: Golf, music
and AIDS awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Washington-BYU game and the 17/3 club: Number of syllables when
Washington defensive tackle Toalei Mulitauaopele tackles Brigham
Young starting tight end Tevita Ofahengaue on Saturday, and number
of play-by-play broadcasters at Husky Stadium whose tongues will
explode in the collision.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks and the 4/16 club: Number of games the Seahawks play
against the NFC East this year, and number of games the Seahawks
would win if they could play all games against NFC East opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mirer and the 27/0 club: Number of NFL teams yet to
discover the former Seahawk quarterback has zero game.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle and the $1.1 billion/2 club: We are the lone New
Testament member of this exclusive list, having dedicated about
$1.4 billion, including interest payments as well as principal, in
public tax money over 20 years for two sports stadiums. The Old
Testament club included Babylon, Sodom and Gomorrah.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle and the $1.1 billion/2012 club: Yet another exclusive
club the city can belong to if it successfully bids for the 2012
Olympics, whereupon it likely will be asked to cough up for
facilities and infrastructure at least as much as was offered for
the pro sports digs.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
