<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY, MOYER TWO-TIME ATHLETICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Their season was officially stamped
``disappointing'' months ago, so for the Mariners, days like
Thursday would seem to be about numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The M's and left-hander Jamie Moyer beat the Oakland Athletics
8-0 to complete a two-game sweep in front of 11,707 fans at the
Oakland Coliseum. The wins over the A's followed a Twin killing in
Minnesota, and gave the Mariners victories in six of their past
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest development Thursday could be the status of second
baseman Carlos Guillen, who will miss the rest of the season after
injuring his left knee on a diving catch in the second inning.
Guillen will have a magnetic resonance imaging test in Seattle
Friday to determine the extent of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The game itself, though, came down to these figures:
</P>
<P>
   --8: That was how many pitches it took Oakland knuckleballer Tom
Candiotti to run up a 3-0 deficit in the first inning. Guillen and
Alex Rodriguez led off with singles, bringing Ken Griffey Jr. to
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   --53: That's how many homers Griffey has after rifling
Candiotti's second pitch over the fence in right field, giving the
M's a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knuckleball,'' the AL home run leader said with a shrug.
``Just swing and if it hits the bat, it hits it, and if it doesn't,
go back to the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti went to the bench for good after five innings, with
the Mariners up 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   Doubles by Edgar Martinez and Shane Monahan contributed to a
three-run rally in the fourth, and the first of two RBIs from Raul
Ibanez brought in a single run in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   --362: Rodriguez went homerless for his ninth game in a row, and
remains at 39 homers as he tries to become the third player ever to
hit 40 homers and steal 40 bases in the same season. He hit a
362-foot fly to lead off the fifth, but the ball hit high off the
17-foot fence and Rodriguez settled for a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``It missed by inches,'' said A's left fielder Rickey Henderson,
who planted himself under the ball. ``It hit the numbers (on the
362-foot sign) up there, so it was just the luck of the draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rodriguez: ``I thought I missed it big-time. I'm surprised
it went that far.''
</P>
<P>
   --0: Moyer has allowed zero runs and zero walks in two
complete-game shutouts of the A's this year. He threw a
three-hitter on June 12 and allowed only four hits Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was changing speeds really well and all his pitches were
hitting their spots extremely well,'' said catcher Joe Oliver. ``I
can't remember any pitches that went over the fat part of the
plate. He was really keeping the ball in a great location and
keeping the hitters off stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer improved to 14-9 and lowered his earned-run average to
3.47. But even numbers like those, Moyer said, can't take the sting
off '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think so,'' he said. ``We're in this as a 25-man
ballclub, coaching staff, organization and city. Whether I'm
pitching or not, I don't like to lose. And when you look down at
the most important column, it's wins and losses, and we're lacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to swallow, because you look around this clubhouse
and there's a lot of pretty good players. We've had some
misfortune, but for the most part we just haven't gotten any run of
consistency together.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the numbers show it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
