u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BO     09-18 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECT 10TH BOOSTS RED SOX OVER ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ They went small, they went old, they went tried and
true.
</P>
<P>
   And when it was over Thursday night, the Red Sox went
triumphantly to Chicago, double winners on a night they beat the
Orioles, 3-2, on Mo Vaughn's single in the 10th inning at Camden
Yards while the Blue Jays were losing in the bottom of the ninth to
the Tigers, 7-4, in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The lead over the Blue Jays in the American League wild-card
race is five games. The magic number is six. Eleven games are left,
the next seven against the White Sox and Devil Rays, two teams the
Red Sox have beaten 11 times in 16 meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is throwing confetti on Yawkey Way just yet, or wrapping
streamers around Pesky Pole. For the Sons of Jimy Williams, there
will be no party before its time. But John Harrington may want to
keep his calendar open in the coming days, just to be on the safe
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, this was huge,'' said Dennis Eckersley, who is two weeks
shy of his 44th birthday and days away from a return to the
postseason for the sixth time in his career but first time with the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the seventh inning, we were losing and the Blue Jays
were winning, and it turned around. This was awesome. It couldn't
have happened at a better time.''
</P>
<P>
   How did it turn around?
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Sadler, who is small enough to be Vaughn's pocket watch,
hit a two-run homer in the seventh off Orioles ace Mike Mussina,
who gave up just six hits all night, three to the rookie second
baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seized the moment without any fear,'' Vaughn said of the
23-year-old Texan, who appeared to begin the season with no clue,
going hitless in his only 11 at-bats before being shipped back to
the minors. ``He's doing all the little things and big things to
help this ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley, who is older than his team's general manager, retired
three Orioles, including Cal Ripken, on five pitches in the bottom
of the ninth. Rafael Palmeiro, who had homered in the fourth off
starter Pete Schourek for Baltimore's first run, had singled off
Greg Swindell to start the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley threw one pitch to Ripken, who popped up his bunt
attempt foul to catcher Scott Hatteberg, a fundamental failure by
one of the all-time masters of the basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funny how he bunted,'' Eckersley said. ``He didn't
square around. Maybe he doesn't bunt that much. But that was
probably the biggest play right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley's next pitch was to Harold Baines, the lefthanded
pinch hitter, who popped out to shortstop Nomar Garciaparra. ``He
knows I'm going to be around the plate,'' Eckersley said. ``I mean,
these guys are hacking off me. All I have to do is put my arm up
and they're hacking.''
</P>
<P>
   Three pitches later, Eckersley was through with Chris Hoiles,
who fouled out to Vaughn. This is as close as it gets to vintage
Eck, who usually is whisked away at the first sign of trouble by
Williams but has not allowed a run in more than a month, spanning
17 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis, who has been battling a slump but was anything but
an easy out Thursday night, doubled off Orioles closer Armando
Benitez to start the 10th. Lewis was back in the leadoff spot after
sitting the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``You stay with the people who brung you,'' Williams said.
``That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   The next batter was John Valentin, who fouled off a bunt
attempt, took another strike, then caught a Benitez fastball in the
back of his left shoulder as his helmet flew off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad it didn't hit him in the head,'' Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn had had little success against Mussina, who struck out 10
batters in nine innings, including the first baseman on a
full-count knuckle curve with the bases loaded in the third. Vaughn
was 0 for 4 when he settled into the batter's box against Arthur
Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arthur Rhodes is one of the toughest lefthanders in baseball
to hit against,'' Vaughn said. ``Against him, I try to stay inside
the ball, try not to get too big, and drive it up the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-and-1 pitch from Rhodes, that's just what he did,
launching a soft single into center that scored Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hit it too hard, but I did what I had to do in the
situation,'' said Vaughn, who has remained a rock no matter how
much the sand has shifted underneath him or how many other players
the Sox sign while leaving his future undecided.
</P>
<P>
   With a lead in hand, Tom Gordon, a.k.a. Jimy's Closer, set a
major league record with his 39th straight save in one season and
42d overall, though it took four outs to do it. Gordon struck out
Mike Bordick, but the shortstop reached first when the third strike
was a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Gordon had broken the club record for saves
held by Jeff Reardon. He said he had a stack of messages at the
team hotel. Someone asked if there were any VIPs in the bunch. A
Kennedy, perhaps, or a Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Gordon said with a smile, ``but I hope I get to talk to
Bill real soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Play deep enough into October and that just might be arranged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
