<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 03:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2015 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAVES-AZR     09-18 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES DO JUST ENOUGH TO TOP DAAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -There's no straitjacket hanging in Omar Daal's locker,
although he's beginning to wonder if there should be.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks left-hander went through another frustrating
evening on Thursday, limiting the Atlanta Braves to a run on four
hits in eight innings but came away empty-handed when the offense
deserted him.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 1-0 Atlanta victory in front of 43,251 at Bank
One Ballpark, putting the Braves within one win of triple digits
(99-55) and dropping the Diamondbacks to 61-93.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' run had a questionable tinge to it. Second baseman
Tony Graffanino bunted down the third-base line to begin the third
inning. Daal and catcher Kelly Stinnett converged on the ball about
halfway down the line, and Daal took a swipe at it with his glove
just as it appeared to cross into foul territory.
</P>
<P>
   Plate umpire Eric Gregg, maintaining a statue-like presence near
his normal position, ruled that Daal had touched the ball while it
was on the line, therefore making it fair and allowing Graffanino
to reach first base safely.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino was sacrificed to second by Denny Neagle, the
eventual winning pitcher, and scored when veteran shortstop Ozzie
Guillen slapped a single to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Daal and Stinnett thought Graffanino's ball was foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Gregg) didn't move from where he was, but he said it was
on the line,'' Daal said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Stinnett: ``Maybe we should have let the ball roll longer,
but it was a good inch off the line already. Omar took a chance and
it didn't go our way.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other hits given up by Daal (7-12) were infield
singles, by outfielder Gerald Williams in the first inning, and by
outfielder Andruw Jones in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Daal's ERA dropped to 2.70, qualifying him for the National
League leaders. Of his past six defeats, four have been when
Arizona has been shut out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got kind of mad when I got out of the game, that I continue
to pitch like that and don't get any runs. I'm trying not to lose
my mind. But what can I do about it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good, had a good slider, fastball and change-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox, who has seen a lot of good pitching
in his day, was impressed with Daal, who was in the bullpen when
the teams last met here in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hearing a lot about Daal for a long time,'' Cox
said. ``I saw him pitch against the Cubs on TV, and he was every
bit as good tonight as he was then. He was awesome. They've done a
wonderful job with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed Neagle, who missed his two previous starts
because of bursitis in his left shoulder, did a wonderful job
himself. He scattered four hits through six innings and got help
from relievers Dennis Martinez, John Rocker and Kerry Ligtenberg to
pick up his 15th victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has five 15-game winners, the first time a team has
accomplished that since the 1930 Washington Senators.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle said he was more concerned about the shoulder than
getting to 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six innings was plenty tonight,'' he said. ``It was the smart
thing to pull myself early.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' biggest opportunity to tie the score or
perhaps win it came against the right-handed Ligtenberg in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Devon White reached first with one out when he
swung for a third strike and the ball got past catcher Eddie Perez
for a passed ball. Matt Williams forced White at second on a
fielder's choice for the second out. Ligtenberg walked Travis Lee,
but struck out Jay Bell swinging for the third out and chalked up
his 29th save. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
