r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-CHAVEZ-A     09-18 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-CHAVEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA'S WBC TITLE, TYSON'S FUTURE ON THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The mismatch and the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   In a city full of wild deuces, it's a dice roll as to whether
the Oscar De La Hoya-Julio Cesar Chavez bout tonight and Mike
Tyson's hearing Saturday for reinstatement of his license will
fulfill or exceed the billing.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the oddsmakers, only the Tyson hearing before the
Nevada Athletic Commission is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield lost part of his ear and Tyson lost all of his
license the last time Tyson faced the Commission. The hearing is
too close to call. Perfect for a rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, De La Hoya (28-0, 23 KOs) is an 8-to-1 favorite to
repeat the bloody whipping suffered by Chavez (101-2-2, 84 KOs) 27
months ago. De La Hoya, 25, looks bigger. He was 146 { pounds, two
heavier than the shorter Chavez at Thursday's weigh-in. Chavez, 36,
is just a couple of years older. It adds up to a mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   But odds never quite capture the inescapable intrigue that
always manages to build. It might prove to be another illusion
among the many cast by the blinking neon.
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing appears certain. De La Hoya and Chavez will fight
tonight for the World Boxing Council's welterweight title at Thomas
&AMP; Mack Center. Opening bell is scheduled for about 8:30. The
pay-per-view television portion of the undercard will begin at 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   There's speculation he will withdraw from Saturday morning's
hearing at Cashman Center, near a minor-league baseball park, out
of fear the Nevada Commission will reject his plea for
reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario has Tyson, under investigation in Maryland for an
alleged assault after a fender-bender, fighting abroad no matter
what Nevada does. He has signed a multimillion-dollar deal with
Showtime. If the cable network is going to make good on its
investment, it's fair to guess that it will go wherever necessary.
If Tyson doesn't get a license, he'll need a passport.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez? If De La Hoya is to be believed, his old boyhood hero
will need a lot of stitches, if not a stretcher. De La Hoya has
repeatedly promised to punish Chavez for not acknowledging him as
an equal after he scored a stunning fourth-round TKO in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been like a crybaby lately, crying about everything,''
said De La Hoya, who is guaranteed about $9 million and a
percentage of pay-per-view sales that promoter Bob Arum says could
top 800,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez might be less vulnerable to cuts this time around. In
the first bout, De La Hoya's whip-like jab opened up a cut above
Chavez's left eye. After the bout, Chavez had more stories than
Bill Clinton to explain the cut.
</P>
<P>
   He got it in sparring. He was nicked while playing with his son.
It was the result of head-butt.
</P>
<P>
   How ever it happened, Chavez hid the wound behind eye makeup
from the Nevada's ring physicians in a pre-fight physical. He also
concealed the wound by wearing a hat low around his eyes. He
couldn't afford not to fight, because of Mexican tax debt and other
financial problems. His purse for tonight is $6 million and a
percentage of pay-per-view receipts.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Nevada Commission took a closer look at the scar
tissue that crisscrosses Chavez's forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the cuts are healed,'' Dr. Barry Markham said. ``The scars
are imperceptible. His skin looks great.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya was glad to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his skin is fine, that makes me happy,'' said De La Hoya,
who already has agreed to a Nov. 21 date with African Ike Quartey.
``I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   If Chavez' paper-thin scar tissue _ the result of 105 bouts _
withstands De La Hoya's early blows, it sets up an interesting
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has been known as a slow starter. Throughout his career,
he has been at his best in the middle-to-late rounds of battles
that exhaust the body and test the will. If there is a last roar in
the aging lion, it'll probably be heard in a late round.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has seldom had to go a full 12 rounds. In his 28
bouts, he has fought into the 12th only four times. He's not
expecting a fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only satisfaction I will get is if I knock Chavez out,''
he said. ``If it's not a clean, devastating knockout, I will be
disappointed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
