r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-CASSTEVENS-A     09-18 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT GUYS, RIGHT TIME  
 HOME RUN DERBY TRANSCENDS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO - The day after Sammy Sosa hit No. 63 the home team
still was in a full pout.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres couldn't get over their own fans celebrating the
grand-slam home run that had beat them. They were upset the
scoreboard flashed ``San Diego Salutes Sammy Sosa'' as the Cubs
slugger circled the bases, and angrier still when fireworks lit the
night sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's garbage,'' Padres pitcher Sterling Hitchcock fumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, are we the ``enemy''?'' pouted Greg Vaughn, knowing they
are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were going to roll out a new car,'' Andy Ashby
groused.
</P>
<P>
   Poor babies.
</P>
<P>
   They don't get it.
</P>
<P>
   This is bigger than the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   This is bigger than the West division champion's attempt to win
100 games and secure home-field advantage in the National League
playoffs. The story is bigger than one team. It's the biggest story
in baseball, the most compelling drama in sports.
</P>
<P>
   It's history.
</P>
<P>
   Did you see Sosa's grand slam? No. 63 launched Wednesday night
landed up there _ where? _ ``way'' up there, see, just to the right
of the Bimbo Bakeries sign, in the second deck. Went 434 feet.
</P>
<P>
   What happened today? Anyone hit No. 64?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone is talking about it, following it. Even world leaders
have taken note of America's magical late-summer preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
   When the president of the Czech Republic was asked at a joint
news conference to comment on the characters in the White House
soap opera, one of whom stood stiffly at his side, Vaclav Havel
replied in halting English, ``I congratulate Mr. Mark McGwire and
wish success to Mr. Sammy Sosa.''
</P>
<P>
   His playful diplomacy broke the tension. Laughter filled the
State Department auditorium. The comic relief brought smiles,
welcomed smiles that remind us that despite all the political
in-fighting and and grim, hand-wringing uncertainty in Washington,
America has the Great Home Run Derby to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   We have Mr. Sosa, and Mr. McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa didn't hit one Thursday. With an opportunity to overtake
McGwire, whose team had the day off, Sosa came to the plate five
times. He hit the ball hard. On one swing, he broke his bat, the
splintered barrel whirling toward the third-base coaching box like
a helicopter blade. But the Cubs slugger failed to turn any pitches
into memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of letdowns, it was like watching the Fire Department
roar into action and aim their hoses only to discover they had no
water pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Out. Out. Out. When Sosa walked in the eighth inning, Padres
fans booed the pitcher, Randy Myers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs won the game, 4-3, with a 10th inning home run, but
Sosa didn't deliver it. Gary Gaetti did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I am not going to hit a home run,'' Sosa said,
almost apologetically. True. In June, which has 30 days, my choice
for National League MVP hit only 20.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa and McGwire. McGwire and Sosa. They have given us a summer
to cheer and cherish. Fifty homers . . . 55 . . . 60 . . . 61 . . .
a record 62. We have watched the count steadily climb like the
mercury on a bulb thermometer. In the bleachers, fans scramble for
souvenirs. Former big league stars shake their heads in wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Jackson lives in Newport Beach, Calif. He took the day
off Thursday and drove 150 miles to San Diego. ``I came,'' Jackson
said, `'to meet the man and shake his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The long ball is an art form with which Jackson is familiar. In
1969, at age 22, he hit a career-high 47 homers, 37 by the All-Star
break. Like others who have played the game, Jackson marvels at
what Sosa and McGwire are doing. Your turn, my turn. One blast
after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me goose bumps,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson shook hands with Sosa before the game. Reggie held
Sosa's bat, gripped the handle, waggled it, admiring it, feeling
its weight. He liked how it felt in his hands, but he likes even
more what its owner is doing for the game he cherishes.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie gets it. This is bigger than the Padres. Bigger than the
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've almost worn Michael Jordan out as a sports hero,'' Mr.
October said. ``These two guys have come along at the right time.
This is great, for everyone.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
