<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-POLLS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY POLLS TAKE CRAZY BOUNCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putting together a preseason ranking of the top 25 college
football teams has never been more than educated guesswork,
although the word ``educated'' should be used loosely.
</P>
<P>
   This season is only two weeks old, and already seven teams in
the preseason poll have dropped out of the Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Four teams ranked in the AP's top 15 only a few weeks ago are
now listed among ``others receiving votes,'' including Michigan
(0-2), which was ranked fifth; Arizona State (0-2), ranked eighth;
North Carolina (0-1), 12th; and Colorado State (2-1), 15th.
</P>
<P>
   The two polls, the AP's and the ``USA Toda''y/ESPN coaches',
have been as volatile the past two weeks as the stock market. And
there are parts of the polls that make no sense. For instance why
did ASU receive 20 more votes than BYU in the most-recent AP poll,
even though the Cougars hammered the Sun Devils, 26-6, last week?
</P>
<P>
   Most experts believe it's too early to get worked up about the
polls, because the inconsistencies usually take awhile to work
themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   ``As (Florida State Coach) Bobby Bowden told me once, by
November those things usually have taken care of themselves,'' said
John Junker, executive director of the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That is Junker's hope. His bowl will host the top two ranked
teams in the country, as determined by a formula devised by
officials from the Bowl Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   That formula includes four parts: record, ranking in the two
polls, strength of schedule and the average of three computer
rankings. The coaches' poll will vote the winner of the Fiesta Bowl
No. 1, while the writers' poll reserves the right to pick another
team if the scenario presents itself.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, when bowl affiliations allowed, the polls almost
always were the determining factor in pairing two teams for a
national title matchup. While officials welcome the new rating
system, it might not eliminate controversy.
</P>
<P>
   What if Kansas State, which has one of the nation's weakest
nonconference schedules, is undefeated and ranked second, and
Florida State has one loss and is ranked third? The Seminoles could
earn a trip to the Fiesta by virtue of their tougher schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Junker is glad the Bowl Championship Series has established
criteria for making the selections and that it's not up to him to
select the two teams for what probably will be the national title
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Dec. 6 (selection day), I don't want to be telling a group
of 120 young men that they are not being invited to play for the
national championship,'' he said. ``I think it will be a healthy
transition to have, for the purposes of a championship game,
objective criteria used.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opening weeks, the polls are largely a work in progress.
And many coaches would like to see the first polls come out in
October, rather than August. That would give voters a better idea
of who is worthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that even if you've won games at this point that
you know what you are,'' said Oregon Coach Mike Bellotti, whose
team is ranked 22nd after starting unranked. The Ducks caught the
nation's attention by opening with a victory over Michigan State,
but Bellotti said too much can be made of such a victory. Last
week, Oregon was less impressive, squeaking by UTEP on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you should get three games under your belt,'' Bellotti
said when asked when a poll should begin. ``Most of the time that
gives an indication of what kind of football team you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Coach Dick Tomey agreed. The Wildcats have risen from
24th to 16th, although their two victories came against Hawaii and
Stanford, which are hardly powers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way too early for anybody to get excited about their team
or down on their team,'' he said. ``There is too much football left
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder also would like the poll to start after a
few games have been played, but he understands the reasoning behind
having early-season rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entertainment dollar and the competitive dollar is with
the NFL in a lot of ways,'' he said. ``They start camp before we
do. That start games before we do. The volume of information in the
papers about them is ahead of us, and more excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are, we would be taking away one of the things that
kind of interests people about college football and delaying it
another month.''
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches have complained that teams that start unranked or
ranked low are at a disadvantage in contending for a national title
because they have so far to climb. By waiting a month, the journey
could be made that much shorter, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Washington State started the season unranked and
didn't move into the top 10 until winning its first seven games.
Starting the poll in the preseason ``makes it more difficult for
Washington State,'' Coach Mike Price said. ``It just takes us a
little longer to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's still possible. Over the past few years, other
underdogs such as Northwestern and Arizona State have been able to
climb into the top 10 despite being unranked in at least one of the
preseason polls.
</P>
<P>
   If there's an advantage to be gained in the preseason rankings,
it belongs to the schools at the top, Junker said. ``If a team is
winning, it's hard to fall,'' he said. ``If you're winning, it's
big news if you fall.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0061 </DOCNO>
