</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALLEN-EAGLES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLES FLYING SOUTH EARLY  
 ENTER VALLEY HOPING TO AVOID 0-3 START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time the Philadelphia Eagles started a season 0-3 Buddy
Ryan was their coach. They didn't have a winner in town, either.
</P>
<P>
   That was 12 years ago. In the interim, the Eagles have made the
playoffs on average every other year, six times, which is six more
than the Cardinals during that span.
</P>
<P>
   So after last year's first-round exit, history would suggest a
step backward for the Eagles. And so it is. The Eagles (0-2) have
shown there is another team in the NFC East just as bad as, or
worse than, the Cardinals (0-2), and the Big Red gets a shot at
them on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles haven't won on the road since beating the one-win New
York Jets two years ago (the Jets' win was over the Cardinals),
haven't won on grass since the 1996 opener, and have lost four of
their past five in Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a deterioration of talent in Philadelphia,
although the Eagles, like the Cardinals, have found a promising
young quarterback in Bobby Hoying.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, free agents such as All-Pro defensive end
Reggie White, Pro Bowl running back Ricky Watters, linebacker Seth
Joyner and end Clyde Simmons have left. The club had a chance to
trade with Green Bay for quarterback Mark Brunell. It fell through,
and Brunell is leading Jacksonville to the playoffs. The Eagles
moved too slowly in an offer to free-agent tackle Lomas Brown two
years ago, and he signed with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a draft, we have the same opportunities as other teams
to get players,'' said embattled Eagles Coach Ray Rhodes. ``We're
not looking for excuses, we just have to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rhodes points out there is a draft, but the Eagles have
squandered many of their picks, among them 1994 first-rounder
Bernard Williams, who was suspended by the NFL under its
substance-abuse policy; 1995 first-rounder Mike Mamula, a career
underachiever who is on injured reserve; and 1997 first-rounder
John Harris, a defensive end whom most clubs projected as a
third-rounder at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite naturally, I think when you're 0-2 no one's going to be
very happy, including myself,'' Rhodes said. ``We're struggling to
find a way to get on track. There's nothing to smile about. I don't
think there are a lot of smiles in Arizona, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles did seem to hit the jackpot with Hoying. The former
Ohio State standout was selected in the third round in 1996,
although Hoying, who turns 26 on Sunday, is suffering many of the
growing pains that Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer is
experiencing. After Hoying was sacked nine times by Seattle in the
opener, the Eagles got the ball out of Hoying's hands more quickly
last week in a 17-12 loss at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get Bobby relaxed again,'' Rhodes said. ``We did
a lot of film study and pinpointed things that he could do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoying emerged as the starter late last season after Ty Detmer
and Rodney Peete were inconsistent. The Eagles went 2-0-1, rallying
into the playoffs. Now, defenses are getting to know Hoying and are
game-planning for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my third year and Jake's second, and it's just
experience,'' Hoying said. ``It's not only seeing it on film but
also in live game situations and at game speed where you're picking
everything up. Seattle lit us up, got to us with various blitzes
and we didn't pick them up. It was a long day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number one thing is just avoiding the bad play and coming
back for the next one instead of trying to make something happen
and taking a sack.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, sacked seven times by Seattle, agrees staying out of
trouble is a key Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby has come out with a lot of expectations and struggled a
little bit, too. Teams are throwing stuff at him. There definitely
are similarities. He's better than what he is playing right now.
It's not me against him, but we both want to get off these losing
streaks.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
