<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-MURRAY-AZ     09-18 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-MURRAY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY'S FIRE FOR THE ICE  
 MINOR LEAGUE VET KEEPS DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Rob Murray won't lie. It's true, he said, he
actually gets excited about coming to training camp every year.
</P>
<P>
   (We pause for a moment while the rest of the veteran players on
the Coyotes snicker quietly.)
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, training camp is a necessary evil for the
guys who have been around the NHL block a time or two.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Murray, who is entering his 12th pro season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As nice as the summer is, I still get that itch,'' said
Murray, 31. ``The fire starts to build, and I really start looking
forward to getting back on the ice again.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray has made a career out of becoming the Crash Davis of
minor league hockey. Just like the fictional character in the
baseball movie ``Bull Durham,'' he dreams of playing in hockey's
version of The Show, but won't let that affect his role _ or his
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation where, frankly, he's going to have a
difficult time making the (Coyotes),'' Coach Jim Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Anything can happen, of course. But Murray knows as well as
anyone that he likely will report back to the team's top minor
league affiliate, the Springfield Falcons of the American Hockey
League, his home for the past four seasons. It's almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm a realist,'' Murray said. ``I understand that the
few spots that might be available aren't really looking my way. But
at the same time, I want to come here and make sure I make an
impression on the coaching staff, on management, so that they don't
forget about me, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they won't. Actually, the Toronto native is a big part of
their plans. He always has been. Just not at the NHL level.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been invaluable as the captain and team leader in
Springfield. In addition to providing quality play and experience
on the ice, he is equally important as a mentor, teacher and big
brother to the dozens of young players who come up through the
system. It's a job most veteran players probably couldn't handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty admirable when you think about it,'' said Dave
Farrish, now in his second season as the Falcons head coach. ``In
the back of his mind, I know he's still hopeful of getting a shot
(to stay in Phoenix). I don't care how old you are, if you're in
the minor leagues, you still have your eyes on the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Take Chad Kilger, for instance. When the highly touted center
was demoted to Springfield, he pouted and retreated into a shell.
His game suffered. No matter what the Coyotes tried to say to him,
it didn't work. Murray was about the only person who could get
inside his head. After a second demotion, Kilger left the team
entirely and eventually was suspended by the Coyotes. He was traded
to Chicago a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I got him back to the NHL,'' laughed Murray, a
third-round draft pick of the Washington Capitals in 1985. ``But
it's just like my situation. If I don't get called up, I can't moan
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Danny (Briere) got called up, I could have went into the
tank. I mean, I've been in the pros for over 10 years, and here's
this rookie who gets called up ahead of me. But you know what?
Danny deserved to go up because he's a great player and a great
kid. I love the guy. I was happy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray hasn't played in an NHL game since 1995-96, when he
appeared in one game for Winnipeg against the New York Islanders.
Two days later, he was back in Springfield. He has appeared in 726
minor league games, just 94 in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   He vows to get back someday. If not as a player, then perhaps as
a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll make a good one,'' Farrish said. ``I have no doubts
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know him well enough,'' Schoenfeld said, ``but
coaching does seem like it would be a natural progression for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But not yet, Murray said. He still has some unfinished business
to attend to, whether it's in Phoenix or in Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``My former coach in Springfield, Kevin McCarthy, told me, `Rob,
you can always coach, but you can never go back and play. So play
as long as you can and do as good as you can,' '' Murray said.
``With expansion coming, who knows? Maybe it'll be too late for me,
but if I can squeeze out another year or two, who's to say?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
