<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-DYNASTY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES KEEP ROLLING ALONG  
 AT TIMES, PLAY GOES UNNOTICED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Maybe you turned off the TV after the daily
installment of The Mac and Sammy Show. Perhaps your eyes grew weary
reading of the epic McGwire-Sosa battle, not to mention the race in
the American League West or the wild-card situations or the other
special individual efforts that turned Baseball '98 into a season
of rebirth, as some of the game's poets have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   It might be that you missed the Atlanta Braves doing something
special themselves, winning a seventh straight National League
division title. They did it Monday, beating Philadelphia to clinch
first place in the East.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, don't we expect this? The Braves certainly do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of spoiled myself, being in this position so much,''
third baseman Chipper Jones said afterward. ``But I cherish every
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Jones' fourth. Pitchers John Smoltz and Tom Glavine
have been around for all seven. Not coincidentally, so have Manager
Bobby Cox, General Manager John Schuerholz and President Stan
Kasten, and a generous, aggressive owner, Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have all those division titles and more victories
than any team this decade. They have been to the World Series four
times since 1991. With the core of its six-time Cy Young Award
winning pitching rotation _ Greg Maddux, Glavine and Smoltz _
intact since 1993, they are the Team of the '90s, perhaps a team
for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   Or so one would think.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are different variations in what people perceive,''
Smoltz said. ``We've done something no other team has done. But
it's disappointing the way our city has treated it, what's been
written and said. It's disappointing when you're viewed as a
failure instead.''
</P>
<P>
   If such harsh judgment exists, it stems from the Braves'
postseason failures. They did win one World Series, in 1995, but
lost the other three _ in 1991 to Minnesota, in 1992 to Toronto and
in 1996 to New York _ plus championship series to Philadelphia in
1993 and Florida in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as Atlanta closes in on 100 victories, there already
are warnings of potholes in the road ahead. Smoltz, who is 16-3
despite going on the disabled list twice, can hardly fathom the
doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given the fans everything they want and more,'' he said.
``One of the best organizations and one of the best owners. But
it's like some people can't wait for us to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand,'' he said in the visitor's clubhouse at
Bank One Ballpark before the Braves' 1-0 victory Thursday. ``This
organization (the Diamondbacks) is an expansion organization.
They'd give anything to be in our position.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter, who scouted the Braves
extensively the past two years, is trying to attain that position.
If a franchise can serve as a role model, Atlanta is it. Showalter
is a big fan of Cox. He also cites the Braves' consistency, how
they develop talent while also filling needs through trades and
free-agent signings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to have that same vision,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks scouting director Don Mitchell, who worked for the
Braves from 1993 through 1995, said the organization's success is
rooted in the dark rebuilding days of the mid-1980s, when Kasten
became president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a commitment to scouting and player development, and
they stuck to it,'' Mitchell said. ``When John Schuerholz came
aboard (in 1990), he filled in some gaps. He signed Maddux, traded
for (Fred) McGriff. But they stuck with the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, young pitchers Kevin Millwood and Kerry Ligtenberg
have blossomed, along with outfielder Andruw Jones, adding to the
list of home-grown talent that includes Chipper Jones, catcher Javy
Lopez and outfielder Ryan Klesko. First baseman Andres Galarraga
and shortstop Walt Weiss were key free agent pickups.
</P>
<P>
   But it goes beyond talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of confidence there,'' said Diamondbacks pitcher
Alan Embree, a former Brave. ``You know everyone at each position
is confident of his ability. . . . Schuerholz is just as confident
as the players and Bobby Cox is as good a manager as I've played
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each player makes the other better. Each one of the starters
wants to outdo the other, night after night. You've got older guys
the younger guys look up to. It's just a really professional
group.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
