<HEADLINE>
GILKEY SETS IMPROVED SIGHTS ON NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Diamondbacks outfielder  &UR; Bernard Gilkey looked like
someone standing on the edge of a swimming pool, waiting to stick
his toe into the water to test the temperature. He wanted so much
to walk onto the field at Bank One Ballpark, but . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta stay away. Can't be around dust too much yet,'' he said
as he stood on the dugout steps before Thursday night's game
against the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, he returned from Calgary, Alberta, where he
had corrective laser surgery on both eyes Wednesday. There is a
remote chance he could play in the season-ending three-game series
against San Diego at BOB Sept. 25-27, but a more likely scenario
has him returning to action at full strength when spring training
begins in late February in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see things a lot better now, and they will continue to
get better,'' said Gilkey, acquired in a trade with the New York
Mets on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird and sort of scary, but it was impressive. I went
from 20/40 to close to 20/20 in about 10 minutes. They didn't put
me under or anything.'' &QL; 
Springer returns &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed middle reliever  &UR; Russ Springer is making his return
to Arizona for the first time since being traded from the
Diamondbacks to the Braves on June 23 for left-handed middle
reliever  &UR; Alan Embree.
</P>
<P>
   He was 4-3 with a 4.13 ERA with Arizona and is 1-1 with a 4.50
ERA in 20 games for the Braves. In his most recent appearance
before this series, he gave up one hit and struck out one in one
inning against Philadelphia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Springer was on the disabled list from Aug. 6-21 with bone spurs
in his pitching elbow. He likely will have arthroscopic surgery
after the season to remove the chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see some of the guys over there (in the Arizona
dugout), but it's also nice to win a few games,'' said Springer,
with thoughts of a trip to the playoffs and a chance at a World
Series championship ring dancing in his head. &QL; 
Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players from the Diamondbacks' farm system who will play in the
Arizona Instructional League reported to Tucson on Thursday night
and will have their first workout today. Games begin Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are looking for a left-handed batting practice
pitcher. One candidate threw to the pitchers Thursday _  &UR; Tony
Dello, who pitches batting practice for Coach  &UR; Pat Murphy at
Arizona State. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
