r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOPSEX-PROBE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-18 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPSEX-PROBE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SEEKS FBI PROBE OF SEX STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders called on the FBI Thursday to
investigate whether the White House is spreading stories of
adulterous affairs by key lawmakers as part of a clandestine
campaign to influence impeachment proceedings against President
Clinton.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The action came a day after the San Francisco-based Internet
magazine Salon reported that 74-year-old Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
had a five-year affair with a married woman in the 1960s. As
chairman of the Judiciary Committee, Hyde would be in charge of any
impeachment hearings against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The White House vehemently denied that anyone on its staff
played any part in exposing the affair. ``If there is someone in
our building who has completely lost their minds that they think
this is helpful, they should be fired,'' said White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart, traveling with Clinton in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But the accusations and counter-accusations set off a vigorous
debate about what has become fair game for public disclosure and
discourse in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the disclosures underscore the hypocrisy of some
lawmakers who, like Hyde, have cloaked themselves in a mantle of
family values and are now in a position to judge Clinton's
indiscretions. To others, they signify a dangerous trend in which
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's graphic report into the sex
life of President Clinton may have invited unwarranted prying into
the private lives of public figures.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who was 41 when the affair started, admitted being ``good
friends a long time ago'' with Cherie Snodgrass, but said that
``the statute of limitations has long since passed on my youthful
indiscretions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hyde report followed an admission last month by Rep. Dan
Burton, R-Ind., perhaps Clinton's most strident critic in Congress,
that he too had had an adulterous affair and fathered a child out
of wedlock. Burton, chairman of the Government Reform and Oversight
Committee, led the investigation into White House fund-raising
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Helen Chenoweth, R-Idaho, one of the most conservative
members of Congress, then admitted having had an affair with a
married man in the 1980s. Chenoweth, who did not hold office and
was not married at the time of the affair, acknowledged the
relationship shortly after she began airing ads that said
``Clinton's behavior has severely rocked this nation and damaged
the office of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, accused White House aide
Sidney Blumenthal Thursday of trying to ``shop the story'' about
Hyde to various media outlets. That, he said, would be a violation
of federal laws, which prohibit attempts to influence Congress in
conducting inquiries. ``I have no doubt in my mind that we have an
operation in the White House that is trying to destroy members of
Congress in order to intimidate them from doing their duty under
the Constitution of the United States,'' said DeLay. ``We believe
it warrants an investigation by the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon editor David Talbot rejected charges that the story on
Hyde came from the White House. Instead, he described in detail how
a man named Norm Sommer, who was a friend of Fred Snodgrass,
Cherie's ex-husband, approached dozens of media outlets with the
story, including the Los Angeles Times and the Boston Globe. Except
for Salon, none expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle McManus, Washington bureau chief of the Los Angeles Times,
said in a statement that the paper passed on the story because ``we
don't write about politicians' sex lives unless they come up in the
context of a story about an issue of legitimate public concern,
such as sexual harassment or abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked into the allegations about Rep. Hyde and found no
issue of legitimate public concern,'' McManus said.
</P>
<P>
   But Talbot said it was Starr, not his publication, who should be
held responsible for encouraging disclosures of the most intimate
details of a politician's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans and Kenneth Starr opened up the Pandora's box of
sexual investigations long before Salon ever got into the sexual
exposure business,'' said Talbot. ``As soon as Ken Starr delivered
that report, he rewrote the rules in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington culture now says you can make someone's private
life the subject of a public investigation,'' he said. ``We just
wanted to level the playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde received support from Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., who
expressed fears that the disclosures could further discourage
potentially qualified candidates from running for office. ``If
everyone is going to look for perfect people in these jobs, the
only ones who are going to run will be from the press,'' she said
in a tongue-in-cheek comment to a group of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said there is a big difference between an affair that
took place decades ago and the one conducted by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is focusing on the president's life 30 years ago, or
even seven years ago,'' said Feinstein. ``The fact that it was in
the workplace, in the Oval Office, under the imperative of the
president, that is very different.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that the new inquisitional climate would create
turmoil in electoral races across the country provoked a remarkably
rapid response from both political parties. Rep. Martin Frost,
chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, and
Rep. John Linder, head of the National Republican Congressional
Committee, both promised to withhold money from any candidates who
attack the private lives of their opponents in the November
election races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen often, but it is certainly possible that it
would happen this year because of everything that has happened,''
said Frost. ``If they engage in it, they engage in it at their own
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Brody, professor emeritus of political science at
Stanford University, said that ever since presidential candidate
Gary Hart was forced out of the presidential race in 1988,
politicians have been at risk of having their private lives
exposed. ``To some degree, the monster has been released earlier
on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Starr's report has pushed the level of exposure to
new extremes. ``Once you look at the president's sex life, every
politician's sex life is subject to examination,'' he said. ``None
of them are or should be immune from scrutiny, no matter how
unpleasant that scrutiny might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the revelations in recent days were not that
different from what has been standard practice in local campaigns
for years _ hiring what are called ``opposition researchers'' to
uncover dirt on an opponent and then leaking it to the press.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that now, the revelations are taking place in
the full glare of the national press, in the middle of an
unprecedented national scandal that at its heart deals with sex.
``Probably the reason it was not done earlier in Mr. Hyde's case is
that none of his opponents ever had the money to hire an opposition
researcher to dig up this stuff,'' said political scientist Mark
Petracca of the University of California at Irvine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
