<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Real Estate Guru Tries to Make REITs Less Vulnerable to Cycles   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Bill Sanders is probably the biggest name in real estate you never
heard of.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you think of Chicago real estate magnates, the predatory
Sam Zell is usually the first name that comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While Zell is relatively accessible and outspoken, Sanders is
somewhat professorial and reclusive. So, when I learned that
Sanders would make a rare appearance at the NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities investment conference, it was worth a listen.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sanders would pitch the long-term benefits of REITs _
which like everything else have taken a beating.
</P>
<P>
   REITs are mutual funds consisting largely of real estate
holdings such as apartments, hotels and shopping centers. And they
are required to pass almost all of their income from rents and fees
along to its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that they are vulnerable to real estate cycles:
When commercial markets get overbuilt, rents go down and so do
yields to REIT shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is trying to make Security Capital REITs less vulnerable
to real estate cycles by linking them to other income-producing
businesses such as parking garages and refrigerated warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   These additional revenue streams provide insurance against real
estate busts, making his REITs less cyclical, Sanders says. ``Real
estate is moving from being an asset class to a (type of) operating
company,'' Sanders says.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is revered in national real estate circles. He founded
Chicago's LaSalle Partners in 1968, which was an innovator in
national tenant representation _ the practice of finding new space
for big corporations as they expand.
</P>
<P>
   As the national real estate picture got ugly, Sanders cashed out
and left LaSalle in 1989, opting for the arid climes of Sante Fe,
N.M. After a couple of years contemplating new approaches to
investing in real estate, Sanders launched his current venture,
Security Capital Group, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Security Capital has a market capitalization of $4.3
billion, and it oversees 17 real estate operating companies with a
combined market cap of about $21 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanders is probably one of the leading visionaries in treating
real estate as an operating business ... and not a passive
investment,'' says Montgomery real estate analyst Chris Hartung.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Sanders is trying to take some of the guesswork out
of real estate by employing hundreds of well-paid executives,
researchers and financial tacticians.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as public real estate companies go, (Security
Capital's) management teams are very deep, and they've found new
avenues to grow revenues,'' says Montgomery's Hartung.
</P>
<P>
   REITs have been pounded much of this year as investors began to
sense that construction is overheating and another commercial real
estate glut is in the offing. Also, investors began to perceive
REITs not as long-term, income-producing investments (as they were
designed) but as growth equities. And when an explosive run-up in
REIT shares slowed, momentum investors bailed on the equities,
investors and analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, REITs were more like bonds, with (income) and
some opportunity for growth,'' notes portfolio manager Eric Von der
Porten, whose Leeward Investments has a fund heavily weighted in
real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, we went through this (recent) period where they were
great growth vehicles,'' Von der Porten said.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-year period ended January 1998, the Morgan
Stanley REIT index was up 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the index is down 21 percent, and it may be a
good time for long-term investors to look at them as a way to
diversify their portfolios, says Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Global real estate ``is a multitrillion (dollar) private
industry in the very early stages of going public,'' said Sanders.
``You are going to see many changes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
