<SLUG> BC-CHIRON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Chiron's Lab Kit Unit Sold   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Chiron Corp. has agreed to sell its diagnostic division for $1.1
billion to concentrate on its core drug, vaccine and blood testing
businesses.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Emeryville firm will receive $1.1 billion from the sale of
Chiron Diagnostics Corp. to Bayer Group of Leverkusen, Germany. The
unit makes kits that clinical laboratories use to test for
conditions such as allergies and cancer.
</P>
<P>
   While the move will cut the biotech firm's revenues in half, it
will increase its earnings by an estimated 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Chiron rose 56 cents to close at $17.44 yesterday.
``Wall Street was happy to see (diagnostics) go and pleasantly
surprised at the price,'' said Eric Schmidt, an analyst with SG
Cowen &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The sales price was about twice the division's annual revenues,
compared to an analyst's estimated value of between 1 and 11/2
times revenues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Chiron will maintain its highly profitable HIV and hepatitis C
blood testing businesses and license rights to them to Bayer and
other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   While no decisions have been made, some proceeds from the sale
may be used for acquisitions, expansion of Chiron's drug and
vaccine businesses or a stock buyback, said Sean Lance, Chiron's
president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron will also pay off $60 million in debt from the
diagnostics unit (Bayer assumed another $10 million of the
division's debt) and improve its data systems, including preparing
its computers for the year 2000, said Lance, who joined the company
in March.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron's board will decide on the company's strategic direction
next month, said Lance. ``The money won't burn a hole in our
pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   Although diagnostics was a mildly profitable business, Chiron
will see higher profits without it.
</P>
<P>
   Bear, Stearns analyst David Molowa estimates earnings per share
next year of 76 cents, compared to 71 cents had Chiron not sold the
diagnostics unit, a 7 percent difference. Revenues will drop to an
estimated $659 million from $1.3 billion with yesterday's sale, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lance says Chiron lacked the scale necessary to compete against
diagnostics giants such as Rhone-Poulenc SA, Novartis AG and Roche
Holding AG, which recently purchased Boehringer Mannheim GmbH.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Chiron's costs of goods sold in the diagnostics
division were about four times higher than the costs of competitor
Amgen when measured against each dollar of revenue generated, said
Mark Edwards, managing director of Recombinant Capital in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron will continue to receive substantial royalty payments
from the diagnostic products it sells to Bayer, said Lance.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close late this year, pending regulatory
approval. About 3,000 of Chiron's 6,500 employees work in the
diagnostics division, including 250 in Emeryville. The division is
based in Walpole, Mass. No significant layoffs are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Chiron has disappointed Wall Street several times in recent
years by failing to bring profitable drugs to market. About 38
percent of analysts who follow Chiron maintain holds on the stock,
according to Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
