<SLUG> BC-PENNER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Financier Penner Quits Capital Co.   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Ethan Penner, the flamboyant financier who helped create the $75
billion market for commercial mortgage-backed securities, resigned
yesterday as vice chairman of San Francisco's Capital Co. of
America after clashes with the firm's owners and rumors of mounting
losses.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only two months ago, Nomura Securities spun off Capital America
as a wholly owned subsidiary with $500 million of equity capital,
and Penner moved headquarters of the 420-employee business from New
York to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Penner hosted the firm's annual $3 million to $5
million gala under a tent at Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   Between quips from celebrities Robin Williams and tunes from Don
Henley, Joni Mitchell, Stevie Nix, Sheryl Crow and Michael
McDonald, many guests traded rumors that Capital America might be
in trouble and Penner might be on his way out.
</P>
<P>
   Capital America and other lenders who bundle securities and sell
them to investors have been under stiff financial pressure since
the world markets went into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   In their search for safety, investors are now demanding yields
on commercial mortgage bonds that are at least 1.25 percent to 1.35
percent higher than those on U.S. Treasury notes. That's an
increase of close to 50 basis points (half a percent) in two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Since the price of bonds moves inversely to their yields,
billions of dollars of commercial loans have nose-dived in value,
and that has put Capital America and its competitors in a bind.
</P>
<P>
   Capital America, for example, has about $4.5 billion in lines of
credit from Morgan Stanley and draws down these funds to make loans
and then pays them back as it sells the loans as bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the falling value of its loan portfolio and reserve
requirements imposed by Morgan Stanley, Capital America has
received two margin calls from the financial firm, one for $15
million a few weeks ago and another this week for $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined comment on rumors that it might have
suffered hundreds of millions of dollars in losses. Spokeswoman
Cameron Brown said, ``We have easily met the margin calls and are
very well capitalized,''
</P>
<P>
   Penner said he was quitting because of frustration with Nomura
management rather than financial problems. ``Everyone involved in
real estate finance has done poorly in the last 30 to 90 days,'' he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Penner said it took him nearly 18 months to persuade Nomura to
spin off the commercial real estate unit he started in 1993. He
also said he wanted Nomura to open ownership to the employees but
``that still has not happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said that he long pleaded to turn the company
into a financial giant like GE Capital with a broad product line
spread around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every business has its cycles and I wanted to diversify our
revenue stream,'' said Penner. ``Finally I ran out of patience with
all the foot-dragging.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Penner gave up the title of chief executive and
day-to-day responsibilities to become vice chairman. But the
37-year-old executive, who earned $47 million last year, said that
didn't resolve his fundamental differences with management.
</P>
<P>
   Before quitting the company yesterday, Penner signed an
agreement not to compete in commercial real estate loan
originations for six months. But he said he already is exploring
other real estate finance opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Penner's friends and co-CEOs Brian Pilcher and Boyd Fellows
greeted Penner's decision with ``great sadness'' in a prepared
statement. They also promised that ``the house that Penner built
will carry on.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the unit that Penner started in 1993 reportedly made
$200 million and was one of Nomura's most profitable businesses.
Stung by mounting financial problems in Japan, Nomura earned only
$322 million on $7.5 billion in revenues in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Capital America is not the only mortgage-backed securities
firm under pressure. Two weeks ago, WMF Group of Vienna , Va. took
a $30 million pretax loss selling $691 million in commercial
mortgage loans to a unit of Merrill-Lynch. Credit Suisse first
Boston also has dramatically scaled back its commercial mortgage
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
