<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Philippines Link Lost  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Philippine Airlines Inc., the only carrier with direct flights from
San Francisco International Airport to Manila, will shut down
Wednesday because of mounting financial losses and labor strife,
the airline announced yesterday.
<P>
   Saddened employees in the airline's downtown San Francisco
ticket office held onto hope that Philippine President Joseph
Estrada would broker a last-minute deal to save the struggling
carrier. Estrada was slated to meet today with Lucio Tan, chairman
and majority owner of the airline known as PAL. Tan owns 70 percent
of the company, while the government owns 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The news stunned passengers like Rene de Guzman, who in the
middle of the frantic two weeks before his wedding suddenly had his
honeymoon plans tossed in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been planning this for a year and a half,'' said de
Guzman, who rushed to the ticket office after learning the news via
the Internet. ``I'm at the point where there's so much to do, you
just have to throw up your hands. What can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Tan said the grounding came after the Philippine Airlines
Employees Association reversed its decision to accept a labor
agreement that suspended the union's bargaining rights for 10
years. In exchange, the union would have received a 20 percent
stake in PAL and three seats on the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management has exhausted all efforts to keep the company
operational,'' PAL said in a statement. ``Unfortunately, the
insurmountable burden of continued losses has become too heavy for
the company to bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Already hit with declining revenues from the Asian economic
crisis, the 57-year-old carrier was crippled by a pilots strike in
the second quarter and posted a loss of $50.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-day strike alone cost PAL about $1 million per day, said
Bert Lim, general manager of the carrier's U.S. and Canada
operations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Lim said the closure was not just a ploy to force the airline
unions to accept the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The revenues are not there,'' said an emotional Lim, a 32-year
PAL veteran. ``I'd rather have a job than dream of any salary
increase.''
</P>
<P>
   PAL was offering refunds but had not worked out any ticketing
agreements with other airline, so stranded passengers would have to
make their own travel arrangements, Lim said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to shutter the country's national air carrier came
even as Philippine Vice President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo was in
the Bay Area trying to convince business leaders and the Filipino
American community that her country has not been as hard hit by the
Asian economic crisis as neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a reputation for spotty service, PAL was popular among
the Bay Area's Filipino American residents because it was the only
carrier offering nonstop flights from San Francisco to Manila. PAL
also operates from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines dropped all service to Manila earlier this year
because it could not attract enough business travelers to make the
routes profitable, said spokesman Joe Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   United continues freighter service between the two cities, but
Hopkins said it was too early to say if United would try to pick up
passenger service once PAL is grounded.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine Airlines carried 10,000 passengers a month with
once-a-day flights, but that number plummeted to about 3,000 during
the strike, said SFO Airport Superintendent Tryg McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   Fer T. David, president of Luvy's Travel Service in San
Francisco, said he was trying to stay calm even though about 90
percent of his business is tied to the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd hate to lose Philippine Airlines,'' David said.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco travelers, though, found during the PAL strike
that they could still fly on several other airlines with connecting
flights to Manila for comparable or cheaper prices.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy said the most popular alternative is Northwest Airlines's
route to Tokyo, connecting to another flight into Manila. Korean
Air and Singapore Airlines also have connecting flights from Seoul,
South Korea, while EVA Airways has a flight from Taipei. Cathay
Pacific Airways also serves Manila from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But David said without PAL, it will be harder finding seats on
those flights, especially during the heaviest Philippine travel
season in December. Many of his clients have already booked on PAL
for that month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
