<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BP Honoring Pledge to Slow Global Warming   By Alex Barnum  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The chief executive of British Petroleum, who last year became the
first oil industry leader to acknowledge the threat of global
warming, will outline an ambitious program today for cutting the
company's share of heat-trapping gases.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEO John Browne is expected to announce today in a speech at
Yale University that the company, No. 3 in the oil industry, will
reduce emissions of carbon dioxide and other gases by 10 percent
below 1990 levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every producing oil field, every refinery, every chemical
plant'' owned by the oil industry giant will ``contribute to the
overall objective,'' Browne will announce, according to a
transcript of his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Browne has been outspoken on the threat of global warming ever
since he broke ranks with other oil industry leaders 17 months ago
and urged the industry to take steps to head off a catastrophic
shift in the world's climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no good preaching precautionary action unless you're
prepared to do something yourself. Now we're in a position to
announce a target,'' Browne says in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   And he notes that the target will have the force of the
company's other goals. ``In our terms, that target will now sit
alongside our financial targets. That means it is a promise, and as
with our financial targets, a promise is a personal commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, some of whom were skeptical that the
company would match its promises with concrete actions, praised the
announcement as courageous and farsighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What BP is going to announce is unprecedented,'' said Fred
Krupp, executive director of the Environmental Defense Fund. The
Washington environmental group is advising BP on its
emission-reduction plan.
</P>
<P>
   Krupp said the fact that BP is willing ``to follow forward and
cut emissions on the same timetable as the Kyoto agreement but
independent of whether it is ratified is an example of corporate
leadership that is historic.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's goal of reducing emissions by 10 percent is double
the 5 percent cut in emissions agreed to at last year's United
Nations conference on global warming, which was attended by roughly
160 nations. Only about 35 nations have signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although uncertainties exist, most scientists believe that
humans gradually are influencing the climate through the burning of
fossil fuels, which releases carbon dioxide and other heat-trapping
gases into the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   William O'Keefe, senior vice president of the American Petroleum
Institute, said many oil industry executives have acknowledged the
threat of global warming and factored it into their business plans.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that Browne is the only one to support the
Kyoto accord. Most industry groups believe that the uncertainties
are too great to justify binding requirements among nations to
reduce heat-trapping gases.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech today, Browne will urge other companies to control
global warming despite the uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the science of climate change is not proven. The
science is provisional and perhaps always will be,'' Browne says in
his speech. ``But it would be unwise and potentially dangerous to
ignore the mounting concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Browne cites a number of examples of how the company will reduce
its emissions over 1990 levels:
</P>
<P>
   _ By developing ways to speed the flow of oil through the Trans
Alaska pipeline, the company is cutting out a number of pumping
stations along the way. The result is a 236,000-ton annual
reduction in carbon dioxide emissions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Since 1995, the company's oil refineries and chemical plants
have cut flaring _ the burning off of waste gas _ by two-thirds.
That has reduced carbon dioxide emissions by 200,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   _ On pipelines used to transport oil from North Sea oil
platforms to shore, BP is installing devices to capture vapors that
escape when tankers are loading oil from the pipelines. That will
reduce emissions by 100,000 tons a year.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, BP is undertaking the emissions reductions in a pilot
program that will involve 12 of the company's 90 business units, or
about 25 percent of its worldwide operations. Eight of the units
are in Europe, three are in the United States and one is in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the pilot program, the company has set up a trading
system with the help of the Environmental Defense Fund that will
enable each unit to buy and sell emissions rights to meet the
targets efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   The trading system is similar to one that has been used
successfully in the United States to reduce sulfur dioxide
emissions from coal-burning power plants. Environmentalists
envision a similar system for controlling greenhouse gases
worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
