<HEADER>
A2064 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOTAPE-CLINTON-SFC     09-18 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOTAPE-CLINTON-SFCRHON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTISAN SQUABBLE STALLS VOTE ON RELEASE OF VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Washington erupted in venomous partisan rancor
Thursday as Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee unexpectedly
delayed release of President Clinton's videotaped grand jury
testimony and other evidence that would be embarrassing to the
president.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After more than seven hours of contentious debate, the
closed-door meeting adjourned after Republicans shot down 11
attempts by Democrats to delay or limit the release of grand jury
material. The sharply divided committee will meet again Friday,
when Republicans are expected to succeed in making the tape public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're partisan, sure,'' said Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of
the 37-member panel. ``It was strongly partisan, vigorously
partisan. I prefer that it would go more smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate Thursday centered not on the videotape, but on the
2,000 pages of supporting documents from independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's report that contain more graphic details of
Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky. Throughout the day, the
panel's 21 Republicans overruled repeated attempts by Democrats to
hold out parts of Lewinsky's sexually explicit testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Despite intense interest in the videotape, the committee spent
so much time squabbling over the other evidence that it never dealt
with the question of what to do with Clinton's grand jury
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over the evidence came as San Francisco Bay Area
Democrats indicated they are united in holding off calls for the
president's resignation, including Sen. Dianne Feinstein, who said
she ``is not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of our democracy is that this is a government
that does not easily fall,'' said Feinstein, in her first extended
comments on the matter. ``People's discontent can be met through a
regular electoral process. When we elect a president, we do so for
four years. This isn't Italy, where you can have a government every
two months. . . . What has to be determined is whether the
definition of impeachment is met.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., urged lawmakers not to make a
decision on Clinton's fate too quickly. ``If you cavalierly draw
conclusions, you are not paying proper respect to our system of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Democrats argue that the videotape will do
nothing to help determine whether Clinton's actions merit
impeachment, and they have fiercely opposed the release of the tape
and other documents on the grounds that it would serve no purpose
other than to humiliate him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's attorney, David Kendall, sounded a similar theme,
saying he had demanded that the tape be destroyed because ``the
only purpose of preserving this videotape . . . was to ensure its
public release and embarrass the president.'' His request was
dismissed by Starr, who pointedly contended that the tape contains
``evidence of a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the judiciary panel decides what evidence to release, the
material will probably not be made public for at least a day
because of the logistics of handling such a large volume of
documents, committee counsel Paul McNulty said. Television networks
are already setting aside time to air Clinton's four-hour testimony
as soon as it is available.
</P>
<P>
   The tape is expected to show Clinton alternately defensive,
angry and evasive in response to questions from prosecutors about
his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee will have even more material to look at
_ and probably release _ after Thursday's surprise announcement by
U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright in Little Rock, Ark., that
she will turn over to the panel Clinton's videotaped testimony in
the Paula Jones sexual harassment case. Wright dismissed Jones'
suit, which provided the initial grounds for Starr's inquiry into
whether Clinton lied under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Wright agreed to relinquish the tape at the request of Hyde,
prompting the panel's ranking Democrat, John Conyers of Michigan,
to protest the decision to seek the tape without the consultation
of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, however, Clinton's grand jury testimony is a
bigger concern, and Sacramento Democrat Robert Matsui, whose wife
once worked at the Clinton White House, said he is ``outraged'' by
its proposed release.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should have some rights,'' Matsui said. Release
of the tapes ``serves no purpose at all. The (impeachment) inquiry
is by 435 of us, not the public. For the Judiciary Committee to try
to influence public opinion, to humiliate the president publicly,
would result in the public putting pressures on members to
impeach.''
</P>
<P>
   But one moderate Democrat, the Central Valley's Gary Condit,
argued strenuously to release all the remaining Clinton material
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said that all the material will eventually become public
and that it is better to get it out all at once than to let it
dribble out and prolong the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, all that information is eventually going to
get out, and it's better for us to have it now, to move the process
along,'' Condit said. ``Today we're talking the tape, last week it
was the report, next week it will be something else, and it just
becomes somewhat suspicious that somebody is parceling out to us
the information whenever they want us to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Without accusing Republicans directly, Condit said, ``Let's get
through that game. . . . We can't make this decision . . . unless
we all have the information. The American people need the
information, to see what we've got and then get to the decisions
that we have to make so that we can get on with our lives and
running the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left Washington for a Democratic fund-raiser in
Cincinnati, where he rallied supporters and criticized Washington's
fixation on the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm concerned about is the rest of the people that live
in this country and one more time having Washington obsessed with
itself instead of America,'' Clinton said. He also assured the
crowd that he and Hillary Rodham Clinton are ``working on what we
need to be working on, and we're fine.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Louis Freedberg contributed to this
report.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 0332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0079 </DOCNO>
