<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2065 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALON-ONLINE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-18 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALON-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYDE ADULTERY STORY ANOTHER SCOOP FOR SALON 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON SWARTZ  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Salon's revelation that House Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde conducted an adulterous affair in the
1960s was just the latest political news exclusive for the upstart
online publication.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-year-old news organization _ started by former San
Francisco Examiner reporters and editors _ has gained national
attention for breaking several news scoops about independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the magazine's relentless coverage of Starr
prompted its critics to suggest that it was being used by the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely false,'' said Gary Kamiya, executive editor of
Salon. ``We are in no way affiliated with the White House. We have
blasted Clinton from every angle, and we've been hard on Starr. We
call them as we see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon has emerged as something of a sophisticated online
counterweight to the muckraking Drudge Report. In March, it ran a
series of articles on David Hale, a key Whitewater witness who
allegedly received payments from conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, it detailed the Arkansas Project, an expensive,
multiyear investigation designed to ``dig up dirt'' on President
Clinton, according to Kamiya.
</P>
<P>
   But Salon has been equally hard at times on the president for
his relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky,
the focus of the Starr report. Conservative columnist David
Horowitz last week called for Clinton to step down.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, Salon has been closely associated
with reports fiercely questioning the nature of the Starr report,
according to media watchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone can report anything on (the Starr
investigation) without being accused of having a political
agenda,'' said Beverly Kees, editor and program director of the
Freedom Forum Pacific Coast Center, a foundation dedicated to media
education. ``Any paper that told the cigar story is not in a
position to take the moral high ground over the Hyde story.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon editors ``agonized'' over the story and were ``leery''
about delving into Hyde's private life, Kamiya said.
</P>
<P>
   But the publication decided to run the story, it explained in an
editorial, because ``Starr opened up his Republican supporters to
sexual scrutiny the moment he delivered a 445-page report to
Congress that was nothing more than a sensationalistic accounting
of the president's affair designed to drive him from the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starr's investigation is the true scandal, a political
lynching party that, finding nothing of legal import in Whitewater,
quick-changed into the most expensive and tawdry sex probe in
American history, sullying the presidency and the nation's world
standing in the process,'' the editorial concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Salon employs 60 people in San Francisco and New York. Its
columns and features are syndicated in about 30 North American
newspapers, including the New York Daily News, Hartford Courant and
Toronto Globe and Mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publication is a salon in the truest sense _ it is a
gathering place and focal point for discussion,'' spokesman Patrick
Hurley said. The magazine has also won kudos for colorful and
lively features by contributors such as sex therapist Camille
Paglia and humorist Garrison Keillor.
</P>
<P>
   Among Salon's investors is Frank Hambrecht, a Democratic booster
who is co-founded of the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist investment banking firm
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the online publication has received financial
backing from Adobe Systems Inc. and ASCII Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, White House officials denied during a senior staff
meeting Wednesday that they had worked with Salon on the story.
</P>
<P>
   Kamiya said Salon got the story from Norm Sommer, a Florida
retiree who is friends with Fred Snodgrass, the former husband of
Cherie Snodgrass, who had an affair with Hyde. The story was
confirmed by other sources, Kamiya said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who has admitted to the affair, vowed the report will not
affect any impeachment proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Despite raves about his Whitewater stories, Salon's coverage of
Hyde has generated criticism because several mainstream
publications chose not to run the Hyde account.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer, 72, a lifelong Democrat who served as a Henry Wallace
delegate at the 1948 presidential convention, said he had called 57
journalists over six months in an effort to publicize the story
Fred Snodgrass had told him.
</P>
<P>
   He said reporters for the Los Angeles Times and Boston Globe
expressed interest but were overruled by editors. Sommer said he
also called the White House and Democratic National Committee for
guidance but that ``nobody would speak to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle McManus, Washington bureau chief of the Los Angeles Times,
said in a statement that the paper passed on the story because ``We
don't write about politicians' sex lives unless they come up in the
context of a story about an issue of legitimate public concern,
such as sexual harassment or abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked into the allegations about Rep. Hyde and found no
issue of legitimate public concern,'' McManus said.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   (Salon magazine can be found on the Web at
 &LR; www.salonmagazine.com &LR; .)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
