A2074 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUAKES-SANANDREAS-SFC     09-18 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKES-SANANDREAS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANDREAS FAULT KICKS UP TINY TEMBLORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID PERLMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Andreas Fault is stirring again beneath
Parkfield, and earth scientists are watching closely to see what
happens next.
</P>
<P>
   A series of six small earthquakes rippled gently through the
ground of the Monterey County village Thursday and Wednesday, and
instruments along the fault there showed ``subtle but significant''
earth movements, said William H. Bakun of the U.S. Geological
Survey in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   People in the area said they felt nothing, but the mini-temblors
intrigued the Geological Survey's seismologists who for years have
conducted an experiment there as they try to tease out the meaning
of the fault's behavior and possibly predict a real shaker whose
magnitude might well reach 6 or larger.
</P>
<P>
   Earthquake records show that quakes of at least magnitude 6 have
shaken the Parkfield area roughly every 22 years since 1857, with
the last one hitting in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   The first of this week's six temblors was recorded at 9:17 a.m.
Wednesday with a magnitude of 2.6, and the most recent, at 8:42
a.m. Thursday, had a magnitude of 2.9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know any of them happened,'' said Bonnie Speer
at the Parkfield Inn Thursday, ``but we're used to it all, and I
don't know that anyone around here has felt anything this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, seismic experts worldwide have followed the
Geological Survey's ``Parkfield Experiment,'' as scientists have
installed more and more subtle detection equipment on both sides of
the fault there.
</P>
<P>
   Today, an elaborate laser Geodimeter shoots beams of red and
blue light against mirrors on the fault's opposite side to measure
the slightest deformation of the ground. Creep meters, tilt meters
and strain gauges cross the fault on the surface, while
seismometers buried more than 600 feet deep measure quakes 10 times
smaller than anything detectable on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Wells pick up tiny changes in groundwater levels and
magnetometers constantly measure changes in the strength of the
local magnetic field, which might cause the fault's movements.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five creep meters installed at Parkfield has measured
a significant increase in the rate of slippage as the two sides of
the ground along the fault have slid almost imperceptibly past each
other this week, Bakun said. But it is still too early to infer
what is happening within the fault's complex geology deep
underground, where the six quakes were all centered a little more
than four miles down.
</P>
<P>
   Their epicenters, about six miles northwest of Parkfield, were
all within a half-mile of the spot around a formation known as
Middle Mountain, where two quakes with magnitudes of 3.5 were
recorded a year ago. A larger quake with a 4.7 magnitude struck in
October 1992 in the same location, and it initiated a brief
official alert for an imminent magnitude 6 temblor that never
happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
