<HEADER>
A2255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN20-COX     09-18 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: A private matter
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ Here's a story from long ago, a small
town's tale of love, sex and six-guns ...
</P>
<P>
   A rich man's daughter had become involved with a married man who
was in the process of a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   The outraged father forbade that she ever see the man again. Her
brother, who could be a hothead at times, warned her that he
intended to enforce their father's orders.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that the brother surprised them one night at her
lover's apartment. Tempers exploded. Gunfire erupted. Her lover
fell wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, it was only a flesh wound. Such was the target that had
presented itself, most fleshy.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrived. An ambulance was called. The wounded man was
taken to the hospital. The brother was taken to jail. Bail was
quickly arranged by the family.
</P>
<P>
   The father, as powerful as he was prominent, made sure nothing
would appear in the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the wounded man was scooted out of town and checked
into a big-city hospital under a disguised name.
</P>
<P>
   After the victim refused to press charges, police let the
incident drop, and it should have ended there.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the big-city newspapers had received a tip about the
story. The editor cared not a whit that it involved a wealthy
family.
</P>
<P>
   All the better to sell newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   As reporters began searching high and low for the victim, the
family began to seek counsel. What should they do? What could they
do?
</P>
<P>
   If there was to be a confrontation, wise heads advised them, let
it be on their own terms. Turn the tables. Surprise the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Their attorney did exactly that, marching the shooting victim,
still badly limping, into the office of the big-city newspaper,
unannounced and demanding to see the editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand you've been looking for me,'' the man told the
editor. ``Well, here I am. What I can I do for you?''
</P>
<P>
   The editor called in a reporter, and together they quizzed him
at length.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there had been a shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he had been wounded, but not seriously.
</P>
<P>
   No, he had not pressed charges, nor did he intend to.
</P>
<P>
   The questioning went on for an hour or more. The answers were
always the same.
</P>
<P>
   This was a private matter. It was being handled privately.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the editor threw up his hands and threw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the reporter, he said, ``If the guy who got his butt
shot off doesn't care, why should we?''
</P>
<P>
   End of story.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is recounted simply for the purpose of saying this:
</P>
<P>
   If the wife of the man who was involved with Monica Lewinsky has
forgiven him, why shouldn't we?
</P>
<P>
   P.S. For the record, the rich man's daughter married the man she
loved. It was predicted the marriage wouldn't last six months. But
they remained husband and wife for more than 30 years, separated at
last only in death.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
