<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2331 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDSVS-SOSA19-COX     09-18 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDSVS-SOSA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sosa frenzy comes to Cincinnati
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ The Cincinnati Reds once again dip their very
cold toes into the hot waters of Sammy Sosaville, where there is a
feeding frenzy of home runs and very real dreams of playoff
qualification for the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley Field, baseball's brickyard of dreams, will be a boiling
cauldron this weekend when the Reds and Cubs play three straight
afternoon games September 18, 19, and 20.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is Sosa's chase of the all-time home run record,
coupled with Sosa leading the Cubs toward the promised land of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And right now, that's what makes Sammy run.
</P>
<P>
   While Mark McGwire has nothing for which to play _ no postseason
aspiration, at least _ Sosa is driven by the obsession of taking
the Cubs to the playoffs. They are in a noose-gagging battle with
the New York Mets for the National League wild card, a spot from
which the Florida Marlins won the World Series last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa actually is on a three-pronged mission _ playoffs, home run
title, Most Valuable Player. He can have all three. McGwire can
have only one, the home run crown.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes what Sosa is doing all the more special, all
more important than what McGwire is doing. Sosa is slam-banging
home runs for the glory of the Cubs, not just for the glory of The
Man.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect example was Wednesday night in San Diego, against one
of baseball's best teams, and in the roiling waters of pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa broke a 0-0 tie with a two-run bases-loaded double, then
won the game with a grand slam home run, his 63rd, tying McGwire
for the all-time record. It was another step toward the home-run
record, a bigger step toward leading the Cubs to the playoffs and a
giant step toward the MVP title.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa leads the league with 154 runs batted in. The grand slam
was the third this year for Grand Sammy. . .this from a guy who had
no grand slams before this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what everybody waits for me to do,'' Sosa said. ``It's
my responsibility to go out and finish strong to take the Chicago
Cubs to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Finish strong?
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday, Sosa had 26 home runs and 60 RBI in his last
49 games. Numbers like that are mythological, but there is nothing
mythology about Sammy Sosa, who has blown more kisses this year
than Tiny Tim.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Cubdom wants the playoffs. But they want more from Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are all here to see Sammy make history and he continues
to make it,'' teammate Mark Grace said after Sosa received a
standing ovation from the tightly packed Qualcomm Stadium crowd,
nearly all San Diego Padre fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has carried us all year and he did it again,'' manager Jim
Riggleman said after Sosa drove in all six runs of Wednesday's 6-3
victory. ``He wants to get in the playoffs and that's what is
driving him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa just keeps flashing that coast-to-coast smile, blasting
home runs and blowing kisses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I live a miracle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he wants to win the home-run title or make
the playoffs, Sosa said quickly, ``I would like both.'' Nobody
asked about MVP. That's a no-brainer. Put S-o-s-a on the trophy and
hand it to him now.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati manager Jack McKeon hopes a packed Wrigley and the
national media lifts his team out of a funk _ 11 defeats in 16
games. It didn't a couple of weeks ago when the Reds lost three
straight to Sosa &AMP; Friends in Wrigley, then went to St. Louis and
lost two of three to McGwire &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the excitement and fanfare in Chicago will perk us
up,'' McKeon said. ``And I'm going to tell Sosa, 'Hey, if things
get tough for us, I'm gonna walk you, buddy.'''
</P>
<P>
   While McKeon has walked McGwire several times, situations
haven't called for him to pitch around Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember any instances this year where Sammy could
beat us, so we pitched to him,'' McKeon said. ``There were several
times where McGwire could beat us or hurt us, so we walked him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is 12 for 34 (.353) against the Reds this year with a
double and four home runs _ including two off Brett Tomko, whom he
won't face, one off Scott Sullivan and one (No. 56) off Jason Bere,
whom he will face Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
