NYT-09-18-98 1012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2340 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-REVIEW-RUSH18-COX     09-18 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-REVIEW-RUSH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Review of ``Rush Hour''
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Rush Hour'' is a lame action-comedy that
proves a good rap has more punch than a good slap.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel-injected motor-mouth Chris Tucker teams with balletic
brawler Jackie Chan, who's really the top name here. But it's
Tucker who strong-arms center stage, lassoing the formula buddy
picture with his elastic tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Chan fans will be disheartened watching their hero reduced to
wooden straight man here. The congenial stunt pixie rarely gets to
demonstrate why he's Hong Kong's most adored action deity. His
famous physical pyrotechnics are snuffed for banal chop-socky
exchanges, and the end-credit outtakes reveal the worst news of
all: None of Chan's high jinks placed him anywhere near the maw of
death. Too many scenes ask Chan to act, and we all know how painful
that can be.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker plays the obligatory loose-cannon cop, whose wildly
irresponsible law enforcement tactics have landed him a demotion in
the LAPD. When the Chinese consul's young daughter is kidnapped by
a sinister crime lord, Tucker gets the flunky assignment of keeping
Chan's crack Hong Kong cop out of the hair of the FBI, which is
depicted as an inept force of nebulous evil destined to bungle
every big case.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson and Glover, er, Tucker and Chan will have none of it.
Their renegade spirits fling them smack into the eye of the
criminal storm, where Tucker's slapdash tactics collide with Chan's
contained professionalism. The resulting friction, of course, makes
potent chemistry, a righteous force the baddies aren't prepared
for. The movie tries to wring comic energy from the hackneyed clash
of East and West. But unless watching Tucker call Chan ``Mr.
Rice-a-Roni'' and Chan call a black man the ``N'' word strikes your
fancy, you'll expose the equation as just more cuddly racism from
Hollywood (see, too, ``Lethal Weapon 4'').
</P>
<P>
   And don't think the filmmakers don't know they're being racist.
They do. They just think we're too stupid to detect it as such. The
cynicism involved here is breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   If Chan disappoints, Tucker furnishes some vague pleasures. He's
a rapper par excellence, brandishing his underwear-too-tight voice
like a weapon. His rapid, serpentine prattle swirls and coils
around people like a quicksilver cobra, annoying them into
surrender. If only he had more than four funny lines.
</P>
<P>
   Why Chan gets dragged behind the Tucker hurricane is easy to
figure: Even in an action caper you can only battle bad guys in
staggered spurts; kicking people in the face takes a lot out of
you. But lips _ especially Tucker's mad puckers _ can jabber on
without pause.
</P>
<P>
   (Parenthetical kudos must be given to the film's most piercing
presence, Ken Leung, who plays vile henchman Sang with a
self-possession that nicely finesses the line between Zen placidity
and killer iciness.)
</P>
<P>
   The fear lingers _ and is fueled by this wan romp _ that Chan is
being misused in his late American phase. Where we once likened his
gonzo daredevilry to Buster Keaton by way of Gene Kelly, we're now
tempted to compare his mugging, prop-reliant antics to Carrot Top.
He spins and bludgeons foes with whatever he can get his hands on,
be it a food tray, giant rug or another body. The goofy grin
doesn't budge.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, Chan was a one-man supernova, who wrote, directed and
starred in his hugely entertaining movies. Hampered by a weak grasp
of English, his smarmy charm doesn't translate well in the
multiplex. And, at 44, he's not about to jump a motorcycle on top
of a moving train anymore. That Chan has to be yoked with a
scene-stealing co-star says it all. `Rush Hour' 2 stars Starring:
Jackie Chan, Chris Tucker Director: Brett Ratner Screenwriters: Jim
Kouf and Ross Lamanna MPAA rating: PG-13 for action-comedy
violence, language Chris Garcia is the Austin American-Statesman's
film critic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2342 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-REVIEW-THING18-CO     09-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-REVIEW-THING18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Review of ``One True Thing''
 &HT;    By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Near the end of ``One True Thing,'' Kate Gulden
(Meryl Streep) admonishes her daughter, Ellen (Renee Zellweger), to
``love what you have.'' It is one of the film's most affecting
moments because it marks a turning point between mother and
daughter, a moment of realization for Ellen as her once lovely
mother, now ravaged by inoperable cancer, speaks candidly about the
choices she made in her own life. Choices that helped Ellen to
succeed in her own way as an independent, talented and driven
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Anna Quindlen's semi-autobiographical second novel,
``One True Thing'' is an emotional movie, and it is a smart film.
An oxymoron? Hardly. As former journalist Quindlen demonstrated in
her regular columns for The New York Times, to acknowledge one's
emotions while interpreting current events and contemporary issues
is not to admit one's weaknesses. Rather, it is one way of making
the political personal, and therefore more relevant for many
people.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Gulden is a magazine writer living in New York. When her
mother is diagnosed with cancer, Ellen's father, George (William
Hurt), an esteemed professor of literature, instructs his daughter
to move back home to care for Kate. Such a move threatens Ellen's
career, but she agrees, partly out of a sense of duty and partly
out of a lifelong habit of seeking her father's approval.
</P>
<P>
   The dichotomies that exist among the Gulden family, which also
includes Ellen's younger brother Brian (Tom Everett Scott), are
familiar not because they are cliche(accent)d characters but
because these contrasts are universal among families. Ellen grows
up to be much like her scholarly father: bright, witty, a talented
writer. In her nearly absolute devotion to her father, she looks
down upon her mother, who represents little of the cerebral world
Ellen wishes to live and succeed in.
</P>
<P>
   What is refreshing about ``One True Thing'' is that it avoids
the either/or split that cripples so many debates about feminism.
The film (and the novel) is not saying that Ellen is wrong for
wanting to succeed in her career, nor is it condescending to Kate
for her desire to care for her family above all else.
</P>
<P>
   ``One True Thing'' explores the emotional landscape of a
mother-daughter relationship with patience, humor and realism.
Directed by Carl Franklin (``One False Move,'' ``Devil in a Blue
Dress'') and adapted from Quindlen's novel by Karen Croner, the
film succeeds as well as it does because of the performances by
Streep and Zellweger. Streep's dramatic talents are obvious. Less
familiar to audiences but equally appealing is her comedic ability,
and Kate's witty observations establish a subtle connection between
mother and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Although Zellweger's breakout role was as Tom Cruise's biggest
fan in ``Jerry Maguire,'' her other performances (``The Whole Wide
World'') do a better job of forecasting her range. In ``One True
Thing,'' Zellweger and Croner's script successfully capture the
schizophrenic dance that occurs when adult children, particularly
women, return home to visit their parents.
</P>
<P>
   One book reviewer wrote of Quindlen's novel that it was not
great literature, but it was a compelling story. Similarly, the
screen adaptation of ``One True Thing'' is not great cinema: The
story has its problems, such as the prologue-as-framing-device in
which Ellen is questioned about her role in her mother's death. But
``One True Thing'' is a compelling story. It is a story about
mothers and daughters and the messy, emotional bonds that nothing,
not even death, can sever completely. `One True Thing' 3 stars
Starring: Meryl Streep, Renee Zellweger, William Hurt Director:
Carl Franklin Screenwriter: Karen Croner MPAA rating: R for
language Alison Macor writes for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-09-17-98 2108E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
