<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The other kind of baseball immortality
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball is a game of long memories.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire not only faced down this year's
pitchers but generations of past players. Nobody really plays them
one game at a time. Each game projects into an eternity of
statistics, lists and stories.
</P>
<P>
   This continuity enlarges the game's best moments. Gives them
permanence. Transforms tobacco-spitting kids into immortals.
</P>
<P>
   It works the other way, too. One bad moment, one dumb move can
overshadow a career.
</P>
<P>
   Example: Fred ``Bonehead'' Merkle. So-called for a single action
that happened 90 years ago this week.
</P>
<P>
   Merkle had a solid career -- played 16 seasons, earned a .273
batting average in the dead-ball era, appeared in five World
Series. Still, his place in baseball lore comes from failing to
touch second base in a game played Sept. 23, 1908, at the Polo
Grounds before 25,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   In the 9th inning of a 1-1 pitching duel between the Chicago
Cubs and the New York Giants, two men were out and a 19-year-old
Merkle was poised on first base.
</P>
<P>
   Al Bridwell singled to center field bringing Moose McCormick
home with the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   That's what it looked like to the thousands of fans who streamed
onto the field. That's what it looked like to Merkle as he stopped
midway between bases and headed to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next would be debated years afterward. Cubs second
baseman Johnny Evers (of Tinkers-to-Evers-to-Chance fame), seeing
that Merkle hadn't reached second base, called to the center
fielder who caught the single. The outfielder couldn't pick out
Evers in the milling crowd. He threw toward him and missed.
</P>
<P>
   A Giants coach noticed and went for the ball. Evers and Joe
Tinker wrestled him for it. The coach threw the ball into the
stands where a delighted fan in a bowler caught it. Another Cubs
player chased down the bowler-guy, slugged him, recovered the
souvenir and threw it to Tinker.
</P>
<P>
   Tinker tossed it to Evers at second. The umpire said Merkle was
out. The game-winning run didn't count.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the game was declared the rarest of the things in
American baseball -- a tie. It had to be replayed. The Cubs won the
re-play and gained the 1908 National League Pennant by one game.
</P>
<P>
   New York said it was robbed. Fans and sportswriters were
apoplectic, and when not cursing the umpire, blamed one player:
Merkle.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, Merkle still was living it down.
</P>
<P>
   When he left baseball in the '20s, he moved to a place that was
the next best thing to the end of the earth -- central Florida. He
manufactured fishing gear in Daytona Beach, Fla., and became
something of a recluse.
</P>
<P>
   There was a story that he coached an Ormond Beach, Fla., team
only to walk off the field, never to return, when someone used the
word ``bonehead.''
</P>
<P>
   By the '40s he shook it off a little. He became a regular at
Florida State League games, sitting on a stool near the first-base
foul line in what is now called Jackie Robinson Ballpark. A park
that became, as fate would have it, home to the Chicago Cubs'
single-A Daytona Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   A large, quiet, kindly and introspective man, Merkle seemed
haunted and hurt the rest of his life for not touching second base
in that one game played when he was a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Kahn, a sportswriter for the Daytona Beach News-Journal,
struck up an acquaintance with Merkle, always being careful never
to allude to the 1908 season in print or in his presence. Here's
what he wrote in 1956 when Merkle died: ``Reticent Fred Merkle,
perhaps the most maligned man in the history of baseball, has gone
where the jibes of the wiseacre wolves can't hurt him anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   We live in a busier time now. We can sit in a sports bar and
follow six games in three sports on a dozen monitors pulled in by
cable and satellite. It's hard to recreate the emotions stirred 90
years ago when a city was riveted on the only game in town, one
keenly felt, heartbreakingly close race for the pennant that hinged
on a single disputed play.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has a long memory. Merkle is one of those few players
to whom it granted immortality.
</P>
<P>
   But only as a bonehead.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
