<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zippergate, think of Reno
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Americans should think of Janet Reno when are
grossed out by the Clinton-Lewinsky zippergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Parents disgusted by the need to shelter their children from the
emerging details of the White House sexcapade should think of Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Had Attorney General Reno recommended the appointment of an
independent counsel to investigate serious and credible evidence of
President Clinton's felonious corruption of America's election
laws, it's possible that the nation would have been spared the
sordid Clinton-Lewinsky scandal, at least with Clinton as
president.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though Reno is reluctant to ask for the appointment
of independent counsels. She has asked for seven independent
counsels to investigate credible evidence of law-breaking by
Clinton or his administration officials. This is the most
investigated administration in American history.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the charges that should be the easiest to
investigate and the easiest for everyone to understand, Reno has
refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
   Besides nationwide newspaper editorials (including in the
Tribune-Herald) that have urged her appoint an independent counsel
to investigate allegations of the repeated and systematic breaking
election laws, many Democratic heavyweights, including Sens. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., Russ Feingold, D-Wis., and Jay
Rockefeller, D-W.Va., have asked her appoint a special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's hard-headed refusal also is against the advice of FBI
Director Louis J. Freeh and FBI Special Agent James V. Desarno.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, former Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles G. LaBella,
who oversaw the Justice Department investigation of 1996 campaign
finance abuses, advised Reno that the law required her to seek a
special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans may be willing to overlook lying and covering up
of an adulterous Oval Office affair with a White House intern, but
it's unlikely that the public would be as dismissive of evidence
that Clinton sought dirty money to help him buy the election.
</P>
<P>
   Lies and cover-ups stemming from sex are one thing. But few
Americans tolerate lies and cover-ups when they involve money.
</P>
<P>
   If an independent prosecutor presented Congress with evidence
that Clinton engaged in a pattern of perjury, witness tampering and
obstruction of justice to cover up illegal acts designed to
influence the 1996 presidential election, few Americans would
defend him by saying that lots of politicians are corrupt and have
bought elections.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Americans have a strong bipartisan intolerance to
lies and cover-ups when they involve dirty money and underhanded
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Due to Reno's refusal to ask for an independent counsel to
investigate a lengthy list of allegations that put the White House
at the hub of an illegal fund-raising scandal, Americans may never
know if an investigation would have cleared Clinton or found
evidence of impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   We do know that Clinton turned the White House into a hot-bed
flop house as he rotated campaign contributors in and out of the
Lincoln bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   We also know the White House had a rate card that listed what
donors could get for their money. We know that Clinton ran a series
of felons, swindlers and tax-cheats in and out of the White House
along with fat cat donors, Hollywood stars and the occasional
Chinese arms-dealer and fugitive Lebanese businessman. We know that
White House telephones were used to solicit campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   We also know that Clinton himself said most of the money he
raised for his 1996 campaign was legitimate. That's like being a
little bit pregnant, except you go to jail when it involves the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever zippergate makes you ill, think of Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
