<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Struggling to keep identity, Jewish groups nourish tradition
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dipping apples in honey and chanting ancient prayers mark the
Jewish new year that begins Sunday at sundown.
</P>
<P>
   Most Jews throughout the world will eat traditional foods Sunday
night to taste the sweetness of the new year. At synagogue, they
will repent the misdeeds of the past, reciting appointed prayers
for Rosh Hashana.
</P>
<P>
   And they will begin the 10 Days of Awe leading to Yom Kippur,
the most solemn day in the Jewish year.
</P>
<P>
   But for many American Jews, these are lost traditions. They have
neglected or forgotten _ or never knew _ the ancient ways of their
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Interfaith marriages, the cornucopia of choices available in
America and the openness of American culture could weaken what
centuries of persecution could not destroy. And Jewish educators
are out to make sure that doesn't happen here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish community is struggling to hold onto its
identity,'' said Rabbi Alan Sherman, community chaplain at the
Jewish Federation in West Palm Beach, Fla. ``Society is so open and
so accepting that being Jewish now becomes a choice among other
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Carla Atkinson is typical of the dilemma confronting segments of
American Jewish life.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson, 39, moved to Palm Beach Gardens about a year ago and
has relatively few Jewish friends. Her family did not observe the
traditions of the Jewish home, and her husband, Blaine Mercereau,
is not Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   But the interfaith couple want to raise their three kids in
Jewish tradition. They want to discover the richness of a Jewish
home, keep the Sabbath and celebrate Jewish holy days.
</P>
<P>
   So, Atkinson has joined a new yearlong program that begins this
fall for about 50 young, unaffiliated, interfaith families.
</P>
<P>
   In a program called ``Around the Shabbat Table,'' they will
explore the ancient traditions and modern joys of keeping the
Sabbath from sundown each Friday until sundown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to catch people who are not in what I call the
Jewish net and may not be doing Jewish things,'' said Carolyn
Yasuna, director of the Mishpacha Family Center of the Commission
for Jewish Education in West Palm Beach. ``What we are trying to do
is give people a forum to connect with other families who do not
have a history with Shabbat but want to learn more about the
holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Groups of three or four families, children included, will share
a Sabbath meal every other month until May, Yasuna said.
</P>
<P>
   Each group will begin at the home of a trained ``mentor'' family
who will demonstrate how to keep the Sabbath. Then, each family in
the group will host a Sabbath evening throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, four workshops will teach Jewish Sabbath rituals,
cooking, songs and traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no more beautiful time for a Jewish family than
Friday evening,'' said Barbara Steinberg, the executive director of
the Commission for Education and principal of the Meyer Jewish
Academy in West Palm Beach. ``The love of parents and children is
obvious. The importance of Jewish traditions is primary.''
</P>
<P>
   But the danger of losing that way of life is real. By some
estimates, nearly 85 percent of the Jewish community in South
Florida is not affiliated with a temple or synagogue, Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary freedom possible in America has taken a heavy
toll on the traditional patterns of Jewish life. A highly mobile
society tends to separate families that once formed close-knit
communities. Intermarriage can weaken the resolve to keep one's
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we suffer assimilation from the freedom this country
allows,'' Sherman said. ``Not that I want it any other way. Jewish
people come into contact with others very freely. We've been
welcomed into many groups where we were not previously.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes it harder to keep Jewish customs and meet Jewish
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie and Jeff Garelick have been married for 10 months,
recently moved to Jupiter and want to connect with the Jewish
community. They joined a newly formed havurah, a small group that
meets monthly to study and observe Jewish life together.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Jewish Community Center in West Palm Beach,
five havurahs flourish. Each includes about 15 couples who meet for
two years with a trained coordinator and, thereafter, meet as the
group decides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found couples who are often isolated, without family,
busy and unable to find social connections,'' said Charlotte Kula
from Boca Raton, who with her husband, Morton, are havurah
coordinators. ``With both working, you come home. You eat dinner.
You watch TV. You get on the Web. Other people just aren't
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Federation of South Palm Beach County in Boca Raton
also offers programs to preserve and celebrate Jewish life.
</P>
<P>
   One innovative club is designed for Jewish teens and meets after
school at Omni middle school and Spanish River High School in Boca
Raton.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the club, JIST, stands for ``Jewish identity scene
for teens.'' It is modeled after Christian groups that meet on
school property before and after school hours.
</P>
<P>
   The club was formed to attract teens who were bar or bat mitzvah
as youngsters but have not been to synagogue since.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are probably not affiliated and their parents probably
aren't either,'' said Ken Swart, speaking for the South County
Commission for Jewish Education. ``The club is designed to re-spark
Judaism in them.''
</P>
<P>
   The club wants to attract older kids. Kathryn Kesler wants her
children to discover their Jewish roots at home before they are old
enough for school.
</P>
<P>
   But Kiley, 6, and Lindsey, 4, live in a very different world
than Jewish kids did a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kesler, 36, who lives in Jupiter, remembers the stories of happy
Sabbath dinners when she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   She can almost smell the table laden with traditional foods. She
can see, in her mind's eye, the extended family gathered around it,
hear their laughter and feel their support.
</P>
<P>
   Today, members of her family live in four other states. She has
an interfaith marriage, and her kids are exposed to the unrelenting
demands of a non-Jewish culture.
</P>
<P>
   So, her family is gathering ``Around the Shabbat Table'' for the
program in Jewish customs. They hope to preserve the roots of their
faith and assure its future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to meet with other people who have shared traditions
and show our kids what Shabbat and other holidays are about,''
Kesler said.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS OF ROSH HASHANA
</P>
<P>
   Rosh Hashana begins at sunset Sunday to mark the beginning of
the Jewish year 5759. The holiday lasts for two days for Orthodox
and Conservative Jews, one day for Reform Jews. Rosh Hashana is
Hebrew for head of the year. Here are the holiday's customs:
</P>
<P>
   _ THE RITUAL focuses on leaving the old year and entering the
new.
</P>
<P>
   _ IT BEGINS 10 days of repentance called the Days of Awe that
culminate with Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
   _ JEWS PRAY to be inscribed in the Book of Life for the coming
year. They take stock of their sins, examine their commitment to
repentance and affirm their faith in God's mercy.
</P>
<P>
   _ THE SHOFAR (ram's horn) is blown during synagogue services as
an expression of God's sovereignty, his role in history and the
people's faith in the future.
</P>
<P>
   _ DURING ONE CEREMONY, Tashlich (Hebrew for throw), Jews toss
bread crumbs into a body of water to symbolize casting away their
sins from the past year.
</P>
<P>
   _ HOLIDAY FOODS include honey and apples to symbolize hope for a
sweet new year.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: The Jewish Theological Seminary, New York
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
