<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharp and the 'Truth Squad' squabble
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Comptroller John Sharp, who is running for lieutenant
governor, is battling accusations by Republican backers of his
opponent, Agriculture Commissioner Rick Perry, that his claims of
having saved the state $8.5 billion over the past seven years are
grossly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   A trio of GOP legislators who've dubbed themselves ``The Truth
Squad'' have been meeting with newspaper editorial boards,
brandishing a thick book they say proves Sharp, who gained a
national reputation with his performance reviews of state agencies,
has inflated the amount the state saved by implementing his
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth Squad came through here several days ago. (A Sharp
spokesman jokingly refers to them as The Goon Squad.)
</P>
<P>
   All three GOP legislators were earnest, intelligent and
determined to convince me Sharp's claims are exaggerated. Then,
they hoped (but didn't say), I would write an editorial saying just
that, which would end up being used in a political commercial.
</P>
<P>
   It's happened before. Once I was lying in bed in a hotel room in
Austin as an election neared, about half asleep, when I heard a TV
political commercial that used one of my editorials to convince
voters what a wonderful fellow this particular candidate was. I
can't remember anymore who it was, or if they even won. And I
wonder how many voters in Austin were swayed by a TV commercial
touting this little newspaper's editorial. Darned few, I suspect.
</P>
<P>
   What made this latest foray by these backers of Rick Perry a bit
novel is that:
</P>
<P>
   -- All three legislators admitted voting for all of Sharp's
recommendations. The only exceptions were that two of the
legislators haven't been in office the entire time, but they did
back his recommendations in the last session, and say if they had
been in the Legislature at the time they would have voted for the
earlier recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   -- Further, all three said they would vote for those proposals
if they had it to do over again.
</P>
<P>
   -- None of them made any secret about backing Rick Perry, or
being Republicans. They're being sponsored by the Associated
Republicans of Texas, a group that Sharp says tried hard to get him
to switch parties after lavishly praising his performance reviews.
There was no attempt at subterfuge, at least concerning which horse
they're backing, and who's paying the bills.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers over whether some of Sharp's ideas are
really ``savings,'' as he claims in his campaign material and out
on the stump. Some of his proposals included putting off paying
state bills for a week, or maybe a fiscal quarter. Some
recommendations meant raising money off increased fees and
licenses. Sharp recommended being more aggressive at getting money
out of the federal government for school meal programs as a way to
cut state costs. And, he pushed a spate of cuts in spending -- far
more than were actually implemented by the Legislature, which had
the ultimate power to act on Sharp's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Gang of Three say that while they supported Sharp's
ideas, many of them aren't really ``savings,'' as Sharp claims. For
example, they contend putting off paying bills until a later time
isn't a savings because the bill still has to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   I called the Sharp campaign to get a response. The next day,
Sharp called back to defend his program. As might be expected, he
has a different interpretation. His contention is that if the cuts,
delayed payments and other measures weren't enacted during a
particular session, taxes would have been raised. Putting off
payments kept taxes from being raised, and luckily the economy
improved enough in the interim to allow the state to make the added
payments the following year, or quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, if we hadn't done these programs, we
would have spent $8.5 billion more than we did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp admits it could have gone the other way, if the economy
hadn't improved when it did. ``It was a wing and a prayer,'' he
said. Remember, all this started in 1991, when the state faced
sizable deficits and a sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp points out he recommended far more cuts than were enacted,
which is one reason he had to use some money management tricks to
tide the state over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're (state legislators) the ones who decided they couldn't
stomach the cuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He makes a persuasive case, especially when he points out
legislators, Republican and Democrat alike, praised him to high
heaven when his recommendations kept legislators from having to
consider that ol' bugabear, a state income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sure never complained (back then),'' he said, adding the
performance reviews were often praised as ``the best thing since
sliced bread.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know for sure if Sharp can prove to the penny that he
saved the state $8.5 billion in seven years. But I'm personally
unpersuaded by the Gang of Three's road show, especially since they
all backed Sharp's ideas and say they would do it again.
</P>
<P>
   As an aside, I asked Sharp if he thought President Clinton's
travails would hurt him and other Democrats; he doesn't think so,
but he has no plans to get up on a stage with the embattled
president during this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to explain to my children why I'm up there with
him,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a smart politician to me.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
