<HEADER>
A2353 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PROTEST19-COX     09-18 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROTEST19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohioans protest: ``Adulterers end up in hell''
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington and Laura Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI , Ohio _ It took Bill Clinton's sexual turmoil to put
the civic spirit into Debbie Graham and Peggy Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The two, from nearby Kenwood, Ohio, stood in a warm, drizzling
rain in a crowd of about 150 protesters recently near a Amberley
Village home where Bill Clinton visited for a $5,000 per plate
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   They had never protested anything in public before, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called her today and said 'I'm angry' and she said she was
angry, too,'' said Graham, 43.
</P>
<P>
   The two were not alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about sex; this is about honor,'' said Jane Thole,
a homemaker from suburban Sycamore.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a crowd filled with veteran protestors were
dozens of people who said Clinton's behavior with Monica Lewinsky
infuriated them so much they came to shout their outrage in public
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Their signs were blunt:
</P>
<P>
   ``Resign''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is unfit for any public office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Adulterers end up in Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said Clinton's affair with Lewinsky and the public
turmoil it has created has made her job more difficult trying to
raise her son to respect women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of mothers who are dealing with these very
difficult issues,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The new protestors found strange bedfellows with the others,
most anti-abortion protestors, who unfurled religious banners and
held large, graphic photographs of fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   A protesting regular, who would not give his name but said he
had picketed hundreds of abortion clinics, looked around. ``There
are a lot of people here I have never seen before,'' he said. ``New
faces. It's real good.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's dark-windowed limousine and its caravan whisked past
the group in less than a minute, serenaded with the angry shouts of
``Time to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the home of attorney Stanley Chesley, Clinton helped
raise an estimated $250,000 for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, eating lunch with about 50 people including
Cincinnati Mayor Roxanne Qualls, who is running for Congress, and
Ohio Democratic Party Chairman David Leland.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told them the money raised would help get Qualls and
other Democrats elected to Congress. He alluded only briefly to the
Lewinsky scandal, talking instead about work that needs to be done
to strengthen the economy and the nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary and I are fine,'' he said. ``We're working on what we
need to work on. We are doing fine.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Chesley's home, Clinton made unscheduled visits in
downtown Cincinnati, dropping in at the Findlay Market for about 20
minutes, shaking hands and saying hello to the 100 patrons there,
then crossing the street for a bowl of Tex-Mex chili.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an experience for me because I knew the chili was good
but I didn't know it was that good,'' said Greg Magruder, co-owner
of the Gold Star Chili on Race Street. ``It was an experience I'll
probably never get over in my life _ to meet a person of that
magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Magruder answered the president's questions about how he got
into the restaurant business and served Clinton a 3-ounce bowl of
chili and cup of Maxwell House decaf. ``He seemed to enjoy it,''
Magruder said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was becoming well fed; in his remarks an hour earlier at
the Chesley fund-raiser Clinton said he had eaten so much he was
feeling a little sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   Magruder said Secret Service agents ate at the restaurant on
Wednesday and asked questions without identifying themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Magruder plans to hang the photo of him and the president in the
restaurant as well as in his home.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kroeger of Kroeger &AMP; Sons Meats in the Findlay Market said
Clinton received cheers from most of the people around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of neat to see. It was good for the neighborhood.
It made people here feel special,'' Kroeger said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
