A2359 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BROMELL1     09-18 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BROMELL19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dolphins aren't fed a line_just a lineman
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Some NFL rookies take their newfound wealth and
stockpile cars. A Porsche for Monday. A Mercedes for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Lorenzo Bromell. He has loaded up on baseball
caps. Not different caps, mind you. Just New York Yankees' caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the Bronx, 20 blocks from Yankee Stadium,'' he
explained. ``It's in my blood.''
</P>
<P>
   New York to Miami. It's hardly an unusual journey. But the path
Bromell took to get where he is today _ a fourth-round pick who
suddenly looks like the steal of the NFL draft _ is different.
</P>
<P>
   His journey included high school in a small South Carolina town,
5:30 a.m. wakeup calls at a military school in Georgia, and,
finally, two years at Clemson University _ all of which went
virtually unnoticed by NFL scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to tell people about him,'' said Reggie Herring,
Clemson defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was trying to convince people to look past the fact
that Bromell didn't have 285 pounds on his 6-foot-6 frame, that he
``only'' weighed 265. Herring tried putting into words what made
Bromell special, what had made Clemson alumni repeatedly come up to
the coaching staff and say, ``We love that 99.'' But even as
Herring was uttering the words, he knew they sounded like hyperbole
and cliche.
</P>
<P>
   (ITALICS) ``He's so fast he can pluck a rooster while he's
chasing it. ... He works hard every day, every snap. ... He loves
to play.'' (END)
</P>
<P>
   As Herring tossed out this praise, he could see the scouts' eyes
glaze over. They had heard it all before. Another kid who plays
really hard. Yeah, yeah. Probably gives 110 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all figured I was just another coach trying to sell one
of my kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came the guy who gave Herring his first coaching job
back at Oklahoma State: Jimmy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson figured Herring wouldn't feed him a line. He looked at
the tapes of Bromell. He saw a player who lived in the opponents'
backfield. So on draft day Johnson waited until the fourth round.
Then, as the Baltimore Ravens were on the phone talking to Bromell,
telling him they were going to draft him, Johnson traded a fourth-
and fifth-round pick to Philadelphia. The move was only 10 spots.
But Johnson calls it the second-best trade he's ever made _ behind
the one that landed Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Bromell missed the season opener with a knee sprain. But in his
NFL debut, he sacked Buffalo quarterback Rob Johnson twice. That,
combined with his play in preseason, has made believers around the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all coming back and saying, `Boy, we blew it on that
Bromell kid,''' Herring said. ``(Johnson) got a Wal-Mart special.
... He paid 35 cents and got a kid that I guarantee they're having
a hard time keeping off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Bromell off the field has been a problem ever since that
Saturday morning when Rita Bromell took her son to sign up for
Little League football. He fell in love with the game instantly.
Kept telling his mom he was going to be a football player. She was
more worried about other things _ like an education, and how he was
going to get one in New York.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Rita Bromell knows all about the New York Public School
System. She has been working as school security officer for 17
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lock up kids every day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, when it came time for her second son to enter high
school, she shipped him to Georgetown, S.C., the small town where
she and her ex-husband grew up, the place where Lorenzo's father
still lived and worked in a steel mill.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, violence had become a part of Bromell's life. He
shrugs when asked about the time he got mugged _ then explains it
was hardly one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get used to it,'' he said. ``It sounds funny, but you get
used to it. You see it. You end up doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   To take him away from that, his mother sent him South. That
started the process. But it didn't complete it. That required two
occurences. First, he failed to meet academic requirements to play
Division I football. Second, he met Robert Nunn.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn is the football coach at Georgia Military College, a small
two-year college located in Milledgeville, Ga. It is a school where
the football players used to get up at 5:30 a.m. _ now they get to
sleep to 6 a.m. _ put on a military uniform and begin a highly
structured day. Classes. Morning formation. Study hall. Meetings.
The only free time is the 45 minutes before the 10:30 p.m. lights
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were more schools like GMC, there'd be a lot less
jails,'' Nunn said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say Bromell was headed to jail. The problem, Nunn
recalls, was that he didn't seem to be headed anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed direction,'' he said. ``My wife tutored him. She
said right away, `Lorenzo is plenty smart enough. He just needs
some guidance.'''
</P>
<P>
   He got that from Nunn, who played for Johnson and Dolphins tight
end coach Pat Jones at Oklahoma State. Nunn laughs when he recalls
some of the talks he had with Bromell during Bromell's freshman
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wore out my size 12 Nikes a few times,'' he said. ``But
eventually something clicked. It was like there was a switch. And
once it was flipped, it stayed on.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still on.
</P>
<P>
   He has made it to the NFL and he is doing everything Nunn and
Herring said he would. He is making cliches come true every day in
practice. And afterward, he is slipping into a New York Yankees'
cap. The first-place Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life,'' he said, ``is grand.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
