<SLUG> BC-FBN-LONGHORNS-NYC19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longhorns fight the odds
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Manhattan is the land of opportunity, with or
without a little help from Vernon Jordan. In 1626, an enterprising
Peter Minuit flagged down some passing locals, plied them with
beads, cloth and trinkets worth an estimated $24, and walked away
with the whole island.
</P>
<P>
   OK, different Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan where the Texas Longhorns will venture September
19 has transportation woes _ they're trying to figure out where to
put the bike paths _ and it's nickname officially is the Apple. The
Little Apple.
</P>
<P>
   There lurk the Kansas State Wildcats, bullies of the weak,
untested claimants to the title of the nation's best.
</P>
<P>
   There, for the Longhorns, lurks opportunity. To get crushed,
humilated, ripped apart _ yes.
</P>
<P>
   To find out what they've got _ you bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's giving us a chance,'' Coach Mack Brown said. ``I told
the team the other day their nickname should be, 'Against All
Odds.'''
</P>
<P>
   Little is expected from the Longhorns defense, which would have
to play far above its collective heads to remain competitive
against a Wildcats offense that has a quarterback and kicker who
can hit the deep ball better than Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   And they probably really haven't shown anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   Brown marveled over the Wildcats' 59-7 halftime lead against
Northern Illinois. ``That game plan didn't even get to the second
page,'' he said. ``Not even to the second column.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Longhorns' opportunity comes in. If the Horns
can match up to the 25-point favorite Wildcats anywhere, it is on
offense, even with redshirt freshman Major Applewhite getting his
first career start.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the only running back with a 100-yard game against
the Wildcats was Nebraska's Ahman Green, who ripped them for 193.
Ohio was the only other team with success running on KSU last year,
utilizing an option attack and losing only 23-20 in the season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   So far this season, the Wildcats have faced two option teams.
They dismantled both. They haven't even shown much of their blitz
packages. They will Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bode well for the Horns and their West Coast
offense, even though KSU plays an overshifted front similar to
UCLA's, and the Horns had moderate success against the Bruins, who
are good, but not at KSU's level.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have time for miscommunication or a slow start,''
said tackle Jay Humphrey. ``We have to go after it from the get
go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose, we won't be slaughtered,'' Horns halfback Ricky
Williams said. ``If we're slaughtered, it'll be because we beat
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Williams said, ``For me to win the Heisman,
the team has to go out and win the rest of our games, or close to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Horns to win their next game, Williams needs to be even
more powerful, more elusive, a better blocker and a more competent
receiver than he has in any game he's played at Texas. And he must
do it against a defense he lumps with the '95 Oklahoma and Texas
A&AMP;M defenses as the best he's faced. Williams averaged .5 yards a
carry against the Sooners, but against the Aggies he averaged 11.6.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because of (Kansas State's) linebackers,'' Williams said.
``They're aggressive, hit, take pride in playing defense, and
they're fast. They come after you.''
</P>
<P>
   So it's a challenge, a mano-a-mano confrontation, whose pads get
lower, whose legs stop driving last . . . something to relish,
right Ricky?
</P>
<P>
   ``It really depends on who the line blocks,'' Williams said.
``If they don't block well, I won't like going up against them.''
</P>
<P>
   For Williams, every play will look like a Wildcats team picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always outnumber you,'' offensive coordinator Greg Davis
said. ``Their philosphy is to outnumber the run. We have to do
things, formation-wise, to establish the run. The key is to make
sure Ricky knows where the extra guy is.''
</P>
<P>
   And he must beat him. Flanker Kwame Cavil, who will have to make
the most of the passes he sees on Saturday, has the right idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a receiver you want them to stack it up, because then it's
you and the corner, how bad you want to beat them, how bad they
don't want to get beat,'' he said. ``When it's one-on-one it's his
heart on yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get that, too. We'll see eight on the line . . . nine .
. . 10 . . . 11 . . . 12 . . . however many they can put there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
