<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tame hockey takes over rink
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ Remember the joke about the guy who went to the
fights and returned home to report that a hockey game broke out?
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the new $185 million home of the Florida Panthers
are probably more concerned that fans will leave their rink talking
about the heated croquet match that ignited.
</P>
<P>
   The days of going to a hockey game and getting intimately
acquainted with the beer breath and body odor of the fan in the
next seat have come to a screeching halt for some. Just listen to
the latest point-of-sale buzzwords pitched to corporate patrons of
the new National Car Rental Center: `
</P>
<P>
   `Segregated from the general population.''
</P>
<P>
   In a press tour Thursday, managers for the Panthers' impressive
new digs explained how the almost 4,000 club-level and
executive-level patrons will park their cars under the arena in
private lots, be met by a concierge and whisked quickly up four or
five flights in private elevators to private rooms with private
seating equipped with private bathrooms. Private bars (with private
bartenders) and private catering is par for the course. In-house
business centers provide access to fax machines and computers, and
private media rooms are nearby if the big deal is cinched.
</P>
<P>
   And if your corporate customer wants a smoke, there are private
outdoor patios for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Beer and pretzels? You'd be slumming it. The catered menu in the
private suites, leased for $70,000 to $120,000 a year, include
herb-encrusted salmon, pulled pork and boeuf bourguignon carving
stations, sushi, fruit salad and 18 different types of desserts _
all made on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   The upscale facility is the most recent example of the new wave
of sports complexes competing for the same buck. Facility managers
know the way to break into the black after eight-digit investments
is to tap the vast corporate entertainment dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual suites have become more entertainment venues than
just sports facilities,'' said Michael Thompson, president of
Boston Concessions Group, which provides food for the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting the suite patrons to pay $25 to $30 a head (on
food) and the general public to spend between $7 and $10 on
concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend of upscale arenas and ballparks started in the late
'80s with sequestered seating and has taken off ever since. The
972,000-square-foot National Car Rental Center, with three function
rooms that can be rented out for anything from conventions to
weddings, is designed to maximize tangential profits.
</P>
<P>
   The arena was built in just 26 months. The Panthers, owned by
businessman H. Wayne Huizenga, are moving from the Miami Arena,
which they shared with the Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise, which came up with $34 million in incentives, was
chosen from among six sites. To pay for the new digs, Broward
County sold $185 million in bonds. The arena's $13.4 million debt
will be covered by rent (the team will pay $3.4 million annually),
Broward County's hotel tax and the state sales tax rebate. A study
in 1995 by Arthur Andersen estimated the arena would generate $87
million in annual fan spending.
</P>
<P>
   National Car Rental Center will seat 19,088 for Panthers games.
It also features The Lexus Lounge, The Budweiser Terrace and
Stanley's Shoot Twice sports bar, a high-class pub with faux
panther-claw scratches on the glass tables. The pub is open only to
the upper echelon of clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Situated to take advantage of the Broward, Dade and Palm Beach
County markets, the arena offers a good view of the Fort Lauderdale
skyline, the Sawgrass Mills Outlet Mall and the Everglades from the
upper patios.
</P>
<P>
   Though the seat covers for Joe Sixpack aren't leather and the
armrests are plastic, not wood, the sight lines from every section
are exceptionally good. Even the nosebleed seats offer an excellent
view: Just 95 feet above the rink, compared with 250 feet at other
stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Hot dogs ($3.50) and beer ($4.50-$5) are on sale at the public
concession but so is conch chowder ($3.50) and chicken Caesar salad
($5.50).
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices for Panther games start at $14 and go up to $65,
but parking is $10 for each of the 4,787 general spaces. Suite and
club seat parking is $15. There are a total of 7,600 spaces,
including 95 disabled spots. The lot is lighted, and officials say
every space is within a seven-minute walk of the center.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibition hockey games will be played at the center Sept. 27
and Oct. 1. Celine Dion will play Oct. 3, and Elton John is
scheduled for the following day.
</P>
<P>
   The facility also will house boxing matches, basketball
tournaments, arena football (AFL South Florida Bobcats) and indoor
soccer (the Florida Thundercats), ice shows, circuses and
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   And as far as potty parity is concerned, Huizenga kept his word
when he promised two years ago that the new facility wouldn't have
any of the long lines at women's restrooms so common at arenas.
There are 274 toilets for women and total of 226 toilets and
urinals for men. Both are NHL records.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
