<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Starr Report, Fanny Hill and the dangers of pornography
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reading the Starr Report, skimming and skipping to get to all
the good parts, I couldn't help but feel as if I had read all of
this before. Nothing in the recent past, to be sure, but sometime.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit me. As a blossoming teenager (and I use that term
loosely) I had uncovered a copy of Fanny Hill, an 18th century
novel by John Cleland underneath my parents' bed.
</P>
<P>
   Starr Report; Fanny Hill. Much the same. The writing is better
in Fanny Hill, but there are more good parts in the Starr Report.
I'd call it a toss-up.
</P>
<P>
   (Which brings me to an aside. Why would any parent who wanted to
hide anything put it under their bed? It is the first place
children look. No, if you want to hide something put it smack dab
in the middle of the bookcase where it will be totally safe from
the observation of children. Put math books under your bed. It
might be the only way to get your kids to study.)
</P>
<P>
   In any case , reading Fanny Hill was a revelation for me. Well,
it was in a way. Unfortunately, I couldn't tell all that much about
what was going on in Fanny Hill.
</P>
<P>
   I recognized the word ``bosoms'' which, for a 13-year-old, is
pretty much all I needed to know. I had no idea what ``tumescence''
meant or the dozens of other high-class words Cleland used to write
what essentially was porn. Funny, but once I was old enough to
understood the words, I had no desire to read the book.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between Fanny Hill and the Starr Report is, of
course, that what my parents called filth, kids today have another
word for: Homework.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the first time in the history of the Republic that
everyone in civics class actually completes a reading assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is we're going to have to convince all those boys
to just say no to cigars.
</P>
<P>
   What I hope is that pornography, whether from your dirty book
store or direct from your government, doesn't become a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I can tell you a story of woe what happened to a friend
of mine when she and her husband ventured into the seedy world of
pornography and literally found the world crashing down around
them.
</P>
<P>
   It began so innocently, as such things usually do. My friend and
her husband were getting frisky one night and began talking about
watching a dirty movie. Her husband allowed as how he had never
seen one (which sounds a bit fishy to me). My friend said she
hadn't either but was willing to try anything once.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, had they only known what the future would hold.
</P>
<P>
   What they did know was that the local video store rented porn of
the ``soft'' variety, just a little bit more risque than you might
find on HBO. They hopped in the car and made it down to the store,
which was uncommonly busy for being so late at night.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the dilemma. Which one of them would actually get the
movie from the shelf? Then, once pulled from the shelf, who would
present it to the clerk for actual rental? They negotiated back and
forth and, having a good marriage, they decided to share the
responsibility. My friend would quickly grab the movie and her
husband would actually check it out. This did not make it any
easier for my friend to do the grabbing,
</P>
<P>
   especially since there was a large sign above the area that said
``Adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she had a plan. She would walk backwards to the section
and then, lo and behold, just be there. It would not be necessary
to actually pick and movie, since all pornography is essentially
the same. She would grab the first box she found and get out.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the plan worked perfectly. She sauntered
sideways and backwards until she was standing by the adult movies
but actually looking out toward the middle of the store. She
reached up quickly and grabbed the first video she put her hands
on.
</P>
<P>
   That is when it happened -- blame it on fate, a higher power, or
even termites. Because at the exact moment my friend reached up and
took that movie, the entire shelf of pornography gave way. That
shelf fell upon the next shelf, which also gave way, which fell
upon the next shelf and the next.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust cleared a few moments later, my friend was holding
one tape of pornography and standing in the middle of dozens of
other tapes, lying at her feet.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the entire store saw and heard the whole thing,
people asking her, in a standoffish kind of way, if she had been
hurt. Several of them undoubtedly noted that she was an education
official with the local adult learning program.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband was nowhere to be found, having fled the store as
the avalanche began. Needless to say, she was not feeling romantic
that night. Fortunately, their marriage survived this brief brush
with pornography, but remember their experience if you should ever
be tempted.
</P>
<P>
   Because porn weakens not only moral fiber, but apparently wood
fibers, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
