r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BUCKEYES-GERMANY1     09-18 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BUCKEYES-GERMANY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Germany becomes Buckeye amid media scrutiny
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Sporting a bright lime-green T-shirt,
glow-in-the-dark sneakers and Nike ballcap with neon green swoosh,
Reggie Germany stood out at a recent interview like Dennis Rodman
would at an accountants' convention.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the blend-into-the-woodwork posture the
St. Louis, Mo., native tried to take two years ago when he shunned
his home state school to sign with Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, one of four top wide receivers at the Buckeyes'
disposal this season, whipped the Missouri Tigers and their fans
into a temporary frenzy in 1996 when he verbally committed to their
program in December, then reneged on his decision three weeks later
to sign with OSU.
</P>
<P>
   Germany said he initially said yes to the Tigers to stay close
to home. But after his mother told him to do what was best for him,
he decided OSU, with its history of producing NFL receivers, was
the better choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he changed his mind, we were sick,'' Missouri coach Larry
Smith said. ``We got a lot of heat for losing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one felt the heat as much as Germany, a prep
All-America at Hazlewood East High School who had to endure the
phone calls and questions and media scrutiny that surrounded his
decision to become a Buckeye.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a good three weeks where he was really down with
it,'' Germany's mother, Jeannette, said. ``There was a lot of
criticism. They kind of bad-mouthed him on some of the radio
stations. But I told him, 'You have to make your decision and then
you have to live with it.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Germany, a 6-2, 195-pound sophomore backup to
starting OSU receivers Dee Miller and David Boston, has done. But
with No. 21 Missouri visiting Ohio Stadium on Saturday, the
questions cropped up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have a lot of people looking at me to see if this
was the right place for me,'' said Germany, whose only reception
last season came against Missouri in a 31-10 Buckeye victory. ``I'm
not trying to go out and prove people wrong or have a big game.
I'll get more satisfaction out of my team winning the game than me
having big individual stats.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with a year under his belt and an impressive
two-touchdown performance against Toledo last week, Germany said
he's finally at peace with his decision.
</P>
<P>
   `` I wanted to be a better receiver and I felt that with
(Missouri's option quarterback) Corby Jones being there, I wasn't
going to get a good chance to be the best possible receiver I could
be,'' he said. ``I'm happy, very happy that I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   OSU coach John Cooper is, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably in terms of all around play _ blocking, recognizing
the defense, making adjustments, running the right routes and all
that kind of stuff _ he's as good as any receiver we have,
including David Boston and Dee Miller,'' Cooper said. ``He's been a
very dependable receiver for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State receivers coach Chuck Stobart said it's just a matter
of time before Germany works his way into a starter's role. Germany
said he's looking forward to that _ as long as he can maintain his
low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt this would be the place where I could live my life and
get away from a lot of the fame that I had at home,'' he said. ``I
just want to be an ordinary person.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
