</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-ANDERSON19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson needs ``A'' against Packers to make Pro Bowl
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ If Bengals right tackle Willie Anderson plans
to reach his goal of making the Pro Bowl, then he needs an A on his
Sunday exam.
</P>
<P>
   All he has to do is block one of the most feared and revered
linemen in NFL history _ Packers' left defensive end Reggie White,
a 14-year veteran and the league's career sacks leader with 179.5.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 300-pound White, who earned a record 12th straight
Pro Bowl trip in 1997, turned in a dominant three-sack performance
in the Packers' 23-15 victory over Tampa Bay last week, beating
Buccaneers' tackle Jerry Wunsch at least a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   That Bengals quarterback Neil O'Donnell isn't among the 64
quarterbacks sacked by White only adds to the pressure on the 6-5,
340-pound Anderson, the Bengals' top pick (10th overall) in the
1996 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bengals offensive line coach Paul Alexander was moved to tears
talking about Anderson's matchup against White.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have one heck of a right tackle,'' Alexander said.
``We're going to find out just what kind of right tackle we've got.
I'm kind of choked up about it already. We've been talking about
this game for quite a while. I can't wait to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Anderson, ``I grew up a fan of Reggie White. I watched him
for 10 years. He's probably the best defensive end to ever play the
game. He's great and that's it. That's the only comment I'm going
to give you about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People around here _ when we play against a great player _
tend to put a little more added pressure on. That's why I'm not
going to mention it any more. He's Reggie White and it's a big
game. There's a sold-out crowd. It's pressure, but it's another
game.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes White so good?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much he can come at you with,'' said Bengals
defensive end Clyde Simmons, White's teammate at Philadelphia from
1986-92. ``He's strong enough to run over you. He's fast enough to
run by you. And he's quick enough that he can make you miss. That's
the difference between him and a lot of players in this business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the measuring stick as to where you are as a player.
Willie understands he's going to have to play one of his best games
ever. He's going to play Reggie hard and clean and do his best.
That's all I can ask. He's going to come out all right.''
</P>
<P>
   White generated controversy in the offseason when he made some
remarks to Wisconsin lawmakers that offended gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes great courage to speak your mind,'' Simmons said.
``He was just saying what he believes. He's probably the most
loving man, the most genuine, giving man that you could ever
meet.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the football field, White's a true warrior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an unbelievable player,'' Packers quarterback Brett Favre
said. ``We've run out of adjectives to say about Reggie White. He's
a class act on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``To watch what he did Sunday is something you can look back on
in 20 to 30 years and tell your kids and grandkids what a feat that
was. He took young guys and handled them like they were little
kids. As I told Reggie: 'You took 'em to school.' It was really
fascinating to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   White announced his retirement in the offseason, then changed
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he made the decision to play again,'' Packers coach Mike
Holmgren said, ``he dove into this offseason program and really is
in as good a shape as he's been in in five or six years. He showed
he's a force to be reckoned with still. I'm glad he changed his
mind and unretired.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
