<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREX-PROBLEMS19-COX     09-18 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREX-PROBLEMS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forex Intenational Inc. faces financial troubles
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson, John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ His company is closed. Lawsuits are piling up.
State and federal investigators are looking into claims of
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But Russell Erxleben, former University of Texas football great
turned foreign-currency trader, wants the world to know he isn't
running away.
</P>
<P>
   In a five-minute press conference filled with concerned
investors looking for answers, Erxleben said his Austin Forex
International Inc. has experienced trading losses because of world
currency instability.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't offer angry investors any answers about what is
left of their money _ some say the company had as much as $60
million in investors' money _ or what he will do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past few days there's been a lot of speculation, a
lot of accusations concerning my stealing client money and running
off,'' Erxleben said. ``I'm here. I'm not running anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he decided last Friday to stop trading foreign
currencies, and on Sunday he met with attorneys and Michael
Shapiro, a former officer in the company who now runs a trading
company that has Austin Forex as a customer. He said he directed
Shapiro to keep the office open and send a letter explaining the
situation to investors.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Erxleben, Shapiro told an assistant to close
the office and tell other employees not to come to work. A
spokesman for Shapiro declined to comment on Erxleben's assertions.
</P>
<P>
   Closing the office, Erxleben indicated, has fueled confusion,
concern and rumors about himself and the company that he said are
untrue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story has gotten to a point that yesterday afternoon my
little girl came home from school and said, ``'Daddy, why did you
steal everybody's money?' ``My little boy at breakfast this morning
said, ``Mommy, I wish I could be in heaven right now,''' Erxleben
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These false stories and reports have got to stop,'' he said.
``I'm telling you they will stop. I have nothing more to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, when Erxleben's company closed its doors, he has
been at the center of a firestorm. The Texas State Securities Board
is investigating him and his company, and so is the Federal Bureau
of Investigation. Meanwhile, investors and former partners have
filed several suits against the former All-American kicker and his
company. and even Erxleben's attorney says it could take weeks
before they figure out what is left of the company. On the same day
that Erxleben was attempting to quell rumors that he has left town
with investors' funds, a group of 16 investors in Erxleben's
foreign currency trading activities filed suit in Austin, claiming
they were defrauded out of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The two lawyers who filed the suit Friday said they each had
invested hundreds of thousands of dollars, as part of an estimated
$3 million to $5 million the entire group invested.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Polotko, one of the two Houston attorneys who filed the
suit _ and one of the 16 in the investment group _ claims he was
planning to travel to Austin to meet with Erxleben on Tuesday. But
Austin Forex closed its doors on Monday and hasn't reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Named as a defendant in Polotko's suit was Bradford D. Keene,
who filed a suit against Erxleben and others earlier this week
claiming he was lured by Exrleben through ``intentional
misrepresentations and false promises'' to invest in ownership of
Austin Forex.
</P>
<P>
   Others defendants named in Polotko's petition are Erxleben,
Shapiro, David McGee, and E-Forex, a separate California company
that worked with Austin Forex.
</P>
<P>
   The suit claims Austin Forex traded foreign currencies using
E-Forex and had accounts at Bank of America. The investors are
seeking an injunction prohibiting the transfer of any of their
funds from Bank of America or E-Forex. According to Polotko and
David Slaughter, another attorney who filed the suit, between 600
and 800 people have invested in Austin Forex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We and our clients would like to know as current investors
what happened to the money,'' said Slaughter, who also is one of
the 16 investors in the group.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't the only ones.
</P>
<P>
   One of the investors who came to Thursday's press conference to
hear Erxleben with hopes of learning more about what's happened to
her money was Lynn Alexander-Mints.
</P>
<P>
   She said she gave $240,000 to Austin Forex to invest in foreign
currencies, but fears it is all gone now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost everything I own,'' said Alexander-Mints. ``I mortgaged
my home. I have children that are going to college next year and I
don't know how I'm going to make the mortgage payment. I just got
married last month, I have nothing, nothing. I have no way to even
make a car payment.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Erxleben assured her she could never lose more than 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me this is as safe as going to the grocery store,''
she said. ``That's his exact words.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Yeakey said he invested with Austin Forex and also had
worked seven months as an independent trader for an affiliate,
International Foreign Exchange Corp. Yeakey said his family
invested $94,000 with Austin Forex. He said he invested after he
heard that in its first year Erxleben's clients had doubled their
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to hear more facts, what really happened,'' Yeakey
said. ``He said there's substantial losses, we ceased trading. What
are substantial losses? Does that mean all the money is gone? Does
it mean there's some left over? How did it happen? Why can't he
tell us that?''
</P>
<P>
   John Stratton, an attorney representing Erxleben, said he
expects it to take several weeks before a true picture of the
company's financial situation can be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors are left to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Talbert, an Austin investor who continued to interrupt
Erxleben during Friday's press conference, said he invested ``six
figures'' with Austin Forex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be a can't lose situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I realize it was 'can't win.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
