<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panthers: Some rise in Sunrise?
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla._ The dateline is perfect, they hope.
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise. The signal of a new day.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers are in their new digs _ though National Car Rental
Center, to be accurate, remains in the finishing-touch stages of
construction _ looking for a new start.
</P>
<P>
   They have slipped from Stanley Cup finalists three seasons ago
to first-round playoff losers two seasons ago to last season's
standing as the next-to-worst team, by record, in the NHL. It is
not quite as precipitous a fall as the Marlins have suffered in
transforming themselves from World Series champions to baseball
laughingstock, but it's close.
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business during this summer's training camp
has been for the Panthers to settle and soothe themselves after the
turmoil of a year ago when General Manager Bryan Murray fired head
coach Doug MacLean and took the spot behind the bench himself.
</P>
<P>
   Murray is still the head coach, but now it's Bryan's brother,
Terry on the job. The goals this season are modest ones _ show some
improvement on the ice and recover some balance off it.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret Panthersville was not a happy place last season.
</P>
<P>
   There was a locker-room schism between veterans and young
players that grew deeper and more divisive as the losses mounted.
There was a distracting season-long contractual squabble involving
goalie/franchise hero John Vanbiesbrouck, who has since packed his
pads for Philadelphia. And, as Vanbiesbrouck abdicated his role as
a team leader, no one emerged as a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had tremendous highs and tremendous lows here in the
last few years,'' said Murray the GM. ``We hope we're good enough
to make the playoffs. For now, that sets the standard.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, must Murray the Coach set a standard, because he
inherits a team a team that had softened in terms of discipline
after his brother replaced MacLean as coach. Bryan admits as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I had the reputation of being firm,'' he said. ``Not
tough-tough, but someone whose teams played hard. But when I took
over, I thought we had very little confidence and were fragile.
Doug had been very emotional, and I think the guys were sensitive
to criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, I probably should have been tougher on them.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he hired his brother to do what he couldn't (or wouldn't)
do.
</P>
<P>
   After a lackluster practice Wednesday, it was Terry Murray who
scolded the Panthers for falling into their old routine. And his
explanation Thursday afternoon _ after spending six hours on the
ice with the team broken into three groups _ was succinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are reasons things fall apart on you very quickly,''
Murray the Coach said. ``I don't know how it happened. It doesn't
matter. It's behind us. We need to wipe it clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that you have to keep the pressure on. Push.
Kick. Shove. The guys who are looking to win want us to do those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Panthers will have a few more young players on the
roster this year (wingers Oleg Kvasha, Marcus Nilson and Mark
Parrish). Maybe other young players already on the roster _ Rob
Niedermayer, Ed Jovanovski, Radek Dvorak _will rediscover early,
promising form. Maybe the loss of Vanbiesbrouck, replaced by Sean
Burke, won't be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, maybe, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   They are the possibilities of every sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
