 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release the weekend of Saturday, September 19,
1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ In the end, public opinion may
decide whether President Clinton serves out the rest of his term.
But, for now, public opinion is having little impact on the nasty
doings here. (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ While we all vicariously joined the president of
the United States as he contemplated Monica flashing her thong
undies and in general were puzzling out who had done what and with
which and to whom, there was a murder in Washington. Congressional
Republicans finally did in campaign-funding reform. (Teepen, Cox
News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ Baseball is a game of long memories. Sammy Sosa
and Mark McGwire not only faced down this year's pitchers but
generations of past players. Nobody really plays them one game at a
time. Each game projects into an eternity of statistics, lists and
stories. (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ There are lost episodes of ``The
Honeymooners,'' lost episodes of ``I Love Lucy,'' lost episodes of
just about any timeworn sitcom. And television is not alone in this
gambit. Now Ernest Hemingway will publish another ``posthumous''
book. It's his fourth. I don't think he'd agree with the decision.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN19 _ Who can recall what you did with the pan after
your mother finished baking cookies or cake? John C. Westervelt of
Tulsa, Okla., remembers it in delightful detail. Here's his story.
(Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN20 _ ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ Here's a story from
long ago, a small town's tale of love, sex and six-guns. (Murray,
Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ Texas Comptroller John Sharp, who is running
for lieutenant governor, is battling accusations by Republican
backers of his opponent, Agriculture Commissioner Rick Perry, that
his claims of having saved the state $8.5 billion over the past
seven years are grossly exaggerated. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ I have difficulty understanding why President
Clinton or any leader who cared about his family and country would
not resign, given the nature of his behavior in the Lewinsky affair
and the public revelation of it. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ What I hope is that pornography, whether from
your dirty book store or direct from your government, doesn't
become a way of life. (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Americans should think of Janet
Reno when they are grossed out by the Clinton-Lewinsky zippergate
scandal. Had Attorney General Reno not recommended the appointment
of an independent counsel, it's possible that the nation would have
been spared the sordid Clinton-Lewinsky scandal, at least with
Clinton as president. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
