<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-NOTES19-     09-18 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expect sack rate to get Slashed
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Don't expect a repeat performance from the
Dolphins' pass rush this week. After all, Pittsburgh's Kordell
Stewart isn't about to sit around waiting for a hit as did
Buffalo's Rob Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins dropped Johnson eight times last week, a number
that would have been reduced had Johnson taken lessons in
scrambling and/or throwing away the ball. Stewart, conversely, is
considered the best running quarterback in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so difficult rushing the passer any way, but when you're
having to rush the passer and you have to be very disciplined about
your lanes and how you rush. ... you just can't open up gaping
holes for the quarterback to run through,'' Dolphins coach Jimmy
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   And Stewart will run. Slash, as he is called by Steelers coach
Bill Cowher, was Pittsburgh's second-leading rusher last season
with 476 yards. By comparison, Miami's Dan Marino has rushed for 96
yards in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to contain him,'' linebacker Zach Thomas said.
``He's a great athlete. He can run, he can catch. He does it all
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami has 12 sacks in two games, almost 40 percent of its entire
total of 31 last season. But those came against a confused rookie
(Peyton Manning) and a statue (Johnson). Jimmy Johnson says Stewart
is the best ``running quarterback'' in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Miami _ and most Steelers opponents _ is it
never faces a quarterback like Stewart and cannot emulate his
running ability in practice. But all agree the Dolphins cannot lose
their aggressiveness despite Stewart's ability to escape the rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be less aggressive, you just have to be more
disciplined,'' said defensive end Trace Armstrong, who is tied with
Jason Taylor for the team lead in sacks with three. ``You can get
into a lot of trouble by being less aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   More praise for Marino: Johnson continues to back peddle on his
criticism of Marino, saying Thursday more was made of his comments
than warranted when he said Marino was missing open receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also gave another excuse for the Dolphins' low passing
yardage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping more receivers in to block,'' he said. ``The
priority for us right now is to protect Dan Marino. We've been able
to do that fairly well. I look around the league and there are nine
or 10 quarterbacks no longer playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Light at the end of the dog house: Wide receiver Charles Jordan
will return to the active roster after a good week of practice.
Jordan has bounced back after losing his starting job, sulking,
suffering a groin injury and being placed in the inactive list last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan will be the fourth receiver and play on special teams.
</P>
<P>
   History says plan for playoffs: The Dolphins are 2-0 for the
14th time in their history, and have qualified for the playoffs
11-of-13 years in which they won their first two games, missing in
1977 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Of those years, Miami finished first in the AFC East eight
times, second four times and tumbled to fourth with an 8-8 record
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Robbie honored: A statue of team founder, the late Joe
Robbie, will be unveiled at Pro Player Stadium Sunday at noon
outside Gate G. Members of the Robbie family and the Dolphins
organization will be present for the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Boo!: Johnson continues to insist the running game is on
schedule, but says it isn't exactly in the Steelers class just yet.
Pittsburgh led the NFL with 154.9 yards per game last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that our running game is going to scare anybody
right now,'' Johnson said. ``Hopefully they'll be a day here that
people will be concerned about it. We're kind of feeling our way
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy that we have run the ball better these first couple
of games than we did a year ago. But we're not there yet. We still
have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami is averaging 126.5 yards on the ground, 11th best in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
