<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2370 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-CONDOS19-COX     09-18 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CONDOS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pre-sales keep condo developers in line with market
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the past, luxury condominium developers
needed little more than a dream and a few million dollars to build
their posh palaces.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, luxury condo developers, investors and lenders _
still smarting from their experiences during the last real estate
downturn _ are waiting for sales before they turn their first
spades of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers are attempting _ as much as possible _ to be
responsive to the market without getting too far ahead of the
market,'' said Ron Witten, president of Dallas-based M/PF Research,
a real estate research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Nokonah, the 70-unit condo project planned for
Ninth Street and North Lamar Boulevard on the edge of Austin's
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Developers won't break ground on the project until half the
units are pre-sold, said Robert Barnstone, vice president of New
Urban Partners GP Inc., which is building the condo. In Dallas,
developers waited until more than half of the 145 units in the
23-story Mayfair were sold before it broke ground.
</P>
<P>
   To secure construction financing for a high-rise condo project,
most banks these days require developers to sell between 30 percent
to 90 percent of the units before they can begin construction.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they're able to find financing without plenty of
pre-sales, they may have a hard time selling the individual units.
</P>
<P>
   That's because for most new condo projects, permanent mortgage
lenders require that half the units be sold to ensure the project
won't become a glorified apartment, Witten said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nokonah will include 30,000 square feet of office and retail
space. Units in the project will range from $250,000 to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, work on the project could start during
the second quarter of 1999, with the first residents moving in by
Christmas 2000.
</P>
<P>
   New Urban Partners is halfway toward its goal of pre-selling $15
million worth of units at the Nokonah.
</P>
<P>
   It won't commit to long-term construction financing for the $30
million project without reaching that goal, Witten said. The list
of people who have put down deposits on units in the project
include local politicos, business leaders, doctors and a federal
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our buyers view (this conservative attitude) as a positive,''
Barnstone said. ``They can be assured the project will be a success
from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s and early 1980s, banks were eagerly pouring
money into condo projects. With inflation high, it wasn't always in
a developer's best interest to pre-sell a project when he or she
might be able to get more for the units after the building was
completed, Witten said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no Austin luxury condo was more indicative of the 1980s
way of doing business than the Towers of Town Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The $30 million in financing was easy to get for the 183-unit
condo off Interstate 35, even though there wasn't a proven market
for these units, which sold for up to $750,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the project faced tough times when it was completed in 1984.
More than a year after it opened, only 37 of the units had been
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Then the real estate bust hit. The Towers of Town Lake went back
to Texas Commerce Bank, which provided the construction financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disaster,'' recalled Bert Pence, one of the project's
original investors.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade later, the Towers of Town Lake is finally a
success. The Austin condo market, dormant for more than a decade,
is stirring and new projects are rising around the city.
</P>
<P>
   And along the way, condo developers learned a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenders and developers have become more conservative,'' Pence
said. ``Debt, we've learned, can destroy you. And nothing stays the
same, whether it be good times or bad times.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
