<HEADER>
A2381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-WOLFERT-2TAKES-B     09-18 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-WOLFERT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAULA WOLFERT: MISTRESS OF THE MEDITERRANEAN 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Repeating for Allenton and all needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Paula Wolfert demands that you leap into her
passion. She is standing in the kitchen of Casablanca, where chef
Ana Sortun and guest chef Joe Simone of Hingham's Tosca are cooking
from Wolfert's new book and _ at this moment _ memorizing
everything she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taste this,'' she commands a visitor, holding up a cup of
seedless Turkish red-pepper flakes called Maras with a color so
startling they look fearsome _ not fire-engine red or candy-apple
red but a red that embodies burnt sienna, vermilion, port, pumpkin,
umber, dark ocher, crimson, carmine, and plum.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the taste. ``Notice,'' she says. ``No seeds.''
The tiny scarlet dots hit the tongue in layers _ not fiery layers
but smooth ripples, smoky and pleasingly warm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this not the elixir of the '90s?'' Wolfert asks.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if Wolfert says so, it shall be. At least if the pepper
flakes follow the route of preserved lemons and couscous, which she
found in Morocco 40 years ago; foie gras, the crowning glory of her
intense research into southwestern French cuisine in the early
1980s; and pomegranate molasses, the sweet-sour syrup she stumbled
upon in wanderings along the eastern Mediterranean. All of these
ingredients, now on restaurant menus across the country, were swept
up by her passion _ and her influence. Professional cooks listen to
Wolfert. They cook from her books and they eagerly learn from her.
The San Francisco resident willingly teaches everything she knows.
</P>
<P>
   Her sixth book, ``Mediterranean Grains and Greens''
(HarperCollins), offers more ingredients that you never heard of,
grains that have been around since the beginning of civilization,
and greens similar to the ones the earliest gatherers collected,
sorted, and boiled down until vast basketfuls were reduced to small
bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how they say that the oldest profession is motherhood
and the second oldest is whoring? That's ridiculous,'' she says.
``The oldest is gathering.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert loves ethnobotany, the plant lore of a particular
culture. Information about ancient history and historical
geography, religion and anthropology pours forth when she talks
about food.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the subtleties of a culture, some hard to
comprehend at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put water in your bulgur, and no man will marry you,'' a
cook in Turkey told Wolfert. Good cooks, she learned, moisten the
bulgur with the juices of the flavorings they add _ such as chopped
young greens, onions, tomato paste, and red pepper paste _ then
knead them into the grain. Pummel is more like it, really,
according to a slide shown as part of Wolfert's lecture at Boston
University's Seminars in the Culinary Arts, the day after dinner at
Casablanca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grains and greens are canvases,'' she says. ``People still eat
this way, even though they're moving to the cities. Cottage
industries are bringing the ingredients to the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The cultures for whom grains and greens are essential components
of the diet live in the remotest regions, where the food uses
seasonings _ Maras pepper flakes, for instance _ largely unknown on
Western tables. Wolfert is famous for long treks into the
countryside to visit a cook. She travels with a translator and a
driver (she doesn't have a license), and always leaves with a
recipe whose edges seem parched by the ancient sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone should document how it's made, right?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert took on the job of recording food that might be
forgotten, dishes that might start with a shepherdess in Tunisia
who collects khobbeiza (mallow leaves with the same mucilaginous
quality as okra), brings them home, and pounds them with oil, the
hot-pepper paste harissa, and coriander, until the greens are
creamy.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Wolfert found nettles, purslane, salsify greens,
lamb's-quarters, wild mustard, bergamot, garland chrysanthemum,
borage leaves, and shepherd's purse. She watched cooks work wonders
with stale bread and rice, chickpeas, semolina, and green wheat.
</P>
<P>
   The world spins more slowly where she travels, and Wolfert, 60,
softens her pace in those corners. She is mellow from many years
with these ordinary women, no longer prickly. And she is more
understanding when chefs take her recipes and multiply them to feed
a restaurant full of customers _ and don't succeed.
</P>
<P>
   She brings food she has learned about in unusual dialects and
diverse languages, from cooks who unravel their kitchen lives to
her. ``I kiss each woman on both cheeks and I touch my heart. It's
the way women are with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert describes them in the countryside where they spend their
days, scarves tied tightly under their chins to keep the dust away,
pocketed aprons secured around their broad middles, as they collect
``apron greens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The farther east you go in the Mediterranean,'' she says,
``the better the hospitality.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-WOLFERT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     09-18 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-WOLFERT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (Repeating for Allenton and all needing)  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... the hospitality.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wolfert's stories begin like this: ``We flew from Istanbul to
Kars, near the Armenian border. Then we drove to Trabzon on the
Black Sea coast of Turkey. We had a Kurdish driver, of course. It
was Ramadan and no one had eaten all day.''
</P>
<P>
   During her visit here, someone wants to know if she has ever had
to sleep in a tent in some faraway place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that plural?'' she countered. ``I've slept in many, many
tents. I've also slept high up so the scorpions wouldn't get me.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wobbles like your belly'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paula Wolfert stumbled into the world of food. She was a young
bride when she went with her husband at the time to live in Morocco
in 1959. ``Couscous and Other Good Food From Morocco'' was born
there. It took many more years, the end of the first marriage, and
the beginning of a romance with crime novelist Bill Bayer to
finally produce the couscous book in 1973. It is still the
definitive work on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   She has eaten so much ill-prepared couscous that ``Grains and
Greens'' covers the territory again. By the time she finishes her
lecture at BU, she has most of the students convinced that they'll
never simply follow the package directions on instant couscous.
They'll steam it, aerate it, steam it again. ``It multiplies 18
times,'' she says. ``You lift the couscous. This is the most
sensual thing. Play with it.'' She shows slides to demonstrate.
``This is air,'' she says. ``It wobbles like your belly.''
</P>
<P>
   Instructions for couscous from scratch appear in ``Grains and
Greens.'' You begin with coarse semolina and add fine semolina,
cold water, sea salt, and olive oil. You have to press it through a
strainer, then a fine sieve, and steam it three times. But you
don't have to do it sitting on the floor the way they do in North
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   As Wolfert says, someone's got to record this, right?
</P>
<P>
   When she spent a brief interlude in southwestern France, she
made confit and foie gras sound so irresistible, they showed up on
menus as soon as ``The Cooking of South-West France'' was
published. As a result of the book, Ariane Daguin, the daughter of
French chef Andre Daguin, set up the foie gras business D'Artagnan,
which is flourishing today. Her father sold his two-star restaurant
in Auch last year. American foodies already had made a pilgrimage
there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Mediterranean course &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mediterrean cooking has taken a different course. It spans
restaurants in so many demographics that it appears on the tables
of celebrity chefs and at fast food-places along the highway.
Wolfert never set out to research food that would become
commonplace. Her cooking is too involved, and many ingredients
aren't available here, although she gives extensive mail-order
lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The larder's better on the East Coast than the West Coast,''
she declares. She has found the Maras peppers in Formaggio Kitchen
in Cambridge, and she likes the Middle Eastern markets along
Belmont and Mt. Auburn streets in Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert and Bayer, who have been married 15 years, moved to San
Francisco several years ago. At the time, she told a reporter that
she went ``kicking and screaming.'' She had already moved with
Bayer from Manhattan to Connecticut; the couple summered at his
house in West Tisbury. They sold both homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer had a ``midlist crisis'' and changed his nom de plume to
David Hunt. His ``The Magician's Tale,'' set in San Francisco, came
out last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now they weekend on six acres in Sonoma, where Wolfert is
growing wild greens from seeds she has collected all over the
Mediterranean. In the city, she's friendly with restaurateur Alice
Waters, cookbook writer Carol Field, and author Peggy
Knickerbocker. It took some time to settle into this life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you live in New York, you come up in the trenches
shoulder to shoulder,'' she says. ``In San Francisco, it takes a
long time to make a best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert stocks her larder mostly from Kalustiyan, the Manhattan
purveyor of Middle Eastern foods. She and Bayer live on
California's ``unbelievable'' produce, her own greens, and Sonoma
lamb. Her house salad comes from Greek Cyprus and combines shredded
savoy cabbage, baby spinach, arugula, cilantro, scallions, and
green olives tossed with a lemon and olive oil dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blending greens is the art,'' she says. ``If I tell you to use
Swiss chard, and it doesn't look good, don't buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert wants cooks to try uncommon ingredients. ``In the
Mediterranean, you have a meal and you think you'll never reproduce
it at home. But now you can make the dish and share it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon you'll see these greens everywhere,'' she says. She keeps
repeating this, not so much to amass support for her book but
because she knows something we don't: Jean-Georges Vongerichten,
the celebrated, much imitated, New York chef, hired Francois
Couplan, an ethnobotanist who lives in Switzerland, to teach him
about leafy greens and weeds. Someone grows them for Vongerichten
in upstate New York. They're all over the Jean Georges menu.
</P>
<P>
   So it shall be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
