<HEADLINE>
FINGER BOWLS ADD A GENTEEL TOUCH TO THE DINNER TABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ There's nothing like a finger bowl to lend an air
of sophistication to a formal dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Finger bowls were used at the best tables from the 19th century
through 1950. The purpose of the finger bowl was to cleanse the
fingers and wipe lips prior to the dessert course. This also saved
the main dinner napkin, which was usually made from the very best
materials, from getting too soiled or ruined.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 19th century, doilies were often placed under the
finger bowl to be used to wipe the finger tips dry after dipping
them in the bowl. Because dining tables were so highly polished,
this created a demand for complete sets of doilies for table
service. These small fabric circles, or squares, protected the
table's finish after the (perhaps soiled) tablecloth was removed
prior to the fruit or dessert course.
</P>
<P>
   A finger bowl half full of warm water was placed above the
dessert plate of each guest or served with the doily directly on
the dessert plate, with the fork to the left and dessert spoon to
the right.
</P>
<P>
   Finger bowls are most apt today to be used for appetizers, cold
soups and desserts. They're used in a formal sit-down dinner only
if finger food, such as artichokes and corn-on-the-cob, are being
served.
</P>
<P>
   They often are brought out on china or clear or colored glass
plates with a doily or small fruit napkin in between.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a common practice to float a fresh flower or flower
petals in the water, or a slice of lemon or orange. You dip your
fingers into the bowl and rub them with the slice of fruit before
wiping with the doily or small napkin.
</P>
<P>
   Some sets of new china come with finger bowls. But it is more
common to find them at antiques shops and estate sales. Victorian
or 20th-century American glass bowls from the 1920s and '30s sell
from $300 to $400 for a set of eight to 12 crystal bowls, and
English Regency sets of six have sold for $1,200 and up. Finger
bowls are often mixed and matched with sets of china. Contemporary
ceramic bowls for $2 or $3 also work well.
</P>
<P>
   It was the custom in the mid-1800s on both sides of the Atlantic
Ocean to rinse the mouth out from the finger bowl, spitting the
rinse water back into the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That is one use that is frowned upon today. No gargling, please.
Fingertips only.
</P>
<P>
   If you are served a finger bowl, for the first time, don't worry
about making a faux pas. It occasionally happens to the best of us.
</P>
<P>
   Finger bowls contributed to Martin Van Buren's failed bid for a
second term as the eighth president of the United States. An 1840
speech by Charles Ogle, a Whig congressman from Pennsylvania,
denounced Van Buren's lavish spending on furnishings and his
aristocratic ways while at the White House, which included the
purchase of a set of green finger cups ``to wash his pretty, soft,
white, lily fingers, after dining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
