<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2569 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-TRUE-HNS &LR;      09-18 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-TRUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREEP RESCUES AN OTHERWISE MIDDLING MELODRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``One True Thing,'' Meryl Streep reaffirms her place in
America's film acting corps: She's peerless. No one else assumes a
character as fully and selflessly, and no one else has been as
outstanding in such remarkably different roles. Think of ``Sophie's
Choice,'' ``Ironweed,'' ``Death Becomes Her.''
</P>
<P>
   Streep's work elevates what is otherwise a middling melodrama
that's part coming-to-terms-with-your-family story and part
``few-months-to-live'' plot. She isn't even the central figure
here, but when she's on screen she moves the picture to a different
level.
</P>
<P>
   While the emotional focus is on Streep's 50ish matriarch,
technically the main character is her daughter, Ellen, played by
Renee Zellweger. Ellen's an intense and ambitious Harvard graduate
trying to make a name for herself as a reporter at New York
magazine. She's tracking down a juicy story when she hears
devastating news from her father, George (William Hurt), a
brilliant and well-connected professor of literature.
</P>
<P>
   Kate, her mother _ a homemaker and nonintellectual _ is to be
operated on for cancer. Citing his responsibilities as a department
head, George asks Ellen to take a leave from her job and move home
to care for mom. Reluctantly, she does so.
</P>
<P>
   The Ellen we meet early on is a hard case: self-centered,
aggressive and totally career-focused. She's simply an exaggerated
version of her father, who's a bit less driven since he's already
made his mark in life. In contrast to this cerebral pair is Kate, a
member of the local ladies' auxiliary and busy with charity work
during the holidays _ the picture of domesticity and a lover of
simpler things. In case we should miss the point, we learn that she
enjoys Erma Bombeck and even see her dressed up for a costume party
as Dorothy from ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Firecracker Ellen can hardly stand it.
</P>
<P>
   She'll learn differently, and also discover cracks in her dad's
sterling facade. She begins to suspect him of fooling around with a
female graduate student _ and not for the first time. And she is
increasingly upset as he keeps his distance from the family crisis,
insisting that he's terribly busy. At the same time, Ellen finds
her mother much more than a dull homebody. Kate has depth and an
understanding of life and matters of substance that is far beyond
anything her daughter suspected.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen's callowness is exposed, and it's only as her mother's
sickness accelerates that she begins to understand her, and how
much she, Ellen, is about to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``One True Thing'' is based on the best-seller by Anna Quindlen,
the former New York Times columnist. Her story doesn't rely on
challenging insights; it's the dependable nature of what
transpires, the glowing lessons learned by hard-hearted Ellen in
the face of her mother's death, that are the reassuring core here.
You may find yourself weeping toward the end, and, later, you may
also find yourself wondering why. The revelations are staggeringly
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all praise is due to Streep for a magisterial performance
as the wise, down-to-earth and serenely centered mother, shepherd
to a family of lost sheep. Zellweger (``Jerry Maguire'') is better
than you might expect as the arrogant but emotionally needy
daughter; but even though she gets the lion's share of screen time,
she's simply overwhelmed by Streep. And the English professor with
the feet of clay is a role Hurt was born to play; he is the soul of
cockiness _ the East Coast, literary brand.
</P>
<P>
   The direction by Carl Franklin (``Devil in a Blue Dress'') is
quiet and assured, as actor-centered as the material requires. He
springs no surprises and makes no unexpected turns; neither does
the story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1227EDT &QL; 
