r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-PERMANENT     09-18 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-PERMANENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ABOUT HOLLYWOOD OFFERS CONVINCING PERFORMANCE IN `MIDNIGHT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Ben Stiller the busiest guy in Hollywood, or what?
</P>
<P>
   Host of the MTV video awards, a star in the hit gross-out movie
of the summer, ``There's Something About Mary,'' and a key player
in the latest misanthropic piece from Neil LaBute, ``Your Friends &AMP;
Neighbors,'' the man doesn't seem to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stiller, known for his comedic work, takes a surprisingly
smooth turn into drama in ``Permanent Midnight,'' playing a TV
scriptwriter with a $5,000 a week heroin habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Permanent Midnight,'' written and directed by first-time
helmer David Veloz from a 1995 memoir by Jerry Stahl, is nothing
new, thematically speaking. Otto Preminger told the tale of a
self-destructive junkie better in 1955's ``The Man With the Golden
Arm.'' But ``Midnight'' is vividly rendered and nicely paced and
serves as an expressive audition tape for Stiller.
</P>
<P>
   Gaunt, permanently sweaty, face covered with stubble, eyes
bloodshot, speed-rapping his way into trouble, Stiller convincingly
portrays the obsessiveness and desperation of a man in way over his
head. He ties off and shoots up in the hospital john when his
girlfriend (Elizabeth Hurley) is giving birth to their child, again
just before an interview for a job he needs, and _ sickeningly _
again while he has his infant daughter in the car on a dark Los
Angeles street.
</P>
<P>
   Even the scene with the infant, though, pales next to the truly
horrific moment where Stiller's character, Jerry, and a new-found
druggie friend hurl themselves at the ceiling-to-floor window
inside a highrise, bouncing off the glass with laughing, howling,
maniacal energy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite its subject _ an addict's dark interior life _
``Permanent Midnight'' offers little in the way of character
development and no jolting insight. Moreover, we glimpse little of
Jerry's life before he becomes addicted, so it's hard to measure
how his drug-related losses changed him. The movie's overriding
point _ heroin is bad for you _ is true, but hardly novel. There's
a hole at the center of this familiar cautionary tale to match the
holes in Jerry's arm.
</P>
<P>
   As Stiller's co-star, Hurley plays a British producer who
marries Jerry so she can get a green card, then unwisely falls for
him. Hurley has improved as an actress, but she doesn't show the
range or depth needed for this part; moreover, with her strong,
angular frame and crisp diction, her Sandra doesn't look or sound
needy enough to be Jerry's patsy.
</P>
<P>
   Maria (``ER'') Bello is lovely and empathetic as Kitty, a fellow
ex-junkie to whom Jerry tells his life story, shown in flashbacks.
Jeanane Garofalo is her usual smart self as a Hollywood agent who
Jerry really should flatter and court. It's a small part, and
Garofalo can't get enough out of it to match her portrayal of a
hilariously droll FBI agent in the upcoming ``Clay Pigeons,'' but
she lets a little badly needed light shine into ``Permanent
Midnight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0144 </DOCNO>
