<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-MILITARY DISCOVER JOBS IN CIVILIAN LIFE ARE HARD TO FIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The military used to sell itself as a training ground for the
future, but veterans are finding it's increasingly difficult to be
all they can be once they leave the service.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to recruiting for the civilian work force,
companies are often reluctant to hire ex-military people, said
Linda Carlson, author of ``How to Find A Good Job in Seattle,''
(Barrett Street Productions, 1990, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   The seventh edition of her book, available next month, has a new
chapter focusing on problems faced by the growing number of
ex-military people looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   The military has been downsizing along with everyone else, which
means more people are leaving the service and needing to find other
jobs, she said. About 275,000 people leave the military every year.
</P>
<P>
   While potential employers don't admit they won't hire people who
have been in the military, the reality is many don't.
</P>
<P>
   People coming out of the service often come across as rigid and
seem out-of-place in the ``real world,'' she said. Companies are
nervous about hiring them, fearing they won't work well in
high-risk, fast-changing, unstructured business environments.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson recently worked with one colonel who was shocked to
discover he would have to use a computer terminal himself, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The military is a ``somewhat artificial environment,'' she said.
Its structure, promotion system and pay scales are all different
than those in the civilian world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Operating destroyers,'' she said. ``Those skills are not in
demand.''
</P>
<P>
   To succeed in finding new jobs or careers, those leaving the
military have to figure out how to sell themselves to civilians,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, their problems are similar to those of people
coming out of very large corporations, and their coping strategies
would be similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``A corporate executive who says, `I've had it,' after 25 years
and walks out is going to suffer some of the same challenges'' (in
the job market, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first step for both is to translate their skills into ones
the market can use and understand.
</P>
<P>
   For military folks that means eliminating military jargon and
titles when they speak to recruiters, and translating their job
experiences in the military into business terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use phrases such as, `What I did was similar to running a ...
' or `Managing a facility like yours would be much like when I ...
''' Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough to tell a potential employer that you've worked
on multi-million dollar equipment he wouldn't understand, or that
all your experience is classified, she said. ``That comes across as
arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   Employers want to know how someone cut costs or saved money at
his or her previous job. They want to know how flexible people are
in their skills, and how well they work with others.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the military get promotions without
interviewing,'' she said. They may never have thought about or had
to present their experiences in those terms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to assessing their skills in light of the market,
ex-military people need to be realistic about the demand for those
skills and the pay, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of military people have had staff jobs, such as directing
personnel, that are not valued as highly in the civilian world, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The business world tends to put a premium on line jobs _ those
involved directly in creating or selling the company's products or
services, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of the military is often a chance for people to
consider a whole new career, such as teaching, she said. ``People
who have a commitment to something, or feel as though they have a
mission, tend to adjust better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some military skills are in demand. People with
training in engineering, languages or adult education can find
satisfying niches in the private sector, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out of the military is an adjustment, but it can be
done, she said. It just takes overcoming some culture shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't expect anyone to call you Sir, or Ma'am,'' she said.
``Or even Mr. or Ms.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Smith is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. Her e-mail
address is carolsmith(at)seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
