<HEADLINE>
`WILL &AMP; GRACE' STANDS TALL AMONG NEW FALL OFFERINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the all-female comedy block NBC tried on Monday nights
last season? For two hours straight, it was sitcom after sitcom
with a different woman in the lead, but with what seemed like the
same show playing in repertory.
</P>
<P>
   The network has bagged the ``Must She TV'' approach in favor of
a little more gender equity, and guess what. ``Conrad Bloom'' still
looks like all those other Monday comedies _ from the departed
``Fired Up'' and ``The Naked Truth'' to the still extant ``Suddenly
Susan'' and ``Caroline in the City.''
</P>
<P>
   It is from the space between the latter two that ``Conrad''
blooms. Whether it will thrive is open to question. Mark
Feuerstein, the star of the show, knows the territory; he was a
supporting player on ``Fired Up.'' But ``Conrad Bloom'' is on the
same turf that countless other comedies have trod, many of them
better, most of them about the same.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is that Conrad is one of the last of the nice guys
in Manhattan. As such, he is fair game to the women in his life:
his mom, his ex-girlfriend, his boss, etc. They take advantage of
him ad nauseam, and we get to watch while he musters up enough
courage to say no without a trace of guilt. By my calculations,
that will be _ oh, let's see _ never.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein isn't bad as Bloom. Linda Lavin is even better as his
mother. But there's a sameness to this workplace series that fairly
shouts: ``You've seen this before and you probably have something
better to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep your fingers crossed. ``Will &AMP; Grace'' is one of those
comedies that seems to have gotten it right. This endorsement, of
course, is subject to retraction, but even the second episode looks
good enough to anoint ``Will &AMP; Grace'' as the best new comedy of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The credit may rest with James Burrows, the most popular hired
gun among TV sitcom directors. Burrows directs scads of pilot
episodes each season, but the difference is that he has signed on
to direct at least the first 13 of ``Will &AMP; Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to good direction, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' has the
attractive cast and snappy writing that most comedies never have
the luck or skill to achieve. Debra Messing is smartly cast as the
vulnerable but not insufferable Grace Adler, a successful young
interior designer who, on the advice of her best friend, decides to
leave her fianc &UR; gfacute &LR; e at the altar.
</P>
<P>
   The best friend is Manhattan attorney Will Truman (Eric
McCormack), but don't get the wrong idea here. Will doesn't have
eyes for Grace. At least not in that sense. He's gay.
</P>
<P>
   Will and Grace do see eye to eye on everything else, and since
Will just ended his own long-term relationship, it's only, uh,
natural that they live together. (Memo to gay bashers: No need to
call or write; if you don't like the premise, just don't watch.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; xr &LR; It's a touch of d &UR; gfacute &LR; ej &UR; gfgrave &LR; a vu for Messing, who
had a similar oddball arrangement in ``Ned &AMP; Stacey,'' but this
time she's in a better ensemble package with McCormack and two
riotously funny supporting players, Megan Mullally and Sean Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   With a little will and a touch of grace, this show could be a
big winner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hyperion Bay, Calif., is a sleepy, economically depressed
coastal community that somehow has escaped the notice of
vacation-home developers and eco-tour operators.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Sweeny might change all that. The computer wonderboy has
returned to his hometown to open and manage a new plant for his
Bill Gates-style boss, who reminds Sweeny during a visit to this
burg named for a Greek god that it is the geeks who now rule the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Like any high-tech magnate these days, Sweeny is viewed with
equal parts awe and suspicion, even by his own family. Is his
return a monumental ego trip? Does he want to revive the town?
Change it forever? Or is he just trying to show his father and
older brother that he isn't a loser?
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities for conflict seem limitless, but the first
episode of ``Hyperion Bay'' bogs down in some unconvincing writing
by creator Joseph Dougherty, who earned his stripes on
``thirtysomething.''
</P>
<P>
   The angst-filled earnestness of ``thirtysomething'' is there,
though. And the performances are reasonable enough, especially by
Mark-Paul Gosselaar as Dennis Sweeny and Dylan Neal as older
brother Nick, so ``Hyperion Bay'' may yet catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   But with family-relationship dramas as plentiful as adulterers
in D.C., ``Hyperion Bay'' could get lost in the fog.
</P>
<P>
   _ Conrad Bloom. Half-hour comedy about a young ad executive with
lots of women in his life. Premieres Monday, NBC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG. Check local listings. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _ Will &AMP; Grace. Half-hour comedy about a man and woman who are
compatible in every way but one. Premieres Monday, NBC. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Check local listings. Grade: A-.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hyperion Bay. One-hour drama about family dynamics in a small
seaside town. Premieres Monday, The WB. KTZZ/22. Parental guideline
rating: TV-PG. Check local listings. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send e-mail to:
tvguy(at) &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
