<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-SHOP-$ADV20-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN CONSUMER CONFESSES HIS FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMINGTON, Minn. _ Wall Street is on a wild ride, economies
around the world are shaking like banana trees in a hurricane and
Alan Greenspan is still Alan Greenspan, which means nobody knows
what he really thinks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So as a true patriot, I'm taking matters into my own hands. I've
come here to the super, huge, mega, humongous and pretty big Mall
of America to do my Christmas shopping early. And I'll start as
soon as I finish my chicken fingers, fries and fruit punch and quit
gawking at the Camp Snoopy roller coaster that wooshes over my head
every few minutes on green rails. (I've never ridden a roller
coaster in a mall. I have my standards.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My theory is that if America is to keep its strong economy, the
job, as usual, will fall to consumers because our econony is based
largely on consumers buying expensive and unnecessary stuff for
themselves and others. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most American place to acquire this wretchedly excessive
collection of junk, of course, is at a suburban mall. And the
largest, most astonishing suburban mall in the world is right here
at the edge of the Twin Cities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mall of America has more than 400 stores on a 78-acre site,
meaning 2.5 million square feet of retail space. And it employs
nearly 12,000 people, including the young woman running the Schafer
Crystal kiosk on the mall's first level (of four). She has no
customers just now so she's reading a paperback, ``The Last Day''
by Glenn Kleier. It looks stupid. I don't think I'll buy it _ or
any of her crystal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But I want to help the economy, so I have my shopping list and
my credit cards ready because, well, America has been very, very
good to me, allowing me to rise from the upper-lower middle of the
middle class to the lower-upper middle of the middle class, all the
while accumulating debt that my upper-lower middle-class parents
could only have dreamed about. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And America has allowed me to rear children who already owe more
money than I ever could imagine at their age. What a country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, as I say, I intend to help out. But first, now that my
chicken fingers (I ordered them minus the nails) are gone, I'm
engaged by a small competition going on at a mini bumper-car game
at the edge of this middle-of-the-mall amusement park, Camp
Snoopy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two little kids, egged on by grandparents, are operating red car
No. 9 and white car No. 10, smashing one into the other in that
most American of sports _ demolition derby _ in this most American
of places. It's fun to watch these squirts learning to destroy
cars, no doubt in preparation for teen-age driving years. But I
need to move on if I'm going to stay on task here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But wait. What's this? A ``Log Chute''? Ah, I see. A small
log-shaped boat with one passenger (or empty, if no one wants to
ride) is shot down a steep hill flowing with water and into a small
lake, where it splashes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If I had a spare hour and lived near here, how sad would my
existence have to be to spend it coming to the Mall of America and
riding the Log Chute? Or, around the corner, the Screaming Yellow
Eagle, which I refuse to describe to you for fear you'll want to
come ride it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking just now of stopping in a sportswear store called
``Going to the Game.'' But I'm here the day after Mark McGwire has
hit his 62nd homer. And guess whose baseball jersey is prominently
displayed in the store window. Sammy Sosa's. McGwire's, meanwhile,
is half-hidden on a rack inside. What can these people possibly
know about sportswear? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before long, I notice that what usually happens to me at malls
has happened again. I have spent all my allotted shopping time
wandering around wondering why all this stuff is here, and I've
bought nothing but chicken fingers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My fellow Americans, I've done my best to be your friend. But I
also let you down and I let my family down and I let this country
down. But I'm going to try to make it right. And I'm determined
never to let anything like this to happen again. And I'm convinced
that nothing I've done or not done here at the mall rises to the
level of an impeachable offense. God bless America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column for release Sunday, Sept. 20, and after.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
