<SLUG> BC-TONGUE-DEPRESSORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPANISH GALLEON EMERGES FROM DOCTOR'S FLOTSAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA LEE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Dr. Alfredo B. Cruz, a family practitioner, had too
many tongue depressors. He can only use depressors that are
entirely round at the ends, and the extras had been stacking up. So
he decided to make use of them by building a detailed,
six-foot-long model of a Spanish sailing ship.
</P>
<P>
   The project also gave him something to do on nights he couldn't
sleep and it turned out to be a great stress release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am on call every night,'' he said. ``When the nurses call
and wake you up at night, you can't get back to sleep. One of my
patients said you must be under stress and asked how I cope with
stress. This is better than taking medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruz's ship is a replica of the Spanish galleon the Concepcion
which was featured in the November 1990 issue of the National
Geographic Society Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interested in Spanish galleons,'' Cruz, 55,
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,000-ton wooden ship was built in 1600 in the Philippines
when the Philippine islands were under Spanish rule. It sailed
between Manila and Mexico. During one of its voyages, the Golden
Hind under the command of Francis Drake intercepted the ship off
the coast of California and ransacked it. Queen Elizabeth I of
England was so impressed that she knighted Drake.
</P>
<P>
   The Concepcion continued to sail until 1638 when it went down in
a typhoon. The magazine showed a cut-away section of the ship, and
Cruz used his imagination to fill in the details. Along with the
tongue depressors, Cruz used 2,000 wooden coffee stirrers and
toothpick nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I laid the keel the way it would have been done at the time,''
Cruz said. Some of the tongue depressor planks were fastened by
drilling holes and pegging them with toothpicks. Other joints are
held with carpenter's glue. The windows, which can be opened, have
panes made from microscope slides. Inside the ship's cabins are
tiny stairwells and working, battery-powered lanterns. The string
rigging can be adjusted with working pulleys. Cruz even constructed
a tiny, functioning cannon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put a pellet in here, light it, and it fires,'' he said
with a grin. Cruz completed his model at a surprising pace. He
began work two years ago, shortly before Thanksgiving, and
completed it early last year. The ship is not his first woodworking
project. The doctor's office is decorated with many original
carvings.
</P>
<P>
   When a storm knocked down his cherry tree a few years ago, Cruz
carved a mermaid from the wood. Beside it is a humming bird made
from wood shavings. Cruz plans to make more cannons for the ship,
and to continue working with wood, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to keep my hands busy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
