<SLUG> BC-CALIF-INSURANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA OFFERS INSURANCE INFORMATION ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Working on the premise that the last thing most
people want to do is shop for insurance, California's insurance
commissioner has provided a forum for doing just that. But this is
different: It's state-of-the-art.
</P>
<P>
   At the Department of Insurance's World Wide Web site _
www.insurance.ca.gov _ a new feature called ``premium comparisons''
offers a mountain of information and estimates on auto insurance
premiums, and additional data on homeowner, condominium, renter and
earthquake insurance premiums. While the Web site has quickly drawn
fire from critics of Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush, he praises it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people shopping for insurance tend to stop at the first
place they call when they can get a much better deal somewhere
else, something much more appropriate for their own particular
needs,'' Quackenbush said Thursday as he demonstrated the free
on-line service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to make this as painless as possible,''
Quackenbush said. ``If they come here, they are going to see this
wide variety, the many choices available to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Insurance is strictly regulatory;
only an insurer or their appointed representative can provide
actual quotes. Therefore, the numbers in the survey are estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can enter information about themselves and receive the
estimated premiums.
</P>
<P>
   The survey provides profiles of each insurance company and links
to agent organizations. Consumers can learn the size of a company,
see how willing they are to pay claims, check for enforcement
action against a company.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers who do not have access to the Internet, the
information is also available via the Department of Insurance's
Consumer Hotline at 800-927-HELP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the private (insurance) comparisons on-line are
motivated by a hidden sales force, and some even charge fees,''
Quackenbush said. ``This neutral comparison is free of charge and
arms consumers with information needed to arrive at smart insurance
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, a Republican seeking a second term in the November
election, is challenged by Democratic Assemblywoman Diane Martinez.
Martinez asserts that Quackenbush has not been an advocate for
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet service, Quackenbush said, illustrates his
commitment to consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's critics said Thursday it was disturbing that the
service provided direct Internet links to the 29 companies it
featured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unethical, and possibly illegal, for the commissioner to
be providing quick Internet access to the companies,'' said Gina
Calabrese, litigation director for the consumer-advocacy group
Proposition 103 Enforcement Project, based in Santa Monica.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-18 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRIVATE MATTER INDEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To borrow from Tina Turner, President Clinton would have us
believe that he and Monica Lewinsky were merely private dancers.
That would explain his chutzpah in asking Americans not to ``get
mired in all the details'' of Kenneth Starr's sleaze sheets. He
begs us to ignore the details so he can play president with Vaclav
Havel, Nelson Mandela, and anyone else whose larger-than-life
presence stuffs straw into his empty and ever-shrinking suit.
</P>
<P>
   What has yet to be explained or thoroughly debated in either the
press or public opinion is whether Clinton's actions with Lewinsky
were truly private. Even though I have already written that Clinton
should resign, I pose this as an open question, one that should be
debated not just to determine the fitness of this individual
president, but to determine whether we should allow politicians
different standards to retain their jobs than we know darn well
would not be accepted for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton's lawyers, in their 78-page rebuttal to
Starr's report, said ``holders of public office are therefore not
to be impeached for private conduct.'' But I wonder how that fits
with the first alleged sexual encounter, on Nov. 15, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lewinsky's testimony, Clinton took at least one
telephone call from a member of Congress. She performed oral sex on
Clinton ``while the President continued talking on the phone.''
Starr said White House records showed that during the time span of
the encounter given by Lewinsky, Clinton talked on the phone to
then Representative Jim Chapman, Democrat of Texas, and
Representative John Tanner, Republican of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman, now retired from office, does not remember such a call.
Tanner does not recall the specifics of his call, but said he was
``flabbergasted'' about the possibility of what happened. He said
the call was likely about welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Was that private or public? A president who may have been
discussing his get-tough, get-a-job, close-your-legs rhetoric for
millions of low-income single parents while being sexually serviced
in the area of the Oval Office?
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, Clinton and Lewinsky had their second sexual
encounter. Lewinsky testified she performed oral sex on Clinton
``While the president was on the telephone'' with ``a member of
Congress with a nickname.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr said White House records corroborate that Clinton spoke
with Representative Sonny Callahan, Republican of Alabama. Callahan
said, ``I have not seen the Starr report, nor the alleged reference
to me. However, if it is true that my name is somehow mentioned in
this report, I can say unequivocally and without hesitation that I
had no knowledge I was sharing the president's time or attention
with anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do recall talking to the president during which time he was
seeking my assistance for the American mission in Bosnia. But I do
not have any recollection of any inappropriate behavior or comments
coming from the president during my conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Was that private or public? A president being sexually serviced
while perhaps discussing an operation in which the lives of
American soldiers are at risk? Does this not make it particularly
ironic that Clinton, our commander-in-chief, claims his actions
with Lewinsky, a direct subordinate as a 22-year-old White House
intern, is his own business?
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months ago, Defense Secretary William Cohen
announced the prohibition of intimate contact between senior
officers and junior troops. Is the president asking us to excuse
him for behavior that could get any of our 1.4 million soldiers a
dishonorable discharge?
</P>
<P>
   In February of 1996, Clinton and Lewinsky allegedly had a Sunday
afternoon affair. According to the Starr report, ``After their
sexual encounter, the president and Ms. Lewinsky sat and talked in
the Oval Office for about 45 minutes. Ms. Lewinsky thought the
president might be responding to her suggestion during their
previous meeting about `trying to get to know me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Was that public or private? A starstruck groupie gets 45 minutes
of chit-chat in the most powerful office in the world when
Americans with all kinds of legitimate causes would kill for five
minutes of White House time?
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the use of the White House secretary to conceal
the relationship, the use of top White House personnel staffers to
find Lewinsky a job after her internship, and the implicit threat
by Clinton to fire uniformed White House Secret Service guards who
were on duty during Lewinsky's visits.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony, Captain Jeffrey Purdie said, ``I was
just in the Oval Office with the president and he wants somebody's
ass out here.'' Thus a Secret Service officer might have lost his
job and his family might be scrimping by on unemployment because
the president could not keep his pants zipped up.
</P>
<P>
   A private dance or an abuse of the public trust that fatally
weakens the presidency? You decide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
