<HEADLINE>
THE DISCREET CHARM OF THE WASP-OISIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best books I read this summer was a review copy of
``My First Cousin Once Removed,'' by Concord's own Sarah Payne
Stuart. ``Cousin'' has all the virtues of my favorite opera, Henry
Purcell's ``Dido and Aeneas'': It is beautifully written, it is not
too long, and it is in English.
</P>
<P>
   The first cousin in question is Robert Lowell, the magnificent,
batty Boston poet who was related to Stuart's mother. But the book
trades lightly on Lowell. His presence might have helped Stuart
land a book contract _ ``Cousin'' springs from her amusing 1994 New
York Times essay on Lowell titled ``Bobby Was a Difficult Child'' _
but he's not the center of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cousin'' is simultaneously a wry primer on WASP folkways _
their obsession with the family burial plot; their inexplicable
lust for turtle soup at Thanksgiving _ and a poignant, loving
memoir/meditation/investigation of the manic-depressive ``madness
gene'' that ravaged the Lowells and several members of the author's
own family. ``Half of my family is manic depressive,'' Stuart
writes, ``the rest is screwed up about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also much family interplay between money and genius.
The Lowells, Cottings, and Thorndikes who count, in the Boston
WASPocracy, are those with money. Long after Robert Lowell won the
first of his two Pulitzer prizes, the family elders had no idea why
he garnered so much praise for trashing them in his poems. Lowell's
wealthy aunt Sarah once complained to the author (on the deck of
her yacht, no less): ``Why doesn't Bobby write about the sea? It's
so pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also Aunt Sarah who said, ``I never read Bobby's poetry,
so I can have him to dinner.'' Eventually, inevitably, she stopped
having him to dinner, and cut him out of her will.
</P>
<P>
   The book should be in stores within a few days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Around Campus 1
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston University officials are bracing themselves for a tough
article about their disastrous involvement with Seragen Inc.
scheduled to run in Sunday's New York Times. Seragen is the
biotechnology firm into which BU has poured $85 million over the
years, an investment now worth about one-quarter of that.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Times story springs from the pen of the one
reporter in America who understands BU president John Silber better
than any other journalist. He is David Barboza, formerly a
roustabout with the BU student newspaper who has devoted seven
years of his (young) life to researching a biography of Silber.
</P>
<P>
   Barboza crossed swords with Silber at BU and became fascinated
by the mercurial academic. He traveled to Texas and Germany to
research Silber's roots. In 1990, after initially refusing, Silber
agreed to cooperate with the journalist, who signed a book contract
with John Wiley &AMP; Sons.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1989 and 1997, Barboza says he spent countless hours
with Silber and conducted 1,000 interviews. In 1994, the pair
shared a weekend alone at Silber's Squam Lake, N.H., hideaway;
Barboza handled the tape recorder while Silber wielded the skillet.
(Barboza: ``He was a very good cook; he really knew his food.'')
Silber allowed Barboza unprecedented access to his files, deluging
him with Xeroxes that Barboza scrupulously paid for. ``I think I've
sent him thousands of dollars' worth of checks over the years,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   How does this story end? Eighteen months ago, the Times offered
Barboza the first full-time job of his life, as a business
reporter. ``I dropped the book'' and canceled the contract, he
says. Silber likes and respects Barboza, who wrote a firm but
fair-minded profile of the BU prexy for a Times education
supplement three years ago. After this weekend's Seragen story,
Barboza jokes, ``he'll hate me as much as he hates you'' _ a
statement that I suspect is wrong on all counts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Around Campus 2
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; sv1,0,0,0,0 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind the Crimson Curtain,'' David Greenberg's cover story in
the current issue of Lingua Franca, is a must-read if only for this
detail: Backers of Harvard political science prof Peter Berkowitz,
who was turned down for tenure, hired famed sleazomane Terry
Lenzner to ``investigate'' the murky details behind their man's
rejection. Lenzner, himself a product of the World's Greatest
University, is a top-shelf private investigator whose most recent
clients include President Clinton and the Brown and Williamson
Tobacco Co., which hired him to help discredit whistle-blower
Jeffrey Wigand.
</P>
<P>
   But wait _ it gets better. According to Greenberg, Lenzner
muffed the assignment! Retained to ferret out the names of the men
and women on Berkowitz's tenure committee, Lenzner got one of them
wrong; he apparently confused New York University's Jerome Bruner
with Harvard's Jerome Kagan. (Hey _ they're both named Jerome, OK?)
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Berkowitz movement, spearheaded by New Republic owner
Martin Peretz and WGU law prof Charles Nesson, lies dormant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
