<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PERMANENT-BOS &LR;      09-18 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PERMANENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PERMANENT MIDNIGHT' TOO WHOLESOME FOR ITS OWN BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
PERMANENT MIDNIGHT 
Directed and written by: David Veloz (based on Jerry Stahl's
memoir) 
Starring: Ben Stiller, Elizabeth Hurley, Maria Bello, Owen Wilson,
Cheryl Ladd, Peter Greene, Janeane Garofalo 
Running time: 87 minutes 
Rated: R (pervasive graphic drug use, strong sexuality and
language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ben Stiller has become the bad-news nerd of 1998. Farcially in
``There's Something About Mary,'' malignantly in ``Your Friends &AMP;
Neighbors,'' but palely and opaquely in ``Permanent Midnight.''
Based on Jerry Stahl's memoir, it sets up a wallow through showbiz
heroin addiction and a subsequent back-from-the-ashes detox story
that rewards its protagonist with good sex from the woman whose ear
he bends with his saga. And who, you may ask, is Stiller's
self-made loser, Jerry Stahl? A highly-paid TV writer for such
shows as ``Alf'' and ``Moonlighting,'' who, we are told, feels
guilty of making big money for writing drivel and for pocketing a
lot more take-home than his hard-working father back home in
Pittsburgh ever dreamed of.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Stahl took it home. Although Stahl was making $5,000 a
week, he was spending $6,000 a week on his drug habit while
rendering himself unfit for work, or much else. Although Stiller
can do a lot when he flexes his eyebrows, leans forward in a simian
slump and throws his lower jaw forward in a determined way, there's
only so much he can do to supply what writer-director David Veloz's
script lacks, namely any compelling reason to care much about what
this shlemiel does to himself. We get little more of Stiller's
Jerry than a succession of glowering stares, needles, cold sweats
and, worst of all, episodes of self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   He's funny when he exhibits self-deprecating irony, responding
to a comment about his black leather garb with, ``It's Jewish
leather, it's designed for humiliation.'' But when his habit begins
upstaging him, the interest level drops drastically. When he
whines, ``I need six bags just to turn to the typewriter,'' one
does not feel an uncontrollable urge to commiserate. Not only is
there no psychological complexity from a character ostensibly so
sensitive that he can't stand the fact that high-priced hack
writing has turned him away from more rarefied creativity, there
isn't even much back story.
</P>
<P>
   In short, ``Permanent Midnight'' is about what you would expect
from a mild-at-heart movie that wants to titillate with a fallen
artist story that has a wholesome outcome. The ones who evoke
sympathy are Maria Bello's patient listener to the post-rehab
Jerry's saga, and especially Elizabeth Hurley as Jerry's British
green card wife, who married him to be able to stay and work in the
US. We're never really clear on why she takes her sham marriage as
seriously as she does, or why she cares. We only know she's more
appealing than anything else in this half-baked consignment of
narcissism masquerading as uplift. As for Stiller, two nerds out of
three isn't bad, but ``Permanent Midnight'' is the kind of movie
that gives reform a bad name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
