A2684 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBSTER-GIRLFRIEND-BO     09-18 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBSTER-GIRLFRIEND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON STAND, LONGTIME BULGER COMPANION ADDS LITTLE TO LORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She lived with gangster FBI informant James J.
``Whitey'' Bulger for 30 years and says she never knew his deepest
secrets. She didn't ask. And he didn't tell.
</P>
<P>
   That's just the way it was with Bulger, according to his
longtime companion, Teresa Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Still, US prosecutors called Stanley to the witness stand
Thursday, hoping she could refute defense claims that the FBI
warned Bulger to skip town on the eve of his January 1995
racketeering indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Although today Bulger is believed to be on the lam with another
girlfriend, he was with Stanley, driving back to Boston after a
sojourn in the South and West, when the warrant was issued for his
arrest. In an earlier interview with the Globe, Stanley said Bulger
heard on the car radio that investigators had nabbed his longtime
partner, Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi. That news, according to
Stanley, changed his plans and ultimately drove him away for good.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, after waiting in the hallway outside US District Judge
Mark Wolf's courtroom for more than three hours, Stanley, 57, took
the stand at the federal courthouse in Boston. She initially cited
her Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination when asked if
she knew James Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   Then Stanley, a soft-spoken woman with snow-white hair, was
granted immunity and compelled to testify against the man who had
treated her like a wife and helped raise her four children. She
testified for only 15 minutes, then was told that court was
suspended for the day and she'd have to return today.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanley's brief debut on the stand was long enough to
demonstrate that the ever-cautious Bulger was guarded even with
her.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1994, Bulger and Stanley vacationed in Dublin,
London, and Rome, where they traveled without an itinerary. In
fact, Stanley said, she was never told how long they'd be gone.
</P>
<P>
   They were home in South Boston for only a few weeks in November
1994, Stanley testified, when Bulger ``just said he wanted to go
away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he tell you where you were going?'' asked Assistant US
Attorney Fred Wyshak.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he tell you for how long you were going?'' Wyshak asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ask?'' Wyshak said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said she packed one bag for the trip and set off in a
car with Bulger, ending up in New York. She is expected to resume
testifying today, when she will be asked how Bulger learned he was
facing federal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi testified earlier that Bulger was warned by former FBI
supervisor John Morris that the indictment was about to be
returned. Morris, testifying under a grant of immunity, admitted
taking $7,000 in bribes from Bulger and Flemmi, but denied tipping
them to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   James G. Reardon, a Worcester lawyer who represents Stanley,
said, ``She's here to tell the truth exactly as she knows it.
She'll testify without any anger or hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley declined to comment Thursday, but in an interview with
the Globe in April she described her travels with Bulger in the
weeks before he became a wanted man.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving New York, the couple traveled to San Francisco and
then to New Orleans, she said. They were driving back to Boston
from Louisiana when Bulger heard on the car radio that Flemmi had
been arrested, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple stopped at a hotel for the night while Bulger
considered what to do, Stanley said. After deciding not to
surrender, Bulger dropped Stanley off at a Hingham restaurant and
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said, `See ya,' or something like that,'' Stanley
said. ``I have not heard from (Bulger) since he's been gone,'' she
said in the interview. ``I haven't laid eyes on him or spoken to
him. I don't know where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   But authorities say that on the same night he dropped Stanley
off in Hingham, he picked up Catherine Greig of Quincy, a woman he
had been seeing secretly for 20 of the 30 years he spent with
Stanley. Greig now faces charges of harboring a fugitive, and the
FBI has offered a $250,000 reward for Bulger's capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real womanizer,'' Stanley said. ``He was leading a
double life with me and a double life with the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley cooked dinner for Bulger nearly every night, and he
spent every holiday with her family. And yet, she said, she never
knew he was an FBI informant until it was revealed in federal court
last year, when Flemmi argued that the FBI allowed him and Bulger
to commit crimes in exchange for information about the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's testimony came in hearings launched in January to
explore allegations of FBI misconduct that could topple the case
against Flemmi, Bulger, reputed New England Mafia boss Francis
``Cadillac Frank'' Salemme, Robert DeLuca, and John Martorano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MONET-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     09-18 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MONET-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... including Sargent.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Londons,'' as he called them, made fog and soot romantic,
and made buildings and bridges blend in an opalescent haze. In
addition to admiring the dream-like dissolve Monet gave the British
capital, it's fun to trace the provenance of some of these
paintings. One oddity, the 1904 ``Houses of Parliament, Seagulls,''
includes a flock of birds, quick V-shapes that hover on the
surface, bringing the depths of the painting up for air.
``Seagulls'' was bought right out of its first and only Paris show,
by Sergei Shchukin, the visionary Moscow collector whose holdings,
including a total of 13 Monets, were nationalized after the Russian
Revolution. Shchukin's ``Seagulls'' now ``belongs'' to Moscow's
Pushkin Museum; its trip to Boston marks the first time it has been
seen outside Russia since the year it was painted.
</P>
<P>
   The last and largest of the Evans galleries includes a
staggering number of waterlilies _ 24, all but one from the
landmark 1909 show that saw Monet pushing the boundaries of his
art. He aimed at nothing less than besting those two younger stars,
Picasso and Matisse, by reinventing Impressionism. Scrapping the
horizon line, immersing himself in water, that's just what he did.
</P>
<P>
   What's wonderful about this room is the collision of the placid
and the explosive: You sense the artist fighting to grow. Some
tondo paintings seem demurely 19th century, cameo-like. Others,
like the 1907 water lilies owned by the Goteberg Museum of Art in
Sweden, are raw. The Goteberg picture has a tart, even jaundiced
palette, and slashing strokes. Monet so abstracted the subject here
that you can almost imagine the painting hanging upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The Venice pictures come next. Monet edited the fairytale
architecture, cropping the tops of palazzi to focus on facades
where recessed doorways are as mysterious as caves. Some of these
paintings, however exquisite, are also touristy. The most dramatic
are those painted from the island of San Giorgio Maggiore, which
have an asymmetrical, angular slice of pavement jutting up from the
bottom, an oddly contemporary touch. Had Monet stepped to the
water's edge, he would have had a far more conventional postcard
view.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the shocker, a room of waterlily studies that will
make you gasp. These huge, scribbly works didn't leave Monet's
studio during his lifetime, and one, a dazzling 1914-1919 ``Weeping
Willow and Water Lily Pond,'' has never been exhibited before. Its
barbaric tangled strokes have none of the gentle evanescence of
earlier Monet.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these works surfaced in the 1950s, just in time for the
powerful critic Clement Greenberg to proclaim these pictures the
root of the kind of abstraction he championed, conveniently
ignoring Monet's profound and permanent connection to nature. Not
everybody in the avant-garde has always agreed with Greenberg's
rewriting of the history of modernism. The Museum of Modern Art, no
less, deaccessioned one of the most radical of these sketchy works
in the MFA show _ one you might assume was abstract were it not for
the ``Water Lilies'' title _ in the late 1980s. Its permanent
residence is now the boardroom of Japan's Asahi Breweries, Inc., a
company that has also built a Monet mini-museum outside Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
   Of a trio of circa 1917-1922 waterlilies in the MFA show, one
that the artist considered finished, two that he regarded as
studies, it's the latter that most appeal to contemporary
sensibilities attuned to spontaneity and process-oriented art. The
weeping willows that follow these works have an agitated,
anthropomorphic presence. Their trunks seem engaged in a
shamanistic dance; their spooky environs could be the set for a
Wagnerian opera.
</P>
<P>
   Late in life, Monet revisited that Japanese bridge he'd made
into an icon _ but with what a difference! The early bridges make
you yearn to be there, under that wisteria canopy; the late ones,
from around 1920, fairly snarl at you. And so crusted with paint
are the late ones that in some, it's hard to discern a bridge at
all. These are anguished canvases, overheated and apocalyptic. It's
easy to imagine Monet working at not being pretty here, in the same
way that some contemporary glass artists try to make an ugly work
in their medium, which is an automatically alluring one. This was
also the era of Monet's cataract surgery: There is much speculation
about the state of his eyesight when he made the works in this
room.
</P>
<P>
   Grandeur and generosity of scale and spirit mark the
exhibition's last gallery. Plenty of previous painters had tackled
canvases this big, but generally their works were on themes of
history or myth, not landscape _ certainly not on so narrowly
focused a landscape, nor on one that so bared the artist's soul.
These ``Grandes Decorations'' prophesy installation art and
earthworks. But what a shame it would be to see them only as
beacons pointing the way to the future; they're so much more. Be
prepared to surrender yourself to these panoramas, to enter their
end-of-the-world wooziness. ``End'' is what Monet must have known
they were; he was, after all, in his 80s when he made them.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest of these final works at the MFA is ``The Water-Lily
Pond'' from the Kunsthaus in Zurich, a painting nearly 20 feet
across. Dark clouds encroach from either side. For the moment, they
fail to reach the golden heart of the piece. You feel you're
looking down onto a world in microcosm, reflected in the water. But
Monet also creates a sense of elegy and inevitable leave-taking.
You first sense yourself being pulled into this beauty; ultimately,
you're pulled away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
