<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTENDERS TRY TO GET TO THE FORE IN THE WOODWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Free House and Gentlemen from the West, and Skip Away and
Coronado's Quest from the East, were entered Thursday for
Saturday's $500,000 Woodward Stakes at Belmont Park in New York. If
all four face the starter, the 1 1/8-mile Woodward would contain
without question the most talented field assembled to this point in
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Free House, Gentlemen, and 6-5 morning line favorite Skip Away,
who is 6 for 6 in 1998 and the leading candidate to be Horse of the
Year, are all handicap division powerhouses.
</P>
<P>
   The horse risking the most is Coronado's Quest, the only
3-year-old in the race. A former bad boy, Coronado's Quest has
redeemed hmself, winning five in a row, including the Haskell at
Monmouth and the Travers at Saratoga, against felllow sophomores.
Entering Coronado's Quest, who now has a long-shot chance to be
Horse of the Year, against the iron was a brave act by trainer Shug
McGaughey, who could have shipped him to Louisiana Downs to run in
the Super Derby Sept. 27 against horses his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the Woodward,'' said McGaughey. ``This
looks like as tough a race as I've ever been in, but I'm looking
forward to walking over to the Belmont paddock instead of spending
a week in Shreveport. I know he's up against it. He'll be running
against seasoned pros. But to run a 3-year-old against older
horses, you have to have a horse with experience and talent, and
we've got that. If you're going to do it, this is the time of year.
We'll get a little bit of weight (3-year-olds carry 121 pounds in
the Woodward, older horses 126), and the older horses have been
lugging a lot of weight all year. They're maybe not as fast as they
were in July. I'm hoping that Coronado's Quest is starting to
improve and maybe he's on the same level as the older horses right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woodward probably will be the second-to-last career race for
Coronado's Quest. Owner Stuart Janney has announced that the gifted
son of Forty Niner will be retired to Claiborne Farm at the end of
the year, likely after the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic at
Churchill Downs Nov. 7. Janney indicated that the downside to
racing Coronado's Quest as a 4-year-old would be a necessary return
to Florida, where the horse acted badly last winter, including for
the Breeders' Cup, which is at Gulfstream next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the Travers and Haskell with him is what I set out to
do,'' said McGaughey. ``Now we'll just see how he can do against
these older horses. Basically, the pressure is off. He's doing
fine. He's at home. I'm not worried about that other stuff
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Running Stag, an invader from Europe, was the fifth Woodward
entrant. A 4-year-old son of Cozzene, Running Stag has won only
three of 20 starts but captured a Group III race on the turf in
France. ``I beleive he is the best dirt horse in the United
Kingdom,'' said trainer Phillip Mitchell, who saddled hin to an
allowance tally over a dirt course at Lingfield earlier this
sesson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
