<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS KNOW THAT MCNAIR CAN GIVE THEM A RUN-AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ This much you can predict about Tennessee
Oilers quarterback Steve McNair. When the Oilers' offense takes the
field against the Patriots here Sunday, the fourth-year veteran
will step up to the line of scrimmage and, upon calling signals,
take the snap from center.
</P>
<P>
   What's likely to happen after that was one of the main topics at
Patriots practice Thursday, according to coach Pete Carroll. Ask
the coach or any player about McNair's options and you get varying
answers but one theme.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Force the signal-caller out of the pocket and he'll dash forward
with the speed and power of a running back. Make him go east to
west, cut off the running lanes, and he can throw a spiral across
his body downfield to the open receiver the defensive backs ignored
while trying to get in on the pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   Put him in a grasp and he'll shake your hold with one motion,
then start over again. Corner him for an arm tackle and you'll
discover how difficult an agile 6-foot-2-inch, 225-pound frame is
to bring down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those quarterbacks that's not afraid to run it. A
lot of guys are scared. They throw it away,'' said Patriots free
safety Willie Clay, who will try to contain the multiple threat who
is eighth in the AFC in passing efficiency while averaging 8 yards
a carry. ``This guy is looking to make a play every time.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair, who has never played against the Patriots, has run or
thrown for a touchdown in 19 of 24 NFL starts. He is fourth in the
league in third-quarter passing _ 7 of 14 for 98 yards and a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   He did not avoid the rash of injuries that bedeviled NFL
quarterbacks the first two weeks. He suffered an elbow injury in
the first half of the opener against Cincinnati but came back last
week to rush for a team-high 31 yards on just three carries in a
13-7 loss to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``He breaks a lot of tackles and a lot of sacks,'' said
defensive end Willie McGinest, who offered a critique of McNair
that would rival that of any NFL scout. ``He brings something else
a lot of quarterbacks don't bring to the table _ there are only a
few who do, like (Mark) Brunell and (John) Elway _ and that's
speed. He can get outside and he can throw on the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a strong arm, so that makes it hard for defensive backs
to come up and try to contain him, because if they leave their guys
in coverage, he can usually hit them downfield. He also has good
awareness of where the rush is and he can see guys coming from his
back side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so quick he can let you get close and spin out with a
quick juke move. He usually sends guys flying. We want him to move
around because any quarterback is not as accurate if he's on the
run, but we have to be careful we don't give up any big yardage on
third down because of his scrambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the Chargers. McNair avoided several would-be tackles
and sacks against San Diego last week to complete 20 of 34 passes
for 193 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``(San Diego was) all over him and he slips out of there and
he's out of nowhere,'' said Carroll. ``That's the fact that is
difficult that we are stressing a great deal in particular,
Thursdayjust so we can adapt to the quarterback running.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Patriots haven't seen running, scrambling
quarterbacks before. Elway, Brunell, and Pittsburgh's Kordell
Stewart have had success out of the pocket. But McNair, though not
possessing the passing numbers of those three, has more options.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has that same type of speed, but the one thing that
separates him from those guys is he's stronger,'' said Ty Law.
``He's not going to go down with an arm tackle. He's like a
fullback playing quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   This season he has more weapons with which to work, with the
acquisition of former Pittsburgh Steelers wide receiver Yancey
Thigpen. Still, Carroll believes the Oilers are bent on being a
running team _ despite the troubles of Eddie George (15 carries, 11
yards last week).
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to get back to their running emphasis,'' said
Carroll. ``I think they got out of the mode they'd like to be as
far as hammering the football. They have very good receivers. If
they can get the running game going, they will have the balance
they're seeking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
