<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First lady shows poise under pressure
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The only figure in the Clinton-Lewinsky-Starr lineup
who has consistently exhibited dignity is first lady Hillary
Clinton. While independent counsel Kenneth Starr, son of a
fundamentalist preacher, rejected legal writing for pulp fiction,
and ``family values'' lawmakers nodded for the lurid sex report to
go on the Internet for the world's young people to read, Mrs.
Clinton issued a simple statement, saying she remains committed to
her marriage. Then she proceeded to carry out her normal duties
with calm competence.
</P>
<P>
   And for her loyalty in the face of unprecedented embarrassment,
she's being criticized not by her political enemies but by feminist
friends who say her trailblazing independence is forever tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary can't direct her energies toward social policy if she's
busy maintaining ``domestic tranquility,'' cried Wendy Wasserstein,
prize-winning playwright, in a New York Times opinion piece. Well,
why not? Wasn't feminism about allowing women to be the complex
beings they are instead of simplistic stereotypes?
</P>
<P>
   I have seen and heard the first lady close-up, though I'm no
close friend, and I'm not at all surprised by her poise under
pressure. She was in my home on two occasions when I was practicing
law in Denver, once to tape ``PrimeTime Live'' at the height of the
Gennifer Flowers flap. After answering two hours of questions from
Sam Donaldson, she drew the line on her time and rushed back to
Little Rock for Chelsea's dance performance. She hurriedly ate a
tuna sandwich in my kitchen, apologized for the ABC cameras' black
marks on my light wood floors and later sent me flowers the color
of my living room drapes.
</P>
<P>
   The part of the interview that stood out in my mind was edited
out. Nobody but the ABC crew and a handful of aides and onlookers
ever heard her comments about the need for equal partnership in
marriage or the differing strengths she and her husband have as
lawyers. Essentially, she said, she liked being an advocate, going
to bat for a cause, while her husband was better at conflict
resolution _ negotiation and compromise _ skills suited to
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Her approach to speaking of the president has been unwavering.
She does not gush as if he were some superior being _ the penchant
of political wives. She speaks respectfully of his policy
decisions, nothing more. How she conveyed that respect again last
week in an introduction at a fund-raiser was a wonder _ but she did
it.
</P>
<P>
   Scandal aside, the Clintons' relationship is none of our
business, and it has nothing to do with feminism.
</P>
<P>
   Women of all political persuasions should appreciate this first
lady's effective advocacy of policies that benefit women and
children. From the committee rooms of the U.S. Congress to the
villages of Africa to the controversial podium of the Beijing
Women's Conference, she has used her position to strengthen
families. (History, I believe, will credit her for pushing health
care issues to the top of the policy agenda in Congress, which has
resulted in positive legislation, though many still call her work a
failure.) That legacy cannot be taken away from her, whether Bill
Clinton's presidency survives or not.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, after listening to Mrs. Clinton address a women's group
in my home, I attended an event at which then-Gov. Bill Clinton
spoke. It was a small gathering, and most of us shook his hand on
the way out. I told him jokingly that I had come to see if he was
as splendid a speaker as his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``She sets a high standard, doesn't she?'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Higher than his. Then and now.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
