<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-CONFUSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLITZ OF NUMBERS BAFFLES SHORT-DISTANCE CALLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hope Carmines likes to travel a lot now that she's retired from
her job as a nurse in Edenton, N.C. She doesn't much care, however,
for one previously simple task that she has to perform in each new
city she visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know from place to place just how to dial the
telephone,'' she said while waiting for her luggage at Logan
Airport. ``After a while you get used to just about anything, I
guess, but it still drives me absolutely crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   She's got a lot of company.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so long ago that you had to dial just seven digits to
reach someone within your dialing area, plus a ``1'' at the
beginning for a toll call elsewhere in your state. Anywhere.
Anytime. But not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Even people who learn the rules for their home regions today
aren't likely to know them for the states next door _ and don't
even know whether to dial seven, eight, 10, or 11 digits. Or
they're thrown for a loop when flying into a new place and
discovering that the airport has a different area code than the
downtown it serves. Or can't figure out whether to put in a quarter
(or is it 35 cents?) before or after dialing a pay phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at home it drives you nuts,'' said Victor Tartaro, an
insurance agent who lives in Newton. ``With the 617s and the 781s
and the 978s and all the long-distance carriers trying to get your
business ... and then there's all the different kinds of billings
for different phones. It's just insane sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   While America's technological revolution is changing many
aspects of everyday life, it's the intriguing and
imagination-stirring new inventions and processes _ the Internet,
for example _ that get the most attention. Few technologies touch
people's lives more directly than the telephone, however, and the
modifications taking place in its use provide a vivid example of
how modernization can turn previously simple tasks into complicated
and frustrating operations.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, little about using the phone has remained constant since
the breakup of the AT&AMP;T monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The number of local and long-distance carriers seems to grow
daily, as evidenced by the dinnertime solicitations many people
receive, forcing consumers to deal with choices they never had to
consider before. Likewise, the proliferation of alternatives for
making calls, particularly with access numbers and credit cards,
leads many people to dial 35 digits or more to save money when
placing long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   On all those issues, though, people can make choices. But when
it comes to making a local call, what you get is what you get _ and
what you get today is fragmented and uncoordinated because each
state makes its own decisions on how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, if you go to Maryland, you've got to dial 10 digits every
time, 11 if the person being contacted is outside the immediate
calling area, which you'll learn from the recording telling you to
hang up and try again. Go to California and it's 11 key punches
even if you call next door, a consequence of the state's 22 area
codes _ heading up to 23 in two months.
</P>
<P>
   Even within a given state, say, Massachusetts, the explosion of
area codes _ from two in 1988 to five today _ often makes it
difficult for residents to know which adjoining jurisdictions are
local and therefore exactly which, not to mention how many, numbers
to dial. (Dial isn't the right word anymore, of course, but no one
seems to have come up with a better one.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a point where one has to ask how many nuisances
you have to accept,'' said Richard Tedlow, a professor of business
and technology at the Harvard Business School. ``And there is that
sort-of psychic tariff today that didn't exist when you used to
have just one phone company. ... I think cumulatively, except for
people up to speed on these technological advances, it adds to the
sense that you have less and less control over the environment in
which you live.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Cooprider, an associate professor of computer information
systems at Bentley College in Waltham, Mass., suggested that the
designers of increasingly sophisticated equipment were to blame for
not taking into account the ability of consumers to adapt to
innovation. Rather than build in ways to make a product easier to
use, for instance, Cooprider said inventors tend to think only
about how far they can advance technologically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way a user uses it is really irrelevant to many
technologists,'' Cooprider said, ``and I think that's very true,
even especially true, of telephones.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of area codes, regulators do seem to be trying to
provide a smooth road _ but they've been left with few easy options
because of the seemingly ceaseless explosion of computers, cell
phones, fax machines, and start-up phone companies that buy tens of
thousands of lines to resell. The result is that all the numbers in
some area codes are running out, so more digits and new area codes
are added.
</P>
<P>
   Many specialists believe it will be only a few more years before
nearly every state, except perhaps low-population ones like Montana
and New Hampshire, will require 10- or 11-digit dialing for local
calls. And sometime in the longer term, they believe, all 792
possible area codes will be assigned; so far, 260 have been.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, analysts foresee more and more people talking
to computers in the future, especially while they work their way
through long series of options to connect to the person or
department they want. ``That's what I find most annoying, not
getting to talk to real people anymore,'' said Deanne Josephson of
Brookline, Mass., an advertising agency producer.
</P>
<P>
   This multinumbered, mechanical vision of the future conjures
fears that making any call could become a nightmarish experience,
particularly for people who have trouble remembering all the phone
numbers they need already. But most specialists predict other
technologies will come along to alleviate the aggravation and even
make phone use easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``All revolutions take longer than expected, and the changes
they cause are more fundamental than expected,'' said Samuel Simon,
chairman of the Washington-based Telecommunications Research and
Action Center, a nonprofit consumer-advocacy organization. ``We're
at an early and most irritating stage of all that in terms of the
telephone, but we'll get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Deak, who oversees Lockheed-Martin's government-directed job
of administering the implementation of additional area codes around
the United States, was among several specialists who predicted that
fewer Americans in the future were likely to try to remember phone
numbers, while more would carry electronic devices that either
store or dial them. More also will use their computers to dial,
while others will increasingly use the Intenet rather than any
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these innovations already are available and in use,
along with Caller ID systems that automatically return calls
without the user needing to know the number being dialed. Voice
activation also is expected to become commonplace, perhaps allowing
consumers to simply tell their phones to ``call Mom'' rather than
dialing or saying any numbers at all.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, most analysts believe people get enough benefits from
newfangled systems _ from lower rates to convenient use (such as
cordless phones) to easy message recording _ that they are willing
to live with short-term hassles. And the analysts maintain the
irritations won't last, because they are more the result of
people's difficulty in adapting to any change than the result of
any complexity of the innovations themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of readjusting,'' said Ellen Langer, a
psychology professor at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that people aren't finding the situations
caused by telephones stressful; they are,'' she added. ``People buy
into the notion that life is becoming more complicated. But
whenever there's a transition, people go through this. ... In the
end, they'll get used to it. It's no big deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
