<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CASINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATIONALIZING ROULETTE: GAMBLING IN JERICHO  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; JERICHO, West Bank _ In the land of the Bible, people for
thousands of years have learned about the high and lasting price of
sin.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Israelis and Palestinians who flocked to the grand
opening of a new casino here this week dismissed warnings from
Orthodox Jewish rabbis and conservative Muslim sheiks alike about
the sin of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Yeshiva students in black yarmulkes played roulette
while women in traditional Islamic dress hovered around the
blackjack tables. Israeli surfers with ponytails and Teva sandals
lined up to buy chips as Palestinian Authority officials tried to
remain invisible. Russian immigrant tough guys in open shirt
collars and Star-of-David gold chains mingled with glittery Tel
Aviv types who are heavily into spandex and body piercing.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the entire cast of characters in the long, bloody
drama that is Israel and Palestine put aside their religious and
political differences to put down bets.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Shteren, 26, a Yeshiva student spreading his chips on the
roulette table, said, ``The Torah says not to gamble, but I gamble.
There's money in it. I do it for fun and money. I think God's OK
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou'ai Izheman, 35, a Palestinian hotel worker from a devout
Muslim family in Jerusalem's Old City, pushed his week's earnings
through the slot at the cashier's window to collect $200 in chips.
``My family doesn't know I'm here,'' he confided. ``They wouldn't
like it. But if I win, they'll like it. And I don't think Allah
will mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oasis, which opened to the public Wednesday night, is a $50
million venture that is majority-owned by Austrians. There have
been Israeli and Palestinian news reports as well that one of
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's chief aides, Khaled Salam, is a
large investor in the venture, and that other Palestinian officials
helped the casino to open. Once the casino turns a profit, the
Palestinian Authority will take a healthy 25 percent of revenues in
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Oasis captures the surreal contradictions of
life in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   First, it is located in the Palestinian-controlled West Bank
because the Israeli government, bowing to the powerful Jewish
orthodox lobby, does not allow casinos on its soil. Nonetheless,
casino advertising targets Israelis, who have flocked for years to
casinos just across the border in Taba, Egypt. Oasis is expecting
big crowds over the High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Palestinian Authority permits casinos, most
Palestinians are traditional Muslims who avoid gambling because it
is ``haram,'' or a sin, in Islam. Even if they did, the Palestinian
Authority, bowing to pressure from powerful Islamic
fundamentalists, formally bans them from the casino. The spiritual
leader of the Islamic movement, Hamas Sheik Ahmed Yassin, called it
``Satan's casino.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Palestinians can skirt the ban by using their Israeli
employment identity cards. Still others can use passports from
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night, the Palestinian parking attendants checked the
trunks of cars for bombs. At the door, guests passed through a set
of metal detectors. Amid the flickering lights and bells of the
slot machines, Palestinians and Israelis gambled side by side. The
decorum was Las Vegas kitsch, with ``elements of the Orient,'' as a
brochure put it.
</P>
<P>
   The casino has 35 gaming tables, 220 slot machines, a bar
serving cheap, strong drinks, and a restaurant. Kosher? Not by a
long shot. The ``Jackpots Cafe'' menu features bacon, a bald insult
to observant Jews and Muslims alike.
</P>
<P>
   Saeb Erekat, a senior official in the Palestinian Authority and
chief negotiator for the stalled peace process, lives in Jericho
and has been a vocal opponent of the casino. ``We are the oldest
city in the world, but we are actually a very small town,'' he
said. ``We are puritans. We are a Christian and Muslim society with
deep family values, and we don't want a casino and all that it
brings in terms of drugs and prostitution and fast money.''
</P>
<P>
   And gambling is only the beginning. There are grandiose plans
for the addition of a luxury hotel, swimming pool, and golf course
as well. Alexander Tucek, director general of the resort, said,
``Our role, together with the Palestinian Authority, will be to
create jobs, which is the first step of all people to create peace.
Our role is not to touch any religious or political questions.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Palestinian leaders, like Erekat, scoffed at the notion
that the casino will somehow bring people together in the spirit of
the peace process. ``Palestinians and Israelis don't need to get
together at a gambling table,'' he said. ``They need to get
together over dinner tables, and at negotiating tables, and board
tables in business, but not a gambling table.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the majority of gamblers Wednesday night were cynical about
the ability of a casino to pave a path to peace. ``The casino wants
to make money. People want a chance to win. And that's it. Don't
look beyond that because there's nothing there,'' said Habib Nimri,
40, an Israeli Arab who works as a tax collector.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few people who felt that the casino could contribute
to peace was Ilana Haimovich, a librarian in Farsaba, who only came
to accompany her husband, Nimrod, an arson investigator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't gamble. Never in my life,'' she said. ``But this place
is very pretty really. I think it will be very good for the people
of Jericho that Israelis come and do shopping and eating. It's good
for them and it will be good for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband pulled hard on a cigarette and rolled his eyes.
``Everybody looks after their own pocket,'' he said. ``This has
nothing to do with peace, only has to do with whether you win or
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the casino say Jericho, a faded city of 25,000,
benefits because of the 400 jobs that the casino has created. But
at least half of those jobs have gone to European veterans of the
casino circuit and many to Israelis as well.
</P>
<P>
   At night, it is difficult to tell from its front entrance that
the casino is located directly across the street from the Akbet
Jaber United Nations Refugee Camp, where 5,000 Palestinians live in
cracked mud huts with tin roofs, open sewers, and garbage-strewn
streets.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority are devout Muslims from traditional families
who refuse to work at the casino on religious grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Yaghi, 40, who still lives in the refugee camp where he
was born, said, ``I don't believe it will bring jobs. We always
hear promises here. Promises from the UN, the Israelis, the
Palestinian Authority, and now the casino. They are all liars. What
we need are factories, housing that will provide jobs and a good
life for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   On a scorching day this week, Jamal Samarat, 22, was breaking
bricks with a hammer for a sidewalk that leads to the casino. He
makes about $25 a day. He explained that he was brought to the
casino by the Israeli contractor for whom he has worked for two
years. He protested, but was told that he would lose his job if he
refused to work there. ``I have to work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Samarat blames not the Israelis for the casino, but the
Palestinian Authority officials who made it a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to make money at the sake of our Islamic principles.
This is the core of corruption,'' he said. ``God destroyed Jericho
once before and after this casino he will destroy it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
