<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS FROM THE HYDE AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scooped again.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after Clinton testified for the grand jury and then,
unwisely, tired and angry and wrung out, went on TV to talk
Monica-talk, I sat in as guest host of C-SPAN's morning call-in
show on national politics. That same day, a viewer in Florida wrote
to me: ``I just caught you on C-SPAN, and ...''
</P>
<P>
   For seven years, the writer had been aware that one of his
friends, a regular tennis partner, bore a grudge against US
Representative Henry Hyde, Republican of Illinois and chairman of
the Judiciary Committee that is now mounting the impeachment drive
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde is one of the GOP's elder statesmen, elected to Congress 24
years ago from Chicago's western suburbs, an Irish Catholic
conservative whose name is on ``the Hyde Amendment'' banning
federal funding of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The letter writer wanted The Boston Globe to know that Hyde had
cuckolded his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This `family values' salesman broke up my friend's family ...
my friend was seriously damaged economically and emotionally,
permanently and irreparably, and his family was left dysfunctional.
Hyde took advantage of my friend and his former wife by using his
superior status (successful lawyer and state legislator) to seduce
a young mother (of three children) and have a 5 1/2-year affair
with her, while still managing to maintain his own marriage. So
much for his version of `family values.'''
</P>
<P>
   The writer was obviously hostile to Hyde and the conservatives
running Congress, and angry at ``the amount and volume of hypocrisy
in this lengthy and vigorous effort to bring our president down''
and offered to make his friend available to confirm the tale and
make public this ``Jekyll and Hyde story.''
</P>
<P>
   I turned a copy of the letter over to an experienced Globe
colleague, who talked to the letter-writer, the husband who had
been victimized, and confirmed details: His wife, then mother to
three kids aged 5, 8 and 9, ran an unlicensed hair salon in her
basement. The 6-year old son began telling his dad of a man named
``Hank'' who called often; mom began staying out late.
</P>
<P>
   ``The couple (Hyde and the hairdresser) went to restaurants and
ballgames together, traveled together. Hyde bought her a Lincoln
convertible, pink luggage, jewelry, set her up in an apartment and
set her up in business for herself.'' The hairdresser's husband,
after his divorce, a remarriage to the same woman, and a second
divorce, later remarried and divorced again, ``is quite bitter,''
my colleague found. ``He never remarried. He says that the affair
screwed up his marriage and the divorce screwed up his three
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Globe editors decided not to publish the story initially, a
decision that will confound right-wing media bashers. The on-line
magazine Salon broke the tale Wednesday. A Reuters account in
Thursday's Globe said that the Los Angeles Times, Miami Herald, and
Globe ``had all turned down an opportunity to do the story.''
Hyde's office put out a press release: ``The statute of limitations
has long since passed on my youthful indiscretions,'' which began
when he was in his 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde called the story ``an obvious attempt to intimidate me and
it won't work.'' With the sort of unthinking partisanship for which
he is noted, Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas blamed ``the Clinton
attack dogs'' for promoting the story. DeLay is completely off
base; the cuckolded husband has been telling his friends his tale
of woe for years, the Globe check showed.
</P>
<P>
   The real lesson of Henry Hyde's Scarlet Letter is the Bible's
oldest: ``Let him who is without sin cast the first stone.'' With
the same sort of hubris in their power that led them to shut down
the government, the Sun Belt conservatives running Congress felt
they could tear down Clinton while avoiding any damage to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For the lipreaders in Congress, who don't understand how the
devil-ray of scandal harms those who shine it as well as those upon
whom it is shined, I will explain how this works:
</P>
<P>
   First the dime drops; then the shoe drops; and then your
reputation drops. You start splashing around in the mud, and your
nice dress shirt gets muddy. No one in politics got into power
without making mistakes, enemies, and misleading statements about
some embarrassing moment or other. That's human nature. But it's
also human nature to suspect duplicity in harshly partisan
political skunkfights.
</P>
<P>
   This Monica business has gone nuclear. There's radioactive waste
all over Washington, and the media act like the devilish winds that
wafted radioactivity thousands of miles from Chernobyl, spreading
cigar tales and DNA-drenched stains everywhere. Not every news
medium picks up every scrap of garbage. But some one will print it,
sooner or later, and then we all recycle the garbage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightline'' began as the nightly chronicle of the Iran hostage
outrage. Cable news networks thrived on O.J. gore. Now the Lady in
the Black Beret is the profit center for all those double-digit
channels on the cable box. And the longer the Republicans screw
around with impeachment, the more exposed they become to just the
sort of dime-dropping that nicked Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Congress's biggest foe of abortion is unmasked as a
long-time-ago adulturer. Mr. Family Values broke up another man's
family. The stain is not just on that infamous blue dress. The
stain is spreading. This Congress is not squeaky-clean; no Congress
ever is. There'll be more collateral damage if impeachment talk
lasts beyond the midterm elections in November. The warning signs
abound: don't go there, or you may be next.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
