<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DIGGING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DIGGING' IS A TENDER MINIATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DIGGING TO CHINA 
Directed by: Timothy Hutton 
Screenplay by: Karen Janszen 
Starring: Kevin Bacon, Evan Rachel Wood, Cathy Moriarty, Mary
Stuart Masterson, Marian Seldes 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Rated: PG (thematic elements and some emotional moments) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actor Timothy Hutton ably follows the less-is-more route in his
directing debut, ``Digging to China,'' keeping the canvas small,
but filling it artfully and with a sensitive, tender eye for
behavioral nuance. It adds Evan Rachel Wood to the list of
expressive child actors as the film's protagonist. Harriet is an
unhappy 10-year-old longing for a UFO to rescue her from her drab
rural Pennsylvania '60s milieu, where her alcoholic mother (Cathy
Moriarty) halfheartedly runs a motel and an older sister, Gwen
(Mary Stuart Masterson), distracts herself with promiscuity. If the
UFO doesn't show, she's willing to start digging and come out on
the other side of the world; hence the film's title.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Harriet's world expands with the arrival of a
character whose world is shrinking, and who knows it. Kevin Bacon's
childlike Ricky is about to be delivered to a permanent-care
institution by his mother (Marian Seldes), who has been diagnosed
with terminal cancer. When their car breaks down en route to the
institution, they check into the motel until repairs can be made,
and a friendship develops between Harriet and Ricky. Just as they
reach a fragile equilibrium, based on Ricky's ability to empathize
with Harriet's desire for escape, Harriet's mother dies in a car
crash, whereupon a family secret is revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Masterson's Gwen starts mothering Harriet as if to make up for
lost time, which means trouble for Harriet's sweetly platonic
friendship with the retarded but exquisitely sensitive Ricky.
Bacon, given a new kind of acting stretch, never overdoes the
physical dimension of the role and achieves the film's most
poignant moment when he looks into the future. All the women, from
the youngest to the oldest, take their material to the max,
convincingly running a gamut from innocent camaraderie to hollow
weariness.
</P>
<P>
   All the characters are sympathetic, or at least not badly
motivated, especially Bacon during Ricky's moments when his face
tells us he knows that to do what Harriet asks is to invite
trouble. But he does it anyway, out of a desire to please her,
right to the end. Obviously, Hutton remembered from his acting
debut in ``Ordinary People'' that details matter. This film is
meticulously crafted, keenly observed, beautifully gauged in climax
after climax. ``Digging to China'' confirms Hutton's abilities and
instincts and whets our appetite for his next directing assignment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
