<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ONE-TRUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHENTIC PERFORMANCES DEEPEN `ONE TRUE THING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
ONE TRUE THING 
Directed by: Carl Franklin 
Screenplay by: Karen Croner, based on Anna Quindlen's novel  
Starring: Meryl Streep, Renee Zellweger, William Hurt, Tom Everett
Scott, Nancy Katt, Lauren Graham 
Running time: 128 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you think Meryl Streep's woman hollowed out by illness
in ``One True Thing'' is going to be all technique, with no
emotional jolts, she swings around and zings you with a
tough-mindedness that wipes away all the dithery domestic
role-playing and overpitched cheerfulness in which she had been
trafficking. Pale and raccoon-eyed under layers of makeup, her
character reminds us in one extraordinary assertion of personality
that she's no victim now, and, what's more, never had been one,
despite appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, her grown daughter, played by Renee Zellweger as if
from a briar patch of tension and love and anger, had been raging
at her selfish father, partly on her mother's behalf, but also for
her own reasons. Zellweger's Ellen Gulden is the counterweight in
Anna Quindlen's novel about an ambitious journalist yanked off the
career express in Manhattan to return to her family home in an
upstate college town to care for her mother. She's tart and
impatient, so much so that you can't help wondering if Quindlen
borrowed her last name from a popular brand of mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, played in one of his more memorable displays of
lockjawed emotional stinginess by William Hurt, is an academic and
enough of a literary light to have won a National Book Award. Yet
he's insecure enough and egocentric enough to feel he has to crush
what he sees as competition from his daughter. He dismisses her
career by ignoring it, then laying a few empty homilies on her.
Making it clear that his career is too important to interrupt, but
that his daughter's is not, he guilt-trips her home, then hides on
campus from his wife's needs and his daughter's resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Matters are exacerbated by Ellen's inability to continue her
freelance writing from her parents' home and, more wrenchingly, by
the fact that she has always looked down her nose at what she
perceives as her mother's trivialized world filled with meaningless
activity _ ladies club lunches, volunteer work, artsy-craftsy
decorating projects. When Ellen's mother, Kate, stages a costume
birthday party for her husband and dresses as Dorothy from the
Wizard of Oz, Ellen is ready to scream. Instead, she lapses into
begging for scraps of approval from her father, whom she has
idealized.
</P>
<P>
   His cruel reward to Ellen for asking her to take on her mother's
care is an offer to let Ellen write the introduction to his next
book of essays. As Kate's confinement continues, Ellen's view of
her parents shifts. Her father's stock falls, her mother's rises,
and Ellen finds herself growing and deepening. Finally, she
realizes how horrifyingly apt her mother's choice of costume was,
that her father, like the Wizard of the Emerald City, is something
of a humbug, and that her mother's lifelong denial _ so
astonishingly and completely repudiated _ was a kind of strength
and mercy, not stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   Streep's acting is filled with mature mastery, more internalized
than her previous bravura performances. And Zellweger holds the
screen with her, scene for scene, deepening her capacity for
projecting waspish anger with a weight and gravity that leave us in
no doubt that she, too, is a formidable personality. The film's
framing device seems superfluous, and the ending succumbs to
sentimentality. But ``One True Thing,'' which represents an
impressive change of pace for ``Devil in a Blue Dress'' and ``One
False Move'' director Carl Franklin, delivers the emotional goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
