<HEADER>
A2718 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-MERRY-BOS &LR;      09-18 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MERRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A MERRY WAR' AIMS FOR ORWELLIAN BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A MERRY WAR 
Directed by: Robert Bierman 
Screenplay by: Alan Plater 
Starring: Richard E. Grant, Helena Bonham Carter, Julian Wadham,
Jim Carter, Harriet Walter, Lesley Vickerage 
Running time: 101 minutes 
Rated: Unrated 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Merry War'' is a nice try that doesn't quite nail the
double-edged complexity of its target, George Orwell's gently
satiric novel, ``Keep the Aspidistra Flying.'' One says gently
satiric because one of the things Orwell was satirizing was himself
in his portrayal of a successful ad man turned impoverished poet
and thinking himself pure because he's chasing his muse instead of
Mammon. Still, Mammon is never far off in the wings and Orwell's
novel is always aware that the hubris of the would-be poet is a
little silly. The truth is that Orwell was at least as
affectionately disposed toward the lower middle class as he was
contemptuous toward it, and he knew it. The leafy green house plant
in the window of any respectable house with curtains was at least
as reassuringly comforting to him as it was a symbol of
capitulation to mindless conformity.
</P>
<P>
   The film, while handsomely mounted, is a bit too single-stranded
to capture the ironies and contradictions of the novel. Richard E.
Grant's Orwell surrogate, Gordon Comstock, is a bit too exclusively
manic and wide-eyed. There's little of the Orwellian mix of slyness
and anger in this bumptuous Comstock, who's acute enough to mock
the left-wing poses of his rich publisher, but conveniently blind
to the fact that he pays for a minimally fancy lunch in the country
with his girlfriend with money borrowed from the hard-earned tips
of his spinster sister working for starvation wages as a waitress
in a tea shop. Not even stylishly arrogant (his publisher fills
that slot), he's merely loud and toilsome.
</P>
<P>
   Helena Bonham Carter, as Comstock's patient girlfriend who
considers herself lucky to have her illustrator's job in the depths
of an economic depression (the story takes place in 1934), becomes
the sympathetic character by default, the one who keeps her wits
about her while the man she loves goes off the deep end on the
strength of a favorable review of his slim book of poetry, a review
he doesn't find out until later was written by his publisher. What
does emerge is a picture of all the people close to Comstock
putting up with his nonsense with more than a little grace. Ditto
for the inhabitants of his descent through the social order, from a
bed-sitter in Camden Town to a squalid but comfortably unbuttoned
neighborhood in Lambeth.
</P>
<P>
   The political incorrectness that emerges intact from the pages
of Orwell's affectionate lampoon of British life is refreshing, but
the pieties about money and purity seem banal in the pop-eyed
earnestness with which they are unrelievedly uttered. His
sentimentalizing of the poor puts you in mind of Preston Sturges'
patronizing Hollywood director in ``Sullivan's Travels,'' deciding
to mix anonymously with the underclass in order to add authenticity
to his impending social protest film called ``O Brother, Where Art
Thou?'' The kindness and patience of Bonham Carter's and Wadham's
servitors of capitalism are, in the end, what make ``A Merry War''
worth seeing for more than its picture-postcard views of
Depression-era London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
