<SLUG> BC-FANTASY-FOOTBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALING BEGINS WITH BIGGER LOSERS FOR LOCAL TEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - This week, we get a first-hand look at the difference
between college and pro football.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Sun Devils and the Cardinals. Arizona State is off to a
bad start (see national title hopes: dashed), losing to Washington
and Brigham Young, mostly because its secondary developed a
pathological fear of opposing receivers.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, ASU gets a breather, the 0-2 Eagles from North
Texas, who have been getting knocked down ever since they stepped
up to Division I.
</P>
<P>
   Then you have the Cardinals. Arizona is off to a bad start (see
playoff hopes: dashed), losing to Dallas and Seattle, mostly
because the West Coast offense went surfing.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, Arizona, instead of a cream puff, must play the
0-2 Eagles from Philadelphia, who . . .
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. Maybe there isn't much difference after all.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Beagles in town, that old fantasy football adage
comes to mind: You can always mine mediocre teams for good talent.
</P>
<P>
   After all, most fantasy football fans are like regular football
fans, that is to say, they're front runners. Everybody wants the
marquee players, like Brett Favre, Barry Sanders and Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   But those guys are gone in the first few rounds. In fantasy
football, success depends on the lower picks, and then finding good
no-name guys during the season to replace all the players who break
important bones in Week Two (see Brad Johnson, Dorsey Levens and
Troy Aikman: yee-ouch!)
</P>
<P>
   And there's no better place to find replacements than on bad or
overachieving teams.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at Atlanta, San Diego and New Orleans. They're all
2-0, a tribute to luck, bad competition and a few good players who
want to win.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, before the season started, were you dying to draft
running back Jamal Anderson, wide receiver Bryan Still or
quarterback Danny Wuerffel? How about quarterback Chris Chandler,
tight-end Freddie Jones or receiver Sean Dawkins?
</P>
<P>
   If you were, stay out of my FFL league.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler and Anderson have carried the Falcons, Still and Jones
(not to mention 6-foot-5, 235-pound receiver Mikhael Ricks) have
loads of potential for San Diego and Dawkins and Wuerffel hooked up
for 110 yards and a touchdown Sunday for the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   And the teams don't have to be overachievers to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   On the Eagles, I'd take a look at running back Duce Staley, who
has done a good job filling in for oft-injured Charlie Garner. And
don't forget the ageless Irving Fryar, who is still catching balls
like he invented the forward pass.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, that's not true. Some other guy invented the forward
pass. Fryar just caught it.
</P>
<P>
   What about the much-maligned Chicago Bears? Quarterback Erik
Kramer doesn't quicken the pulse, but he has the brains to get rid
of the ball. He also has good receivers in Curtis Conway and Bobby
Engram.
</P>
<P>
   Quick quiz: How sorry do you think the Packers are that they let
Edgar Bennett slip away? Can you spell Travis Jervey?
</P>
<P>
   Nice try. &QL; 
Tip of the week
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm betting Jake Plummer gets back on track Sunday against the
Eagles at Sun Devil Stadium. Then again, I also bet that this whole
Monica Lewinsky business would blow over. Don't forget, the dreaded
bye weeks start Sunday. Atlanta, Carolina, New Orleans and San
Francisco are off. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Waiver wire
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dawkins is a quality receiver who probably wasn't taken in your
draft. Cincinnati receiver Darnay Scott is flourishing with Neil
O'Donnell throwing to the right-colored jerseys. San Francisco
49ers tight-end Irv Smith should get plenty of action. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
One-hit wonder &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week it's running back Chuck Levy, 49ers. Levy's numbers
look good (eight rushes, 44 yards, one touchdown), but he did it
against a pathetic Washington defense that gave up in the second
half. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at bill.muller(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
