<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROGE TAKES PRIDE IN BEING HUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pete Droge is not a musician who sits with his head buried in
the trade magazines, scanning the latest chart positions and record
sales while plotting his next commercial move. No, Droge is a
throwback to the days when musicians tried to be blissfully
ignorant of such things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to keep reminding myself that the music is what's
important _ and appreciating the fact that I'm able to play,'' he
says. ``The numbers and the sales and all that don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Droge, who had a minor hit in 1994 with the lovably warped ``If
You Don't Love Me (I'll Kill Myself),'' has come into his own with
his latest album, ``Spacey and Shakin'.'' It's his third album, but
the first in which he has distanced himself from past comparisons
to Tom Petty and Bob Dylan. It brims with lyrical twists, hard-won
truths, and a heavier, uptempo rock pulse compared to the folk-rock
slant of his first two CDs.
</P>
<P>
   It was again produced by Brendan O'Brien, who has worked with
Pearl Jam, Dylan, Neil Young, Rage Against the Machine, and Matthew
Sweet. ``He pushed me to do things that are less stock,'' says
Droge. ``When I first hooked up with him, I wanted to make more
rootsy, standard-type records. But he's shown me there are more
interesting ways of doing things _ to change the spirit and
approach it from a fresh angle, rather than be predictable and
same-y.''
</P>
<P>
   Droge, who has been called ``Generation X's John Hiatt,'' has
also shown incredible fortitude in staying on the road to ply his
craft. He and his band, the Millionaires (formerly the Sinners),
have done various tours this year with Ben Harper, Edwin McCain,
and Cracker. They also have some upcoming dates with Marcy
Playground. It's all part of Droge's philosophy to get the music
out to the public, regardless of radio airplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a challenge to think that way,'' he says.
``You could think instead that if I had massive airplay, we could
sell more tickets and stay in nicer hotels. You start thinking of
job security. But I think these things are all traps. It's much
healthier to stay in the present and enjoy what you're doing at the
moment, rather than projecting into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to slip into the thought of `OK, how many (radio)
stations have added the record this week?' But I need to take the
power from that thought and put it back into performing for
people,'' adds Droge. ``As long as you love playing, that's going
to make it all worthwhile. Nowadays, the scale of success is so
bloated that in order for something to be considered a success, it
has to sell multimillions. But a career that is more humble is
often overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Droge, who formerly lived in Portland, Ore., and is now based in
Seattle, doesn't mind having that humble career. He takes pride in
it _ and is so dedicated to the concept that he even plans to show
up unannounced for guerrilla-style acoustic shows this fall, before
playing his nighttime club gigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be completely unplugged. We're just going to
show up on campus areas and start to play,'' he says. ``It's going
to make us tighter as a band.'' And then in the evening they'll
plug in and go electric.
</P>
<P>
   Droge &AMP; Co. will be around Boston this afternoon at some
as-yet-unspecified site, followed by tonight's Bill's Bar gig. Hey,
with this schedule, they don't have time to read the trade
magazines anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and pieces: Reveille, a teen band from Harvard, Mass., has
signed a seven-figure deal with Elektra Records. The group's
attorney, Frank Cimler, describes Reveille as a cross between Korn
and Rage Against the Machine. So much for Harvard's reputation as a
sleepy little town ... Johnny Adams, a New Orleans legend and
Boston favorite, died Monday at age 67 in Baton Rouge, La., after a
long bout with cancer. He recorded for Rounder Records and will be
missed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
