<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2725 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-RESCUING-BOS &LR;      09-18 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RESCUING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE STUDIES IN ACHIEVING THE IMPOSSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
RESCUING PROMETHEUS 
By Thomas P. Hughes 
Pantheon, 372 pp., illustrated, $28.50,  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston's ``Big Dig'' is in extraordinarily good company in
``Rescuing Prometheus,'' an account by historian Thomas P. Hughes,
emeritus professor at the University of Pennsylvania and a visiting
professor at Massachusetts Institute of Technology, of four
megaprojects of our time.
</P>
<P>
   The four all have neat names _ SAGE, Atlas, ARPANET, and CA/T _
and their stories all contain lessons about how humans accomplish
the arguably unaccomplishable. But CA/T _ the Big Dig, formally the
Central Artery/Third Harbor Tunnel project _ is unique here not
only because it is more recent than the others but also because it
is a concrete construction project, whereas the others were
defense-related systems heavy with computers and electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these ambitious undertakings are part, as Hughes
believes, of ``a technogical transformation that can be seen as a
second creation; the first ... mythologized in the book of
Genesis'' I leave to other students of history. However, the
results of the four projects, and their valuable unexpected
consequences, certainly place the teams that worked on them in the
category of modern-day Heracleses. The hero Heracles in Greek
mythology (in Latin, he's Hercules) freed the imprisoned creator
Prometheus, who had stolen fire from heaven for use by humans.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes focuses on the Big Dig's relatively successful management
_ an overlay of private consultants on a small government-employee
group, and its postmodern ``open'' style, which allowed negotiation
and accommodation with a multitude of environmental and other
groups. He pays almost no attention to the cost of the consequent
appeasements, the one notable hole in the book.
</P>
<P>
   MIT plays a huge part in the book, none larger than in the SAGE
chapter. SAGE stands for Semiautomatic Ground Environment, an
air-defense system built in the 1950s. By the time it was turned on
in 1958, the bombers that SAGE was designed to defend against had
given way to missiles. ``Critics have called SAGE the best
peacetime air defense system ever deployed,'' Hughes notes. Though
the plug was pulled in the 1980s, it was deemed a central learning
experience in communications and management and pushed computers
over the hump from narrow problem-solving to broad information
processing.
</P>
<P>
   Atlas, the first successful intercontinental ballistic missile
project, might have seemed the most interesting of the projects in
the book, but it is the least, perhaps because Hughes's focus is on
management systems, a dry topic. It was, Hughes writes, ``the
largest and most costly military-funded research and development
program in history _ the Manhattan Project notwithstanding.'' Atlas
ushered in big thinking. As Simon Ramo (the ``R'' in TRW Inc.) put
it, ``Systems engineering is the design of the whole as distinct
from the design of the parts.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is ARPANET, the presursor to the Internet, begun
(of course) for defense purposes so warrior-commanders could better
coordinate their weapons. Talk about unintended consequences. This
project, begun by linking up a few nerds' computers at universities
here and there, was a fraction of the size of Atlas. (All
computer-related projects funded by the Advanced Research Projects
Agency in the late 1960s amounted to $30 million annually _ just
the price of one good Big Dig ramp.) Yet, as one MIT computer guru
said, ``what the military needs is what the businessman needs is
what the scientist needs.'' Hughes reports, ``As early as 1973,
e-mail constituted three-quarters of ARPANET traffic,'' most of
them personal _ and this wasn't even intended to be a message
system.
</P>
<P>
   This book is decidedly not light entertainment. Hughes writes,
``... the ceramicist slightly varied the material composition of
the cores, seeking a combination with the magnetic characteristics,
including a square hysteresis curve, that would provide
lightning-fast magnetization and demagnetization.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's about bright, young, energetic, successful people, and
it contains a readable telling of the Big Dig, a chapter aptly
titled ``Coping With Complexity.'' The bottom line here, if that
isn't too sensitive a term for a $10.8 billion project, is that
this largest of urban transportation projects in the nation _
``messier'' than the others chronicled in the book _ was planned
and has functioned in the open, and has survived.
</P>
<P>
   As with ARPANET, there was a counterculture influence among the
Big Dig thinkers and managers _ the process was designed to appease
angry opponents and those affected by the project, while still
going forward, if at inflated cost. And perhaps _ in contrast to
SAGE _ the new Central Artery won't be obsolete on the day it
opens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
