<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA PINS HOPES ON HIGH-TECH UNIT IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Motorola Inc. is best-known for its cellular phones, pagers, and
semiconductors _ businesses that have all stumbled in the past year
_ but the success of its Massachusetts-based Internet and
networking division may be one of the company's best-kept secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a painful corporate restructuring that included the loss of
15,000 Motorola jobs, or 10 percent of the company's total work
force, the Mansfield, Mass.-based Internet group has emerged as a
technology leader in the converging worlds of voice and data
communications.
</P>
<P>
   And that cutting-edge technology could very well help lead
Motorola out of its current troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola has suffered a triple whammy lately. In addition to a
worldwide slump in the demand for semiconductors, Motorola's
wireless phone and paging businesses have been hurt by tougher
competition and weak sales in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet &UR;  &LR; division, already a leader in networking equipment
such as frame relay access devices and cable modems, is a pioneer
in the transmission of voice, data, and video over a single
communications network.
</P>
<P>
   While this technology has important cost-saving implications for
businesses, Motorola also expects to extend it to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Through the creation of ``personal networks,'' Motorola
envisions a world where people can access the information they need
_ be it in voice or text form _ through the use of personal devices
such as cellular phones, personal digital assistants (PDAs),
computers, and pagers, whether they're at the office, at home, or
on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world of telecommunications is on the precipice of
violent change,'' said senior vice president Randy Battat, general
manager of the $600 million business.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of the Internet, for instance, has not only changed
the way people get their information and their entertainment, it
has fundamentally changed the way companies do business.
Deregulation and the replacement of analog networks by digital
networks are also driving change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the changes that occurred in the computing
industry over the last couple of decades and their effect on Route
128, then the changes in telecommunications are going to make those
look like child's play.''
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing these changes on the horizon _ and the failure of an
earlier turnaround strategy _ Motorola last July overhauled its
business yet again, creating the Internet and networking group as a
critical unit within its new Communications Enterprise division.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet and networking unit combines new and previously
segmented technologies under one umbrella organization headed by
Battat, a former Apple Computer Inc. executive who joined
Motorola's paging business in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The unit's presence in Mansfield dates back to Motorola's
acquisition of Codex Corp., a maker of modems for mainframe
computers, in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   As mainframes gave way to minicomputers and, ultimately, to the
era of personal desktop computers, the modem business was gradually
replaced by other types of networking equipment that allow
geographically dispersed computers to talk to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Though Motorola is now a major supplier of computer networking
equipment _ competing with giants such as Cisco Systems Inc. and
Northern Telecom Inc. _ the Schaumberg, Ill.-based company has
maintained a low profile in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks of Motorola for wireless phones, pagers, and
computer chips,'' said Erin Dunne, senior analyst at Vertical
Systems Group, a research firm in Dedham. ``But industry people
know they're a data networking access company and they do it very
well. They have a breadth of product nobody else can touch.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, in fact, is the leading provider of frame relay access
devices, with more than 22 percent of the $600 million market. Its
closest competitor, Cisco, has 15.5 percent, according to Vertical
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   What sets Motorola apart from its rivals, however, is its
technology that allows both voice and data to travel on the same
network, which is especially attractive to corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of businesses want to save on long-distance phone bills
by riding voice on the back of data,'' said Ladan Mestchian, a
senior analyst at International Data Corp. in Framingham.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues from all of Motorola's corporate networking products,
including routers, were nearly $500 million in 1997, Battat said.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's unit, which has about 1,600 employees, is also a
major supplier of high-speed cable modems, which are becoming
popular as cable television providers also begin offering Internet
and telephone access to consumers. Motorola sold about $100 million
worth of cable modems last year, Battat said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
