<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE FINANCIAL STRAITS, STICK WITH RETIREMENT SAVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 20, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a 42-year-old divorced male with an annual salary of
$44,000. After paying child support, child care, wage-garnished
attorney's fees, and taxes, my take home pay is only $423 a week.
Due to my divorce, I've recently gone through a bankruptcy
proceeding. My only remaining assets of any value are my two 401(k)
plans. I have approximately $2,000 in my present employer's plan _
I've only been on this job for six months, and I am no longer
contributing to the plan. I have $55,000 in another plan, 30
percent of which is invested in Vanguard Index 500, 40 percent in
Vanguard Primecap, and 30 percent in Vanguard Windsor. I'd like to
buy another house and could possibly qualify for a mortgage,
despite the bankruptcy, with a very large down payment and a low
selling price. I am thinking of cashing out the Vanguard holdings
to come up with the down payment. I have been relying on the
benevolence of friends for housing for the past eight months, and
I'm about ready to take the heavy tax and penalty hits just to get
started again. And I might be able to avoid some of the tax and
penalty hits just by buying a house. Any advice?
</P>
<P>
   L.D., El Cajon, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I applaud your desire to get yourself back on the track
toward financial security. But I also think you're probably trying
to move too fast, and in the process you're likely to take yet
another giant step backward. As you say, you have emerged from your
divorce and the bankruptcy proceedings with little save your two
retirement accounts. A sum of $57,000 is not an overwhelming amount
for a 42-year-old to have amassed toward retirement, but it's a
whole lot better than nothing. Especially given your current
financial situation, you should hold on tenaciously to what you
have. It seems to me more critical at this point to bootstrap
yourself up into a situation in which you can resume contributions
to the 401(k) plan at work.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some math: If you were to leave that $55,000 as
invested _ and you've built a portfolio of solid funds (although I
suggest you switch from Windsor to Windsor II if you can) _ the
pool should amount to $492,486 by the time you're 65. That
calculation presumes average annual portfolio growth of 10 percent,
but no ongoing contributions. To replace such a sum over the same
period would require monthly contributions of $493 _ clearly
something you won't be able to afford for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   But let's approach this from a more pragmatic point of view: Is
your plan likely to work? I doubt it. Were you to cash out the
401(k), the odds are that you'd realize only about $35,000 after
paying the taxes and penalties. Would such a sum represent a
sufficient down payment to offset a lender's reluctance to deal
with a person who has recently emerged from bankruptcy proceedings?
Would a lender deem your weekly take- home pay sufficient to enable
you to handle not only the mortgage payments, but also insurance,
maintenance and taxes? I suspect the answer to both questions would
be no.
</P>
<P>
   And bear in mind, if you are able to find a lender who will
accept you, the odds are overwhelming the institution would quash
its reluctance to deal with you only by charging a whopping
interest rate. The chances are that if you were able to do this,
the cost would be something close to half your current take home
pay, putting you in a financial situation that would substantially
preclude any substantial effort to rebuild your retirement savings.
</P>
<P>
   But I'd rather see you stay with your retirement savings for a
different reason _ that you decide that continuing to work toward a
secure retirement is more important than jump-starting your
immediate return to financial comfort.
</P>
<P>
   For all of those reasons, I suggest you check out the rental
market. Certainly if you can find a house that you might be able to
buy in your current financial situation, you also should be able to
find a rental that will serve your purposes until you work your way
into a more solid financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently read a column you wrote dealing with the finances
of a person in a nursing home. I have an 84-year-old uncle in an
assisted living facility in Florida. He is in good health. His
present finances include $300,000 in AARP GNMA and US Treasury
fund. We will need about $1,700 from this fund to combine with his
$1,300 retirement checks, for a total of $3,000 monthly. I have
very little knowledge of stocks. Do we have a safe investment, or
should we be doing something better? What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   R.B., Ellsworth, Maine
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You should have no problem in getting the income stream you
need from this account.
</P>
<P>
   You would require a 6.8 percent yield from your uncle's
investment to supply that $1,700 a month with no decline in
principal. As this is written, the yield on the AARP GNMA and U.S.
Treasury fund is 5.84 percent. Is that discrepancy enough to worry
about? No. The interest rate is close enough to the required yield
that you can simply ignore the fact that the principal is slowly
eroding. For example, if the interest rate held steady and if you
simply maintained the pace of $1,700 monthly withdrawals, it would
take nearly 32 years for the account to be depleted.
</P>
<P>
   As for the fund itself, it's exactly the kind of thing for a
person in your uncle's situation.
</P>
<P>
   It typically holds about 80 percent of its assets in
government-guaranteed mortgages and the balance in long-term US
Treasury securities. It is therefore a bond fund, with no
participation in the stock market. The effect of combining Treasury
notes with GNMA holdings is that the fund's yield is usually a
little lower than that of all-GNMA funds, but it is also a bit less
risky than they are. Its 10-year record shows 7.73 percent average
annual total returns, a figure which compares to a 7.13 percent
peer average for the short-term government bond sector. But
counterbalancing that slightly lower return is less volatility in
the market. The current bellwether year for considering what
happens to a bond fund in a bad market is 1994. During that year,
AARP GNMA and U.S. Treasury lost 1.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That year the average intermediate-term bond fund _ the category
that includes most all- GNMA funds _ lost 4.15 percent. Morningstar
Mutual Funds ranks the fund above average, with average grades for
performance and below-average grades for risk. It's absolutely
appropriate for a person in your uncle's situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
