<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS COMPANIES RUSH TO DO STOCK BUYBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   State Street Corp. made plans Thursday to buy back 2 million of
its own shares, a total that exceeds the entire amount of its stock
that changes hands in an average week.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it's not very big news.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have been tripping over themselves to launch stock
buybacks ever since the market started to tumble. Nearly two dozen
Massachusetts companies have authorized about $860 million in stock
repurchases since the market peak on July 17, according to
Securities Data Co.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend that's been sweeping the entire stock market. There
were 283 stock repurchase plans announced nationwide last month
alone, second only to the 551 plans launched in October 1987, the
month of the stock market crash. There have already been 223 more
buybacks announced this month and September could finish with the
new record.
</P>
<P>
   Repurchase plans are usually greeted warmly on Wall Street, a
signal managers are confident in their company's business. Also,
the company becomes another buyer in the market for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   But buybacks have their limits, certainly when it comes to
propping up the price of a stock that has been hammered in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buying power of the corporation purchasing its own shares
is relatively insignificant compared to the overall volume,'' said
Syl Marquardt, director of equity research at John Hancock Mutual
Funds.
</P>
<P>
   And board authorization to buy a large number of shares isn't
the same thing as actually purchasing the stock. Many repurchase
plans only buy a fraction of the authorized amount of stock and a
few end up not acquiring any shares at all.
</P>
<P>
   Some financial executives also think that their ability to wink
at investors, suggesting good times ahead by announcing buybacks,
is diluted because the strategy has become so widely adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago it had more signalling effect because it was a less
commonly used tool,'' said one executive at a company which has
launched a recent buyback. ``They really had to make a case to the
board that the fundamentals justified it. Now, it's so common.''
</P>
<P>
   But many investors still smile when one of their hard-hit
companies announces a buyback. Brooke Cobb, the Boston-based co-
manager of Neuberger &AMP; Berman's Manhattan fund, is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb pointed to a buyback announced Tuesday at Suiza Foods
Corp., a Texas dairy company and one of the stocks in his Manhattan
portfolio. Suiza's stock price had been cut in half since July, but
actually gained ground in Thursday's declining stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was a signal and it was calming to the market,''
said Cobb. ``It gave the investor some comfort and I think that's a
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies repurchasing stock sometimes retire the shares, making
those still in circulation a bit more valuable. But many
corporations use the repurchases to buy shares that will fullfill
employee stock options and awards, sometimes at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   The plan announced by State Street Corp. Thursday was actually
the latest extension of a repurchase plan that bought its first
share four years ago. It has bought millions of shares since then
and used the securities for everything from employee options to
stock-swap acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   State Street bought 280,000 shares in the first quarter of this
year and 210,000 more in the second quarter. The announcement
Thursday suggested the company has already purchased 800,000 shares
in the third quarter, when the price of State Street stock plunged
from 70 to as low as 49 1/2. It finished Thursday at 52 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   State Street still had authorization to buy back more than 1
million shares as of Thursday. Did the latest extension suggest the
company wanted to aggressively accumulate more stock while the
price is low?
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have the flexiblity,'' said Steven Arst, a senior
vice president at State Street, who declined to comment on the
company's buyback plans.
</P>
<P>
   Marquardt at John Hancock said the spate of corporate repurchase
plans points to a strategy that has less to do with investor
hand-holding and a much closer connection to financial basics.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between interest rates and the prices of stock
make this one of the best times in the last 20 years to spend free
cash or even borrowed money on share buyback programs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Low interest rates makes money cheap and lower stock prices mean
a buyer gets more value. For many companies, a buyback is the best
use of money available at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see large numbers of companies do (buybacks) it
reflects this relationship,'' he said. ``It's not as much
confidence building as it is the right financial maneuver for the
corporate officers, so I think it's a good sign,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
