<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAKHID A REVOLUTION SCAPEGOAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When David Nakhid joined the Revolution, he was
described as an All-Star player by coach Thomas Rongen. And in the
preseason, Nakhid demonstrated an ability to be among the team's
most influential players.
</P>
<P>
   After Rongen was replaced with the Revolution in last place in
Major League Soccer's Eastern Conference, he blamed unnamed players
for creating many of the team's problems. Under the new coach,
Walter Zenga, Nakhid was not on the traveling squad for the first
game and left on the bench for the next two, implying that he was
among those accused by Rongen.
</P>
<P>
   The benching and possible blaming of Nakhid is not a simple case
of a disenchanted individual or of someone with inferior abilities.
Nor does it seem plausible that one player could cause a team to be
unsuccessful. And if such were the case, that player surely would
have been discarded long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nakhid's situation is symptomatic of a team that had been
fractured for many weeks. Nakhid had been involved in both the
team's most impressive performances, which became rare after a
decent start, and in its worst games. The discord among the players
became apparent during a nine-game losing streak and devastating
losses to Columbus (6-1) and Los Angeles (5-1) last month.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has taken steps to remedy the situation, and the
Revolution will take a two-game winning streak into tomorrow's game
against Tampa Bay. He has inherited problems that will not be
easily solved. But for now, his ability to organize the defense and
inspire the team has been sufficient to salvage playoff chances and
provide hope for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first day here was Aug. 27, and I knew five players on the
team,'' Zenga said Thursday. ``Everyone had a chance to show what
they could do. I had no problems with anybody and I don't want to
know about the past. We have many offensive players, and
unfortunately, I can only play 11 players. We need to balance the
team. And we've won two games in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution probably could have used Nakhid, at least in a
reserve role, during a 3-2 loss to Miami in Zenga's first game Aug.
30. That defeat was likely the fatal blow to their playoff hopes _
they trail the Fusion by 6 points with three matches remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has kept Nakhid in reserve in the last two games, 2-0
victories over the MetroStars and Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone was looking for a scapegoat, and maybe they found
one,'' Nakhid said. ``But my concern is winning games and
satisfying the fans, who are the best in the league. As long as the
team wins and the fans are happy, I have no problem. I will keep
training every day and I look forward to playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can keep me down. I'm not the first to be scapegoated
and I won't be the last.''
</P>
<P>
   Nakhid became the center of a small controversy when he
requested permission to play for the Caribbean All-Star team
against Jamaica in New York before the World Cup. He correctly
pointed out the perception of a double standard _ if a Revolution
player had been chosen to perform for a European All-Star side, he
would have been exalted by the team instead of encountering
resistance. As captain of the Trinidad and Tobago national team,
Nakhid felt obligated to participate in what became a highly
successful promotion, and he was named among the outstanding
performers in the match.
</P>
<P>
   Though Nakhid missed only one Revolution game, this incident
raised questions about the perception and treatment of Caribbean
players. They are certainly the lowest-paid group in MLS, with a
combined salary of less than $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any other place in America,'' Nakhid said. ``We are
seen as cheap labor. There is no way we will be paid as much as
Europeans, even if they don't have comparable technical skills or
production. It's something I disagree with. And if I deem a
situation unfair, I will say it is unfair, no matter the
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign players are usually the first to receive the blame if a
team is failing, and that has been the case with the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Nakhid, 33, an international relations major at American
University, played for 10 seasons in Europe and the Middle East
under highly respected coaches such as Leo Beenhakker and Ottmar
Hitzfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on teams that had more diversity than this team,''
he said. ``Here we needed someone with the character and philosophy
to put the team together.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the (coaching) change was made, I went along with it. I
gave my opinion about the decision to fire Thomas Rongen during a
player-management meeting. I went along with the program. I had no
problem with the change. I expected a fair chance, or least an
explanation. But before the Miami game, there is no way you can
tell me that I shouldn't be playing. That had to come from a higher
authority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
