A2737 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-GROSS-BOS &LR;      09-18 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-GROSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLEASURES OF `GROSS INDECENCY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ED SIEGEL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
GROSS INDECENCY: THE THREE TRIALS OF OSCAR WILDE 
Play in two acts by Moises Kaufman. 
Directed by Michael Bloom. Set, Robert N. Schmidt. Lighting, Nancy
Schertler. Costumes, David Murin. Produced by Huntington Theatre
Company. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He lied under oath about having an adulterous affair. He was
then hounded by hypocritical lawmakers who had done much the same
thing themselves, and a press hungry for salacious details of his
private life.
</P>
<P>
   You won't be the only person thinking about Bill Clinton while
taking in ``Gross Indecency: The Three Trials of Oscar Wilde.'' And
by all means you should take in ``Gross Indecency,'' not only for
its uncanny and depressing parallels to what Alan Dershowitz has
called today's sexual McCarthyism. Had we never heard the Monica
moniker, the Huntington Theatre's first-class production of Moises
Kaufman's imaginative and provocative play about the dandiest dandy
of them all would still be, well, dandy. And don't succumb to Wilde
fatigue if you saw last year's one-man show in Boston or ``The
Judas Kiss'' with Liam Neeson in New York or London. ``Gross
Indecency'' is something Wilder, and in many ways the Huntington
production is preferable to the highly acclaimed off-Broadway
original.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bloom, who directed ``The Day Room'' and ``The Writing
Game'' for the American Repertory Theatre, hasn't taken that many
liberties with the staging, in which five actors stick primarily to
the roles of Wilde; his lover, Lord Alfred Douglas; Douglas's
father, the Marquess of Queensbury, whom Wilde sued for libel; and
the lawyers for both sides. Additionally, there's a quartet of
gray-suited wags playing a variety of roles (and musical
instruments) from George Bernard Shaw to Queen Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of the more horizontal Beardsley-like set that
Kaufman used in New York, Bloom has given the play more room to
breathe. The action is juxtaposed against set designer Robert N.
Schmidt's backdrop of two chalkboards, one of which is Wilde's
glowing prose about art and society; the other an arid,
antihomosexual legal definition of gross indecency, set next to a
large, morose picture of Victoria. By the second act, Big Brother _
or Super Sister _ will have obliterated Wilde. The scenic effect,
combined with Nancy Schertler's often eerie lighting design, is to
downplay the more carnival atmosphere of the New York production
without impinging on Kaufman's creative way of addressing the
aesthetic and political issues concerning Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues come bounding onto the stage in the first act when
the Irish genius _ buoyed by his popularity in West End theaters,
his creed that twinned love of art with the love of young men _
decided to sue Douglas's father for publicly calling him a
``somdomite'' (sic). How Wilde thought he could win a libel case
without speaking the name of the love that dared not speak its name
is left a mystery here. Wilde is usually depicted rushing into the
trap at the instigation of his petulant and spoiled lover, but
Kaufman treats Douglas much more sympathetically than do most other
playwrights and biographers, particularly Richard Ellmann.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman, whose play is more impressive than on first viewing,
draws on other sources. These will be cited in a mockumentary way
by the gray suits throughout the play, to show the puritanical
walls closing in on Wilde, whose free spirit is represented by the
clever ways in which Kaufman inserts his writings and bon mots
throughout the play. Unfortunately, Donald Carrier's delivery is
not equal to other aspects of the production. He doesn't have the
outsized carriage (and ego) that we have come to expect from actors
like Liam Neeson and Stephen Fry, who so brilliantly captured him
in the recent movie. The issue isn't that Carrier is too breathy or
not foppish enough, but _ worst sin of all when it comes to playing
Wilde _ that he is too bland. The rest of the cast is up to par,
except for James Waterston in a variety of roles, mostly all of
which are performed with the same adolescent whine that was more
appropriate to last season's ``Ah, Wilderness!'' Kelly Groves, on
the other hand, is a standout.
</P>
<P>
   Carrier is by no means a bad actor and his lack of charisma
doesn't really detract from the play. Wilde has much to say about
the artless prudes of any age, but given the moralism of today's
media and congressional spokesmen, this production of ``Gross
Indecency'' is unmissable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
