 Friday, Sept. 18, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed or will file these
stories for Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Chuck Lewis or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. For questions about
Houston Chronicle sports stories, please call the Houston Chronicle
Sports Department, 713-220-7896.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HASTINGS (Washington) _ Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., is
an expert on impeachment. As a federal district judge, Hasting was
impeached by the House, convicted by the Senate and removed from
the bench. Now, as a member of the House, Hastings speaks his mind
on the case against President Clinton. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AGENDA (Washington) _ As he braces for congressional
release of his videotaped grand jury testimony and details on his
18-month affair with Monica Lewinsky, President Clinton immerses
himself in foreign relations, preparing to meet with leaders of
Italy, Pakistan and Japan and speak at the United Nations. By
STEWART POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   PERJURY-IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ With President Clinton widely
accused of perjury for denying that he had sexual relations with
Monica Lewinsky, the House Judiciary Committee will have to
determine whether lying under oath is an impeachable offense. The
White House is expected to argue that perjury in the context of
private misconduct is not an impeachable offense. By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Impeaching the president is a
decision that House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said is next to a
declaration of war in terms of the most important action that
Congress can take. Congress' first brush with impeachment occurred
in 1868, when Republican radicals sought unsuccessfully to oust
Andrew Johnson from the White House because of his post-Civil War
policies of reconciliation with the defeated South. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
