<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-DRIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SURVIVOR'S STORY PLAYS OUT ON STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This much we know: The narrator of Paula Vogel's Pulitzer
Prize-winning drama, ``How I Learned to Drive,'' is a survivor of
child abuse. We know it from the first line of the play, when she
announces that she is going to teach us a lesson and tell us a
secret. That confidence, it turns out, concerns the seven years
that she was sexually abused by her uncle. The play becomes a
process of remembering, of sifting through the fragments of a
shady, stealthy past not only to create a cohesive narrative but
also to put mind and body back together again.
</P>
<P>
   The play, a production starring Debra Winger and Arliss Howard,
takes us on this journey of recovery without ever introducing the
trite stage device of a therapist taking notes. Vogel gives the
audience the comfort of knowing that the little girl grows up to
find safety, but she doesn't tell us how she gets there. ``I never
answer that question, and I'm not being elusive,'' Vogel says. ``I
ask the actors to fill in that story. I've always thought there
would be therapy or AA in her future. I would like to envision that
she finds other people through support networks or friendships or
religious counseling. There are also ways of working it out through
the body, like martial arts or meditation or yoga.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other actors who have tackled the role, Winger is
approaching the play as a kind of dramatic therapy: By reliving her
memories, her character can find a way to move on. Her past comes
to life in a series of nonlinear jolts, snippets of voices and
images that do battle in her mind. And that is precisely the way
most victims of child abuse recall their experiences, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that characterizes a traumatic experience is
that people don't have a frame to put it in,'' says Judith Lewis
Herman, associate clinical professor of psychiatry at Harvard
Medical School and the author of the pioneering 1993 treatise,
``Trauma and Recovery.'' ``People who you thought you loved and
trusted turn out to be exploitative and manipulative, and that is a
shocker for a little kid who needs the care and affection of
adults. So yes, typically people don't have a linear, logical
chronology of what happened. They have little fragments, and they
can only focus on it a little bit at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrator's name, by the way, is L'il Bit. Her memories are
dwarfed, along with her self-image.
</P>
<P>
   Vogel read Herman's book about post-traumatic stress disorder
before writing the play, and director David Wheeler is using it as
a guidepost for his production at ART. The play, which experts say
is psychologically accurate, places us directly in the mind of the
victim, where notes of a certain song on the radio or the smell of
a particular aftershave can trigger visceral reactions. It's like
we're flipping through the channels of a young girl's memory bank:
We see the matriarchs of her dysfunctional family lecturing about
the perils of sex and offering absurd advice about alcohol
consumption. We see the youngsters at school and the old folks at
home, taunting and teasing a self-conscious child. And we see the
only person who seems to understand the young. That would be Peck,
the seemingly sensitive and funny uncle who is married to the
sister of L'il Bit's mother. He does the dishes. He listens. He
comforts. He gives driving lessons. He also crosses the line.
</P>
<P>
   The play offers a complex psychological portrait of Peck, who
isn't cast as a dastardly demon with a waxed mustache and an evil
snarl. Instead, there are hints that he may be suffering from
post-traumatic stress disorder himself, since he is a veteran of
World War II who came home scarred in some ambiguous way. This
compassionate portrayal is not unusual, says Iris Shuey, assistant
clinical professor of psychiatry and human behavior at Brown
University who has seen ``Drive'' twice and plans to see it again
at ART in Cambridge. ``We'd like to have a pure villain, where you
flash the light and you can see it,'' she says. ``But that's what
makes these relationships so difficult for young women. There is a
part of the relationship that is quite honest and quite caring,
which makes for a very complicated view.'' She pauses, then adds,
``There are things that make this guy appealing, but perpetrators
do such horrible damage. You can never reclaim those years that are
lost. You can't erase what's happened. You can't become a blank
tablet.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play, L'il Bit is drawn to the twisted relationship with
her uncle, no matter how secretive, no matter how potentially
destructive. That doesn't surprise Herman, who has spent 20 years
working with trauma victims. ``Oh sure, these are human beings, you
know,'' Herman explains. ``Often, it's a relationship where the
perpetrator is paying a lot of attention to the victim, which is
something kids want and crave and need and appreciate. What's
unfortunate is that kids learn there is a price you have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   That price, of course, is the abuse itself and the scars it
etches on both the body and the mind. Some victims, like L'il Bit,
turn to alcohol to numb the pain and obliterate the memory. Often
they experience what is clinically referred to as dissociation, a
separation of the body and the mind that enables them to disconnect
from the experience. In the play, Peck observes that his niece has
a ``fire in her head'' rather than a ``fire in her belly,'' but he
fails to note that she might be healthier with a more integrated
sense of self. In ``Trauma and Recovery,'' a patient describes what
happened to her after being raped by her father: ``I unscrew my
head from my body as if it were the lid of a pickle jar. From then
on I would have two selves _ the child who knows, with guilty body
possessed by Daddy, and the child who dares not know any longer,
with innocent head attuned to Mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   So how do you put those two splintered selves together again?
How does Vogel's character get from a fractured childhood to the
place where she is able to remember her story and thus remember
herself?
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Herman offers this cautionary advice: ``No one can
face trauma alone.'' She outlines steps for recovery, which include
finding a safe place, reconstructing the event and then
reconnecting with life. The process requires a grounding influence,
be it therapy, a support group, or a nurturing friend.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the arduous stuff of psychotherapy isn't always the
stuff of great drama, and Vogel leaves that stuff offstage. We're
not giving away any secrets by saying that her character displays a
wistful yearning to go back to that time before it all went wrong,
to return to a childhood that was taken away too soon. In the first
scene, she asks us to imagine a bucolic landscape ``before the
malls took over,'' a place where ``the smell of sleeping farm
animals is thick on the air'' and ``the smells of clover and hay
mix in with the smells of leather dashboard.''
</P>
<P>
   We're also not giving away too much to say that many of the
scenes in the play occur in a car, as Peck teaches his young niece
the rules of defensive driving. A disembodied offstage voice offers
pithy instructions from a driver's manual, reciting chapter
headings like ``Idling in Neutral,'' or ``Vehicle Failure,'' or
``Implied Consent.'' And this is precisely the metaphor the experts
use when they talk about recovery. ``There is a very general
roadmap I try to lay out in trauma and recover,'' Herman explains.
``Each individual finds her own way, and it's something that people
come to bit by bit, with a lot of detours and false starts.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear what path L'il Bit follows, but for experts like
Herman, the journey is essential, not just for individuals but for
society. Her pioneering work has been criticized ever since her
book was first published in 1993, and in some ways, she is
heartened that a play about the subject could receive critical and
audience acclaim as well as the Pulitzer Prize. ``The artists are
always the ones who lead the way because they really do convey the
complexity of human dilemmas,'' Herman says. ``The artists make it
possible for us to make that leap of compassion, and we in the
mental health profession follow behind and make it more systematic
... We're dealing with a situation of massive human rights
violations of sexual and domestic violence. These violations have
been condoned, accepted, rationalized, excused, and considered an
entitlement, and so it causes enormous amounts of conflict and
social disruption when people accustomed to abusing their power all
of a sudden find themselves exposed, criticized, and held to
account for something they thought was not only their right but
part of the natural order of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman takes a breath here, then extends the metaphor one final
time. ``There are a lot of different roads to understanding. Some
are convinced by art, some by social science, some by biological
data. But some people don't see it until it happens to someone they
care about.'' And it happens onstage in ``How I Learned to Drive.''
Yes, it happens to L'il Bit: That much we know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
