<SLUG> BC-ART-MONET-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONET'S GRAND FINALE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The glorious Monet show now at the Museum of Fine Arts
reads like the final chapters in an absorbing autobiography _ even
though there's not a single person in any of these paintings.
They're all landscapes. But so closely did Claude Monet ally
himself with the natural world, and so personal was his translation
of it onto canvas, that these pictures tell you far more about how
he felt than about how his lily pond looked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Monet in the 20th Century'' _ which opens to the public on
Sunday _ is a triumph on several counts. It deserves to break the
MFA's previous attendance record, which was set by the same curator
and same artist: Paul Hayes Tucker, organizer of ``Monet in the
'90s,'' the 1990 show that drew over 537,000 visitors. Tucker's
``Monet in the 20th Century'' is not only sequel but culmination.
</P>
<P>
   This largest-ever look at the late Monet includes some paintings
never seen in public before and others that Monet's heirs kept
hidden for decades after his death, thinking them so radical they'd
besmirch the great man's reputation. Through these works, Tucker
tells the story of an artist indelibly identified with the 19th
century and with the Impressionist movement that took its name from
one of his paintings, and how that artist not only survived through
the first quarter of the 20th century but redefined painting while
he was at it.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a perfect show, but it comes close. There were loans
Tucker couldn't get because of competition from another late Monet
show now touring America. A different selection of the monumental
waterlily murals in the show's final room could have packed an even
greater emotional punch. And it's sad _ especially with this show,
which stands to be a major money-maker anyway _ that the MFA has
resorted to the shabby, if now standard, practice of a mandatory
walk at the show's exit through an auxiliary gift shop filled with
Monet tchotchkes.
</P>
<P>
   Your path through the show is tightly choreographed. It's
chronological: You start with the birth of the century and end with
the artist's death, in 1926, at age 86. Each room has a unifying
theme; the layout is blessedly lucid. The labels entertain you with
asides about the painting Monet may have traded for a car, or the
one he donated to a charity auction to aid soldiers wounded in the
First World War. And they tell you that Monet is not only Boston's
favorite painter but possibly the world's: Loans have come from all
over Western Europe and America, as well as Russia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But so compelling are these canvases that I'll bet even people
who would generally rather read than look will give only brief
attention to the labels and wall texts _ which are themselves brief
_ and dare to lose themselves in the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   They're ravishing. Thank goodness Tucker took a visual route
rather than a theoretical one, that he didn't do ``Monet in
Context.'' As it stands, the show is a pleasurable lesson in
looking, great training for the eye. Try to count the kinds of
brushstrokes Monet used, or the numbers of colors. You can't.
</P>
<P>
   You can track his progress, though, as he challenged himself
through travel and struggled mightily to keep his painting fresh.
His journey echoed the pyramidal structure of classical drama, with
turmoil at the peak and resolution at the end. Along the way, his
brushwork became violent, his scale, heroic; his imagery, all but
submerged in abstraction. The toughest works in this show go far
beyond the pallid ``Impressionists'' who followed Monet and persist
to the present day: They tend to imitate his earlier, sweeter
style. Look at the late pictures, though, and you think of such
sturm und drang paint-pushers as Pollock and de Kooning.
</P>
<P>
   The leap in Monet's 20th-century work is the painterly
equivalent of Debussy and Stravinsky rolled into one. To underscore
that shift, the MFA installation starts in the stateliness of the
Evans Wing _ a place of herringbone parquet floors, wainscoting,
and marble-lined doorways _ and ends in the spare white anonymity
of the Gund Gallery. You enter between two cloth banners, each
printed with part of a Japanese bridge. The large room beyond is
dominated by an outsize black-and-white photograph of the great man
himself, standing in the center of the very same bridge, wearing a
broad-brimmed hat, a gardener-monarch engulfed by vegetation: You
can almost feel the humidity.
</P>
<P>
   After this pulse-racing intro, you pass through a bare-walled
room that cleanses your eye and into another that's sparsely hung
with five paintings of the garden at Giverny. It was a subject
Monet didn't stay with long; perhaps, compared to the waterlily
pond that would soon obsess him, it was too conventional. One work
here that does point to the future is the 1902 ``Path at Giverny,''
dominated by a dramatic palette of dried-blood red and grayed-out
purple. Here is nature at her most abundant; you get the sense
there's not room for a single petal more on this canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Monet's 20th-century travels included excursions to London and
Venice. He made them look quite similar because his true subjects
weren't cities and architecture, but water and light. He traveled
to pit himself against other painters, past and present. In London,
he competed against Turner and Whistler, also masters of
atmosphere; in Venice, against La Serenissima's pantheon of
painters, Bellini to Titian to Canaletto, and also against
contemporaries including Sargent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
