<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN'S JAFFE: YOU CAN APPLY THE TERM POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Jaffe is hardly a household name, but he has one of the
greatest sports jobs imaginable: He is responsible for hiring
everyone from the exalted on-air talent to the lowly production
assistants who watch every game and detail every play to find that
one highlight _ that one miraculous catch or smashing collision _
that might find its way onto ``SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   At ESPN, Jaffe is, plain and simple, The Man, and he has the
resumes and videotaped auditions to prove it. On average, he
receives 900 job applications per year _ just for production
assistant jobs. People have followed him into bathrooms at job
fairs. Some have sent their resumes attached to baseball bats. For
every 100 of those who get interviews, only 20 make it into ESPN's
seven-month program. Maybe seven out of 10 are eventually hired
full-time. And still the resumes come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being the admissions director at Harvard,'' Jaffe
said. ``We get to choose from the best and the brightest.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just for the entry-level positions. Jaffe receives an
additional 500 or so videotapes per year from talent. ``I could
start the Resume Channel,'' he once joked to USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe can't take credit for Chris Berman. He came with the
building. As did Bob Ley, Chris Fowler, and the late Tom Mees.
</P>
<P>
   But Keith Olbermann? Yup.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Eisen? Yup.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Scott? Yup.
</P>
<P>
   He can even take credit for NFL analyst Sterling Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, Sharpe was not exactly media-friendly during
his playing days with the Green Bay Packers. When he retired,
ESPN's Andrea Kremer landed an interview with him. She was
extremely impressed, and her assessment eventually reached Jaffe.
She was right. ``Sharpe was articulate, smart, had a lot of
energy,'' Jaffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe was brought to Bristol, Conn., soon after for an
audition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can rememeber his interview as if it were just yesterday,''
Jaffe recalled. ``He was doing his audition and I was in the studio
booth with Bob Raschler. We both looked at each other and nodded.
He had it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' is difficult to define. Jaffe has been defining it since
his days at Emerson College, when he did critiques of on-air talent
at a Boston radio station for the station's owner, his roommate's
father. At the time, he worked for Emerson's radio station,
WERS-FM, and also for then-CBS affiliate Channel 5. When he
graduated in 1968, the TV station hired him full-time.
</P>
<P>
   He worked on the news side as a writer and producer. He left
after a few years and became news director at a San Jose televison
station. From there, he moved on to Sacramento, where he remained
for five years before joining ESPN in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, ESPN was expanding like crazy, adding programming
and outlets such as ESPN2 and ESPN Radio. When Jaffe arrived, ESPN
had only 10 production assistants. Now it has 110.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants are judged on creative talent, knowledge of sports,
and ability to fit into the ESPN system. The interviews are
probing. ``I'll ask the general background things at first but then
test their sports knowledge by asking about their favorite team and
asking them to assess their strengths and weaknesses,'' he said.
``I want to learn about their depth of knowldge.'' So far, six
production assistants have worked their way to becoming
coordinating producers, the most senior-level producer at ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   On-air talent is different. Those applicants must write a
mini-``SportsCenter'' show _ about 13 minutes worth of material _
in three hours and then deliver it on the air. Most have come from
local television stations and are accustomed to giving three-minute
sports reports for their newscasts. Because of the volume of
material and inherent pressure of anchoring ``SportsCenter,'' a
tape sent over the transom is usally not a suitable indicator of
the applicant's ability.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe grew up in Pittsfield and has been a Boston sports fans
for years. ``When I worked in news, I hated receiving telephone
calls at night,'' he said. ``It was usually some disaster, some
fire where people had lost their lives or endured some tragedy. But
sports is much different. I was with a guy recently whose beeper
went off while we were at dinner. He told me that a University of
Texas coach had been fired. I went, `Oh that's great.' No one lost
their life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
