(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Sept. 19:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee
votes to release the videotape of President Clinton's grand jury
testimony and an additional 2,800 pages of material from Kenneth
Starr's investigation. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD (Washington) _ A news analysis: The
Republican rush to put out the Clinton deposition and other
salacious material, which Rep. Barney Frank calls ``basically an
effort to discredit the president,'' creates a spectacle that makes
it look as if all restraint, caution and decorum has evaporated on
Capitol Hill. Some members ponder the larger meaning of this
shredding of the political culture and its consequent alienation of
the public. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GINGRICH (Washington) _ House Speaker Gingrich and
others address Christian Coalition meeting. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BLACKS (Atlanta) _ In dozens of interviews this week,
black Americans ranging from the NAACP's chairman, Julian Bond, to
the comedian Chris Rock cited everything from Clinton's choice of
friends to his choice of woodwinds in explaining why he has
connected with minorities unlike any previous president, viscerally
as well as politically. And while blacks, like most Americans, are
deeply disturbed by Clinton's infidelity, recklessness and
dishonesty, they are not willing to jettison what they see as a
unique relationship in exchange for an uncertain and potentially
threatening future. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAY (Washington) _ The president's day: he meets with
the advisory panel on race, other developments. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORE (Nashua, N.H.) _ With the vice president on tour.
By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-ABORTION (Washington) _ The Senate fails to muster the
votes to override Clinton's veto of the ban on late-term abortions,
which Majority Leader Lott calls most important issue of the year.
By Katharine Q. Seelye. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-SALVAGE (Halifax, Nova Scotia) _ The salvage effort to
recover the tangled remains of Swissair Flight 111. By Anthony
DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KENYA-BOMBING (Undated) _ More on Wadih el Hage, of Arlington,
Texas, the first American citizen known to have been charged in the
investigation of Osama bin Laden and the embassy attacks. By
Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Developments in the Russian political and
economic drama.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-MOOD (Jerusalem) _ The mood of Israelis as the Jewish
holidays approach and as an American peace team winds up its
Mideast trip. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-AFGHAN (Tehran) _ To shouts of ``Death to Taliban!'' and
the wail of a Shiite dirge, tens of thousands of people throng the
streets of Teheran in protest as the bodies of six slain Iranian
diplomats are borne toward martyrs' graves. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Today is a ``triple-witching'' day, with
stock and index options and futures contracts expiring, which could
make for even more volatility than usual. At 12:45 p.m., the
industrial average was down 10 points and the Nasdaq index was up 5
points. Overseas, prices gained 0.9 percent in Tokyo and fell 1.7
percent in Hong Kong. They fell 0.1 percent in Frankfurt and 1.2
percent in London. On the American debt market, the long bond was
up 2/32 point at midday, with the yield at 5.18 percent. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ After weeks of wrangling, Japan's governing
Liberal Democratic Party and the opposition forge an agreement over
legislation that lets the Government take over or shut down
crippled banks. But the agreement is vague in many areas and leaves
important issues unresolved, in particular how much public money
will be used to cover banks' bad debt. To win opposition approval,
the Liberal Democrats agree that Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
will be placed under the Government's control, making it the first
bank to be dealt with under the proposed legislation. Originally,
the governing party wanted to bail out the bank using taxpayer
money. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-CONFIDENCE (Undated) _ In the midst of bad news from
Asia, Russia, Latin America and the Starr report: the resilient
state of consumer confidence. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   BP-GLOBAL-WARMING (London) _ The chairman of British Petroleum,
who last year broke from his peers to cite the role of fossil fuels
in global warming, says his company will seek to cut its emissions
of greenhouse gases by 10 percent over the next decade. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Russell Baker's ``Observer''; detail to come.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rich is on vacation.
</P>
