<HEADLINE>
FISH OR FOUL? PROTEST FOR WHEATIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And so it comes down to the Wheaties box, America's billboard
for star athletes, now a battlefield for the anthropomorphic
conscience of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Sneaker-shod glitterati from Mary Lou Retton to Michael Jordan
have grinned at breakfast eaters from the orange cardboard box.
Olympic skaters, home run heroes (McGwire or Sosa on November's
box?), and tennis whackmeisters have all appeared on that icon of
healthy starts and daily nutritional pyramids.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong with Denny Brauer?
</P>
<P>
   After all, isn't Brauer the best at what he does? A superstar
head and shoulders above the rest in his sport? A runaway money
winner?
</P>
<P>
   How about $1.35 million in prize money, for starters?
</P>
<P>
   How about the fact that Brauer, a 49-year-old pro from
Camdenton, Mo., is a consummate champion, a winner of his sport's
biggest tournament?
</P>
<P>
   So why the beef about his picture on the Wheaties box?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tricking small animals into impaling themselves on hooks and
ripping them from their homes _ from the comfort of an expensive
boat _ requires no athletic skill whatsoever,'' keens a letter of
protest about Brauer's appointment by General Mills to its most
pretigious marquee of sports superpowerdom.
</P>
<P>
   Brauer, you see, is a fisherman, an angler from the Ozarks, and
his promotion to the Wheaties box has driven the group People for
the Ethical Treatment of Animals into howls of opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anglers have no place next to real sportsmen like Michael
Jordan and Tiger Woods, who better represent the breakfast of
champions,'' claimed PETA's president, Ingrid Newkirk, in her
organization's position statement.
</P>
<P>
   Brauer is not just a fisherman. Early in August, he won the BASS
Masters Classic championship in High Rock, N.C., a feat that made
him the biggest money winner in the history of the Bass Anglers
Sporstman Sociey. And lest anyone try to belittle the feat,
Brauer's $1.35 million in earnings are a reminder of just how big
the bass fishing craze has grown in this country.
</P>
<P>
   But another growth trend is in that small but very aggressive
group of anti-hunters who have now spilled over from bullets to
hooks and try to thwart fishing as a cruel and barbaric treatment
of our fellow creatures on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, high-profile fishing tournaments, favorable publicity
showing fishing as a wholesome family outdoor sport, and such
world-class promotions as the Wheaties box fisherman have all
become the targets of PETA, one of the most radical
anti-hook-'n'-bullet groups around.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter to General Mills chairman Charles Gaillard,
Newkirk put together the following argument: ``In June, Wheaties
snubbed Sen. John Glenn, astronaut and American hero, denying him
the box front on the basis that he is not an athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishing, Newkirk sniffed, ``requires no athletic skill
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   However, General Mills politely rebuffed PETA _ and dealt it one
more blow. Starting with October's box depicting a pro bass
fisherman, the huge food manufacturer intends to feature fishermen
once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just looked around,'' said Jack Sheehan, spokesman for
General Mills, ``and we saw 45 million-50 million people fishing in
this country. There's such a growing popularity, it just seemed to
make sense for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan has searched company archives to come up with about 60
pages of material on Wheaties boxes dating back to 1935, when the
practice of featuring an athlete on the front began. Not long after
the start, the first nontraditional athlete was featured: polar
explorer Robert Bartlett. Next to be featured on the box were the
Flying Wallendas.
</P>
<P>
   Sports, says Sheehan, have been broadening past the traditional
athlete. ``There are all kinds of sports that haven't yet been
represented on a Wheaties box,'' he said. ``But this box (Brauer)
is a way of showing that we want to be part of the expanding of
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Fishing, added Sheehan, is a sport whose time has apparently
come. He would not divulge company plans in detail but said
Wheaties boxes will feature many more nontraditional athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, PETA remains steadfast in its opposition to fishing
``in any form.'' Said Newkirk in a phone interview, ``All animals
feel pain. They must biologically. So when they get hooked and
ripped up out of the water, that is cruel.''
</P>
<P>
   Brauer regrets the controversy, saying he would like a chance to
meet with the PETA folks. He says he and his 26-year-old son spent
countless hours fishing together before Denny turned pro 20 years
ago. ``It is one of the most wholesome ways a family can all be
together outdoors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Never, it seems, will the twain meet, nor is either side giving
in. But starting next month, anglers can begin their day by
munching their breakfast while having something familiar to stare
at at the table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
