<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEXUS LS400 _ NEARLY PERFECT, CAN'T QUITE FIND ITS WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, September 20, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lexus LS400 is a luxury car that is boringly close to perfect
and quietly becoming the stuff of legend. In a world where the
words ``automobile'' and ``grief'' are virtually synonymous, Lexus,
the luxury arm of Toyota, has concentrated so diligently on
details, quality control, and customer service that the occasional
glitch in the flagship car is frequently remembered with pleasure _
when is the last time you enjoyed a visit to the service
department?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the pampering and peace of mind that come in the
Lexus LS400 wrapper have a price _ a steep price: $52,900 plus $495
delivery for a roomy four-door very well equipped. The flasgship
comes with virtually all the bells and whistles, everything from A
to W.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all. There is a short list of extras _ the XYZ, you
might say _ with some very lo-o-o-ong prices. The in-dash compact
disc changer, located just above the glove box, is another $1,050.
High-intensity discharge headlights are $500, and the lowly mats to
cover the fancy carpet, should you desire them, are $112 for the
floor, $65 for the trunk. But wait, there's more.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Lexus find its own way home with the $2,250 navigation
system, and, while you're cruising there, listen to the $2,250
Nakamichi premium audio system while your passenger gazes through
the open $1,120 tilt/slide power moonroof. Heat the seats for $420;
splurge for the wood/leather steering wheel and shifter knob for
$330. The air-suspension system is $2,970, but it includes the
moonroof _ but you have to buy either that fancy radio or the
navigation system to get it. Lastly, put the whole shebang on fancy
chrome wheels for only $1,700 and protect them with the $48 wheel
locks.
</P>
<P>
   So far, with everything, we're up to around $62,000 _ that base
price is beginning to look like an admission fee. The tested model
came with the navigation system and a respectable portion of the
rest of the list for a delivered price of $58,790 _ obviously, not
a car for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   The LS400 is a car of comfort in the extreme, a car that appears
to pamper. Enter, sit, place the key in the ignition and the blank
void that is the instrument cluster suddenly lights up and the
steering wheel, recessed out of the way for ease of entry, now
glides closer for easy reach.
</P>
<P>
   The drivetrain is a 32-valve V-8 coupled with a 5-speed
automatic transmission, very smooth and sufficiently potent. The
transmission offers three modes for travel: economy, obviously for
the best fuel economy; snow, for those nasty winter days when
takeoff traction is problematical; power, which adjusts shift
points upward to allow maximum acceleration _ the columnist's
choice. In the economy mode, the LS400 is lively enough, but it is
so smooth, so quiet, as to be a bore. In the power mode, the car is
brighter, the driving more spirited, more fun.
</P>
<P>
   Handling is very good. This is not a sports car for bending
around sharp corners, but this luxury boat is supple enough,
precise enough to be some fun on the country roads and nimble in
city traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Radio controls are convenient enough, and the air
conditioning/heater controls are very good; the Lexus maintained
fairly even temperatures within, despite some extreme changes
without. Interior room is generous, trunk space looks generous _
but, alas, would not accommodate boxed computer and VDT; one box
went into the back seat. The trunk is deep front to rear but
shallow top to bottom. And that was not the only imperfection in
this almost flawless car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whoever programmed the navigation system has an excellent feel
for computers and a lousy sense of geography.
</P>
<P>
   First test: We want to go from the Globe parking lot to a
specific address in Lowell, about 30 mils from Boston, by the
shortest route. Lowell for the uninitiated, can be one tough town
to navigate, but I do know where I'm going and how to get there.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexus navigator, however, isn't going my way. It knows some
short cuts _ shorter in distance, to be sure, but longer in time
most days because it eliminates a lot of interstate. Tonight it's
not such a problem _ in fact, thanks to the mindless little
calculator, I miss a traffic upset on Interstate 495. In Lowell,
directions become less clear; displays and the directions offered
up by the disembodied computer voice do not match what I'm looking
at. It is telling me to go through a traffic circle, but I'm not at
a circle, and the only thing resembling a circle is a block or two
to the left. I guess wrong; the computer goes into the ``disgust''
mode and begins recalculating.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it has recalculated, I've already made another
unprogrammed move, forcing still another recalculation. We set off
again, the microprocessor and I, and once more the maze of streets
before me does not match the computer imagery. I move into the
wrong street, reverse, turn, and enter the correct street. The
satellite-guided navigator now has an electronic headache. I wait
while it takes an electronic aspirin and recalculates.
</P>
<P>
   Underway once more, I am guided to my destination from the
opposite direction of my ususal approach, but the navigator puts me
right on the doorstep. Great!
</P>
<P>
   Business accomplished, I now solicit a route to Rochester, N.H.
The computer directs me to choose from among Rochester, N.Y. ,
Rochester, Minn., or Rochester, Mich. _ it knows no Rochester, N.H.
We argue; it wins. Above Portsmouth is Terra Incognita.
</P>
<P>
   This must be how those early navigators felt with their lousy
maps long on imagined dangers and short on geographical
information. Unlike them, however, I did know where I was going.
For a tourist figuring to explore New England, however, it could
pose a problem _ there is more to New England than Boston, Lowell,
and Portsmouth.
</P>
<P>
   The LS400, for all its pomp and power to romp, is still easy on
the fuel budget; EPA-rated 19 miles per gallon city, 25 highway,
the tested model delivered 21.63 miles per gallon overall in 900
miles of spirited driving over a variety of terrain. It's a lot of
car, but it's a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
