<HEADLINE>
INTERNET IS BIGGER THAN STARR REPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's epic report on the
dalliances between President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky was
released last week, it was a contest as to which drew more
attention from media pundits _ the lurid details in the report or
the fact that it was available on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with discussions of the president's bleak political
future were golly-gosh-whiz pronouncements that, bygum, the
Internet has finally arrived! Welcome to the real world, Netboy,
and have a cigar!
</P>
<P>
   Phrases like ``defining moment'' and ``the Web's finally
mainstream'' were tossed around.
</P>
<P>
   And, they were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The posting of a government-sanctioned work of pornography is
not how the Internet is going to be defined. Making that document
available on the Web for millions to read doesn't mean the Net is
now ``mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the Web arrived a long time ago. And on the other
hand, the Web is far from being ``mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Those two arguments are not as contradictory as they appear on
the surface.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the traditional media continue to insist on
overlaying a different model on top of the Internet, and usually
that model is TV. But it's not like print, radio or television,
though it has elements of all these.
</P>
<P>
   That's why efforts to present the Net as television fail
miserably. Witness, for example, the Microsoft Network's creation
of ``channels'' for organizing Web-based content on its service.
Subscribers found it confusing and clumsy, a classic case of
jamming the square peg into the round hole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REAL DEFINING MOMENTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Net is not like television because it's far more personal,
even in its one-to-many transmission mode. That's why a single,
grand event cannot define the Internet. Instead, the Net has
thousands of defining moments every day.
</P>
<P>
   When a wife e-mails her husband who's a thousand miles away on a
business trip that she's pregnant with their first child _ that's a
defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   When someone who's been laid off uses the Web to find and land a
new job _ that's a defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   When a shade-tree mechanic finally finds an online source for
that part he's been needing to rebuild an antique car _ that's a
defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   When a student gets a better grade because she used the Internet
to help with studying _ that's a defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   When a small, local company wins business from a customer on the
other side of the world after e-mail-based negotiations _ that's a
defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   When a teen-ager makes a friend in another country by competing
in an online multiplayer game _ that's a defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   The common thread in these examples is the Internet's use as a
tool, a way of getting things done. The release of Starr's report
also is an example of utility. Depending on your point of view,
members of Congress were getting vital information to the citizenry
as quickly as possible _ or delighting in the humiliation of a
president who doesn't fit their ideological ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Congress put the report on the Internet. In the
Information Age, what else were they going to do with it?
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that there are not big events associated with
the Net. But I'd argue these big events are incidental; they are
not what the Net is all about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THEN WHAT IS IT? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To a certain extent, the Internet is more like the telephone
than any mass medium. The telephone had no dramatic, defining
moment. It's daily, mundane, human communication that defines the
telephone _ and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Net is not yet a part of the mainstream. These
experiences do not happen to everyone. In fact, they don't happen
to a majority of people.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures from International Data Corp., the
Framingham, Mass., high-tech market research firm, about 45 percent
of the estimated 107 million U.S. homes have computers in them. Of
those, about 62 percnt are online in some way _ the vast majority
connected to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That means about 19 million homes have Internet access, or less
than 18 percent. And despite the popularity of sub-$1,000 PCs, most
Internet users are better educated and make more money than the
average American.
</P>
<P>
   Even taking into account people with Internet access at work,
the Net still is not mainstream. Someday, it will be. And it won't
because of the Starr Report, but rather because it's rapidly
becoming the most effective way for our species to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a comment or question about computing? Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
