<HEADLINE>
TO KEEP YOUR PC RUNNING `CLEAN', LIMIT UTILITIES, BACKGROUND
ACTION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. You list many utilities that are beneficial to keeping a
machine in good working order. I have just about all the utilities
that you've referred to. My problem is that I can't get them all
running at the same time without having system problems. I have
disabled the McAfee virus shield on your advice, and now use it
only to scan periodically. I have Cleansweep, but do not have the
monitoring activated. I also have Norton Utilities (although I have
not updated for Windows 98), and Oil Change, etc. ad nauseum. I
depend upon Act! 4.0 with the Act loader and with Sidekick running
on the side, have a spell checker running for my CompuServe mail,
Microsoft Office bar and a total of about a dozen programs that
show up on my Task Manager that I don't even know the functions of.
Where does one draw the line?
</P>
<P>
   A. Where you draw the line depends on your personal computing
comfort zone. At what point are you willing to sacrifice the
convenience of having all these bells and whistles running in the
background in order to have a more stable system? It's a decision
you have to make for yourself, based on the state of your PC and,
to a certain extent, your level of computing sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   I've evolved a bit in my thinking lately about computer
utilities. While I think some products are must-haves _ for
example, you need something to help with uninstalling programs,
something to scan for viruses and something to help recover from a
crash _ there is such a thing as having too many utilities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there's no need to have both First Aid and Norton
Utilities on your system and, in fact, some of their components can
conflict with each other.
</P>
<P>
   I think you should run as few programs in the background as
possible. The ``cleaner'' your operating system, the better _ and
that goes for all platforms, including Windows, Macintosh and Unix.
</P>
<P>
   You mention in your question that you have Norton Utilities, but
not updated for Windows 98. If you are running Norton Utilities 3,
you should definitely use the LiveUpdate feature to apply the patch
that makes Norton more compatible with Windows 98. Not doing so is
asking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using an older version of Norton Utilities, you
should upgrade at once to 3.0.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the speed of a 56K modem significant enough for me to make
the upgrade from a 28.8 modem? Is the difference noticeable? Or,
should I just stick to my old reliable 28.8 and hold out until
better technology arrives? Should I wait until the cable company
offers an Internet connection, free ISDN from the phone company or
some other cheap technology?
</P>
<P>
   A. At best, you can expect to get about 53K out of a 56K modem,
though most folks don't even get that. The average speed from most
56K modems seems to be in the 40K to 48K range _ though some folks
certainly get less.
</P>
<P>
   However, assuming your connection is average, that's about a 30
to 40 percent increase in your current speed, which would be a
noticeable improvement. When a 56K modem is working at its best,
you can classify the results as a dramatic improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Given that cable modem service for most consumers in Houston
won't happen until March at the earliest, and that a decent 56K
modem will cost about $100-$120, it might indeed be worth it if
you're feeling constrained.
</P>
<P>
   Don't hold your breath, by the way, waiting for the phone
company to offer free ISDN. Unfortunately, expansive bandwidth
doesn't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to dwight.silverman at
chron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter access code 1001.
</P>
</TEXT>
