<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE SCENARIO IS NOT PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The formula seems simple: Win enough football games and you can
not only earn a bowl berth but contend for the national
championship. That, however, was before the advent of the Bowl
Championship Series, as NCAA planners call their new format to
determine who will play in this year's national championship game,
the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   We're only two weeks into the season, and already we have
glimmerings of a problem with one school. In the parlance of people
who study the Weather Channel during hurricane season, it's just a
tropical wave at present. Nothing to worry about _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   The team we're talking about is Kansas State, which some people
think has a legitimate chance to win the national championship. Now
those of you with a sense of history should be doubled over with
laughter at seeing ``national championship'' and ``Kansas State''
mentioned in the same paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Kansas State was as far down the Division 1-A food
chain as you could go. From 1985-89, the Wildcats won four games.
During one particularly bleak strtech en route to an 0-10-1 record
in 1987, K-State lost three games by a combined 171-17.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, a coaching change occurred during that period,
with Stan Parish being replaced by Bill Snyder. But an arrival just
as important was that of Steve Miller as the athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had a new concept. Instead of overscheduling K-State, he
decided to underschedule. Nonconference opponents such as Iowa,
Tulane, and Arizona State disappeared from the schedule and were
replaced by teams such as Northern Illinois, Indiana State, and
Akron.
</P>
<P>
   The theory was simple. Winning any game, even against a 1-AA
opponent or a less-than-high-profile team, was better than getting
beaten by a Top 25 team.
</P>
<P>
   After three so-so years of testing this theory, Kansas State
broke into the bowl busines in 1993, going 9-2-1 and earning a trip
to the Copper Bowl, the Wildcats' first postseason bid in 11
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   K-State has been to a bowl game every year since, topped off by
last season's Fiesta Bowl win over Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   But critics _ and there are many _ charge that K-State, with top
facilities and a national reputation, has gone beyond simply
scheduling 1-AA and bottom-of-the-barrel 1-A opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State is off to a nice 2-0 start after romps over Indiana
State and Northern Illinois. The pollsters have the Wildcats in the
Top 10, although one voter says he has dropped them a spot each of
the last two weeks for piling on.
</P>
<P>
   K-State sees nothing wrong with its plan and no reason to change
it. It has provided the school with a sense of pride in its
program.Let the other teams beat each other up in the nonconference
part of their schedules. Next year will bring more of the same,
since Kansas State has Temple, Texas-El Paso, and mostly likely
Idaho scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the rub. Part of the BCS formula includes computer
rankings, which factor in strength of schedule. It is conceivable
that Kansas State could run the table with an 11-0 record and be
nudged out of a slot in the Fiesta Bowl by a team with one loss.
</P>
<P>
   Although wins are paramount, under the BCS formula, a team with
the same number of wins and one loss can pass an undefeated team if
it is 25 slots ahead of that team in strength of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Schools are aware of that formula and understand the importance
of scheduling. ``You don't want to overschedule yourself,'' said
Boston College coach Tom O'Brien. ``So you get a couple of games
you feel you should win, but you also schedule a couple of good
intersectional games that you have a chance to win and will also
give you some national exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's nonconference schedule includes Notre Dame, Georgia Tech,
and Navy this year and will feature teams such as Stanford and Wake
Forest in future years. Not suicidal, but not Cupcake U, either.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Kansas State is 20th in the Sagarin computer rankings,
which factors in strength of schedule. That is a far cry from the
Wildcats' No. 4 ranking in the ESPN/USA Today coaches' poll and
their No. 5 ranking in the Associated Press writers' poll.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this scenario: After the league championship games,
Ohio State and Kansas State are undefeated and ranked 1-2 in the
polls, but a surging Florida State, which has won 10 straight,
including a victory over previously undefeated Florida, is No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The FSU schedule, which also includes games against Miami as
well as Top 25 teams Texas A&AMP;M, Southern California, North
Carolina, and Virginia, would put the Seminoles more than 25 slots
ahead of Kansas State, boosting the Seminoles into the No. 2
position and into the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Kansas State will have no one but itself to
blame.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
At a loss to explain
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State is 0-2 and looking for reasons. As a starting
point, try 22 penalties for 210 yards in losses against Washington
and Brigham Young ... Speaking of BYU, there seems to have been a
change in philosophy for coach Lavell Edwards, who is running the
ball more than passing ... Oregon and Oregon State are a combined
4-0, stunning for Oregon State fans. The Beavers have had an
NCAA-record 27 straight losing seasons and have won only one
Pacific-10 game in the last three seasons ... Oregon coach Mike
Bellotti is 11-0 in nonconference games ... Nebraska has become
quite an attraction on the road. When the Huskers visited
California in Berkeley last week, they drew 67,000, the largest
Memorial Stadium crowd since Notre Dame came to town in 1959 ...
Florida State quarterback Chris Weinke threw six interceptions in
the Seminoles' 24-7 loss to North Carolina State, and he expects to
hear criticism until FSU wins again. ``There are people who want to
run me out of town _ I know that,'' said Weinke, who gets a chance
to redeem himself Saturday against Duke. ``But you aren't going to
run me out of this game.'' ... Who would have thought? After two
games, Duke (2-0) has a better record than Flordia State (1-1) ...
FSU is out of the Top 10 for the first time since Oct. 9, 1994. The
Seminoles have been out of the Top 10 for only one week since 1990
... Missouri fans are hoping their team can repeat last year's
performance against a No. 1 opponent when the Tigers meet
top-ranked Ohio State in Columbus Saturday. Last year the Tigers
came within a foot of upsetting No. 1 Nebraska, their bid falling
that far short on the game's final play ... Kansas band members are
irate after being pelted with whiskey bottles at halftime of last
week's Missouri game in Columbia. Mizzou officials are apologizing
all over the place ... Texas's defense is allowing an average of
535.7 yards per game ... Although Kansas State and Texas are in the
same conference, the teams have not met since 1942 ... When
Louisiana State faces Auburn Saturday, count on the game being
close. Since the series became a regular part of both teams'
schedules in 1991, the game has been decided by 6 or fewer points
five of the six times they have met ... Good news for Clemson,
which was shut out by Virginia Tech, 37-0, last week. The Tigers
are 8-0 in games they play on Sept. 19, the only date on which the
Tigers are perfect (in more than five games). That could be bad
news for Virginia, the Tigers' opponent Saturday ... Florida, which
has beaten Tennessee five straight times, has outscored the Vols,
59-6, in the first half the last two times the game has been played
at Neyland Stadium ... Michigan is not only not the best team in
the country right now, it's not even the best team in its county.
Eastern Michigan in Ypsilanti is 1-1, the Wolverines are 0-2 ...
Balance? Not at Utah State, which had 19 yards rushing but 338
passing in a 39-36 loss to New Mexico ... Battle of the
quarterbacks when Indiana meets Kentucky: The Wildcats' Tim Couch
is No. 2 in the country, trailing only Hoosier redshirt freshman
Antwaan Randle.
</P>
</TEXT>
