<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SCANDAL SAPPING SENSITIVITY AT OFFICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The confirmation hearings of Supreme Court Justice Clarence
Thomas in 1991 forced employers to confront the reality of sexual
harassment in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Companies quickly put out statements explaining how employees
could make harassment complaints, hired experts to caution managers
of the perils of dating subordinates, and warned managers about
creating a hostile work environment to prevent their own Anita Hill
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers went so far as to tell employees they couldn't
comment on their co-workers' attire for fear the comments would be
taken the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   All that sensitivity about discussing sex and its overtones flew
out the window when the Starr Report was released last week on the
Internet and reprinted by many newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, employees huddled around the water cooler and talked
about the revelations that President Clinton allegedly had cigar
sex with Monica Lewinsky, whether oral sex constitutes a sexual
relationship and the morality of the president having a tawdry
affair with a young intern.
</P>
<P>
   The human resource director at one of Houston's biggest
companies said that conversations are popping up everywhere _
during meetings, during lunch and in the halls. People are talking
about the disgust they feel toward the president and how the
president could think the public would buy his argument that oral
sex isn't really sex, said the director, who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with those kind of bawdy details usually have been
reserved for locker rooms or beer halls.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Majuk, publicity director for Amacom Books in New York
City, said she would never have talked about sex with her male
boss, but when details of the Starr Report came up at a recent
lunch the conversation was as normal as gardening.
</P>
<P>
   No one blinked an eye, said Majuk, remembering the salacious
details that were discussed. Obviously impeachment hangs on perjury
and how can you discuss that without knowing the details?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JOKES NOT BOTHERING MANY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Starr Report has spurred a lot of jokes, but even those
don't seem to bother people who might be annoyed by tasteless
sexual commentary at the workplace. After all, it has become one of
the most intense legal and ethical debates of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce King said the jokes she hears around the Oil, Chemical and
Atomic Workers Local 4-227 in Houston don't bother her a bit. She's
worked with the same people for 20 years and everyone understands
the conversation is nothing more than discussing the political news
of the day, said King, a secretary.
</P>
<P>
   All this talk does raise an interesting question. When exactly
does the rehashing of cigar sex and hallway encounters rise to the
level of a hostile work environment? When does the conversation get
so offensive that an employee can claim harassment?
</P>
<P>
   That hinges on whether a reasonable person would find the
conversation offensive, said Gerald Holtzman, an employment lawyer
with Beirne Maynard and Parsons in Houston. There's no right to
talk offensively just because it's a &UR;  &LR; public issue.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks also would have to be pervasive enough to constitute
a hostile working environment, said Holtzman. An isolated comment
is not sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SPEAK UP IF YOU ARE OFFENDED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If someone is offended by the conversation, he should speak up,
said Kathy Butler, an employment lawyer with Butler and Harris in
Houston. Butler has a hard time imagining conversation about the
Lewinsky case rising to the level of harassment unless one employee
uses the case to torment another.
</P>
<P>
   And there would probably be other examples of abuse if one
employee is making cigar sex references to another employee, Butler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent laxity regarding sex talk at work, the rules
still haven't changed, said Dennis Powers, author of ``The Office
Romance: Playing with Fire without Getting Burned'' (Amacom Books).
If you don't know someone very well, it's better not to start
commenting on the nitty-gritty details in the report. Stick to
general questions: ``What do you think about Clinton?''
</P>
<P>
   Powers said the Clinton scandal is having at least one positive
effect at work: It's raising the consciousness about sex, dating
and romance at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Sexually related issues will be easier to discuss because we're
talking about the Clinton affair in a way that doesn't cause
embarrassment, said Powers, who also is associate professor of
business law at Southern Oregon University in Ashland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To voice comments, telephone (713) 220-2000 and dial in code
1002. Send e-mail to lm.sixel at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
