<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CULPEPPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUNTE CULPEPPER: FAVORITE SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The relatives came from all over the state.
Cousins, nephews, aunts, uncles, brothers, sisters. All for a
family reunion/end-of-summer party at a beach about two hours from
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I bet it was over 75 people,'' says Daunte Culpepper,
Central Florida's All-America quarterback. ``People talking about
the Heisman, doing this, beating that team. People telling me, `You
got to beat Auburn.'''
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper smiled at the memory. All that attention. All those
expectations. All the expressions of faith in what he can do.
</P>
<P>
   Faith?
</P>
<P>
   His whole life had been based on faith, on people's belief in
making the impossible possible.
</P>
<P>
   Take his mother, Emma. It was faith that had brought Daunte and
Emma together 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Emma Culpepper was 62 years old, content in a life that
had unfolded around her and included 14 children.
</P>
<P>
   Emma had been a widow since 1956 and had never borne children.
But that didn't stop her from being a mother. After her brother
died, she raised his four children, a sister-in-law brought seven
other children into Emma's domain, and she adopted three more.
</P>
<P>
   One of the adoptees was Daunte, who arrived after another
desperate call for help. A prisoner at the Ocala, Fla.,
correctional institution had given birth and wanted to give the boy
away.
</P>
<P>
   This call was different. A stranger's call. But Emma's heart was
huge. She took in Daunte as her youngest son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I'd be without her,'' Daunte says of Emma,
who has slowed down some at 83 but still is sharp enough to follow
Daunte's career and offer advice.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Emma about Daunte and she will talk not about a football
player but a young man with an unlimited future. ``He was always
special,'' she says. ``He knows what he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about her decision to become a mother again at 62, she
says, ``I never had any regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Emma Culpepper, approaching retirement with a house already full
of children, had faith that taking in an infant boy when it made no
sense to do so would work out all right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It was also faith that brought Culpepper to Central Florida.
In high school, he was a hot shot at quarterback but not so hot in
the classroom, prompting most Division 1-A schools to back away
from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My academics weren't up to par,'' says Culpepper. ``It wasn't
that I wasn't able to do the work. It was just that I
procrastinated and did other things instead of going home and doing
my homework. It didn't hit me until after my junior yuear, when I
started getting serious about college. I said, `Man, my grades
aren't what they need to be.' A lot of schools backed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Culpepper smiles, knowing how the story has turned out,
knowing that he is months away from being a millionaire as one of
the top picks in next spring's National Football League draft. He
knows that if he has a good season, the Culpepper bandwagon will
become crowded; a few good performances in key games can earn him
Heisman consideration. Such consideration would seem to have merit
after Culpepper began his season with two Heisman-like efforts,
including a six-touchdown (four passing, two running) effort in a
64-30 win over Louisiana Tech two weeks ago and a seven-touchdown
(four passing, three running) splurge in a 48-0 rout of Eastern
Illinois Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  This from a player who was largely unwanted by Division 1-A
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame them,'' says Culpepper, who will show his act on
national television tomorrow against Purdue. ``I probably would
have done the same thing if I were them. You don't make investments
in things you don't think you're going to get nothing out of. They
felt like they weren't going to get anything out of me, so they
stopped calling and writing and doing the things they do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Central Florida had faith. UCF, which was about to move up
to Division 1-A and had big-time ambitions, needed players.
Then-coach Gene McDowell and his staff decided to look beyond
grades.
</P>
<P>
   When their interest turned to Culpepper, they sent offensive
coordinator Paul Lounsberry to check things out. ``I talked to his
teachers and coaches,'' says Lounsberry with a big smile, standing
in the qaud of the sprawling Central Florida campus. ``It wasn't
that he didn't know things. He just wasn't working as hard as he
should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Lounsberry and Ocala Vanguard High School coach Phil Yancey came
up with a plan in which Culpepper would take some classes over, so
he could earn a diploma and become eligible to play football.
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida was making Culpepper a project as much as a
recruit. If it took a year, two years, the coaches figured, it
would be worth it. Anyone who had seen the 6-foot-5-inch, 245-pound
quarterback throw for more than 3,000 yards and 31 touchdowns in
his senior season knew that.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCF came to me and said they were going to offer me a
scholarship no matter what happened,'' says Culpepper. ``I thought
about it for a minute and said, `This school is going Division 1 in
my sophomore year. It's in Orlando. It's something new.' I wanted
to be a part of something new, up-and-coming. And I thought, `I
could be a diamond in the rough.'''
</P>
<P>
   So Culpepper took the classes over. Turned some D's into B's. He
not only graduated but became immediately eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Once he became eligible for athletics, Culpepper was seen as a
big-time prospect, not only in football but also in baseball, a
sport in which he was good enough to be drafted by the Yankees as a
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Too late. Culpepper remained loyal to Central Florida, enrolling
in a school whose football program offered no guarantees of
on-field success.
</P>
<P>
   By last season, he had become a star who was rising and taking
an entire program with him.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper and UCF went into Lincoln to take on defending
national champion Nebraska, and they matched the Cornhuskers
touchdown for touchdown for more than a half, taking a 17-14 lead
into intermission before losing, 38-24.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper completed 24 of 35 passes for 318 yards for a
seven-touchdown underdog.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans even started booing them,'' says Culpepper, relishing
the memory. ``We went into the game with the mind-set we were going
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida took the same approach against the other
high-profile Division 1-A schools it faced, barely losing to
Mississippi and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   For the season, Culpepper completed 62.5 percent of his passes
for 3,086 yards and 25 touchdowns. He surpassed 300 passing yards
in five of 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Had he decided to turn pro last spring, some people told
Culpepper, he would have been almost as desirable a quarterback
prospect as Tennessee's Peyton Manning and Washington State's Ryan
Leaf, who went 1-2 in the draft. Manning signed a contract worth
$42.7 million and received a signing bonus of $11.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people came up to me and said, `Man, that could have
been you,''' says Culpepper. ``I'm like, `I got a season to look
forward to and I'm not going to worry about that now.'''
</P>
<P>
   He came back because of faith, perhaps wanting to prove himself
to be the best quarterback in college football before moving on to
the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Some people thought Culpepper was crazy to stay at Central
Florida. Others, including interim coach Mike Kruczek, who had an
offer from the Indianapolis Colts but chose not to leave when he
learned Culpepper was returning, were grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tremendous prospect,'' says Kruczek, a former Boston
College quarterback who was Terry Bradshaw's backup with the
Pittsburgh Steelers for four seasons. ``He's not 6-6, but he's put
together, muscular sizewise, that he can be 285 and not be fat. I
think he brings more to the table than Ryan Leaf and Peyton Manning
as a football player at the next level. I make that statement and
people think I'm crazy. But I just think he's a can't-miss guy. If
he gets in the right system, someone is going to win with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida's system is the one Culpepper is currently
making work. A year ago, the Golden Knights lost four games in
which they were within 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   This year is different because people are now watching UCF, not
stunned at high-quality performances. But Culpepper and his
teammates want more than almosts. They want wins, enough to get
them to at least 7-4, which might bring a bowl invitation. Beating
Louisiana Tech was the first step in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   If a bowl invitation comes _ and it's a huge if _ Culpepper
knows he will get recognition as well. He knows he could become a
legitimate Heisman contender with a superb performance against a
team such as Purdue, which the Golden Knights meet Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper says he gets pumped going into big stadiums and
feeling the breath of the crowd leave when he and Central Florida
make a quick strike, the way they did last year against Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our attitude is that we respect everybody but we fear
nobody,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper knows what awaits him after this season if he stays
healthy. He's such a hot prospect that he has taken out a $5
million insurance policy on himself.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that his world will change again no matter what happens
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Daunte Culpepper says he is ready for the next phase of his
life, but his link with his past is strong. He has kept in touch
with his biological mother. He never knew his father. But he is not
without family.
</P>
<P>
   There are all those brothers and sisters, nieces and nephews.
And there is Emma. Daunte says one of the first things he will do
when he does get a contract is move Emma into a mansion, a house
with lots of rooms for all the relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not going to think about that now,'' he says. ``I got
to worry about what's here at UCF right now. What happens after
that happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
