<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Annals of leaking
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You rarely see Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., in the news these days
without it being mentioned on the authority of the writer that he
is widely respected and wise. There are some things you must take
on faith. Hyde is chairman of the House Judiciary Committee,
usually called powerful, since it seems ready to swing Bill Clinton
from the highest limb.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde is notable for his distinguished appearance and his
statesmanlike oratory, a central c asting prototype of a 1930s
congressman. His name has been plastered all over the media the
past few days since someone leaked a humiliating story to Salon,
the Internet magazine. Hyde admitted he had an affair with a
married woman 30 years ago. As a journalistic enterprise, it was
enough to make sleaze cringe.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's stately response, however, may be savored. ``The statute
of limitations,'' he said with what one assumes is characteristic
largeness of spirit, ``has long since passed on my youthful
indiscretions.'' That one's a real keeper. If you do the math, as
several reporters did, Hyde's youthful indiscretion occurred when
he was a lad of 41.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyde leak predictably inflamed Georgia Rep. Bob Barr, the
famously irritable impeachment buff, who perceived in this yet
another criminal charge against Bill Clinton. If the source was the
WhiteHouse, he said, the leak would be a felony obstruction of
Congress. Nice idea. If we want to get efficient, maybe we can
charge everyone with felony obstruction of everything and not sweat
the details.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
