<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC FACES PROBLEMS WITH TENNESSEE ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's not as if Boston College's defense has never faced
an option-oriented offense. Army runs it. So does Navy. And Georgia
Tech, in its 41-31 loss to BC, sprinkled in the option.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Eagles host Temple Saturday at Alumni Stadium,
their defense will be uniquely challenged by an Owl offense that
ranks fourth in the nation in rushing, averaging almost 298.5 yards
per game.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls run the option on almost every down, save for the
occasional play-action pass by multitalented quarterback Kevin
Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, our offense is fairly simple,'' said first-year
coach Bobby Wallace, whose team will arrive at Chestnut Hill
seeking its first victory after two losses. ``But it just isolates
people on the field, and we do have some athletes who, when the
ball is in their hands, can do some good things.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason it's so hard to defend is that you have to be so
disciplined to play dive, quarterback, and pitch. It keeps the
defense from being able to pursue the ball quite as much because of
the responsibilities they have before running to the football.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the crux of the battle for BC's defense: Stop the
option at the point of attack. Rather, the Eagles must contain the
option, because as defensive coordinator Tim Rose pointed out, ``If
you make a mistake on the first part, then you're destined for
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have used the term `assignment football,' but that's
exactly what it is,'' said Rose, whose defense is ranked third in
the Big East, allowing 331.5 yards per game (109 rushing).
``Everyone has to know their assignments. One guy has to tackle the
dive. One guy has to tackle the quarterback. One guy has to tackle
the pitch. You have to be disciplined on every play because the
attack is across such a broad front.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why it will involve more than just BC's front seven.
Junior strong safety George White and junior free safety Pedro
Cirino are expected to play critical roles in run support. Wallace
singled out Cirino as a player ``who's going to be extremely active
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The free safety is a guy generally utilized to run inside and
out on the football and make a lot of tackles on the quarterback
and the quarterback to pitch,'' Wallace said. ``He's a great
player, and that's going to be a matchup we've got to try and
control in some forms, whether it's throwing the football or by
trying to block him. But that'll be an interesting matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be,'' agreed Cirino. ``I played against Kevin Harvey
in high school in the North-South Game, and he put it on us real
bad, too. He's a great athlete and good quarterback, so it's going
to be a good challenge for me and the whole defense to try and
contain him. But it's not just him. They've got a lot of weapons on
the offense. Guys like Stacey Mack and the rest of their backs are
pretty damn good.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it the most demanding offense a defensive back can face?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it's the most demanding, but you just got to
know your assignments,'' said White, BC's No. 2 tackler (14). ``If
you know your assignments, you stop their offense. Their depth at
their skill positions is going to put a lot of stress on me and
Pedro to make a lot of tackles, so it's something we've got to do.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why there can be no deviation from the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy has the dive, one guy has the pitch, one guy has the
quarterback _ every play,'' said junior nose guard Chris Hovan,
BC's top tackler (16), who earned Big East Co-Defensive Player of
the Week honors after recording eight tackles (six solo), two for
losses of 11 yards, and one quarterback sack in last week's 41-14
victory over Rutgers. ``It can never be like, `Oh, I forgot, I
thought I had him.' On every play, you should know who you have.''
</P>
<P>
   The assignments?
</P>
<P>
   White: ``It depends on the defense. It's either dive,
quarterback, or pitch. Simple as that. It just depends on the
defense; I'll take whatever I have in that defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirino: ``It varies. I'll have the pitch on some coverages and
the quarterback on others. But rarely dive. I'll probably be just
helping more than anything on the dives.''
</P>
<P>
   Hovan: ``I just got the dive. I try to make sure I clog up the
middle and make sure the quarterback doesn't pull it when he
pitches. It doesn't mean I'll make lot of plays. It's not sexy,
it's not glamorous, but it's doing your job. And that's what
everybody is going to have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
