<P>
   THE CLINTON CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ The White House criticizes the decision
to release more Starr materials as partisan and unfair. President
Clinton appears this afternoon at a meeting of his race advisory
board. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Cox photos are available to illustrate this story.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAPES _ WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee is
trying again to approve release of more information on President
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky following furious
arguments over whether to make available phone sex conversations
and other graphic material. As the committee resumed its closed
deliberations, Republican congressional leaders appeared before a
meeting of the Christian Coalition and told the conservative group
they would press ahead with their investigation of the president.
(Carr/Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BIPARTISAN _ WASHINGTON _ Sharp partisan exchanges
between members of the House Judiciary Committee on Friday showed
that Congress is far from the kind of bipartisan consensus that
must precede the forced removal of a president. (Mollison, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JURY _ WASHINGTON _ Why is grand jury testimony,
normally secret, being released in the Clinton case? Should
ordinary citizens subpoenaed before a grand jury have reason to
fear their testimony will become public? (Harlan, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REDACTIONS _ WASHINGTON _ The Judiciary Committee voted
to leave scores of items out of the released material, mostly for
privacy reasons, and those redactions won broad support. About 20
items, though, were disputed, as Republicans insisted on keeping in
graphic sexual material. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HASTINGS _ WASHINGTON _ Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., who
himself was removed from a federal judgeship through impeachment,
called Friday for impeachment proceedings against Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAMPAIGN _ WASHINGTON _ The heads of the Senate
Democratic and Republican campaign commitees Friday joined their
House counterparts in vowing to cut off financial support to any
candidate who launches a personal attack on an opponent. The
bipartisanship and abhorrence of sexual topics comes as a sharp
contrast to the process enveloping President Clinton. (Shepard, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TOUR _ WASHINGTON _ What people touring the White House
Friday are saying about President Clinton's problems. (Monroe, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate fell three votes short today
of overriding President Clinton's veto of a ban on certain
late-term abortions. The 64-36 vote followed emotional arguments
over why Congress should take the rare step of enacting legislation
over a president's objections. Four Republicans joined 32 Democrats
to sustain the veto, while 13 Democrats and 51 Republicans voted
for the override. The vote means Clinton's veto will stand _ at
least until a new Congress convenes in January. Sen. Max Cleland
(D-Ga.), who was under intense pressure to vote for the override,
voted no. Coverdell (R-Ga.) voted yes. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ The high-tech industry has a
legislative wish list for the waning weeks of the 105th Congress.
What are its prospects in a distracted capital? (Regan, Cox News
Service 1000).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Thursday in advance in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ Ohio State and Sen. Glenn make official announcement of
the $20 million endowment to the new Glenn Institute for Public
Policy. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   QUAYLE _ GAINESVILLE, Ga. _ Former Vice President Dan Quayle
campaigns for GOP gubernatorial Guy Millner on Friday as Millner
continues to bring in a string of national luminaries to help
bolster his bid against Democrat Roy Barnes. Quayle, who is a
potential presidential contender in 2000, will likely talk about
national politics in general, and Bill Clinton in particular, as
much as he will about the Georgia governor's race. (Pruitt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). ETA: 9 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   SLAVEWALK _ Before the nation embarked on its initiative on
race, a group of about 60 people from the United States, Bulgaria,
Japan, Cuba, Chile, Peru and other parts of the world, called the
Interfaith Pilgrimage of the Middle Passage, launched a pilgrimage
from Massachusetts to South Africa with the goal of healing the
history of racism. The group began their journey in May and expects
to complete it in May 1999. The group is holding rallies around
metro Atlant and has one scheduled at the MLK Center. (PScott,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CARIBBEAN-HANGINGS _ Barbados _ Gallows unused for 10 years will
soon return to active duty in Jamaica when the country hangs
Neville Lewis for murdering a motorist who asked for directions
later this month. St. Kitts and Nevis had its first hanging in 13
years last month. Barbados and Trinidad and Tobago have hangings
planned later this year. Governments in many countries unofficially
stopped hangings and floggings in the 1980s in response to protests
from international human rights groups. But rising crime has
brought about calls to resume hangings and floggings, a vestige of
British colonial rule in the region. A number of governments in the
Caribbean have even undertaken controversial steps to change their
justice systems and constitutions and sever ties with international
appeals bodies to make it easier to carry out executions.
Proponents of capital punishment contend that those condemned to
death have been using appeals to stall their fates for years at a
time. Countries like Barbados want to cut tie with the British
Privy Council, a supreme court for former British colonies, and
establish a Caribbean Court of Justice by next year. (Emling, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With HANGINGS-BOX _ Barbados _ Information on executions and
number of people on death row in Caribbean countries. (Emling, Cox
News Service).
</P>
