<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2843 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-HNS &LR;      09-18 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS SAY CLINTON SHOULD STOP MINCING WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SETH ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Leading lawyers have this advice for President
Clinton: Make sure your lawyers don't act like lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The public is tired of hyper-technical, legalistic and semantic
arguments about the definitions of sexual relations and perjury,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing a lawyer can do for Bill Clinton at this
point,'' said Juanita Brooks, a San Diego defense lawyer who has
handled several high-profile cases. ``His best friend would be a
plumber to get in there and try to plug some of these holes and
keep the ship afloat.''
</P>
<P>
   To cut loose from the tangle of sex, lies and videotape, the
president's advocates must move past the sordid details, portray
his affair with Monica Lewinsky and his efforts to hide it as
personal failings not worthy of impeachment, and present the attack
on him as partisan, according to several criminal defense experts
interviewed for this story.
</P>
<P>
   This hurdle could be raised higher if Clinton appears to be
overly defensive or equivocating on the videotape of his grand jury
testimony, which the House Judiciary Committee voted Friday to make
public.
</P>
<P>
   So his advocates _ led by Gregory B. Craig, a State Department
official _ must make a human appeal not to the courthouse but to
the public and Congress, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, his biggest problem is political, so I'm not sure a
lawyer should be doing it all,'' said Stephen Gillers, a New York
University professor of legal ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton must show the public he has assumed moral culpability
and convince members of Congress they face public backlash if they
impeach him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are not things you learn in law practice or law
school,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco lawyer James Brosnahan, Clinton's advocates must
realize his political survival depends on reaching three key
audiences: the American public; the House Judiciary Committee,
which will decide whether to issue articles of impeachment on which
he would be tried in the Senate, and about 15 middle-of-the-road
senators who could block the Senate from getting the two-thirds
vote necessary to convict the president should he be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Clinton must drop the technical arguments about whether
he committed perjury in his deposition in the Paula Jones civil
suit and in his testimony before independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Such technical arguments alienate the public, make the president
look evasive and invite counter-arguments oozing with graphic
sexual description, Brosnahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Clinton's representatives might best try to negotiate
an agreement under which he would be censured in exchange for not
holding impeachment hearings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Goodman of Las Vegas is one of the few lawyers in the
country to have defended an impeached official, former U.S.
District Judge Harry Claiborne. The judge was first convicted of
tax evasion, and in 1986 the Senate convicted Claiborne for the
same crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's between a rock and a hard place,'' Goodman said of
Clinton. While Clinton wants to be as contrite as possible, any
admission that he perjured himself could prove fatal in a
subsequent criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's best shot now is to ``do an awful lot of lobbying,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would stop talking like a lawyer and start talking like a
politician, and try to arrange an agreement that everyone could
live with. He's very popular with the public, and that means a lot
with politicians,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would remind all the Republicans that if they get rid of
President Clinton, they might end up with President Gore, and he
would be a strong incumbent'' in the next election, said Goodman, a
past president of the National Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman also would argue that an impeachment hearing ``won't do
any good. He's already been publicly humiliated. He's going to go
down in history not as creating this great prosperity but for a
stain on a dress. He's been punished enough.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William Osterhoudt, a San Francisco defense lawyer who has
defended government officials, agreed that Clinton should stop
acting like the lawyer he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense has to get away from trying to split hairs and say
he told the truth when he denied having an affair with her,'' he
said. ``That doesn't go down well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders should drive home the idea that the perjury
allegations against Clinton _ even if true _ are weak, Osterhoudt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Paula Jones' lawyers gone to any district attorney's office
seeking prosecution of a witness for lying in a deposition, they'd
have been ``laughed right out of the office,'' he said. ``No one
ever gets prosecuted for lying in a civil deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's true,'' he added, ``how can it be such a crime to
remove this elected official? That's why Congress shouldn't take
that seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should cast the charges as the product of a Republican
effort to undo a duly elected leader and ``play up that most people
think he's doing a good job'' of running the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2854 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BUSINESS-2ndT     09-18 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BUSINESS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: not surprising. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren, addressing a group of industry chief executives in
June, urged his colleagues to emphasize creativity, not market
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look at a computer. You can't look at focus groups.
... I trust my instincts,'' Lauren said in a report in Women's Wear
Daily.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including the chief executive for publicly traded Liz
Claiborne, said they depend heavily on research. But Lauren blasted
``depressing'' department stores for relying on too many
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a business about passion,'' said Lauren, who is chief
executive officer as well as designer. ``It's not a business about
numbers. If you're going to be in the numbers business, get out.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy may inspire designers, but it doesn't exactly
reassure investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That opinion might be offensive to people who've lost a lot of
money,'' says Kathy Oher, research director for Southwest
Securities in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   In the three months following Lauren's speech, his company's
stock fell 23 percent, three times the drop of the market during
the same period. Since going public in June '97, Polo Ralph Lauren
Corp. has declined more than 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Liz and Ralph and Donna Karan, and I'd buy any of their
products,'' says Leon Hall, creative director for the Dallas
Apparel Mart and a fashion commentator on cable's E! network. ``But
I don't buy their fashion stocks. I've done it before, and I've
never made any money.''
</P>
<P>
   That's easy to believe. The stock prices for many of the
best-known fashion plays have held their value about as long as
last-season's garments.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan stock, for example, has never returned to its
opening day price. Mossimo and Gucci have been on roller-coaster
rides, climbing huge peaks in a few months and plummeting just as
fast.
</P>
<P>
   Such swings may be attractive for short-term traders, who buy on
the cheap and dump the stock before it peaks. But long-term
investors, who prefer to buy a stock and hold it for years, should
realize what they're getting into, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these companies should never go public,'' Cabell
suggests. ``The designers really want to run them like a private
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein, in contrast, has never tapped the IPO market _
``we're happy to be private,'' said spokesman Robert Triefus. Nor
have many small garment manufacturers. Giorgio Armani and Gianni
Versace also have remained private, although some expect both to
tap the public markets soon.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few high-profile fashion plays that investors can
applaud. Take Tommy Hilfiger and the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in Tommy's 1992 IPO have seen their stock rise from
$7.50 (adjusted for stock splits) to more than $40 a share. Tommy,
which began as a menswear maker, is now called a ``lifestyle
brand'' because it expanded successfully into women's and
children's clothes, home furnishings, fragrances, athletic shoes
and retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, that diversification makes Tommy less vulnerable to
fashion cycles, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gap _ the nation's No. 3 retailer that wants to be the
clothing supermarket to the world _ the secret is great retailing
and solid design. Its clever TV spots, the first in five years, and
its saturation advertising on buses and billboards have drawn in
customers. Its simple, straightforward designs have kept profit
margins high.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Navy division, offering low-priced goods with an
attitude, topped $1 billion in sales three years after it was
launched. Last month, the Gap reported that second-quarter profits
almost doubled.
</P>
<P>
   How much does Wall Street like those numbers? Before the
market's recent sell off, the Gap's stock price had doubled in the
past year, and it's still up sharply.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens to companies that fall short? They get
hammered.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, St. John Knits announced that quarterly earnings
would be shy of analysts' projections for the second quarter in a
row. The stock price plunged 30 percent in a single day, and it's
down 60 percent since late May.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzooks, the teen retailer that operates more than 300 stores
nationwide, has been alternately boosted and blasted by investors.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzooks is not a clothing manufacturer, but much of its
business is tied to fashion. When it anticipates a hot teen trend,
as it did with the ``South Park'' phenomenon last holiday season,
sales soar and the stock price follows.
</P>
<P>
   But it suffers when it guesses wrong: Last year, Gadzooks bet on
beige retro-wear only to see the schoolgirl look take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzooks' stock went public at $14 a share in 1995, and within
six months hit $60. This summer, when the company warned investors
that profits would be lower than projected, the stock plunged 40
percent in a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're hot, the market makes you hotter than you should
be,'' says Gerry Szczepanski, the company's chief executive. ``When
you're not, they beat you down unmercifully.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Wall Street valued Gadzooks at $280 million, he
says. Five weeks later, the market value had dropped to $54
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a business, we really hadn't changed,'' Szczepanski says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
