<HEADER>
A2855 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BUSINESS-960(     09-18 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BUSINESS-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR FALL FASHION PORTFOLIO: THE LOOKS, THE STOCKS AND THE BOTTOM
LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fashion business has always been about the ``in'' look. The
cool factor. The style of the stars.
</P>
<P>
   But the hottest fashion craze of the '90s may be the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren, Donna Karan, Tommy Hilfiger, Mossimo, St. John
Knits, Guess?, Gucci. These trend-setting fashion companies usually
don't agree on hem lengths or fall colors, but all seem to concur
about cashing in on Wall Street. In recent years, they've used
stock sales to attract millions of dollars to expand their
businesses, pad their pocketbooks and tout their names around the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, going public has worked for them. The question is:
What's in it for you?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer: Some thrills, some spills, some heartache.
</P>
<P>
   With designer clothes, what you see is pretty much what you get.
With designer stocks, the trick is to cut through the style to the
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Think of a stock as a bet on an entire company. The price is
affected by the industry, the economy and conditions around the
world. Buying a fashion stock is not just a gamble on Ralph's
favorite skirt or your ability to pick suits that sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think they're buying a brand or a designer, but they're
really buying the whole way the business is run,'' said John
Cabell, who picks stocks for USAA's $680 million aggressive growth
mutual fund. ``It's like looking out over the ocean and thinking
you know what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of the action is beneath the surface. Fish are
eating fish, shipwrecks are decomposing, the world is tumultuous
down there. And you can't see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabell has bought _ and sold _ plenty of fashion-related stocks,
including Ralph Lauren, Mossimo, St. John Knits and Gadzooks, a
teen retailer based in Carrollton. His mutual fund still holds
shares of Tommy Hilfiger and Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, but he doesn't
recommend fashion companies for most people.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Kurt Barnard, who makes his living by following the
latest styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stocks have a major disadvantage: They're in the fashion
business,'' said Barnard, who publishes Barnard's Retail Trend
Report in New York. ``And everything that's in fashion also goes
out of fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes famous names lose their cachet, in part because
they're so popular. That alone shows how treacherous the fashion
business can be.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, once the favorite of the youth market, has faced a
backlash for months, especially among teen-agers in Japan. Mossimo,
whose ``sore-eyes'' T-shirt was so popular a few years back that
stores couldn't keep it in stock, is barely moving now.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 17 and your 14-year-old brother walks in wearing
the same shirt, you won't put it on again,'' says Kathy Karagin,
marketing director for Gadzooks.
</P>
<P>
   Cabell has other concerns about the rag trade. Many companies
grew up around New York's flashy runway life, so they tend to spend
lavishly on parties and perks. They love edgy, expensive
advertising campaigns, and they often stretch too far to expand
their business.
</P>
<P>
   They may also lag competitors in technology. Some national
retailers, such as J.C. Penney, use electronic controls to monitor
sales and instantly adjust inventory levels. Many artsy designers
still bet on their instincts.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the management issue. Many fashion companies are
run by designers or family members, rather than professional
managers. The huge egos that make designers so influential with
consumers can hamstring a company on the business side.
</P>
<P>
   Mossimo Giannulli was the driving force behind Mossimo's
meteoric rise. He designed the popular urban look and orchestrated
the firm's rapid expansion. When sales slowed, costs soared and the
stock slid from $50 a share to less than $5, Giannulli was the fall
guy. He stepped down as chief executive this year, and the company
named John Brincko, a former Barneys executive, to the top post.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan International made a similar move last year. Saddled
with disappointing profits and stock prices, the company removed
Donna Karan as CEO so she could focus on the creative side. It
installed John Idol, a former Ralph Lauren executive, as top
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are sort of like rock stars,'' Cabell says of the
big-name designers. ``They're artists who focus well on building
their name and market share. But generally, there aren't too many
rock stars who can also run the record company.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street and Seventh Avenue are not exactly a natural fit.
The stock market is obsessed with financial numbers and profit
projections. Designers, who are seen as artists, tend to focus on
emotions and passion. That the two worlds would collide is not
surprising.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
