<HEADER>
A2856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARIBBEAN-HANGINGS-$A     09-18 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARIBBEAN-HANGINGS-$ADV19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FACED WITH RISING CRIME, CARIBBEAN TURNS TO HANGINGS AS
DETERRENT
 &HT;    With HANGINGS-BOX-$ADV19.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Sept. 19 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGETOWN, Barbados _ Caribbean governments have a message for
the 250 or so inmates sitting on death row in the region: Hangings
are coming back, and with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Officials stopped hangings in the 1980s in response to protests
from human rights groups. But judges have started to impose the
punishment again, seeing it as a deterrent to rising crime _ much
of it drug-related.
</P>
<P>
   To make it easier to carry out hangings, governments are taking
controversial steps. They're changing their justice systems and
constitutions, and breaking long-standing ties with international
appeals bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once somebody has been found guilty of a really bad murder, I
feel that that person should go down,'' said Barbados Attorney
General David Simmons, a strong proponent of hangings. ``We don't
want to hang people all the time, but we do want to use it for the
worst types of murders.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbados, a country of 266,000 people, generally experiences
only nine or 10 murders a year. But calls to impose hangings have
grown louder in the wake of the shooting deaths of four men in
August that allegedly occurred as gangs jostled over a missing
supply of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in parts of the Caribbean, floggings also have been
revived as a form of punishment after years of being discounted due
to an outcry from human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Floggings are performed with the cat-o'-nine tails, which
consists of nine knotted cords attached to a handle designed to
tear an offender's back to shreds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, for example, a judge in Jamaica sentenced Noel Samuda,
30, to 12 strokes and 15 years in jail for rape and burglary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a feeling that crime is up and that something must be
done about it,'' Simmons said. ``You'll find judges in many
countries imposing tougher sentences on criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International and other groups estimate that there are
nearly 250 prisoners on death row in the English-speaking Caribbean
out of a population of five million _ one of the highest rates in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Kitts and Nevis, the first hanging since 1985 took place
in July when David Wilson was hanged for beating a man to death in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Hangings also are imminent in Barbados, Trinidad and Tobago, and
in other Caribbean countries following the hearing of last-ditch
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Neville Lewis, 32, was scheduled to be executed on Sept. 4 in
Jamaica, where the gallows have been idle for 10 years. But Lewis
has appealed to the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights,
which may hear the case as early as Sept. 28. Lewis was convicted
in 1994 of robbing and strangling a businessman who asked him for
directions.
</P>
<P>
   In Jamaica, where there were a record-breaking 1,038 murders
last year, support for the death penalty has become widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Six people were killed in shooting incidents in Jamaica last
weekend, bringing this year's total number of murders to 659.
</P>
<P>
   ``If hanging is the penalty, as it is in Jamaica, then those who
ought to hang, ought to be hanged,'' said Jamaica National Security
Minister K.D. Knight. ``Otherwise, the law will become a laughing
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, there were nearly twice as many people on
death row in the Caribbean as there are today.
</P>
<P>
   But the sentences of many prisoners were commuted to life terms
following a 1993 ruling by Britain's Privy Council _ the region's
final legal arbiter _ that deemed it inhumane to hang inmates who
are on death row longer than five years.
</P>
<P>
   This ruling virtually eliminated hangings since appeals often
drag on for anywhere from five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Britain banned hangings in 1991 in its five Caribbean
possessions, but they remain on the books in all 12 former British
colonies in the Caribbean, including Barbados and Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Britain has pressured these former colonies to
abolish the death penalty, which the European Union has long
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The Privy Council's ruling has so frustrated Caribbean
governments that many have decided to change their constitutions to
free themselves of the council. They hope to replace the council
with a Caribbean Court of Justice _ to be headquartered in Trinidad
and Tobago _ as early as next year.
</P>
<P>
   Ending ties with the council would break a colonial link
stretching back 165 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are re-evaluating our relationship with Britain, and one
reason is because we want to resume hangings,'' said Barbados Sen.
Phillip Goddard. ``There have been some brutal crimes here and the
people here want the government to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean governments also are severing relations with
international appeals bodies that officials say are used by death
row inmates to stall their fates for years.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad and Tobago partially withdrew from the U.N.
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights this year and
pulled completely out of the Inter-American Commission on Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica, too, plans to drop out of that commission.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups vehemently oppose the push to revive both
hangings and floggings, saying there is no evidence that they deter
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad trend that is taking shape across the region and
we're watching it closely,'' said Sarah DeCosse, an expert on the
Caribbean for Human Rights Watch in Washington, D.C. ``We are
worried that some due process protections are being taken away from
the prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   But most residents in the Caribbean support harsher punishments,
emphasizing that the relatively small size of the region means
everyone shares the impact of even the slightest increase in crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's a really bad crime, everyone knows about it, and
everyone feels it,'' said Jeff Cowen, a taxi driver. ``If someone
takes a life, well, we don't believe that person has a right to
live.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
