<HEADLINE>
ANTI-LOGGING ACTIVIST KILLED DURING PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An environmental activist from Texas has become
the first fatality in the long struggle between environmentalists
and the timber industry over logging old growth redwoods in
Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   David ``Gypsy'' Chain, 24, of Austin was struck in the head and
killed by a falling redwood shortly after noon Thursday near the
town of Fortuna.
</P>
<P>
   Chain, a member of the Earth First environmental group, ``was
out there running through the woods, trying to talk to loggers,
telling them not to fell the trees'' when a falling tree cracked
open his skull, said Darryl Cherney, a local Earth First leader.
</P>
<P>
   The death occurred in a grove being logged by Pacific Lumber
Co., owner of the Headwaters Forest and the focal point of
anti-logging demonstrations. Chain's body was removed by a
California Department of Forestry helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gypsy was the first person ever killed at an Earth First
protest,'' Cherney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Humboldt County Sheriff's Department was investigating the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber President John Campbell said the logging crew did
not see anybody in the area and had no idea Chain was standing
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felled a tree and apparently heard some yelling, and then
the feller was cutting the tree into segments when the body was
found under a limb,'' Campbell said. He added that sheriff's
investigators said Chain's death was ``an unfortunate accident,''
and that the company would conduct its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Earth First spokesman Josh Brown said the organization was ``not
assigning blame to the feller or Pacific Lumber Company or anybody.
It's just a complete tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Earth First activists have been protesting what they contend is
illegal logging near Grizzly Creek Redwoods State Park for more
than a week. They contend that Pacific Lumber has committed
multiple violations of state law and is destroying the habitat of
the endangered marbled murrelet, a bird that nests in the tops of
old growth redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   Eight activists were arrested for trespassing on Pacific
Lumber's Grizzly Creek logging operation on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Grizzly Creek grove where Pacific Lumber is logging is near
but not within the Headwaters Forest and adjoining acreage that is
being purchased by California and the federal government from
Maxxam Inc., Pacific Lumber's parent company, for $495 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
