<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAILWIND-SUIT-HNS &LR;      09-18 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAILWIND-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM VETERANS SUE CNN, TIME OVER NERVE GAS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGAME, Calif. _ Unappeased by the retractions and apologies
offered by Cable News Network and Time Inc., 11 combat veterans are
suing both, charging that reports alleging military use of nerve
gas in Vietnam defamed them.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint for libel, slander, invasion of privacy and
intentional infliction of emotional distress was filed Thursday in
federal court at San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   It accuses Time and CNN of intentionally twisting the facts and
sensationalizing reporting in the program titled ``Valley of
Death,'' broadcast June 7 and 14 and published as an article in
Time on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latest in a series of problems that have dogged CNN
and Time since the story came out. The news organizations have
already retracted the story and apologized for ``serious faults''
in the reporting. Subsequently, the report's executive producer
resigned, and two staff members involved in reporting the story
were fired.
</P>
<P>
   Neither CNN nor Time responded to requests for comment on the
suit, which is the latest of several filed by a total of 25
veterans involved in _ or linked by the reports to _ ``Operation
Tailwind.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the plaintiffs _ an Air Force pilot, a Marine
helicopter pilot and an Special Forces sergeant _ appeared at a
news conference at their attorney's office to denounce the
reporting and scoff at the apology.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Bishop, 65, a former Air Force major who flew an A-1
Skyraider on Operation Tailwind and dropped concentrated tear gas
on enemy troops, called the program, ``A media My Lai ... a
farce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called retraction wasn't one at all, it was only a
press release,'' said Bishop, who insisted that he had made it
emphatically clear to CNN producer April Oliver and reporter Peter
Arnett that he had dropped concentrated tear gas, not nerve gas, to
assist in the removal of U.S. troops and their allies from the
field. ``What I got was nerve gas questions, and I gave her tear
gas answers.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint alleges that CNN and Time knew or should have
known that the representations made in the program were false in
fact and that its conclusions were reached in the face of
overwhelming contradictory evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy is that the true story is a better story, and
nobody has told it,'' said Joseph Driscoll, 51, of Monterey,
Calif., who flew a Marine Cobra gunship during the four-day
operation in Laos in September 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN-Time retractions were ``as bad as the original story,''
said Michael Sheppard, 60, of Albuquerque, N.M. Sheppard was a
Special Forces staff sergeant who participated in more than 30
cross-border operations in Laos and Cambodia but was not on the
ground in Tailwind, although his photo was shown and his words were
used. ``There was a complete breakdown of responsibility in this
case.''
</P>
<P>
   All three men said the lawsuit was not financially motivated: If
they recover money damages, they said, the award would be put into
a charitable trust to aid U.S. casualties of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN program was intended to be an expose of a secret the
military had allegedly kept since the Vietnam War: that U.S.
servicemen used lethal sarin gas in Laos to kill American defectors
and may also have killed innocent Laotian women and children.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sheppard said, the 16 Special Forces troops, along with
about 100 Montagnards (indigenous forces assisting U.S. troops),
were sent to Laos to block the Ho Chi Minh Trail and were given
heavy air cover by the Marines and Air Force to do the job. They
held off or diverted 2,000 North Vietnamese troops, obtained
valuable code books and other intelligence and were extracted from
the field by helicopter with just three Montagnard casualties, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon review of Operation Tailwind found no evidence to
support the conclusion that the United States had used nerve gas
during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pentagon investigation, the substance used in
the four-day operation was concentrated but non-fatal tear gas. The
mission's purpose was to gather intelligence and to distract North
Vietnamese and Viet Cong troops from a secret CIA mission that was
under way simultaneously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
