<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-SCIENTIST-BUDGET-     09-18 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-SCIENTIST-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This budget has been transmitted three times _ into
the ``v'' advisory, ``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news
files.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., Sep. 21 and
anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I SPY WITH MY FLYING EYE &LR;  _ A tiny, pilotless spyplane that can
be fired from a cannon is under development at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology. The miniscule aircraft is designed to
emerge from the case of an artillery shell and fly over enemy
territory, sending back video pictures of the target. A San Diego
company is working on a similar project, with the aim of carrying a
bomb. By Kurt Kleiner. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-PILOTLESS-SPY-PLANE-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW BEDDING TO COMBAT DUST MITES &LR;  _ A British company has
launched novel bedding material to combat dust mites, which can be
responsible for triggering asthma. The new fabric contains a
substance that starves the mites to death by attacking the fungi on
which they depend. By Kurt Kleiner. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-BEDDING-TO-COMBAT-DUST-MITES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW TECHNIQUE OFFERS NONSTOP DIGITAL MOVIES &LR;  _ The Digital
Versatile Disc is meant to replace videotape for home recording,
but there is not enough space on one side of a DVD to record an
entire movie. Matsushita of Japan has solved the problem by putting
two layers of recording material on one side of a DVD. By Barry
Fox. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-NONSTOP-DIGITAL-MOVIES-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LET'S GO SURFIN' TO THE MUSIC STORE &LR;  _ Two music copyright
bodies have begun a pilot scheme to determine how record companies
can sell music on line. At www.musictrial.com, music tracks can be
downloaded and copied for free. By Barry Fox. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-BUYING-MUSIC-ON-LINE-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
