A2898 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARRREPORT-KIDS--TEX     09-18 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARRREPORT-KIDS--TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STARR REPORT FOR KIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're a parent, the words ``Starr Report'' might make you
blanch in fear. Lucky for you, Cynthia Leacock, a counselor and
children's author, has decided to filter it for fifth-graders.
Leacock, the owner of Novel Writing Publishers, has written ``Ken
Starr's Report for Kids,'' a vastly condensed and considerably
bowdlerized version of the report. It's available on the Internet
at www.novelwriting.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the parents told me is that kids are talking about it in
dirty language on the playground,'' says Leacock, who aimed the
report at fifth- and fourth-graders. ``They don't understand all of
what's going on. Parents want to be armed with information like
this, to help explain it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than read the whole Starr Report, Leacock anticipated the
questions it would create, then answered them in a primer format.
For instance: ``What did President Clinton do wrong?'' and ``What
is impeachment?''
</P>
<P>
   We know, you want to know how she deals with _ well, with that
Bill-and-Monica thing. She sort of dances around it, explaining
that some sorts of extramarital physical contact _ hugs, kisses on
the cheek, platonic kisses on the lips _ are OK, but that the types
that Clinton and Monica Lewinsky engaged in are not.
</P>
<P>
   More typical is the answer to ``Can Congress decide Clinton is
just in trouble?'':
</P>
<P>
   ``They may decide the president only needs a censure,'' Leacock
writes. ``A censure is like when your teacher puts your name on the
board for talking in class; you are in trouble, but you are not
kicked out of school. President Clinton might get in some trouble
for what he did, but will still be president.''
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have Internet access, call Leacock at (800)
480-9984, and she'll get you a copy of the report. Or fax a request
to (734) 761-8540.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
