<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2905 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TEACHABLE-MOM     09-18 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEACHABLE-MOMENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON/LEWINSKY OFFERED US A `TEACHABLE MOMENT' -- WAS IT LOST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JIM CASTELLI &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Religious leaders often talk about a teachable moment -- a time
when events focus public attention on a moral question in an
unprecedented way.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the months leading up to the Gulf War,
Americans conducted an extensive discussion about the nature of a
just war.
</P>
<P>
   The eight months since the Monica Lewinsky scandal emerged has
been a painful time for all Americans. But it has also been a
teachable moment -- a time when the public's attention has been
focused on core moral and ethical issues, including the nature of
sin, forgiveness, and trust; professional ethics, and the
connection between private and public morality.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this moment has been squandered. The tone of
moral debate has been set by the tabloids -- a category that now
includes just about all of the media.
</P>
<P>
   There may be some improvement now that the Starr Report is out.
The president himself has said he hassinned and commmitted to
working out his personal problems with an accountability circle of
three ministers.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the only religious leaders who have spoken
out are those who hate President Clinton no matter what he does and
those who love him no matter what he does. Most religious leaders
are extremely reluctant to talk about public controversy involving
sex or partisan politics, and this controversy involves both.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure to speak out in a situation that demands cool
heads, nuance and moral perspective is a dereliction of duty on the
part of America's religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   This may not be surprising at a time when the professions of
politics, law and media have generally disgraced themselves. But we
expect more from religious leaders, if only because they tell us we
should.
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, are some of the things that religious leaders, and
anyone concerned about morality and ethics, should be saying:
</P>
<P>
   --It is always wrong to spread false or malicious stories.
</P>
<P>
   --Everyone sins. The American Heritage Dictionary defines sin as
``a transgression of a religious or moral law, especially when
deliberate. Someone once called original sin -- the belief that
every human being sins at some time or other -- the most
empirically verifiable religious belief. Jesus came to the defense
of an adulteress woman by telling a crowd, ``Let he who is without
sin cast the first stone.Lots of people who mistakenly believe they
are without sin are throwing a lot of stones today. No one alive
could go through $40 million of federal investigation and not have
a sin or two turn up.
</P>
<P>
   --All sins are not equal. Sins differ in both their nature and
their context. Stealing a pizza is wrong and so is murder, but the
offenses are far from equal. And stealing a pizza for fun, stealing
it to trade for drugs, and stealing it to feed a starving family
are also very different offenses.
</P>
<P>
   --When someone asks for forgiveness, he or she must also do
penance and take steps to show that he or she will not repeat the
offense. Most of those at the Prayer Breakfast believe the
president is sincere in his efforts to repent and change his ways.
Itis far less clear what the president would have to do to repent
in his public life, partly because the public continues to believe
he's doing a good job.
</P>
<P>
   --The test of your commitment to ethical standards is your
willingness to stick to them when it's not convenient. If grand
jury testimony is supposed to be secret, it's supposed to be secret
even when leaking it would give you an advantage. If reporters are
supposed to verify stories before they report them, they have to
verify them even when skipping that stage would give them a scoop.
If we throw out ethical standards to seek a temporary advantage,
then our commitment to those standards is a sham.
</P>
<P>
   --We must evaluate people by the sum of their actions. About 20
years ago I mused to a wizened editor that good people sometimes do
bad things and bad people sometimes do good things. He replied,
``And there are very few good people or bad people.'' We should
practice humility when we attempt to judge people.
</P>
<P>
   --What we think of someone today can change dramatically
depending on what they do tomorrow, or what new facts emerge
tomorrow. We evaluate people in different ways in different
circumstances; we may stop considering someone a friend, but still
admire his or her talents. When George Wallace died recently, he
was remembered as a symbol of racism in the 1960s and early 70s,
but also as a symbol of racial reconciliation since then.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have always lived with ambiguous attitudes toward
their presidents. Did John F. Kennedy risk his presidency with his
reckless private life? Did Lyndon Johnson do more good with the
Great Society than he did harm with the Vietnam War? Even many
liberals who detested Richard Nixon when he was in office look back
on many of his domestic policies as surprisingly liberal by today's
standards. Many people who stand by Clinton today believe, for
example, that some of the tough provisions in the 1996 welfare law
he signed were immoral, but still support him for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   --We should evaluate public officials primarily on the basis of
their public responsibilities to advance the common good. Private
action is not irrelevant, but it must be seen in perspective.
Several clerics at the White House breakfast argued that Clinton's
personal failings, which they described as adultery,sexual sin and
broken marriage vows, must be seen in the context of his record as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Morality is often a matter of proportionality. The just-war
theory argues that to be morally justified, the good that a war
achieves must outweigh the evil that it causes.
</P>
<P>
   That's a daunting standard -- one that should apply to every
major public undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Jim Castelli is the author of ``A Plea for Common Sense:
Resolving the Clash Between Religion and Politics'' (Harper &AMP; Row).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2909 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-CLINTON-PERSPE     09-18 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-CLINTON-PERSPECTIVE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR FROM WASHINGTON'S GLARE, MYSTERY AND SADNESS AMID QUIET LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I don't care about Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky.
 &HT;    For months, preachers and pundits have chided the unconcerned
masses -- in whose ranks I find myself -- about our laissez-faire
attitude regarding morality.
 &HT;    Surely, these critics scold, America is morally bankrupt. Does
anyone care that the president cheated on his wife and lied about
it?
 &HT;    Although I can't speak for my fellow citizens, I know why this
scandal fails to engender my moral outrage. I have been overwhelmed
with family matters and have little energy to expend worrying about
who did what with whom.
 &HT;    This summer, as Clinton's troubles multiplied, my father
struggled with lung cancer. For nearly two years, he had fought the
disease with dignity -- using his own small victories to cheer
others fighting cancer.
 &HT;    As the months passed, however, his pain increased and his breath
shortened. Three weeks ago, his lungs collapsed and he died in my
mother's and sister's arms.
 &HT;    Within a few days, my mother, overcome by stress, suffered a
heart attack.
 &HT;    For my family, the nightly news mattered little -- background
noise as we planned my father's funeral; something to watch while
waiting outside the emergency room.
 &HT;    Bill and Monica? Kenneth Starr? Perjury? Those were not our
questions.
 &HT;    Rather, we puzzled over an open casket, an appropriate memorial,
and the funeral sermon. And, the most immediate concern, would mom
make it?
 &HT;    My parents -- not famous, rich, or well-educated -- were always
profoundly decent people. Like everyone, they made mistakes and did
not always make wise choices. They were not perfect parents.
 &HT;    However, they lived with the quiet dignity of many Americans who
try to be good and do the right things. Their world centered on
children and church, monthly bills and the mortgage.
 &HT;    This summer, my father's illness and death pulled me away from
``big issues,'' writing projects, and scholarly research. My
parents needed me. They needed to talk about their fears and needed
to spend time with my daughter. They needed to share memories and
make new ones while there was still time. They needed hands held as
they walked through the journey to death.
 &HT;    My parents' gallant sojourn taught me -- as I have never known
before -- that life's simplest joys are its richest. A dying man
crying as his wife holds him. Pleasure over seeing one's
granddaughter in a pink ruffled party dress. Recalling birthdays,
anniversaries, and family vacations. Telling stories of military
service and old flames.
 &HT;    When I was a bit younger, such things seemed boring and dull.
Now I understand that memories and family stories, common joys and
sorrows weave together lives and generations in what Christian
tradition calls ``the communion of saints.''
 &HT;    My parents persisted in faith in the face of pain and fear to
the end. My father's courage and my mother's compassion (stressful
though it was) have become part of the journey -- for them, for me,
for their grandchildren.
 &HT;    Their struggle was heroic. But it remained hidden to most of the
world. This passion played itself out in the confines of their
family, neighborhood, church, and jobs.
 &HT;    It is on such small stages that most of us enact our own dramas.
In terms of what ``counts'' as fame or influence, my parents --
like most of us -- were not candidates for the nightly news.
 &HT;    Yet these dramas, shape us and enrich our lives. In life's
common places, we face tragedy and triumph, become heroes of our
own epics, and find the mysteries of the universe revealed. In
small ways, faith, hope, and love confront us with powers beyond
our ken. We meet grace. We find God in the journey.
 &HT;    So, columnists and preachers, I do not care about Bill and
Monica because I am busy with the mystery and sadness of death and
helping my mother recover and pay her bills.
 &HT;    I do, however, care about fidelity and truth-telling; I care
about how such things played out for my parents and me. From our
struggles, I know about moral leadership, sin, forgiveness, grace
and mercy. I know -- and care -- about such things.
 &HT;    But I couldn't care less about your political agendas telling me
who, what, and how to forgive.
 &HT;    My parents quietly embodied the courage of a 40-year marriage --
of love, companionship, forgiveness, of birth and death. American
moral decline? My parents? The millions like them?
 &HT;    We care, but we're too busy raising children and paying bills to
obsess about presidential scandal. Sure, we're disappointed, but we
know Bill and Monica are human, too. Their mistakes happen to be on
a bigger stage than ours.
 &HT;    And that's their tragedy. Most of us have the grace of quiet
lives.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
