<HEADLINE>
COLOR OF MONEY CAN'T HIDE THE DECAY IN ATLANTIC CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ The tourism and convention crowd likes to
promote Atlantic City as ``America's Favorite Playground.'' A new,
$268 million convention center is marketed as ``America's New
Northeast Business Address.''
</P>
<P>
   At the old convention center, the historic Boardwalk hall that
still hosts the Miss America Pageant, a table in the media room is
strewn with press kits touting everything from hotel/casino
expansion to housing redevelopment projects. If the brochures are
accurate, the gambling business is pouring money into the community
as relentlessly as the tourists are cranking their hard-earned
quarters into slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   And if all this is true _ well, better late than never.
</P>
<P>
   Casino gambling came to Atlantic City in 1978, bringing hope for
economic rebirth in a city that had fallen on hard times after a
long and proud history as one of the Atlantic Coast's great resort
towns.
</P>
<P>
   In the days when cities and states looked upon gambling as a
criminal activity rather than an easy route to souped-up tax
receipts, tourists flocked to Atlantic City in the summertime to
enjoy the simple pleasures of white sand beaches and Boardwalk
amusements. The Miss America Pageant, in fact, was concocted in
1921 as a gimmick to entice out-of-towners to stay past Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   But as vacationers began to seek out destinations that offered
more scintillating pursuits than soaking up sun and strolling six
miles of oceanside Boardwalk, Atlantic City fell prey to the urban
blight that has assaulted so many American cities.
</P>
<P>
   The developers and politicians arrived with an easy solution for
the complicated problems confronting a failing municipality:
Casinos would bring the tourists back to Atlantic City and would
keep them here, not just for an extra week or two in September but
all year round.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected that even the avalanche of cash touched off by
casinos would rescue an entire city _ not overnight, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The developers and casino operators weren't setting up shop on
the South Jersey Shore to engage in philanthropy, after all. Their
purpose was to make money _ as much as they could, as fast as they
could. If some of the money spilled onto the streets of Atlantic
City, good for Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such thing as a quick fix for urban decay.
</P>
<P>
   But who could have guessed that so many residents of Atlantic
City would still be waiting for the casino money to trickle in
their direction? Who could have guessed that now, 20 years after
the first coin plopped into a slot machine, you could look out an
eighth-floor window in one of Donald Trump's hotels and see a slum?
</P>
<P>
   Who could have guessed that in 1998 the eruption of cash from
the Boardwalk would not have reached Pacific Avenue, just one block
away from the glitter of the casino/hotels where money flows as
freely as the complimentary drinks that are served to thirsty
gamblers?
</P>
<P>
   Step out of the massive Trump hotel-casino complex that
surrounds Convention Hall, walk up Florida Avenue to Pacific, and
you are suddenly awash in urban blight. Away from the blinking neon
of the Boardwalk, you suddenly see nothing but rundown buildings
occupied by cheesy cash-for-gold shops and nude go-go joints.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic City may be America's Favorite Playground, but it is
also America's Capital of Dichotomy, America's Mecca of
Incongruity. You'd be hard-pressed to find a place where
eye-popping wealth and abject poverty coexist in more intimate
proximity _ or in more apparent obliviousness to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all this is about to change. The Atlantic City Convention
&AMP; Visitors Authority is heralding a ``multibillion-dollar
renaissance'' that will change the face of Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   The Casino Reinvestment Development Authority is talking up a
housing program that will encourage home ownership and engender
revitalization of Atlantic City's neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   If all this is true, it's better late than never. If it's all
nothing but empty promises _ well, that's a crying shame.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
