<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK PINK FOR SPRING, DESIGNERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Do you look pretty in pink? It's a question we're all
going to have to ponder this spring (even men) because that's a
dominant color we'll be seeing in stores.
</P>
<P>
   During this fashion week, a number of designers presented pink _
both hot and soft _ as a top new color for spring. (While most
designers showed their women's spring collections, Helmut Lang
draped male and female models in the hue.)
</P>
<P>
   It's a far cry from this fall's conservative gray. Certainly, it
won't be recommended for work. But after seasons of black,
chocolate brown, and now gray and winter white, why not wear a
splash of bright color?
</P>
<P>
   Designers were full of fresh ideas _ perhaps because they knew a
lot was at stake. This week represented the first time in fashion
history that New York-based designers unveiled their collections
prior to the European design houses such as Chanel and Versace.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the Americans show comes weeks after those of
designers in London, Milan, and Paris. By showing last on the
fashion calendar, Americans have always faced accusations of
copying _ right off the runway _ the innovations of their European
counterparts. Many believe that by showing first this season New
York-based designers had a chance to prove their creativity (and
score orders from retailers who haven't seen spring clothes
anywhere else yet).
</P>
<P>
   Well, creative they were. Helmut Lang presented lots of
contrasts in his collection, such as cotton-crepe skirts that were
smooth in the front and pleated in the back. Many of his dresses
were sheer organza (in nude or hot pink colors) and were worn over
cotton T-shirts and skirts, creating an interesting layered
dressy-casual effect.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his trousers were decorated with holster-style pouches
(for money or keys, for example) attached at the hip and wrapped
around one leg. And in a true contradiction, model Alek Wek
strutted past the audience in an elegant black silk skirt, sheer
cotton-crepe tank top, and _ go figure _ athletic-looking black arm
pouches worn above her elbows. (They looked like elbow pads.)
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan presented interesting skirts. Some, made of
parchment taffeta, were of doubled-up fabric twisted around the
models to give a feeling of motion. (They seemed to twirl around
the models' bodies.) Other skirts consisted of long strips of
layered fabrics such as chiffon and organza (like a hula-skirt).
Many of Karan's accompanying sweaters and shirts were oversized,
giving a feeling of comfort and relaxed luxury.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest news in Karan's collection was all the
color. Karan has always embraced black and white as fundamental for
women's wardrobes. This season, however, the designer _ inspired,
she said in her program notes, by the ``beauty of nature'' _
selected soft pink, green, blue, and yellow as some of her colors.
Gray and white were present too. But, in a major shift, there was
no black in the show (although retailers can order any item in
black, the company says).
</P>
<P>
   The designer Jussara Lee opened her show with a live performance
by an accordion player, a signal of what was to come: clothes from
old Europe. Many outfits were peasant-like, with floral fabrics,
empire waistlines, gathered sleeves with ties, embroidered designs,
and hems with ruffles.
</P>
<P>
   Other outfits had apron accessories _ embroidered aprons worn
over dresses and pants. While it was an interesting touch, the
question one has to ask is: Do modern women want to wear aprons on
the street? They certainly can't wear them to work, unless they
work in a kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Jussara's collection had some modern elements too, including a
miniskirt (a rarity these days), sparkling and iridescent fabrics,
and trendy drawstring pants.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more interesting designers to show this week was the
up-and-coming German Thomas Steinbruck _ who has worked for
Gianfranco Ferre at Christian Dior and Geoffrey Beene. Two of the
inspirations for his collection (which was displayed in a showroom,
not on a runway) are the ocean and the beach. They're reflected in
his quirky embroideries (lobsters on sheer tops) and his soft
colors (ocean blue and sand-like cream). He also used crinkled
iridescent fabric to create texture in jackets and dresses (like a
rippling ocean) and asymmetrical hemlines to give skirts and
dresses an edge (like a sand dune). His silk-cashmere cardigans
were presented with miniature shells or pearls stitched around the
collar and sleeve cuffs. Taken together, it was a striking look.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 New York-based designers presented collections this
week, including Nicole Miller, Mark Eisen, and Han Feng. But about
40 others _ including Bill Blass, Oscar de la Renta, and Ralph
Lauren _ are waiting to show during the traditional, official New
York fashion week Nov. 2 to Nov. 6, after the European shows.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these designers aren't opposed to showing before Europe
in theory. But since this week's shows were organized on short
notice over the summer, many of them weren't able to shorten their
production schedules to participate.
</P>
</TEXT>
