<HEADLINE>
GM DROPPING THE RIVIERA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say goodbye to Buick Riviera. Once again, having perfected a
car, General Motors will kill it. If it's anything the General
can't stand, it would seem to be class.
</P>
<P>
   With the '99 model year, Riviera enters the realm of collectible
_ well maybe the name is already there, at least when it's on a
ragtop. Although Buick has turned out more than a million cars
bearing the Riviera badge since the Riviera first showed up as a
``concept'' in 1963, only 3,000 convertibles were built spanning
1982-1985.
</P>
<P>
   Production of the front-drive, full-size coupe is scheduled to
wind down with a limited-edition 1999 Riviera Silver Arrow _ the
name Silver Arrow is taken from that first concept Riviera still
owned by the Sloan Museum in Flint, Mich. Only 200 of the '99
Silver Arrows are to be produced before the line shuts down for
good Nov. 25 at the Orion, Mich., assembly plant. Only 2,000
Rivieras total are to be turned out for the '99 model year.
</P>
<P>
   The current model, a strikingly handsome exercise in aerodynamic
design, was introduced in model year 1995 to high praise and
general acclaim. The new swoopy Riviera is a far cry from some of
the early editions, as different from that first Silver Arrow as
Boeing jetliners are from biplanes. The Riviera is a study in
style, a delight on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The name goes back to 1949 and the Roadmaster Riviera hardtop,
but the name became a model line in 1963; in 1979, it went
front-drive, sharing a platform with Olds Toronado. It started out
as a $4,333 coupe with a 401-cubic-inch, 325-horsepower V-8. Since
then it's been praised, downsized, a test bed of technology,
upsized, and finally passes from view as a $32,500 exercise in
technical sophistication and style.
</P>
<P>
   So, Riviera joins another front-drive paragon of excellence, the
Buick Reatta, a sporty little coupe/convertible that had been built
in a state-of-the-art modern assembly plant, Buick City, until it,
too, was consigned to the ranks of the collectible _ where it is
prized by the knowledgeable today.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Pontiac Fiero, a revolutionary, plastic-skinned,
two-seater concept that had a painful evolution into a worthy
little car _ dropped as soon as the problems were solved.
</P>
<P>
   And who can forget Cadillac Allante, a two-seater made expensive
by squandering resources on fancy transport and Italian assembly,
made silly with a jukebox dashboard, made history as soon as it
became a really smart little roadster.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Riviera have slumped in recent years, even as the
economy surged. GM would have us believe that the fault lies
somewhere in a market that shuns two-doors, even two-doors with
exceptional styling and a virtually flawless 240-horsepower
turbocharged engine. So how does that explain sales of Japanese
two-doors?
</P>
<P>
   But, let us not rush to blame GM's marketing. After all, the
company has combed the nation to find the best and the brightest in
diaper, cookie, and notions sellers. Riviera, unfortunately, was a
child of car guys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
