s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWISH-HOLIDAYS-$ADV2     09-18 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-HOLIDAYS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRUCING UP FOR HOLIDAYS: IT'S A MITZVAH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 20) 
(JT) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   September is the month when my mailbox is jammed with fall
fashion catalogs and glatt kosher caterers have signs in their
windows urging, ``Place your holiday orders now.'' For me, the
coincidence of these two rituals inspires a single unifying drive _
to select a wardrobe for Rosh ha-Shanah and Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as I can remember, I have been gripped by a fashion
fever before the High Holy Days that begins in late August and
peaks in mid-September. This feeling of urgency, the need to buy
something new and special for the Jewish New Year, I believe, is a
lasting effect of growing up in Great Neck, N.Y., an affluent,
predominately Jewish suburb on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Great Neck is a place where I remember women wearing fur coats
over tennis dresses to the supermarket. Where the natural look was
shunned. Where grooming, like chicken soup, was the remedy for
everything.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as I would return from summer camp as a girl, where the
electricity was faulty and a blow-dryer didn't always work, my
mother would whisk me off for a ``wash and blow'' at Peter's Place,
a hair salon formerly situated on Middle Neck Road in Great Neck,
and now known as Peter Coppola on Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the exhilaration of passing through the smoked-glass
doors of Temple Beth-El of Great Neck, decked out in a spiffy wool
outfit purchased for the High Holidays. It never mattered that my
turtleneck sweater, midi skirt and opaque tights were too hot and
itchy for the Indian-summer weather that invariably hung over the
holidays. Oblivious to physical discomfort, I felt exalted by the
chance to flaunt something new and stylish before the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years have passed since I observed the holidays in Great
Neck. In Manhattan, at Central Synagogue, where I now attend
services, I can get away with wearing the same old thing year after
year because I'm just another dress in the crowd. But I miss the
communal primping that I remember preoccupying my hometown at this
time of year. So recently, I went back to see if anything had
changed, hoping to re-experience the sacral shopping and ablutions
of my youth.
</P>
<P>
   Coifing for the holidays _ Rosh ha-Shanah begins Sunday night _
it turned out to be just as frenzied as I recalled. ``The women
start the big work _ the highlights, hair straightening _ about a
week to a week and a half before the Jewish holidays,'' Michael
Mazzei, the owner of the Nubest Salon on Northern Boulevard in
Manhasset, told me. Thirty percent of his clients are from Great
Neck. ``The books have been filled up six weeks in advance for the
Sunday before the holiday,'' he said. ``The clients want the hair
and nails done. We will need an extra 10 cutters.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition to be well dressed is just as fierce as always.
The hunt for holiday attire begins early, in the dog days of
summer. Pity the congregant who puts off her shopping till the last
minute. By early September, the local clothing racks are likely to
be lined with nothing more than empty hangers.
</P>
<P>
   Right after Labor Day, Shari Kaynes, the owner of Shari's Place,
a Great Neck boutique selling high-fashion designers like Thierry
Mugler and Moschino, confirmed: ``We hardly have any skirt suits
left. We're waiting for a new shipment. The best selection is in
August and mid-September, if you can wait that long. But it's
cutting it close to the Jewish holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think all is vanity, only vanity, the fall fashion
sprees have a religious grounding. Wearing something new for a
festive occasion is a mitzvah, a commandment and good deed in
Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an expression of one's feeling of respect for the
occasion to dress up,'' said Jerome Davidson, the senior rabbi at
Temple Beth-El. ``The High Holy Days represent not only the
beginning of the year but a time of spiritual renewal, a sense of
cleansing and purity. To some, being nicely garbed would reflect,
in an outer way, the inner importance of renewal.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up, I did not know that there was a rabbinical seal of
approval to shop. If I had, I might never have become a religion
school dropout by age 10. I still went to synagogue twice a year,
for the Jewish holidays, but I only lip-synced the Hebrew prayers.
Buying a new outfit was one of the few rites I could cling to. I'm
not sure whether the liturgical imperative meant lingering outside
temple, sizing up other congregants, but that's what we did.
</P>
<P>
   ``A holiday means something new,'' Ms. Kayne said. ``You don't
want to repeat last year's suit. This is a place where you see your
acquaintances, friends and family. If you're fashion-conscious, you
want to look right.''
</P>
<P>
   There was even pressure to buy not just one, but two new
outfits, the first for Rosh ha-Shanah, the New Year, and the second
for Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement. For some, not having that
second outfit was close to sinning. ``You had to have two outfits,
because God forbid you'd be seen in the same outfit for Yom
Kippur,'' recalled Cindy Markowitz, 37, a childhood friend who now
lives in Hewlitt.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, much has changed in Great Neck. The
Orthodox are now more prominent, with additional synagogues and
meeting places. The Lubavitch Chabad, a Hasidic group, recently
established a religious center in the town. A large influx of
Middle Eastern Jews, particularly from Iran, has led to the
building of at least three Sephardic synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   Although the great majority of Jews in Great Neck are
non-Orthodox, and most businesses remain open on the Sabbath, there
are more kosher butchers now than when I lived there, as well as
new stores and markets catering to Persian tastes. Great Neck is no
longer the real-life version of Philip Roth's fictional world of
Jews who have assimilated.
</P>
<P>
   But thankfully, some things have stayed the same. ``I'm here 30
years _ it hasn't changed,'' said Shari Zelin, 36, of Great Neck.
``You go to temple, you wish everyone `Good yom tov' _ `Happy and
healthy New Year' _ you tell everyone they look beautiful, and
`Where did you get that outfit?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
