<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ Amid objections from Democrats,
the House Judiciary Committee votes to release evidence sent to
Congress by independent counsel Kenneth Starr, including the
videotape of the president's grand jury testimony. The material
will be edited to remove ``salacious and redundant information,''
says Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill. By GREG MCDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HASTINGS (Washington) _ Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., is
an expert on impeachment. As a federal district judge, Hasting was
impeached by the House, convicted by the Senate and removed from
the bench. Now, as a member of the House, Hastings speaks his mind
on the case against President Clinton. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH-CHRISTIANS (Washington) _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich
addresses a Christian Coalition convention in Washington, taking a
low profile on President Clinton's troubles. But others addressing
the conservative organization are not so reticent. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS (Dallas) _ More than any other NFL team over the
years, the Dallas Cowboys have been known to thrive when forced to
use their backup quarterback. Through the years, such names as
Roger Staubach, Clint Longley, Danny White and even Jason Garrett
have come off the bench in dramatic style. With chart. By JODY
GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Pittsburgh) _ The Houston Astros open their final
road trip of the regular season, sending Randy Johnson to the mound
against Pittsburgh for the third time this season. By CARLTON
THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AGENDA (Washington) _ As he braces for congressional
release of his videotaped grand jury testimony and details on his
18-month affair with Monica Lewinsky, President Clinton immerses
himself in foreign relations, preparing to meet with leaders of
Italy, Pakistan and Japan and speak at the United Nations. By
STEWART POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   PERJURY-IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ With President Clinton widely
accused of perjury for denying that he had sexual relations with
Monica Lewinsky, the House Judiciary Committee will have to
determine whether lying under oath is an impeachable offense. The
White House is expected to argue that perjury in the context of
private misconduct is not an impeachable offense. By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-ELECTION (Berlin) _ Gerhard Schroeder, the politician who
hopes to unseat Chancellor Helmut Kohl in next Sunday's national
elections, bears an uncanny similarity to Bill Clinton. In other
ways, the elections here would give many Americans a distinct
feeling of deja vu. By MARK HELM. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-RECONCILIATION (Fawaaa, Lebanon) _ Eight years after
Lebanon's civil war ended, the country remains as divided along
religious lines as ever, with Christian and Muslim sects dominating
different regions of the country. While rebuilding has begun on a
limited scale, reconciliation remains elusive, sectarianism
threatens stability, and Lebanon's wartime agonies endure. By
DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TX-IMMIGRANTS (McAllen, Texas) _ More and more of the immigrants
illegally crossing the Rio Grande near McAllen are from Central
America, causing some problems for the U.S. Border Patrol. With
limited space to house detainees, about one-fourth of the
non-Mexicans who are apprehended, are merely turned loose this side
of the border. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   With: TX-YOUNG-IMMIGRANTS
</P>
<P>
   RACE-BIAS (Mineola, Texas) _ Against steep odds, Hulbert Perkins
made the big score. He became a prosperous black businessman in a
region of Texas long known as Ku Klux Klan country. By 1997, it
seemed to Perkins that Mineola had finally laid to rest the
remnants of the Old South for which East Texas is storied. Then he
tried to buy a house. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Impeaching the president is a
decision that House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said is next to a
declaration of war in terms of the most important action that
Congress can take. Congress' first brush with impeachment occurred
in 1868, when Republican radicals sought unsuccessfully to oust
Andrew Johnson from the White House because of his post-Civil War
policies of reconciliation with the defeated South. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
