<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2993 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINNEY-FILM-PROFILE-$     09-18 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINNEY-FILM-PROFILE-$ADV20-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACTRESS PLAYS ELIZA TO A DESIGNER'S HIGGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Sept. 20)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By PETER McQUAID   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``The Truman Show,'' Laura Linney plays Jim Carrey's wife, an
actress pretending to be a real person. In life, Ms. Linney is an
actress struggling to project a movie star, now that ``The Truman
Show'' has brought her the widest attention yet during a career
built on theater and television.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing to attend the Venice and Deauville Film Festivals,
where ``The Truman Show'' made its Italian and French premieres
recently, Ms. Linney faced a real-life star quandary: What, oh
what, to wear?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, for every Hollywood actress in distress there is a
designer eager to come to the rescue, happy to link the name of a
design house to that of a celebrity. Susan Sarandon has Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana. Nicole Kidman has John Galliano. Ms. Linney has Donald
Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me?
</P>
<P>
   Deal, a smallish evening-wear designer popular with Vanessa
Williams, Toni Braxton, Lisa Kudrow, Kathie Lee Gifford and Barbara
Walters, caters to stars who care more about looking quietly
terrific than being current with the trends. That's perfect for Ms.
Linney, who is inching toward high fashion with baby steps. ``I
went to Cannes with `Absolute Power' when it closed the festival,
and that was overwhelming,'' she said, recalling the frenzy of
flashbulbs scrutinizing her _ and her outfit _ for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, she sat on a white sofa at the center of Deal's
living-room-like showroom, in the garment district. ``I need
help,'' she admitted.
</P>
<P>
   With her blond hair falling gently around her face and
shoulders, Ms. Linney comes across very much like Mary Ann
Singleton, the earnest Midwestern transplant she played in ``Tales
of the City,'' the television version of Armistead Maupin's
chronicles of San Francisco in the 1970s. Like her roles, Ms.
Linney is normal-seeming and approachable.
</P>
<P>
   Uma Thurman may have played a character named Poison Ivy in
``Batman Forever,'' but the down-to-earth Ms. Linney actually gets
the rash. As she made her preparations to jet off to Europe, her
wrists were streaked with it. ``Ugh _you should have seen it a week
ago, swollen out to there!'' she said, explaining how she
contracted poison ivy while planting blueberry bushes at her
Connecticut home. ``I was praying it wouldn't spread to my face.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier meetings with Deal, Ms. Linney had picked through his
collection for gowns and dresses suited to the two European
premieres, each with its sartorial challenges. ``The direction for
Venice was formal,'' Deal said. ``They're honoring Sophia Loren.
Deauville is seaside, less formal. There's a red carpet in Venice,
which makes it much more formal.''
</P>
<P>
   It was time for final fittings. An assistant brought out the
Deauville gown, a low-cut sarong, composed of a sheer black outer
layer and a lace skirt beneath. The sophisticated sexiness of the
dress had unnerved Ms. Linney when she first tried it on. Her
instinct had been to change at once, but Deal persuaded her to take
a good look at herself in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little shy when it comes to fashion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Given her upbringing, that's surprising. Contrary to her
farm-fresh image, Ms. Linney, 32, was born and reared on
Manhattan's Upper East Side, the daughter of a nurse and Romulus
Linney, the playwright. She majored in theater history at Brown
University, learned her craft at Juilliard and honed it on
Broadway, most recently in ``Honour.''
</P>
<P>
   Deal understands her skittishness about fashion. ``There's an
identity crisis when people have to dress up, and I don't think it
has to be that intimidating,'' he said. ``She comes up here, and we
play. We try on 15 different gowns. We put on long, we put on
short, we try sling-backs, we try pumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney returned from the dressing room in the Deauville
gown, teetering atop a pair of black suede Valentino pumps.
``Well?'' she asked, turning to display the full effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darling, you look fabulous,'' gushed Cindy Berger, her
publicity agent. It was Ms. Berger who had introduced Ms. Linney to
Deal in the first place, during a search for something to wear last
spring for ``Late Show With David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship that has evolved between actress and designer
is typical of the love fest between Seventh Avenue and Hollywood _
a marriage of mutual promotion. Ms. Linney receives Deal's evening
gowns, which retail for $2,000 to $5,000, at a discount (the
designer would not say how much). In all, she went to Europe with
eight or nine Donald Deal dresses _ a well-made match between a
semifamous actress and a semifamous designer.
</P>
<P>
   In the Deauville dress, Ms. Linney looked transformed: the
plunging neckline and the hemline just above the knee showed off a
Barbie doll figure. Catching sight of herself in the mirror, she
looked innocently pleased. ``Who KNEW?'' she said, mimicking a
Brooklyn accent. ``Who woulda thought?''
</P>
<P>
   Deal said little, busily looking for flaws in the fit. The
direct attention of a designer is one reason Ms. Linney is devoted
to Deal. She could have sought out a more high-profile designer
(and indeed, Donna Karan outfitted her for daytime press junkets),
but Deal's more modest business allows him to personally dress Ms.
Linney, rather than delegating the job to a subordinate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney knows how rarefied her shopping experience is; she is
not yet blase about the perquisites of stardom. ``It's very easy to
take this type of relationship for granted, for any actress who's
being dressed and being offered clothes,'' she said. ``I'm really
learning from Donald.''
</P>
<P>
   She disappeared into the dressing room again, to try on the
dress for Venice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not fluff,'' Deal said in her absence. ``I feel I'm
represented well, not just because of her talent, but because she
carries herself well.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes pride in being somewhat distant from the fashions of
the moment. ``I'm not here to tease or shock or provoke, and that's
where fashion seems to be going right now,'' he said. Deal, 39,
credits his traditional interpretation of high glamour to an
apprenticeship with James Galanos, the master dressmaker, who was a
favorite of Nancy Reagan's. ``What's interesting is that the
clients don't want to be noticed when they dress up to go out,'' he
sighed. ``That's why they always go for black.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney made a second entrance, this time in the Venice
dress, a floor-length, loden-green halter dress with black satin
straps and diamante clips at the bust and waist. A slit in the
front opened to reveal legs as long as Cyd Charisse's. ``Feel
this,'' Ms. Linney said, holding up the green velvet of her skirt.
``This dress feels like it's been painted on _ in the best way.''
</P>
<P>
   If it was formality that was to be the order of the night in
Venice, the dress delivered. Why, it even had a train. ``A lot of
women don't know how to walk with a train,'' Deal said, adding that
the hard part is executing a turn. ``They start walking, and they
walk down the dress, and soon they're walking on their knees,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Unexpectedly, Ms. Linney demonstrated the way to do it. ``What
you do is turn, then kick the train out of the way and walk,'' she
said, gliding around the showroom. ``You can't always hold it, and
the only time you want to gather your dress is when you're walking
upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   But how had Ms. Linney, a self-described fashion neophyte,
learned such a maneuver? Had she been taking secret lessons in
high-gloss glamour?
</P>
<P>
   No, she said. ``I learned it from my theater training.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
