<HEADER>
A2994 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV20-NYT     09-18 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SILICON VALLEY, TALENT IN RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
 (bl)  
 By VIVIENNE WALT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1994, Michael Bowles was skulking outside his office at
Hughes Electronics in El Segundo, Calif., whispering on public
telephones to potential investors and pleading for financing to
start his own cable modem company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty discouraging,'' he said. ``None of them knew me,
and they had a lot of trepidation about handing over a company to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowles, 49, finally pieced together the money to move to
California's Silicon Valley and start Com21 in Milpitas. In classic
Valley style, though, the thrill ended for him the moment the
company went public last January. But rather than return to the
phone booth, he became one of the high-technology industry's most
desired modern commodities: an entrepreneur in residence.
</P>
<P>
   That meant that for six months, Crosspoint Venture Partners in
Woodside, Calif., paid Bowles to scrutinize potential business
plans and pick which company he might want to run next _ ``quite a
contrast'' to his situation five years earlier, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just sat around and talked about, `Gee, wouldn't this be a
cool business?''' Bowles said. Three months ago, he founded iBeam
Broadcasting, an Internet satellite broadcasting company, with
financing from Crossport.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley's frantic hunt for the new, cool and profitable
has come to rely increasingly on executives like Bowles, who,
between jobs, set up shop in venture capital firms and plan their
next moves. Several venture capitalists say they regard the
arrangement not only as a successful strategy but also as a crucial
edge in the scramble for good investments.
</P>
<P>
   The concept isn't new. Since the early 1980s, larger venture
capital firms have brought in _ sometimes for as long as two years
_ managers they regard as candidates to run a company. The firms
introduce these entrepreneurs to potential investors, have them
evaluate business plans and draw up their own.
</P>
<P>
   Until two years ago, though, competition for such posts was so
fierce that they were unpaid. The opportunity alone, said John
Mumford, the managing director at Crosspoint, was something
entrepreneurs ``would just die to come do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They received no pay,'' he added, ``and, in fact, they would
have paid the VCs to sit there and find the next golden nugget.''
</P>
<P>
   But Silicon Valley's arithmetic has shifted the balance of
power. Awash in capital, many venture capital firms have more money
to invest than can readily be soaked up by new, sure-fire
companies. In one measure, Venture Economics, a research firm in
Manhattan, said venture capital firms raised $10 billion in 1997;
through just the first half of 1998, the firms raised $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And in the second quarter, venture capital investments in the
Valley alone were $1.24 billion, one-third of all venture funds
spent nationally, according to a survey of 721 companies by
PricewaterhouseCoopers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As capital has flooded in, the number of start-up deals has so
accelerated that venture capital firms have been left begging for
people to run the new companies.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, entrepreneurs in residence have become high-priced
chief executives in waiting. According to those interviewed, they
earn about $10,000 a month from the venture capital firms, a
princely rate that Mumford calls ``stupid'' but which is paid
partly to keep the entrepreneurs from going elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneurs face few rules or expectations. When they find
a business plan they like, they don't even have an obligation to
choose their sponsoring firm as an investment partner _ though
almost all do.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the goal is to breed a group of loyal entrepreneurs
who will return again and again to the venture capital firm to
build their next companies and thus undercut the executive
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent pool has been very, very heavily diluted because of
the amount of new companies being formed,'' said Steven Baloff,
general partner of Advance Technology Ventures in Palo Alto, Calif.
``Fifteen years ago, if your company failed, it was a black mark on
your resume. Now venture capital firms almost prefer it. You've got
your scars, and you've learned some hard lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Chris Risley announced last year that he was
resigning as chief executive of On Technology, a network management
software company in Cambridge, Mass., venture capitalists on both
coasts began calling him. He declined all offers, moved to Silicon
Valley and spent three months vacationing throughout California
with his wife, Susan, and son, Luke.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he became an entrepreneur in residence at Bessemer
Venture Partners in Menlo Park, where he spent six months reading
``several deal pitches a week.'' Two weeks ago, Risley joined
Insite Innovations, a software start-up in Menlo Park, as its chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   His transition, he said, might have been trickier without the
entrepreneur-in-residence program. He said the most common mistake
entrepreneurs make ``is to send in a business plan in the hopes
that someone will get excited and call them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience, that never turns into a deal,'' he said.
``You need a meeting to do a presentation, and for that, you need
someone to refer you to a venture capitalist.''
</P>
<P>
   That need gives the entrepreneurs in residence a huge advantage.
In turn, it also risks creating a fairly narrow circle of start-up
executives.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bowles, he could be set to become another of the Valley's
most highly prized commodities: a start-up addict. Mumford of
Crosspoint, who has backed both of Bowles' ventures, expects to see
him again. ``Mike will be back in our office starting a new company
a year from now,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
