<SLUG> BC-SALON-HYDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAILS OF HYDE AFFAIR CAME FROM TENNIS MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While powerful Republicans accuse the White
House of leaking the Henry Hyde infidelity story to an Internet
political magazine, a World War II veteran says the secret was
first revealed through an offhand remark at a tennis match six
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a damn lie that I have any connections to the White
House,'' said retired salesman Norm Sommer, reached at his
Aventura, Fla., home. ``I'm a 72-year-old World War II vet who
doesn't want to see a bloodless coup at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommer says he was the moving force behind a story by Salon
magazine that House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde had an
affair with a married woman in the 1960s. Salon broke the story
Wednesday, and the Illinois Republican admitted the affair. Hyde
was not a member of Congress at the time of the extramarital
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   David Weir, managing editor of Salon, insisted Thursday that
Sommer _ not the White House _ had tipped off Salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one, absolutely no one from the White House, or connected
to the White House, had anything to do with the story,'' Weir said.
</P>
<P>
   Angry Republicans have openly accused the Clinton administration
of planting the story in an attempt to discredit or intimidate
Hyde, who as head of the Judiciary Committee is responsible for
investigating impeachment allegations against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, asked the FBI Thursday
to determine whether the White House was the source of the story
about Hyde's affair. DeLay said he wanted to know whether
administration officials had tried to unlawfully intimidate a
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt who it is,'' DeLay said. ``I just don't have
the evidence to prove it, and that's why we want the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommer said he had heard of the affair six years ago while
changing sides during a doubles tennis match with Fred Snodgrass,
whose wife, Cherie, had the affair with Hyde. One of the players
mentioned that he used to make suits for Hyde, Sommer said, and
Snodgrass exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fred stopped dead in his tracks and started shouting, `Henry
Hyde? That son of a bitch ruined my family,''' Sommer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Snodgrasses were divorced. Cherie Snodgrass, now Cheries
Soskin, lives in San Antonio and told the San Antonio Express-News
Wednesday that she had an affair with Hyde 30 years ago but did not
know at the time he was married.
</P>
<P>
   Weir said staff members of the San Francisco-based magazine had
been able to put the story together solely because of help from
Sommer and members of Snodgrass' family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
