u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-RECONCILIATIO     09-18 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-RECONCILIATION-2TAKES-$A-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEBANON'S CIVIL WAR IS OVER, BUT INTERNAL SKIRMISHES THREATEN
STABILITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Editors: 2 TAKES, for release SUNDAY, SEPT. 20. &HT;     By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   FAWWARA, Lebanon _ Seven years after Lebanon's militias laid
down their arms to end a many-sided civil war, Rabih Elia is still
afraid to go home.
</P>
<P>
   A Maronite Catholic, Elia fled the Shouf Mountains in the 1980s
when fierce fighting broke out between religious factions. His
family's stone house, part of a string of communities built along a
ridge, has been deserted ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Elia, like other Maronites, feels safer living in Junieh, a
French-speaking Christian suburb north of Beirut. The Shouf, he
says in English with a slight French accent, is dominated by the
Druse, a breakaway sect of Islam whose militia battled the
Christians during the war, and by Syria's occupation army.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have perfect security here and we are afraid of
fighting between the Christians and the Druse,'' said Elia on a
recent visit to Fawwara under government auspices.
</P>
<P>
   His sentiments are shared by most Maronites in Lebanon, whose
animosities with the Druse date back more than a century. Their
fear highlights what may be the biggest problem faced by Lebanon's
weak central government as it tries to resurrect itself from the
rubble of a civil war: how to get the country's 17 different sects
to live together once again in peace.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting turned the landscape upside down when terrified
civilians sought safety with their own factions. Sometimes, entire
communities traded places. By the time the 17-year war ended in
1991, the warring sides had carved Lebanon into a mosaic of
sectarian districts and displaced as many as 900,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lebanon is as divided along religious lines as ever, with
Christians, Druse, Shiite Muslims and Sunni Muslims, all of whom
fought each other at one time or another, dominating different
regions. While rebuilding has begun on a limited scale,
reconciliation among the country's religious factions remains
elusive, and Lebanon's wartime agonies endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war really changed the communal landscape of Lebanon,''
said Farid el-Khazen, a political scientist at the American
University of Beirut. ``People feel more comfortable living in
their own communal areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Resettlement is not the only difficulty Lebanon faces. The
country's big plans for reconstruction, so far concentrated almost
exclusively along Beirut's seafront, have plunged the government
into billions of dollars in debt. In the south, a costly guerrilla
war grinds on against Israel, which occupies a 10-mile-wide zone
next to its border.
</P>
<P>
   But many Lebanese worry that the ancient religious hatreds
lurking beneath a veneer of peace enforced by Syrian troops pose
the most dangerous threat to the country's long-term stability.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a $700 million government effort to rebuild war-torn
villages, skeletons of concrete and brick dot the mountain sides
where Maronite and Druse villages once thrived, sometimes side by
side, before the war broke out in 1975. While some Druse have begun
to trickle back to their homes, most Maronites have not.
</P>
<P>
   Elia, now 24 and an accountant in Junieh, admits that it is
unlikely he will ever return to Fawwara to live. He did go back
recently to attend a government-sponsored camp aimed at healing the
sectarian hatreds unleashed by the war.
</P>
<P>
   But the camp did little to change the thinking of most
Maronites. Of the 150 Christian and Druse families who lived in
Fawwara before the war, only 30 have moved back. In Brih, a mixed
Christian-Druse village built on the next mountain ridge over, the
Christians have not returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really feel comfortable with the idea of living
here,'' said Elia. ``We are scared. The Syrians are with the Druse
now. The people are afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such fears, Lebanon's billionaire prime minister, Rafiq
Hariri, has pushed ahead with a $1.6 billion plan to reconstruct
Beirut's bombed-out Central District, where prolonged fighting
between Muslim and Christian militias turned luxury apartments into
crumbling slums.
</P>
<P>
   A wheeler-dealer who made his fortune in construction in Saudi
Arabia, Hariri has put up $125 million of his own money toward the
rebuilding, and so far the project to transform the gutted district
into chic residential areas and business parks is on track.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials hope the new buildings will help Beirut
recapture some of its prewar glory when the glittering Arab capital
was known as the Paris of the Middle East. ``Beirut will be one of
the most important cities in the region,'' predicted Hariri's
spokesman, Abdul Satar al-Laz.
</P>
<P>
   But outside the seafront district, little has changed. Thousands
of impoverished people remain crammed in bullet-riddled buildings.
Lebanese guerrillas are fighting the Israelis in southern Lebanon.
And, as Elia's visit to the Shouf Mountains indicates, it will take
much more than money to erase the scars left by the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a lot of effort,'' said Narkiss Naoum, a
political scientist at the American University of Beirut. ``The
differences between the Lebanese religious communities are still
very big.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other people of the Middle East, the Lebanese have often
defined themselves more by their religious affiliation than by
their national identity. Religion, in turn, has shaped the
country's politics, particularly after it gained independence from
France in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Lebanon's constitution reserved the
presidency for the Maronites, who essentially ran the country,
concentrating their political power and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   The constitution required the prime minister to be from the
Sunni Muslims, Islam's dominant sect, and the Sunnis shared in
power and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The Druse were not given a specific position in government, but
they nonetheless wielded great power. The constitution did require
that the speaker of Parliament come from the Shiite sect, Islam's
largest minority.
</P>
<P>
   The Shiite population, among the poorest, grew so rapidly in the
years after independence that they became the largest sect in the
country by the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Their ignored demands for increased power were one of the two
chief causes of the civil war in 1975. The other was the arrival of
Palestine Liberation Organization fighters in Beirut, following
their ouster from Jordan. The PLO and Muslim militias formed an
alliance and fought side-by-side in the early years of the war
against the Christian militias.
</P>
<P>
   The Taif Agreement, which helped bring the civil war to an end
in 1991, maintained those same sectarian divisions of government,
but stripped the presidency of most of its authority and gave the
Muslims more power.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Lebanon's postwar governments have tried to play
down the country's religious differences, in part by promoting the
army as a unifying force. On the streets of Beirut, posters of
fatigue-garbed soldiers cover walls with the slogan, ``We are all
the army.''
</P>
<P>
