</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3025 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-RECONCILIATIO     09-18 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-RECONCILIATION-$ADV20-2N-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Editors: FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20 
 
BC-LEBANON-RECONCILIATION-2ND TAKE-HEARST
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEBANON: the army.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The drive seems to be working. When six soldiers were killed
earlier this year by Israeli troops in southern Lebanon, the local
media quickly pointed out that each belonged to a different sect.
``The incident really brought people together,'' said Firass
al-Amine, a journalist at the prestigious Arabic daily, An-Nahar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, some Lebanese say the presence of Syria's occupation force
is the main reason that the country's fragile peace is holding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without (Syria), there is a potential for tensions to arise,''
said Georges Khoder, a Greek Orthodox bishop who writes a weekly
column on politics and ethics for An-Nahar.
</P>
<P>
   Radwan al-Sayyad, an Isamic studies professor at Lebanese
University in Beirut, agreed. ``If Syria left, we may not have
civil war but we will have political trouble. There definitely
would be troubles,'' he said. ``We still have sectarian tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   While others may disagree, one thing is certain: With 35,000
troops patrolling Lebanon and a feared intelligence network
operating in the shadows, Syria has become the real power broker
here.
</P>
<P>
   A postwar Treaty of Cooperation sealed Syria's grip, while
Syrian troops at checkpoints keep a jittery public under control.
Every year several Lebanese disappear at the hands of Syrian
operatives, according to human rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's hold makes it unlikely that Lebanon will strike a
separate deal with Israel soon. Israel wants to reach an agreement
on security arrangements before it withdraws its 1,500 troops, who
have occupied the so-called ``security zone'' since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But most analysts say Syrian President Hafez Assad would
undermine an Israeli-Lebanese peace agreement because it would
leave him with little to pressure Israel into returning the Golan
Heights, a plateau of snow-white mountains and grassy ranches that
Syria lost in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Syria pulls out of Lebanon, it is unlikely that the
Christians, particularly the Maronites, would regain the privileges
they enjoyed before the war.
</P>
<P>
   President Elias Hrawi, hand-picked by Assad, is a Maronite, but
critics say he does not represent the majority of the country's
700,000 Maronites who despise the Syrians. ``They want to keep
their hegemony, but they can't. They do not have the means.'' said
Naoum, the political analyst at the American University of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   To Muslim, Druse and even Greek Orthodox Lebanese, the
Maronites' loss of power was long overdue and a just reward for
having allied with Israel during the civil war. When Israel
withdrew from Beirut in 1983, Druse revenge led to battles like the
one that drove Elia and his family from the Shouf Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians have two choices,'' said Naoum, ``to be pro-Syrian
so that they can have protection for their community, or to
continue their struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second choice _ this means suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Since reconstruction began in 1994, some 10,000 mostly Syrian
workers have demolished 650 bombed-out buildings along Beirut's
seafront and picked up 5 million cubic meters of garbage to make
way for Prime Minister Hariri's Central District project. New
highways have been cut along the Mediterranean. Beirut's airport,
caught in the line of fire for much of the war, has been renovated
and reopened.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department has lifted a ban on Americans
traveling to Lebanon, and U.S. businessmen have started to return.
Later this fall, the country's first McDonald's is slated to open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lebanon is moving toward better days,'' said Jean Zoghzoghi,
the 30-year-old scion of a wealthy Lebanese family, who recently
acquired the McDonald's franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the air of optimism, Lebanon holds together like a
tattered patchwork quilt,
</P>
<P>
   In the Christian north, as many signs appear in French as in
Arabic. Young women wear miniskirts and high-heeled pumps.
Bikini-clad swimmers parade at exclusive beach clubs, and western
restaurants attract European tourists.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern suburbs of Beirut, where the bearded Shiites of
Hezbollah rule the streets, the miniskirts disappear, and the clean
sandstone streets of the north give way to crowded, crumbling ones
in the city. Women don veils and long, shapeless coats, while
yellow-and-black Hezbollah flags flutter from telephone poles.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours' drive to the east, in the Bekaa Valley, Lebanon's
primary agricultural area, the atmosphere changes again. There,
murals of Syrian President Assad and his late son, Basel, tower
over villages and farms, where Muslim workers pick tobacco under
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Another two hours' to the south, murals of the late Iranian
leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeni, greet the people. Women walk
outdoors garbed in black, head-to-toe chadors, which are also worn
by Iranian women.
</P>
<P>
   But at places like B018, a disco in Beirut where the children of
the rich, Muslim and Christians alike, gather to drink and dance on
black stone ``martyrs' graves'' all night, the country's sectarian
divisions are less evident.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even among those who pretend not to care, religion can
get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a Christian marries and looks for an apartment, he still
looks in east Beirut,'' said al-Amine, the An-Nahar journalist. ``A
Muslim, when he marries, looks for one in west Beirut.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Lebanese give no thought to crossing this barrier, said
al-Amine, the seeds of the civil war will finally have disappeared.
Then, the rebuilding and reconciliation can truly begin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many Lebanese believe that the country's sectarian divisions
may be hard, if not impossible, to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a generation for people to go back to their
previous ways,'' said el-Khazen, the political scientist. ``Maybe
it will never happen.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
