<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING: TAKING CHARGE IN INTERVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
(Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used in the last graf
instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper
systems.) 
(lb) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Next week I have a job interview. I really want the job, but
I know there will be many other candidates. Some people seem to
glide effortlessly through interviews and get offers every time
they apply. But for me, the process is a stressful ordeal, and
though I am often told I've made the short list, I rarely get an
offer. How can I make myself stand out from the crowd this time?
</P>
<P>
   A. Be yourself. Take deep breaths. Maintain eye contact. Dress
conservatively. Ask questions. Blah, blah, blah. All of these
much-mouthed chestnuts are true, and not one will distinguish you
in a field of candidates, all of whom have also been practicing
firm handshakes and interested gazes. To seal the deal, you need to
transform your interview from a generic Q&AMP;A into a demonstration of
your abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't just sit there like a bump on a log,'' says Nick A.
Corcodilos, a longtime headhunter and author of ``Ask the
Headhunter'' (Plume, $14.95). ``Tell the interviewer that you'd
like to talk about what you see as some of the challenges of the
business, how you would address those challenges if hired and how
you could make the company more successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Get specific, he says. ``Suggest to the interviewer, `I'd like
you to lay out a hypothetical problem I'd be facing and let me roll
up my sleeves and try to solve it,''' he urged. ``It takes real
brass to do this, but if you don't feel you can at least attempt
it, you have no business in that interview.''
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the wisdom of the Boy Scout credo: Be
prepared. Do not walk into an interview without first doing your
homework. ``It is really, really key that someone comes in knowing
a lot'' about the company, said Margaret Ingate, a vice president
in charge of recruiting and selection at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   To this end, recruiters and hiring consultants recommend pulling
out the stops: Search the library and the Internet for news
articles about the company; gather information about top
competitors and clients, as well as industry trends; and, of
course, see if the company has a World Wide Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this requires more effort than working up pithy answers to
the top 10 interview questions. But a little legwork could be the
difference between ``Welcome aboard'' and ``We'll call you.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into an interview armed with information and ready to
discuss how you would do the job shows that you're motivated and
resourceful. It also takes the pressure off the interviewer to keep
things moving.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the dirty little secret of interviewing, according to
Pierre Mornell, author of ``45 Effective Ways for Hiring Smart''
(Ten Speed Press, $24.95), is that most managers hate the process
more than candidates do. ``It can be so boring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By opening the door for your interviewer to discuss the business
_ and the ways you can contribute _ you turn the conversation
toward practical issues that she knows and cares about. You can
worry about that firm handshake later.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she will
respond to readers' questions about career and workplace issues.
Send them by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by regular mail to
Working, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
