</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC VIEW: THE HAVE-NOTS, AT LEAST, ARE USED TO THIS WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
(lb) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Income inequality is taking on a new dimension these days. Not
only have people's weekly earnings grown more disparate than in the
past; what they possess _ their accumulated wealth _ has also grown
more unequal lately. The haves and the have-nots, or more precisely
those who have prospered and those who have stood still, are
becoming easier to tell apart. Now the have-nots might get a break.
</P>
<P>
   The haves in this race _ the hares, so to speak _ are the 25
percent to 30 percent of all U.S. households that in the 1990s have
become much wealthier than many ever anticipated. They are the
families earning north of $75,000 a year, often far north. And
while they own homes, they have invested most of their savings in
the stock market, which boomed fabulously until midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Their net worth, adjusted for inflation, has grown by nearly 20
percent since 1989. The least wealthy among them are worth more
than $100,000, and the nest eggs go straight up from there.
</P>
<P>
   The have-nots _ the tortoises _ are the mass of families earning
less than $75,000 a year but more than $25,000, just enough to
afford a semblance of middle-class life in much of the country.
Their incomes, adjusted for inflation, have remained largely
unchanged, despite a brief rise in 1989 and another one now.
</P>
<P>
   These families' biggest investments are their homes, which rose
smartly in value in the 1970s and 1980s, often outpacing the stock
market, and family net worth grew in tandem. The 1990s have been an
entirely different experience for these families: For the first
time, their net worth shrank; it has made only a partial recovery
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is that the assets of these families, mainly
housing, were not the big winners of the 1990s,'' said Edward
Wolff, an economist at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   In the children's story of the tortoise and the hare, the steady
tortoise wins the footrace. But the odds of a tortoise victory in
the net-worth race are remote, although the tortoise has closed the
gap slightly.
</P>
<P>
   A victory would require that housing prices, employment and
earnings all hold up as the national economy slows or falls into a
recession brought on by the spreading Asian crisis. Stock prices
would have to fall simultaneously, far more than they already have.
By some estimates, the Dow Jones industrial average would have to
drop to 5,500 or below for the tortoise to edge out the hare.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, housing wealth has been more equally
distributed than stocks and most kinds of other financial wealth,''
said James Poterba, an economist at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. ``If house prices rise and stock prices fall, that
translates into more equalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new information on household wealth comes from
Wolff, who has analyzed data collected by the Federal Reserve Board
through 1995 and has calculated projections for 1996 and 1997. The
Economic Policy Institute has provided additional information.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists agree with Wolff's findings, although some
question his definition of wealth. Wolff, for example, includes
401(k) plans and similar retirement accounts, but he excludes
Social Security, most company-paid pension plans, and ``things'' _
the appliances, furniture and cars, for example, that families own.
Counting these would raise estimates of the wealth of the less
affluent.
</P>
<P>
   By Wolff's calculation, the median wealth in the United States
(the level at which half of all households have more, and half
less) rose to $54,600 in 1989, from $51,000 in 1983 and $36,200 in
1962. But it fell from the 1989 peak to $45,600 in 1995, and then
rebounded part way, to $49,900, last year. (All these figures are
adjusted to 1995 price levels.)
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the decline are clear enough: Home prices have
risen, particularly since 1996, but mortgage debt and home equity
loans have risen faster, diluting net worth.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending has risen faster than earnings, forcing
middle-level families to borrow or cut into liquid savings, which
they hold mostly in bank accounts. Many more Americans own stock
today than in the past, and this is billed as evidence that the
benefits of a rising stock market are spreading across the
population. But in fact, the vast majority of shareholders have
less than $10,000 in stock and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   So the tortoises have actually lost wealth during the economic
expansion of the 1990s, which is now perhaps ending. If wealth is a
buffer against job loss, the tortoises are less secure than they
were in 1989. And if political clout and campaign contributions are
linked, then the growing wealth of the upper 25 percent of hare
households has made them even more politically powerful .
</P>
<P>
   But there is a silver lining, or a gray one. ``If the market
continues to take a hit, that will demoralize wealthy Americans
more than the less affluent,'' said Daniel Yankelovich, chairman of
DYG, a polling firm. The latter ``are used to seeing their wealth
decrease, and won't feel as bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
