<HEADLINE>
FASHION SQUARE EXIBITS HALF-CENTURY OF STYLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Perky little hats, suits with long, narrow
skirts, gowns that look like slips and feature beadwork ...
</P>
<P>
   They're all part of our past. And our present.
</P>
<P>
   To see how they fit into our current fashion stance, take a
gander at the special exhibit from the Fashion Institute of Design
and Merchandising in Los Angeles that is currently on display at
Fashion Square mall in Sherman Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute to 50 years of fashion will be held on the lower
level of the mall, along with current designs from local retailers.
There's also a clothing drive at the mall to benefit the Discovery
Shops of the American Cancer Society in Toluca Lake. If you've got
something to donate, take it to the concierge desk in the center of
the mall and they'll give you some shopper's coupons as a thank
you.
</P>
<P>
   And while you're there, check out the Judith Leiber evening bag
exhibit at Bloomingdale's. They've got oldies on loan from
shoppers, as well as new designs on display through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Still on mall patrol? There's a free fashion show sponsored by
the Acrylic Council at 12:30 and 2:30 p.m. today at the Glendale
Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   And at all Kmart or Sears stores, you can find Martha Stewart's
new house paint collection. The decorating maven has 256 colors
available, each packaged like an ice cream container. And just so
you won't commit a fashion faux pas, the paint chips feature
complementary shades on the back of each chip.
</P>
<P>
   LOST AND FOUND: You're off the beaten track, can't find your way
and refuse to ask somebody for directions. Miz Hot Tips knows all
about men who would rather take the scenic route than ask for help,
so she was thrilled to hear about two new auto navigation gadgets
that are quicker to read than a map. For the budget-conscious
there's Road Whiz, a small high-tech gadget for $29.95 with limited
directions. And for those who are direct descendants of Christopher
Columbus, there's UltraFinder, a hand-held electronic device with
mega-sized memory chips to give you complete directions,
turn-by-turn. It'll even calculate the nearest restaurant, hotel
and gas stations for you. For that kind of service, expect to pay
the price: $99.95.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S GOOD MANNERS: You've finally been invited to the boss's
house for dinner _ and there's that little fork at the top of the
plate (it's for dessert), plus two forks on the left. If only you'd
listened to the latest installment of the Instant Genius cassettes
by etiquette expert Letita Baldrige. It's a 60-minute tape to keep
you from making all kinds of social faux pas in the areas of table
manners, introductions, thank you notes, and even body language.
The cassette is $12 and the CD is $13 at Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders
Books &AMP; Music stores.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-STRUCK PRODUCTS: Miz Hot Tips wonders how many celebs who
endorse products actually use them. For instance, she's seen Jaclyn
Smith shopping at Neiman Marcus a couple of times, and she knows
the store does not sell her line of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, for those who do follow the stars, Cybill Shepherd is
the newest Ultima II spokesperson and is now hawking Glowtion skin
brightening moisturizer on TV. You can find the moisturizer at J.C.
Penney and several upscale drugstores.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to appeal to those not yet worried about wrinkles or age
spots, Cover Girl cosmetics has hired pop icon Brandy as its
spokesgirl. And she's even singing the company's praises in
television commercials already airing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jane Seymour is busy advertising do-it-yourself hair
color. It apparently improved her appearance, as the Dallas
International Apparel Mart is going to honor her on Oct. 16 with
its annual Personal Style Award.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks in part to Monica Lewinsky and the prez, Zegna ties
are now a household name. On Oct. 11, the Italian menswear company
will be in the spotlight again, but this time as the presenting
sponsor of the eighth annual Environmental Media Association
Awards. They'll be held at Will Rogers State Historic Park in
Pacific Palisades.
</P>
<P>
   ROMANTIC ONE-LINERS: So, you're in love and can't think of a
single romantic thing to say to him or her? You'll get plenty of
help from the new book ``Happily Ever After'' by Helene and Jim
McMullan ($16.95; Angel City Press). The authors, who have been
married 28 years, quote the best of the world's love lines, from
philosopher Nietzsche's comment that ``the best friend is likely to
acquire the best wife,'' to actress Jill Clayburgh's mother's
suggestion: ``Marry a man with good teeth and high arches.'' Think
of it for wedding and anniversary gifts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
