<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BESTWORST-TV-LADN     09-18 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTWORST-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW, HWAT'S NOT FROM THE NETWORKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Six networks, 36 new shows and _ if you listen to
the networks _ each one is either the next ``Seinfeld'' (if it's a
comedy) or the next ``ER'' (if it's a drama).
</P>
<P>
   They are all liars.
</P>
<P>
   This was another in a long line of poor network television
development years. All of the inventive stuff is popping up on
cable as the networks regurgitate old themes and poorly executed
plots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollyweird'' was so bad it was bumped off the schedule before
it ever aired.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the best and worst that each of the six
broadcast networks has to offer in the upcoming season. And
remember, we warned you. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ABC BEST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   FANTASY ISLAND: Talk about old themes. This time-tested show _
which drives home the old adage ``Be careful what you wish for
...'' _ is a well-done update. It is darker with Malcolm McDowell
in the role of Mr. Roarke. &QL; 
ABC WORST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   THE SECRET LIVES OF MEN: A bunch of guys golf and whine
together. This is a unique comedy in that it has no laughs. &QL; 
CBS BEST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   TO HAVE AND TO HOLD: A battle of the sexes that is packed with
wit and bite. Executive producer Joanne Waters comes to the show
with no television baggage and brings a freshness to an age-old
struggle. The romantic comedy has a likable cast and a distinctive
feel. &QL; 
CBS WORST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   MAGGIE WINTERS: Remember the movie ``Hope Floats''? You're
better off renting it. This is the same premise. The girl most
likely to succeed doesn't and comes back home. Series star Faith
Ford, though, is no Sandra Bullock. Maybe this sitcom won't be
around as long as the two-hour movie. &QL; 
FOX BEST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   THAT '70s SHOW: A trippy look back at the era of disco and
southern rock; long hair and shag carpets; American cars and
American cheese. &QL; 
FOX WORST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   HOLDING THE BABY: The baby would be better off being dropped.
This smarmy sitcom has no basis in reality, and the opening episode
features a debate on what euphemism should be used for fecal
matter. They should try calling it ``Holding the Baby.'' &QL; 
NBC BEST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WILL &AMP; GRACE: This comedy is about a gay man and his best woman
friend. The cast is likable, but the show is not great. NBC has
just unleashed a bunch of comfort food on its prime-time schedule
and this is the tastiest of the weak bunch. &QL; 
NBC WORST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WIND ON WATER: Take Bo Derek, add a bunch of hard-body extreme
athletes, put them on a cattle farm in Hawaii and what do you have?
A very bad show. &QL; 
UPN BEST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   SEVEN DAYS: A sci-fi thriller in which a genius with a gambling
problem is set free from a mental hospital to use a time machine to
prevent future crimes. The catch is the machine is only good for
seven days. &QL; 
UPN WORST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   THE SECRET DIARY OF DESMOND PFEIFFER: Abraham Lincoln's head
servant is an African-American man from Britain. He has his own
servant. The jokes are crude and the show is so over-the-top, it's
on its way down. &QL; 
THE WB BEST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   FELICITY: It has been called ``Ally McBeal Goes to College.''
This show may even make a couple of 12- to 20-year-old females
forget about Dawson and his creek. Kerri Russell is an appealing
star who plays a woman who heads off to college, learning from her
wrong decisions along the way. &QL; 
THE WB WORST &QC;
</P>
<P>
   THE ARMY SHOW: Poor Phil Silvers must be rolling in his grave.
This lightweight version of his Sgt. Bilko-centered show has, among
others, Anthony Higgins, the heavyweight from ``Ellen.'' A court
marshal is in order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
