<SLUG> BC-CATEGORIES-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FEW IDEAS, SO MANY NEW SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Television has been copying itself since its
early days, so this season's offerings of familiar scenarios will
come as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow in development meetings all around town, people seem to
be pitching the same stuff _ and networks are still buying it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some coincidences that are categorically
undeniable:
</P>
<P>
   Blond barmaids, who want to go to college despite protests from
men in their lives, in shows with one-name titles: NBC's ``Jesse''
starring Christina Applegate and Fox's ``Costello,'' starring Sue
Costello.
</P>
<P>
   Fat city: Since the days of Oliver Hardy, fat men have made
people laugh. This television schedule has more overweight guys
than an all-you-can-eat buffet. David Anthony Higgins on the WB's
``The Army Show,'' Kevin James on CBS' ``The King of Queens,''
Sammo Hung on CBS' ``Martial Law,'' Nathan Lane on NBC's ``Encore!
Encore!'' John DiResta on UPN's ``DiResta'' and Chi McBride on
UPN's ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Networks want their MTV (talent): The latest television genre _
shows featuring former MTV personalities. Jacinda Barrett is in
NBC's ``Wind on Water''; her boyfriend Chris Hardwick, who was the
sidekick to Jenny McCarthy and Carmen Electra on ``Singled Out,''
is in UPN's ``Guys Like Us''; and former host and VJ John Sencio is
in the WB's ``The Army Show.'' Another common thread: All of these
shows stink.
</P>
<P>
   Shows with lawyers, cops and private eyes: Television has a love
affair with anyone in any kind of legal profession. Want proof?
Read on. NBC: ``Will &AMP; Grace'' and ``Trinity.'' CBS: ``Buddy
Faro,'' ``To Have and to Hold'' and ``Martial Law.'' ABC:
``Vengeance Unlimited.'' Fox: ``Brimstone.'' UPN: ``DiResta'' and
``Seven Days.'' And those are just the !ital!new shows featuring
law enforcers.
</P>
<P>
   The luck of the Irish: Networks must be looking for that Irish
demographic because there seem to be more Irish families on
television than in Dublin: NBC: ``Wind on Water'' and ``Trinity.''
CBS: ``To Have and to Hold.'' Fox: ``Costello.'' The WB: ``Hyperion
Bay.'' UPN: ``Legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Women _ you can't live without 'em, except on TV: Single men and
the kids they bring up on the next ... ``Brother's Keeper'' and
``Two of a Kind'' on ABC, ``Holding the Baby'' on Fox and ``Guys
Like Us'' on UPN. Oh, and representing the single moms of the
world: NBC's ``Jesse.''
</P>
<P>
   Movin' on up: Two new shows try to update the ``Jeffersons''
theme of African-Americans moving to a dee-luxe white community:
``The Hughleys'' (ABC) and ``Living in Captivity'' (Fox).
</P>
<P>
   Hunting for ratings: ``Good Will Hunting'' did well at the box
office. It was set in South Boston. Hey, what a great place for a
show: ``To Have and to Hold'' (ABC) and ``Costello'' (Fox).
</P>
<P>
   Start spreading the news: New York, New York. They named it
twice because there are so many shows based there: CBS has ``The
King of Queens.'' NBC has ``Conrad Bloom,'' ``Will &AMP; Grace,''
Trinity'' and ``Jesse'' (OK, it's Buffalo, barely N.Y.). ABC has
``Sports Night'' and ``The Secret Lives of Men.'' The WB has
``Felicity.'' UPN has ``DiResta.''
</P>
<P>
   Aloha: Two shows _ ``Wind on Water'' (NBC) and ``Fantasy
Island'' (ABC) will be filmed in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Go west, young show: If it's not New York, it's probably going
to be California. In the Golden State, you'll find ABC's ``The
Hughleys'' and ``Brother's Keeper.'' On CBS, ``Buddy Faro,''
``Martial Law,'' ``The Brian Benben Show'' and ``L.A. Doctors.'' On
NBC, ``Encore! Encore!'' On Fox, ``Brimstone'' and ``Living in
Captivity.'' And The WB sets both ``Charmed'' and ``Hyperion Bay''
in California.
</P>
<P>
   The right to remain silent: Two television characters have
unusual name pronunciations. There is Darryl Hughley (pronounced
YOO-glee, where both H's are silent) and Desmond Pfeiffer
(pronounced PFIFE-fer, where the P is not silent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
