<HEADLINE>
WHO'S IN, OUT AND BACK AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Hunks begone.
</P>
<P>
   The two most-ogled male television stars will be leaving your
living room this season.
</P>
<P>
   George Clooney (Dr. Doug Ross) will leave ``ER'' at the end of
the season, and Jimmy Smits (detective Bobby Simone) has six
episodes left on ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Big stars leave television shows _ that's nothing new. This is
the second major change on ``NYPD Blue'' since its 1993 premiere.
And ``Law &AMP; Order'' has been using the interchangeable star system
for years and is no worse for the tumult.
</P>
<P>
   But this year there seems to be a major talent drain,
particularly in dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Braugher (Frank Pembleton) is leaving ``Homicide,'' Jason
Priestley (Brandon Walsh) will leave ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' (Luke
Perry's Dylan McKay will be back to the rescue), and Carey Lowell
(prosecutor Jamie Ross) will leave ``Law &AMP; Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at major cast changes you can expect to see this
season:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal'' In: Portia de Rossi (Nelle Porter, a rainmaker
and another rival for Ally).
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' Out: Jason Priestley (Brandon Walsh).
Back: Luke Perry (Dylan McKay). In: Laura Leighton (wanna-be
actress Sophie Burns), Vanessa Marcil (Gina, an ice-skater), Daniel
Cosgrove (lawyer Matt Durning).
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy Meets World'' In: Maitland Ward (Rachel, a co-ed who
becomes Eric and Jack's new roommate).
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago Hope'' In: Eric Stoltz (Dr. Robert Yeats, an offbeat
surgeon who's into Eastern philosophy).
</P>
<P>
   ``Dawson's Creek'' In: Meredith Monroe and Kerr Smith (a brother
and sister who come to town).
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' In: Kellie Martin (third-year medical student Lucy
Knight). Out (at season's end): George Clooney (Dr. Doug Ross).
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Improvement'' Out: Jonathan Taylor Thomas (Randy Taylor)
leaves &UR;  &LR; after two episodes but will be back in a holiday show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicide'' In: Giancarlo Esposito (FBI agent Mike Giardello,
the estranged son of Al Giardello), Michael Michele (detective Rene
Sheppard, a onetime beauty queen). Out: Andre Braugher (detective
Frank Pembleton).
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order In: Angie Harmon (assistant district attorney
Abbie Carmichael). Out: Carey Lowell (prosecutor Jamie Ross).
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Boat: The Next Wave'' In: Heidi Mark (cruise director
Nicole Jordan).
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' In: Christopher Barnes (waiter Leonard
Rickets).
</P>
<P>
   ``Melrose Place'' In: John Hayme Newton (Ryan McBride, Kyle's
younger brother), Steve Wilder (fashion designer Alex Bastian).
Back: Josie Bissett (Jane Mancini).
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium'' In: Klea Scott (the new female lead as an FBI
agent).
</P>
<P>
   ``NewsRadio'' In: Jon Lovitz as Max Lewis to replace his friend,
late newsman Bill McNeal (the late Phil Hartman).
</P>
<P>
   ``NYPD Blue'' In: Rick Schroder (Danny Sorenson, a young
detective from the narcotics division). Out: Jimmy Smits (detective
Bobby Simone).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice'' In: Charles Durning (Bobby's father), Marla
Sokaloff (secretary Lucy Hatcher).
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place'' In: Suzanne Cryer
(Ashley, a medical student to challenge Berg in the classroom).
</P>
<P>
   ``Working'' In: Debi Mazar (Liz, a street-smart and tough
executive), Rebecca McFarland (Val, an Ivy Leaguer who becomes the
new secretary). Out: Sarah Knowlton (uptight secretary Hal), Dana
Gould (office prankster Jimmy), Kate Hodge (single mother Chris).
</P>
