<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HISTORY, NOT SCANDAL, IS THE DRAW FOR WHITE HOUSE VISITORS
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For White House tourists, the richly decorated
walls of the Red Room, the glimmering candelabras in the State
Dining Room and the ornate chairs of the Blue Room seem far more
fascinating than the sex scandal haunting the residence.
</P>
<P>
   As they move through the Executive Mansion on self-guided tours,
few visitors ask questions about where President Clinton's affair
with Monica Lewinsky was conducted, staff members say. Instead,
they are curious about what function each room serves, where the
president sits when he visits each room and who his guests are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about this building is, there is a whole lot of
history related to it,'' said Roger Gerwe of Cincinnati, who took
the tour Friday. ``The players come and go, but the history and
integrity of the office, those things remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerwe said he believed that while the public needs to know the
facts about Clinton's conduct in office, media attention to the
issue has been excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Thompson of St. Croix in the Virgin Islands said what
impressed her most about the self-guided tour was being able to
view historic furniture and paintings, not the possibility of
sneaking a peek into the president's private life.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said she is a Clinton supporter, but lost respect for
him when the president admitted wrongdoing. ``I think they are
going this far to reprimand him and show him the error of his
ways,'' she said. ``It will show him that he can't take the
presidency and the American people for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
