<P>
   PAXNET _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ According to Bill Scott,
president of programming for PAX TV, better than expected ratings
won't mean the network will be going on the air more quickly with
more original programming. The network has 17 or 18 projects in the
works now _ some are specials like the ones we have mentioned
before _ but probably won't be introducing new ones in January. He
said, however, the network won't wait until fall premieres to
introduce new shows _ when they have them ready, they will go on
the air. At the same time, they want people to get used to the type
of programming they have now and don't want to change things too
quickly. (Plunkett, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE _ Review of the Mitsubishi Galant (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CONDOS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ In the past, luxury condominium
developers needed little more than a dream and a few million
dollars to build their posh palaces. But these days, luxury condo
developers, investors and lenders _ still smarting from their
experiences during the last real estate downturn _ are waiting for
sales before they turn their first spades of dirt. (Breyer, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOREX-PROBLEMS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ His company is closed. Lawsuits
are piling up. State and federal investigators are looking into
claims of wrongdoing. But Russell Erxleben, former University of
Texas football great turned foreign-currency trader, wants the
world to know he isn't running away. (Tyson/Maher, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
