<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS CLINTON LOSING SOME SUPPORT IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ President Clinton's image has eroded among
Californians, according to a new poll, but he retains support in
the nation's most populous state and there appears to be no
groundswell of pressure for him to leave office.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 812 people likely to vote in the Nov. 3 election
showed that 52 percent thought Clinton was doing a ``good'' or
``excellent'' job as president, down from 60 percent in February.
The poll was of conducted for the San Francisco Examiner by
Mason-Dixon Political/Media Research of Columbia, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's job-performance rating has hovered around 52 percent
in most Mason-Dixon polls since 1993, then peaked in February.
``These findings have been pretty consistent everywhere,'' pollster
Del Ali said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton said he still has the moral authority to
lead the country. But among Californians, a few red flags were
revealed in the poll:
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stands on shaky ground if there is proof he obstructed
justice in trying to conceal his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
Forty-eight percent said he should be removed from office if that
proves to be true, compared to 46 percent who said he should stay.
</P>
<P>
   And 56 percent of those surveyed said they thought Clinton
should not resign, but only 43 percent said they trusted him. Women
trust the president more than men, the poll found, and slightly
fewer women said they thought the president should resign.
</P>
<P>
   If the evidence shows that Clinton committed perjury in his
deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, then he
should be removed from office, 44 percent of those surveyed said.
Women also gave Clinton more support than men when asked this
question, according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed that the sordid details of Clinton's
extramarital fling may influence the U.S. Senate race in
California. State Treasurer Matt Fong, the Republican candidate, is
trying to unseat incumbent Barbara Boxer, the Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how, if at all, their opinion of Clinton would
influence their vote in the U.S. Senate race, 18 percent said they
would vote for state Fong over Boxer, who was first elected to the
Senate in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Although a convincing 70 percent said the Clinton scandal would
have no bearing on how they will vote, Ali said even a small margin
could influence the tight race. Recent polls have shown Boxer and
Fong in a virtual dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked this question in every state that has a Senate race
this year, and unless the candidates are in a close race, the
Clinton scandal doesn't amount to a hill of beans,'' said Ali,
senior vice president of Mason-Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now in California, this could be enough to swing it to Fong.
The other factor is turnout. It's essential for Boxer to energize
her base of Democratic voters. ... It doesn't help that she's
running against a moderate Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Results from Tuesday's primaries in Minnesota, New York,
Massachusetts, Maryland and Washington show that Democratic turnout
declined in every state but Massachusetts. But Republican turnout
declined as well.
</P>
<P>
   The survey has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.5 percentage
points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
