<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Sept. 20, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AGENT (Undated) _ Bill Fischer, travel agent for brats
and other rich folks who have to get to the be-seen hot spots,
chartering planes, getting his clients into parties in St. Barts,
Aspen, Final Four. By Monique P. Yazigi. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-HOLIDAYS (Undated) _ For as long as I can remember, I
have been gripped by a fashion fever before the High Holy Days that
begins in late August and peaks in mid-September. This feeling of
urgency, the need to buy something new and special for the Jewish
New Year, I believe, is a lasting effect of growing up in Great
Neck, N.Y. By Elizabeth Hayt. (Moved).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LINNEY-FILM-PROFILE (Undated) _ In ``The Truman Show,'' Laura
Linney plays Jim Carrey's wife, an actress pretending to be a real
person. In life, Ms. Linney is an actress struggling to project a
movie star, now that ``The Truman Show'' has brought her the widest
attention yet during a career built on theater and television. By
Peter McQuaid. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER-UNIFORMS (Undated) _ A century ago, butlers often wore
mismatched trousers with their evening tail coats, to make sure no
one ever mistook them for dinner guests. Today, having a staff
that's decked out as stylishly as the guests is precisely the point
for many hotels and restaurants, which are hiring designers like
Isaac Mizrahi and Dolce &AMP; Gabbana to create uniforms. By Bill
Powers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Among the insects that plague a
garden, the aphid has no equal. Old-timers call them plant lice, an
appropriate sobriquet. A gardener's life would be easier, nay,
blissful, if it weren't for the lousy aphids. By Cass Peterson.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
