<HEADER>
A3165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESIGNER-UNIFORMS-ART     09-18 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGNER-UNIFORMS-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESSING THE HELP IN DESIGNER WEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 20) 
(ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By BILL POWERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A century ago, butlers often wore mismatched trousers
with their evening tail coats, to make sure no one ever mistook
them for dinner guests. Today, having a staff that's decked out as
stylishly as the guests is precisely the point for many hotels and
restaurants, which are hiring designers like Isaac Mizrahi and
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana to create uniforms. If the staff looks even sweller
than the patrons, so much the better in the age of hipper than
thou.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uniforms are pretty horrible, as a rule, and I don't like the
idea of them,'' maintains Todd Oldham, who outfitted the staff at
the renovated Tiffany Hotel, an Art Deco landmark in Miami Beach,
which will reopen next month. ``We wanted to make the staff feel
special in their uniforms.'' This did not mean black tie or
epaulettes. For bartenders, bellhops, pool attendants and maids,
Oldham created a colorful line of shirts and dresses in crush-dyed
cotton, the same fabrics as the sarongs and bathrobes provided for
Tiffany guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about who had the worst job, and who gets the least
credit, and it has to be the maid,'' Oldham said. ``So we really
turned her out. We did an easy shirtwaist dress in a blue and white
crush-dyed cotton with a smart little barbecue apron. I wanted her
to feel really tidy.'`
</P>
<P>
   At upscale hotels like the Allegro in Chicago (where Calvin
Klein designs are worn) and the Metropolitan in London (Donna Karan
garb), fashionable uniforms make the guests feel they're in good
hands. A concierge in a cashmere twin set is reassuring, like a
doctor in surgery scrubs. It lets guests know the wearer can get
the job done _ in the concierge's case, that she's hip enough to
get you into the right club.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to a uniform-supply house won't make it anymore, So
hoteliers and restaurateurs are turning to the same designers their
guests would wear. At Clementine that means Agnes B. and Daryl K;
at Chez Es Saada, Badgley Mischka; at Union Pacific, Donna Karan,
and at Gramercy Tavern, Armani. At the Mercer Hotel in SoHo, Andre
Balazs has asked Mizrahi to be the uniform ``conceptualizer and
curator,'' said Roman Alonso, Mizrahi's spokesman. ``Andre
expressed an interest in having his employees look as if they
belonged in the neighborhood.'' Balazs said that he wanted the
young staff to have ``the ability to go straight from the hotel to
a party without changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mizrahi attired the doormen in understated four-button,
charcoal-gray suits and the receptionists in shift dresses or
flat-front pants with baby-blue twin sets. The bellboys, houseboys
and engineers wear Nehru jackets, color-coded by job, in navy,
burgundy and dark green.
</P>
<P>
   In a hotel where even the guy carrying the suitcases must look
as chic as the guests, designer uniforms do not come cheap.
Although Mizrahi sells his clothes to the Mercer at wholesale, the
pieces are still expensive. (One of Mizrahi's pencil skirts, worn
by the receptionist, can retail for $180 to $900.)
</P>
<P>
   This summer, when the hotel expanded operations and opened the
Mercer Kitchen, Balazs planned to outfit the whole staff in
Mizrahi. But budget concerns made that impossible. So, said Balazs,
``We wound up using a lot of J. Crew and Banana Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason hoteliers are willing to pay a premium, even for
wholesale designer uniforms, and designers are willing to discount
their wares, is that they trade off each other's image for
publicity. Such arrangements can be traced back as far as 1948,
when Scandinavian Airlines System adopted Christian Dior's New Look
to demilitarize the appearance of steward-esses, who were
originally required to be registered nurses.
</P>
<P>
   Dior transformed their image. He put them in pleated skirts and
snug-fitting jackets, turning them into sexy air hostesses from
whom you'd want to order a scotch on the rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from Dior, Pucci, Valentino and even Calvin Klein
later supplied their versions of flight-attendant garb for Braniff
Airways, Trans World Airways and SAS, respectively. Of course, air
travel possessed more prestige back in the days before Tower Air.
</P>
<P>
   Such collaborations aren't always easy, as Mark Thomas Amadei
discovered this summer, when he was preparing to open Cafeteria, an
all-night restaurant in Chelsea. Amadei asked one of his partners,
Victor Alfaro, the designer behind the Iceberg label, to create
uniforms for the staff. Alfaro suggested that the waiters wear jump
suits with wide-flair legs _ perhaps inspired by the restaurant's
garage-style doors. But after the preliminary sketches, it was
decided, Amadei said, that Alfaro's uniforms were ``a little over
the top'' and impractical for a waiters working up a sweat over a
long shift.
</P>
<P>
   The design team of Dolce &AMP; Gabbana was brought in to dress the
staff in something easier to run around in. For the waitresses, the
designers pulled items from their fall collection _ a black
sleeveless crochet top, paired with a slim pencil skirt. For the
men, they chose white short-sleeve shirts and slim black pants made
in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outfits have a very '50s feel about them, but at the same
time are very modern, keeping with the feeling of both Cafeteria
and D&AMP;G.'' Domenico Dolce said In addition, everyone wears a brown
apron with a none-too-suble Dolce &AMP; Gabbana logo.
</P>
<P>
   Now if only Helly Hansen would agree to supply dishwashers with
waterproof anoraks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
