A3170 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-CONFLICT-CONSTRUC     09-18 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CONFLICT-CONSTRUCTION-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTION INDUSTRY SAYS FOUNDATION IS SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do construction executives know something the rest of us don't?
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for thinking that the present boom in construction has
run its course are plentiful:
</P>
<P>
   _ So many professionals left the building trades during the last
recession _ and so few young people are opting for careers in
building now _ that builders find it hard to hire construction
engineers, let alone welders or bricklayers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cement and other building materials are in short supply, and
prices are rising.
</P>
<P>
   _ Economic turmoil in Asia and Russia is stifling overseas
demand, as project after project is halted or postponed, while the
resulting financial-market gyrations provoke caution among American
corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, across the country, construction executives are
clicking their heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, some people are in trouble overseas, and some are facing
shortages, but by and large, this industry is in really good
shape,'' said Gary Tulacz, a senior editor at Engineering News
Record, a construction trades journal.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Tulacz may be right, but analysts are sounding
alarm bells about the not-too-distant future. ``Everyone is busy,
but materials and people are really being stretched thin,'' warned
Louis Taylor, senior real estate analyst at Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Murray, vice president of economic affairs for the F.W.
Dodge unit of the McGraw-Hill Construction Information Group,
predicted that total building activity would rise just 3 percent in
1998, compared with a 7 percent leap in 1997. ``The industry is at
cruising speed, but the strongest growth years are behind it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's woes, meanwhile, may prove to be a double whammy for the
American construction industry. The Fluor Daniel Inc. unit of Fluor
Corp., whose revenue from telecommunications work has stalled at
about $160 million a year because so many overseas projects are on
hold, worries that hungry Asian contractors will start competing in
the United States. ``They're already bidding for work in Latin
America,'' said Ron Oakley, president of Fluor Daniel's
Infrastructure Operating Co.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for cement, insulation and materials are inching up even
though manufacturers have been stepping up production. ``There's a
significant gap between supply and demand, and that's going to
continue for the foreseeable future,'' said Edward Pile, a
spokesman for Lafarge Corp., a large cement company.
</P>
<P>
   The labor shortage is also likely to persist, warned Louis
Coletti, chairman of the Building Trades Employers Association in
New York. ``The lack of a skilled work force has leaped out as the
single biggest issue facing the construction industry in this
country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With so many alarm bells clanging so loudly, why are
construction executives feeling so good?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, many say their exposure to trouble overseas was
much smaller than a casual observer might suppose. Many projects
scuttled by economic meltdowns in Asia and Russia were being
handled by local contractors, while multinational companies like
Merck, Exxon and Hoechst continue to hire American companies to
design and build oil refineries, power stations and pharmaceutical
plants _ and pay for them in dollars. ``Our bookings are at an
all-time high,'' said Richard Swift, chairman of Foster Wheeler
Corp., which gets two-thirds of its revenue overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Another bright spot is an anticipated torrent of government
spending. Congress has authorized $217 billion for highway
construction in coming years, and localities are taking advantage
of low interest rates to float bonds that will pay for projects
like new schools. ``The government is going to be a huge source of
growth for us,'' said Bradley Jacobs, chairman of United Rentals,
which rents building equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a while before that money is disbursed, giving
builders time to prepare. ``Companies are already pulling kids out
of Burger Kings and training them in construction, just to be ready
for when the highway money hits,'' said Tobias Levkovich, an
analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors are mitigating the labor and materials shortages.
Industry consolidation and modern communications have made it
easier to shift people, equipment and even work where they are
needed. United Rental has gobbled up local rental companies, adding
to its fleets of movable cranes, compactors and other equipment.
Fluor Daniel uses new engineering centers in New Delhi and Manila
for work on many American projects. ``If you don't have people
where the work is, you move the work to where the people are,''
said Ron Peterson, a Fluor Daniel group president.
</P>
<P>
   Some makers of building materials, like Owens-Corning, are
supplying U.S. projects from plants in China and Europe, while
others, like Lafarge and Certainteed, are building or opening new
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the industry was roaring like this was in the late
1980s, just before a recession brought new construction to a crawl.
No one expects another such crash, but cautious notes are being
sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market, the overseas uncertainty, all of it has
caused a tremendous caution to well up in executives who were
positively ebullient a few months ago,'' said Thomas Falus,
president of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield New York, a real estate firm owned
by Mitsubishi Estate Co. ``They are not going to commit to a lot
more space right now. And that has got to mean a real damper on
construction.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
