<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3174 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-COLUMN-$     09-18 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRELUDES: BREATHE DEEPLY, AND START SAVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
 (bl)  
 Abby Ellin is a New York writer. Her column on starting out in the
world of money will be filed for publication on the third Sunday of
each month. E-mail: preludes(AT)nytimes.com.  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In ``Down and Out in Paris and London,'' George
Orwell wrote that ``poverty annihilates the future.'' In a way, he
was right. There is something liberating in being down to your last
centimes and surviving, especially if you're George Orwell.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't Paris in the 1920s. This is New York on the cusp
of the 21st century, with $9 movie tickets, $75 theater tickets,
$300 for dinner for two at a four-star restaurant and $2,000
monthly rent for a one-bedroom apartment. At times, it's enough to
make you long for a small town _ say, Ithaca, N.Y., where the
winters can be dreadful but where Stephanie Winston, 32 and
formerly of Manhattan, pays only $450 a month for a one-bedroom
apartment with free off-street parking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my car, I've got my job, and I don't stress trying to
make ends meet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the city, most people I know _ actors, writers, musicians,
doctors, lawyers, chefs, professors, even an M.B.A. candidate _ DO
stress. And that anxiety has forced them to get serious about their
fiscal prospects.
</P>
<P>
   They now engage in all sorts of new behavior: scanning stock
reports, lamenting the potential demise of Social Security,
investing in condos. Partly, this stems from the fact that many are
single women who have had to learn to take care of themselves. But
some have reached genuine turning points, minor existential crises
that propelled them into financial maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 31, I was robbed at gunpoint, and it made me start
thinking about my future,'' said Jill Diamond, now 33. ``I realized
I wanted security and stability, that I wanted to buy an apartment
in New York, have a house in the country, afford clothing, travel
and dining to my liking, and give my kids a similar upbringing as I
had _ safe, and full of opportunities that money lends itself
to.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So she educated herself, sitting down with accountants, lawyers
and family members and questioning them about her finances.
</P>
<P>
   She remembered the process: ``I asked my family about the
investments they already had in my name: What were they? How much
was invested? What kind of access did I have to them? I never knew
or really cared about any of that before.''
</P>
<P>
   She read books on money and self-esteem. And she abandoned her
early career aspirations, of becoming a singer, instead opening a
language school in Manhattan, which gave her a steady income and a
greater sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, she said, she found herself ``dishing out thousands
of dollars to musicians and making zilch on every gig, and teaching
at a university as an adjunct with no prospects of a full-time job
with benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't conducive to saving money,'' she noted. Almost two
years later, the school is successful and her bank account solid.
</P>
<P>
   Others took inventory after economic realities smacked them in
the face.
</P>
<P>
   Like many new college graduates, Amy Trapp moved into an
apartment in New York long before she could support herself. ``I
ended up charging way too much and got myself in deep credit-card
debt,'' recalled Ms. Trapp, now 38, of those days in the early
1980s. ``One day when I realized that I couldn't take a cash
advance on my Lord &AMP; Taylor card _ the only one that wasn't charged
to the max _ I decided to consolidate my debt and begin paying off
the balance each month. It took 18 months, but it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked so well that after she paid off her debts, she kept
making the same monthly payment to herself, putting the money into
a savings account. Once she acquired a critical mass of cash, she
moved up to a higher-interest, money-market account.
</P>
<P>
   And after she received her first raise in her job as a credit
analyst, she began setting aside half the after-tax amount. With
enough money for the minimum investment, she tried a mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I spent the money I'd saved and times
when my expenses got ahead of me, but I'd just go back and start
again,'' she said. ``Saving can be done in baby steps, and if it's
done in smaller and more frequent increments it hurts less.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it does _ much less than watching your ATM spit out a
notice of insufficient funds. And this is true even if you believe,
as Orwell did, that there is ``a great consolation in poverty,''
which he later described as ``a feeling of relief, almost of
pleasure, at knowing yourself at last genuinely down and out.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``You have talked so often of going to the dogs _ and
well, here are the dogs, and you have reached them, and you can
stand it. It takes off a lot of anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   Orwell may have been on to something, and all the poets, actors
and artists of the world can take solace in it. But the rest of us
find solace in knowing ourselves genuinely secure. THAT takes off
the anxiety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAID-PROFILE-ART-825(     09-18 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAID-PROFILE-ART-825(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PALESTINIAN LITERARY CRITIC CONFRONTS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JANNY SCOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Several years ago, Edward W. Said began writing a
memoir mostly about his childhood in Palestine in the years before
Israeli independence in 1948, before his family fled to Egypt,
before he landed at Columbia University, before he became one of
the most influential literary and cultural critics in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, something struck Said about his timing: The
writing of the memoir, which he is currently finishing, had
coincided exactly with his treatment for leukemia, which was
diagnosed after a routine cholesterol test in 1991 and which is
likely one day to end his life.
</P>
<P>
   The start of chemotherapy in 1994 had been a point of no return,
an acknowledgment that Said was entering what he calls a final
phase. The start of the memoir was the opposite, a going back, an
effort to rescue from oblivion a time and places that had all but
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   So they fell into a rhythm, the writing and the illness, each in
counterpoint to the other. For the first six months of last year,
Said was too sick to teach. He had various viruses, and then
pneumonia. The leukemia worsened. Unable to work, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the inverse of my illness,'' he said in an interview
recently. ``It's like a mirror, but from which all the actual
images have been effaced. There is nothing in the book about it.
And I found that very salutary, having something like that to go
back to.''
</P>
<P>
   Said, 62, is a man of many dimensions. He is one of the most
important literary critics alive, a professor of English and
comparative literature at Columbia, the author of 15 books, a music
critic, a scholar of opera, a pianist, a father of two grown
children and arguably the most eloquent spokesman for the
Palestinian cause in the West.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a major force in recreating the field of literary
studies over the past two decades. His work helped give form to
entire new scholarly areas, like postcolonial theory. His 1978
book, ``Orientalism,'' revolutionized the study of the Middle East
and has been argued over bitterly for years.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Said has done as much as anyone to raise the
profile of the Palestinian cause in American intellectual life. He
writes frequently on the subject. He was a member of the
Palestinian National Council until 1991 and recently made a film
about the Palestinians for the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   He is a relentless critic of Israeli policy on the Palestinians;
of U.S. foreign policy in the Middle East, and, in the last few
years, of Yasser Arafat and of the Oslo accords, calling the peace
agreement between Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization
``an instrument of Palestinian surrender.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of admirers, Said is brilliant, charismatic,
passionate, funny, erudite, engaged. For some, he is also a
personal model, managing to combine a rigorous intellectual life
and impassioned political engagement.
</P>
<P>
   To those who dislike him, he is polemical, extremist,
conspiratorial, irresponsible, anti-American. They say he
attributes political motives to everyone but himself. Detractors
have called him a Nazi, a ``professor of terror,'' Arafat's
apologist. In 1985 his office was set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a very unconventional brain,'' said Daniel Barenboim,
the Israeli pianist and conductor, who has known Said since 1992
and considers him one of his closest friends. ``I think he has
great intellectual courage.''
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon this summer, Said was in his office at Columbia
for the first time in weeks. He had been spending his days
commuting to Long Island to be hooked up to an intravenous tube as
part of a clinical trial of an experimental treatment for patients
like him for whom chemotherapy failed.
</P>
<P>
   Three afternoons a week, he found himself ``a Palestinian
patient in a Jewish hospital being taken care of by an Indian
doctor and Irish nurses,'' as he put it, pumped full of antidotes
to the therapy's side-effects like soaring fever and uncontrollable
shaking while fighting the urge to nod off.
</P>
<P>
   On a day off from treatment, his face looked drawn. Beneath the
broad shoulders of a dark blue sport coat, his frame seemed to
disappear. His arms had grown so thin he could barely hold a tennis
racket. In the BBC film, which he wrote and narrated, pneumonia had
weakened his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Said rises at 5 a.m. to work in the Riverside Drive
apartment where he lives with his wife, Mariam Cortas Said. He
travels frequently and has multiple books scheduled for publication
next year: a collection of lectures on opera; his political
columns, published twice monthly in the Arabic newspaper Al Hayat,
and his memoir, titled, with some resonance, ``Not Quite Right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've decided that it's possible to live with a sword of
Damocles hanging over you,'' he said, when asked how long he might
live (he prefers not to know). ``You can, by an act of will, not
think about it. That was, I think, the major victory that I won. I
don't think about death.''
</P>
