<SLUG> BC-STATES-CHUCK-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        WATERGATE FIGURE FEELING DEJA VU 
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 18 -- Charles Colson knows how difficult it is
to tell a president he needs to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   As special counsel to President Nixon during the Watergate
scandal, Colson said he confronted Nixon on two consecutive days,
only to be met with a stern rebuttal -- the same sort of rebuke, he
says, Clinton aides would face today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who tried to tell Nixon the truth got rebuked. No
president wants to hear the truth,'' said Colson, who served seven
months in federal prison for helping cover up the Watergate
break-in that triggered the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Colson was the only Watergate defendant not charged with
perjury, and he credits the scandal with forcing him to look at his
own moral character: he became a born-again Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Capitol Friday, where he attended the Senate vote on
the effort to ban partial-birth abortions with such religious
luminaries as Cardinal Anthony Bevilacqua of Philadelphia, Colson
said there are many parallels between the current scandal and
Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a small crime -- in this case perjury -- that
mushroomed into a much larger crisis as the president refused to
come clean with the American public, he said. Most of all, Colson
said, the issue will be decided by whether or not the public trusts
its president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues are very similar. It's a question of the moral
authority of the president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala
tried to criticize Clinton at a cabinet meeting, but was chastised
by the president. In February 1973, Colson said he twice tried to
tell Nixon that his old friend and former attorney general, John
Mitchell, who also ran Nixon's 1972 re-election, oversaw a slush
fund that paid for the Watergate break-in and other misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me I'm supposed to turn on John Mitchell,'' Nixon
replied, according to Colson. ``I'm not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   From his experience, Colson said he believes some of Clinton's
top aides are doing some serious soul searching, similar to his own
in the 1970s, and that very soon someone will step down, disgraced
with the scandal. ``I just have to believe someone's going to,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
