<SLUG> BC-TX-IMMIGRANTS-$SADV20-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20 
 
NON-MEXICAN DETAINEES RELEASED AS INS STRUGGLES TO FIND PLACE TO
PUT THEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN _ While illegal immigrants from Mexico caught by U.S.
Border Patrol agents are usually returned to their country the same
day, one in four non-Mexicans apprehended is set free in South
Texas, U.S. Border Patrol officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The growing number of mostly Central American immigrants allowed
to continue on to their destinations in the United States _ more
than 5,500 in the past two years _ has alarmed anti-immigration
groups and discouraged many rank-and-file Border Patrol agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all get frustrated and say, ``Why are we going to mess with
them? They're going to cut them loose anyway,' '' said one Border
Patrol agent in Brownsville, who spoke on condition he would not be
identified. ``But by the same token, it's our job. We're here to
enforce the law, not to be immigration judges. It's aggravating,
but it's our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans entering this country illegally can easily be taken
back across an international bridge _ standard procedure for those
who have committed no crimes and agree to return voluntarily. But
noncriminal immigrants from other countries cannot be deported so
easily.
</P>
<P>
   If there is room to hold them in one of Texas' INS detention
facilities in Port Isabel or El Paso _ or in private facilities in
Houston or Laredo _ they are locked up until it can be confirmed
that they have a legal right to be here or until they can be
escorted back to their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   Often these immigrants, particularly those traveling as
families, are freed and given a summons telling them when to show
up for a court hearing. They frequently disappear, never to be
heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   The reason they are freed is that the border detention centers
are full and are not equipped to house families together, the head
Border Patrol agent in South Texas confirmed last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we release somebody on their own recognizance, it's
because of a special situation, such as a mother with minor
children we cannot separate or place in jail,'' said Patrol Chief
Joe Garza, who is in charge of the McAllen Border Patrol sector,
which has apprehended more non-Mexican border crossers than any
other sector on the southern U.S. border.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of these cases,'' Garza said, ``they already have
relatives here in the United States and these people are going to
join them.''
</P>
<P>
   Garza said other non-Mexican immigrants that his officers
release are &UR;  &LR; people with special needs, such as pregnant women and
injured or disabled immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers will only increase, Garza said. Despite intensive
border containment operations by the Border Patrol in South Texas
and El Paso, the number of non-Mexican immigrants being detained
along the Texas-Mexico border continues to rise. In the McAllen
sector alone, the number has tripled in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; However, Chief Garza emphasized that the non-Mexicans
immigrants still represent only 4 percent of the 246,000
undocumented immigrants apprehended by Border Patrol officers last
fiscal year. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; South Texas historically has been a principal entry point for
undocumented immigrants from Latin American countries, as well as
Mexico, in part because it is the closest stretch of border to
Central and South America. But in recent years, international
smuggling organizations also have begun using the South Texas
corridor, guiding clients from China, India and Pakistan up from
Mexico and across the shallow Rio Grande into Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, a Washington-based human rights group blasted INS
detention policies, noting that nearly 60 percent of immigrants
being held for immigration offenses nationwide are currently in
city or county jails because INS facilities are full.
</P>
<P>
   Crowded conditions at Texas' two INS detention centers, in Port
Isabel and El Paso, at times force Border Patrol agents to release
immigrants who cannot legally be returned to Mexico, officials
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hollenbeck, a Border Patrol intelligence agent in the Marfa
sector, expects more non-Mexican immigrants to try to enter via the
Big Bend area because of stepped-up enforcement in the lower Rio
Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Marfa detains few non-Mexicans now, Hollenbeck said
there are times when no space is available at the nearest INS
detention center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camp we send them to is in El Paso, if there is camp
space,'' said Hollenbeck. ``Otherwise, we have to release them on
their own recognizance and give them a court date at a later time,
through the mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollenbeck said camp officials in El Paso won't turn away
immigrants who are criminals, in keeping with a new immigration law
mandating the detention and deportation of immigrants convicted of
felonies. But for noncriminals, he said, ``If they're full, they
say, ``Sorry, we can't accept anybody,' and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   The patrol chief in McAllen acknowledged that savvy immigrant
smugglers take advantage of the INS' humanitarian policies and
routinely coach their clients to falsely claim they are related to
each other if they are caught by the Border Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smugglers are very aware of what procedures we have,'' Garza
said. ``They're very aware we try and consider humanitarian reasons
so they try every which way to get their (smuggled
clients) &UR;  &LR; through. And that's the difficult part of our job. We
want to do the right thing, and people take advantage of the system
and the generosity of this country by trying to pass themselves off
as a family when they are not.''
</P>
<P>
   In the McAllen sector, the impact is considerable. In fiscal
year 1997, Border Patrol agents released 2,199 of the 8,573
undocumented non-Mexican immigrants they apprehended, or 26
percent. Roughly the same percentage of the 12,084 non-Mexican
immigrants caught during the first 11 months of this fiscal year
also have been released.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, advocacy groups seeking tighter controls on
immigration charge that the INS is not serious about enforcement or
detention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no evidence they've made expanding detention space the
kind of priority they've devoted to naturalization (citizenship
programs),'' charged Dan Stein, executive director of the
Federation for American Immigration Reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important priority for the commissioner of
immigration must be to maintain adequate detention space, to detain
OTMs (Other Than Mexicans) until their court dates. Once detention
space is overcrowded and becomes overfilled, you lose your
deterrence value and illegals abuse the system,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   Key players in the nation's immigration policy, such as U.S.
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, are anxious to see results from historic
funding increases that have doubled the INS budget, including the
money to hire 1,000 new Border Patrol agents each year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who authored the 1996 Immigration Reform and Immigrant
Responsibility Act, which strengthened laws on the detention and
removal of immigration violators, has since worked to increase the
agency's funding, said spokesman Allen Kay.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal year 1996, the INS detention budget was $366.6
million, but was increased by Congress to $540 million in the 1997
budget year, and is $732.5 million for the current budget year. The
INS is asking for $771.4 million for next year's detention budget,
which includes $22.5 million to expand the Port Isabel detention
center. Another $12.6 million will be earmarked to upgrade older
facilities around the country and start design work for four new
detention centers to open in the year 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (1996) Act calls for dramatically increasing the amount of
detention space, and it is in the process, but it is not happening
as quickly as the congressman would like,'' Kay said. ``It is a
problem, and it is a problem that needs to be worked out quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   As they wait for new facilities to be built, INS officials are
spending millions each week _ paying city and county jails an
average of $58 per day to house each illegal immigrant who cannot
be housed in an INS facility.
</P>
<P>
   That practice was strongly condemned earlier this month by Human
Rights Watch, which noted that the INS currently holds 9,000 of its
15,000 detainees in jails, including those seeking asylum. The lead
researcher for the organization said that in addition to being
mixed in with criminals, some of the detainees were being abused by
their jailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found instances of physical mistreatment by jail officers,
inadequate medical care, and their right to legal counsel is
undermined by being placed in local jails,'' said Jennifer Bailey,
a research associate with Human Rights Watch in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said guards at the Jackson County Correctional Facility
in Florida in July allegedly used electric cattle prods to shock
immigration detainees who were tied up. At the Wharton County Jail
in Wharton, southwest of Houston, immigration detainees had not
been outside in over a year, Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going on because the INS detention capacity is currently
overwhelmed. There are no more beds available in their own
processing centers,'' Bailey said, adding that the INS has
``essentially abdicated its responsibility for the well-being and
safety of its detainees.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, INS regional spokesman Tomas Zuniga said there are
5,503 people in detention, but existing INS facilities in the state
can hold only 2,140. The rest are being housed in 121 Texas jails
and out-of-state jails with which the INS has contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Rio Grande Valley, immigration attorneys are no longer
surprised when told that a client has been abruptly transferred
from the INS detention center to a county jail somewhere upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Lang, a Harlingen attorney who, through the American Bar
Association, coordinates free legal services for immigrants seeking
asylum, said the transfer to a county jail often ends an asylum
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever they get pressed (for space), they send people to the
county jails,'' Lang said of the local INS camp in Port Isabel.
``And those people who are sent to county jails, on average, accept
deportation in greater numbers than those people detained at INS
detention centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? No. 1, they are housed in harsh conditions, they lose
contact with lawyers, and are far more restricted in their ability
to communicate with family and friends.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
