<HEADER>
A3213 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES--NAT     09-18 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES--NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      SECURITIES INDUSTRY PREPARING FOR MILLENNIUM BUG
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ron Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 17 -- Utah Republican Bob Bennett, chairman of
the Senate Special Committee on the Year 2000, compared the
technological glitches expected to come with the new MILLENNIUM to
a snow storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything might be shut down for a couple of days,'' Bennett
said during a hearing to examine the effect January 1, 2000 will
have on pensions and mutual funds. ``But snow melts of its own
accord. This problem won't melt. It will need to be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   But leaders in the securities industry told the committee not to
worry; they said they will have solutions for the Year 2000, or
Y2K, problem before the champagne bottles are uncorked.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said chose to focus on pensions and mutual funds
Thursday morning because more than one-third of American households
now own shares of mutual funds with assets of more than $5
trillion. In addition, nearly 84 million Americans participate in
pension plans which invest nearly $1.8 trillion dollars in
equities.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, he said, wanted to know whether fund managers
have enough information to make informed judgements and take the
correct precautions to deal with the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for investors to feel confident that the
managers of their pension funds and investment companies are taking
the necessary steps to secure their investments for the Year 200.
Without this confidence, investors will move available funds from
the stock market in anticipation of the century date change, and
that movement could have a dramatic impact on the world market and
the global economy,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   But Laura S. Unger, a commissioner of the Securities and
Exchange Commission, said she is confident the crisis will be
averted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the mutual fund industry is well aware of the
potential problems that the Year 2000 presents, and is preparing to
meet this challenge in a timely manner,'' Unger testified. ``Funds
and advisers generally appear to be expending the effort and
resources necessary to ensure Year 2000 compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Kittell, executive vice president of the Securities
Industry Association, shared the commissioners optimistic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Year 2000 effort is the largest business and technology
effort the financial services industry has ever undertaken, with a
cost projected to range between $4 and $6 billion,'' Kittell said.
``The most important element of the project is a comprehensive
testing program ... We are strongly encouraged that Wall Street
will be ready when Year 2000 arrives.''
</P>
<P>
   Averting Y2K problems are high priority for senior managers at
mutual fund firms, testified Investment Company Institute President
Matthew Fink. He said companies are working to identify internal
Y2K problems, while dedicating special staffs and special budgets
to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The one concern shared by senators on the committee and industry
insiders was the readiness of partners overseas, creating concern
over companies with international portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to get assurances that 'We're going to be O.K.' from
companies over here, but we seem unsure of foreign producers,
suppliers and partners,'' Bennett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
