<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3247 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALL-COLOR-COX     09-18 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-COLOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall's the ideal time for adding color to a graying landscape
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any day now, you'll glance out the window and wonder when you
moved to Dodge City.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly that rainbow of summer-flowering annuals has shriveled
to a torched hedge of tumbleweed. The green carpet of lush lawn you
moaned about mowing has withered to a bad shade of brown shag.
That's the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that fall _ the best gardening season of all _
is the perfect time for infusing your garden with plants that will
provide color during the next three seasons until summer returns.
</P>
<P>
   Some color can be had now by incorporating plants that don't
begin flowering until late summer and fall. For an instant punch in
winter, the easiest color _ pansies, mums and ornamental vegetables
_ will come by setting out these annuals over the next few weeks.
And for that early-spring splash, when landscapes are still gray,
now's also the time to plant bulbs and perennials so that they will
become established over winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring color doesn't just happen in March. It happens in fall,
when you plan for it and plant it,'' said Sharon Roth, a
spokeswoman for Pike Family Nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   So why's fall so great for planting?
</P>
<P>
   -- Cooler temperatures make the soil soft and workable yet still
warm enough to encourage root growth. Less heat also means plants
lose less moisture through their leaves.
</P>
<P>
   -- Shorter days offer fewer hours of the stressful sun that
bakes plants in midsummer. Less daylight also slows plant growth,
enabling energy to be spent on establishing roots instead of
foliage, which makes the plant strong.
</P>
<P>
   -- Garden centers often offer better prices and selections on
plants in fall than in spring, when demand is highest.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to dig in? For the novice, here are some tried-and-true
plants _ and for the seasoned, some new varieties _ to consider for
fall, winter and spring color, all of which can be planted now.
</P>
<P>
   FALL
</P>
<P>
   -- Stretch the summer. Some summer annuals _ petunias, marigolds
and lantana _ can still be planted to prolong the season. Add
fall-blooming perennials, such as asters, goldenrod and ornamental
grasses (left) to the mix, and you can sustain color until frost.
</P>
<P>
   -- Color can be subtle. As sunlight grows weaker, warm colors
such as reds, oranges and yellows aren't as necessary for
enlivening the garden. Fall perennials such as Autumn Joy sedum,
whose flowers turn from whitish-green to pink to russet (above),
and Mexican sage, with its bluish-purple or white plumes, are good
choices.
</P>
<P>
   -- It's trailgating season. Those lush vines that enveloped your
arbor, fence or mailbox all summer don't have to meet a dead end in
cooler weather. Try Sweet Autumn clematis, with its fragrant white
flowers (left); Boston ivy, which turns red; and Clematis armandii
and Confederate jasmine, for year-round green.
</P>
<P>
   -- Azaleas in fall? Flowerwood Nursery introduced its Encore
series of repeat-blooming azaleas, ranging from lavender to red,
last year, and new colors, including Bravo (a rich red) and Monarch
(coral, above) are available at retailers such as Pike and Home
Depot. ``What's so great about them is they bloom in spring, again
in the summer and then in fall until frost,'' said Amy Coker of the
Florida company. For shrubs that offer foliage color, consider
barberry, oakleaf hydrangea, sweetshrub, nandina and fothergilla.
</P>
<P>
   WINTER
</P>
<P>
   -- Grass is a gas. Ornamental grasses are popular choices for
creating height in borders and containers. ``Most will turn brown
in winter, but their plumes add color and interest,'' said Sally
Alcock, an assistant manager of Hastings Nature &AMP; Garden Center.
Consider Morning Light miscanthus, Little Bunny pennisetum and
Japanese Blood Grass. For shrub interest, consider berry producers,
including beautyberry, tea viburnum and hollies.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't hide your veggies. Color doesn't come only from
flowers; foliage can range from chartreuse to red to purple _
especially when you consider vegetables. Both edibles and
ornamentals no longer are relegated to a backyard patch. Herbs and
leafy vegetables, such as cabbages (above), make colorful landscape
and container plants, especially when complemented by pansies.
``People are getting more and more into lettuces, red mustard,
green mustard, Mizuna, Tatsoi, kale and parsley,'' said Denise
Smith, owner of GardenSmith Greenhouses in Jefferson. Among her new
offerings this season are a dark green Toscono kale and purple and
orange cauliflowers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mum's the word. Chrysanthemums, pansies and snapdragons are
old standbys. Instead of planting en masse, mix these low-growing
annuals in beds and containers with small evergreen shrubs;
perennials such as Maiden grass and salvias (for height) and golden
Creeping Jenny (for cascaders); or winter vegetables such as Red
Giant mustard, dinosaur kale or Swiss chard. The mix of annuals and
perennials will keep a container flourishing through the winter.
``People tend to think only fall or spring when planting, but
perennials can extend those seasons into winter,'' said Sally
Alcock of Hastings garden center.
</P>
<P>
   SPRING
</P>
<P>
   -- What's hot? Orange. Long the bane of gardeners, the color is
expected to be popular next spring, especially when paired with
purple. ``We're awash in requests for lists of orange flowers,
especially tulips,'' said Sally Ferguson of Netherlands Flower Bulb
Information Center in Brooklyn, N.Y. (In this area, wait until
November to plant tulips.) The Fosteriana tulip `Orange Emperor'
(above), a large salmon-orange bloomer, has gotten a big plug from
its biggest fan, Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mix 'n' match. Fall is an ideal time to mix bulbs with early
spring-blooming perennials, which also are best planted this
season. Consider planting tulips with hostas, purple hyacinth with
heather (above).
</P>
<P>
   -- Cheaper by the dozen. By planting some spring-flowering
perennials now, you can save money. A dozen 4-inch pots of
foxgloves are less expensive to plant now than several 10-gallon
containers of mature plants will be in spring, nursery owner Denise
Smith said. Yet those planted in fall typically perform better than
those planted in spring. Mail-order giant Wayside Gardens in
Hodges, S.C., is introducing a new foxglove, Digitalis purpurea
`Pam's Choice,' that sports white bells with maroon throats.
</P>
<P>
   -- Variety is the spice ... Some color can come from pattern,
like that of hostas' variegated foliage. New varieties are rampant.
Be among the first on your block to grow Wayside's `White
Christmas,' which has white leaves edged in green (above).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
