<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LMAY19-COX     09-18 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Hint of autumn awakens need to restore order
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I telephoned him at his Paulding County(Ga.) home recently,
John Yow, my editor at Longstreet Press, took awhile getting on the
line. Guessing _ I apologized for taking him from his gardening,
and we went on taking care of book matters.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, John was talking about what had driven him to
the garden that day. It wasn't to admire his corn, okra, hot banana
peppers, tomatoes or even his fabulous moonflower. ``I was pulling
weeds,'' he said. ``My garden had gotten overgrown. Weeds
everywhere. It looked awful. I had to weed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardening always is a competition between order and disorder,
and disorder reigned. I couldn't stand it.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, a chaotic garden can make you feel that all of life
is out of control. Rampaging weeds, overgrown shrubs, unpruned
trees, spent blooms, burnt out annuals and seedy perennials amount
to the horticultural equivalent of hamburger wrappers carelessly
tossed onto the sidewalk, soda cans plopped thoughtlessly along the
roadside _ amid the trashy butts of cigarettes. It is like a house
with filthy floors and piles of unwashed laundry and undone dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Like many this year, I understood all that intellectually, but
the fact is for several months I did little to bring order to my
garden. Keeping plants watered enough to keep most alive had been
as much as I'd had the will to do.
</P>
<P>
   As leaves hinted at autumn color and September's sharp-edged
light began shining upon us, pointing toward a change in the
weather, I felt a change of attitude. Let order begin.
</P>
<P>
   So motivated, I took to the garden of weeds. Yes, I struggled
into the task a good month or so behind John, but I don't have his
youthful stamina.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, I gathered great emotional vigor, assailing the crab
grass and the tree and shrub seedlings, the dandelion, plantain and
a million others growing happily where they were not wanted.
</P>
<P>
   I felt good and righteous ridding my garden of these uninviteds
_ and in the process uncovering and showing to better advantage
what I had planted. The dwarf mondo no longer was obscured by
ordinary grass, and the lush barberry was rid of the skanky green
weeds that had thrust themselves down its burgundy throat.
</P>
<P>
   I pulled and dug and gouged away weeds, and I pruned and
groomed, too, gathering twigs that had fallen. I had begun working
my way out of the slough of disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, what a revealing journey this turned out to be. Trying to
bring order to chaos is, in some ways, the flip side of planting;
they both can be obsessions. Just as I am given to sowing in the
rain and hoeing at midnight, I found myself weeding at dawn,
pulling grass invaders as the afternoon bulged to its hottest
point.
</P>
<P>
   Once I got chaos on the run, I couldn't stop. On the way to
anywhere, I had to pull something, dig up something. I had to
uncover just one more little piece of order.
</P>
<P>
   I know there is some point between chaos and the obsession to
create order _ the gardening equivalent of what politicians used to
call ``the sensible center.''
</P>
<P>
   Too, I know that middle point doesn't satisfy me. I want nothing
or everything. Let disorder reign or fight it to the death. Leave
it alone or be consumed by the need to destroy it. Give me chaos,
or give me obsession.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
