<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-NOUWEN-COX     09-18 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-NOUWEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'The Wounded Healer'
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most religious leaders dispense wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Henri Nouwen did more _ he gave his tears.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dutch Catholic priest died on Sept. 21, 1996, he left a
legacy that many compare to such spiritual giants as C.S. Lewis and
Thomas Merton.
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen proved that a spiritual mentor could be vulnerable. He
wrote some of the most moving and confessional passages in
Christian literature, including one searing book that detailed his
recovery from a midlife breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen was, as the title of one of his books suggested, ``The
Wounded Healer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was incomplete, yet he knew he was complete in God,'' said
the Rev. Charles Black, an associate pastor at Atlanta's First
Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   As Nouwen fans gather this month at his grave in Toronto to mark
the second anniversary of his death, there are signs that his
popularity is soaring.
</P>
<P>
   -- Three major publishers have released a collection of Nouwen's
writings within the past year. One biography has been released and
another is upcoming.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sales of Nouwen's books have actually increased by about 10
percent since his death, his publishers report.
</P>
<P>
   -- In a poll cited by Christianity Today magazine, a majority of
North American pastors reported that Nouwen was their most
influential theologian.
</P>
<P>
   -- Three of Nouwen's books are currently on the Top Ten book
list for Catholic religious books, according to Publishers Weekly,
the trade magazine for the book industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Byrns, an editor with Crossroad Publishing, said Nouwen was
a bridge between Catholics and other religious traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a Catholic priest, but an evangelical Protestant deep
in the heart of Alabama would also be reading Henri Nouwen,'' Byrns
said.
</P>
<P>
   A restless mind
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen, 64 at his death, wrote about the big issues of the day:
poverty, violence, materialism. Yet his biggest gift was in helping
readers steer through their struggles with loneliness, anger and
anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote with clarity but with so much wisdom,'' said Sherry
Nicholson, 46, an Atlanta public relations executive who stumbled
onto Nouwen during a period of depression. ``He was so human and so
willing to share his own feelings about where he was in different
circumstances of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen's 39 books (most are still in print) reveal a restless
mind that could draw spiritual lessons from unexpected places: a
billboard looming over a Los Angeles freeway, a trapeze act or a
Rembrandt painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made the spiritual life accessible,'' said Chris Glaser,
47, an Atlanta writer and former Nouwen student. ``He had a feeling
for contemporary dilemmas, but he didn't use highfalutin language.
He spoke in a way that people could understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was a priest, Nouwen did not simply contemplate God.
He lived the issues he wrote about. He participated in the civil
rights movement, became a peace activist, and served as a
missionary to the poor in Lima, Peru.
</P>
<P>
   People who knew Nouwen, however, recall his humility more than
his activism.
</P>
<P>
   ``His apartment door on campus was always left unlocked so that
students could come and see him if they wanted to see him,'' said
Glaser, who was a student of Nouwen's at Yale Divinity School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once when one of the students talked about all of the books in
his office library, he realized that his books seemed
intimidating,'' Glaser said. ``So he removed the book because he
didn't want anything to come between him and students.''
</P>
<P>
   Childlike fragility
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Nouwen also recall another quality _ his childlike
fragility. A priest who took on vows of celibacy, Nouwen struggled
with loneliness. Nouwen confessed in one of his later books (``The
Inner Voice of Love'') that his ``inexhaustible need for
affection'' became an addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really needed friends and people close to him,'' said
Sister Sue Mosteller, who befriended Nouwen at L'Arche Daybreak
community, a sanctuary for mentally disabled people near Toronto.
``When that didn't happen, it was tortuous.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, Nouwen and Mosteller had just finished lecturing at a
religious retreat in North Carolina. When Mosteller told Nouwen
that she felt they had not reached their audience, Nouwen burst
into tears, saying, ``Oh, I try so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen was born into a pious Catholic family in the Netherlands
in 1932. His father was a lawyer and his mother a bookkeeper. He
was ordained to the priesthood when he was 25.
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen's first success came in academia. After his ordination,
he held positions at the Menninger Clinic, Notre Dame, Yale and
Harvard universities. While teaching, Nouwen started writing,
publishing his first book, ``Intimacy: Pastoral Psychological
Essays,'' which attempted to answer the typical questions about God
he encountered from students.
</P>
<P>
   As Nouwen's book gained in popularity, he became a sought-after
speaker. Invitations literally poured in from the world. His
speaking style was dramatic. Nouwen didn't use notes and often
paced the floors, waving his large hands _ he was 6 feet 3 _ while
speaking in his Dutch-accented lisp.
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen developed a worldwide reputation, but he was exhausted by
the time he was 49. He resigned his tenured position at Yale and
eventually accepted an invitation to become the chaplain at
Daybreak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here didn't know Henri from his books,'' Mosteller
said. ``Most can't read. His big lectures didn't impress them. But
they loved him. He knew he was loved for what he was, not for what
he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen was transformed by one resident in particular, Adam, a
severely retarded young man who was unable to talk, walk or dress
himself. Nouwen took two hours to clean and dress Adam each
morning.
</P>
<P>
   One visitor asked Nouwen whether his time could have been spent
better elsewhere, but Nouwen told him that Adam was his teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my past life has been built around the idea that my
value depends on what I do,'' Nouwen wrote. ``I earned my degree
and awards and I made a career. ... But as I sit beside the slow
and heavily breathing Adam, I start seeing how violent that journey
was. So filled with desires to be better than others, so marked by
rivalry and competition, so pervaded with compulsions and
obsessions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nouwen's neediness continued to cause him problems, even as
he searched for peace at Daybreak.
</P>
<P>
   'So vulnerable'
</P>
<P>
   He became attracted to another staff member, a younger man who
some said resembled Nouwen: sensitive and outgoing. Nouwen began to
talk to his friend every day, reaching him by phone when he was
traveling. ``He was putting more demands on the friendship,'' said
Wendy Greer, a friend of Nouwen's. ``He was almost suffocating the
other person.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the man told Nouwen that he could not carry the weight
of their friendship. Nouwen was devastated. He wrote later that ``I
could no longer sleep. I cried uncontrollably for hours. ... Within
me there was one long scream coming from a place I didn't know
existed, a place full of demons.''
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen left Daybreak and entered a monastery for six months. A
friend told him that the celibate life wasn't meant for him because
he was so needy, but Nouwen decided that he would stick to his
vows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he was so sensitive he was also so vulnerable,'' said
Robert Durback, a former Trappist monk who edited an anthology of
Nouwen's works called ``Seeds of Hope'' (Doubleday, $11). ``I was
talking to him on the phone once when he said, `You know, I must
continually pursue a relationship with Jesus. If I didn't, I could
get into trouble.'''
</P>
<P>
   Instead Nouwen got help. He sought psychological and pastoral
counseling while in seclusion. He wrote about his experiences in a
private journal that later became ``The Inner Voice of Love.''
Nouwen described his stay as ``a time of intense purification and a
new inner freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinvigorated, Nouwen returned to Daybreak. He even resumed his
friendship with the man he had become so attached to. He spent his
last years at Daybreak. On Sept. 21, 1996, he suffered a heart
attack in the Netherlands after flying there for an interview with
a film crew.
</P>
<P>
   Nouwen was honored with a state funeral by the Netherlands.
Mother Teresa attended. His coffin was decorated with colorful
drawings made by the disabled people of Daybreak.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his death, Nouwen's life still burns brightly as more
people discover his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every real encounter, every real meeting, every real intimacy
growing out of the divine love we carry within us is not ended or
stopped by death,'' Nouwen said during an interview with the
National Catholic Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen ... that some intimacies people have lived in
marriage, in friendship or in effective relationships, can continue
to bear fruit beyond the person's chronological life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
