<HEADER>
A3250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-ROSH-COX     09-18 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ROSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powerful rituals are common with the High Holy Days
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The water of baptism and mikvah, the wine of Seder and
communion, the colors of liturgy _ religion is full of symbols and
rituals.
</P>
<P>
   For Jews, some powerful rituals are connected with the High Holy
Days, which begin with Rosh Hashana at sundown Sunday and end Sept.
30 with Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life without ritual can be extremely empty,'' said Rabbi Mark
Kunis of the 830-family Shearith Israel, a traditional synagogue in
Atlanta. ``Ritual has the power to take our highest ideals and
manifest them in our daily lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis of the High Holy Days is that ``man is not doomed,
that man can change for the better and be reborn, that there is
always hope,'' said Kunis. ``These ideas are borne out in Jewish
rituals for the new year.''
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon before Rosh Hashana begins, many Jews go to a
natural body of water, recite prayers and drop bread crumbs into
the stream. The bread symbolizes sin and arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gather with our families as the sun sets over the water and
it is very beautiful,'' said Kunis. ``When the most important thing
in our lives is what television program is on that particular
evening, we live with the feeling that maybe we have wasted a lot
of the precious time God has given us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shofar
</P>
<P>
   The sound of the shofar is piercing, not sweet or mellifluous,
because it is meant as a wake-up call, says Rabbi Steven Lebow of
the 720-family Temple Kol Emeth in Cobb County. ``It's meant to
wake up your spirit right down to your soul,'' he said. ``It tells
you it's time to change, time to put away what is past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Torah gives no reason for blowing the shofar, or ram's horn,
on Rosh Hashana, but Jews connect the ritual with the story of
Abraham, who was asked by God to prepare his son Isaac to be
sacrificed. But when Abraham got to the altar, he found a ram
caught in the bushes nearby. God then told him to sacrifice the
ram, not his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe mystically that God looks down from heaven, sees us
blowing the ram's horn and is reminded of the tremendous faith of
our ancestor,'' Lebow said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kittel
</P>
<P>
   From a German word for smock, the kittel is a white garment that
is worn over other clothes. The Torah is also covered in white
throughout the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wearing of white represents purity,'' said Kunis. ``On
Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur, we ask and are forgiven of our sins
and face the New Year with that sense of purity. Also, white seems
to be an allusion to the garb of the angels. With the forgiveness
of our sins, we achieve a level of purity comparable with that of
the angels.''
</P>
<P>
   But a kittel is also a burial shroud, and its use at this time
of year reminds Jews of their mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is on Rosh Hashana that our fate is decided for the coming
year, who shall live and who shall die,'' said Kunis. ``There is a
saying that repentance, prayer and charity can avert the evil
decree. In other words, if God has decreed against us for the
coming year _ death, disease or financial disaster _ these three
actions can change God's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Observant Jews are very generous this time of year, spend hours
praying in the synagogue, and ask forgiveness of God and of each
other, he said. ``God doesn't forgive on high unless we forgive
below.''
</P>
<P>
   The Priestly Blessing
</P>
<P>
   When Leonard Nimoy as Mr. Spock on television's ``Star Trek''
raised his hand in a split-fingered salute, many Jews recognized it
as the sign of the Kohanim, or Jewish priestly class, for the
blessing of the congregation on Rosh Hashana. As part of the Rosh
Hashana service in many synagogues, the Kohanim remove their shoes,
have their hands ritually washed, then stand before the Ark.
</P>
<P>
   At the appropriate time, they cover their heads with their
prayer shawls and recite a benediction: ``Blessed art thou O Lord
our God, king of the universe, who hast hallowed us with the
sanctity of Aaron and commanded us to bless his people Israel in
love.'' They raise their hands to form ``windows'' through which
God can send blessings.
</P>
<P>
   Lebow's Reform synagogue still does the ritual. ``I think it's
very meaningful to feel that power of blessing that goes back
thousands of years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
