<TEXT>
<P>
   WOMEN IN SPORTS:
</P>
<P>
   A SEVEN-PART SERIES FROM THE AJC
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution will begin a
seven-part series on the rapidly changing women's sports scene.
Unlike men's sports, which has been evolving for several decades,
even centuries, women's sports has advanced relatively overnight
from pick-up or intramural status to high-profile, organized events
that increasingly find their way way onto TV. As the women's sports
scene evolves, it is becoming more and more like the men's _ for
better or worse. The AJC series will summarize how far women's
sports has come and will address numerous issues that it is, or
will be, facing. The time hook is the 25th anniversary of Billie
Jean King's monumental win over Bobby Riggs in a tennis exhibition,
along with the implementation of Title IX.
</P>
<P>
   Stories for the Sunday's Part One will move on the Cox Wire
tonight. Photos and graphics for the series will be available
beginning Monday. Extensive budgets for each part of the series
will be included on the daily budgets. Sunday's Part One budget is
listed below.
</P>
<P>
   If you need more information about the series, contact Tom Oder
on the CoxNet desk in Atlanta at 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DAY ONE: OVERVIEW
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-INSPORTS _ Twenty-five years ago, the Bobby Riggs-Billie
Jean King tennis match was one of the most talked-about sports
event -- but as a circus-like exhibition. From that farce, women's
sports have gotten serious. Now there are so many more
opportunities, with two pro basketball leagues, soccer and hockey
in the works and thousands of college scholarships available to
young women. They are getting on TV and in the print media. And
their stars are becoming role models as well as marketing tools.
Women's sports is at a crossroads, with several road bumps ahead.
This sweep story will look at how big women's sports has gotten,
what's driving it, who the big names are. Plenty of numbers, TV,
marketing. (Schultz/Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 117. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WCOMPARE _ Some expectations that women will catch up someday to
guys may be fueled by vast improvements but experts say that, while
the gap is closing, the guys won't have to worry about women
matching their performances. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
36.
</P>
<P>
   WITH GRAPHICS _ showing how many years women's records are
behind men's records; comparing swim, track bests in 1973 and '98;
showing differences in the gender sports, such as basketball size,
net height in volleyball; Text chart on most popular sports for
girls, boys; timeline graphic; comparing participation; on earnings
disparity; of AJC survey (5 questions) on women's sports issues.
</P>
<P>
   WKRONE _ First-person woman's voice from jockey Julie Krone
about lack of women jockeys. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 7.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
