<SLUG> BC-TEXANS-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS ON JUDICIARY COMMITTEE HAVE DIFFERENT VIEWS ON STARR
ALLEGATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two Texans on the House Judiciary Committee
have vastly different views on the strength of independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's allegation that President Clinton committed
impeachable offenses related to his illicit relationship with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their disagreements, Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Houston, and
Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio, both say they will be guided solely by
the evidence _ and not polls or party _ as they vote on how the
House should proceed with regard to the president's possible
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to vote an unpopular vote,'' Jackson Lee said, ``I
am prepared to do that.'' She added that the Constitution will
serve as her ``guiding force'' as she weighs the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Starr's allegations and Clinton's defenses must be
weighed objectively before a decision regarding impeachment can be
made. The San Antonio Republican said he will follow the law and
his duty as a member of Congress during the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee, a staunch supporter of Clinton's policies, said the
American people should remember that Starr is a prosecutor
advocating the president's impeachment with a one-sided argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to put Starr's case in context,''
Jackson Lee said, referring to the independent counsel's report to
Congress. ``It is a prosecutorial document. The American people and
Texans should perceive it just as that.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Jackson Lee added that Clinton's defense has as great a
bias as the prosecutor's case. ``The president's position should be
equally subject to scrutiny,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a Clinton critic, believes the independent counsel
presents a strong case that Clinton lied under oath, obstructed
justice, tampered with witnesses and abused power to prevent public
disclosure of his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has made ``very, very serious allegations that I thought
were supported by credible evidence,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Judiciary Committee, a collection of 21
Republicans and 16 Democrats, have called on members to put party
aside in favor of the good of the nation as they consider whether
to begin formal impeachment proceedings against the president.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ideal of bipartisanship broke down this week as the
committee voted along party lines to release Clinton's videotaped
testimony before a grand jury examining the president's alleged
cover up of his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee opposed making the videotape public, saying ``due
process'' and ``fundamental fairness'' argued against releasing any
grand jury testimony _ even the president's _ because the jury's
proceedings are supposed to be conducted in private.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Smith, advocates a wide release of information to
ensure the American people are fully informed.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee said Clinton, although he is president, remains
entitled to the same constitutional and statutory protections as
anyone else who testifies before grand juries, including the
assurance that the testimony will remain sealed. ``The president is
neither above the law nor is he beneath the law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith countered that other strong interests come into play when
serious allegations are raised about the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people and Congress deserve to get the best and
most accurate information available,'' Smith said. ``We should fall
on the side of providing the most people with the most
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending the release of the tape, Smith said that ``hearing a
person's voice, watching them as they speak give a more accurate
picture than just reading their words on a piece of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Smith said information should be released because it is
relevant, not because it is titillating.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their vast differences, Smith and Lee agreed that the
committee should resist any partisan temptation to rush to
judgment. Instead, the panel should strive for consensus, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot proceed willy-nilly,'' Jackson Lee said, adding her
praise for Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde's, R-Ill.,
efforts to keep the panel's proceedings bipartisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have faith and confidence in what I believe will be
reasoned deliberation,'' Jackson Lee said. ``I would not at this
point suggest that we cannot proceed in that (bipartisan) way.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, citing the seriousness of the allegations, said the
American people should not expect quick action from the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an instance where we want to proceed cautiously,''
Smith said. ``This is going to take some days or even weeks. We
have a lot of material to assimilate and that takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he expects the Judiciary Committee to vote to
recommend that the full House proceed with an impeachment inquiry.
But he declined to predict what would happen after that.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he his heartened by what he called ``emerging''
bipartisanship on the committee. ``I hope it will continue,'' he
added. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
