<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI, HARSHBARGER HIT THE GROUND RUNNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 20, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final stage of the race for governor in Massachusetts begins
with the two contenders starting just about dead even.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-week sprint that ends Nov. 3 will find the acting
governor, Paul Cellucci, enjoying advantages of incumbency and
campaign cash. Attorney General Scott Harshbarger commands the
loyalty of a re-energized union movement here and an advantage in
Democratic party voter totals that, while hard to tap, is
nevertheless substantial.
</P>
<P>
   If you agree that the real race begins when the primary winners
go before the TV cameras election night, the rivals had smooth
starts Tuesday. Both finished strongly against robust challenges,
and carry momentum into the runoff. Both their acceptance speeches
were well-delivered. Cellucci's was crafted more as an artful
attempt to box Harshbarger as a tax-and-spend Dukakis liberal who'd
tip over the Bay State economy.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger, pegged for years as a humorless plodder and policy
wonk who'd indict his grandmother if she failed to dot her legal
''i's'' or cross her ethical ''t's,'' re-introduced himself on
primary night as more lively and passionate than his Democratic
critics ever conceded. Neither candidate has the technical
articulateness of a Dukakis, the stylishly-quirky odd-ballish humor
of a Weld, the jagged intellectual firepower of a Silber, the cool
acerbity of a Kerry, nor the bring-down-the-house brass section of
a Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci read his speech better than he reads most of his
speeches, and despite a rather stumbling campaign which has raised
doubts about his staying power, he holds intact his reputation for
being a nice guy, even if his caliber is small-bore. Harshbarger is
riding a 16-year career as a prosecutor. eight as Middlesex DA,
eight as attorney general, and generally knows the law, knows the
facts, and can deliver on demand.
</P>
<P>
   But the AG has never been known for unleashing barnburners on
the stump. So his emergence Tuesday night as a highly-charged
fist-pumping microphone-seizer gave his speech the slight edge, in
my mind, over Cellucci's.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary grappling was a wash. Cellucci laid down the
foundation for his game plan, a replay of the
run-against-Dukakis-and-bad-memories-of-the-past strategy that
carried Weld to victory in the last governor's race over token
opposition. But the let's-run-against-Dukakis-again strategy proved
to be bankrupt in the Weld-Kerry fight that propelled Weld out of
elective office.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger did not get the mileage he'd hoped for in laying
down his primary night challenge to Cellucci to forswear negative
advertising. It is taken as a given in both camps that Cellucci
cannot win without going negative, early and often. But the papers
and TV glossed over Harshbarger's challenge, and Cellucci managed
to finesse it _ for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that becomes a core issue of this fight depends more on
the media than on the candidates _ and the media puts most of its
attention on the sex scandal gripping Washington.
</P>
<P>
   My hunch is that the Clinton turmoil will not tip the governor's
race much one way or another, unless there is a dramatic falloff in
Democratic turnout. Bill Clinton's stature has been diminished
substantially, even here in the state where he was arguably most
popular. But Hillary Clinton remains a very popular figure here,
and I find it hard to believe that her private hurts will prevent
her from delivering a riveting political speech toward the end of
October that will try to revive her demoralized party's turnout
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The reception given the battered President by the Democratic
establishment here Thursday night at the ``unity dinner'' was
different than previous love-ins featuring the same cast. The
applause was prolonged, but not so loud nor as intense as it would
have been in earlier days.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of interesting sub-plots, in addition to the
awkward Clinton scandal. Mayor Menino's oft-noted coolness toward
Harshbarger helps Cellucci. But Harshbarger shrewdly lavished
praise on Menino in his brief remarks, lauding the mayor for
reducing crime, taking on the school dilemma with vigor, boosting
economic development robustly.
</P>
<P>
   But like many establishment Democrats, Menino harbors grudges
against the attorney general. And in Boston, personal scores often
weigh more than party loyalty. Still, with organized labor solidly
behind him, Harshbarger can afford to make nice with the mayor,
despite the chill that is still apparent. Menino will need
organized labor in his corner down the road.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, after Cellucci staged an event at Doyle's with a
handful of defecting Democratic legislators, Harshbarger shrugged
it off. His aggressive stance against casino gambling has hurt him
with some pro-casino legislators, and rumors abound that Cellucci
is promising cabinet-level jobs to some defecting Democrats (Public
Safety is in play, apparently).
</P>
<P>
   Most visible among the Harshbarger-bashers on Beacon Hill is
House Speaker Tom Finneran, who questions whether his party's
standard-bearer will lurch to ``the loony left.'' This is
ludicrous, till you remember two things:
</P>
<P>
   First, Finneran was elected speaker off the votes of Republican
House members, and in the Weld-Cellucci days, enjoyed great
leverage against the liberals. Second, if Harshbarger wins,
Finneran's power shrinks, his clout diminishes, and, more
ominously, there is very likely going to emerge a liberal power
center to counter the speaker's iron grip on the House agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The liberals now in the House are leaderless and generally
feckless. But with a governor to give them cover and encouragement,
Finneran's survival as speaker could be in jeopardy. It's been ten
years since a governor was in position to dictate terms to the
House Speaker, because the last two years of Dukakis ('89-'90) were
a time of national recession and economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   But put a strong Democrat in as governor, with powerful labor
backing, and Finneran is no longer the 800-lb. gorilla standing
astride the State House dome. So factor that in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
