<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VIDEOTAPE AVAILABLE ON INTERNET, BUT SPECIAL TECHNOLOGY
NEEDED TO VIEW IT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When President Clinton's videotaped testimony in the Monica
Lewinsky sex scandal is made public on Monday, it will be available
for viewing at several sites on the Internet. But seeing it won't
be as easy as reading the text-only independent counsel's report.
</P>
<P>
   The sites will use a technology called ``streaming video'' to
show the 4-hour-plus testimony, and viewing it will require a
relatively fast Internet connection and special software.
</P>
<P>
   Computer users with up-to-date systems and the latest World Wide
Web browsers should have what's needed. Netscape Communications'
Communicator 4 and Microsoft Corp.'s Internet Explorer 4 both come
with the necessary software.
</P>
<P>
   Users of older Web browsers may or may not have the software
already. If not, they will need either RealNetworks' RealPlayer,
available at no charge for both Windows and Macintosh computers at
www.real.com, or Microsoft's free Media Player, available at
www.microsoft.com/windows/mediaplayer/download/default.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to view the testimony should have at least a
28,800 bits-per-second connection.
</P>
<P>
   Streaming video puts a heavy load on a computer that's
dispensing the feed, so expect an Internet traffic jam at those
sites offering it online.
</P>
<P>
   Among the news-related sites planning to offer the deposition
are CNN (www.cnn.com), MSNBC (www.msnbc.com), Broadcast.com
(www.broadcast.com), National Public Radio (www.npr.org), Fox News
(www.foxnews.com). HoustonChronicle.com will offer excerpts from
the deposition, and provide pointers to Web sites with the complete
video. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
