<HEADLINE>
DID TAX LAW CAUSE RECENT STOCK DROP? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is the capital gains tax high enough to keep the market from
plunging more than it has because it discourages selling by those
who don't want to pay taxes on their gains of recent years? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or did the easing of the long-term cap gains qualification
restriction in July prompt the current sell-off that has caused
most stock prices to tank since the major indexes reached record
highs July 17? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first question was posed by a colleague who has decided, for
the time being at least, to endure his portfolio's paper losses
rather than take some profits and thereby incur a hefty tax
liability. The answer is that while tax considerations may have
discouraged some selling in recent weeks, the effect probably
hasn't been widespread enough to have made a significant
difference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, a lot of individual money these days is in
employer-sponsored 401(k) plans that allow investors to shift out
of stock mutual funds and into bond and money market funds without
any immediate tax consequences. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the conventional wisdom in investment circles is that
dread of a tax hit shouldn't affect decisions to get out of an
investment if cashing in looks like the intelligent thing to do.
This is easier said than done, however, and the ebb and flow of
capital gains tax revenues show how investors do react to taxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When taxes on capital gains have been raised beyond what
investors consider a tolerable level, they will tend to resist
taxation by holding on. The practical result has been that cap gain
receipts have tended to rise after the rate was lowered and to
contract after cap gain tax increases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon has led at least one observer to claim that the
tax law changes enacted in July retroactive to Jan. 1 are largely
responsible for the heavy selling of stocks since mid-July. The
primary element of that legislation reduced the holding period to
qualify for the lower long-term capital gains tax rate from 18
months to 12 months. That rate is 20 percent for most taxpayers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Dessauer recently told subscribers to his Investor's World
newsletter that the stock market's abrupt turn wasn't a response to
Asia's continuing turmoil or Russia's emerging problems. Rather, he
said, it was the positive influence of the newly legislated more
taxpayer-friendly cap gains treatment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time our government cuts the capital gains tax rate,''
he said, ``there is a wave of selling. In fact, when investors
sense that a capital gains tax cut is coming, they defer normal
selling until the cut is certain. Then comes a huge selling
wave.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Dessauer's line of logic, this is apparently what
began to happen after the July market peaks were reached. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Dessauer observation worth noting is his expectation of
Federal Reserve interest rate relief. The most interesting aspect
of his forecast is that the easing may come only after the Fed
learns its lesson the hard way by first raising rates. Even so, he
predicts, ``one way or another the Fed will cut interest rates (by)
a full 1 percent.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dessauer expects that the ``slightest hint'' of Fed easing and
an end to the Asian crisis will cause markets ``to shoot back to
their former highs.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dessauer's case is convincing enough to lead to the conclusion
that, if anything, this summer's congressional effort to give
investors a tax break was a significant factor in the correction
that has since ensued. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
