<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3274 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORTGAGE-RATES-KAN &LR;      09-18 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGE-RATES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SILVER LINING IN ECONOMIC GLOOM: LOW MORTGAGE RATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Steve Everly  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market is down, Russia's economy is crumbling and
consumer confidence is shaken. So with all these economic worries,
why are Julie and Scott McDonald so upbeat? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In less than two weeks, they will move into a new house in
Shawnee, Kan. It's the first home they've owned, and part of the
credit goes to the lowest mortgage rates in decades. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very lucky,'' Julie McDonald said. ``This is a dream
come true for us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, turmoil in the stock market has a silver lining. Some
worried investors are fleeing stocks for the safety of U.S.
government bonds. The influx, in turn, is driving down the interest
rates on bonds. And because mortgage rates generally follow bonds,
they are going down as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The result is a financial windfall for cul-de-sac America.
Freddie Mac, a company that buys mortgages from lenders, said
Thursday that rates for 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages were at the
lowest level since it began collecting the data in 1971. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other groups that compile mortgage data say the news is even
better. Rates are hovering above 6.5 percent with the payment of
one point _ 1 percent of the loan balance _ they say. That's
considered the lowest since Lyndon Johnson was president in 1960s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only other time in the last three decades when rates came
near that level was in 1993. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great in '93, but this is a different type of great,''
said Chuck Rusnak, a mortgage loan officer for Hillcrest Bank in
Overland Park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage rates are fickle. They were up Wednesday and down
Thursday, and they also vary among financial institutions and
brokers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, mortgage rates in the Kansas City area have
been beating the national average, with rates between 6.5 and 7
percent for a 30-year, fixed-rate mortgage and the payment of no
points. Pay one point, and you can get them even cheaper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The recent declines in rates can even justify homeowners who
refinanced mortgages just two years ago to do it again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Many homeowners with mortgages that were just recently
considered too low to refinance now have the opportunity to move
into even lower-rate loans,'' said Freddie Mac's chief economist,
Robert Van Order. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A quick lesson in Mortgage 101 shows why. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take a 30-year mortgage with a 8.5 percent rate, which was the
average rate two years ago. If a $100,000 loan was refinanced at 7
percent, the annual savings would be $1,200. Any closing costs
would typically be repaid in one to two years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even a 1 percent gap can produce savings. Consider, for example,
a mortgage in which the lender pays the closing costs in exchange
for a rate that is a half percent higher. Refinancing that 8.5
percent mortgage with a 7.5 percent loan gives you savings of more
than $800 a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same economics, of course, are working in favor of people
buying homes now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julie and Scott McDonald are able to buy a nicer home than they
normally could afford. Both are in their mid-20s and _ while the
stock market is important _ they have plenty of time to ride out
the downturn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a mortgage with a lower interest rate helps them to
achieve one of their main goals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have plenty of time for the stock market,'' said Julie
McDonald. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mounting benefits of lower rates are making themselves known
as news of the decline spreads. The Mortgage Bankers Association of
America says that applications rose more than 80 percent last
week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Palmer, who lives in Lenexa, Kan., this week closed on a
mortgage that refinanced an existing 10 percent mortgage with a
$75,000 balance. Because his house had appreciated in value, he was
also able to take out an additional $44,000 to remodel his home's
bathroom, install a new driveway and make other improvements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although his loan balance increased more than 50 percent, his
monthly payment increased only $134 because of the lower rate. A
bonus was that the mortgage company paid the closing costs in
exchange for a slightly higher rate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he paid off other debts, which leaves him with
monthly expenses that are less than before the refinancing. That
has helped take the sting out of recent losses in his stock
portfolio because of the market downturn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As for my personal finances, I'm in a real good position
now,'' Palmer said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic decline in interest rates _ about a half
percent _ has occurred in the last couple of weeks. The question is
how much more of a decline, if any, is in store. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It depends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nutter Jr., president of the James B. Nutter &AMP; Co. mortgage
company, said rates could decline further. But he's not making bold
predictions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In our business, when rates are at this level they generally
don't stay there all that long,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind the recent decline make mortgage rate
predictions even tougher. Instead of worries about the domestic
economy _ the typical reason for changes in interest rates _ the
concern has been about overseas economies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is also the issue of President Clinton and possible
impeachment proceedings that could add to the jitters in financial
markets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Gumbinger, an analyst for HSH Associates in New Jersey,
which analyzes and compiles mortgage rates, said the mortgage
market generally follows the 10-year bond. Any flight to safety by
investors would bring the interest on the 10-year bond down, along
with mortgage rates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Typically, rates for 30-year mortgages are about 1.5 percent
higher than the bond. A 4.8 percent 10-year bond would typically
mean a 6.3 percent 30-year mortgage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But recently the gap has grown to about 1.9 percent, in part
because mortgages at these rates are being snapped up, Gumbinger
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even without further declines, consumers are enjoying rates that
seemed impossible a decade ago, when mortgages were above 10
percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at historic lows,'' Gumbinger said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
