<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Sept. 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt across the upper Middle West on
Saturday as humid air flowing northward from the Gulf of Mexico is
lifted by an approaching cold front. A broken line of strong storms
over North Dakota on Saturday morning will move east and intensify
during the day.
</P>
<P>
   As descending air currents within the thunderstorms intercept a
zone of fast-moving air aloft, powerful downburst winds will occur,
producing damaging gusts in several locations.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the cold front, unseasonably cool air will pour into the
northern Rockies and Pacific Northwest. Clouds and scattered
showers will accompany the chill, especially over the Cascades and
Bitterroot Mountains where the air is forced to ascend the higher
terrain. Some snow will occur at elevations above 9,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will plague much of
Florida and the Gulf Coast on Saturday. A weak tropical system over
the western Gulf of Mexico may bring a period of heavier showers to
the Texas and Louisiana coasts.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case for the last several days, some flooding
will occur, particularly in areas where heavy rain has already
fallen. Meanwhile, powerful Hurricane Georges will churn steadily
westward through the central Atlantic on Saturday afternoon,
possibly affecting the Lesser Antilles on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, breezes from the south will transport humid air into
the Great Lakes and northeastern states. Isolated afternoon
thunderstorms will form near the Ohio Valley and central
Appalachians as a weak jet-stream disturbance passes overhead.
Otherwise, partly sunny skies will prevail across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Strengthening Hurricane
</P>
<P>
   Winds in Hurricane Georges reached 100 mph on Friday as the
storm intensified over the eastern Atlantic. The surface pressure
in the eye decreased to 28.88 inches of mercury. The
intensification was a result, in part, of a high-pressure system
40,000 feet above the eye. The lofty high forced upper-level air to
flow away from the storm's center. Thus, like a chimney over a
fireplace, the high ventilated the hurricane, preventing rising,
turbulent air from piling up aloft. Such a pile-up would have
produced a weightiness that would have unfavorably increased
surface pressures in the eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
