<SLUG> BC-STATES-WISH-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;       ENGLISH: CONGRESS SHOULD ALLOW WISHES TO COME TRUE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Andrea Berman  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 18 -- Rep. Phil English, R-Penn., called on
Congress Friday to pass legislation allowing needy children with
life-threatening diseases to accept gifts from wish granting
foundations without risking the loss of supplemental income or
Medicaid benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, some kids with illnesses who accept cash
gifts for spending money or meals from the ``Make-A-Wish''
foundation and other tax-exempt foundations risk losing some of
their Supplemental Security Income and Medicaid benefits because
the gift is counted as income.
</P>
<P>
   English has introduced a measure, which is expected to be
considered next week by the House, that would exempt cash payments
under $2,000 from charitable foundations from being considered
income.
</P>
<P>
   English said his legislation ensures ``no children making a wish
will be punished for it ... sick children should not be punished by
the bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure would help 500 to 1,000 children nationally, English
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
