<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-UNEMPLOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE UNEMPLOYMENT AT 3 PERCENT OF WORK FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' unemployment rate, already at a historic
low, dipped even further in August. But Friday's state jobs report
pointed to a slowdown in employment, caused by turmoil in Asian
economies and on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   US workers to date have been largely insulated from the sharp
downturn over the past year in world economies from Japan and
Russia to, more recently, Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's unemployment rate has held at a low 4.5 percent for
three consecutive months, and the state's jobless rate dipped by
one-tenth of a point in August, to 3 percent, the Massachusetts
Division of Employment and Training reported.
</P>
<P>
   But the change, insignificant by statistical standards, masked a
worrisome turn in the jobs report: The number of Massachusetts
residents holding jobs declined by 1,800, to 3,210,600 in August
from 3,212,400 in July.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the apparent discrepancy is that the unemployment
rate is based on a survey of households, while a separate survey of
businesses is used to determine employment in specific industries.
The two surveys often conflict, especially in the midst of economic
transition. The business survey is viewed by economists as a more
reliable gauge of job activity.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Johnson, &UR;  &LR; chief regional economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's
DRI, said the report supported forecasts of a marked slowdown in
job growth next year by her Lexington research firm. Job growth,
which is likely to be 2.9 percent this year, could slow to 1
percent in 1999, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report suggests, at least in August, job growth stopped,
and we're seeing the influence of Asian and financial market
turmoil,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   While it's too early to say for certain whether August is the
beginning of a downturn or just an aberration, there are other
signs of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts exports by high technology and other important
industries doing business with Asia have declined this summer. At
the same time, a drop in the US and world stock markets is taking a
toll on the financial industry, a cornerstone of Boston business.
Consumer confidence, which propelled growth, has also flagged.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing companies saw the biggest decline in their
payrolls _ 4,100 jobs were lost last month. The financial industry,
which had been red hot and hiring at a rapid pace, stagnated and
produced no new jobs last month.
</P>
<P>
   But the jobs report showed signs that there is still growth. In
August, there were 2,400 more jobs in Massachusetts than there were
in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A strong housing market and the Big Dig construction project
added 200 new construction jobs last month. The services industry,
which includes everything from dry cleaning to business consulting,
added 1,300 jobs. While high-tech manufacturing lost 200 jobs,
other high-tech companies added 800.
</P>
<P>
   A revised report by the US Department of Commerce found that the
average income of Massachusetts residents in 1997, at $31,207, was
the third-highest in the nation, following Connecticut and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our record low unemployment rate,'' acting Governor A. Paul
Cellucci, who is running for re-election, said in a statement,
``will help families across the Commonwealth share in the state's
economic good times.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Cellucci's comments referred to data from a separate survey of
Massachusetts households that indicated August saw an ``all-time
high'' of 3,115,800 jobs, according to the Division of Employment
and Training. But that survey, which is the basis of the
unemployment rate, is widely viewed by economists as less reliable
than the survey of businesses, which showed the decline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3311 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HASTINGS-HNS &LR;      09-18 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HASTINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHED MEMBER OF CONGRESS MOVES TO IMPEACH STARR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of all 435 members of the House of Representatives,
Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., has a unique claim to being an expert
on impeachment: He was impeached when he was a U.S. District Court
judge.
</P>
<P>
   After the Senate convicted him and removed him from office in
1989, Hastings went back to Florida and successfully ran for a
House seat. Now, claiming he is ``the most experienced person
here'' on impeachment issues, Hastings took to the House floor
Friday to introduce his own impeachment resolution _ against
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Starr has violated his oath of office and committed high
crimes and misdemeanors against the Constitution,'' said Hastings,
a staunch defender of President Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the good of the country, and the protection of the
Constitution and the rule of law, Mr. Starr must be called to
account and removed from his position.''
</P>
<P>
   As grounds for impeachment, Hastings cited leaks from Starr's
office, spending $40 million on ``an investigation that he knew
could not justify such extraordinary expenditures,'' and
embarrassing the United States ``before the international
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is in the air in Congress as the result of Starr's
charges that Clinton should be impeached for lying and obstruction
of justice in the cover-up of his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   If the House Judiciary Committee recommends impeachment,
Hastings and the other House members would vote on whether to
impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said he has not discussed impeachment with Clinton, nor
did he consult anyone in the White House before filing his
resolution that Starr should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think such a conversation will take place,'' he said.
Had one taken place last month, however, Hastings said he would
have advised Clinton not to appear before the Starr grand jury,
which he did Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are a high-profile person that may be charged with a crime
and you're going into a prosecutor's playhouse,'' Hastings said.
``I would have said that to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In October 1989, then-U.S. District Judge Alcee Hastings of
Miami was removed from the bench by a 69-26 vote in the Senate. He
had been nominated for the judgeship by President Jimmy Carter in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   His Senate conviction came two months after the House voted to
impeach him on charges participating in a 1981 scheme to lighten
the sentences of two racketeers in exchange for $150,000. Hastings
denied wrongdoing and, in fact, was acquitted of bribery charges in
a 1983 criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   When he looks back on his own impeachment, he calls to mind the
late heavyweight champion, Joe Louis. After every fight, regardless
of outcome, he would tell interviewers, ``Tell my ma I'm glad I
won.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my emotion,'' he said. ``I'm glad I won. Otherwise I
wouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, Hastings has cultivated a reputation as a careful,
thoughtful member who performs his duties without a trace of
bitterness toward the institution that expelled him from the bench.
``I'm a non-vengeful person,'' he told an interviewer in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings has mended fences with Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., a
34-year House veteran and senior Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee who spearheaded the House effort to have Hastings
impeached. After Hastings entered Congress, Conyers nominated him
to be second vice-chair of the Congressional Black Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said he hoped his Starr resolution would lead the House
to ``slow down a moment'' and make the impeachment .. I'm motivated
and driven by the fact that this process must be made to be fairer
than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm not talking about whether Bill Clinton has done
anything good, bad or indifferent. That will be judged. He will
have his disgrace and humiliation. But I will not sit idly by, and
you better believe I will tilt some windmills.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
