<HEADLINE>
ALL DEDICATED HACKERS, ARISE!
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Parenthetical material is by Dr. Bombay) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dr. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I appreciate the fact that you replied to
``oo'' like that. (Remember him, boys and girls? He was the barely
sentient slug who fancied himself a hacker. I'm still quaking in my
boots worrying about exactly when he'll make my speakers make rude
`ffwwaaaapppp!!' noises.) All over the place now, wannabe hackers
are replying in your aforementioned ``remedial English'' and
expecting some attention from it. (Actually, I think most of them
were too caught up fantasizing about Gillian Anderson to notice.)
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, there are sincere hackers out there. That group is
the youth and young adults of today. (I just wish you darned kids
would turn down that new-fangled record player.) I myself am a
sincere _ not wannabe _ hacker. Everything I know about hacking
I've taught myself. I didn't go to some Web site and have it all
spelled out for me. I didn't get a book with a packaged CD that has
all the hacking programs on it already. No. I, if you will, am a
geek. If I need to do something, I program it myself from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the exception: I, like my fellow hackers, have strict
codes, guidelines and rules just like the average person. It's what
we like to call the ``duh factor.'' We, as sincere hackers, are not
destructive without cause. (And who gets to pick the cause this
week? You? Zero Cool? Acid Burn? Lord Nikon?) Our sole purpose in
learning what we do, in perfecting the skills that we do, is a mere
defense. You and I both know that as time passes, our world becomes
more of a cyber-war than a gun war. I, along with my peers, am your
only defense in the act of an all-out attack on the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So to close, those of you out there who are the sincere hackers,
the ones that follow these codes and guidelines, thank you for your
dedication. However, the rest of you, and you know who you are,
please, PLEASE, go buy a book on machine code and talk to me again
when you do some sincere, nondestructive, true hacking. I pity the
disgrace you will feel when the whole world comes crashing in on
top of you. Go hackers!
</P>
<P>
   _ The Wizard
</P>
<P>
   DEAR WIZ: Don't waste your brain. The CIA already has that
cyber-war stuff taken care of. Go give Bill Gates a run for his
money instead. That's the ``real'' war. And lighten up while you're
at it. You're too young to be so cynical about the world. That's my
job.
</P>
<P>
   STUPID SOFTWARE TRICK: Proving that they can indeed maintain the
international lead in the increasingly vital field of time
waste-ology, Microsoft Excel 97 programmers labored tirelessly to
produce the following Easter egg, pausing only briefly to
capriciously change the Excel format, angering and disenfranchising
spreadsheet users the world over.
</P>
<P>
   Launch Excel 97 and press F5. Type in X97:L97 to jump to that
cell. Press Tab and let it go. Now, hold down Control and Shift
while left-clicking the Chart Wizard button on the toolbar (It's
the bar-chart-looking thingie to the left of the little globe).
</P>
<P>
   Surprise! A little flight simulator. Navigate with the mouse and
find the mountain on the edge of town with the scrolling list of
developers who have so much free time on their hands they won't see
the next generation of hackers coming.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. Right now, he wants
your stupid software tricks because he's getting really bored with
Quake II. He can be reached on Internet at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817) 390-7257.
His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
