<HEADLINE>
IN CLINTON DEFENSE, A LEGAL MINDSET GETS PART OF THE BLAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (Ideas) 
(Also moved in ``e'' category.) 
(lb) 
David Margolick is a contributing editor at Vanity Fair. 
 By DAVID MARGOLICK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a cascade of contrition, President Clinton is almost greedily
accepting responsibility for his present predicament. But the
finger-pointing in the Monica Lewinsky matter also goes in another
direction: toward Clinton's lawyers, who are being blamed for
failing to anticipate his problems, and then for making them worse.
</P>
<P>
   Privilege shrouds all discussions between the president and his
lawyers, making second-guessing hazardous. But authorities on legal
ethics and culture _ that is, lawyers who monitor other lawyers _
say the president has clearly received bad legal advice, reflecting
weaknesses found today among even sophisticated practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   These weaknesses, experts say, are both as timeless as the
inherent tensions between lawyers and powerful clients and as new
as the deterioration in how lawyers are trained.
</P>
<P>
   There is little reason to think Clinton was initially any more
candid with his lawyers, notably Robert Bennett and David Kendall,
than he was with his closest associates, his Cabinet or his family.
And by training and temperament, lawyers don't always press their
clients for the truth or try to learn the truth themselves,
especially when the client is the president.
</P>
<P>
   That has always been the case. But to some experts the
president's highly legalistic defense, using a tortured definition
of sex that has earned him great ridicule, stems from something
new: the training that elite lawyers are now likely to get, which
can blind them to what matters most.
</P>
<P>
   While the best and brightest have always marched off to Wall
Street-style law firms, the firms themselves have changed, largely
as result of a vastly more competitive marketplace. Increasingly
profit-oriented, less likely to have long-term relations with
clients, less concerned with inculcating values into young
associates, these firms are producing lawyers who are more
parochial, with dulled ethical and political instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawyering business really has kind of shrunk from a
profession of general counselors and advisers to the notion of a
very narrow technical specialty in which what the lawyer does is
simply advise on the available legal strategy,'' said Robert
Gordon, a legal historian at Yale Law School. As a result, Gordon
said, lawyers are more likely to focus on minutiae than on the
larger issues usually involved in highly charged political cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get very little sense from Bennett or Kendall that what is
at issue is a president, his capacity to govern, his place in
history,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   To William Simon of Stanford Law School, the very lack of
perspective for which Clinton's lawyers have been faulted applies
even more strongly to the unrelenting independent counsel, Kenneth
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put lawyers in charge of a moral crusade, you risk
that they'll handle it without any sense of proportionality,
largely because it's not part of their makeup,'' he said. ``We try
to teach lawyers to make value judgments, to weigh principles, but
the professional culture of technicality and literalism is even
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Legally speaking, it was Paula Jones who begat Monica Lewinsky;
perhaps the most fateful decision by Clinton and his lawyers was
not to settle Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment suit. Strictly as a
legal proposition, the case was extremely weak, and sure enough,
Bennett's elaborate, powerful arguments persuaded a federal judge
(and a Republican) to throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   But in the unique context of presidential politics, what
mattered most was not the fate of Mrs. Jones' case but what her
lawyers learned along the way. Bennett's approach, like that of
many lawyers, reflected great faith in precedent, logic and the
primacy of winning in court _ safe assumptions in many cases but
not in so politically charged a suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legal education and legal culture make victory in court the
only victory,'' said Stephen Gillers of New York University Law
School. ``But the Jones-Clinton case was only partly about what
will happen in court, and mostly about the survival and reputation
of the president. So it became dangerous to let lawyers control the
progress of the case. People unencumbered by legal training and
experience might have chosen differently.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Arthur Liman, in his memoir, ``Lawyer: A Life of Counsel and
Controversy'' (Public Affairs, 1998), makes a similar criticism of
Starr, comparing him to other prosecutors who have wrongly ``tried
to make criminal cases out of political offenses.'' Liman himself,
however, was faulted as being overly legalistic in the Iran-contra
hearings, letting Oliver North outmaneuver him in the court of
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Also endemic, arguably, was the way in which both Bennett and
Kendall apparently reacted to Clinton's lies about his relationship
to Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   That clients lie to their lawyers is nothing new. ``The first
reaction of every white-collar client is not to tell the whole
truth and nothing but the truth,'' said Kenneth Mann, a law
professor at Tel Aviv University and author of a study on American
lawyers who represent white-collar criminal defendants.
</P>
<P>
   And lawyers are not ethically bound to ferret those lies out.
``I never ask a client whether he did it or not,'' Alan Dershowitz
of Harvard Law School once said. ``I don't want the client to feel
that he has to start his relationship with me by lying.''
</P>
<P>
   While the American Bar Association has condemned the practice of
avoiding knowledge, no lawyer has ever been sanctioned for doing
so. So lawyers can look the other way. But what is ethically
tolerable is not always tactically wise. ``About half of the
practice of a decent lawyer is telling would-be clients they are
damned fools and should stop,'' Elihu Root, a prominent New York
lawyer who went on to become secretary of state, once said.
</P>
<P>
   Tipped off by the Linda Tripp tapes, by questions from the Jones
lawyers and by Clinton's own evasiveness, Bennett and Kendall could
well have surmised that his denials were implausible. Had they any
doubts, a review of the very records Starr was poring over _ phone
logs, White House records, Secret Service documents _ could have
confirmed their suspicions. The lawyers then could have questioned
Clinton aggressively and perhaps persuaded him to change his
answers before perjury charges could attach.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took months to recant, suggesting that nothing of the
sort ever occurred. More likely, the lawyers questioned him, heard
him reiterate his denials, and then moved on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers too often submit to demanding and powerful clients,''
said Gillers, who examines Clinton's counsel in the coming issue of
American Lawyer magazine. ``To call the president a fool or to tell
him he's acting like an ass is no easy thing. But it's precisely
when you represent a president that you have to be tough and blunt
and shake him up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that Clinton's lawyers _ or today's crop of
lawyers _ are deficient. Monroe Freedman of Hofstra Law School, a
pioneer in the field of legal ethics, said Clinton's high-caliber
counsel surely pushed him as far as they could. Nor, he said, were
contemporary lawyers necessarily any less public-spirited and
worldly, or yesterday's lawyers any more enlightened, as Gordon
contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can he think that the lawyers who represented the robber
barons were not pulling hypertechnical stuff?'' Freedman asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
