<HEADLINE>
RESERVATIONIST TO THE STARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 20) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eager for an invitation to a private party at Le
Cirque 2000?
</P>
<P>
   Need dinner reservations for eight at Bond Street in two hours?
</P>
<P>
   Think it might be fun to fly to London for the night, stay at
the Lanesborough hotel, even though it's already booked up, and
bring six friends to Nobu London because it is your birthday?
</P>
<P>
   If so, then you might want to consider becoming a client of Bill
Fischer, a travel agent extraordinary, who specializes in getting
people into sold-out hotels, onto overbooked flights and into
restaurants with unlisted phone numbers. He satisfied all three
requests during a typical day last Monday, for clients who pay
$10,000 solely to get him to answer their calls.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the package tours Fischer leads for the rich
and social to resorts that are hot, hot, hot _ sort of Carnival
Cruises for the Forbes 400.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, during the Cannes Film Festival, he escorted four
clients to the Hotel du Cap in Cap d'Antibes, where they could rub
elbows with Winona Ryder, Johnny Depp, Harvey Weinstein and other
Hollywood folk who made the cash-only, super-private hotel their
base.
</P>
<P>
   Last Christmas, he chartered a private jet to St. Bart's for 70
people, including the art dealer Mary Boone and the family of
Michael Lynne, the head of New Line Cinema. He arranged rooms for
14 days in the Isle de France hotel, which normally sells out a
year in advance. During the day, Fischer could be seen on the beach
behind the hotel, asking about hot parties to which he could escort
members of his group.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Boone, who could probably get into any party she cared to on
her own, thank you, said that the real value of Fischer Travel,
Fischer's 18-person agency, is its ability to handle last-minute
reservations and travel emergencies. ``They can get you on a seat
on a flight to St. Bart's when you decide on Dec. 10 you want to go
for Christmas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a week before her son, Max, 11, was supposed to go
to Venice, Ms. Boone realized that his passport had expired. Max
was at sleep-away camp in Beckett, Mass. Fischer Travel arranged
for a camp counselor to drive Max to Lenox, Mass., pose for a
passport picture, have the photo sent by Federal Express to New
York and, through contacts at the passport office, have a new
passport issued in 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The cost? ``I don't know,'' Ms. Boone said. That's the attitude
Fischer likes. With a client list of 400 and with what he says is a
waiting list to join it, Fischer decided a year and a half ago to
charge a fee to enroll as a client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's $10,000 to say hello to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fee is nonrefundable and is not applied to tickets,
reservations or services. It can be a one-time fee or an annual
fee, depending on how demanding a client is. If potential clients
balk at the fee, Fischer said, he decides right away not to take
them on. ``If they are going to haggle over the fee, then they are
going to haggle over the rates of hotels and flights,'' he said
with an air of distaste.
</P>
<P>
   His attitude is that he will do whatever it takes to meet
clients' needs, but he expects them to pay whatever they are
billed, virtually no questions asked. ``They are so rich, what's 10
or 20 thousand to them,'' he said. A source of pride at his agency
is that the phone number is unlisted. And he makes no apologies for
his policy requiring potential clients to present two or three
references.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like joining a country club,'' he said. ``We have to
accept you.''
</P>
<P>
   Though such practices seem to imply breathtaking hubris,
inviting disbelief about Fischer's business claims, a proffered
list of his blue-chip clients checked out: Diane Sawyer; Martin
Scorsese; Calvin Klein; Jonathan Tisch, the hotelier; Bruce
Wasserstein, the financier; Sanford Weill, the Travelers Group
chairman. Spokesmen for all these individuals said they used
Fischer's services.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Schwarzman, the president and chief executive of the
Blackstone Group, the private investment bank, who is a client,
said, ``Bill is a unique resource and regularly does the
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   When Schwarzman's wife, Christine Hearst, was in Paris recently
and decided at the last minute she wanted to take her daughter,
Janet, to Jules Verne, the popular restaurant on the Eiffel Tower,
Fischer went into action. ``You need six months' advance
reservation,'' he said. ``She gave me six minutes.'' After 10
trans-Atlantic telephone calls, he got mother and daughter a table
at Jules Verne for Janet's 10th birthday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-AGENT-ART-$ADV     09-18 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AGENT-ART-$ADV20-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: 10th birthday. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fischer, who grew up in Brooklyn, started in the travel business
more than a quarter-century ago, selling $199 packages to Aruba.
Since then, he said, he has flown a client's dog to Los Angeles
alone so the animal could attend dog camp while the owner went to
Europe, and he got an emergency face-lift appointment for a client.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dancing stock market and a White House in crisis,
Fischer said his business has felt nary an economic ripple. ``All
I've noticed is that no one asked me to get them into the lunch
Denise Rich had for President Clinton in her apartment today,'' he
said on Monday from his midtown offices on Third Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer says he gets his clients impossible reservations and
unavailable seats by persistence and prodigious networking. He
recounts how he once got clients into a small, sold-out hotel in
Gstaad, Switzerland, by telephoning twice a day for three months,
until a room finally opened up. A tan, fit man of 62, he deals with
the stress by popping 50 vitamin pills a day. But many employees _
who include a daughter, Stacy Fischer, 36, and 16 others _ do not
handle it as well, and staff turnover is high.
</P>
<P>
   On the phone to a reservations agent, Fischer is not above
dropping the names of his famous clients, implying that if a hotel
can accommodate client X, then a Calvin Klein or a Diane Sawyer
might be steered there in the near future. One former client,
however, gave a different explanation for Fischer's success: he
overpays enormously for hotel rooms, and tips the staff of hot
restaurants and hotels extravagantly, passing the costs back to his
too-rich-to-complain clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk into a hotel and they know he sent you, they
treat you very well _ it's like when a sugar daddy walks in and
spreads the money around,'' said the former client, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. He said he ceased using Fischer several
years ago because he thought he was being gouged. ``He charges off
the charts for everything,'' the former client said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the claim that he gets results by lavishly
greasing palms, Fischer said: ``Absolutely not. We send them
clients and they like who we send. I show them my list; it's a
`Who's Who' list. We're sending the kind of people who are not
going to complain and will pay for anything. The hotels want our
clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said that if a couple called last Thursday wanting to
fly by Concorde to Paris for the weekend, spend two nights at the
Ritz and dine at Alain Ducasse, Fischer Travel would charge $30,000
to $40,000, not including dinner.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a reporter who tried to book the trip directly was
quoted by Air France a fare of $21,824 for two on the Concorde.
Both the Ritz and Alain Ducasse said they were booked solid for a
month.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the daughter of one of Fischer's famous
clients asked the agency to have her father's frequent-flier miles
switched to her account, and to use them to make free reservations
for her to Europe. Her father's office received a bill for $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made one phone call for me,'' said the daughter, who was
furious and declined to be named, to protect her family's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer's response to all questions about billing is to shrug.
``Look, we charge for our services,'' he said. ``That's it. My
clients can afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3350 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-OSNOS-ART     09-18 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-OSNOS-ART-$ADV20-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRANGE PLACE FOR A PAGE TURNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20.)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
(js) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By rather brief tradition, the literature of choice
at the year-old Public Affairs publishing house started by the
Random House refugee Peter Osnos is intelligent and reflective _
serious nonfiction scorned by conglomerates seeking best-seller
profits.
</P>
<P>
   So how is it that Osnos' leading title on his debut list this
fall is a breast-heaving 421-page tale of unrequited love, of a
tormented affair of a young woman scorned and a married man
scarred, of an impossible relationship characterized by
bodice-ripper sentiments and romance-book regrets? A book with
lines like: I ``cannot ignore what we have shared together. I don't
care what you say, but if you were 100 percent fulfilled in your
marriage I never would have seen that raw, intense sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect no grainy photographs for your $10 purchase, but there's
not much else left to the imagination in ``The Starr Report'' _
That Book _ which Public Affairs started shipping before dawn on
Monday with a dignified crimson-and-gray cover and the complete
text of the report of the Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth
Starr, chronicling President Clinton's relationship with the former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky. Also contained inside is the
White House rebuttal and early news articles from The Washington
Post about the steamy government document, which makes ``The Valley
of the Dolls'' read like a telephone book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know that when we chose Public Affairs for this
company's name that we literally meant public affairs, but that's
the way it worked out,'' Osnos, 54, said dryly from the company's
headquarters _ spare, dorm-like offices that share the 18th floor
of the Fisk Building in midtown Manhattan with the nonliterati,
like Arista Dental and Dentogenic Studios.
</P>
<P>
   The company's maiden catalog does indeed boast serious books,
like Arthur L. Liman's posthumous memoir of his legal career and
the Iran-Contra investigation and Neil Baldwin's exploration of
Mexico and the myth of Quetzalcoatl, the principal god of the
Aztecs. But the company has printed far more copies of ``The Starr
Report'' than of any of the nine other titles, with 300,000 books
shipped on Monday, and Osnos is poised to gamble by printing still
more. ``We could print hundreds of thousands right now,'' Osnos
said. ``We still are going to print as conservatively as we can
because we don't know how long this is going to last.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, copies of ``The Starr Report'' are moving as if
they were Stephen King paperbacks _ and are a far better bargain
for Osnos than a blockbuster novel would be because his company can
publish the government document without paying advances to its
authors, subsidizing expensive book tours or sparring with agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sold out in Cincinnati, Denver, Paramus, Dallas and Las
Vegas,'' an exuberant Osnos marveled before bolting from his office
to meet with another company employee to debate how many more
copies to print. (To be sure, Public Affairs has at least two
competitors, which also report brisk sales of Starr's report _ a
$5.99, mass-market paperback from Simon &AMP; Schuster's Pocket Books
and a $9.99 trade paperback from a small California publisher,
Prima.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It's a rather odd state of public affairs for Osnos, a former
reporter and editor at The Washington Post who left Random House
two years ago as the publisher of its Times Books imprint. One of
the last books he published there was a slim political tome by
Clinton, which certainly failed to match the sales power or Oval
Office sizzle of ``The Starr Report.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was the publisher of Times Books _ once owned by The
New York Times Co. _ Osnos came to believe that the system for
publishing serious books was flawed and the audience for them too
limited to support standard author advances and corporate overhead.
It bothered him that ``Times Books was doing more and more consumer
reference books and crossword puzzles, and I wanted to do
public-affairs books,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he resigned to start his own company, and set about looking
for partners to share the costs of author contracts. ``PBS
Frontline'' signed on in return for exclusive rights to produce
documentaries tied to the books it helped underwrite. His plan also
attracted minority investors like the ABC News anchor Peter
Jennings and the former C-Span chairman Robert Rosencrans. It also
prompted Frank H. Pearl, a lawyer and chairman of the venture
capital firm Perseus Capital, to buy a majority interest and make
Public Affairs a part of his expanding publishing group, which also
includes Basic Books, a bastion of scholarly works, and
Counterpoint, a literary press.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Osnos has no qualms about making a publishing
debut with a government page turner of Oval Office romance and
footnotes that helpfully provide the definition of telephone sex
and Ms. Lewinsky's dry-cleaning habits _ or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not have a moment's doubt that a report by this special
counsel, recommending the impeachment of the president of the
United States, is a historic document,'' Osnos said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot think of anything more substantive,'' he added. ``Do
you think I should curl my lip at the president of the United
States? I'm not in the business of judging whether history is
elegant or not. History in this case is degrading.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Starr Report'' _ as The Book _ could have a significant
impact on the fledgling Public Affairs, letting it subsidize more
projects and ``change our sense of what is possible,'' Osnos said.
</P>
<P>
   But he is trying to remain cautious _ and practical. Is there a
sequel? Osnos is waiting for the release of Starr's next 2,000
pages of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
