<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'BRIEN HOPES NOT TO REPEAT DEBACLE OF LAST YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tom O'Brien's recollection of his first game as Boston
College coach was not very enjoyable. He shook his head as he
recalled the sloppiness that victimized BC in its 28-21
season-opening loss a year ago at Temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were forcing things, we had bad snaps on field goals,
penalties at crucial times _ both on offense and defense,'' he
said. ``It was just your typical nightmare for a first game.''
</P>
<P>
   When the undefeated Eagles (2-0 overall, 1-0 Big East) host the
winless Owls (0-2) in a conference home game Saturday at Alumni
Stadium, the last thing O'Brien will want is to relive his
nightmarish debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``They already had a game under their belt, so they had worked
their kinks out,'' O'Brien said, pointing out how Temple entered
last year's meeting with some game experience, though it came in a
34-14 loss at Western Michigan. ``But it took us a while to get
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, when Temple arrives in Chestnut Hill for
Saturday's conference matchup, the Owls will encounter a BC team
that has it going pretty well, offensively and defensively.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles followed up their season-opening 41-31 triumph at
Georgia Tech with another offensive show in a 41-14 romp over
Rutgers. They capitalized on a balanced attack that amassed 486
yards total offense and converted on seven of eight red-zone
opportunities, improving their overall red-zone efficiency to 93
percent (14 for 15).
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston College's a very good football team and they run the
ball extremely well,'' said Temple first-year coach Bobby Wallace,
whose team suffered a 35-28 loss to Akron, its second in a row to a
Mid-American Conference opponent. ``They have a great running back
(Mike Cloud) and a quarterback (Scott Mutryn) who does great things
with his running and throwing ability. The offensive line, it's
been documented how big and strong they are, and defensively,
Boston College's nose guard (Chris Hovan) and free safety (Pedro
Cirino) are great players.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to try and control them,'' he added. ``It will
be an interesting battle, especially with the free safety, because
the nature of our offense involves the free safety in stopping the
running game. It'll be interesting to see how that matchup comes
out.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's defense, which ranks third in the conference in total yield
(331.5 yards per game), will likely face its toughest test _
Temple's option offense, which boasts the nation's No. 4 rushing
attack (298.5 yards per game) and is led by 5-foot-11-inch,
195-pound junior quarterback Kevin Harvey of Paulsboro, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's nasty, he's good,'' said Cirino, who's from Jersey City,
N.J. ``He's the real deal, and I saw that firsthand when I played
against him in an all-star game in New Jersey. He holds state
records that I think will never be broken. He's a great player and
they're lucky to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirino is hoping BC can contain, if not stop, Harvey from
executing Temple's option, which sputtered when it came up short on
two critical scoring opportunities last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the ball inside the 10, and it was the fifth time in
two weeks that we've had the ball inside the 10-yard line and come
away with only two field goals,'' said Wallace. ``We've scored some
points other times, but it's very disturbing when you rush for 365
yards during the course of the game. Had we scored, it would've
made it 35-35 and we would've had a chance to get it into OT.
Defensively, we didn't stop their run, and that's going to be a big
problem for us this week against Boston College. You can't play
defense and at least be able to slow somebody down from running the
football.''
</P>
<P>
   The other interesting matchup will pit the conference's top two
rushers: Cloud (178.0 yards per game) and Temple's Stacey Mack
(108), who carried 16 times for 121 yards and scored the winning
touchdown on a 27-yard run in last year's triumph over the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily see it as a duel between us,'' said Cloud,
who had 201 all-purpose yards, including 156 rushing, and a pair of
TDs last week. ``I see it as a great opportunity for BC and the
whole program to come out with a third victory. If we can go 3-0,
it's going to be a great thing for the program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
