<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TURNS TO FOREIGN AFFAIRS TO DEFLECT DOMESTIC TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is plunging into international
summitry to tackle terrorism, communal warfare in the Balkans, the
nuclear arms race in South Asia and global economic problems as he
braces for repercussions from the release of his videotaped grand
jury testimony and fresh details of his sexual liaisons with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton heads to New York City late Sunday to dive into two days
of substantive diplomacy centered upon the annual opening of the
U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to address the General Assembly at 10:45
a.m. EDT Monday as the nation's attention focuses on the expected
telecast of his videotaped testimony before a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The video of Clinton's Aug. 17 testimony about his relationship
with the former White House intern, along with 2,800 pages of
supporting documents, should be released at 9 a.m. EDT Monday, said
House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   White House Deputy Press Secretary Barry Toiv said Clinton looks
forward to continuing to do his job in the face of the anticipated
furor over the videotaped testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has responsibilities abroad and he obviously has
responsibilities here at home, and he will continue to do both,''
Toiv said. ``He will continue to do the work that he was elected to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the four hours and 12 minutes of testimony ``will
not have an impact'' on Clinton's readiness to represent the nation
``with distinction'' at the United Nations, Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, Clinton's national security adviser,
said world leaders continue to voice support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want and expect the United States to lead,'' Berger said.
``They very much look to the president to lead _ and we intend to
continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger discouraged renegade foreign leaders such as Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein from trying to exploit Clinton's domestic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a grave mistake for any foreign leader or any
group to believe that if the United States' interests are
threatened, the United States will not respond in a firm and united
way,'' Berger declared. ``Anybody who made that calculation would
make a grave miscalculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants to devote his Sunday evening summit with Italian
Prime Minister Romano Prodi to refining western efforts to quell
ethnic violence in Albania and the Serbian province of Kosovo,
Berger said. Clinton and Prodi also are to discuss the stubborn
economic crisis in Russia, where President Boris Yeltsin has just
installed hard-liner Yevgeny Primikov as the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton would focus his address before the U.N.
General Assembly on persuading world leaders and diplomats that the
international community has ``common obligations'' to combat
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hoped to deflect international criticism _ particularly
from Islamic nations _ about last month's cruise missile attacks on
suspected terrorist targets in Afghanistan and Sudan. The attacks
were a response to terrorist bombings of the U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The ``fight against terrorism is not a clash of civilizations or
cultures,'' Berger said. ``The dividing line is between those who
practice, support and tolerate terror and those who understand that
terrorism is plain and simple murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then intensifies personal involvement in efforts to
defuse the nuclear arms race that flared between Pakistan and India
in May, when the neighboring countries traded tit-for-tat
underground nuclear explosions in a bid to obtain nuclear weapons
capability.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to use his first face-to-face meeting with
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to seek a commitment from the
Islamic nation to ease the arms race and open direct negotiations
with India over disputed territory in Kashmir. The land dispute has
triggered three wars in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott plans to press Indian
envoy Jaswant Singh to commit India to similar steps at a follow-up
meeting in New York on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton still hopes to add stops in
Pakistan and India to a long-scheduled trip to a pan-Pacific summit
in Malaysia in November _ if Pakistan and India reach agreement to
end their confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have discussed with the Indians and with the Pakistanis the
steps that we think need to be taken to put them back on track,''
Berger said Friday. ``I think there's been some movement, but I
think so far it's been insufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton leaves the hubbub of Manhattan Tuesday for the
Rockefeller family's sprawling country estate in Tarrytown, N.Y.,
where he will hold an emergency summit with Japan's new prime
minister, Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was forced to scrap a long-scheduled summit in late July
with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, who was forced to
resign by setbacks in parliamentary elections and the country's
economic stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that Clinton would press Obuchi to stimulate Japan's
$2.8 trillion economy.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's stubborn recession is ``a tremendous drag on the overall
Asian financial situation,'' Berger said, adding that the United
States ``cannot see a reversal of the general Asian financial
prospect without a significant upturn in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans to continue his focus on foreign affairs after his
return to Washignton late Tuesday. He is scheduled to award the
Congressional Gold Medal to South African President Nelson Mandela
at a ceremony on Capitol Hill Wednesday; meet with Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong later that day; and have a working lunch
with Saudi Arabian Crown Prince Abdallah bin Abd al-Aziz on
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
