r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMURTRY-HOMETOWN-960     09-18 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMURTRY-HOMETOWN-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARRY MCMURTRY'S HOMETOWN IS A LITTLE-KNOWN BUT QUAINT DESTINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCHER CITY, Texas _ Outsiders. City slickers. Tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Call me self-conscious, but I'm pretty sure that's what the
regulars were thinking when my husband and I walked into the
American Legion Hall, Post 198, on a recent Friday night. Every
head turned our way. Conversations paused. The bartender studied us
suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I'd done my homework on Archer City, a tiny outpost
120 miles from Fort Worth. Calls to two local establishments prior
to our trip indicated our best bet _ our only bet _ for
entertainment there on a Friday night was the American Legion Hall.
Unless we preferred the Dairy Queen.
</P>
<P>
   What the locals neglected to mention was that the Post 198 bar
was a ``members and guests only'' establishment, as a sign above
the tap clearly read. Several uncomfortable seconds passed before a
festive woman whom the bartender introduced as Buttons volunteered
her sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be my very special guests,'' she called, waving her
hands in the air and miraculously maintaining the inch-long ash at
the end of her cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we made our first friend in Archer City. Conversations
resumed, the jukebox dished out Stevie Ray Vaughan and bar manager
Carlyn Parrish offered us the Legion Hall tour _ from the 12-burner
stove where Legionnaires prepare Thanksgiving dinner for the needy
to photographs of former post commanders that decorate the dance
hall.
</P>
<P>
   Archer City, said Parrish, ``is the Bermuda Triangle of Texas.
Once you come here, you can't never leave.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it has turned out for Larry McMurtry, too. The
Pulitzer Prize-winning author graduated from Archer City High
School, spent years in the big city, and now resides in the town
that shaped him _ a town he's now reshaping.
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry, after all, initially plunked Archer City on the
cultural map in 1966 with his novel ``The Last Picture Show,'' a
poignant and somewhat dark chronicle of small-town life. Though
McMurtry called the town Thalia, Archer City folks recognized they
were clearly McMurtry's subjects, and some were less than pleased.
Five years later, director Peter Bogdanovich brought his cast and
crew here to film the movie version, changing the town's name to
Anarene. It didn't matter; Archer City was never the same.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the exposure (or maybe because of it; the film portrayal
of the town makes it look like one of the bleaker spots on earth),
tourists have bypassed this dusty North Texas outpost 25 miles
south of Wichita Falls. But McMurtry is again drawing the attention
of literati to quirky Archer City, this time with his 10-year-old
used-book operation, which in recent years has grown to fill four
scattered storefronts in the sleepy town square.
</P>
<P>
   Booked Up Inc., in turn, has spawned a mini-but-promising
tourist trade: one hotel, one restaurant, one brand-new
bed-and-breakfast in the former Archer Hospital. The Archer County
News heralded the opening of the Lonesome Dove Inn with a
front-page story.
</P>
<P>
   The bookstores house 150,000-200,000 volumes as valuable as a
first edition of William Faulkner's ``The Sound and the Fury''
($2,500), a publisher's galley proof of ``Catch-22'' ($850), and
facsimiles of Shakespeare's original folios ($175). First-edition
copies of ``Lonesome Dove'' sell for $350, but the budget-minded
can buy it in paperback for $5.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the books we looked at cost between $8 and $50, such as
an illustrated collection of Edgar Allan Poe short stories ($30).
The inventory that Booked Up rejects goes to places like Half Price
Books.
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry doesn't own Booked Up in the sense that Arnold
Schwarzenegger and Bruce Willis own Planet Hollywood, lending their
star status to the venture and reaping the profits. McMurtry
actually owns and works at Booked Up, sometimes seven days a week,
parking a rented white Cadillac outside a storefront and getting
lunch at the Dairy Queen.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend before our current adventure, we were in Archer City
for the afternoon and caught McMurtry shelving books in Booked Up
No. 3. We elbowed each other and tried to look nonchalant. Should
we ask for an autograph? No, too tacky. Should we say hello? No, he
looks absorbed in his work. Besides, we had heard McMurtry could be
a tad grumpy.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, we returned for a night's stay at the Lonesome
Dove Inn, opened in August by sisters and owners Mary Slack Webb
and Ceil Cleveland (McMurtry has no financial stake in the
business). In 1978, the former hospital was converted to a home,
and it still retains a few disco-era touches like shag carpeting.
Webb, who lives at the inn, and Cleveland, who lives in New York,
have redecorated with antiques and lace bedspreads.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
