<HEADER>
A3379 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCMURTRY-HOMETOWN-2nd     09-18 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMURTRY-HOMETOWN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
ARCHER CITY, Texas: lace bedspreads. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Webb showed us the seven guest rooms, each named for a McMurtry
novel, and asked us to select one (it was a little lonesome at the
inn that night). We chose ``The Evening Star'' chamber for its
Indonesian teak bed frame and proximity to the shared upstairs
bathroom. The $90 charge included breakfast the next morning; for
$6 a person, Webb will pack guests a lunch, too.
</P>
<P>
   A former schoolteacher in North Texas, Webb moved back to Archer
City to be near her 90-year-old father. She, her two brothers and
sister Ceil were childhood friends of McMurtry, who dedicated his
novel ``Anything for Billy'' to their mother, Margaret Ellen Slack.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks say McMurtry modeled the Jacy character in ``The Last
Picture Show'' after Ceil, who followed up by writing a nonfiction
book, ``Whatever Happened to Jacy Farrow?'' about growing up in
Archer City. McMurtry displays it prominently at Booked Up No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Webb is a treasure trove of McMurtry anecdotes, and upon our
arrival launched into several about the loquacious preteen McMurtry
_ like the times he'd sleep over in her brothers' bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Ceil and I were in the room next door, but we could
just hear him droning on and on all night with these wild tales
he'd be making up as he went along. And the boys would be fast
asleep and he'd still be talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories of the famous picture show loom large here, as well.
Scrub brush has consumed the carcass of the Royal Theater, where
Parrish remembers seeing films for 13 cents. But groundbreaking on
an ambitious restoration project is scheduled for November. Larry
has given his blessing to that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, Webb made breakfast and we plotted our day
over eggs and biscuits. We'd hit the bookstore after a tour of the
museum and lunch at the tearoom.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer County Museum used to be the Archer County Jail,
until Jack Lofton moved his collection of memorabilia, archaeology
and antiques from the courthouse to this 3-story relic. When we
arrived, caretaker Dolores Cox and her mother, Doris Day Hohhertz,
were playing canasta in the air-conditioned front room.
</P>
<P>
   We were the only visitors, and Dolores was happy to give us the
tour, from the rheumatism machine to the circa 1900 bustier. On a
dresser was a hand-colored photograph of a stern couple. The
caption read, ``Captured by the Indians.'' Dolores wasn't sure if
it was the couple or the photograph that the Indians caught.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton, a prolific amateur archaeologist, has reconfigured
prehistoric lizards with bones found in the area. Dolores pointed
out the 250 million-year-old dimetrodon in a locked glass-top case.
Another case holds curtains from the Royal Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could spend all week here and never see it all,'' Dolores
correctly pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   We lunched at the Cottage Tea Room, an antiques shop and dining
establishment open 11:30 a.m. to 2 p.m. Tuesday through Friday and
by reservation on Saturdays. Harold and Bertie Beekman opened the
place eight years ago and live next door. She cooks; he seats,
serves and fills the water glasses on cue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My chicken breast and chocolate pie put me on the map,''
Bertie told us. The homestyle roast beef platter came with stuffing
and gravy and carrots coated in brown sugar; it was like an early
Thanksgiving dinner (for $7.95 including dessert). We each finished
with a piece of the famous chocolate pie and desperately needed a
nap by the time we left.
</P>
<P>
   But the bookstore beckoned, and McMurtry was hardly difficult to
find. He was sitting at the round wooden table in the front room of
Booked Up No. 1, sipping from a foam Dairy Queen cup. He wore jeans
and a taupe polo-style shirt with a Dr Pepper logo on the sleeve,
and eyeglasses with heavy black frames. His gray hair was slightly
tousled, and, for the record, he didn't look grumpy at all.
</P>
<P>
   After a bit of small talk, my star-struck spouse asked McMurtry
to autograph his copy of ``Lonesome Dove,'' which he was happy to
do (for us and the couple who requested a signature right after we
did). We spent the rest of the afternoon browsing and occasionally
passing McMurtry in the aisles. We even bumped into him back at the
inn, where he was helping move a friend's luggage into the ``Terms
of Endearment'' suite. He promised Webb he'd bring over videos of
the miniseries and movies based on his books so she could dub them
and have them for her guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have felt like I've left, particularly,'' McMurtry had
said earlier of his boyhood home.
</P>
<P>
   Archer City seems content to have McMurtry back, too.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
