<HEADER>
A3380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REDACTIONS19-     09-18 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REDACTIONS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REDACTIONS WON'T GIVE MATERIALS A 'PG' RATING
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite scores of deletions made by the House
Judiciary Committee, the 2,800 pages of evidence compiled by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr it plans to release Monday will
still be rated XXX.
</P>
<P>
   Although some ``redactions'' deleted explicit sexual material,
most dealt with privacy issues, such as names or phone numbers of
people mentioned incidentally in the report. When Democrats sought
to excise more graphic details, they were outvoted by the
Republican majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a general view among the Democrats not to reveal
anything, and there was a general view among Republicans to reveal
as much as possible consistent with responsible redactions to
protect people whose names and vital statistics and involvement in
this was very peripheral,'' said Committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
</P>
<P>
   R-Ill. ``We agreed on 120 (redactions) and I think there were
about 20 we didn't agree on.''
</P>
<P>
   The disagreements came over sexual details, said Rep. John
Conyers, D-Mi., the ranking minority member. He described some of
the newly released material as ``sexually explicit,'' ``obscene''
and ``offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Jerry Nadler, D-N.Y., said that three items
sexual in nature that Democrat and Republican staff counsels had
agreed to delete were reinstated for release by the committee's
Republican majority. He said the Democratic staff sought 27 other
redactions of sexually explicit passages, but were turned down by
the GOP staff.
</P>
<P>
   In defending their votes, Republican members insisted they were
carrying out the mandate of the full House, which voted last week
to release all of Starr's materials by Sept. 28, subject to review
by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would actually prefer that we be able to sanitize this thing
before it gets too much into the public, but our House colleagues
said no,'' said Rep. Lindsay Graham, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view was to get out as much information as possible,'' said
Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., explaining that protecting the privacy of
innocent people was the main grounds for the redactions he
supported.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., said members from both parties
readily agreed to redact material ``unrelated to the independent
counsel's investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An example of that could be in any tape-recorded conversations
between parties, they may have, in gossipy chatter, mentioned the
name of a co-worker in an unflattering light,'' he explained.
``That clearly is something that doesn't belong in the public
domain, and we don't want to see innocent people held up to
ridicule in church.''
</P>
<P>
   As raunchy as the released materials are, the evidence would
have been more graphic without redactions. The original Starr
report was ``PG'' compared to this material referred to in the
footnotes, some committee members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``America, you may think you got the details. You did not get
the details at all,'' said Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a good-faith effort was made to redact the most
salacious matter, with one or two exceptions,'' said Rep. Lamar
Smith, R-Texas. ``These exceptions were necessary because they were
directly relevant to allegations in the Starr report.''
</P>
<P>
   One of these exceptions involves Monica Lewinsky's testimony
about a sex act with President Clinton that involved a cigar, said
Smith. That was deemed necessary because Clinton has so narrowly
defined his concept of sexual relations, the congressman said.
</P>
<P>
   The list of redacted materials filled 10 pages, said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
