<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMLOCK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING AN UNDYING ISSUE: RIGHT TO DIE  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Good arguments can last awhile. This one is thousands
of years old.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Gerster, M.D., and John Westover, Ph.D., carry the
argument today. They have argued in the halls of the Arizona
Legislature, in the halls of Congress and through their
organizations' attorneys in the halls of the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of this dispute, which traces back through the mists
of history to Socrates and Hippocrates: the right to end one's own
life.
</P>
<P>
   Gerster, a Scottsdale internal medicine physician, was the
national president of her side of the argument. Westover of Tucson,
a retired Army officer and military historian, was the national
president of his side.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic asked them to meet again to engage the
issue so our readers can enjoy champion soul wrestling over one of
the great issues of the human condition. The following dialogue is
a compilation of remarks made face to face and in follow-up
comments. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: ``I think over the years there has been a cheapening of
human life,'' says Gerster, chairwoman of the anti-abortion Arizona
Right to Life and the past president of National Right to Life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think human life means as much anymore. You can see it
in children killing children and mass suicide. I don't think people
are concerned about their neighbors. I don't think people are
concerned about members of their own family. I don't think we are a
caring people anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Prolonging life _ quality life _ has become central to the
philosophy of this doctor, in practice now for 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   She lost an infant son to pneumonia, a grandfather to suicide, a
mother last year to cancer. She isn't in a mood to easily give
anyone else up to death. Anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: ``I get annoyed with people who are so sure that
somebody wants to take what little money I have away from me. I
just don't feel that way, and I don't worry about my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Westover, 80, has heard the argument about people being rushed
into premature death many times before. He is a past national
president of the Hemlock Society, which advocates people's right to
die as they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: But you have a good family. What about other families?
A few years ago I had a patient who had a very treatable illness
and she was all for the treatment. Then she came in with her only
son and a daughter-in-law from hell. The daughter-in-law said,
``Who's going to take you to the oncologist all the time? Who is
going to do that? If you get sick, who's going to lift you? I can't
do any lifting. I don't have any time to drive you! '' It was the
most withering moment. I saw this woman shrink and say, ``I guess
not. I guess I won't have the treatment.'' That is the sort of
thing I see.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: If some families have problems, should that prevent me
from having what I need at the end of my life? Even if there are
some abuses _ and there will be abuses _ do they negate the basic
rights of individuals?
</P>
<P>
   We are coming to a greater respect for the individual and their
right to make decisions for themselves. We have gotten to the point
where you may stop a medical procedure, stop rescue workers from
coming in and breaking the bones of the elderly with unwanted
resuscitation. We are making progress, and it is directed toward
individual rights and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: You already have rights. You have the right to be
hospitalized or not; the right to get rid of your doctor; the right
to request or refuse treatment. But you don't have the right to
have someone else kill you. Suicide is the easiest thing in the
world; you don't have to commission someone else to kill you. My
grandfather did the same type of killing that Kevorkian does: he
went into the garage, turned on the motor of his car and killed
himself.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors shouldn't be killers. Doctors should be healers.
Physician-assisted suicide, terminal sedation are all perversions
of medicine. Many physicians have tolerated third-party intrusion
and have allowed financial considerations above the life of a
patient.
</P>
<P>
   I mean the HMOs. The fact that you, as a doctor, no longer feel
responsible to your patient, but to the HMO. The HMO dictates when
you can see a specialist _ if you can see a specialist, when you
can have a mammogram, when you can see an oncologist. Woody Allen
once said, ``Death is a great way to save money.'' I'm afraid this
idea has pervaded the era of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: But in many instances the effect (of the medical
system) is to drag out the dying process _ lengthening death. The
fact that more people are going into hospice these days is good,
but in too many cases they go in within hours or days of dying.
That says to me that the doctors aren't letting go. Should
treatments continue when it is futile? I know of a 90-year-old man
dying of cancer who had a pacemaker installed. That's someone
wanting money.
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: Today, dying is less painful and it should be less
painful. It should be a time of reconciliation for the family.
Patients should be pain-free, which is within our capabilities.
Many doctors are woefully inadequate in this, but the technology is
out there.
</P>
<P>
   We have always had morphine. But there are advances in the ways
it can be introduced, (like with) morphine pumps implanted in the
body. Instead of destroying life we should destroy the conditions
that make death intolerable. When my mother died a year ago, we did
everything we could. In the end, she had no pain.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: In the transcripts of that End of Life Commission, I
read that there are 8 million people with cancer and 50 percent are
going to die in serious pain.
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: Unless they get good pain relief treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: But that kind of treatment is so rare.
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: Only 10 percent require higher technology. Many of the
90 percent are dying in pain needlessly because doctors don't
understand how to treat them with oral medications.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: But there are still some patients that cannot be made
pain-free short of putting them into unconsciousness. Isn't that
correct?
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: I would say that 99 percent of pain could be
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: Most individuals, if they were assured that their pain
would be controlled, would not request an immediate end of life. We
are finding in Oregon and California and elsewhere that our Hemlock
members who have prescription drugs they know could kill them don't
use them. But having those drugs makes them feel that they are in
control, in case the pain became more than they could bear. But
they should have the right to be in control.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Gerster was asked if there are any cases where she
would see the value of physician-assisted suicide (where the
patient takes a pill or pulls a switch provided by a physician), or
terminal sedation (where the patient is fully sedated while such
life supports as food and water are withdrawn). (endital)
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: As I see it, terminal sedation is homicide. Some
doctors are using terminal sedation with people who have no pain.
It has slipped up on us very quietly. It's covert. At least with
physician-assisted suicide, people know what they are getting into.
</P>
<P>
   I had a patient recently who was concerned because her
father-in-law had been told he probably had six months to live. He
had mild pain but it was well controlled. Suddenly they started the
I.V. and he became sleepy. The next day when family members voiced
their concern about him, they were told that they were making him
comfortable. ``You agreed to make him comfortable, right? '' they
were asked. The next morning he was dead. It was only 36 hours
after the sedation began. I think this is happening more often.
When you start misinterpreting the law, as we are seeing happen
now, it can become very dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: As a matter of fact, terminal sedation is recognized
by the AMA isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: Not the inappropriate use of it. And this is something
really new in the way it's being used.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: The Supreme Court recognized it as appropriate for
relief of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: It is being used as an excuse to allow a person to die
very quickly. The terminally ill and chronically ill are unwanted,
expensive people. The drains on some of their families are
emotional and financial. No matter how much they might want to
live, they can be coerced.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are misdiagnoses. The ``Archives of Internal
Medicine'' this year reported that autopsies reveal significant
misdiagnosis in a third of cases. That can put someone on the fast
track to death.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon, 70 percent of members of minority groups voted
against the physician-assisted suicide referendum. And among those
over 65 _ the people who would be most affected by it _ 63 percent
voted against it. The bill was popular among 30- and 40-year-olds
who felt invulnerable and probably sick and tired of caring for
their parents. The older people and minorities voted against
physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: In Arizona, most of our Hemlock Society members are
over 65, well-educated with above-average incomes. We are talking
about mature adults who are near the end of life and they want to
end it on their terms. We believe this is the correct thing _ they
should be allowed to do it. They are not injuring anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: I think people who don't want to live are by and large
depressed and should be treated for that. I think patients want to
be pain free and alert at the end. And this is absolutely
attainable.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: Pain is not always the issue. There are people who
want to end life. When they are terminal they want to speed the
process. They want to die on their terms and it is their right.
They should have assistance. Why shouldn't a doctor help?
</P>
<P>
   The greatest gulf between us is our attitude toward death. As a
physician, you see death mainly in medical terms. I see it more in
its societal and personal terms. Of course, you recognize the
impact of death on the family and community, but less on the
individual whose life is ending. I think it is the terminally ill
person's wishes which should be paramount.
</P>
<P>
   Pain management doesn't address suffering, severe dependence,
prolonged waiting and the financial drain, which is occasioned by
the terminal illness.
</P>
<P>
   And in the final analysis, whose life is it? If a person has
reason to believe the six-month judgment is correct, and if they
want to shorten the period, I would see no reason why they
shouldn't have that right. It is the availability of a gentle,
dignified death which Hemlock members wish as a right for
themselves and for others.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) How will the issue shape up in the coming Arizona
legislative session? (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: I think the right-to-life movement better get
legislation out there on the state level. I would like to see
legislation on physician education on pain relief, education of the
public that hospices exist and what care they are entitled to, and
guidelines on pain relief. I would like to see more of an
educational bill that reiterates what already is available.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: I have just reviewed a grant proposal submitted by the
Governor's Advisory Commission on End-of-Life Issues that looks
like a good proposal. What happens with that will influence
Hemlock's actions in the coming year in Arizona. We are cautious
though, as similar projects in other states have shown zero
improvement in end-of-life patient care. We aren't going to push
this coming year. Maybe in 2000 or 2002 if things don't work out
right, we would consider putting an initiative on the ballot, a
measure that would give people choice. One that will allow
terminally ill patients, with control, to get a prescription,
similar to what they have in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   What are your thoughts about your own death?
</P>
<P>
   Gerster: I would like to have my family around me. I'd like time
to try to mend fences and have reconciliations. I'd like to be
alert and pain free, which is my right and easily attainable today.
I'd like to make peace with my God. I'd like to live as long and as
fully as I possibly can.
</P>
<P>
   Westover: My mother's family all came down with something
equivalent to Alzheimer's and had long, slow declines. I watched my
mother, who had been a very active, very artistic, very happy woman
go through years of decline. When Derek Humphrey announced the
formation of the Hemlock Society in 1980, I said, ``That is for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   My oldest brother reached up to a cabinet and dropped dead. That
was about as painless as you could possibly go. My next older
brother went through five years of medical treatment and he died
with some pain. I am not a soldier who wants to be shot on the
battlefield. I think a painless, easy-going death _ the soprano
hits the last high C and then out. I don't mind dying, but when I
do, I want it to be while my dignity is intact. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
