<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Editors: Please note correct spelling of KINSTON, N.C., in
paragraph 20 
 
ROBERTSON URGES REPUBLICANS TO FORGE AHEAD WITH IMPEACHMENT
PROCEEDINGS 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans should shed their
timidity and forge ahead with impeachment proceedings against
President Clinton, Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson told
his followers Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are watching the office ennobled by Washington, Jefferson
and Lincoln become the playpen for the sexual freedom of the poster
child of the 1960s,'' Robertson told the gathering of the nation's
largest and arguably most influential group of conservative
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition, which has long been highly critical of
Clinton and the Democrats, has clearly been energized by the
president's problems, believing the scandal will push moral issues
to the forefront in the upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, mindful of polls showing fundamentalist Christians
more likely to vote, are paying attention to this constituency. A
number of top congressional leaders, including House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., and House Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
addressed the Coalition but largely sidestepped the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson played directly to the group's visceral dislike of
the president, saying Clinton had ``mocked, demeaned, belittled,
and lied'' to America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House located at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue is not Little
Rock on the Potomac. This is the people's house. As landlord of our
house it is time to say his lease is expired,'' said Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   But Robertson said resignation was not a sufficient way to get
Clinton out of the White House. He said justice could only be
served if Congress went ahead with impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``While resignation might be easier for America, it's not better
for America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson also chided some top congressional Republicans for not
being aggressive enough in moving against the president, accusing
them of ``sitting in the foxhole of political safety.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Robertson's scathing criticism was not enough for some
of those in attendance. He elicited scattered boos when he said
``we must be the first to forgive Bill Clinton the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Robertson compared Clinton unfavorably to predecessors
in the White House he did not mention that some of them had their
own scandals. Jefferson, whom Robertson said had ennobled the
presidency, was attacked during his tenure in office for having an
affair with his black slave.
</P>
<P>
   GOP congressional leaders maintained their policy of not
commenting directly about the president in regard to his affair
with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lott urged members to defeat Democratic senators who had refused
to vote to override President Clinton's veto on a bill banning
late- term abortion. On Friday the Senate fell three votes short of
overriding that veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year that we can nail down a solid, pro-family,
pro-life majority in the United States Senate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich briefly referred to the scandal saying, ``We in the
House will do our duty. We won't do an inch more than our duty for
partisanship, and we won't do an an inch less than our duty out of
intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Republican also defended House Judiciary Chairman
Henry Hyde, R-Ill, who this week acknowledged having an adulterous
affair 30 years ago after a liberal Internet magazine, Salon,
reported about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Henry's case, it's human and it's personal and he is a
decent, wonderful man and many of you have known him over the
years,'' said Gingrich, who urged the crowd to ``drop him a little
note and let him know that you share his pain and that you're sorry
that doing his duty leads to that kind of treatment by the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich and other Republicans have accused the White House of
leaking information about Hyde's affair to news organization and
have asked the FBI to investigate. However, Salon editors have
denied that the White House supplied them with the information, and
Republicans have so far failed to come up with evidence linking the
Clinton administration to the story.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who attended the meeting, seemed more willing to
forgive Hyde's affair than the president's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong is wrong. It doesn't matter who did it. But I don't
think what he (Hyde) did cost us millions of dollars,'' said Pam
Elimore of Kinston, N.C., referring to the cost of independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition is involved in a court battle with the
Federal Elections Commission who charges that the group violated
its tax exempt status by aiding the 1992 Bush presidential effort
and other campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition has denied it broke any laws. Coalition president
Randy Tate said that the group will be engaged in the upcoming
election by distributing 45 million voters' guides on Nov. 1, just
a few days before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Tate warned that any candidate who is on the wrong side of the
morals issue ``will have a big problem on election day.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NYT-09-18-98 1822EDT &QL;
</P>
