<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALPACA-RANCHING-ART-2     09-18 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALPACA-RANCHING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVICE RANCHERS FIND FUN AND PROFIT IN BREEDING ALPACAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Wash)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARKSPUR, Colo. _ As an afternoon thunderstorm splashed their
pasture, a small herd of alpacas trotted toward shelter under the
overhanging roof of a nearby barn.
</P>
<P>
   Some, kids only a few weeks old, were about the size of large
dogs; others, full grown, stood nearly five feet tall with their
long necks erect. Their dense, velvety fleeces made up a
fashionable palette of earth tones _ white, tan, brown, gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Cleopatra,'' said Charles Stewart, presenting a female
with dark facial markings that look like too much eyeliner. ``This
is Summer Rain. She's due any day. And this is Vixen, and this is
Calliope.''
</P>
<P>
   The gentle animals milling sociably around Stewart seemed like
exotic pets, but, as a growing number of people are finding,
breeding alpacas can be a profitable business. Some of his animals,
Stewart said, are worth more than $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to do very much at this to make more than you
do at most jobs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 56, has been a rancher for less than five years. Just
three years ago, he quit a job as administrator of a medical clinic
to devote himself full time to his Colorado spread, 40 hilly acres
on the eastern flank of the Rocky Mountains, about 50 miles south
of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Helen Stewart, a pediatrician, are among more
than 1,000 alpaca owners in the United States, where a growing
national herd now numbers about 15,000 head. Some of them keep the
animals mainly as pets or because their coats provide silky,
luxurious fiber for knitting or weaving. But increasing numbers of
alpaca owners are breeding them for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very lucrative,'' Stewart said. ``The supply is very
low and the demand is high.''
</P>
<P>
   Distantly related to the camel and a smaller first cousin of the
South American llama, alpacas are native to Peru, Bolivia and
Chile. The animals were first imported commercially to the United
States in the early 1980s by American breeders looking to
capitalize on the alpacas' novelty. Alpaca wool _ unlike the
coarser fiber yielded by llama fleece _ has long been prized in
Europe as a luxurious fashion fabric.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the fiber is still used mainly in
artisanal weaving and knitting, but alpaca owners have formed a
fiber cooperative with the goal of expanding the market for their
animals' fleece.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the most profitable aspect of commercial
alpaca husbandry in the United States is breeding the animals for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart sold 18 alpacas last year, 10 of them breeding-quality
females with an average price of $18,000, he said. His
breeding-quality males bring around $5,000 apiece. He paid an
average of $24,000 each for four pregnant females he bought this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Female alpacas, with a gestation period of about 335 days, can
bear one cria, or kid, a year. They remain fertile for 20 years or
more.
</P>
<P>
   Alpaca breeders can take advantage of the same tax benefits as
other livestock breeders, including five-year accelerated
depreciation of breeding animals, according to Stewart, who is
chairman of the marketing committee of the Alpaca Owners and
Breeders Association, in Estes Park, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The alpaca association has 1,550 members, up from 146 in 1991.
Stewart said about a quarter of them are ``wannabes'' who do not
own any animals yet, and most of the rest have fewer than 20
animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely young industry,'' said Stewart, whose
marketing committee was formed last year to spread the word about
alpacas and their business possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hobert, the association's business manager, said the
alpaca herd in the United States has grown steadily at better than
20 percent a year for the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alpaca is easy to take care of,'' Hobert said from his
office in Estes Park. ``It's good for children; it makes for a good
life-style situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Many alpaca owners start off small, with just a few animals.
``They begin breeding their herd,'' Hobert said. ``Then they begin
marketing to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that is by word of mouth or on the Internet. Breeders
can advertise in Alpacas, the association's quarterly magazine (the
summer issue carried more than 120 ads), and some show their
animals in the growing number of alpaca exhibitions around the
country, many mounted in conjunction with llama shows.
</P>
<P>
   Like purebred horses, most alpacas have pedigrees that can
increase the animals' value for breeders. As of July 3, Alpaca
Registry Inc., a private, industry-supported organization, had
registered 16,846 live alpacas in the United States and Canada,
about eight times as many as in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Before newborn alpacas can be registered, their pedigreed
lineage must be confirmed by blood typing. Imported alpacas are
screened for physical characteristics, health and fiber quality.
The registry accepted 650 animals for registration in 1997,
rejecting 170. As of July 1 of this year, 1,016 animals had been
registered.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this year, the registry will stop registering
newly imported alpacas, mainly because some owners worry that an
increase in supply will erode the value of their herds. The
decision was taken by the 1,600 alpaca owners who are members of
the registry.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a fourth of the association members who took part
in the vote opposed the move, arguing that some alpaca strains were
not yet numerous enough in the United States to provide adequate
gene pools for good selective breeding.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Guidry, a member of the registry's board of directors,
predicted that importers would continue to bring in alpacas, even
if they were not permitted to register them.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``The importers have said to us there is no way they're going to
stop,'' she said, and some breeders are concerned that a rival
registry might be created for animals imported after this year. Ms.
Guidry estimated that 98 percent of all alpacas in the United
States are registered.
</P>
<P>
   A similar registry for llamas, which are popular as pack animals
throughout the Rocky Mountains, has not worked well. Only about
half of the nation's llama herd, now estimated to be about 200,000
head, is registered.
</P>
<P>
   As the llama population in the United States has grown, prices
for the animals have fallen, although a top-quality breeding llama
might still be worth several thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Alpaca industry officials say careful breeding practices,
registration and the animals' relative scarcity have helped keep
alpaca prices up. But many owners say that it is the high quality
of alpaca wool that will preserve the animals' commercial value
after their novelty wears off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're breeding toward, to get that fine fiber and
to be able to market fine garments from that,'' said Gordon
Anderson, president of the alpaca breeders association. He said
increasing numbers of alpaca owners operate stores to sell products
made of alpaca wool.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and his wife, Carolyn, have 17 alpacas on their ranch
in Mossyrock, Wash., in the foothills of the Cascade Mountains
south of Seattle and weave the animals' wool into designer rugs. He
said the five-year-old business had annual sales of about $90,000,
including rugs and livestock, and had been profitable since 1996.
Alpaca enthusiasts say the fiber is stronger, lighter, warmer and
softer than wool.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's possible to make an absolutely beautiful garment just
using natural colors,'' said Rachel Hendrickson, chairwoman of the
alpaca association's fiber committee. She said American fashion
houses were beginning to take an interest in alpaca.
</P>
<P>
   The American alpaca industry cannot yet produce enough fiber to
supply a major garment maker. But a step in that direction was the
formation of the Alpaca Fiber Cooperative of North America, which
was incorporated in January and has 400 members. The cooperative is
currently collecting fleece from its members and preparing to ship
it this fall to a mill in Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are really no mills of any size in the United States
that can process alpaca fiber from A to Z,'' said Russell Grattan,
president of the cooperative. ``The mill we're working with in Peru
has been processing alpaca fiber for 95 years.'' The cooperative
plans to send at least 20,000 pounds of fiber, then bring it back
as yarn and finished products like blankets, scarves and rugs. Some
of the goods will be returned to members, and the rest will be
marketed by the cooperative, Grattan said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest alpaca ranch in the United States, the 100-acre
Alpacas of America in Arlington, Wash., has a herd that fluctuates
between 900 and 1,300 head. It has sold more than 500 animals so
far this year, at $12,500 to around $50,000 a head, Randal P. Snow,
the ranch's business manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly profitable,'' Snow said, though he declined to
reveal earnings figures.
</P>
<P>
   Small-scale breeders can also make good money, Snow said. And
that is what Tony and Mindy Simon and Vivian Goldstein, Ms. Simon's
mother, are aiming to do with a 19-head alpaca herd they have built
up on a ranch near Longmont, Colo. They now have three pregnant
females and two recently weaned females for sale at prices ranging
from $14,000 to $18,000.
</P>
<P>
   Those sales would pay off the family's investment in alpacas,
Ms. Simon said. ``So starting next year would be pretty much pure
profit,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Simons, 30, first encountered alpacas in 1994 at a wool
market in Estes Park. ``I went in the alpaca stand and fell in love
with the alpacas,'' she said. The Simons and Ms. Goldstein bought
their first four animals in 1994 and their ranch in 1996. Last
spring, Ms. Simon quit her computer programming job in nearby
Boulder to devote full time to the alpaca business.
</P>
<P>
   Simon, 32, who is also a programmer, said he hoped that the
alpaca business would become profitable enough that he too could
leave his job at IBM in Boulder to spend full time on the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be here than at work _ it's a labor of love,'' he
said. ``I would do it in a heartbeat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
