<HEADLINE>
ADVISORY BOARD ON RACIAL RECONCILIATION FINISHES WORK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An advisory board on President Clinton's racial
reconciliation initiative ended its work Friday with officials
defending the panel's work and endorsing many White House policies.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials tried to bolster the board's
recommendations by announcing the Small Business Administration
would dedicate $1 billion in loans for women and minorities and by
producing another report showing race is often a key predictor of
economic well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make no apologies for what we have not done. There are
limits to what one can do and what one can achieve in 15 months.
After all we have been working on problems that began with the very
first settlement of our country in the 15th century,'' said John
Hope Franklin, the former Duke University legal history professor.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin chaired the seven-member Advisory Board to the
President's Initiative on Race, a unwieldy title for a panel whose
efforts drew a rash of criticism for lacking direction.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced in June 1997 that he would to create
a yearlong dialogue on race and wanted the panel to identify areas
that helped and hindered racial reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accepted the board's report from Franklin at a ceremony
attended by civil rights pioneer Rosa Parks.
</P>
<P>
   The president praised the panel and its staff for ``straining
their imaginations and finding the energy to take on this
tremendous task of focusing the nation's attention on building one
America for a new century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, this has meant enduring criticism, some of it perhaps
justified, some of it I have questioned because, as Dr. Franklin
said, no one could solve this problem in 15 months since it has not
been resolved in all of human history ... Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The board's report recapped information gleaned by the panel in
a series of town hall meetings, including two attended by the
president. Clinton personally directed one discussion group in Ohio
which was criticized for lacking candid exchanges and he
participated in a forum on sports hosted by ESPN in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a nation need to understand that whites tend to benefit,
either unknowingly or consciously, from this country's history of
white privilege,'' the board's report said.
</P>
<P>
   Among proposals, the board:
</P>
<P>
   Supported Clinton's ``mend it, don't end it'' policy on
affirmative action and called for more study.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed creation of a permanent presidential panel to promote
racial and ethnic harmony and dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Flagged for study police misconduct involving minorities,
stereotyping in media, federal employment, bilingual education,
access to technology and conflicts between non-white ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighted racial profiling, in which police use race to
identify potential criminals. It is employed most often in traffic
stops.
</P>
<P>
   Urged Clinton to reduce the disparity in sentences for crimes
involving powdered cocaine and its concentrated form, crack. The
board said longer sentences for crack crimes, largely involving
poor blacks or Hispanics, are ``morally and intellectually
indefensible.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
