<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a 2{-page package of stories on the
president and the charges against him:
</P>
<P>
   The lede will move by  &UR; 7:30 p.m. Eastern Time &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Giving a sharp partisan cast to
deliberations over impeachment, the Republican-controlled House
Judiciary Committee voted along party lines today to release the
videotape of President Clinton's grand jury testimony along with
2,800 more documents on the inquiry into his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky. The materials were set to be made public Monday,
promising a nation that would like the scandal to simply go away,
televised replays of an angry and legalistic president jousting
with lawyers over the definition of sexual relations. By Alison
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   These are the other stories in the package:
</P>
<P>
   Already  &UR; moved: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BLACKS (Atlanta) _ In dozens of interviews this week,
black Americans ranging from Julian Bond, the NAACP chairman, to
the comedian Chris Rock cited everything from Clinton's choice of
friends to his choice of woodwinds in explaining why he has
connected with minorities unlike any previous president, viscerally
as well as politically. And while blacks, like most Americans, are
deeply disturbed by Clinton's infidelity, recklessness and
dishonesty, they are not willing to jettison what they see as a
unique relationship in exchange for an uncertain and potentially
threatening future. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 7:30 p.m. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAY (Washington) _ The president's day: he meets with
the advisory panel on race, other developments. By Steven A.
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8 p.m. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS-SCENE (Washington) _ The scene on Capitol Hill.
By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BOOK (New York) _ In the week since three publishers
started selling sober-looking versions of that book _ the
400-plus-page report of the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr _
the steamy chronicle of the relationship between President Clinton
and Monica Lewinsky is selling at brisker rates than Tom Clancy's
new novel about an elite antiterrorist squad. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GINGRICH (Washington) _ At the opening session of the
Christian Coalition's annual meeting: Even as Pat Robertson, the
group's founder, set the stage for a weekend of partisan appeals to
the loyal, conservative Republican base, subsequent speeches by the
party's Congressional leadership were unusually tame. Speaker Newt
Gingrich and Senator Trent Lott, the Republican leader, instead
called upon the audience to pray for Clinton. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD (Washington) _ A news analysis: The
Republican rush to put out the Clinton deposition and other lurid
material, which Rep. Barney Frank calls ``basically an effort to
discredit the president,'' creates a spectacle that makes it look
as if all restraint, caution and decorum has evaporated on Capitol
Hill. Some members ponder the larger meaning of this shredding of
the political culture and its consequent alienation of the public.
By Jill Abramson.
