<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS JOIN FORCES TO AVERT A FLURRY OF EXTRAMARITAL
``OUTINGS.''
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The heads of the Senate Democratic and Republican
campaign committees Friday joined their House counterparts in
vowing to cut off financial support to any candidate who launches a
personal attack on an opponent this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., exchanged
the vows on the floor of the Senate less than 24 hours after House
campaign leaders, stung by embarrassing disclosures of an
extramarital affair by House Judiciary Committee Henry Hyde, made a
similar pact.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan effort appeared to be an attempt by Congress to
head off what some members fear could be a flurry of ``outings'' of
lawmakers who have had extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digging through their record is one thing, digging through
their garbage is quite another,'' said McConnell. ``Criticizing
someone for their vote on the marriage tax is fair game. Attacking
someone for a failed marriage certainly is not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern,'' said Kerrey, ``...is that if we do not exercise
restraint and show American citizens that we will not fund
candidates who use personal problems or past failures to win their
office, the institutions of democracy will suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey said ``something that happened 30 years ago or 40 years
ago or 20 years ago ... is irrelevant'' to a political campaign,
especially when the offender has ``dealt with their family and
their friends and their God.''
</P>
<P>
   Reps. John Linder, R-Ga., and Martin Frost, D-Texas, who chair
their party's campaign committees in the House, had similar
comments Thursday after the Internet magazine, Salon, reported on
an affair Hyde had 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisanship in the House and the Senate and the
abhorrence of sexual topics came as a sharp contrast to the process
enveloping President Clinton. In a party-line split, the House
Judiciary Committee voted Friday to release more materials from
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's investigation of the
president's 18-month affair with onetime White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely have the leaders of the opposing parties in Congress made
such agreements as those reached by McConnell and Kerrey in the
Senate and Linder and Frost in the Senate. The last such occasion
was in 1990 when the leaders agreed to cut off campaign funds to
any opponent of an incumbent who had voted for a controversial pay
raise.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign committees of both parties and the funds they
control are often vital to congressional challengers who rarely
have as much money for their campaigns as incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   But the pact also reflected concern within Congress that the
public believes it is filled with a high number of philanderers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start to spend $40 million investigating the lives of
members of Congress, you'll see a stampede across the Potomac
River,'' said Guillermo Galindo, a Latino activist in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not reluctant or shy to have full contact sport when it
comes to campaigns, but I do believe that the ultimate objective of
the candidate needs to be to not just acquire the office, but also
to serve the larger good of preserving our Democratic institutions
_ in this case the U.S. Congress,'' Kerrey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in this body knows that I believe in robust, pointed,
hard-hitting campaigns,'' said McConnell. ``And I believe those
kinds of campaigns are good for our democracy and good for the
voters, but only when political campaigns are focused on issues and
not on purely private behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But declining voter turnout and polling data suggest that
presidential and congressional campaigns are increasingly
distasteful to Americans because of their personal attacks and lack
of substantive discussions of issues.
</P>
<P>
   The White House denies it is behind the recent disclosures about
Hyde and two other Republicans who, in response to press inquiries,
acknowledged extramarital affairs: Reps. Dan Burton of Indiana and
Helen Chenoweth of Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
