A3401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON19-COX     09-18 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHITE HOUSE CALLS VIDEOTAPE VOTE PARTISAN AND UNFAIR
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration lashed out Friday at
House Republicans for voting to release a videotape of the
president's grand jury testimony, calling the move a raw political
act designed to further tarnish the embattled leader.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said President Clinton remained determined to reject calls
for his resignation, even as the nation braced for the
unprecedented spectacle of watching its chief executive fume and
squirm under more than four hours of interrogation centered on the
excruciatingly intimate details of his relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ''This appears to be a rush to prejudgment and an effort to get
out salacious and explicit material at the speed of light, not the
pace of justice,'' Jim Kennedy, spokesman for the office of White
House Counsel Charles Ruff, said in a prepared statement. ''But
ultimately it will be up to the American people to decide whether
this process has been fair or simply a partisan effort to embarrass
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said Friday's decision was
poisoned by partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ''It had been our hope that this process would be bipartisan and
fair,'' Toiv said at a White House briefing. ''Today's action was
neither.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not comment on Friday's vote, though he said at a
news conference Wednesday that the matter was out of his hands and
he would not be surprised by a Republican decision to release the
tape.
</P>
<P>
   The videotape is to be aired starting at 9 a.m. EDT Monday, one
hour before Clinton is scheduled to address heads of state from
around the world at the United Nations in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Several television networks have announced plans to broadcast
Clinton's taped testimony just as he prepares to address the
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president is going to deliver the speech that he is
planning on giving,'' said Toiv. ''He will represent this country
at the U.N., and he will undoubtedly do it with distinction, and it
(release of the videotape) will not have an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House declined to predict the effect the videotape
might have on public opinion, though some analysts speculated that
the move could backfire against Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know how seeing Clinton in this setting could alter
the situation much,'' said Thomas Mann, director of governmental
studies at the Brookings Institution, a Washington research center.
''It might heighten the public's reaction against those who are
forcing the public to confront all this.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of being dragged through a scandal revolving around
sex, lies and, now, videotape, said Mann, many Americans may decide
to simply tune out on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The safest bet,'' he said, ''would be that the impact of the
release, on the public, as opposed to on Washington, will be
substantially less than anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
