<SLUG> BC-GREENPEACE-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENPEACE ENDS OCCUPATION OF TEXAS OFFICES IN MEXICO CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A dozen anti-nuclear demonstrators declared their
mission accomplished Friday and ended their 30-hour occupation of
the Texas State Government Office here.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters from Greenpeace entered the office Thursday
morning to denounce the proposed low-level nuclear waste dump
scheduled to be built at Sierra Blanca in the West Texas desert,
near the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a very good reaction in the United States from
various anti-nuclear organizations and have gotten widespread
coverage here in Mexico,'' demonstration leader Alejandro Calvillo
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. organizations like the Sierra Blanca Legal Defense Fund and
the Nuclear Information and Resource Service have begun campaigns
of faxed messages to the Texas offices of Gov. George W. Bush in
support of the Greenpeace protest, Calvillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was targeted by the protesters for his perceived advocacy
of the nuclear-waste dump.
</P>
<P>
   Although the proposed site is in one of the most desolate parts
of the United States, opponents of the waste site on both sides of
the border worry its proximity to underground aquifers feeding the
Rio Grande could pollute water supplies for millions of people in
South Texas and northern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said dump opponents like
Greenpeace frequently downplayed his oft-repeated concerns for the
safety and integrity of any nuclear-waste facility in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``His position is that if it isn't safe, it won't be built,''
Edwards said by telephone from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Blanca is a project approved under former Gov. Ann
Richards and bequeathed to Bush, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will rely on scientists to help determine the safety and
feasibility of the Sierra Blanca site, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission is currently
studying permits for Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   Few here in Mexico support the proposed dump site. The
Secretariat of Foreign Relations has sent diplomatic notes to the
U.S. government outlining the Mexican government's concern and
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that Bush has stated his concerns, but at the same
time he continues support the project, the site and the pact,''
Calvillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The pact is an agreement among Maine, Vermont and Texas
providing that once an adequate site is located and built in Texas,
low-level nuclear waste from the other two states will be shipped
there for storage, Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite more than two years of determined opposition from a
broad spectrum of Mexican politicians and non-governmental
organizations, Bush has done nothing to seek another site, Calvillo
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had been sensitive to Mexican feelings, he would have
proposed an alternative, but he hasn't,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1916EDT &QL; 
