<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-ECON-NYT &LR;      09-18 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMISTS DEBATE HOW TO PROTECT EUROPE FROM GLOBAL FINANCIAL
CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ As dismal news accumulates around the globe, European
economies are proving remarkably resilient. But evidence is
multiplying that the Continent's two-year-old recovery is at risk,
fueling debate about how to shield Europe from the effects of
turmoil elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   With exports to Asia, South America and Russia flagging,
corporate profits are under growing pressure. In Britain, two major
semiconductor manufacturers, Japan's Fujitsu and Germany's Siemens,
announced plans to close factories, citing cheap imports from Asian
countries where currencies have collapsed. In Germany, national
elections later this month have markets unnerved by the
possibility, for the first time in 16 years, that a Socialist-led
government might be returned to power.
</P>
<P>
   Wim Duisenberg, head of the new European Central Bank,
acknowledged this week that international financial turmoil would
have a ``dampening effect'' on global growth, and that Europe would
not be spared. Several major banks and brokerages have already
trimmed their European growth projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd gladly be an isle of the blessed,'' said Werner Becker,
senior economist at Deutsche Bank Research in Frankfurt. ``But
we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Europe is expected to sustain reasonable growth. While
Becker is among a number of economists calling attention to the
region's vulnerability, even he sees no major crisis brewing. He
recently predicted that growth for the 11 countries that will adopt
the euro on Jan. 1 should be around 2.6 percent for next year,
scaling back modestly from his earlier prediction of 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Europe will not escape unscathed from the turmoil raging in
Asia and Latin America, and there is fear that things will get
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contagion effect poses a considerable risk for Western
Europe,'' Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, J. Paul Horne, European equity market economist at
Salomon Smith Barney in London, trimmed his European growth
forecast for 1999, to 2.6 percent from 3.2 percent. For Britain, he
projects under 1 percent growth and calls a recession a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly unsettling, Becker said, is the slowdown in
Britain, which buys roughly 20 percent of the goods and services
exported by Continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Other leading countries, like Germany, are heavily exposed in
Eastern Europe. Though Russia accounts for a mere 2 percent of
German trade, Central European countries like Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic now absorb fully 10 percent of German exports,
more than the United States. Thus, any spillover of the collapse of
Russia's already weak economy into Central Europe would indirectly
hurt Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by many measures, Europe is in enviable shape.
</P>
<P>
   Though Britain may be on the brink of recession, other leading
countries, like France, Germany and Spain, still show robust
growth. Germany's central bank, the Bundesbank, has signaled that
it continues to see inflation as a threat, and officials from other
nations have played down the possibility of quick action on
interest rates or other responses to the global economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Bundesbank, in its September monthly report,
depicted Europe's economies as havens of calm and stability amid
the turmoil disrupting many of the world's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg said that broad indicators showed Europe can expect
to be still on track, with ``continued expansion in the second
quarter, albeit at a possibly more moderate pace'' than in the
first. Taken together, the data showed inflation growing in Spain,
Portugal and Ireland, and an unaccustomed shift in France and
Germany, where domestic consumption, rather than exports, fueled
growth and progress was made in job creation. In the first eight
months of 1998, 320,000 people were taken off Germany's jobless
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   European markets have revived since hitting lows in early
September, and business investment is expected to get a further
lift after the euro is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the four or five channels of transmission
between emerging markets and Western Europe, then the real effects
have been pretty moderate,'' said Eric Barthalon, chief economist
at Paribas in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Trade among the 11 euro-zone countries is so extensive, he said,
that trade with the rest of the world now accounts for only about
11 percent of the region's total gross domestic product, less than
the share in the similarly sized United States, where it is about
14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, falling prices for commodities, like oil, benefit
European manufacturers, and the collapse of stock markets in Asia,
Latin America and Eastern Europe has bolstered Europe financially,
by attracting capital in a ``flight to quality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the United States, European personal and corporate
indebtedness has not grown substantially in recent years, and
because Europeans invest in stocks at a lower rate than Americans,
less money was drained from the pockets of European consumers by
this summer's global market decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident domestic demand will remain strong,'' Horne
said.
</P>
<P>
   One significant problem for Europe is the weakening of the
dollar against European currencies, which makes products sold to
the United States more expensive. And while a weakened dollar
tended in the past to drag fragile European currencies like the
Italian lira down with it, the euro agreement reached last May has
forced the dollar to move more or less uniformly against all 11
currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in several European countries, echoing President
Clinton's appeal earlier this week, are raising their voices for
some kind of concerted push to contain the fast-spreading global
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair has been canvassing leaders of
the Group of Seven industrial nations for proposals. In Italy,
Prime Minister Romano Prodi, addressing parliament on Wednesday,
said the seven must find a ``common neo-Keynesian or expansion
policy to stimulate the economy'' in response to the world's
problems. Both leaders are scheduled to meet with President Clinton
in New York on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While Prodi appeared to be calling for lower interest rates,
European central bankers _ like U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan _ are clearly not yet ready to act.
</P>
<P>
   Many European economists are not convinced a rate cut is even
necessary. Europe's long road to acceptance of the euro, which
required governments in the 11 subscribing countries to rein in
their fiscal policies, has had a lingering effect akin to monetary
easing, from which Europe's economy will continue to benefit for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   With the Jan. 1 adoption of the euro by the 11, the new European
Central Bank must set a Europe-wide ``convergence rate'' for
short-term interest rates, and a growing number of economists
believe it will be pegged to the Bundesbank's current short-term
rate of 3.3 percent. Germany and neighboring countries with low
interest rates will ``doubtless play a type of benchmark role'' in
setting interest rates for all of Europe, Hans Tietmeyer, the
Bundesbank president, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tietmeyer said that despite economic turmoil in Asia and Russia,
Europe's economy has ``remained relatively robust _ at least so
far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
