<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WHEELCHAIR-ADAPT-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR SEATS, BELLS AND WHISTLES  
 (FOR RELEASE, SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERT P. BENNETT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All adaptive equipment for people with disabilities is
considered specialty equipment, but within this category are the
specialty's specialties. If most automotive adaptive equipment
helps people get into and drive vehicles, these devices help make
that experience more pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Any occupant is considered best off riding in a conventional car
seat designed with safety and visibility in mind. In fact, sitting
in a regular car seat is considered so important that many makers
of adaptive devices have included electrically controlled seats to
their inventory to help people with limited mobility make the shift
from wheelchair to car seat.
</P>
<P>
   These seats not only move back and forth, as all car seats do,
they also move up and down and rotate.
</P>
<P>
   Some people with disabilities may want the off-road capability
of a truck or sport utility vehicle. But since most trucks are
higher than are cars, a user who might be able to stow a wheelchair
in a car, might not be able to lift it the extra height into a
truck.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno Independent Living Aids Inc. of Oconomowoc, Wis., has
developed special lifts for trucks. Its Curb-Sider moves the
driver's seat outward and downward to aid access. The company's
Cab-Sider, developed with the cooperation of GM, raises wheelchairs
and stows them inside extended-cab trucks with three or four doors.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies have developed devices that alert people to
auditory signals even if they are deaf or hard of hearing. For
instance, Ears _ early alert response system _ from Harc Mercantile
of Kalamazoo, Mich., translates the sounds of emergency vehicles
into lights that are displayed on the dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   It not only alerts drivers that an emergency vehicle is
approaching, it can identify what sort of vehicle it is. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
