<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3409 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-OVERRIDE-BOS     09-18 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-OVERRIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE FAILES TO OVERRIDE 2D CLINTON ABORTION BILL VETO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Friday failed for the second time to
override President Clinton's veto of a ban on a controversial
procedure called partial-birth abortion. Proponents vowed to take
the issue to the voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have dug to the foundation of our ability to turn votes of
those who are in office,'' said Senator Rick Santorum, the
Pennsylvania Republican and sponsor of the ban. ``The future of
this really lies in the American public and what they do in the
next election.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Senator Bob Smith, the New Hampshire Republican and an
advocate of abolishing all abortions, ``I know there have been a
lot of prayers. Those prayers will be answered in early November.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the proximity of the November elections and an
aggressive lobbying campaign by supporters of the ban, not a single
senator switched position on the issue Friday. The Senate voted,
64-36, falling three votes short of the two-thirds needed to
override Clinton's veto.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen Democrats joined 51 Republicans in voting to override.
Four Republicans, all from New England, voted against the ban with
32 Democrats. The House in July voted to override the veto.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the 12 New England senators voted to override _ Smith
and Judd Gregg, the New Hampshire Republican, and Patrick Leahy,
the Vermont Democrat. Opposing the prohibition, and voting against
the override, were Massachusetts Senators Edward M. Kennedy and
John F. Kerry; John Chafee, the Rhode Island Republican; Jack Reed,
the Rhode Island Democrat; Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, the
Maine Republicans; Jim Jeffords, the Vermont Republican; and
Christopher Dodd and Joseph Lieberman, the Connecticut Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's vote coincided with the national meeting in Washington
of the Christian Coalition, which ran radio ads against the two
Maine senators and others in an unsuccessful effort to persuade
them to change their positions on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have imposed fines and prison terms on any
physician who performed the procedure. It also allowed the father
of the fetus or parents of a pregnant minor to sue the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Although the procedure is distasteful, opponents of the ban say
it is sometimes the safest way to end pregnancies of deformed
fetuses to protect the future fertility of the pregnant woman.
Supporters of the ban say it is never medically necessary. A
last-minute compromise by a bipartisan group that included Snowe
and Collins was unable to bridge the gap. The proposed compromise
would have banned all abortions after viability except those needed
to protect the life or health of the pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vetoed the bill in 1997, but House leaders waited nine
months to schedule the override vote during an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of movement in the Senate on the issue,
lobbying picked up this week. Religious leaders, including Anthony
Bevilaqua, the Roman Catholic cardinal from Philadelphia, watched
Friday's vote from the visitor's gallery. Several women who have
undergone the procedure worked with abortion-rights supporters in
talking to senators about the implications of a prohibition. Some
of these women appeared with Clinton when he vetoed the bill. They
said the procedure saved their lives and their ability to have
healthy babies.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the ban said overriding the veto would have set a
dangerous precedent by outlawing a specific medical procedure and
would have undermined a woman's right to an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``These legislators affirmed today that the campaign of
deception that has been promulgated by the religious right, a
campaign that seeks to outlaw abortion for American women, is
dangerous to women's health and is out of step with mainstream
America,'' said Vicki Saporta, director of the National Abortion
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   But those who back the ban vowed to keep up their campaign to
outlaw the practice and bring the issue up again next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will inevitably pass,'' Santorum said after the
vote. ``The veto will be overridden, and the will of the American
people will be heard on this issue of infanticide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
