A3410 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HASTINGS19-CO     09-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HASTINGS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HASTINGS SEES PARALLELS BETWEEN HIS IMPEACHMENT, CLINTON CASE
 &HT;    With HASTINGS-STARR.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Impeachment. Rep. Alcee Hastings has been there,
done that.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Hastings, D-Fla., the only House member to be
impeached and removed from office _ thrust himself into the
controversy surrounding President Clinton by calling for the
impeachment and removal of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   There is much anger left in Hastings about his impeachment as a
federal judge, and it boiled over as he talked with reporters about
the parallels he sees between his experience and that facing
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings is incensed at what he considers the prosecutorial
misconduct he faced in 1988 and Clinton is facing now. And he's
disappointed that the bipartisanship that existed then has now
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastings said he doesn't ``have any deja vu feelings. My
having been impeached and removed is not a part of my
consideration, other than the facts of my enormous experience that
I have in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago the House impeached Hastings on charges of
participating in a $150,000 bribery conspiracy, despite his
acquittal on similar criminal charges. A year later, the Senate
removed him from his lifetime appointment. He was first elected to
the House in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings has not discussed his impeachment with Clinton, nor
would he offer advice now unless asked, he said. But he chided
Clinton for testifying before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would have told Clinton: ``You're a high-profile
person that may be charged with a crime, and you're going into a
prosecutor's playhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years leading to his removal as a judge, Hastings fought
the legal processes used to bring him to that point _ including the
fact that his impeachment was recommended by a judicial panel, the
manner in which the House Judiciary Committee conducted its
proceedings and the Senate's decision to have his case heard by a
12-member select committee, rather than the full body, before
voting.
</P>
<P>
   He sees a replay of what he characterized as prosecutorial
misconduct in his case and the one Starr has developed against
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenneth Starr has usurped our powers, and I refuse to be a
member of this body _ having had it happen to me _ where people
were looking on and saying 'it's all right for a prosecutor to do
something wrong because somebody else did something wrong.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-uh. No. I can't stay here and let that happen. ...I've been
in that 'it's all right for a prosecutor to do wrong process,' and
it's not a good thing for this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The other parallel that upsets Hastings is the manner in which
the impeachment proceedings developed against him and appear to be
developing against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Congress was presented with lengthy detailed
cases _ developed by a panel of judges in Hastings' case and
prepared by Starr's office in Clinton's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is something inherently unfair with Congress
giving up its powers ...to judges ...(and to) the independent
counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it should be Congress's responsibility to determine the
grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   One major difference Hastings sees between his experience and
Clinton's is today's charged partisan atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that John Conyers in the majority, and Henry Hyde in
the minority, worked more cooperatively to achieve whatever it is
they achieved,'' Hastings said of the two Judiciary Committee
leaders who have switched places since the Republicans took control
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like the end result, but I believe they worked well
together to try to achieve that. This thing has jumped off in
partisan rancor. We're bickering and fighting. ... We're not acting
with decorum. We're not acting in a civil manner toward each other.
We're personalizing, threatening. It's not good.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
