<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STUDENTS-BOS &LR;      09-18 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STUDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEERS GIVE CHELSEA THE SYMPATHY VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV AND GEETA ANAND  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mortified is the word they use most often, trailed
closely by humiliated and just plain ``grossed out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how scores of college students on both coasts said they
would feel if their own fathers got caught having an adulterous
affair with a young woman about their age. Having every detail made
public would be the worst, not just unacceptable but intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   As Andrea Sicuso, a 19-year-old crew team member at the College
of the Holy Cross in Worcester put it, ``I can't imagine my parents
having sex, never mind the whole country knowing your father did
and with someone your own age.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the students' sympathies were not with Hillary
Clinton, who chooses to stay married despite her husband's
infidelities, or with the president himself. Their sympathies were
with the Clinton they can relate to: Chelsea. So was their respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think about her when I hear about it,'' said Laura
Garvey, a 19-year-old sophomore at Holy Cross. ``It makes it even
worse that it could have been one of your friends. It's just gross.
When I see her smiling and holding her parents' hands, I wonder
what she's thinking. I don't know if I could have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the high opinion many students interviewed had of her,
Tim Bradley, a 20-year-old junior at the University of California
in Los Angeles, said simply: ``She can handle it all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the public eye, taught early to anticipate trouble at
home, Chelsea Clinton continues to demonstrate a kind of grace that
her peers said would elude them under similar circumstances. Still,
as student after student was quick to note, the public attention on
such a private family matter would make concentrating on school all
but impossible, especially since the sex scandal is a popular topic
for classroom discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was trained by her parents to live a political life, so
maybe she can handle this better than someone else,'' said Sofia
Carino, a 20-year-old economics major at UCLA. ``But how can you
train someone to deal with a situation like this? ... Any
distraction is hard and this one doesn't compare to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Eileen Donnelly, a 19-year-old sophomore at Holy Cross,
``Because we're her age, we think of her more than anyone. She must
be really embarrassed about the whole thing. To go from being
really proud of your father because he's president to feeling
uncomfortable going across campus, I can't imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Students at both Holy Cross and UCLA pointed out that they had,
in many ways, grown up with Chelsea Clinton, now a sophomore at
Stanford University in Palo Alto, Calif. They listened to the same
music, watched the same television programs, took their college
entrance exams around the same time. They knew she was smart, had a
swimmer for a boyfriend, invited friends for White House
sleepovers. Paying her a high compliment, many called her ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   They also called her unlucky. During a period that is supposed
to be about learning and maturing, she is being forced to confront
her father's unfaithfulness once again. Several students said they
had heard rumors that she was thinking of dropping out of school _
which they hoped she would not do _ or taking a semester off, which
almost everyone said they would understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's strong, which I think she is, she should stay,'' said
Dana Lazarovici, a senior studying neuroscience at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarovici's friend, a recent graduate named Aviva Sufian,
added, ``But it's no big deal to take a semester off. People do it
if they get mono or break up with their boyfriend. If her father
got cancer, she might leave for a while. She might feel her
responsibility is to be with her family right now.''
</P>
<P>
   At UCLA, attended by many former child actors and the sons and
daughters of movie stars, students tended to assume that Chelsea
Clinton could remain relatively anonymous despite the ongoing
coverage of her father's sex life. At Holy Cross, however, many
students assumed the discomfort level would be too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be a very bad feeling, but Chelsea should tell
herself, `This is my life and no one can blame me for what my
father has done,''' said Selin Billi, a business major who recently
graduated from UCLA. ``But I know it's easier to say that than to
put it into practice and actually do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarah Auguste, a Holy Cross sophomore, explained just how hard
it could be: ``Man, if it was me, I'd sit there and cry all day. I
think it's time for home tutoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Most students said they knew the unwanted attention could turn
ugly because they had read at least portions of Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr's report, particularly the sections detailing the
sexual relationship between the president and former White House
intern Monica S. Lewinsky. But they were divided over whether
Chelsea Clinton should do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Some said they would be unable to help themselves, that they
would have to read the words that have captivated the country and
could lead to impeachment hearings, even if those words involved
their own fathers. Others argued that Chelsea Clinton should shun
the report, that it would only hurt her more. Instead, they
suggested she speak with her father directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to read the report or watch the video'' of
Clinton testifying before the grand jury, said Sommer Hammoud, a
19-year-old biology major and soccer player at UCLA. ``It's my dad
and I don't want to know nasty and gross stuff like that. But I'd
want to know what he had to say for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Said David Swanson, 21, a UCLA math major, ``I'd want to hear
about it from him first. I'd expect him to talk to me about it and
to be honest, even if he was the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Most students interviewed, particularly those whose parents had
divorced, said they assumed Chelsea Clinton was furious with her
father and, privately, was taking sides with her mother. All agreed
they would, if put in the same position, be shocked, hurt and
uncomprehending. That Lewinsky was about their age would only make
the revelation harder to digest, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many said they could forgive their fathers. None said
they could forget. Recalling the affair of a friend's father, UCLA
graduate student Amy Sakaldasis noted that her friend's
relationship with her father was never the same. Even after years
of work, it was less trusting, less loving. Today they are more
friends than father and daughter, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he's out of office, I bet their relationship is
different,'' said Amie Hibbard, a 20-year-old senior at UCLA. ``She
probably won't be so smiley around him ... But I don't know. Maybe
she's kind of use to it. Maybe it's all part of being this
president's daughter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
