<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Spurrier's bluster strangely absent
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Fran Blinebury &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The face is familiar, but not the words
coming out of his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the diabolical genius, smiling, plotting, scheming,
doing everything but bragging about what his Gators will do to
Tennessee?
</P>
<P>
   Where is the ``aw shucks'' grin and the incendiary comments
intended to get under the Volunteers' skin?
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the annual Florida-Tennessee showdown, you want to
reach out and grab this impostor by the throat and ask him what
he's done with the real Steve Spurrier.
</P>
<P>
   You know, Steve Superior, the guy everybody in the Smoky
Mountains _ and many other places _ loves to hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just aren't a lot of 2-0 teams around the country, and
at this point in the season, we're just happy to be one of them,''
Spurrier said. ``We've gone out and gotten us a couple of wins. But
I look at our football team, and I know that we have a lot of room
for improvement in a lot of different areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that we have not played extremely well in our
first two games, but over the course of 11, 12, 13 games, you won't
play all of them well. Hopefully, we'll play the big games well.''
</P>
<P>
   This is usually one of the biggest for Spurrier's Gators, who
have taken the Volunteers five years in a row, including a 4-0
shutout of Tennessee that ran all the way through Peyton Manning's
celebrated quarterback career.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier always has seemed to take an extra special delight in
doing it to the Volunteers, maybe because he knows how much it
means to them. There was the time he said Manning had a chance to
become the only four-time starting quarterback in the Citrus Bowl,
which is where the Southeastern Conference's No. 2 team plays on
New Year's Day. There were always so many barbs pointed at
Tennessee by Spurrier.
</P>
<P>
   But not this time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because Spurrier remembers how his team beat
Tennessee last season _ in defense of its 1996 national
championship _ and then went out and lost to LSU and Georgia. Maybe
it's because the Gators are starting on a torturous stretch of the
schedule that has them playing Kentucky, Alabama and LSU in
succession after the Vols. Or maybe it's because he has seen the
upsets that have occurred this season around the country and
doesn't want to put his club between the cross hairs.
</P>
<P>
   There has to be a part of Spurrier that giggled with glee last
weekend when Bobby Bowden and Florida State were upset by North
Carolina State. But there must also be a wary side of him, with
Jesse Palmer his starting quarterback with all of 2{ games of
experience under his belt.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier, like the rest of us, can see what it means to have a
calm veteran hand on the controls of an offense. No. 1-ranked Ohio
State is running behind Joe Germaine and looking like the team to
beat in the early going. Florida State might be out of the
national-championship picture after newcomer Chris Weinke suffered
through a miserable day of 9-for-32 passing with six interceptions.
That produced the Seminoles' first loss to an unranked opponent in
58 games, dating to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden's loss opened the door for the Gators to move up to No. 2
in the polls, but it's obviously an uneasy position, because
``Superior'' hasn't had much to say in his usual fashion of dumping
gasoline on Tennessee's fire.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is a little disappointing, like finding out Ken
Starr is a closet Clinton voter. You expect certain people to act a
certain way, always live up to the image they have created.
Volunteers fans expect it. We all expect it.
</P>
<P>
   But after a pair of opening wins over The Citadel and Northeast
Louisiana, there has been no blast from Spurrier. Maybe because he
is hurt that his team has failed to crack the 50-point barrier
against either of the patsies. Or maybe because he watched
Tennessee venture into the Carrier Dome two weeks ago and pull out
a gutty win over Syracuse and its Heisman Trophy candidate,
quarterback Donovan McNabb.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what Tennessee does, history says Florida will
find a way to be a little bit better. The scouting report says the
Gators have an edge on the lines, offensive and defensive. It says
Manning's replacement, Tee Martin, will somehow fall victim to the
same Florida jinx. It says despite his caution with Palmer _ and
hints he'll frequently turn to Doug Johnson _ Spurrier will do what
he always does to the Vols.
</P>
<P>
   It would just be reassuring to Gators fans to hear him say it.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Fran Blinebury on the Sports Page radio show on KPRC
(950 AM) from 5-7 p.m. weekdays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
