<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT NOW FOR MONICA LEWINSKY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What's to become of Monica?
</P>
<P>
   While the president pleads for public forgiveness, the
prosecutor has his say in a long, eye-popping report, and the jury
on Capitol Hill clamors over a constitutional crisis, the femme
fatale in the sordid soap opera of sex and betrayal has dropped out
of sight.
</P>
<P>
   Monica S. Lewinsky, 25 and unemployed, hasn't said a thing or
been seen around town since the detailed revelations of her sad,
salacious, flirtatious, obsessive, and ambitious affair with
President Clinton rocked the world. Judy Smith, her spokeswoman,
won't confirm whether Lewinsky is still living in her mother's
Watergate apartment or say when, if ever, she'll comment on
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   There are rumors of million-dollar book deals and movie rights,
though publishers have thus far been dismissive. Maybe product
endorsements or a celebrity stint on the gossip/talk show circuit,
too. Lewinsky might move to New York, where Marcia Lewis, her
recently remarried mother, now resides, or return to Beverly Hills,
where Bernard Lewinsky, her physician-father, lives a comfortable
life. Smith won't say.
</P>
<P>
   On her birthday in July, Lewinsky told family she just wanted
``to have my life back.'' But it's hard to find anybody who
believes Monica Lewinsky can duck the spotlight now and won't be
remembered for years to come as the woman who loved ``Handsome,''
resented the ``creep,'' saved a soiled dress, and told the secrets
of a 16-month affair that shattered the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Lewinsky, who had a youthful flair for drama,
might get a leading role in the biggest television miniseries of
her life: Testifying at congressional hearings considering the
impeachment of the president.
</P>
<P>
   John Dean III, President Nixon's counsel and chief accuser
during Watergate, recently wrote an open letter to Lewinsky in the
New York Times, warning that it won't be easy to get on with her
life, which already has been trampled by the media mob and probably
threatened by ``the lunatic fringe.'' In fact, he said, it may get
worse before it gets better.
</P>
<P>
   It could happen soon. The House Judiciary Committee voted today
to release a videotape of the president's grand jury testimony and
additional documents collected by Starr. Lewinsky's lawyers were on
Capitol Hill Tuesday urging committee members to block the release
of parts of Lewinsky's grand jury testimony that would reveal more
sexual detail or prove embarrassing to her family or friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think your privacy has been invaded already, you will
find the grand jury room was like a confessional booth compared
with your visit to Capitol Hill,'' wrote Dean, who in 1973 gave the
Senate Watergate Committee damning testimony on Nixon's coverup.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Americans titillated by Lewinsky's words in Starr's
report have yet to hear her voice. People close to her believe,
however, that she has a lot more to say. They reportedly are
peddling a book by Lewinsky, who boasts of ``a photographic memory
for the entire relationship,'' which began in November 1995 and
ended in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sure there will be a book, but I wouldn't give you a
plugged nickel for it,'' said New York literary agent Virginia
Barber, who says she has been approached by at least two publishers
looking for a writer for a Lewinsky book. ``I don't see the outline
of a challenging or interesting story.''
</P>
<P>
   But best-sellers have been built on much less than 10 illicit
and real-life sexual encounters inside the White House between a
22-year-old intern and the US president.
</P>
<P>
   While the Starr report breathes heavy with sex, Lewinsky's
memoir would surely meander the emotional road of an infatuated
intern who ``never expected to fall in love with the president'' to
the jealous lover who was ``livid'' when the president entertained
another female visitor, to the scorned woman who came to believe
Clinton saw their relationship as only ``a service contract'' to
satisfy his needs. ``It was a lot more than that to me,'' Lewinsky
said ruefully in Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is going to make money and have a celebrity career. There
most certainly will be a book and probably a TV movie that appeals
to our prurient, voyeuristic human nature,'' said Noreen Jenney,
president of the Celebrity Endorsement Network in Woodland Hills,
Calif. ``Beyond that, I can't imagine Monica having an easy time
finding a job. Her behavior was so abhorrent.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenney doesn't think Lewinsky will be in demand for the kind of
big-time endorsements she brokers because Lewinsky conveys a
negative image, and ``no advertiser that needs to sell products
credibly to Middle America would ever use her.'' Like Donna Rice,
who was revealed as Democratic Senator Gary Hart's girlfriend,
Lewinsky might be able to sell jeans or other youthful apparel,
Jenney said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's job offer from Revlon, secured by presidential friend
Vernon E. Jordan Jr., was withdrawn after her relationship with
Clinton was reported by the media in January. The trouble for her
now, if she undertakes a job search, is that the world has read
what amounts to her White House employment evaluation in the Starr
report, and it isn't positive.
</P>
<P>
   The president's secretary, Betty Currie, called Lewinsky a
``pain in the neck'' and ``a little bit pushy.'' White House deputy
chief of staff Evelyn Lieberman said she was a ``clutch _ always
someplace she shouldn't be.'' Timothy Keating, a special assistant
to the president, transferred Lewinsky from the White House to the
Pentagon in April 1996, because she was ``too sexy'' to be around
the boss, according to Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The former intern certainly intimidated and at times exasperated
Clinton, particularly with her persistent demands for a White House
job and her threats of exposing the relationship if Jordan didn't
produce an acceptable position in New York. ``The most important
things to me are that I am engaged and interested in my work, I am
not someone's administrative/executive assistant, and my salary can
provide me a comfortable living in N.Y.,'' Lewinsky said in a note
to the president in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were interviewing her on behalf of a client, I would be
nervous,'' said Jeffrey Davis, president of Mage Inc., an executive
consulting firm in Chestnut Hill, Mass. ``When you are building an
organizaton, you aren't looking for someone who is too
controversial or might distract from the goal at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said it's pretty clear that Lewinsky is not a ``team
player,'' and she would be perceived as a dangerous hire in a
corporate culture that is ``phobic'' about sexual harassment
lawsuits. Lynn Ponton, a San Francisco psychiatrist, says she
``wouldn't be surprised'' if Lewinsky sued the president for
harassment to try to restore her reputation.
</P>
<P>
   There's abundant evidence, though, that Lewinsky aggressively
pursued her boss with what began as ``intense flirting,'' as she
said in Starr's report, including giving the president a peek at
her thong underwear.
</P>
<P>
   For potential employers, Lewinsky could at best be considered
indiscrete and at worst a security threat. She told at least 11
people, including her mother and her therapist, of her workplace
affair. She wrote many e-mail messages about it. And she had a
Valentine's Day love poem to the president published in the
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate in psychology of Lewis &AMP; Clark College in Oregon,
Lewinsky had career goals; at one time she considered getting an
advanced degree in psychology or going to law school. According to
the Starr report, she tried unsuccessfully to impress the president
with her intellect, offering views on education reform or ``my
stupid ideas about what I thought should be done in the
administration.'' Once, when she was ``babbling on about
something,'' the president suddenly kissed her, ``kind of to shut
me up, I think,'' Lewinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Women who have been snared in political sex scandals far less
lofty than Lewinsky's admit they had a hard time going beyond their
15 minutes of fame, finding a career, and getting a life.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Rice Hughes got married, became a born-again Christian,
and now is head of a grass-roots group that battles Internet
pornography. In 1980, Rita Jenrette said she had sex with her
husband, Democratic Representative John Jenrette of South Carolina,
on the Capitol steps and then posed for Playboy magazine. Today she
runs a real estate company but for years ``just wanted to
disappear. I mean, you're just mortified because you'd like to be
anonymous,'' Jenrette said in a recent television interview.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Dale Young, a friend of Lewinsky's, told TV
talk-show host Larry King she expects her to ``land on her feet.''
Young suggested Lewinsky could use her fame to be a spokeswoman for
others who have been ``taken advantage of in a relationship with a
very, very powerful man.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Mitchell, the 28-year-old author of ``A New Kind of
Party Animal,'' says her generation ``won't fall for'' Lewinsky
reinventing or rehabilitating her image like Donna Rice. ``Anybody
who is a peer of Monica's will have a really hard time accepting
her hawking products or being a patroness of charity,'' said
Mitchell, who calls Lewinsky ``naive. My advice to the poor kid is
disappear. Go to Europe or back to California.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more charitable. Susan Forward, author of ``Men who
Hate Women and the Women who Love Them,'' said Lewinsky is young
enough to learn from this bad chapter and grow into a ``productive
person who can get on a career path and focus on herself and not on
having affairs with older, married men. ``While it must be heady
and flattering for the president to say, `hey, baby, I chose you,'
these choices can have terrible consequences,'' Forward said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the consequences is that Lewinsky, already low in
self-esteem, according to her therapist in the Starr report, finds
herself the target of countless raunchy jokes and with the sorry
distinction of being the least-liked character _ in a recent poll,
only 12 percent said they viewed her favorably _ in the whole
drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica won't be forgotten. She will forever be determined by
this notoriety,'' said Suzanne Garment, author of ``Scandal: The
Culture of Mistrust in American Politics.'' ``I suspect she'll have
a social life if she wants it. There are lots of men who would like
to date someone who has been the president's girlfriend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
