<HEADLINE>
FIRMS AGREE TO SOFTEN CLAIMS ON LICE SHAMPOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said Friday that three makers of
over-the-counter head lice treatment shampoos have agreed to stop
using ads asserting that one use of their products will wipe out an
infestation.
</P>
<P>
   Del Pharmaceuticals, Pfizer Inc., and Care Technologies Inc. had
been accused of making sweeping claims about the effectiveness of
their products, without evidence to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   The products cited in the complaint were Del's ``Pronto''
shampoo, Pfizer's ``Rid'' and Care Technologies' ``Clear Lice Egg
Remover and ``Clear Lice Killing Shampoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement called on the companies to make prominent
disclosures in ads, saying that multiple applications of shampoo
may be necessary, and that removing the eggs is essential to
successful treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for Del Pharmaceuticals, based in Uniondale, N.Y., and
Care Technologies, based in Darien, Conn., denied that their ads
deceive parents, and said they were eager to end the FTC case.
Del's president, Charles Hinkaty, said he wanted to settle the
charges ``rather than engage in protracted debate.'' Pfizer could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups, such as the Newton-based National Pediculosis
Association, have urged parents to focus on removing nits manually
rather than rely on shampoos. Others, including researchers from
the Harvard School of Public Health, say lice-killing shampoos may
be helpful, given an effort to remove each nit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1928EDT &QL; 
