</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MISBEHAVIOR `INDEFENSIBLE,' GORE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Vice President Al Gore, making his first extended
remarks on the White House sex scandal, Friday condemned President
Clinton's misbehavior with a White House intern and called the
president's actions ``indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Concord Monitor, Gore said he feels bad
for Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton, but he defended the
president's record in office and praised him for his handling of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   It was a delicate dance for the vice president as he sought to
remain loyal without condoning Clinton's adultery and misleading
statements. But in a series of interviews with local media, Gore
was gradually forced to answer direct questions about the scandal.
Until Friday, Gore had given only short statements of support for
Clinton, whom he repeatedly describes as ``my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his own presidential aspirations had been
tarnished, Gore told the Monitor: ``This shouldn't be about
politics. This should be about what's right for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he condemned Clinton's escapades with former
intern Monica S. Lewinsky, Gore said: ``He himself has condemned it
_ of course.'' He also said his reaction is the same as the
president's reaction to his own wrongdoing. ``He has said it is
wrong,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed for a more personal response to the report by
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, Gore said he had given a
personal response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with him that it's indefensible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was wrong. By and large, the country puts its
reaction to what he did in a larger perspective and balances it
against all the good things he's done as president, and there's no
question whatsoever that he has been and is a great president,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore refused to criticize Starr and said Clinton will not resign
from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it will end up is finishing his term with a
distinguished record that will go down in history as a virtuoso
performance using economic recovery and American renaissance
producing solutions to problems once thought impossible to solve,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to resign, nor should he,'' Gore said,
insisting that he is not distracted by the ongoing scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was asked by the Monitor, and later by The Manchester
Union-Leader, if Clinton had apologized to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never revealed my private conversations with the
president,'' Gore said, ``and I'm not going to start now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Union-Leader also questioned Gore about how parents should
talk to their children about the president's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president said what he did was wrong and indefensible,''
Gore said. ``He has asked for forgiveness. Each parent has to
interpret that for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore assiduously tried to stick to a message of health care and
job creation in his third visit of the year to New Hampshire, home
of the first-in-the-nation presidential primary. During trips to
Keene, Nashua, and Manchester Friday, Gore avoided reporters from
The Boston Globe, The Chicago Tribune, The Washington Post, The New
York Times, ABC News, and CNN. (Tape recordings of Gore's
interviews with local media were provided to national reporters.)
</P>
<P>
   But during an interview with Manchester's WMUR-TV, Gore was
asked whether he had read the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really, but I feel like I'm thoroughly familiar with
it based upon briefings and the news accounts,'' said Gore, clearly
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore criticized the House Judiciary Committee's decision
to release the videotape of Clinton's testimony before the grand
jury investigating Whitewater. ``They should adopt a more
bipartisan approach to this,'' he said in response to a shouted
question.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he believes that people in New Hampshire and around
the country are focused on issues, and that Clinton's behavior will
not become fodder for the midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   If the people are focused on Clinton's problems, it would be
tough to tell from Gore's events Friday. Appearing with New
Hampshire Governor Jeanne Shaheen, Gore led a reverse town-hall
style forum on health care with a preselected audience of patients
and health-care providers. Instead of allowing members of the
audience to ask questions, Gore asked the questions, preempting
anything off his message of health care for all.
</P>
<P>
   Gore knew the stories that each audience member would tell
before they told them. ``Let's start with Judy Weisberg,'' he said,
noting that she has four children and no health insurance for any
of them until recently. ``What do you do when they have a serious
accident or illness?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pay out of pocket,'' Weisberg explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it mean to you to have them covered?'' Gore followed
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be gambling with their health,'' she said
dutifully.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was glad that Weisberg's children are now covered
by health insurance made available through a joint federal-state
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anything you'd like to say to Governor Shaheen?'' he
prompted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Weisberg said. ``Thank you, Governor Shaheen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
