<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS &LR;      09-18 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI WARNED EX-BULGER GIRLFRIEND OF DANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ To get James ``Whitey'' Bulger's longtime girlfriend to
cooperate with the FBI, agents told her that Bulger might kill her
for knowing too much.
</P>
<P>
   Yet agents didn't contact Teresa Stanley, Bulger's companion of
three decades, for more than a year after Bulger dropped her off at
a South Shore restaurant in late January 1995 to begin his life on
the run, according to testimony Friday in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15 months after Stanley returned home to South Boston, FBI
agent John Gamel wrote Stanley a letter seeking help in finding
Bulger. In a meeting in a restaurant, Gamel warned Stanley that
Bulger might murder her to keep her quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I didn't know anything about his business,'' the
57-year-old banquet waitress testified.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had learned long ago not to ask Bulger too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever asked him a question he would tell me to mind my own
business. He would say it's none of my concern,'' Stanley
testified. ``So, I never asked any questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even when she and Bulger heard on the car radio in early
January 1995, while returning to South Boston from a cross-country
trip, that Bulger's criminal sidekick, Stephen Flemmi, had been
arrested, and that authorities wanted Bulger too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ask him what was going on?'' asked Assistant US
Attorney Fred M. Wyshak Jr., who called Stanley as a witness to
rebut Flemmi's claim that Bulger fled after being tipped off by FBI
supervisor John Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``No ... I didn't want to get into another argument,'' Stanley
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than return home, Bulger and Stanley detoured to Long
Island, where he traded his car for a different model. Then they
headed to a Manhattan hotel, where they watched an episode of
``America's Most Wanted'' featuring Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Jan. 23, 1995, Bulger dropped Stanley off at a
Hingham restaurant, before heading to Fields Corner in Dorchester
to meet with his longtime criminal associate, Kevin Weeks. Then
Bulger picked up Catherine Greig, the woman he was seeing behind
Stanley's back for 20 of the 30 years they were together, and
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-examining Stanley, defense lawyer Anthony M. Cardinale,
who represents one of Flemmi's codefendants, New England Mafia boss
Francis P. Salemme, established through an FBI document that
Stanley was not &UR;  &LR; interviewed by the bureau until April 29, 1996.
Stanley testified that she believed the FBI sent her a letter
within 6 to 9 months of her return.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in contacting Stanley supports assertions _ first
voiced by defense lawyers last year when Bulger and Flemmi were
unmasked as FBI informants _ that the bureau was in no hurry to
catch Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau has denied dragging its feet and offered a $250,000
reward for Bulger's capture last year.
</P>
<P>
   After concluding her testimony, Stanley said outside the
courtroom that she's no longer worried about Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``I just had to forget. I can't worry about it anymore,'' she
said. ``I'm just trying to forget that whole existence. I'm trying
to erase 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In other testimony Friday, former FBI organized crime supervisor
James A. Ring, who testified at length earlier in the hearings, was
recalled by the government to rebut key points in Flemmi's
testimony, including Flemmi's &UR;  &LR; claim that he and Bulger were
promised protection from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never told them that,'' said Ring. ``I didn't have the
capacity to tell them that.'' Ring also denied Flemmi's claim that
he had warned Bulger to stay away from a Boston police lieutenant
who was ``wired'' as part of a police corruption probe in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Shelley Murphy of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
