<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3425 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JIMMYPAGE-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      09-18 1508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JIMMYPAGE-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGENDARY JIMMY PAGE SPEAKS OUT  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY RODGERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Ask any rock musician with a few years under his or
her belt for the short list of truly legendary guitarists, and the
name Jimmy Page is sure to be mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage in the '70s with his monster band, Led Zeppelin, Page
was a force to be reckoned with. Clad in black or white outfits
adorned with flaming dragons or celestial bodies, he attacked his
instrument with such speed that his fingers blurred.
</P>
<P>
   With a flair for the dramatic, Page would saw on the strings of
his Les Paul with a violin bow on occasion, and prance about as he
launched booming musical missiles into the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Page had the licks and chutzpah to go toe-to-toe
with the orgasmic vocals of Robert Plant. Nearly two decades after
Led Zeppelin's demise, Page and Plant are on tour together _ their
second in four years.
</P>
<P>
   This outing ostensibly supports the pair's energetic new album,
``Walking Into Clarksdale.'' But as Page explained in a recent
interview with ``The Arizona Republic,'' it also reprises
Zeppelin's classic catalog in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Page, 54, spoke via phone from a tour stop in Vancouver, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: On your ``Walking Into Clarksdale'' album and current
tour, you and Robert have stripped things back to a four-piece
band. What inspired you to move in that direction?
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: It was the most obvious thing to do, really. We'd always
played that way; it felt (like) the most natural combination of
all, to play as that unit. It is basically a four-piece. . . . The
whole meat and potatoes of the show really is improvisation. Not
lengthy improvisation _ the songs change shape. They're totally
recognizable but then people can see, hey, they're thinking about
that and that's cool. . . . What we're really doing now is really
going out there and doing a serious rock and roll set. . . . Every
set's different every night. If you think about it, that's what
I've done all the way back to the Yardbirds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've loaded up your set list on this tour with Led Zeppelin
classics as well as some tunes from your new album. Why the
decision to go that way?
</P>
<P>
   A: We teamed up for the last tour, ``Unledded,'' and we went
around with the orchestras and the ethnic musicians. . . . We
revisited a lot of numbers like ``Kashmir'' and gave them new
colors and new textures. . . . In the (current) set, we're doing
two numbers that one would have assumed would have been on the
``Unledded'' tour _ ``Going to California ''and ``Tangerine.''
Everything seems to work to the opposite of what people would
expect of you! Now, having done the new album, the songs that are
employed from it fit well within the set. They're presented in the
best places, so it doesn't differ at all within context. And the
rest of the material obviously is the songs that we wrote and
performed from the past and the songs that we feel good playing.
That's the most important thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Reports from the tour indicate that you two are in your best
musical form in years. Any reason behind that? Perhaps working a
bit of rust off the last time around, and now you're really in
stride?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, there was no rust on the last time around; the only
problem was that there was so much information for the audience to
take in with two orchestras going at once with the rock band
underneath. . . . But now it's back to how I've always been used to
playing, which is exploring the dynamics of the guitar so they can
hear every nuance, every subtlety and every attack. . . . It's now
totally up front, and you can't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about the chemistry between you and Robert these
days, as opposed to when you worked together years ago. With the
passage of time, is it still the same basic feeling?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's probably more focused now because we've learned from the
past. We know what we are, and we know how to get the best out of
each other, really.
</P>
<P>
   Q: That's on both a personal and a musical level?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How far did the two of you drift apart during that period
(1980 to 1994)?
</P>
<P>
   A: About as far a you could go. . . . If you look at what one
was doing and what the other was doing, it was pretty obvious that
we'd gone that far, and we sort of came back around.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On a personal level, too?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would say in every way. But as it came together, like
walking around the edge of a circle in two different directions, we
bonded up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It must have been an imposing feeling going into that
rehearsal studio in north London that first day (Page's first
studio session with Plant in 14 years).
</P>
<P>
   A: It was sort of a make or break day, but it didn't bother me.
I knew what could be done, what would be done.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've been at this game more than 30 years. Is it more of a
challenge to motivate yourself to compose and tour?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are certain dates as you go through a tour _ key dates,
magical dates, and they're so good. The most important thing for me
is to keep re-creating that and getting better and better. That's
the prime motivation for me, to keep topping the previous show. You
keep building to a point where it gets scary.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've always seemed like a guy who doesn't mind sitting in
the studio and twisting knobs, and you're a wonderful performer.
Does one or the other pull at you stronger as you get a bit older?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm sort of addicted to the adrenaline buzz that you get
playing live. I realize now that it's such a part of my addictive
personality that I have to do that. . . . When you're in the studio
working with the remasters (of Led Zeppelin material), that's
purely technique.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've brought so many musical influences to the table over
the years; I understand you traveled to Brazil before this tour.
What types of music currently intrigue you?
</P>
<P>
   A: In Brazil, there's the sort of music that most people are
aware of . . . those beautiful chord sequences and melodies which
are astonishing. . . . But really beneath it all, there's this sort
of trance drumming. Where I go in Brazil, there's a river that
intersects a village, so there's a hill on each side of it. And
where I stay is on the far side, where you can hear the drums going
on all night, where they're having their . . . magical ceremonies,
healing ceremonies. And you can't escape it. There's two things
there, really: rhythm and sex. And you breathe it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Over the years, a Middle Eastern flavor has crept into your
music. What are the roots of that for you and Robert?
</P>
<P>
   A: Again, it's rhythm. What we're talking about now from Brazil
and Morocco is basically African. It's what came over here to be
blues and then rock and roll. . . . We found that within Arabic
music, Moroccan music, there were some extremely seductive lines -
especially when they started to bring in strings and orchestras.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the years since Zeppelin broke up, you've teamed with Paul
Rodgers in The Firm as well as David Coverdale. Were those outings
satisfying and/or frustrating?
</P>
<P>
   A: Working with Robert Plant, Paul Rodgers and John Miles as
well, on the ``Outrider ''tour . . . and then David Coverdale _
they're all tremendous singers and I've been lucky to work with
people like that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was there a reason that you came full circle back to Robert
Plant?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was obvious that the two of us had a chemistry which I
didn't have with the other people, though we worked well together.
There was a particularly special chemistry that Robert and I had
together. . . . It was clearly evident when we came back together
and wrote two songs on the first day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Led Zeppelin broke so many rules and set so many precedents
as to how rock and roll is performed and marketed. You ignored the
singles charts and tipped the financial scales toward the artist
and away from the concert promoter. What possessed you to push the
status quo instead of playing it safe?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because the music was more important than the business. . . .
The music said more than what the business was going to say. In
those days, we didn't want to break up an album and have singles.
These days, singles are really of the utmost importance. But in
those days, you have to see it as what it was: We just believed
collectively and individually in what we were doing. . . . We
didn't want to be sidetracked with any sort of nonsense. The album
would go out, and we'd just do the concerts, and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the ``Clarksdale'' album getting good airplay and the
two of you in fine form, have you and Robert looked past this
current tour?
</P>
<P>
   A: We've got a couple of plans, actually, and they're
diametrically opposed. Not that we're disagreeing, it's just that
there's two different things to do. . . . Both projects are very
interesting, but I'd rather it come as a bit of a surprise. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Larry Rodgers can be reached at larry.rodgers(at)pni.com via email.
</P>
</TEXT>
