<SLUG> BC-EMLICO-SETTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GE, LLOYD'S SETTLE EMLICO CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a pact that finally ends General Electric Co.'s costly legal
troubles over its collapsed insurer, GE and Lloyd's of London have
reached an agreement that settles Lloyd's claims against the failed
unit, known as Emlico, sources familiar with the matter said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Terms and size of the out-of-court settlement were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The deal comes after similar agreements between Fairfield,
Conn.-based GE and other global reinsurers of Emlico, including
Kemper Re, Allstate, Hanover Re and General Re. Another reinsurer,
Commercial Union, is still in arbitration proceedings against GE.
</P>
<P>
   Both LLoyd's, which is not a company but a London-based exchange
representing scores of individual insurers, and GE declined to
comment on the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Emlico, whose sole policy holder was GE, relocated to Bermuda
from Massachusetts in 1995, citing more favorable business
conditions. It then declared bankruptcy, leaving its reinsurers
holding the bill for around $500 million needed for reserves to
cover GE's asbestos and environmental liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Angered reinsurers sued in Massachusetts courts, charging that
Emlico knew it was bankrupt and that it relocated to avoid lawsuits
stateside. The reinsurers had worried that a formal liquidation of
Emlico in Bermuda would be more favorable to GE than to them.
</P>
<P>
   The case cast a cloud over Insurance Commissioner Linda
Ruthardt's decision to allow Emlico to relocate to a foreign
country. The Massachusetts Supreme Court ruled earlier this year
that Ruthardt had erred.
</P>
<P>
   GE, the manufacturing, technology, and services giant, faces
what some observers say could amount to $2 billion in cleanup costs
related to its US environmental liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Emlico existed to insure GE's corporate activities, as well as
to provide workman's compensation and other products to GE
employees. The firm must still be formally liquidated, and it is
unclear whether a Boston-based US District Court judge will move to
allow the proceedings to take place in Massachusetts instead of
Bermuda, where they are ongoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3431 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-COALITION-BOS     09-18 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COALITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COALITION, IN CONVENTION, CASTIGATES CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For many members of the Christian Coalition, the
issue isn't whether President Clinton must go, but what form his
departure will take.
</P>
<P>
   The rallying cry for religious conservatives Friday at their
annual ``Road to Victory'' convention was ``Impeach him!'' as
several speakers, including coalition founder Pat Robertson,
insisted Congress must do its constitutional duty and oust the
president for immoral behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue is not Little Rock on
the Potomac,'' said Robertson, adding that Clinton was ``debauched,
debased, and defamed'' by his sexual affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky. ``As landlords of the White House, it's time to tell this
occupant his lease has expired.''
</P>
<P>
   To a standing ovation, Robertson said that allowing the
president to resign with his government pension and the possible
promise of a pardon ``wouldn't be all that bad for him.''
Congress's duty is to impeach him, Robertson said. ``While
resignation might be easier for America, it's not best for
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's comments drew criticism from C. Welton Gaddy,
director of the Interfaith Alliance. ``As the opening speakers
filled the hall with divisive rhetoric, it was apparent that
hardball partisan politics, pure and simple, drive the coalition,''
Gaddy said.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition's political clout and power to turn out voters was
noted by Ralph Reed, the group's former executive director, who
warned candidates of both parties that they will be held
accountable by religious conservatives in November for how they
handle the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there are many in the upper reaches (of the GOP)
who are counseling timidity,'' Reed told the 3,500 delegates.
``They say be quiet, stay out of the cameras, and let the process
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, we didn't work, bleed, and pray to attain a
Republican majority in order to preside over the funeral of a
failed politician,'' said Reed, who is now a political consultant.
``Our goal is to restore righteousness to a country that has lost
its way.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott seemed to take heed as they, along with other members of the
House leadership, paid their respects and pledged their allegiance
to the conservative grass-roots activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the president will do the right thing, but we
will do the right thing,'' Lott said. He said he ``prays'' God
helps elect enough new GOP senators to give Republicans a
two-thirds majority and the ability to override presidential vetoes
of bills the coalition supports, including those that restrict
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates reacted with moans of disappointment and angry
boos when Lott announced the Senate Friday failed by three votes to
oveturn Clinton's veto of a bill to ban certain late-term abortion
procedures. The issue is dead for this term, but Lott said he might
revive it next year.
</P>
<P>
   Former Lt. Col. Oliver North energized the mostly white and
middle-aged audience when he told them Congress must not ``cop
out'' with a meaningless censure of the president. North, whose
three felony convictions for his role in the Iran-contra affair
were overturned on appeal, said the rule of law must be applied to
Clinton for abusing the public trust.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle also got an enthusiastic
reception from the crowd and a mini-demonstration from several
dozen supporters carrying ``Run, Dan, Run in 2000'' placards as he
spoke of the need to replace Clinton with a president who makes
morality central to his private life and public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Other GOP presidential hopefuls were planning to woo the
delegates with speeches today. Friday they simply entertained them:
Missouri Senator John Ashcroft scooped ice cream sundaes; Gary
Bauer of the Family Research Council held a late afternoon
reception; and businessman Steve Forbes hosted a fiesta, complete
with a mariachi band.
</P>
<P>
   The intense courtship of the coalition shows how much some
politicians want to be in step with the family-values message of
the religious right. ``We used to be scoffed at when we said morals
and ethics do count in a president,'' said Evelyn Reilly of
Waltham, executive director of the Christian Coalition in
Massachusetts. ``I guess you could say we've been vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's apologies and pleas for foregiveness were acknowledged
but not embraced by the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The view here is that if you confess your sins, we'll give you
space. But if you pull a fast one on God, you're going to pay a
price,'' said Chip Berlet, an analyst for Political Research
Associates, a Somerville-based group that studies the religious
right. ``If you wanted to find the Christian Coalition's poster boy
for Satan's plaything, look no further than Bill Clinton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
