<SLUG> BC-EMC-EGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGAN TO LEAVE COMPANY HIS FATHER FOUNDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John R. Egan, executive vice president of EMC Corp. and son of
the company's feisty founder, will leave EMC to devote his energies
to his family and his venture capital company, according to the
Hopkinton, Mass. maker of data storage devices.
</P>
<P>
   Egan will be replaced by Paul E. Noble, Jr., a 17-year veteran
at EMC and the company's senior vice president for business
development.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was not available for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement marks the departure of the last Egan to be an
executive of EMC, a company cofounded by Egan's father, Richard J.
Egan, who now serves as chairman of the board. At one point, John
Egan worked at EMC alongside his two brothers, Michael and Chris.
John and his parents, who together own 1.3 percent of the company's
stock, will remain on the company's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ruettgers, EMC's chief executive, said John Egan cited
as reasons for his departure a desire to spend more time with his
family. Egan, 40, has three school-age children.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered a possible heir to run EMC, Egan has been
gradually withdrawing from the company's day-to-day operations. The
news of his departure, therefore, did not surprise Wall Street
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was expected to happen sooner or later,'' said Mark
Goodstadt, a technology stock analyst with S&AMP;P Equity Group in New
York. ``It was not a great shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts appeared to take comfort in the fact that Noble, Egan's
replacement, has been with EMC since 1981, when the company was
just 2 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Noble is very experienced,'' said Mark Kelleher, an
analyst with Tucker Anthony in Boston. ``He's quite capable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelleher noted that Noble built and grew the company's reselling
business, which makes up more than 25 percent of the company's
total sales. That business pairs an EMC storage device with a
high-end computer; the two are then sold as a package to business
customers.
</P>
<P>
   EMC is also adding to its bench of senior management. The
company said it hired Cosmo Santullo as vice president and general
manager of enterprise software and Bruce Rampe as senior vice
president for global marketing. Santullo was general manager of IBM
Corp.'s personal computer division, while Rampe was president of
BBN Software Products, a division of BBN Corp.
</P>
<P>
   EMC shares fell 1 11/16 yesterday to 53 3/8 on the New York
Stock Exchange. While the stock is down from a 52-week high of 58
1/8, it has gained 94 percent year-to-date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
