u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN-BOS &LR;      09-18 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CAMPAIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDEALISM GONE FROM CLINTON POLITICAL TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even by the standards of presidential campaigns,
Bill Clinton's 1992 team was a boisterous, self-assured group. They
were going to end 12 years of Republican leadership, reshape the
Democratic party, and change the world.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they are sickened by the media's ravenous appetite for
scandal and livid at Kenneth Starr's incessant probes. And, in many
cases, they are disillusioned with Clinton, the man who used to
inspire them.
</P>
<P>
   ``How on earth could you not be disappointed?'' said David
Stone, who helped the Clinton campaign in Pennsylvania while he
served as a staff member for Democratic Senator Harris Wofford.
``How could you not be stunned by the incredible recklessness (of
Clinton's affair)? It's just breathtaking.''
</P>
<P>
   As Congress decides whether the Starr report will lead to an
impeachment inquiry, this is a time for reflection among the men
and women who knew Clinton. Well-known former aides such as George
Stephanopoulos, who have gone on to high-paying, high-profile
careers, have had their say.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the campaigners were young believers who did not
become famous. They left college and jobs to plot strategy, drive
Clinton through snowstorms, and write speeches. They trusted
Clinton, a candidate who seemed personally flawed yet charismatic
and brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most dedicated acolytes went on to join the
administration after the election, so they ended up spending
several years of their lives working for Clinton. They endured
setbacks on health-care reform and reversals in the 1994 and 1996
congressional elections, but the last few days of revelations about
Clinton's affair with Monica S. Lewinsky have been downright
humiliating for them.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few of the original Clintonites still believe in the
president, and perhaps they have been hit hardest of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still adore him without a doubt, but I feel like a bottle of
tonic that has no bubbles left,'' said Neel Lattimore, who was
considered an old-timer when he joined the '92 campaign at age 31.
</P>
<P>
   After the election, Lattimore spent five years in the press
office of Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``I'm hurting for Clinton, I'm
hurting for Hillary and frankly I'm hurting for myself because I
feel this tremendous sense of loss. People are joking, and it's
devastating. I invested six years of my life working for Clinton,
and it's not how I want him to be remembered because it's not how I
want my public service to be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Connolly, a reserve officer, joined the Army's 82nd Airborne
Division in Iraq during the Gulf War, then stayed on in Kuwait and
Saudi Arabia for nearly a year. The whole time, he followed
American politics through two-week-old copies of Time and Newsweek.
Something about Clinton's charm was infectious, even thousands of
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, who had worked for Michael Dukakis' 1988 campaign,
sought out an old colleague, Michael Whouley, a Clinton adviser.
Two weeks after returning to the United States, Connolly was
directing Hillary Clinton's scheduling operation in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton won, Connolly went on to work at the Pentagon. He
earned fame among colleagues when he quit out of principle in April
1996. Connolly supported a ban on anti-personnel mines, but Clinton
and his top commanders did not.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly was not sore at Clinton then and he isn't now. He still
admires the president's stands on gun control and other issues. But
he wonders how Clinton could hurt his most loyal followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for those I knew personally or those I just knew
by reputation or name, people who toil each day for 12 or 14 hours
working for this man or this administration, working on policies we
believe in,'' says Connolly, who is now a social studies teacher at
a New York high school. ``And then to have this happen and
undermine the whole effort...''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, as if digesting the sordid details of the Starr
report. ``It appears, as the record stands now, that the president
was engaged in activities that would jeopardize beliefs he held his
entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the '92 Clinton campaign reminisce about frenetic
days of living on $10 per diem expenses, sleeping six people in
cramped motel rooms, showing up at airports to pick up tickets
without knowing where they were going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope was always that you could look back at this time and
compare it to working in Bobby Kennedy's Justice Department, or
working on the Great Society,'' said one campaigner who joined the
administration for a few years before taking a private job. ``I and
so many of the people I have worked with now feel that we have lost
a chance at that legacy, for something so reckless.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of those interviewed, he asked not to be named. Much
of his anger is directed at Starr, who spent months ``writing what
is basically a pulp novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most cynical comments come from the campaigners who
worked with Clinton in the New Hampshire primary in February 1992,
when he denied, and then deflected, questions about an affair with
lounge singer Gennifer Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one who was with Clinton in New Hampshire could be naive
enough to discount the Lewinsky allegations when they first came
out,'' said one of Clinton's earliest supporters, who logged
thousands of miles on the road during the campaign and now works in
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Clinton still has ardent defenders. Lisa Caputo, who
joined the campaign in 1992, ran the media operation at the
Democratic National Convention and went on to serve as Hillary
Clinton's press secretary two years ago. ``Clearly, in my view,
there has been a creation of a fourth branch of government with the
independent counsel law,'' she said. ``I think this has all gone
too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gallagher, was a 22-year old Wesleyan College liberal arts
graduate when he signed on to the Clinton campaign in his home
state of New Hampshire in September 1991. He went on to become the
campaign's travel director, based in Little Rock, Ark., and then to
become a White House aide helping with national service programs.
</P>
<P>
   Reached in San Francisco where he now is in the private sector,
Gallagher said Americans should stop intruding on the president's
personal life. Later, he called back to vent his frustration _ not
at Clinton, but at Clinton's detractors. ``The '92 campaign was
more about Bill Clinton's ideas than Bill Clinton as a person,'' he
said. ``Those who mistook the man for the message seven years ago
appeared to be the most distracted and disappointed today.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Connolly put it this way: ``I never believed I was
in a campaign to elect someone Pope.''
</P>
<P>
   A Massachusetts native who worked on the Clinton campaign and
then spent four years in the White House said she has gone through
the whole gamut of relations: denying Clinton's involvement in
January, feeling sorrow because of the Starr report's revelations
last week, and seething with anger at the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the days go on, I tend to agree with what Clinton said in
Martha's Vineyard _ there is a time for forgiveness,'' said the
woman who took a job in business. ``My biggest concern is what's
best for the country, and what's best for the country is not
destroying this man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
