<HEADLINE>
BANK OF N.E. TRUSTEE AGREES TO BANKRUPTCY TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A bankruptcy trustee for Bank of New England Corp.
reached a tentative settlement with federal regulators Friday that
would pay $140 million to creditors of the failed banking company.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement with the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. still
must be approved by the FDIC's board and US Bankruptcy Court Judge
William C. Hillman. A lawyer representing regulators said the FDIC
hopes to gain board approval next month.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators seized Bank of New England on Jan. 6, 1991, marking
the largest-ever bank failure in the New England region. The
company's list of creditors was dominated by bond investors who
were holding more than $700 million in Bank of New England
securities.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of New England was the second-largest banking company in
New England when it was pulled under by a disastrous portfolio of
bad real estate and commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
   Bankruptcy trustee Ben Branch had sued the FDIC, alleging that
more than $200 million belonging to Bank of New England bondholders
had improperly fallen into the hands of the regulators. The case
had been scheduled to go to trial Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a fair settlement and a hard-fought settlment,''
said Bill Eddleman, an analyst at APS Financial Corp. of Houston,
who has been tracking the value of the Bank of New England debt for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement would provide the largest recovery by far for
Bank of New England creditors since the company failed. They have
received about $40 million in distributions to date.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of New England Corp., which issued stock and bonds, was a
holding company that technically owned its banks as subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Months before it failed, Bank of New England Corp. had issued
$200 million in new bonds and distributed the money among its bank
subsidiaries. Once the money moved to the banks, it fell beyond the
legal grasp of bondholders and into the hands of the FDIC for good.
</P>
<P>
   Branch had charged that the banking company was actually
insolvent before the bond issue and well before the banks were
taken over by regulators. Dueling consultants issued hundreds of
pages of financial reports haggling over Bank of New England's
condition in the final months of its business life.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of New England bondholders are divided into senior and
junior camps, depending on what types of securities they had
purchased. Senior creditors had filed claims for about $225 million
and junior creditors had claims of about $525 million.
</P>
<P>
   Eddleman said nearly all of the $140 million in the proposed
FDIC settlment would end up in the hands of senior bondholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
