<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-WOODWARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTS AT STAKE IN WOODWARD FOR SKIP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a lot more at stake than a simple victory
for Skip Away in Saturday's $500,000 Woodward Stakes at Belmont
Park. While his four foes will be running for the $300,000 winner's
purse, Skip Away will be racing for an undefeated season, a leg up
on the all-time North American earnings record, and to keep his
place atop the Horse of the Year standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are finally coming to understand that Skip Away is one
of the greatest horses of all time,'' said Sonny Hine, 67, who
trains Skip Away for his wife, Carolyn. ``Believe me, I don't say
that lightly. I've been around long enough to see some great
horses. All I tell people to do is look at Skip Away's record. He's
never had a break. He's raced in every important race there is and
he has always run his heart out.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away, age 5, has a lifetime record of 35-17-10-5 and
$9,206,360 in earnings. If he wins the Woodward and his next
scheduled start, the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup at Belmont
Oct. 10, which offers $600,000 to the winner, he will break Cigar's
mark of $9,999,815. The big gray has won six in a row this year,
eight overall, and has not been beaten since the now-retired Formal
Gold ran away from him in last year's Woodward. Skip Away finished
1997 strongly, winning the Jockey Club for the second straight year
and the Breeders' Cup Classic at Hollywood Park. However, he lost
the Horse of the Year vote to 2-year-old Favorite Trick, which
embittered Hine, who is doing everything he can to make sure his
horse is not passed over again..
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken this eight-race winning streak for people to
finally give him the respect he deserves, but I want to do more for
him,'' he said. ``He's been good to all of us. He gave Carolyn an
Eclipse Award (Owner of the Year). He helped the careers of some of
the jockeys who rode him. And he's been good for the game. I want
him to get that money title because I think it will make a lot of
people realize just what kind of horse they've been watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The Woodward offers Skip Away, the 6-5 choice, a stern test.
Free House, one of the best of last year's 3-year-olds, has
returned in tremendous form, capturing both of his starts this
season, including the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar Aug.
15, by open lengths. Gentlemen, who defeated Skip Away in last
year's Pimlico Special, is a little bit off his game this year at
age 6, but he's still one of the fastest horses in the country. As
if that's not enough, Coronado's Quest has won five in a row,
including the $1 million Haskell and the $750,000 Travers, and
might be this year's best 3-year-old. Only Running Stag, a European
invader who has been victorious at the Group III level on the
grass, seems overmatched in the elite field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Woodward has those three other good horses, and beating
them would certainly bring Skip Away some attention,'' said Hine.
``Then I really want to win the Jockey Club Gold Cup three years in
a row. Kelso won it five years in a row (1960-64), and to get
three, I think, would cause people to realize how great a horse
Skip Away is.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then, of course, there's the Breeders' Cup. We spent
$480,000 to run (the supplemental fee to the $4 million Classic)
last year because we believed in our horse and he made us look
smart. So I would like for him to win back-to-back Breeders' Cups,
go to the farm as the top money earner, and go with everybody
knowing that he is one of the greatest horses of all time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
