<HEADER>
A3440 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-TV-LADN     09-18 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VITAL SIGNS WEAK ON MONDAY DEBUTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; The networks will be ushering in the nw season
today. And if you liked what you saw last season, you'll probably
like this one too, because the themes are all familiar.
</P>
<P>
   NBC gives us two sitcoms about attractive single people in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   How unique.
</P>
<P>
   CBS unveils three new shows. There is a stand-up comic playing a
family man on Long Island. Can you say ``Raymond''? I knew you
could. The Eye also adds a medical drama not to be confused with
``Chicago Hope'' and, in the post-``Murphy Brown'' era, a show set
in a TV newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   And the WB's entry stars pretty young people in a small town
named for a body of water into which ``Dawson's Creek'' presumably
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at tonight's new offerings. &QL; 
CONRAD BLOOM &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Bloom (Mark Feuerstein) likes women, but maybe too much
for his own good.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's his demanding mother (who makes him be her partner
in ballroom dancing class), his needy ex-girlfriend or hippie
sister (who gets busted at an animal-rights rally), Conrad is
always called in to save the day.
</P>
<P>
   He's a sensitive, good-looking guy who would be a great catch,
except that all his platonic relationships take up so much time he
is rarely available to be caught.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad works in an advertising agency, which lends itself to
some pretty hacky humor. George Dorsey (Steve Landesberg) plays a
burned-out former advertising genius _ and Conrad's hero _ who has
turned his Clio Award into a bong.
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein is very likable, and his timing gets the job done.
The show is at times funny, albeit too jokey.
</P>
<P>
   There are some terribly clunky scenes in the pilot, and the
older cast members _ like Linda Lavin (formerly of ``Alice''), who
plays Conrad's mom, and Landesberg _ seem out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is an above-average sitcom with a lead character
women will love and guys still may want to be friends with. &QL; 
WILL &AMP; GRACE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a great idea. Introduce network television's first gay
leading man and then offend the very people you are trying to
appease.
</P>
<P>
   Will Truman (Eric McCormack) does a nice job of breaking any gay
stereotypes. He is a handsome lawyer who happens to be gay.
</P>
<P>
   But his friend Jack McFarland (Sean Hayes) is a different story.
When we first meet him, he's singing show tunes, and he continues
to build into a finicky, swishy crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   At the center, this is a buddy comedy between Will and Grace
(Debra Messing). By the end of the first episode, they are both
getting out of serious relationships. They are perfect for each
other. They understand a self-made pop-culture code language,
finish each other's sentences and are both attractive. But when
they kiss, ``Nothing.'' ``Not a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another common bond between them is that they both prefer men.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot story was motoring right along, with Will and Jack
becoming roommates and Grace on her way to getting married. Then
Will tells Grace she can do better than that. After that, the story
falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue is contrived throughout, and, despite the first gay
male lead, following ``Ellen's'' first gay lead character, this is
an ordinary sitcom, NBC style _ slick and urban and certainly
white. &QL; 
THE KING OF QUEENS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Doug Heffernan (Kevin James) is suspended in adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   He drives a truck, has three oddball buddies who urinate
outside, and he likes to call his friends ``mook'' and
``sphincter.'' All they want to do is talk about sex and watch
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Heffernan is also a teddy bear around his thinner and much more
attractive wife.
</P>
<P>
   His life seems complete when his wife gets him a 70-inch TV to
finish out his basement clubhouse, where he hangs with his guys,
one of whom _ now get this _ lives with his mother. This is a
running gag in the show as the guy defends himself by shouting,
``She doesn't drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecstasy turns into agony as Doug's father-in-law (played by
Jerry Stiller in an apparent reprisal of his ``Seinfeld'' Frank
Costanza role) moves in. Not only does Stiller steal every scene
from the hapless series ``star,'' he moves into the basement. Bye
bye TV room.
</P>
<P>
   If this setup sounds familiar, it is. It's an almost
beat-for-beat repeat of the pilot episode for ``That's Life,'' a
miserable failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``King,'' a better program, still features some poor acting and
some outrageous turns for Stiller's character, a pot-smoking old
man who frequents hookers and talks in hip-hop lingo.
</P>
<P>
   The funniest thing in the pilot was the resolution to the
70-inch television dilemma. They move it into the bedroom, where it
jams up against the bed. Doug and his three amigos lie in bed and
watch the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for some reason, the television is gone in episode No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Foreshadowing?
</P>
<P>
   Could be. &QL; 
THE BRIAN BENBEN SHOW &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is more ripe for satire than the local news. Overblown
promos, sensationalized stories, choppers at the ready at the first
sign of a jaywalker.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, ``The Brian Benben Show'' misses most of that and
instead chooses to focus on the downfall of the title character,
played by an actor of the same name. Benben is demoted to
human-interest reporter after younger, more attractive anchors _
Chad Rockwell (Charles Esten) and Tabitha Berkeley (Lisa Thornhill)
_ are brought in and his friend and former human-interest reporter
is killed by a gorilla in a zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The setup is weak, and the writing wavers from clunky to clever.
</P>
<P>
   The most annoying attribute to this show is the supporting cast.
Kevin LaRue plays former jock and sports anchor Wendell Pierce,
who, in a groaner of a scene, explains how he lost his groin in a
football game, and Billy Hernandez plays the gay meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   Benben will stop at nothing to get his job back, including
changing TelePrompTer copy to show up Rockwell. Sounds like a
fireable offense _ but not at this station. No one hardly cared.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is trying to cash in on Benben's (``Dream On'') supposed
name recognition by naming the show and the character after him.
</P>
<P>
   Who knew Benben was so well-known?
</P>
<P>
   If the producers shift the focus of the show and punch it up a
bit, he may actually have the name recognition to carry a show by
the end of the season. &QL; 
L.A. DOCTORS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Score one for smart scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   Men around the country will be watching ``Monday Night
Football.'' Those looking for something a little more substantial
will watch ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   And for people looking for three attractive, sensitive male
doctors and their strong female partner, there will be ``L.A.
Doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS has handed out what has traditionally been its best drama
time slot to a medical drama about guys who care about more than
making money. They leave a large practice and start their own,
trying to worry more about patient care than managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Olin (``thirtysomething'') plays Dr. Roger Cattan, a guy who
grew up poor in Van Nuys and now likes fast cars, fast women and
fancy watches that run on time. He hires a publicist for the
practice and commissions his girlfriend to decorate the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Craven plays family man Dr. Tim Lonner, who has two adopted
children. An earnest physician, he still is more concerned with his
time after work than during.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Roberts is Dr. Evan Newman, a sweet guy who is divorced and
is still friends with his ex-wife. He seems to care the most about
his patients.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Lee plays Dr. Sarah Church, a woman with tremendous
credentials who could get a higher-paying job but likes what the
fellas stand for.
</P>
<P>
   The show walks that fine line between touching and sappy with
varying degrees of success. It is very chatty and could use some
more laughs and a quicker pace.
</P>
<P>
   Any delusions of ``L.A. Doctors'' doing for medicine what ``L.A.
Law'' did for the legal profession are just that.
</P>
<P>
   However, CBS probably found a spot for this program where it
will get some time to find its legs and stick around. &QL; 
HYPERION BAY &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Boy that WB network loves teen idols living in small towns named
for bodies of water.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the Sweeneys. Dennis (a dark-haired Mark-Paul Gosselaar) is
a computer whiz who was the high school geek. His brother Nick
(Dylan Neal) was the popular tough guy growing up.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a comma in a paycheck can make.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-driving Dennis, who wheels into town with hot new
girlfriend Jennifer (Sydney Penny), has talked his computer company
into opening up a plant in Hyperion (somewhere in Northern
California) that could save the dying town. As such, every move the
company makes is big news there.
</P>
<P>
   While his marriage is failing, Honda-driving Nick works for the
family's construction company.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is two guys going different directions on a
one-way street.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is the same in Hyperion Bay, and everyone is keeping
secrets. The girls who once shunned Dennis now flirt with him, and
even his own father may be intimidated by him.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the acting is just comical, however, as there is no real
emotion in the fights between the two brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hyperion Bay'' has more conflict than a border skirmish, and
it all seems forced. Dennis' girlfriend doesn't want to be in
Hyperion, and most others seem to want him gone.
</P>
<P>
   Me, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
