<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 No. 2685 Fri., Sept.18: 
 &HT;     (NYLite items can be published if desired;  please credit the
contributor. Contribute to NYLite and get a NYT rolling-writer
style pen.) &HT;    Dr. NYlite can now be reached by e-mail:  nylite(at)nytimes.com 
(use ``at'' sign sted (at)).
 &HT;    
 &HT;     GOOD DAY, WIRE WANDERERS!!!!! 
 &HT;    Offer not available in any store! (Or any other news service!)
 &HT;    Looking for contributors with wit, style, depth, charm and
genius with jokes, anecdotes, humorous news items, bonus NYLite
offerings, or filler material.
 &HT;    Dr. NYLite will respond with a GENUINE New York Times rolling
writer-style pen if your item is used. (But see coffee mug offer
above.)
 &HT;    All items fit to fax to 212-556-3535 (24 hours), via uniformed
government courier, or, now by e-mail (nylite(at)nytimes.com).
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     STEPHEN WRIGHT, REDUX 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I used to work in a fire hydrant factory.
 &HT;    You couldn't park anywhere near the place.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Last week, I went to a furniture store to look for a
decaffeinated coffee
 &HT;    table. They couldn't help me.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I bought some batteries, but they weren't included.
 &HT;    So I had to buy them again.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I replaced the headlights on my car with strobe lights.
 &HT;    Now it looks like I'm the only one moving.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I wrote a song, but I can't read music.
 &HT;    Every time I hear a new song on the radio,
 &HT;    I think `Hey, maybe I wrote that.`
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I got my driver's license photo taken out of focus on purpose.
 &HT;    Now when I get pulled over the cop looks at it (moving it nearer
&AMP; farther,
 &HT;    trying to see it clearly)....and says,
 &HT;    `Here, you can go.`
 &HT;    
 &HT;    My neighbor has a circular driveway. He can't get out.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I have a hobby.
 &HT;    I have the world's largest collection of sea shells.
 &HT;    I keep it scattered on beaches all over the world.
 &HT;    Maybe you've seen some of it.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     REVERSE EXIT 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    At 3 am a desk clerk at a hotel gets a call from a drunk guy
asking what time the bar opens.
 &HT;    `It opens at noon,` answers the clerk.
 &HT;    About an hour, later he gets a call from the same guy, sounding
even drunker.
 &HT;    `What time does the bar open?` he asks.
 &HT;    `Same time as before - noon,` replies the clerk.
 &HT;    Another hour passes and he calls again, plastered. `Whatjoo shay
the bar opins at?`
 &HT;    The clerk then answers, `It opens at noon, but if you can't
wait, I can have room service send something up to you.`
 &HT;    
 &HT;    `No! I don't wanna git in, ah wanna git OUT!`
 &HT;    
 &HT;     AMERICAN INGENUITY 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    There was this little guy sitting in a bar, drinking, minding
his own business when all of a sudden this great big dude comes in
and WHACK he knocks him off the bar stool and says, `That was a
karate chop from Japan.`
 &HT;    The little guy thinks `GEEZ` but he gets back up on the stool
and starts drinking again when all of a sudden WHACK the big dude
knocks him down AGAIN and says, `That was a judo chop from Korea.`
 &HT;    So the little guy has had enough of this so he leaves and is
gone for an hour or so and when comes back WHACK he knocks the big
dude off his stool and
 &HT;    out cold!!!
 &HT;    The little guy looks at the bartender and says, `When he comes
to, tell him that is a crowbar from Sears.`
 &HT;    
 &HT;     REAL DEFINITIONS 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ADULT:
 &HT;    A person who has stopped growing at both ends and is now growing
in the
 &HT;    middle.
 &HT;    BEAUTY PARLOR:
 &HT;    A place where women curl up and dye.
 &HT;    CANNIBAL:
 &HT;    Someone who is fed up with people.
 &HT;    CHICKENS:
 &HT;    The only animals you eat before they are born and after they are
dead.
 &HT;    COMMITTEE:
 &HT;    A body that keeps minutes and wastes hours.
 &HT;    DUST:
 &HT;    Mud with the juice squeezed out.
 &HT;    EGOTIST:
 &HT;    Someone who is usually me-deep in conversation.
 &HT;    GOSSIP:
 &HT;    A person who will never tell a lie if the truth will do more
damage.
 &HT;    SECRET:
 &HT;    Something you tell to one person at a time.
 &HT;    TOMORROW:
 &HT;    One of the greatest labor saving devices of today.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Marriage 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The wealthy wife of a very successful Jewish businessman went to
the portrait artist for her first sitting. The portrait, a gift for
her husband. She explained to the artist what she wanted:
 &HT;    `You should paint me like I am. These little wrinkles, you put
them on your canvas. The lines under my eyes, the flab on my arms,
the turn in my nose, and the mole on my cheek, they all stay....BUT
on my hands you put lots of rings with big diamonds and emeralds
and bright jewels. Around my neck you put chains of gold and
diamonds. Do you understand?`
 &HT;    The artist looked at her in earnest and asked why she should
want such detail of real life in her physical appearance, but adorn
herself with the phony jewelry.
 &HT;    She replied: `When I die my husband will re-marry.
 &HT;    The new wife, she should go crazy looking for the jewels`.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     WESTERN WIT 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Two cowboys are riding along a trail in the mountains when they
suddenly hear tom toms beating very close to them.
 &HT;    `Oh! That doesn't sound good,` one says to the other.
 &HT;    As soon as the words were spoken, an Indian jumps out from
behind a tree and said, `Yeah, our regular drummer is out sick.`
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     SEARCHING FOR MEANING WITH MISS AMERICA 
 &HT;     By DIANE WHITE    c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are so many ways to amuse yourself while you watch the
Miss America pageant this Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   You could try to reach a consensus about which contestant is
most likely to be abducted by aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Or which is most convinced that God is on her side.
</P>
<P>
   Or which has spent the most money on electrolysis.
</P>
<P>
   You can work up a point-by-point comparison of pageant hosts
past and present, Bert Parks versus Boomer Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming you're old enough to remember Bert Parks.
</P>
<P>
   And if you are, you know there's no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   You can compose your own Big Questions for the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Example: ``If you were Hillary Clinton would you run for
president in 2000?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``What would you, as an individual, do to solve the Y2K
problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``With three games left in the season, the Red Sox have a
four game lead for the American League wild card spot. Explain how
they can lose.''
</P>
<P>
   You can think up interesting platforms that might be adopted by
future contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrian rights.
</P>
<P>
   Or stamping out phobophobia, the fear of fear itself.
</P>
<P>
   Or changing the name of the pageant to Ms. America.
</P>
<P>
   You can speculate wildly about which contestants have had
cosmetic surgery and what they've had done.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can decide if the results are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   You can try to figure out how many finalists are taking Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   And how many should be taking it.
</P>
<P>
   You can guess who's suffering from PMS.
</P>
<P>
   Or who's nervous about her tattoo showing.
</P>
<P>
   Or who's thinking: There must be an easier way than this to win
a college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Stage a mini-debate. Resolved: Intelligent life doesn't begin
before age 30.
</P>
<P>
   Have a lively discussion about what exactly people mean when
they use the word ``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Compare and contrast theories about why it's been 65 years since
someone from New England was crowned Miss America. What does this
say about us as a people?
</P>
<P>
   You can sit there and quietly hope that one of the finalists
will be a ventriloquist.
</P>
<P>
   Or somebody who plays ``Dueling Banjos'' on the accordian.
</P>
<P>
   Or roller skates to ``Amazing Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when you're disappointed, you can try to guess what the
contestants real talents are, as opposed to the ones on display.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Vermont: cow-tipping.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Delaware: parallel parking.
</P>
<P>
   Miss California: ``X-Files'' trivia champion, Western states
division.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Connecticut: currently memorizing the opening paragraphs of
the 100 greatest novels of 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Mississippi: has assembled the world's largest collection
of deviled egg plates.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Maine: juggles lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   You can try to guess how many contestants are dog people and how
many are cat people.
</P>
<P>
   And how many have actually described themselves as ``people
persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Decide which finalist looks the most different in real life,
i.e., when she's not wearing big hair and makeup.
</P>
<P>
   And which is most likley to be in big hair and make up all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Be grateful that you never had to parade around in a swimsuit in
front of 50 million people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This was our solution: Release the Clinton testimony tape but
limit its viewing to folks who know the name of their member of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Would our system work better if Americans elected a special
prosecutor and then had the attorney general appoint a president to
be investigated?
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Ilse from Oelwein says her favorite passage in the Starr
Report was the word ``Counsel'' because it's the very last word.
</P>
<P>
   What's the president's best defense against impeachment? No, not
legal strategies. It's Al Gore out giving speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of newspapers have called for the president to resign.
And, we bet, a few have had phone solicitors call him to take out a
subscription.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton has ordered the government to buy only recycled
paper. Appropriate for publishing recycled ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``America,'' says the president, ``has got a stake in rural
America.'' To say nothing of some steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Andrew plans to build a three-hole golf course at
Buckingham Palace. It's the royal family's approach to nearly
everything _ par-tee on!
</P>
<P>
   An unaccredited California law school is offering all its
courses on the Internet. Would graduates be known as, say, Bob
Smith, Esq. dot com?
</P>
<P>
   New figures show business at restaurants was down a bit
nationally in August. Maybe folks stayed home to eat up all the
stuff in the fridge in doggy bags.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
