<HEADER>
A3445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOLE-DROPCHARGES-COX     09-18 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLE-DROPCHARGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nigeria drops charges against activist Soyinka
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Wole Soyinka took the news in stride Friday: Trying
to make peace with the Nobel Prize-winning writer, the military
government of Nigeria had dropped treason charges against him and
14 other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right thing has been done,'' said Soyinka, a leading
spokesman for Nigeria's democracy movement who teaches at Emory
University in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Associated Press, military ruler Gen.
Abdulsalami Abubakar asked last week that the charges be dropped as
a move toward national reconciliation. Police spokesman Young
Arabamen confirmed to the AP Friday that the charges were withdrawn
on Abubakar's orders.
</P>
<P>
   Soyinka said he had been informed through informal contacts that
the charges were being dropped. Filed in March 1997, the treason
charges claimed Soyinka and the others were behind a series of
bombings against military authorities, but the accusations were
always widely believed to have been invented by the late dictator,
Sani Abacha, who died in June.
</P>
<P>
   Soyinka had gone into self-imposed exile in 1994. Three of the
other accused also went into exile, while the 11 others went to
prison until their release following Abacha's death.
</P>
<P>
   While lifting the charges should clear the way for Soyinka to
return to his country, he said he had no immediate plans for a
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us who have been in exile have remained involved very
intensely in the struggle to remove the dictatorship,'' he said.
``We can now begin to act in a more positive way to become involved
in an authentic democratic process.''
</P>
<P>
   But he made clear that the effort to restore democracy to
Nigeria, which has been dominated by the military for all but a
decade since gaining independence from Britain in 1960, is
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very, very uncharitable if we said no progress is
being made,'' Soyinka said. Abubakar has promised a return to
civilian rule next year; many prisoners have been released; and the
press has been allowed to operate more freely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are following all these various details,'' Soyinka said.
But he added that the Nigerian people, whose hopes have been dashed
before, have been treated brutally over the years and that
structures ensuring democratic proceedings still are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
