<SLUG> BC-SLAVEWALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilgramage of slavery makes its way to Atlanta area
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- For the past four months, 65 sojourners have walked
15 to 20 miles a day tracing the pilgrimage of slavery in this
country. The group of men, women and children have trod the back
roads of America without much fanfare, but with a determination
fueled by prayers and commitment to peace and healing.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which began its journey in Leverett, Mass., is
expected to arrive in the city of Atlanta today. The interracial,
multicultural contingent will visit the Martin Luther King Jr.
Center for Non-Violence Social Change today and, on Sunday, attend
a ``Worship Celebration of the Middle Passage Pilgrimage'' at First
Iconium Baptist Church on Moreland Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to plant some seeds of consciousness,'' said
Ingrid Askew, an African-American Massachusetts actress who helped
organize the walk with Sister Claire Carter, a Japanese Buddhist
nun.
</P>
<P>
   As the travelers make their way across the country, churches and
other organizations have been providing food and water. On
Thursday, when the group passed through Covington, 35 east of
downtown Atlanta, the Rev. Hezekiah Benton, Jr. and members of the
Bethlehem Baptist Church served the group a dinner of collard
greens, green beans, baked chicken, corn bread and rice. The dinner
was sponsored by the African American Arts Council of Covington.
</P>
<P>
   The journey has included visits to four Georgia cities where
slaves worked large plantations, and the site of a slave market in
Louisville, located near Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   The route of the pilgrimage was developed by John Bracey, a
historian in the W.E.B. Dubois African American Studies Department
at the University of Massachusetts. The walk in America is
scheduled to end Nov. 3 in New Orleans. Walkers will board a ship
there headed for West Africa. By Jan. 1, a group of European
walkers called the ``Jubilee Pilgrimage'' will meet up with their
American counterparts in Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   The Nipponzan Myohoji Buddhist Order, a walking order of monks,
is a strong backer of the pilgrimage. The order has been connected
with the world peace movement since World War II. However, the
pilgrimage includes people from all walks of life. For example,
Louise Dunlap is a college professor from Cambridge, Mass. Gregory
Dean-Smith of Washington and Aaron Jones of San Francisco are
actors. Tim Liggett, Raina Askew and Christianna Abel are high
school students. Ronald McDonald is a barber; Tizita Assefa is a
college student. The group also has a political activist, Pio
Celestino of Peru, who has been working with Mexican refugees in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Burton, a Bulgarian pacifist who lives in California,
only read about the struggles associated with slavery growing up in
Bulgaria. He joined the walk because he sees it as a spiritual
journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing what I can to help people come together to work out
issues,'' said Burton, who is carrying the group's two flags
representing the earth and world citizenship as the group walks.
</P>
<P>
   Hirofumi Nasu of Japan quit his job as a pharmaceutical
wholesaler to join the walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is beyond time and place,'' Nasu said. ``We
brought Koreans into our country as charges, did not pay them or
paid them cheaper wages_ that's like slavery. Slavery is one of the
mistakes of history. I am a Buddhist walking and praying to purify
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
