<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amendment to suit charges both Yagers
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Philadelphia millionaire who blames Faye Yager
for the disappearance of this two children now wants to make
Yager's husband a part of a $100 million lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Bipin Shah, an electronic banking entrepreneur, on Friday filed
a amendment to an earlier lawsuit in federal court in Atlanta. The
amendment proposes that Howard Yager be named as a defendant and
accuses the couple of racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Yager is the controversial operator of the Children of the
Underground, a network of safe houses that hides children, and
generally their mothers, from allegedly abusive fathers.
</P>
<P>
   While Faye Yager has been sued before _ she was tried and
acquitted in 1992 in Cobb County on kidnapping and child cruelty
charges _ until this summer her husband hasn't been party to those
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Chilivis, the Atlanta attorney representing Shah, said that
while gathering evidence for the original lawsuit filed in January,
Shah learned that Howard Yager is more involved in the underground
than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Before she stopped giving interviews this summer, Yager told
reporters from Time and Philadelphia Magazine that she helped
Shah's ex-wife, Ellen Dever, vanish in June 1997 with Sarah, now 8,
and Genevieve, now 6, despite the fact that no one had accused Shah
of harming the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Like an $80 million lawsuit filed in federal court in July by a
Connecticut man looking for his son for a year, the Shah suit now
accuses the Yagers of racketeering. By placing people underground,
the lawsuit asserts, the Yagers engage in organized criminal
activity, including kidnapping, misuse of passports and money
laundering.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says that Faye Yager often sells the property of the
women going underground and keeps the proceeds. The Yagers also
often keep the property for their own use, the lawsuit states.
</P>
<P>
   A red Jeep Grand Cherokee owned by Ellen Dever was involved in
an accident on April 13 while being driven by Jay Wilcox Davis, a
friend of the Yagers. Wilcox repeatedly invoked her rights against
self-incrimination during an August hearing regarding the case of
the Connecticut man.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Yager's attorney, Robert Schroeder, said he hadn't seen a
copy of the lawsuit and couldn't comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
