<HEADER>
A3451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE-580&AMP;A     09-18 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEFENSE-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LEGAL ADVISERS SAY THEY WERE FORCED TO AGREE TO
VIDEOTAPING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)   (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD, CLINTON-BLACKS,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-DAY)  
(js) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's lawyers and advisers said
Friday that they were forced to agree to the videotaping of his
grand jury appearance last month in order to win other concessions
the president wanted from Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Once Clinton and his lawyers agreed he would testify before the
grand jury, they said, Clinton wanted most of all to avoid having
to travel to the federal courthouse downtown to appear in person
before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The White House advisers who have been subject to merciless
second-guessing for allowing the videotape to be made said in
interviews that they were always aware that the tape could be aired
publicly in an effort to wound Clinton. But they said that, in the
end, they had little choice but to agree to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew right from the beginning that the video was a
bad thing,'' said one adviser who took part in the discussions and
spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``We all knew it entailed a
major risk.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, among the problems Clinton's advisers expect in
endless television replays of his testimony is one early sequence
in which the president engages in an odd colloquy with one of the
prosecutors over whether he is prepared to ``tell the truth, the
whole truth and nothing but the truth,'' especially the phrase,
``the whole truth.'' People familiar with the testimony said
Clinton might come across in that segment, as well as in others, as
needlessly argumentative.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's advisers said they were annoyed that even
though the president knew he was being videotaped he behaved rashly
at times during his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that was part of Starr's strategy in making the taping
of the testimony one of his prime conditions, especially since he
now contends that the tape shows ``evidence of a crime,' meaning
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had a different set of priorities for his lawyers to
negotiate. The White House was most eager to obtain a series of
concessions from Starr, most importantly the agreement that the
president would not have to appear personally before the grand jury
in the federal courthouse. Clinton, the advisers said, was adamant
that his negotiators insure that he testify by closed-circuit
television from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, one explained, is that Hillary Rodham Clinton was
upset, even traumatized, by the carnival atmosphere that attended
her appearance before the Whitewater grand jury at the federal
courthouse in January 1996. The White House also wanted Starr to
withdraw the subpoena so the president could assert he was
testifying voluntarily and wanted to ensure that his lawyers could
remain with him during the session.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the testimony on Aug. 17, White House
advisers again asked the president to reconsider his refusal to
travel to the courthouse, arguing that such a move would block a
videotape from being made. But the president refused, they said,
and agreed to have the testimony videotaped.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr team initially told the White House negotiators that
it was necessary to make a tape to play later to grand jurors who
could not be present on the day Clinton testified via a two-way
television hook-up. On that day, Clinton's lawyers said they asked
whether all 23 grand jurors were present in the courtroom downtown,
but Starr had refused to answer. Lawyers familiar with the grand
jury operation said not all were present during the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Friday withheld public comment on the
Judiciary Committee's plan to release the videotape on Monday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, officials were quick to seize on what
they perceived as an unexpected benefit _ the stark demonstration
of partisanship in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a potential for our enemies to do for us what we
haven't been able to do ourselves,'' said one senior adviser to
Clinton. ``We've been grappling all week, trying to find a way to
unite congressional Democrats, and the truth is they just won't
unite around a defense of Clinton for a variety of reasons _ some
of them very sound.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the official added, ``the Republicans, God bless them, they
have finally given congressional Democrats a reason to coalesce''_-
not necessarily around the president, he said, but at least against
the Republican tactics.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton's advisers watched Friday's events unfold on
television, they were delighted to see one Democrat after another _
including some who have been critical of Clinton for years _ step
up to microphones to lambaste the Republicans as partisans trying
to railroad the president and force-feed smut to the American
public.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just seems to me the House within a few days has turned
into a snake pit and a war room,'' said Rep. David Obey, a
Wisconsin Democrat who is not on the committee. Obey has harshly
criticized Clinton for a variety of issues over the years, painting
him as someone who is politically unreliable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
