</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SELL-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRIGHT TAX NOTE IN THOSE SORRY FUND RETURNS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)  (af)  
 By TIMOTHY MIDDLETON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oof!
</P>
<P>
   That is what a lot of mutual fund shareholders will feel when
they open their next account statement. This quarter through Sept.
17, the average general equity fund was off 15 percent, according
to Lipper Analytical Services, the Summit, N.J., research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Returns for the average small-capitalization stock fund were far
worse, down 22.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors with taxable accounts can do something about those
losses by taking advantage of one of the best features of mutual
funds: the ability to generate tax losses to offset realized gains
and then up to $3,000 of earned income, while allowing investors to
keep the same mix in their portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Other investments, if sold at a loss, can also create a tax
deduction, but traders must not not run afoul of the ``wash sale''
rule of the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   It forbids them to claim the deduction if, after selling the
security, they repurchase it or a ``substantially identical'' one,
as the IRS puts it, within 30 days of the sale. It is far easier to
comply with that rule, while still replacing the holding, when
investing in funds than when trading stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Funds are distinct legal entities, said Rande Spiegelman, a
manager at KPMG Peat Marwick in San Francisco, so the IRS treats
even virtual fund clones as if they are as different as chalk and
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of money is at stake? Spiegelman used the example of
Montgomery Emerging Markets, which was down 44.5 percent this year
through the market low on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   An investor who put $10,000 in the fund at the beginning of the
year would have a short-term loss on paper of $4,170 as of Aug. 31.
If he realizes the loss, it can be used to reduce his tax bill by
as much as $1,651, if he is in the top 39.6 percent federal
bracket, lowering his out-of-pocket loss to $2,519.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the investor who wants to keep his
emerging-markets exposure can afford to reinvest $7,481 _ the
$5,830 realized on the sale plus the $1,651 in tax savings _ in a
similar offering.
</P>
<P>
   With the number of funds expanding, it is getting easier for
investors to find a close double for almost any portfolio.
Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in Chicago, can determine
a ``best fit'' based on portfolio characteristics like standard
deviation and market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   For Montgomery Emerging Markets, for example, Morningstar picked
Vanguard International Equity Index Emerging Markets Portfolio.
That fund, down 37.1 percent for the year through Aug. 31, did
better than its Montgomery rival; it also has a lower expense
ratio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
