A3456 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAMPTON-ARRESTED-BOS &LR;      09-18 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMPTON-ARRESTED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CON MAN HAMPTON ARRESTED IN ALLEGED CHECK THEFT, ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Joseph C. Keane met the man at a South End bar in
May, he called himself Antonio, told Keane he was attending Harvard
Law School, and that he was originally from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The two men struck up a friendship and went to Keane's home,
eventually spending several days together before, according to
Keane, his-new found friend stole his checks and assaulted him.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Keane learned that Antonio was really David Edgar
Hampton Jr., a con man whose scam of some liberal New Yorkers in
the early 1980s inspired the prize-winning play and popular movie,
``Six Degrees of Separation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really impressed. He said he was writing a book. He's
very smart. He's a good talker,'' Keane said Friday about Hampton.
``Obviously, for what he does for a living you have to be
intelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Hampton Tuesday with Keane's help.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Friday, Keane said he was unaware of
the play and movie until told about it by a reporter Friday. He
added that Hampton, when he took his hat off, ``looked just like
Will Smith.'' The actor Will Smith portrayed the Hampton-inspired
character in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, Hampton posed as the son of actor Sidney Poitier
and ingratiated himself into the lives of the New Yorkers.
Playwright David Guare turned that into a one-act play that Globe
stage critic Kevin Kelly called ``a fable in which what is false
has as much power as fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who spent 21 months in prison for the Poitier scam, was
in the Nashua Street Jail Friday being held on $500 cash bail. He
is charged with attacking Keane and cashing two of Keane's checks
after forging Keane's signature on them. Keane said that while
Hampton was in his apartment, Hampton stole six checks from his
check book.
</P>
<P>
   When he learned about a $500 drop in his account balance, Keane
confronted Hampton, who attacked Keane with his own belt and
threatened him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ever tell anyone about this, you're dead,'' Hampton
told Keane, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   After their confrontation in May, Keane said he did not see
Hampton again until this Tuesday when he saw him at another bar in
the South End. Keane summoned Boston police, who took Hampton into
custody.
</P>
<P>
   In Hampton's backpack, police found a Harvard University student
identification card in the name of Patrick P. Owens, a birth
certificate with the same name, a California identification card
for Patrick Owens and a Social Security card in that name.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Friday whether Owens is the name of a student at
Harvard or if Hampton is attending the law school. Spokesmen for
the university could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Police also found a Columbia University identificaton in the
name of Kerry J. Duran and an identification card in that name.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton also had a passport and other identification in his own
name.
</P>
<P>
   At Hampton's arraignment Tuesday in Boston Municipal Court,
Suffolk District Attorney Ralph C. Martin II's office asked that
bail be set at $25,000 cash, said spokesman James Borghesani.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was a flight risk,'' he said. ``I don't think this
the type of guy, if he gets out, is going to willingly hang around
and run back to court. We were worried about his coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Charles Johnson set bail at $500 cash. Hampton remained
jailed on that bail Friday. But Keane said he is concerned about
his safety should Hampton be released and has obtained a
restraining order against Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through some pretty rough things, but this is pretty
bad,'' Keane said, adding that he has become suspicious of people
since his encounter with Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Keane then mused aloud about Hampton. ``So I busted someone
famous,'' he said. ``My horoscope said I would come into a lot of
money in September. I wish it was money instead of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
