<HEADER>
A3457 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BENCHMARKS-TEXTIL     09-18 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BENCHMARKS-TEXTILES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXTILE TRIUMPH: A FABRIC MAKER'S TAPESTRY FOR SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (For release Sunday, Sept. 20)  
 (bl)  
 By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALL RIVER, Mass. _ What could Larry Liebenow have been thinking
in 1989, when he decided to buy Quaker Fabric Corp., an ailing,
43-year-old business in this struggling mill town?
</P>
<P>
   Deserted decades ago by textile companies and other basic
manufacturing industries, Fall River has suffered along with the
rest of southeastern Massachusetts as the state's already high
labor, energy and health care costs have continued to rise. And in
this crowded coastal region, land suitable for a sprawling modern
factory building is hard to come by at any price.
</P>
<P>
   But Liebenow, now 55, a textile veteran whose career has taken
him to Mexico and Argentina, saw possibilities. ``One of the
greatest advantages up here often goes unmentioned: the
particularly high quality of the work force,'' Liebenow said.
``They're committed, energetic and productive. They offset the
disadvantages.''
</P>
<P>
   The reborn Quaker Fabric, along with other thriving factories,
is unraveling conventional wisdom that good times are gone forever
from the state's industrial base.
</P>
<P>
   Quaker is now the largest maker of chenille yarn in the world
and one of the top three United States manufacturers of upholstery
fabric for the furniture industry. It expects 1998 sales of about
$280 million, a 28 percent gain from last year, and net income of
$14.6 million, up 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, after Quaker completes a new plant that was announced
last month, its annual production capacity will grow to about 80
million yards, from about 27 million yards in 1991, and it will
employ 3,100 people, up from 2,400 today.
</P>
<P>
   The company's success mirrors that of the state. After three
decades of decline, productivity, export growth and job growth in
Massachusetts have outpaced the nation since 1995, according to
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI research unit.
</P>
<P>
   Textile-making was one of New England's first large-scale
industries, and it flourished here for a century before the lures
of low taxes, cheap labor and light regulation began drawing
companies to other states or to Latin America and Asia after World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. upholstery fabric industry is now largely concentrated
in the Southeast. With annual sales of roughly $2 billion, it
accounts for about half the global market, which has grown steadily
at about 5 percent a year for two decades and shows no sign of
slowing, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has fertile ground to sow as aging boomers and
their children cocoon around the entertainment pit,'' said John
Baugh, an analyst with Wheat First Union in Richmond, Va. As they
snuggle in, these buyers are gravitating toward soft, cushiony
sofas, chairs and Ottomans covered with the types of luxurious
fabric that are Quaker's forte, Baugh said.
</P>
<P>
   The softness of Quaker's woven brocade and damask upholstery
fabrics comes from feathery chenille yarn, a product that Liebenow
brought with him _ along with his client list, machinery, top
executives and investors _ when he merged Nortex International, the
yarn maker he ran, with Quaker in 1989. Liebenow knew Quaker well
because Nortex had been supplying it with yarn for six years.
</P>
<P>
   His formula for reviving the fortunes of Quaker _ which had
about 800 workers in 1989, when it lost $7.4 million on revenue of
$80 million _ was to rebuild the company as a ``vertically
integrated'' yarn and upholstery operation. He renovated its
four-story brick mill complex and brought in new high-speed looms
and spinners. The company recruited designers to create new
products, courted export sales _ now 20 percent of its output _ and
expanded into fabrics for cars and commercial furniture. Liebenow
took Quaker public in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The company has seen its earnings growth slow this year, in what
analysts describe as growing pains associated with capital
expansion that will amount to $120 million of new equipment to meet
strong demand. The situation hurt the company's stock price even
before the late-summer market slide, pushing it down from a 52-week
high of $21.58 in April to $9.875 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Quaker has a $69.9 million backlog of orders, the largest in
the industry, said Baugh of Wheat First, and analysts expect profit
growth to pick up next year.
</P>
<P>
   Quaker's major rival is Joan/Mastercraft, a privately held
fabric maker with factories in Massachusetts and North Carolina and
sales of about $500 million a year. Two other competitors, based in
the South, are Burlington Industries and Culp.
</P>
<P>
   Quaker must still cope with the inefficiencies of its old mill
buildings and with the high costs of doing business in
Massachusetts, but Liebenow is confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we get so caught up in high tech,'' he said. ``We
forget that basic industries _ which can offer stable jobs to a
broad range of the population _ have found ways to reinvent
themselves and be globally competitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
