<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3461 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TABLOIDTHINK-     09-18 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TABLOIDTHINK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX, LIES AND CLINTON! SCANDAL AS SOAP OPERA  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - I am appalled. Not so much at the president and his
zipper _ which is now an open-and-shut case _ but at the way the
issue is playing out in the American public and press.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it seems as if the entire Clinton fiasco is more soap
opera than a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatis personae are assumed to act not like complex human
beings, but like simpletons in low drama:
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected to fall in love with the President,'' Monica
Lewinsky testified in the now infamous Starr Report. ``I'm
surprised that I did.''
</P>
<P>
   She called him ``Handsome;'' he called her ``Sweetie.'' It was
in all the papers. And I mean ``The New York Times'' and the
``Washington Post,'' to say nothing of ``The Arizona Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, those are the less squalid parts of the report.
</P>
<P>
   But it plays into the same tabloid mentality that I hear all
around me. The real tabloids only put into words what I hear
ordinary people around me saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary &AMP; Monica SHOWDOWN!'' wrote the ``National Enquirer.''
``It's an all out war between First Lady and `The Tramp.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to strangle her,'' Hillary told a friend, at least as
quoted in the tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   Monica, in turn, supposedly told the paper, ``Bill wouldn't have
sought refuge in my arms if you weren't such a cold bitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Hillary a suffering wife, a conniving wife or a business
partner? We cannot know, but the popular press squeezes her _ and
everyone else involved _ into the tight shackles of melodrama. So
little imagination. It is as if the whole plot were dreamed up in a
trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same way with Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Did she finall9AEK9 true love with Dodi? Wasn't she special the
way she cared so much?
</P>
<P>
   ``These were two people who recognized themselves in each other,
who really understood the other's hopes, dreams, wishes, fears and
pain,'' Rene Delorm told the ``Enquirer.'' He was Dodi Al Fayed's
butler.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``National Examiner,'' Princess Di's son, Prince William
warns Camilla Parker Bowles, ``You'll NEVER be my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   There are recurring fantasies in the supermarket tabloids:
</P>
<P>
   Being a celebrity means lots of champagne and glamorous parties
_ to say nothing of oodles of kinky sex _ yet they are no happier
than us ordinary people. In fact, they suffer terrible tragedies of
drug dependency, heartache and spousal abuse. Yet, there is always
the hope that they will lose weight, find true love and start
producing babies.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every celebrity story in a tabloid exploits one or
another portion of that monotonous story. Sometimes they wear good
clothes while acting out their parts in the melodrama; sometimes
they are fashion accidents, with lots of accusatory photos. Madonna
is in every tabloid this week, for instance, with her sweatshirt
drawn up over her head, hiding from the paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   But it's OK; she has her baby.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone has a tragedy that can be overcome. Christopher
Reeve can walk again, Kirstie Alley battles the bulge _ for love.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities have loose morals, but all they really want is
babies and a steady mate.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ``Star,'' Carolyn Kennedy is ``desperate for
baby to save marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Page 1 headline reads ``JFK baby heartache wrecking
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Star'' gossip is that Sharon Stone could be pregnant, as she
``sports a suspicious belly bulge'' on the set of her new movie.
</P>
<P>
   And Cindy Crawford decided to pose nude for ``Playboy''
magazine, reports the ``National Enquirer,'' because she wants to
have a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be my last chance to be a sexy siren in a men's
magazine,'' Cindy told a friend.
</P>
<P>
   It sometimes seems as if the entire Clinton scandal could be
solved if only Hillary would have a baby, or failing that, if
Monica would. We don't care, just as long as somebody gets pregnant
and we all ``ooh'' over the infant.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of pundits have lamented the ``tabloidization'' of the
mainstream press. Stories that would never have been touched in
earlier years make it to Page 1 now, and editors across the land
worry over having to print words they would never have considered
before.
</P>
<P>
   I have to laugh now when I remember the terrible fuss editors
made over whether we could actually print in a family newspaper
what Lorena Bobbitt did. That seems an eon ago in another world.
Now we are forced to print what a president does with his cigar.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't simply that the press makes a fable out of the
headlines. We have always done that. In fact, newspapers naturally
function as a kind of throw-away literature. Like the bigger,
thicker classics, they give us object lessons in behavior and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the lessons the press is increasingly
presenting us is so boringly conventional and unimaginative.
</P>
<P>
   When we read of Anna Karenina, we read of complex emotions
played out against long development and background. The thoughts
expressed are rich, intelligent and most importantly, adult.
</P>
<P>
   The same for most great literature: ``Madame Bovary, The Scarlet
Letter,'' even ``The Iliad.'' Such classics discuss adultery but do
so with subtlety. The complexity of their psychologies and the
social interactions depicted enlarge our understanding of
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   But the way Americans approach the saga of Bill, Hillary and
Monica is in contrast one-dimensional: adolescent and smirky.
</P>
<P>
   There is undoubtedly a larger, involved, complicated and adult
version of the current scandal. Perhaps a novelist will one day
write it.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not what we read in the papers or talk about over
office coffee. There, it is as if we have regressed to our teenage
years.
</P>
<P>
   It is all too ordinary. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
