<SLUG> BC-CARSONPRESIDENT-QUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carson's president quits in shake-up
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Carson Inc. announced Friday that Joyce Roche, its
president since 1995, had resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Roche's resignation comes on the heels of a management
restructuring at Carson, which makes Dark &AMP; Lovely hair relaxers
and colorings and Magic shaving products.
</P>
<P>
   In that restructuring, which occurred earlier this summer,
Chairman Roy Keith relinquished his duties as CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Roche was succeeded by Gregory J. Andrews, who joined the
Savannah-based maker of ethnic personal-care products less than
three months ago as chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's me taking control of the company,'' Andrews said of
Roche's departure. ``We're trying to get our expenses in line, and,
as you know, we had a really top-heavy management group. ... This
is as much as anything us making moves to get our costs in line
with the levels of sales in the corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter, Carson reported a loss of $1.8 million _
excluding one-time items and capital gains _ compared with a profit
of $2.3 million in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Roche said there was no longer a need for her position because
it overlapped with Andrews'. She said top executives discussed her
status several weeks ago and agreed ``this was probably the best
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith said Roche ``is a committed professional. We will miss
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said Roche will serve as a consultant on some Carson
projects and ``with other clients as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Roche's leaving will be felt at the company, which in recent
months has had to contend with flat sales domestically.
</P>
<P>
   Roche, known as a savvy marketing executive, joined Carson in
1995 after 19 years with Avon Products Co. Part of her job was to
help steer the company on an aggressive course, which included an
expansion into South Africa and Latin America markets and
acquisitions of new brands.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the company purchased the Johnson Products Co. ethnic
hair-care unit from IVX BioSciences Inc. for $70 million in cash.
Johnson Products is the No. 3 maker of ethnic hair-care products
with such brands as Ultra Sheen and Afro Sheen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
