A3463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BIPARTISAN19-     09-18 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BIPARTISAN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BATTLE OVER DOCUMENTS REVIVES PARTY LINES IN CONGRESS
 &HT;    420&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sharp exchanges Friday between Republicans and
Democrats in the House showed that Congress remains far from the
kind of bipartisan consensus that must precede the forced removal
of a president.
</P>
<P>
   Though technically possible, it would be politically suicidal
for House Republicans to impeach President Clinton by a simple
party-line majority .
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't want it to look like Republicans are getting rid of
him because he's a Democrat,'' said legal historian Michael Les
Benedict of Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, If the House were to send impeachment charges to the
Senate, conviction of Clinton there would require a two-thirds
vote. That would require some Democratic support, since Republicans
hold only 55 of the 100 Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   After a month in which many Democratic members of Congress have
been nearly as harsh as Republicans in criticizing Clinton's
behavior, Friday's eruption was the first public sign that a
significant number of them are starting to give their party's
leader the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still very fluid,'' said political scientist Calvin C.
Jillson, who directs Southern Methodist University's John G. Tower
Center for Political Studies. Jillson's said he saw indications in
Friday's partisan jousting that ``Democrats would like to retain
Clinton in the presidency if it can be done in a way consistent
with the dignity and the interests of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   The first complaints about GOP conduct of the inquiry into
Clinton's behavior came from Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, the
ranking Democrat on the Judiciary Committee. Conyers learned from
news reports that, without consulting him, Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., had asked for and received permission to obtain a
copy of Clinton's videotaped deposition in Paula Jones's sexual
harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're jumping the gun for political purposes,'' Conyers said.
``I'm going to continue my fight in opposition to this kind of
procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   As committee members emerged Friday from two days of closed-door
meetings, Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said, the committee's
``Republican majority seems intent not on bringing about an
impartial inquiry, but on bringing about maximum feasible
embarrassment of the president by any means necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Hyde said, ``There was a general view among the
Democrats not to reveal anything, and there was a general view
among Republicans to reveal as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Democrats attacked the GOP majority's decision to allow only
light editorial changes in the next batch of materials to be
released from the cartons of material sent to Congress by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. Some 2,800 pages of documents
and a videotape of Clinton's grand jury testimony are to be
released in Monday's installment.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's Democratic and Republican staffs jointly
recommended 120 cuts on the grounds of privacy, irrelevancy or good
taste. During two days of private meetings, Republicans rejected
three of those 120 proposed cuts, and also rejected about two dozen
motions by Democrats to omit other material that Democrats claimed
was salacious, irrelevant , duplicative or unnecessarily detailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a vigorous debate, but it was civil,'' Hyde insisted.
``I would say the spirit of bipartisanship is alive and
flourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very civil, but very partisan,'' rejoined Rep. Barney
Frank, D-Mass. ``If this was bipartisanship, then the Taliban (the
fundamentalist movement in Afghanistan) wins a medal for religious
tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., dismissed Frank's remarks as
``spin'' from one of the 63 Democrats who last week voted against
having the committee review and release all relevant portions of
the material that supports Starr's summary report.
</P>
<P>
   But those upset included some of the 138 Democrats who joined
224 Republicans and one independent in authorizing the committee to
review, edit and then release the documents and audio and visual
tapes.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., told CNN: ``It just seems
to me that the House, within a few days, has turned into a snake
pit and a war room, rather than a rational, thoughtful body in
which the public can have confidence on a matter that's of crucial
importance to every family in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``seem to want to keep alive some sensational,
circus-like atmosphere,'' said another, Rep. Steve Rothman, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints were also raised by House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo., who had ostentatiously cooperated with GOP leaders
at bipartisan meetings prior to release of Starr's summary report.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said Friday that he now thinks that Republicans ``have
absolutely no intention whatsoever of conducting this investigation
under the bipartisan principles that the Watergate investigation
followed.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
