<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JURY19-COX     09-18 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JURY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNIQUE CIRCUMSTANCES LED TO RELEASE OF GRAND JURY MATERIAL
 &HT;    By CHRISTI HARLAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among all the shocking details that are about to be
released from the investigation of President Clinton, one shocker
may be overlooked: in the real world, grand jury testimony is so
secret and so sacred that discussing it is almost always a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a law against violating the secrecy of the grand
jury,'' said former U.S. Attorney James Rolfe of Dallas. ``It is
not public what goes on in the grand jury, who goes there, who is
subpoenaed. ... It isn't a deal where even your buddies in the U.S.
attorney's office are privy to what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   But because of a little-noticed court decision in July and a
vote Friday by the House Judiciary Committee, anyone in the world
will be privy to the grand jury testimony of Clinton, former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky and any number of other witnesses,
from Clinton friend Vernon Jordan to Lewinsky's college chums.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel in Washington gave independent counsel
Kenneth Starr permission to release the testimony to Congress when
Starr asked for that power in July. Starr included the testimony _
Clinton's on videotape and the rest in printed transcripts _ in the
boxes of material that he delivered to Congress Sept. 10 with his
report detailing potentially impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Starr referred to the grand jury testimony in his report to
Congress but, aside from cautioning that the boxes contained some
personal and potentially embarrassing material, he gave Congress no
guidance as to how to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Judiciary Committee voted to release the grand
jury testimony and other evidence to the public, setting the stage
for the broadcast of what otherwise would have been known to only a
few dozen people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently we've now set the precedent for releasing grand
jury testimony,'' said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., a member of the
Judiciary Committee. ``Prosecutors ...will be timing their grand
jury testimony for sweeps week.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors interviewed Friday declined to comment on the
propriety of the Judiciary Committee's decision, but they made
clear that a breach of grand jury secrecy in their jobs is
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The institution of the grand jury depends on its proceedings
being kept secret,'' said District Attorney Ronnie Earle of Austin,
Texas, the only state prosecutor with the power to bring misconduct
charges against state officials.
</P>
<P>
   State rules on grand jury proceedings can vary, but not much:
they generally follow the federal rules, which lay out very limited
exceptions for releasing grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The most common, but still limited, release of grand jury
testimony occurs when a prosecution witness in a criminal trial
also testified before the grand jury. In those instances, the
defense attorney can obtain the witness's grand jury testimony, but
only the part that deals with the same topic as the trial
testimony. Anything else stays secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never'' is when criminal defense lawyers obtain a full grand
jury transcript, said Gerald Lefcourt of New York, immediate past
president of the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers.
Limited amounts of testimony are given ``to the defense attorney
for the purpose of cross examination,'' he said. ``It is not poured
into the public record.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the secrecy are clear, according to both defense
lawyers and prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first place, the grand jury is an accusatory body,''
Earle said. ``The grand jury hears only one side. The secrecy
protects people from groundless accusations and from being
slandered even by accusations of conduct that is not criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules of evidence used in trials to weed out hearsay and
other impermissible evidence ``don't apply in grand jury
proceedings, so anybody can say anything whether they can prove it
or not, and the reason that's OK is because it's in a secret
proceeding,'' he said. ``They can say whatever they want without
having to worry any possible harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It protects the accused as well as the witness,'' Earle said,
``because it provides the witness with a cloak of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
