<SLUG> BC-DOW19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Witching' session casts no spell as stocks gain slightly
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Investors were not bewitched after all in Friday's
trading as stocks moved up in fairly calm trading. Small stocks
continued to stage a comeback by outperforming blue chips for the
day and for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's quarterly ``triple witching'' session _ the expiration
of stock options, index options and index futures _ failed to cause
the usual volatility, although fresh earnings disappointments
surfaced to dampen trader enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Union Carbide was the latest to warn that its third-quarter
results will be hurt by falling raw material prices. Other cyclical
stocks _ the kind that gain in an expanding economy _ declined,
reflected in a 1.6 percent drop in the Morgan Stanley cyclical
index.
</P>
<P>
   The big news may have been the rally in smaller stocks, which
gave the Russell 2000 index a gain of 2.2 percent for the day and
2.7 percent for the week.
</P>
<P>
   The blue chip Dow Jones industrial average rose 0.3 percent in
Friday's trading and 1.3 percent for the week.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising, perhaps, the Russell 2000 has gained 7.5
percent since the bottom of the sell-off on Aug. 31, vs. the Dow's
gain of 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the week ended with the Dow trading 15.5 percent
below its all-time high, while the Russell 2000 was 26 percent
below its high.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Dwyer, chief market strategist at Ladenburg Thalmann, told
Dow Jones News Service that investors should focus more attention
on smaller caps, which he said are likely to continue outperforming
big-cap stocks on the rebound from the recent sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the ability of the small-cap and Nasdaq markets to
rally is a sign that the biggest part of the sell-off may be over,
without necessarily signaling an imminent upward move. That's
because the market is still faced with prospects of disappointing
earnings reports in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointments in earnings are devastating, and many of the
big stocks that seem more predictable in terms of their earnings
performance have taken big hits,'' Alan Ackerman, senior vice
president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co., told Dow Jones News Service.
</P>
<P>
   The market likely would have closed with a bigger weekly gain
except for Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who did not
provide a clear signal in a congressional appearance on Wednesday
that the Fed would cut interest rates soon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
