<SLUG> BC-SBA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SBA expands access to two loan programs
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The U.S. Small Business Administration announced
Friday an expansion and streamlining of two key loan programs.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency said the improvements to the LowDoc and SBA
Express programs are expected to provide an additional $1 billion
over the next year in hard-to-get small loans for start-up
businesses, women and minority entrepreneurs, and businesses in
inner cities and rural areas. The two programs were set up earlier
this decade to help small businesses that need loans under
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's changes raise the ceiling on loan limits in both
programs from $100,000 to $150,000. Also, a small-business owner
will be able to get a loan from either program in as little as 36
hours _ half the minimum time it used to take to process a loan. At
the same time, more than 400 lenders have been added to the SBA
Express program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loans will open the doors of opportunity in new markets,
which include African-American, Hispanic-American and women-owned
businesses,'' SBA Administrator Aida Alvarez said. ``We have
discovered from experience that smaller-size loans tend to be
concentrated among women- and minority-owned business.''
</P>
<P>
   LowDoc, short for ``low documentation,'' which refers to the
program's lower paperwork requirements, was set up in 1993 to help
entrepreneurs who needed small loans. It was aimed at start-ups,
women and minorities _ groups with the biggest need for small
loans. The LowDoc program features a one-page application, and the
SBA guarantees up to 75 percent of each loan.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal year 1997, 14,738 LowDoc loans were processed,
totaling $847 million. In fiscal 1998, which ends this month, the
SBA expects to make 11,300 LowDoc loans totaling $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   SBA Express began three years ago as a pilot program called
FA$TRAK. Express allows lenders to use their own forms and
procedures for making loans in order to reduce paperwork. The SBA
guarantees half of each of these loans.
</P>
<P>
   The Express program processed 4,100 FA$TRAK loans during fiscal
1997, totaling more than $190 million. For fiscal year 1998, the
agency expects to make 5,600 loans totaling about $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, 263 LowDoc loans were issued last year, totaling
$16.8 million and representing 24 percent of all SBA-backed loans
made in the state. So far this year, 172 LowDoc loans, totaling $11
million, have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Express loans in Georgia totaled 38 for about $2 million in
1997. Through August of this year, 32 Express loans were issued,
for a total of about $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   SBA officials tied the decline in the number of loans nationally
and in Georgia to a slowdown in the economy and more banks making
direct loans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
