<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3472 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      09-18 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDICIARY COMMITTEE TO RELEASE CLINTON VIDEOTAPED TESTIMONY ON
MONDAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Over Democratic objections, the House Judiciary
Committee voted Friday to release the videotaped grand jury
testimony of President Clinton in the Monica Lewinsky matter,
giving the American people what one lawmaker said was ``more than
they ever wanted to know about the president's sex life.''
</P>
<P>
   The 37-member panel, which is expected recommend a congressional
inquiry of impeachment in a few weeks, also voted to release 2,800
pages of other information, including Lewinsky's testimony of sex
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 Democrats tried to keep the material from being made
public, arguing that the videotape and other documents supporting
independent counsel Ken Starr's report to Congress would only serve
to humiliate the president.
</P>
<P>
   But their motions failed on party line votes. They were left
with little choice but to help their Republican colleagues decide
what lurid details should be deleted to protect individuals not
central to the question of whether Clinton lied under oath about
his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The materials are to be released Monday morning, and will
include the unedited tape of the president's four-hour testimony to
the Starr grand jury in which he admits to an improper relationship
with Lewinsky while she was a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members said the material is ``salacious.'' But they
said it does not include any new accusations and not much more than
already has been detailed in the 445-page report Starr provided to
Congress last week.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was quick to denounce the committee decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This appears to be a rush to prejudgment and an effort to get
out the most salacious material at the speed of light, not at the
proper pace of justice,'' said White House aide James Kennedy.
``But in the end it will have to be the American people who will
have to see if this indeed has been a fair process or a partisan
effort to embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee is expected to release more information later, and
may decide to make public the president's deposition last January
in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit that was dismissed by
Arkansas U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright. Wright has agreed
to make the deposition available to committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats accused Republicans of ``dribbling out''
information to influence public opinion to support a decision they
have already made _ that Clinton ought to be impeached, or short of
that, driven from office before congressional hearings begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to trickle out evidence, it seems, for only one
reason _ death by a thousand cuts,'' said committee member Robert
Wexler, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Democratic claims that they ``got rolled'' by the 21
Republicans on the committee, Hyde said that the panel sessions
Thursday and Friday were civil even though members had strong
opinions. He even suggested there was a sense of ``collegiality''
as members moved into a debate about which sexually explicit
material to hold back.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, both sides agreed to 120 edits, Hyde said. There
were 27 other passages in testimony and various other materials
that the Democrats asked to be deleted, but the Republicans said
no.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a general view among Democrats not to reveal
anything, and there was a general view among Republicans to reveal
as much as possible consistent with responsible redactions to
protect people whose names and vital statistics and involvement in
this was very peripheral,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. John Conyers, the ranking Democrat on the committee,
said the information remaining is sexually explicit and will
embarrass the president, Lewinsky and others ``for no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is offensive, it is obscene,'' he said, adding that it
still ``does not build up any kind of case one way or the other''
against the president for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   At least one Republican committee member, Rep. Lindsey Graham of
South Carolina, agreed with that assessment, and said that the
materials do not constitute any impeachable offense in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to blow people away, in my opinion,'' he said,
adding that Clinton actually ``handles himself pretty well'' in
some exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   But nonetheless, Graham said Republicans felt it important to
release the videotape and other information to show that Clinton
continued to lie and spar with the Starr grand jury over whether
his intimate contacts with Lewinsky did in fact constitute a sexual
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats objected to the release of the additional Starr
materials primarily out of concern that it sets ``a dangerous
precedent,'' as Conyers put it, for releasing grand jury testimony
that is normally kept secret. They cited the Watergate impeachment
proceedings against Richard Nixon as an example, saying the
committee in that case took months to deliberate before releasing
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watergate is the standard I am going by,'' said committee
Democrat Sheila Jackson Lee of Houston, adding that Clinton
deserves to be treated ``just as fairly'' as Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she said the Republicans' insistence that everything
``be rushed out now'' had ``put a spear through'' the
``constitutional standards that ought to be applied'' when
considering impeachment and ``the spirit of bipartisanship'' that
GOP leaders had promised.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee, joined by Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., tried during
the committee meeting to prevent the release of more Starr
materials until the committee could determine whether the
allegations of impeachable offenses made by the independent counsel
amounted to ``an abuse of official powers.'' Every committee
Republican voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also rejected another Democratic motion that
would have allowed Clinton and his lawyers to review the rest of
the Starr materials before they are released.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Republicans and the Democrats agreed on only a
few things, including whether to make public the record of their
votes on 18 motions presented during the committee's executive
session. Thirteen Republicans joined with 15 Democrats to pass that
motion. The Republicans, however, rejected a motion by Democrats to
release a transcript of their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri said that the
partisan tone of the committee meeting raises questions about how
Republicans intend to proceed on the Starr report. ``It is
increasingly clear that the Republicans have absolutely no
intention whatsoever of conducting this investigation under the
bipartisan principles that the Watergate investigation followed,''
Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints from Democrats spurred Gingrich to announce plans
to convene a meeting of congressional leaders next week to discuss
how to tone down the political rhetoric as Congress wrestles with a
decision about whether to proceed with impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who supported the release
of the videotape and other documents, said he expects Congress to
make that decision within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't surprise me if (the Judiciary Committee) met the
first week of October to decide whether to recommend an inquiry of
impeachment to the full House,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote to release the 2,800 pages of written records,
consisting primarily of the appendices to Starr's official report
to Congress, was 20-15, breaking down along party lines. The vote
to release an unedited version of Clinton's videotaped testimony
was the same.
</P>
<P>
   The votes reflected just how partisan the executive session was.
But as if to erase any doubt about the fierce politics behind
closed doors, the Republican and Democratic members sparred openly
before television cameras after Hyde announced the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, R-Mass., accused Republicans of adopting ``a
new concept of unilateral bipartisanship.'' But Hyde, standing
beside him, responded that he thought members got along ``very
well,'' adding that bipartisanship in his view ``doesn't include
surrender to everything Democrats want.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also complained that Republicans were being
insensitive by releasing the report on Rosh Hashanah, the Jewish
New Year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
