<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3480 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-FLOODS-HNS &LR;      09-18 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FLOODS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION CLAIMS PRI TAKING ADVANTAGE OF FLOODING TO DRUM UP
SUPPORT FOR THEIR CANDIDATES 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW DOWNIE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESCUINTLA, Mexico _ Urbano Escalante trekked for seven hours
across swollen rivers and muddy paths, clutching a list.
</P>
<P>
   He held it tight, because the Mexican army general in charge of
distributing aid to flood victims had told him that if he lost it
he would go to prison.
</P>
<P>
   On the list were the names of the heads of families in San
Antonio Miramar, one of the hundreds of villages hit hard by the
floods that have drenched southern Mexico's Chiapas state during
the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Beside each name was a list of goods: 1 kilogram of rice, half a
kilo of sugar, 1 kilo of beans, a tin of sardines, a carton of
milk, a bag of noodles. Next to the list, in the column marked
``received,'' were signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Escalante, the villager in charge of distributing government aid
dropped from helicopters for this tiny hillside settlement, made
sure that everyone who took a parcel of food left a written record.
</P>
<P>
   In years gone by, the distribution of aid has proven to be a
lucrative business in Mexico. In a country where as many as half
the population of 97 million lives in poverty, the government is
regularly called upon to help the most desperate in times of
drought, hurricanes, earthquakes and floods.
</P>
<P>
   But too often, many Mexicans say, some of the aid has been used
by local bosses to line their own pockets or by political leaders
to buy votes and favors. It is still happening in flood-ravaged
Chiapas, rescue workers, soldiers and opposition politicians say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard that political parties are giving away aid,''
said Armando Paniagua, a Red Cross worker organizing medical
brigades in Escuintla. ``It is a common thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With crucial midterm elections for mayors and state legislators
less than three weeks away in Mexico's southernmost state,
opposition politicians claim that the members of the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, are taking advantage of
the flooding to drum up support for their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous disasters, when the federal government was slow
to react, this time President Ernesto Zedillo was quick to go to
the scene. Zedillo has visited Chiapas four times in the last 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling party does not want to lose,'' said Blanca Laura
Castilla, a local activist with the leftist Democratic Revolution
Party. ``We think that is why he has spent so much time here. They
should not be taking advantage of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is disastrous. As many as 100,000 people were made
homeless by the floods, and hundreds more were reported dead.
Unofficial figures put the death toll into four figures. But with
many isolated villages still cut off, it will be some time before
rescue workers can determine a final count of the dead and missing.
Whatever the casualty toll, Zedillo called the floods ``probably
the worst natural disaster since the earthquake of 1985'' that
killed thousands in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo has toured the region, using his moral stature as chief
executive to make it clear he expects politicians in this
politically divided state to work together for the good of the
people. Acknowledging the reports of abuses, the president said
that anyone caught using aid for political purposes would be
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that government resources will not be
delivered to any political party or any other organization that
intends on running a campaign,'' he said. ``The resources do not
belong to the government but to the Mexican people.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the message relayed to Urbano Escalante by the general
in charge at Escuintla, a small town around 60 miles from the
Guatemalan border.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with his list of names, Escalante sat in the shade of a
tree, awaiting the word on more aid.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old father of six first hiked down the mountain from
his village last Sunday to ask for food and medicine, and army
helicopters dropped supplies 24 hours later. But that food ran out
quickly, and Escalante returned to ask the military to send another
mercy flight.
</P>
<P>
   While handing out assistance, the army made villagers and others
aware of Zedillo's orders. But the army, trying not to rely on
lists made by strangers like Escalante, put a soldier on duty to
oversee the distribution of aid. When the army was unable to
oversee the operations, soldiers were ordered to make return trips
to the villages to ask people if the distribution was equitable.
</P>
<P>
   Several such flights left Escuintla each day as soldiers in
helicopters swooped out across acres of banana plantations and
muddy fields to drop supplies to their starving countrymen and
women.
</P>
<P>
   The deliveries were sometimes haphazard. Lingering rains and
low-hanging clouds forced the cancellation of some flights, and the
Mexican armed forces were limited by the small number of
helicopters available.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's national oil monopoly, Petroleos Mexicanos, sent six
helicopters and pilots, but the fliers did not know the area.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting pilots were forced to rely on photocopied maps and
local spotters who sat in their cabins and pointed the right
direction. On at least one occasion this week, pilots touched down
on a waterlogged sports field to ask villagers the way to a town
they suspected was nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The deliveries were also somewhat patchy during the week, some
say, with places such as San Antonio Miramar receiving two mercy
flights in the week while others waited and watched the sky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Downie is a free-lance journalist based in Mexico City. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
