<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TURNS ATTENTION TO ISSUES OF RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD, CLINTON-BLACKS,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-DEFENSE.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Friday focused his attention
on an area where he has displayed comfort, as well as intellectual
and political surefootedness: race. On a day when the the
appearance of normality was a precious commodity at the White
House, Clinton's only public act was to officially receive the
report of the Advisory Board to the President's Initiative on Race.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a ceremony that included such prominent figures of
the civil rights movement as Rosa Parks and John Lewis, the
president put on display his understanding of the history of racial
conflict and an eloquence about ways to reduce those antagonisms in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes from, yes, opportunity; it comes from, yes, learning;
it comes from, yes, the absence of discrimination,'' Clinton said
in a speech. ``But it also has to come from the presence of
reconciliation, from a turning away from the madness that life only
matters if there is someone we can demean, destroy or put down.''
</P>
<P>
   The event marked the culmination of the work of Clinton's
advisory board whose 15-month tenure was marred by a slow start,
criticism for not including enough conservative voices, anger on
the part of American Indians for not having someone to represent
them on the seven-member panel, and charges of too much white House
interference in its planning and work.
</P>
<P>
   But in presenting the voluminous report to Clinton _ first in a
private meeting in the Oval Office, and later at the public event
in an auditorium at the Old Executive Office Building _ John Hope
Franklin, the head of the board, said the board's work had
stimulated a unique discussion on race throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seemed relieved that someone was doing something about
this,'' Franklin told the president during the meeting in the Oval
Office. ``They felt that they could accomplish something.''
</P>
<P>
   The report the board presented to Clinton was a compilation of
suggestions that had been made to the president during the course
of panel's work. Many were endorsements of policy initiatives _
like funds for teachers, and for school construction in minority
areas _ that the administration has already implemented. Some
people, including at least one board member, have said it was a
relatively bland document that contained no bold initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Its major recommendation, stressed by several board members on
Friday, was the setting up of a permanent Presidential Council on
Race. Such a body would monitor efforts and recommend policies to
promote racial reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely essential that this initiative be carried
forward in a permanent way,'' said William Winter, the former
governor of Mississippi, explaining to Clinton the rationale for a
Presidential Council on Race.
</P>
<P>
   The Oval Office and the public events with the board gave an
edgy White House a welcome respite from the Monica Lewinsky affair.
But even during these moments the scandal's political and legal
challenges intruded, sometimes through gallows humor.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Suzanne Johnson Cook, a New York City pastor and a
board member gave Clinton a present _ a book titled ``Too Blessed
to Be Stressed.'' The president laughed and said, ``I think I need
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
