<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: CATHOLIC CHURCH HAS CHANGED GREATLY IN PAST 20
YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Oct. 16, 1978, 20 years ago next month, Cardinal Karol
Wojtyla, the archbishop of Krakow, became Pope John Paul II.
Evaluations of his event-studded pontificate _ already one of the
longest in the history of the Roman Catholic Church _ and of his
remarkable personality will soon be sprouting left and right (and
no doubt reflecting different predispositions, left and right).
Such evaluations will obviously require political insight,
knowledge about Catholic teaching and a good deal of nuance.
</P>
<P>
   On a less elevated level, they may also benefit from some
numbers, and not only how many times the pope has visited how many
countries and how many major church documents he has issued or how
many copies of his books have been sold. Here are some other
pertinent data, drawn largely from the Vatican's Statistical
Yearbook of the Church.
</P>
<P>
   From 1978 to 1995, the Roman Catholic Church grew to almost 990
million baptized members from 750 million. At the same time, it
shrunk slightly as a proportion of the world's population, to 17.4
percent from 17.8 percent. It especially grew, as has often been
reported, in Asia and Africa, both in absolute numbers and as a
percentage of the population. In the United States and Western
Europe it continued to grow in numbers but, as elsewhere, to shrink
slightly as a percentage of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all these numbers are approximations that blend local
reports of varying precision. Comparisons are further complicated
by the fact that halfway through John Paul's pontificate, the
collapse of communist regimes allowed new statistics where data had
been unavailable. And one wonders how meaningful some of the
figures are.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that 97 percent of the Italian population continues to
be baptized as of 1995, the same percentage that the Vatican
reported for 1978. But that figure scarcely registers the two
decades of secularization that Italy's church officials regularly
lament.
</P>
<P>
   More reliable indicators of the church's health may be found in
the statistics on its ``work force,'' as the yearbook puts it,
primarily the numbers of priests and sisters. Here the general
impression is that John Paul's papacy has put an end to the
hemorrhaging of the church's mid-level leadership, which followed
the Second Vatican Council's recasting of church roles in the 1960s
and the subsequent debates about celibacy.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell a more complicated story. From 1978 to 1995,
for example, the numbers of priests grew by 42 in Africa and 48
percent in Asia, but the decline in North America (13 percent) and
Europe (12 percent) continued. Because North America and Europe
still harbor most of the world's Catholic priests, the overall
picture for the world remained a decline of 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those are absolute numbers, however, and because the numbers of
Catholics have been growing, the ratio of priests to people has
become even more strained. In Africa, there were 3,251 Catholics
for every priest at the beginning of this pontificate; in 1995
there were 4,476; in Asia the figure went from 2,223 Catholics per
priest to 2,620. (In the United States, the figure went to 1,117
from 833.)
</P>
<P>
   The pattern is similar for sisters. The numbers have gone up
sharply in Africa and Asia since 1978, but they have gone down so
sharply in North America and Europe that by 1995 there were 15
percent fewer nuns worldwide serving a much larger church than at
the beginning of John Paul's reign.
</P>
<P>
   It is also interesting to compare such statistics under Pope
John Paul II with those under Pope Paul VI. Pope Paul's
pontificate, from 1963 to 1978, is often considered a period of
extreme postconciliar turmoil and disarray. Yet it is striking how
similar the overall score is for both pontificates. Under Paul VI,
Catholicism grew in absolute numbers and as a proportion of the
population in Africa and Asia, as it would under John Paul II, but
still shrank slightly as a percentage of the world's population.
</P>
<P>
   During the 15 years of Pope Paul VI's reign, the number of
priests declined 2.7 percent, a loss slightly less than that
suffered during the 17 years, from 1978 to 1995, under John Paul
II.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the number of Catholics who had to be
served by each priest grew by 23 percent under Paul VI. Under John
Paul II the number has increased by more than 25 percent. And the
decline in the number of sisters has been much sharper under the
present Pope than the earlier one.
</P>
<P>
   One could tweak these figures in different ways. For example,
one could assume a ``lag,'' as economists often do. Thus the first
five years of John Paul II's papacy might be chalked up to Paul
VI's leadership, and the numbers would almost certainly show that
under the current pope, many of the negative trends that seemed to
build in the decade after 1973 were slowed if not completely
reversed. In some cases, that was probably because John Paul II's
policies were taking effect. In other cases, it was probably a
natural settling down _ for example, the priests most likely to
leave the active priesthood had already done so.
</P>
<P>
   And one always needs to remember the shortcomings of the data.
It would take a major scholarly study to make truly accurate
comparisons. Still, one might risk a few very broad conclusions:
</P>
<P>
   First, as witnessed by the similarities in trends under two very
different popes, the major forces affecting the church's health may
be well beyond papal leadership _ forces like birth rates and
social, economic and cultural changes in both non-Western nations
and the church's European-based heartlands.
</P>
<P>
   Second, while some church leaders hail a shift in the church's
center of gravity from Europe and North America to Africa and Asia
(with traditionally Catholic Latin America partaking of some of the
weaknesses of the Old World Catholicism from which it sprang, along
with the indigenous religious vitality it shares with other Third
World regions), it will be a long time, and a hard time, before the
new growth can compensate for the apparent loss of morale, which
this pontificate does not seem to have arrested, in the church's
European and North American territories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
