<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BLAK18-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        BLACK LEADERS VOW SUPPORT FOR CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Sept. 18 -- Black political leaders visiting the
nation's capital Friday rushed to President Clinton's defense and
vowed to wage a grass-roots campaign designed to discredit
Democrats who publicly denounce him.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Harold James, a Philadelphia Democrat, released a
list of 200-plus lawmakers -- most of them black -- who have
pledged to support the embattled president as Congress decides
whether or not to begin impeachment proceedings against him.
</P>
<P>
   James said recent attacks of Clinton from high profile Democrats
such as U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut and Maryland Gov.
Parris Glendening are ``shameful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is sad to see some of the Democratic leadership
abandoning Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was the first Democrat to publicly scold Clinton from
the Senate floor after the president apologized for having an
``inappropriate relationship'' with Monica Lewinsky. Glendening
snubbed Clinton during two Maryland events earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   James joined hundreds of black leaders from across the country
in Washington this week for the Congressional Black Caucus
Foundation's 28th Annual Legislative Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Americans to Save the Presidency'' group will begin
placing issue ads -- mainly in black urban newspapers -- to let
people know of the betrayal of Clinton by some Democrats,
organizers said. The 1,000-member group is made up of state
lawmakers such as James, local officials, former lawmakers and
other civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   They have scheduled 100 town meetings across the country to
discuss Clinton defense strategy. Supporters of perennial
presidential candidate Lyndon LaRouche helped organize the group.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is designed to embarrass Democrats who attack
Clinton and to make them rethink their positions, James said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. John Hilliard, an Alabama Democrat, said Clinton's
problems amount to nothing more than ``money, power and sex.'' He
said the country would be better served if Congress focused on
issues that affect on people's daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is doing excellent,'' Hilliard said. ``Why would
we attack a president that has built the economy better than it has
ever been before? But the only issue we can find is to try and make
tabloid news.'' State Rep. Louise Williams Bishop, one of eight
Pennsylvania Democrats who signed the petition, said Clinton has
been good for the country despite his personal transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when I voted for him. I knew when I campaigned for him
he was a man,'' Bishop said in a telephone interview from
Philadelphia. ``He is human. He is not a rabbi, a priest or a
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted for him on the basis he was a good candidate, and I
don't think I cast an incorrect vote,'' Bishop said.
</P>
</TEXT>
