</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HASTINGS-STARR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REP. HASTINGS CALLS FOR STARR'S IMPEACHMENT
 &HT;    WITH CLINTON-HASTINGS.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citing what he called prosecutorial misconduct
designed to ``demean, defame and embarrass the president and the
people of the United States, `` Rep. Alcee Hastings called Friday
for the impeachment of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings, D-Fla., filed a ``privileged motion'' at the close of
the House's business Friday. House Speaker Newt Gingrich indicated
he would decide when Congress returns to work Wednesday whether to
let the House vote on the motion. Hastings said he expects the
Republican majority to try to table, or kill, the motion if comes
to the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings, a former federal judge who was impeached by the House
10 years ago and removed a year later by the Senate on bribery
conspiracy charges _ after being acquitted on similar criminal
charges _ said he was bringing the action to slow to the proceeding
moving against Clinton and to express his outrage at Starr's
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give the salacious, tawdry, trashy details (in the report)
was taking this thing to a realm that, when it was released, there
was no useful way that the president could defend himself,''
Hastings said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to take the focus off of President Clinton, but
I don't want somebody to have a hammer _ I don't care if they are a
Democrat or a Republican _ to beat up on somebody the way that
Kenneth Starr has.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Congress would have the power to impeach
Starr, whose appointment was requested by Attorney General Janet
Reno and who reports to a three-judge appellate panel.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastings said Starr should be impeached and removed for
``submitting to the House an unnecessarily pornographic report''
and ``leaking grand jury material for the purpose of embarrassing''
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings also criticized Starr for ``wasting more than $40
million in an investigation that he knew could not justify such
extraordinary expenditures'' and by embarrassing the United States
``before the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his actions thus far, Hastings said Starr had
attempted to disrupt the House and ``disgust a nation grown weary
by hinting that Whitewater, Travelgate, (and) Filegate, like a
Sword of Damocles, hang by a thread just beyond our horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastings said he had not discussed his intent to file the motion
with anyone in the Clinton administration or with Democratic
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the rule of law, and I don't think Kenneth Starr
is above the rule of law any more than is Bill Clinton or Alcee
Hastings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
