<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-295&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA TO PUMP HUGE RUBLE RESERVE INTO BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In the latest example of a leaky ship bailing out
sinking boats, the Russian central bank said Friday that the
country's insolvent banks could use about $1.65 billion in precious
ruble reserves to enable them to make good on customers' bills and
debts that are going unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble has been hopping up and down for weeks now as banks
and the Russian government manipulated its value against the dollar
to make it easier for Russian banks to pay off debts denominated in
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   While this provided brief comfort to delinquent banks, it has
thrown the finances of Russian citizens into disarray and made it
impossible to predict the ruble's daily value. That
unpredictability and a lack of cash have led banks to stop
processing bill payments and have brought financial activity in the
country to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   The government's reasoning is that freeing up the reserves,
which banks typically pledge to the central bank as a nest egg
designated to cover bad loans, will grease the wheels of the
payment system and get financial activity moving again.
</P>
<P>
   But the central bank is gambling that it can trust its errant
banks to use the reserves to settle stalled bills. Russian banks,
many of which operate more like freewheeling speculative funds than
banks in the Western sense, may instead use the rubles to buy
dollars. Such was the case when the International Monetary Fund
injected some cash into the central bank a couple of months ago.
</P>
<P>
   If the banks buy dollars, that will further drive down the value
of the ruble and take another bite out of the buying power of
rubles held by Russian citizens. Moreover, the central bank said it
would print extra rubles to replenish the reserve fund, a move that
will be inflationary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The central bank said Thursday that it would print rubles to buy
short-term government bonds, known as GKOs, from banks. Russian
banks' GKO holdings are currently worthless, although they were
worth about $8 billion when the ruble was, in effect, devalued in
August. It was unclear what price tag the government intends to put
on worthless bonds, but it said it would also print rubles to
accomplish the task _ another inflationary exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Russian finance is essentially a shell game right now, with the
government's printing press issuing increasingly devalued rubles in
an effort to create enough momentum so the economy can begin
creating real value again. Russian banks lauded the decision
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first serious step to improve the situation of the
Russian banking system,'' said Rossiisky Kredit chairman Dmitri
Lyubinin in a prepared statement. ``We hope the payments which were
coming from other banks to our clients will at least be made and
our clients will get the money they have been waiting for for so
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the government is far from being the ideal candidate to be
bailing out flailing banks because its own finances are in
dangerously sorry shape. The government has slightly more than $12
billion in foreign exchange reserves, a standard by which its
financial wherewithal can be measured. But about $5 billion of
those reserves are in gold, leaving about $7 billion in liquid
assets that the government can use to prop up the ruble or pay off
foreign debt. Foreign debts may total as much as $200 billion,
however, so the government is left with desperately little room to
maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   To build a lifeline that can pump funds into the central bank,
the government said on Thursday it would nationalize the tobacco
and alcohol industries. Alcohol sales abroad earn Russia a sizable
chunk of hard currency reserves that can be earmarked for
government use, while control of the tobacco industry gives the
government access to a steady stream of rubles.
</P>
<P>
   While many experts raised serious doubts about the viability of
the government's recent initiatives, others had mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand it offers further benefits to Russian banks in
terms of the domestic restructuring, and so will aggravate the
concerns of foreign investors,'' a brokerage firm, United Financial
Group, said in a research report. ``On the other hand, the plan
does seem well-conceived as a way to solve the ruble payments
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, American companies are watching the unfolding
economic situations with a close eye and lot of caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business community feels like it was hit by a neutron
bomb, and we've all been irradiated,'' said Scott Blacklin,
president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in Russia. ``We are alive
today, but in 30 days, 60 days, 90 days some are going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
