<HEADLINE>
OXFORD CURATOR TO DIRECT MIT MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jane Pickering, a former assistant curator of the
Oxford University Museum in England, has been appointed as the new
director of the MIT Museum, the university announced this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is coming to us with a fresh vision, a passion for the
very idea of a museum in an academic setting,'' said Alan Brody,
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's associate provost for
the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering, 33, will be leading a reexamination of the museum's
programs, hoping to widen its scope of exhibitions and increase its
public outreach and educational activities.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering, who most recently was senior curator for the Royal
College of Surgeons' four museums in England, said that her work
there and at Oxford ``made me very aware of the pivotal role that
university museums can play in bringing together researchers with a
story to tell and the wider public who are eager to hear it.'' At
best, she said, such museums can be ``a genuine interface between
the two `worlds,' with an active flow of ideas and information in
both directions.''
</P>
<P>
   She holds degrees in natural sciences and museum studies from
the universities of Cambridge and Leicester. Her husband,
Christopher Norris, is a museum zoologist.
</P>
<P>
   The MIT museum, founded in 1971 to collect and exhibit materials
related to MIT research, will open a long-term exhibit next
Friday &UR;  &LR; (Sept. 25) devoted to the work of legendary MIT professor
Harold ``Doc'' Edgerton, who made major advances in high-speed
stroboscopic photography.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering said the Edgerton exhibit will ``celebrate one of the
fascinating people that makes MIT such an exciting place ... It's a
perfect example of something I'd like to see even more of at the
museum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
