<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA URGES REVOLUTION TO LOOK AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Revolution have not lost to Tampa Bay in three
games, an indication of the Mutiny's decline more than New
England's success this season. But Walter Zenga is preaching
vigiliance for Saturday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to forget the previous games,'' Zenga said. ``In
soccer, if you think you have an easy game, it is certain that you
will lose.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Zenga's advice has found a receptive audience in the
Revolution players. They have outscored three opponents, 6-1, in
the last five halves of play and have salvaged their playoff hopes.
A defense which had been the most generous in Major League Soccer
became impenetrable in 2-0 wins over the MetroStars and Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mentality is to play for the win, always,'' Zenga said.
``We must stay balanced, compact, play intelligently and with
pride, and concentrate for 90 minutes. If we are good enough, we
will win the game. If the other team wins, we will respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Zenga to replace Thomas Rongen as coach last month
changed the momentum of the team. Zenga might have arrived too late
to get the Revolution a playoff berth _ they trail Miami by 6
points for fourth place in the Eastern Conference. But he has
helped restore the team's credibility and self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Zenga's success has been through tactical adjustments.
He has been resourceful enough to redefine some roles and to
rejuvenate players such as Paul Keegan and Carlos Rocha. The
defense has become an asset rather than a debit.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Zenga has injected an effective mixture of
aggressiveness and safety-first conservativism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not true that we played defensively against Columbus,''
Zenga said. ``You can say you are playing a 3-5-2, a 4-4-2, or a
9-1-1. It doesn't matter what you say before the game. Once the
game starts, you are either on the attack or in defense. It depends
on the players. If we get the ball in their box for 90 minutes,
that's great. And if they get the ball in our box for 90 minutes,
we will play defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one logic to the game. It all depends on
circumstances. The other team can have 80 percent of possession and
you can win, 1-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay won four of the first five games against the
Revolution, but the Mutiny soon were stripped of most of their
assets by coach John Kowalski, who then was replaced by Tim
Hankinson. Now the Mutiny are seeking a new home after the demise
of Houlihan's Stadium and could be leaving Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though the Revolution have found recent success, they
remain last in the conference with the lowest point total in MLS
and the No. 3 average attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tampa has won a couple of games in a row, so they cannot be a
bad team,'' Zenga said. ``You can't look at the standings. We just
need to play well in front of our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's Frankie Hejduk, the only US player to earn a
contract in Europe from his World Cup performance, will miss the
game with a leg injury. Hejduk is to join Bayer Leverkusen in the
German Bundesliga when the Mutiny is eliminated from playoff
contention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
