<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL TUNES HIS TEAM FOR TENNESSEE OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Pete Carroll is like the instructor trying
to prepare his pupils for the Scholastic Aptitude Tests. The
Patriots coach has spent the week training the offense for Sunday's
exam. It's one which the unit may experience just once this season,
yet its success or failure may determine how others prepare for the
Patriots for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The exam is the Tennessee Oilers' 46 defense. Test time is 1
p.m., at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As if the Patriots didn't have enough to be concerned about with
an inconsistent running game and an All-Pro tight end who has been
hobbled, though he is excpected to play. Surely, both the run and
pass will be tested by Tennessee's aggressive, blitz-oriented
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very difficult scheme that historically has been a
real problem,'' said Carroll, who considers himself fortunate to
have someone on his staff quite familiar with the scheme _
defensive coordinator Steve Sidwell, a former Oilers assistant.
``This is the kind of game where they try to disrupt you at all
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Patriots fans should be well acquainted with the 46
defense. The scheme had its heyday during the 1985 season, when
defensive coordinator Buddy Ryan devised an attack that helped lead
the Chicago Bears to one of the most dominant NFL seasons ever.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Bears' 15 victories that season came against the
Patriots, including a 46-10 rout in Super Bowl XX. Ryan went on to
coach the Eagles from 1986-90, beating the Patriots in 1987 (34-31
in overtime) and 1990 (48-20). He was defensive coordinator with
the then Houston Oilers in 1993 when they beat the Patriots, 28-14.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who aren't familiar with the scheme, here's a
refresher course from the Patriots coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scheme is born out of threatening the line of scrimmage
with personnel so that they can be in position to blitz,'' said
Carroll. ``It's born out of having a bunch of guys at the line of
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unusual defense in that they put two linebackers over
the tight end, one right on him and one outside of him, and either
one can blitz and drop. They also have a defensive back as a
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are eight guys at the line of scrimmage, which all can
threaten to blitz. So there are eight guys in the box, so it's
difficult to run the ball, and you can't tell who they are sending
to blitz. The reason it's not a universal defense is you have to
come from the philosophy of being a blitzing, aggressive football
team and you have to learn to live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been Tennessee's mainstay since Ryan's tenure,
and many teams run some variation. ``Denver ran a little bit of it
(in the season opener),'' said center Dave Wohlabaugh. ``They may
have it as one of their premier packages.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to beat the 46, Carroll said, ``you have to get rid of
the football. It makes it difficult because they can confuse you
and send so many different guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears Carroll's pupils have absorbed much of his
instruction. At least they know what they're in for Sunday. ``We
all have to be aware of what your responsibilities are and what
everyone else's responsibilities are,'' said guard Max Lane. ``We
have to know what the fronts are and when they blitz and pick it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Shawn Jefferson agreed, adding that receivers
spend more time performing noncatching duties against the 46 than
any other defense. ``We are going to have to block a lot with this
thing,'' he said. ``They send so many guys out there, and if we're
in maximum protection, a lot of guys are going to have to stay back
and block. But on the flip side, there's a chance for us making a
big play.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll pointed out that one of the keys in getting rid of the
football against the 46 is to read and react quickly. It doesn't
hurt to have a quarterback with a quick release, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is knowing who's hot and when they're overloading
the blitzes,'' he said. ``And there's a lot to it. It's not just
the physical quickness. It's recognizing you have to release'' in
response to what the defense shows.
</P>
<P>
   It won't hurt to have an additional receiver. Carroll said
Friday that tight end Ben Coates, who missed last week's game with
ankle sprains, practiced Thursday and is expected to suit up
Sunday. ``Just the experience of him being able to pick up the
stuff _ and he will have some protections and hot reads and stuff
like that _ will help us,'' said Carroll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
