<HEADER>
A3518 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-CONFIDENCE-3     09-18 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-CONFIDENCE-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS HAVE BECOME ONLY SLIGHTLY MORE CAUTIOUS, SURVEY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The financial and political events of recent weeks have yet to
shake Americans' basic faith in the U.S. economy or their own
finances _ good news for the seven-and-a-half-year-old expansion
and for the president.
</P>
<P>
   Since Russia's collapse, the tumble in stock prices and the
release of the Starr report, consumers have turned only slightly
more cautious, according to a major poll of consumer attitudes
disclosed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Michigan's consumer sentiment index, a
barometer of influences on spending, slipped to 100.1 in September,
from 104.1 in August _ showing only somewhat less upbeat
expectations for the economy in the next year or so.
</P>
<P>
   By past measures, confidence remains exceptionally high. Between
the late 1960s and early 1997, the Michigan index hit 100 or higher
only three times, even during the long, strong expansion of the
1980s. Its average value since 1947, when the survey was begun, is
85.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are demonstrating a remarkable degree of
resilience,'' said Richard Curtin, director of the Center for
Consumer Surveys at the University of Michigan. ``If this is all
the decline there is, the consumer sector will be the strongest
part of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers account for two-thirds of the $8 trillion U.S.
economy. With other sectors, like business investment, slowing, a
sharp retrenchment by consumers could tip the economy into
recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers perceived that the economy slowed significantly in
the third quarter and they expect the slowdown to continue in the
year ahead,'' Curtin said. ``But they still do not expect a
recession.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is especially good news for President Clinton,
whose popularity rests on the healthy economy that has dominated
his time in office. While Congress considers what if any action to
take against the president in coming months, public opinion will be
crucial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A poll released Wednesday showed that a near-record portion _
more than two thirds _ of households rate the condition of the
economy and their own finances as good to excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tells us what the average American is experiencing,''
said Gary Langer, who updates that personal financial survey each
week for Money magazine and ABC. ``What they're experiencing
influences decisions they make and what decisions they make
influence the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although spending is no longer growing rapidly, consumers are
still in a spending mood. With the General Motors strike settled,
car dealers are reporting brisk sales. Despite a wait-and-see
attitude among prospective buyers of luxury homes in some parts of
the country, most builders are reporting strong traffic and a jump
in permits. And retailers posted excellent results on the Labor Day
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The big fear lately has been that fear itself will turn into a
self-fulfilling prophecy. Consumers could take one look at the
declining Dow Jones industrial average, conclude that the economy
will follow stocks downward and retrench in a hurry. Something
similar happened in July 1990 after Iraq invaded Kuwait and
worldwide oil prices doubled.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan poll is reassuring on this score. Back in 1990,
confidence, which had been hovering at 90, plunged by 10 points in
the month following the Kuwait invasion and by 25 points within
three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``In June and July 1990, we were jumping up and down yelling
about the way consumer confidence crating,'' Langer said. ``We're
not jumping up and down right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan report is a preliminary one. Conducted over the
first two weeks of the month, it is based on telephone interviews
with roughly 325 people, out of a total monthly sample of 500
households, chosen to be representative of the nation's consumers.
One encouraging sign is that the tenor of responses did not
deteriorate over the polling period, despite the avalanche of bad
news from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The September reading seems to confirm what pollsters have long
suspected: That the stock market and Washington do not loom as
large in consumer consciousness as do everyday pocketbook issues.
``People don't look to the stock market for cues about the
condition of the economy,'' Langer said. ``They look to their own
experience, especially their pay, their job prospects and the cost
of things they have to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtin said that it would be surprising if the president's
troubles affected confidence much. ``In Watergate there wasn't a
direct effect,'' he said, ``but rather an indirect one, as
consumers eventually concluded that the president was too
preoccupied to deal with the growing economic problems.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not hard to come up with reasons why consumers might
continue to feel good. Prices are remarkably tame, rising 1.6
percent in the past year compared with 1.7 the previous year.
Consumers are paying more for clothing and many services, but they
have rarely seen lower gasoline prices. Home mortgage rates have
plummeted to a 30-year low.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers' moods are most sensitive to their income levels and
job prospects. Income after taxes is growing handily. And the
economy is still adding an average of 200,000 jobs a month.
Consumers' biggest concern, reported Curtin, was that economic
troubles abroad would result in layoffs and higher unemployment at
home. Outside select manufacturing industries, such cutbacks have
not yet materialized. This week, the government reported that
first-time unemployment claims fell below 300,000 in the second
week of September, a 10-year low.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, consumer spending was expected to slow down from its
red-hot pace in the first half of the year. Spending then grew 5
percent, well ahead of the 3 percent growth in after-tax income.
Spending was so strong, in fact, that the saving rate _ the
difference between income and spending _ narrowed to nearly zero by
summer. ``Obviously, that couldn't last under any circumstances,''
said Bruce Steinberg, the chief economist at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in the stock market _ nearly 20 percent from the July
high until the end of August _ means that well-to-do households
that own stock can no longer count on automatic portfolio growth do
their saving for them. The extra kick in consumer spending during
the previous three and a half years as stock prices soared will now
evaporate. The wealth effect, used to describe how much extra
consumers spend as their wealth grows on paper, contributed about
$75 billion to overall consumer spending in three years.
Macroeconomic Advisers Inc. in St. Louis estimates that about
one-third of the growth in spending in the first half of 1998 was
directly attributable to the market. That contribution will drop
from 1.9 percentage points early this year to just 0.5.
</P>
<P>
   In short, most economists expect spending to grow no faster than
income _ about 2 to 3 percent in the next year. That's half the
pace of earlier this year, but still solid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
