<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MURDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS SAY MURDERS APPEAR TO BE DRUG RELATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SAUZAL, Mexico - Fermin Castro is best known in this seaside
coastal village for the fine horses he keeps and the American-style
rodeos he puts on with them.
</P>
<P>
   He also was apparently becoming a big figure in this area's
burgeoning marijuana and heroin market, which the authorities here
believe is why Castro and 20 other members of his family were
pulled from their beds early Thursday morning, lined up against a
wall and shot one by one. Among the dead were two children, ages 1
and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, while Castro, 38, lay in a coma in a hospital in the
nearby fishing and resort town Ensenada, police and army
investigators continued to comb the sprawling, hillside ranch he
owned with two other families. Officials said they also took 10
people into custody for questioning and seized several vehicles and
weapons, ranging from a .45 caliber pistol to an AK-47 rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the testimonies we've received to this moment, it
seems clear that Fermin Castro had activities connected to
narcotics trafficking,'' Jose Luis Chavez, an army general and one
of the lead investigators in the case, said at a press conference
Friday afternoon. ``Let me make it clear that this is not based on
our own evidence, but on the statements we have received.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials also insisted that they could not yet establish a
connection between Thursday's pre-dawn massacre and any other of
the known drug cartels that have sprouted in recent years in the
northwestern state of Baja California or in the state of Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
   Investgators in Mexico City and Tijuana initially suggested the
executions could have been the work of the Arellano Felix
organization, the dominant drug ring in this region, or perhaps be
linked to an equally powerful band in Ciudad Juarez once headed by
the late Amado Carillo Fuentes.
</P>
<P>
   But what remained clear to authorities and residents alike in
this area was that they had never before seen or heard of such
brutal violence, especially against women and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't understand why someone could be so heartless as
to kill babies,'' said Eugenio Sanchez, an 80-year-old resident who
works as a nightwatchman at a ceramics factory that sits about 100
yards from the iron-gated entrance. ``If this was something about
Fermin, that's one thing, but why the women and babies?''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said investigators found a blood-stained chair in the
2-story house and that forensics officials found cuts and lesions
on Castro, signs that he was tortured before being shot in the
head. He added that Castro was the only one who appeared to have
been tortured.
</P>
<P>
   There were two other survivors of the massacre - a 12-year-old
boy, who was shot, and a 15-year-old girl, who is six-months
pregnant, but avoided injury because she hid under a bid throughout
the ordeal and was never spotted by the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the children have been taken to secure and undisclosed
locations, said the state attorney general, Marco Antonio de la
Fuente. Officials did not say if they had yet interviewed the
children.
</P>
<P>
   The victims, some of them wearing pajamas and some naked, were
apparently dragged from their beds at about 4:30 Thursday morning
by a group of intruders who wore black. They were taken outside and
shot at close range. Their corpses were discovered by police less
than an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   One California-based U.S. drug official, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity Friday, said that even though the
Ensenada-Tijuana corridor has seen a significant increase in
drug-related violence in recent years, the brutality demonstrated
by the gunmen was unique for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of this year, a police officer has been
killed and two women have disappeared in what authorities believe
were drug-related incidents in Tijuana and Ensenada. Friday, de la
Fuente and other investigators said the executions at the Castro
ranch did not appear connected to those crimes.
</P>
<P>
   For many residents in the suburb of El Sauzal, where Castro and
his family had lived for about 15 years, the image of Fermin Castro
as an up-and-coming drug baron left many residents surprised and
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the tiny Indian village of Santa Catalina, about 100
miles south of Ensenada, Castro was a bilingual instructor,
teaching both Spanish and his tribal language. He emigrated north
nearly two decades ago and eventually married into a family in this
area that owned restaurants and other small businesses in nearby
San Miguel and in California.
</P>
<P>
   But Castro is most famous among locals for the rodeo he runs,
which travels around the region, and the dozens of show-quality
horses he breeds on his ranch. On Tuesday, as part of El Sauzal's
Independence Day celebrations, Castro put on another rodeo, which
was seen by hundreds of families.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Castro hosted a raucous party at his house,
said Sanchez, the nightwatchman who heard the festivities from his
post. Live bands played a mix of northern and mariachi music well
into the morning.
</P>
<P>
   There were more parties at the ranch nearly all day Wednesday,
neighbors said, but things appeared to settle down that night --
until the shots rang out. Some residents thought the pops were left
over fireworks. But Sanchez said he knew something was wrong when
he heard a woman screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was gunfire and I knew something horrible was
happening, but I stayed down on the floor and away from the
window,'' he added. ``I didn't want to look because I was afraid
that they might shoot me, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
