<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-U.S.-POLICY-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIAN SERB HARDLINER'S SEEMING VICTORY VEXES WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinton administration officials said Friday that
they were dismayed by projections that a hardline nationalist would
be the new president of the Bosnian Serbs, an outcome that would
threaten to undo U.S. efforts to reintegrate Bosnian Serbs, Croats
and Muslims into a single nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nightmare,'' a State Department official said of
reports this week that Nikola Poplasen, an extreme nationalist who
is leader of the Serbian Radical Party, had defeated the
U.S.-backed incumbent, Biljana Plavsic, in elections last weekend
in the Serbian-populated half of Bosnia. ``What do we do if the
thugs are back in charge?''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials say they are hoping that the projections being
offered by European election observers are wrong. Administration
spokesmen have not provided any official comment on the outcome,
noting that the ballot counting is expected to continue into next
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously a lot of the factions are making claims, as they are
wont to do, but it is our view we have to wait for the final
returns and for those results to be certified,'' said James Rubin,
the State Department spokesman. He acknowledged that it was not too
early to describe this as ``the freest and fairest election in
Bosnia's short democratic history.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said it was hard to imagine how the United States
could do business with Poplasen, who promised voters during the
election campaign that the Serbian republic in Bosnia would remain
strong and independent of Muslim influence and Western
manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   A political science professor in prewar Sarajevo, Poplasen
became a leader of Serbian paramilitary units in Bosnia that were
accused by human rights groups of widespread atrocities against
Muslims and Croats, as well as looting and extortion.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was not shy during the campaign about its
support for Mrs. Plavsic, who had wrested control of the government
of the Bosnian Serb republic away from nationalists aligned with
Radovan Karadzic, the wartime leader and indicted war crimes
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright campaigned for Mrs.
Plavsic during a tour of the Balkans last month, standing beside
her at the opening of an electrical substation in Bosnian Serb
territory that had been rebuilt with U.S. aid money.
</P>
<P>
   The United States spent tens of millions of dollars in the last
year to bolster Mrs. Plavsic's standing with the public, hoping
that large U.S.-sponsored public works projects would convince
Bosnian Serb voters that there were tangible benefits to her
government's support for the 1995 Dayton peace agreement that ended
the war.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials say they now fear that the effort
may have backfired, creating for many a perception that Mrs.
Plavsic is a dupe of the United States and is too willing to
compromise with her Muslim and Croatian counterparts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   U.S. officials say the only encouraging news from the election
results is that the weak showing of Poplasen's party in legislative
races might force him to appoint a moderate prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   There is at least a possibility, they said, that he will
reappoint the incumbent, Milorad Dodik, who was named by Mrs.
Plavsic and is another favorite of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get Dodik or someone like him in place, there is
some hope,'' said an administration official. ``If we can't, then
you have to wonder about the point of our efforts to hold Bosnia
together. The election results would certainly suggest that the
Bosnian Serbs are not looking for any sort of reconciliation with
their Muslim and Croat cousins.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say that if the voting trends hold and
Poplasen proves victorious, the United States will cut off millions
of dollars in development aid to the Bosnian Serbs unless it gets a
clear statement from his government that it intends to abide by the
U.S.-brokered Dayton agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of which candidates take office, our expectation of
them will be the same,'' Rubin said. ``If you are prepared to
implement the provisions of Dayton's requirements, then we are
prepared to work with you. If you are not, we will respond
accordingly. And our financial assistance, our diplomatic work and
all of our work will be premised on that simple principle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
