<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3525 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE0919     09-18 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE0919 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RACE BOARD, IN FINAL REPORT, URGES AMERICANS TO CONFRONT HISTORY
OF ``WHITE PRIVILEGE''
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Civil rights leaders, praising the work of
President Clinton's race advisory board Friday, endorsed its final
recommendations, including the creation of a permanent White House
panel on race relations, and urged the president to help Americans
confront the nation's history of ``white privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed, it was worthwhile,'' the Rev. Jesse Jackson said as he
departed an Old Executive Office Building ceremony in which the
board presented the president with its 121-page report on the state
of race relations in America. ``The more we talk to each other, the
more we see the advantage of building relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end, but the beginning,'' said Rep. John
Lewis, D-Ga., a pioneer of the civil rights movement of the 1960s.
``In its own way, the board has started people thinking and
talking.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the board completed its yearlong mission, the ``national
conversation'' on race that the president launched in June 1997
with such high hopes appeared in some jeopardy as a result of the
moral wreckage of Clinton's personal life since his confession of
an extramarital affair with onetime White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the president and his board continued to receive
criticism from the leaders of the movement to abolish affirmative
action programs and all race-based remedies for discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The board ``has failed to recommend any new or interesting
policy ideas,'' said Ward Connerly, chairman of the American Civil
Rights Institute in California and a leader of the anti-affirmative
action movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike President John F. Kennedy, who said that 'race has no
place in American life or law,' President Clinton and his advisors
believe that race matters,'' added Connerly.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Phyllis Berry Myers, a member of the conservative
Center for New Black Leadership, said the board's deliberations
were ``a tired, old side'' of the debate over the course of civil
rights in the next century. ``The real work of racial
reconciliation will never happen in the offices of the federal
government, but on the streets, in our schools and at our
churches,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Joseph Lowery, the retired leader of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, said, ``In an issue as complex as
race, there are a lot of people in denial.'' But he credited the
board with ``pointing us in the direction we need to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential board said America has yet to confront the
damage that ``white privilege'' has done. ``We as a nation need to
understand that whites tend to benefit, either knowingly or
consciously, from this country's history of white privilege,'' its
report said. It is the job of the president to make Americans
understand ``the facts of racial domination,'' it added.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the seven-member board found that ``significant
racial disparities and discrimination continue despite more than 30
years of civil rights laws and some progress directly attributable
to affirmative action and other programs.'' It found ``steadily
improving racial attitudes, especially among whites,'' but
suggested that more direct presidential involvement was needed,
particularly as the population shifts from primarily whites and
blacks to increasing numbers of Hispanics and Asian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   According to the 1990 Census, 73 percent of Americans were
white, 11 percent Hispanic, 12 percent black, 4 percent Asian
Pacific American and 1 percent American Indian and Alaska Native.
</P>
<P>
   The projected figures for 2050 say 53 percent of the population
will be white, 25 percent Hispanic, 14 percent black, 8 percent
Asian Pacific and 1 percent American Indian and Alaska Native.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommended that a permanent board on race relations
be created within the White House. It also endorsed the president's
policy of mending rather than ending affirmative action. And it
recommended areas of study: police misconduct, stereotyping of
minorities in the media, bilingual education, federal employment,
access to technology and conflicts between nonwhite ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's ceremony, the president made only an oblique
reference to his current troubles. ``The more I stay in Washington,
the more I realize that sometimes the very ability to hold strong
opinions depends upon being able to be deaf to the facts,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in an apparent effort to shore up the moral underpinnings of
the event, the White House arranged for Rosa Parks to attend _ and
to be introduced to the audience before the president and the
members of his advisory board. Parks is credited with sparking the
modern civil rights movement with her refusal to move to the back
of a bus in Montgomery, Ala., in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   John Hope Franklin, the noted historian who chaired the
president's race initiative board, told the White House audience
that ``strong leadership'' would be required of Clinton in order to
realize the board's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview following the ceremony, Franklin insisted
that Clinton's confession of moral shortcomings had not undermined
the president's moral authority to promote racial healing in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the president had lost that authority, Franklin
replied, ``Not a great deal. It's not for me to make a judgment.
But he hasn't lost it with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the president did not specifically endorse the board's
recommendations, he praised its work and credited it with having
``raised the consciousness and quickened the conscience of
America.'' He added, ``They have moved us closer to our ideal. But
we have more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he added, ``I think we have to begin with one
clear understanding: When we approach others with discrimination
and distrust, when we demean them from the beginning, when we
believe our power can only come from their subjugation, their
weakness or their destruction, as human beings and as citizens we
pay a terrible price.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony included the announcement of a $1 billion program
for new loans to minority- and women-owned businesses through the
Small Business Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has suggested that he would like racial healing to
be his legacy, is expected to address racial issues again Saturday
at a meeting of the Congressional Black Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
