 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. on the Short End Of Vacation Benefits &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As summer ends, that vacation taken just weeks ago is already a
distant memory, with credit card bills the only real souvenirs.
Perhaps it's not necessary to know that in some countries, many
employees have vacation allowances three times as long as those in
the United States. Hewitt Associates, a management consulting firm
in Lincolnshire, Ill., notes that many other nations set minimum
vacation lengths by law. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never Mind the Starbucks. Please Pass the Carafe &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a small dinner-table revolution, Americans are drinking more
beer, wine and distilled spirits and less coffee, according to a
new study of the nation's eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by the NPD Group of Port Washington, N.Y., found that
alcoholic drinks have slipped past coffee as a beverage at in-home
dinners for the first time in the survey's 13-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The survey asked 5,200 people to keep two-week diaries of
everything they ate and drank. Alcoholic drinks were served at 3.5
percent of all home dinners, edging out coffee, at 3.4 percent. The
top beverage continues to be milk (19.7 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The biggest jump in alcohol use came among consumers 55 to 64
years old. Citing studies that suggest a daily glass of wine can
reduce some health risks, Harry Balzer, an NPD vice president,
said, ``we're going to try to drink ourselves to health.''
</P>
<P>
   Constance L. Hays &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Job Moves: They're Not Just For Sluggish Economies &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a weak economy, people often relocate to find jobs. But a
strong economy can also feed the urge to move.
</P>
<P>
   Among people looking for new jobs, 27 percent relocated in the
second quarter, according to a quarterly survey of 3,000
job-seekers by Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, an outplacement
company in Chicago. That compares with 18 percent in the first
quarter, and with a quarterly average of 21 percent for 1995-97.
</P>
<P>
   There are seasonal factors for the second-quarter increase _
more people move, for example, as the weather warms up. Still, the
27 percent figure is about equal to the quarterly averages for a
two-year period when the economy was slower _ 1991 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Relocation now can be a result of tight job markets that force
employers to offer candidates lucrative salaries and signing
bonuses, said John A. Challenger, executive vice president of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that more double-income households are
moving. ``With such a hot job market, spouses are reassured that a
move doesn't mean demotion,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laura Castaneda
</P>
</TEXT>
