<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-MARATHON-DRIVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BROOKLYN GRANNY'S 30,000-MILE DRIVE BRINGS SERENITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lookout posted outside Melvin Mister's house gave
the doorbell two urgent rings, prompting him to scramble from the
parlor to the sidewalk. He got outside in time to see his wife,
Joan, drive up in her silver Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There she is,'' Melvin said, as his wife stepped into the
street and gave him a peck on the cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went out for a short drive,'' she said. ``How is
everybody?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember me?'' Melvin asked as he embraced her.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, he helped carry some of her travel bags into the
house. She looked at him and smiled. ``You look real good,'' she
said. ``Nothing like a little absence.''
</P>
<P>
   With all that affection, that must have been some drive. It was.
Joan, 65, had returned Wednesday to her neighborhood in Lefferts
Gardens, Brooklyn, after her Big Trip: a six-month, 30,038-mile
journey through 48 states. She easily surpassed her goal to drive
as far as the earth's circumference, logging 1,000 miles for every
year she has been married to Melvin, 60, with whom she spoke every
day she was gone. Her route resembled a spaghetti heap that looped
and crossed over prairies, plains and mountains, as she followed
her heart rather than a compass.
</P>
<P>
   There's a similar tangle of emotions inside her, since the trek
by the self-described ``Brooklyn Granny'' was the kind of open-road
adventure that combined equal parts of mythic heroism and American
wanderlust. She savored every moment: moonlit nights spent in a
tent, sharing dinners in simple homes, casual conversations at
diners, and even a spirited church service where the black
congregation called her Sister Mister.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times I felt like Luke Skywalker, driving along on the
surface of the planet,'' she said. ``Especially in southwest Texas,
where I wouldn't see another car in front or behind me. There I was
in this scrubby area on the frontier. It was astounding. It looked
the way God flung the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't totally alone. A few days into her trip, she visited
the Antietam National Battlefield in Maryland. She thought about
the young men who died there in the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought: `You guys didn't see too much of the world in your
time. You died young. Why don't you come along?''' she said. ``I
needed some company. I think they all said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   She could have used their help when she locked her keys inside
her car. But she did just fine another time when a drunken man
shouted obscenities at her while she was using a pay phone at a
campsite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been given mountain lion training because a mountain
lion had swiped a woman and her child,'' she said. ``We were told
if we saw one, keep your ground, act big and make a lot of noise. I
never saw a mountain lion, but that's what I gave this guy. I never
shouted so loud in public.''
</P>
<P>
   The drunk was one of the few grouches she met along the way. Of
the many who shared their lives with her, she is especially fond of
two women she met at a Shoney's in Florida. One had a brother in
Brooklyn, and they got to talking. By the end of their conversation
the woman, a poet, offered to write a poem for her. ``The people I
met along the way affected me deeply,'' she said. ``I don't know if
the internal or external journey was the deepest.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin shares that feeling, since his wife's example led him to
reconsider his own work-work-work life and nurture his secret
desires. He took a trip of his own to Montana and started catching
up on sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joan's pursuit of her Big Trip made me feel like it was
possible for me to chart some new directions,'' he said. ``Your
sense of freedom is something very internal. These external things
_ the car, the job, the money _ they are important. But what goes
on inside is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife learned that lesson by the mile, with help from a book,
``Zen Driving,'' her son Tommy gave her. It spoke of the ``eternal
moment,'' which seemed appropriate the other day as she was stuck
in traffic near Court Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving is about experience and awareness,'' she said. ``That
may be sort of what life is all about, too. All we have in life is
the present. Whatever the moment is. The moment at hand is a
traffic jam.''
</P>
<P>
   She seized it, chatting up a man who was unloading crates of
beer into a warehouse. Small talk for a small moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only going to see what I see,'' she said as the traffic
cleared. ``Even if it's only this intersection.''
</P>
<P>
   After 48 states, she was serene. She was in a state the frantic
jaywalkers and horn honkers would envy, if they only knew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
