<HEADLINE>
NEW DATA WON'T OFFEND DURING ROSH HASHANA, JEWS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As Jews across the country attend religious services
Monday in observation of Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year, the US
House will release reams of x-rated documents and television
stations will begin broadcasting President Clinton's sexually
loaded videotaped grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sanctity of the holiday, however, Jewish leaders say
they were not offended by the GOP's timing in making public the
latest round of details about Clinton's extramarital affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said they hoped religious observances that day
would give Jews a chance to escape the continuing flood of
publicity about the issue. They also expressed the belief that the
inevitable uproar Monday won't cause Jews to pay less attention to
one of their holiest holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be a distraction to Jews,'' said Rabbi
Michael Menitoff of Congregation Mishkan Tefila in Chestnut Hill.
``I'm not sure that releasing it on Rosh Hashana would be different
than releasing it on any other day.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosh Hashana is a time when Jews reflect on their lives,
families and communities, and consider ways to become better
citizens. Jews traditionally attend special services with their
families, and many refrain from doing work or watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Emily Lipof of Ohabei Shalom in Brookline said she was
glad that the House Judiciary Committee had decided to release the
documents and videotape on a Jewish holy day. That way, she said,
Jews won't ``be listening to that garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipof said she was angry that Republican members of Congress
decided to release the tapes at all, saying the public already
knows that Clinton lied and had an adulterous affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the saddest, ugliest moments in history,''
Lipof said of the tapes' upcoming release. ``It's much worse than
anything Clinton has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipof nevertheless said she doubts anyone who feels the spirit
of the high holy day will allow the Clinton testimony to moot their
synogogue experience.
</P>
<P>
   Another Brookline rabbi, William Hamilton of Congregation
Kehillath Israel, said he wasn't offended by the decision to
release the tapes on Rosh Hashana because he's used to major news
stories breaking on Jewish holidays.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to stay away from the topic during his sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my congregants know very well what's right and what's
wrong and about the predicament this country now faces. They know
deceit when they see it. They know partisan politics when they see
it,'' Hamilton said. ``Frankly, there's very little I can add.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said he wants to give his congregants a respite from a
``media culture and societal obsession that seems rather
relentless.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the Sabbath Friday, Debra Hachen, rabbi of
Congregation B'nai Shalom in Westborough, said she has more
important spiritual issues on her mind than what day Congress will
release the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter what day they release the tapes. I
don't take offense to it. ... There are lots of things that happen
on Saturday,'' Hachen said, referring to the Sabbath, when
observant Jews refrain from watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   She said any Jew interested in watching the president's
testimony can do so during replays later in the week anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something they have to act on right away,'' Hachen
said. ``They can deal with the tapes any day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
