<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLISHERS SAY STARR REPORT IS A BEST SELLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD, CLINTON-BLACKS,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-DEFENSE)  
(js) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the week since three publishers started selling sober-looking
versions of ``that book'' _ the 400-plus-page report of the
Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr _ the steamy
chronicle of the relationship between President Clinton and Monica
Lewinsky is selling at brisker rates than Tom Clancy's new novel
about an elite antiterrorist squad.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 1.5 million copies of ``The Starr Report''
printed, two of the book's three publishers are poised to issue
sequels with the expected release of 2,800 pages of evidence
compiled by the independent counsel's investigators. Since
government documents are in the public domain, publishers are free
to use the material without paying royalties or advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rate of sales so far is fairly astonishing,'' said Liz
Hartman, a spokeswoman for Simon &AMP; Schuster's Pocket Books, which
initially printed 650,000 copies of its $5.99 paperback and has now
increased its run to a total of 800,000. She added that the company
is still uncertain about how many copies of the sequel it will
print but that the sequel already has a title: ``The Starr
Evidence: Testimony From President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky and
Other Documents From the Independent Counsel's Investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of the report has also created a sudden burst of
literary demand for Walt Whitman's ``Leaves of Grass.'' Whitman's
book receives a warm endorsement from Ms. Lewinsky in the Starr
report, which quotes her as calling it ``the most sentimental
gift'' the president gave her.
</P>
<P>
   At the national Borders Books &AMP; Music chain, sales of ``Leaves
of Grass'' increased by 100 percent with the release of the Starr
report, but even more impressive was the demand for all three book
versions of the report itself, according to Jody Kohn, a
spokeswoman for the chain, which operates more than 225 stores.
</P>
<P>
   The early sales of the three versions, published by Pocket
Books, Prima Publishing and Public Affairs, ``were twice as strong
as the first day of sales of the new Tom Clancy novel, `Rainbow
Six,' '' Ms. Kohn said.
</P>
<P>
   Prima, a 14-year-old independent publisher in Rocklin, Calif.,
has published government documents before, including a report by
the surgeon general on health in America and a study on exports.
But its president and founder, Ben Dominitz, said the company had
never encountered such keen demand for a government report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are buying our book as a collectible as well as
perusing it at leisure,'' said Dominitz. He added that his company,
which printed 300,000 copies of the report, tried to strike a
dignified tone with a dark-blue and white cover.
</P>
<P>
   California-based Dove Audio is preparing an eight-hour, $19.95
audio version of the document, ``The Starr Report: Substantial and
Credible Information.'' The company expects to start shipping to
stores by Oct. 12, although it would like to rush the tape out
faster, according to Charna West, a sales representative for
Newstar Media, which owns the imprint. A male and female actor will
read the various parts of the report, with the White House rebuttal
and some commentary read by two lawyers, including the well-known
trial lawyer Alan Dershowitz.
</P>
<P>
   This sudden rush in sales, obviously, does not mean the original
authors will share in any of this wealth, because the report is
part of the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't seem to disturb Lynn Chu, a literary agent whose
clients include Newt Gingrich and whose New York literary agency,
Writers Representatives, has in the past represented Starr and
Stephen Bates, one of the main authors of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me,'' Ms. Chu said. ``I'm sure there will be
many cool books written about this.'' She added, ``I actually tried
to lend a hand by calling the publishers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
