<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WHITE-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PREPARING TO DEFLECT IMPACT OF NEW MATERIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House is bracing for a negative public
reaction to more tawdry details of President Clinton's relationship
with Monica S. Lewinsky, while hoping against hope that the
American people will be so disgusted that they will direct their
anger primarily at the Republicans for releasing the material.
</P>
<P>
   Senior White House officials are ready to pounce on possible
news leaks as early as this weekend, though the GOP majority on the
House Judiciary Committee voted not to release until Monday the
videotape of Clinton's grand jury testimony and 2,800 pages of
documents on the sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Those officials openly fretted Friday about the contents of the
material and about the reaction to the videotape. Their chief worry
is that viewers will take the information at face value, even
though it represents only the prosecutor's side of the case; they
said they are particularly concerned because they are trying to
formulate a defense without having been shown the potentially
volatile materials in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we are put in a very difficult posture having all
this released without an opportunity to review it,'' said James
Kennedy, a White House lawyer and spokesman. ``One must recognize
that this is raw, untested grand jury material, and it will be
magnified to the extent that there are leaks emanating from various
sources that could be taking things out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House aide, who spoke on the condition of
anonimity, said: ``Anytime you've got a party that has control of a
committee and that has a hard-core political agenda and is so
heavy-handed about it and they have all this material _ you have to
be concerned about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, White House officials are left to talk on the
margins of the evidence against the president. They portray the
Judiciary Committee's release of the material as overtly partisan
while accusing Republicans of having politicized the impeachment
process, an argument the White House plans to make when
administration officials fan out on Sunday's talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``At bottom, this will fall on the judgment of the American
people and whether they conclude that the process is fair,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the administration was buoyed by some long-desired
reinforcement from Democrats on the Judiciary Committee, who went
before reporters immediately after the party-line vote on releasing
the grand jury materials. For the first time in weeks, a chorus of
Democrats spoke out, condemning any notion that the process had
been fair and nonpartisan.
</P>
<P>
   Representative John Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on
the Judiciary Committee, said that during the investigation of
President Nixon in 1974, records were kept private for seven weeks
to give congressional officials a chance to carefully examine them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we've dumped process and fairness on its head,''
said Conyers, who also served on the committee during the Watergate
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials viewed Friday's reaction of House
Democrats _ many of whom have been harshly critical of the
president's handling of the Lewinsky affair _ partly as a product
of the recent hiring of several aides to help repair Clinton's
relationship with his own party on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   White House deputy press secretary Barry Toiv, in a briefing
with reporters, repeatedly referred to committee Democrats'
statements to back up the administration's rallying cry that the
House process is proceeding unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Based on ``what a number of the members coming out of the room
have had to say about the process,'' he said, ``we would have hoped
for a process that was bipartisan. Last week, it seemed like they
were headed in a direction towards bipartisanship, and they seem to
be going in the other direction now.''
</P>
<P>
   Another senior aide described the process as ``wholly
political,'' and therefore one that the White House, with its
political agility, may have a chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make people understand how this has now become a
political process, a partisan effort to cancel the election, and
how they (Republicans) are determined to batter us all with all
this information,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, White House aides said their plan is to keep Clinton
from being dragged down by the scandal, by staying focused on
policy; to continue making comparisons to congressional leaders'
handling of Watergate to underscore the fairness question; and to
expand their outreach to congressional Democrats, whose support
they will need even more in the event of an impeachment hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going someplace none of us has been before,'' said Ann
Lewis, communications director at the White House. ``We are going
to have to take it step by step.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide, meanwhile, underscored just how political and
partisan the administration's view of the situation has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a point at which they (Republicans) pay the
price for politicizing this,'' said the aide. ``There's not an
appetite for, based on the polling, a long and drawn out and
explicit and revealing yearlong public debate about this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
