<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-DIVEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD SLOW   TO DROP SOUTH AFRICA-LINKED INVESTMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Surrounded by black-velvet pageantry and
time-honored etiquette, Nelson Rolihlahla Mandela walked through
Harvard Yard Friday a president and an icon of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The honorary degree he accepted _ only the third the university
has granted to a single individual outside of commencement _ put
him in a thin stratosphere with George Washington and Winston
Churchill, whose 1943 Latin citation foreshadowed Mandela's legacy:
``A statesman and warrior whose tenacity and courage turned back
the tide of tyranny in freedom's darkest hour.''
</P>
<P>
   But 20 years ago, in 1978, the picture at Harvard could not have
been more different.
</P>
<P>
   In South Africa, Mandela languished in an island prison,
breaking rocks on a diet of stale vegetables. And on a bleak winter
day in Cambridge, students protesting Harvard's refusal to divest
funds from the country that imprisoned him transformed Harvard Yard
into a symbolic cemetery, planting black crosses into the packed
snow of its lawns.
</P>
<P>
   This week, some who watched and lived through the waves of
protest that rocked Harvard for a quarter-century said Mandela's
arrival brought strange closure to a protracted moral crisis at the
university.
</P>
<P>
   Through sit-ins, hunger strikes, and even the election of
Archbishop Desmond Tutu to the Harvard Board of Overseers, the
university clung to its refusal to totally divest in South Africa
through 1990, when Mandela's release from prison signaled the end
of white rule and eased worldwide pressure to divst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard was a slow and reluctant participant in the campaign
to push companies it had stock in to influence the South African
government,'' said Robert K. Massie, author of ``Loosing the
Bonds,'' a prize-winning book that chronicles US-South African
relations over the last 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Massie, who lives in Somerville, attended Friday's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``They questioned the idea that a university should have any
role in ending an unjust system such as apartheid,'' Massie said.
``Now, after so many years, it is both fitting and ironic that they
are honoring the man who, more than any other, helped to bring that
cruel system of racism to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement to divest began in the 1960s as a groundswell of
church leaders, left-wing activists, and foundations who saw US
investments in South Africa as an endorsement of apartheid, and
mushroomed into a national push to force US companies to withdraw
economically from South Africa. Injecting moral urgency into the
equation of capital and profit, the movement spurred some of the
world's largest corporations and many US cities to pull billions of
dollars worth of stock out of firms that did business in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, an anti-apartheid coalition called MassDIVEST
spearheaded an effort that led the state in 1983 to sell $68
million in investments in companies doing business in South Africa.
It was the first full divestment of a state pension plan in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard, with an endowment of $4.5 billion and some $400
million in South Africa-related stock, was slow to pull its capital
interests out of the country. While student protests at other US
universities like Yale and Columbia led those schools to divest
completely, Harvard adopted a policy of gradualism and partial
divestment that fueled a constant, consuming battle between
students, many alumni, and the university's managers.
</P>
<P>
   The school argued against divestment repeatedly, saying it was
ineffective, costly and could potentially worsen conditions for the
country's already-oppressed blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tenure of former Harvard president Derek Bok, the
sometimes-dormant, sometimes-volatile controversy focused worldwide
attention and pressure on the school _ so much so that Bok later
said his 20-year tenure ``sometimes seemed like one long debate
about divestment.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as 1972, dozens of black students took over
Massachusetts Hall, the oldest building on campus and the heart of
Harvard's central administration, forcing Bok to find temporary
office space in another building. Six years later, Stephen Biko's
murder, rioting in Soweto and the lack of movement on issues of
divestment inside the university reignited mass protests.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, 1,500 students streamed into Harvard Yard and again
took control of Massachusetts Hall, blocking Bok from his own
offices after a report released by Harvard's corporate managers
said the board would review investments on a case-by-case basis,
but would not take a stand for blanket divestment.
</P>
<P>
   After the protests waned, in the 1980s, students and alumni
developed new strategies, holding their donations to Harvard's
endowment in escrow pending divestiture, and inflitrating Harvard's
Board of Overseers through petitions that put pro-divestment
candidates on ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The argument of ineffectiveness would soon prove fragile, when,
in 1991, Harvard sold $51 million in Citicorp debt instruments when
the bank decided to lend money directly to the South African
government. That decision sent shock waves to policy-makers and
Wall Street watchers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   With Mandela's US arrival focusing new attention at Harvard
Friday, the first president of a democratic South Africa spoke only
of Harvard's contributions to the anti-apartheid fight, not its
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Some who fought for divestment in years past said it was in
keeping with optimism and the serene diplomacy Mandela has shown to
those who took conflicting positions in the struggle to end
apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration of the university strongly resisted taking
what clearly was the most effective action which other people in
the world took, and that was divestment,'' said Robert B. Zevin, an
economist and retired portfolio manager who was active in the
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that this was the most important step in
a chain of events that brought apartheid to an end. Mandela himself
has said that without the international community boycott and
sanctions, apartheid would not have ended,'' said Zevin. ``He does
Harvard honor by accepting a degree.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
