</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-SCENE-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLING BEHIND CLOSED DOORS; PONTIFICATING FRONT OF TV CAMERAS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas, Ind., Fla., Ga., S.C.)   (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD,
CLINTON-BLACKS, CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-DAY,
CLINTON-DEFENSE.) 
(lh) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By midday, the principal legislators at the heart
of the crisis left their debating chamber and eagerly strutted
toward what threatens to be the dominant forum in their judgment of
President Clinton, the television screens of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last day and half has been a sobering experience,''
declared Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., as a group of Judiciary
Committee members descended on the clot of cameras and microphones
waiting at the news media's traditional crisis oasis, by the shade
of a big elm tree southeast of the Capitol dome.
</P>
<P>
   At great length, members told alternate tales of what went on in
the private meeting that led to the decision to flood the nation's
airwaves first thing Monday with fresh reams of lurid detail about
the case against President Clinton. The promised tape of the
president's grand jury testimony was not yet public, so television
producers could afford to give the lawmakers extra swathes of air
time to argue their differences and complaints on camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``A voyeuristic peep show,'' decried one Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted civility was salvaged. ``Nobody hit anybody
else over the head with a cane or anything, like in the old days,''
said Lamar Smith, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But as the partisan passion became acidly clear on television
screens across the nation, other members offered private accounts
of the tooth-and-claw battling that, under a portrait of Watergate
committee chairman Peter Rodino, went on behind closed doors for
two days in the Judicary Committee room.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise highlight, by common measure of Democrats and
Republicans, was an unexpected proposal to describe one of
approximately 120 proposed ``redactions'' _ deletions of explicit
file material _ not simply as ``sexual description'' but as a more
specific description of the interplay between the president and Ms.
Lewinsky. Even in private, participants reported, the chairman,
Henry Hyde, was obviously startled by the proposal to use such
explicit language.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare moment of recognizing a common danger, the proposal,
attributed to Rep. Bob Inglis, R-S.C., was voted down and the less
titillating label set in place. Of such were the redaction fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a pretty sight,'' one losing Democrat summarized
with a near shiver of the committee's two days of private wrangling
in the Sam Rayburn House Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   Out by the elm tree afterward, members sought to explain what
they had done. Hyde noted that the committee's delving into this
underside of the crisis was hardly over, with the contents of 17
cartons still to be analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think there was graphic sexual material in the report
itself?'' asked Democratic minority counsel Abbe Lowell of the
impeachment allegations offered last week by Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr. ``Just wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde offered the television a genial pronouncement: ``The spirit
of bipartisanship is alive and flourishing.'' Nearby, Democrats in
the camera-ready crowd offered double-takes of disbelief.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At first, the Republican majority hoped to have the deletions
and the release of fresh material settled by 2 p.m. Thursday. But
Democrats weighed in with a tattoo of time-consuming counter
proposals, from an attempt to debate a basic definition of ``high
crimes,'' to a simpler motion to at least release to the public the
first few hours of speechifying at the closed session. After a
burst of dispute, this was defeated, but the Republicans' target
release time was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the members reassembled and skirmished, by several
accounts, over perhaps 10 of the 120 redactions agreed upon for the
agenda by the majority and minority staffs. One of these was
described by one participant as centering on one of the more
ludicrous and lurid details of the long investigation, with the
call to make it public finally lost by Bob Barr, R-Ga., a longtime
advocate of impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at every context, every nuance,'' said Barr
after the committee broke for the larger TV forum.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the material, Bill McCollum, R-Fla., apologized, ``is
sexually explicit, and I think that's unfortunate.'' But, he
explained, the president had forced this through his testimony on
the soon-to-be-revealed television tape ``which you've been asking
about.'' As he spoke, the White House was denouncing the committee
majority for engineering a ``rush to prejudgment'' and Democrats
warned that polls show that the public heartily opposes another
wave of sexual revelations from the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying not to be guided by polls, but by our instinct
and principles,'' said Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Off-camera, a Democrat bracing for Monday muttered, ``Sure, this
means the public has to see every jot and tittle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
