<HEADER>
A3537 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     09-18 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO BRUINS, WINLESS MEANS DANGEROUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Stiff and sore and settling onto his couch, UCLA
safety Larry Atkins flicked on ``SportsCenter'' last Saturday and
was amazed by what he saw: North Carolina State 24, Florida State
7. Atkins leaned toward the TV, inhaling the highlights while
expecting a correction. There had to be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit him.
</P>
<P>
   If it happened to the mighty Seminoles, it could happen to
anyone _ including No. 4 UCLA, a four-touchdown favorite this
afternoon against winless Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the type of games you have to watch for, games when
a team is expected to win,'' Atkins said. ``You can't have that
attitude. We've got to have the same attitude (against Houston)
that we had against Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, UCLA's sky glows with warning flares. There's one
coming from Chapel Hill, N.C., where the Tar Heels lost to Miami
(Ohio) two weeks ago. There's one coming from Ann Arbor, Mich.,
where the defending national champions are 0-2 after a home loss to
Syracuse. And another coming from Tempe, where Arizona State coach
Bruce Snyder talks of ``finding the black box'' to decode the Sun
Devils' disastrous 0-2 start.
</P>
<P>
   But the brightest flare is in the mirror. Just last year, the
0-2 Bruins got their shot at a ranked team, locked and loaded, and
did not miss. Now the roles are reversed. They're the heavies, with
0-2 Houston thinking upset, hoping to catch UCLA in a lull between
Texas and next week's foe, Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to remind (ourselves) of last year,'' UCLA
quarterback Cade McNown said. ``We were 0-2 and came out and put up
66 (against Texas). I don't see us looking past anybody now. We're
not in the position to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not with the national title on their radar screen. To that end,
the Bruins face 11 rounds of single-elimination play _ an extended
NCAA Tournament _ because their first loss will be their last loss
as far as the Bowl Championship Series is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loss to Houston is like a loss to Texas,'' McNown said.
``It's like a loss to Miami. It's a loss. It's the early season,
and we want to work out the kinks and get to be a well-oiled
machine quickly. Houston presents an opportunity to get geared up
for league (play).''
</P>
<P>
   Since its school-record 11-game winning streak began, UCLA has
performed at high efficiency against lesser opponents. The Bruins
smashed Houston 66-10 last year at the Rose Bowl, then crushed
underdogs Oregon State (34-10) and Cal (35-17) later in the season.
But those Bruins had seniors on defense and seniors at the scoring
positions and a chip on their collective shoulder the size of Ryan
Leaf and Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   This group oozes underclassmen _ 16 of the 22 starters, in fact
_ and they know only success. Who's to keep tailback Jermaine
Lewis, flanker Freddie Mitchell, defensive end Kenyon Coleman or
cornerback Marques Anderson from taking a three-hour snooze in the
heat and humidity of Robertson Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Toledo, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be careful,'' Toledo said. ``We can fall into a
trap and not be ready. I'm constantly reminding them: `We can't
lose respect.' We've got to find something to fear.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't be easy. The Cougars are younger than UCLA, with
three senior starters. They scored 10 points at Cal and seven
points against Minnesota. Their quarterback, Jason McKinley, has
been sacked 10 times, and their tailback, Ketric Sanford, missed
last year's game (emergency appendectomy) and remains a mystery to
the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, Toledo will focus on Houston's defense, which ranks
second in the nation in rushing (19 yards per game), and on the
unusual atmosphere. Robertson Stadium holds 20,500 and is little
more than a glorified high school field. He'll warn the Bruins of
nasty weather and intense crowd and a potential ambush.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo received no help from Houston coach Kim Helton, whose
effusive praise for McNown and Co. _ ``The best college offensive
team I've enjoyed watching in a long time'' _ appeared plagiarized
from the Lou Holtz Guide to Sandbagging.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to the Bruins to prove Helton right, and to avoid
turning Houston into this week's version of N.C. State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
