<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HOLIDAY FROM FEAR, OR HOPE, IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the bustling, open-air Mahane Yehuda Market,
David Biton pressed his ear to a cell phone and then barked out his
wife's holiday food orders to the vendors: apples, honey, fish,
head of lamb.
</P>
<P>
   On the last full shopping day before the Jewish New Year begins
on Sunday night, Israelis Friday crowded this market, the target of
many past bombings. At the same time as 5,000 Palestinians marched
through the West Bank calling for a return to violence, shoppers
said they were willfully ignoring the threat of reprisals for the
Israeli army slaying of two Islamic militants last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep in their hearts, everyone here is afraid,'' Biton, a
41-year-old drug counselor, said, standing inches from the site
where 15 people were killed by suicide bombers last summer. ``But
it's best to believe that we have extra protection from above
during the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   On the next to last day of an American peace team's visit here,
a kind of national skepticism about the stalemated peace process
softened ever so slightly following Friday's reports that Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright has promised to meet next week in the
United States with the Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But holiday errands took precedence as busy shoppers said there
was no point in following every downturn and uptick in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another meeting is another meeting,'' Batsheva Eliyahu, 52, a
secretary, said as she waited to buy honey cake. ``Someday,
hopefully, there will be peace. Then we will pay full attention.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five years since the Oslo interim peace agreement was
signed, the negotiations over Israeli withdrawal from Palestinian
territories have become so protracted that much of the nation has
turned away from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing, at least on the Israeli side, is a growing
apathy to the process,'' said Chemi Shalev, political analyst for
Maariv, one of the three major newspapers. ``So long as there is no
great outburst of terrorism, they feel they can live with the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a year since the last deadly terrorist attack hit a
pedestrian mall in the heart of Jerusalem, which was preceded by
the suicide bombing five weeks earlier at the Mahane Yehuda market.
</P>
<P>
   Facing new threats, Israeli security officials said they were
most concerned about car bombs in the major cities and the
abduction of soldiers. Soldiers received special training in how to
behave when hitchhiking home from their posts for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Aggravating tensions was Thursday's killing of a Palestinian
teen-ager by a Jewish settler, who gunned down the boy after his
car was stoned in a town outside Ramallah. When angry Palestinians
marched Friday, they chanted for a coffin to be specially made for
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   During the Americans' 11-day visit here, negotiators have
hammered away at details of the Israeli troop withdrawal from 13
percent of the West Bank, and at a security agreement that calls
for a Palestinian Authority crackdown on terrorism and extremist
propaganda. The American envoy, Dennis Ross, has ping-ponged
between Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, with
occasional sidetrips to see Egyptian and Jordanian officials.
Tight-lipped in public, Ross issued a rare burst of optimism
Friday, declaring that he had ``made headway.''
</P>
<P>
   During Ross' visit, each side has vehemently accused the other
of intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   Given the deep-seated mistrust between them, many Israelis and
many Palestinians question the value that any agreement would have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not talking about peace any more,'' said Orly Levy, 23,
an English-speaking Israeli student who was shopping for a New
Year's dress on Ben Yehuda Street. ``We are talking about a piece
of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Abu Manmoud, a retired worker and resident of the West Bank town
of Bitunya, agreed: ``What they are talking about is nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Political insiders have been debating both leaders' motivations
for pursuing or abandoning an agreement at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   One of Netanyahu's advisers said that the prime minister feels
he needs an agreement to enhance his political standing at home and
abroad. Another adviser, though, said he is reluctant to turn over
more of the West Bank because then Arafat will have more territory
if he makes a unilateral declaration of statehood next May.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian advisers to Arafat are also of mixed mind. One said
that he wants as much land as possible in advance of next May. And
another said it could be politically advantageous to arrive at next
May without any agreement because then the world would blame the
Israelis for giving him no choice but to declare a state.
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to rise above the local pessimism, Ron Pundak, one of
the authors of the Oslo agreement, said the nation was weathering
what would look, in 20 years, like ``mere hiccups in the historical
process of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the ground, though, what many factored into their
skepticism was growing doubt about the authority of the current
American administration, not to broker a deal but to see it
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder if, in the end, this shuttle diplomacy is
going to produce anything but frequent flier mileage,'' said Hannan
Ashrawi, a Palestinian leader who recently resigned from Arafat's
cabinet. ``We don't want to be used, to be subject to the domestic
political considerations of the American administration.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
