<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT PROCESS CLOUDED BY RELEASE OF NEW MATERIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the 37 men and women who will oversee the first
stage of the impeachment inquiry into President Clinton, there
could hardly have been a more ignominious start to their most
serious task, constitutional scholars said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A week that began with solemn talk of sacred oaths and
commitments to bipartisanship ended, for the House Judiciary
Committee, in a polarizing vote to release another trove of lurid
materials.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, even the committee's white-thatched chairman,
Henry Hyde, respected for his judicious manner, found himself
fending off tales of his own three-decades-old marital misdeeds.
And Friday's closed-door vote was followed, seemingly inevitably,
by a series of hyperbolic press conferences, as members sought to
impose their spin on what had transpired inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the initial rhetoric was promising, but the way it
ended this week was less promising,'' said Michael Gerhardt, a law
professor at the College of William and Mary and author of a
respected text on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The infighting bodes ill for the country, because the integrity
of the impeachment process depends on members' abilities to reach a
consensus, Gerhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that members of Congress can rise above partisan
politics,'' he said. ``The framework of impeachment encourages them
to do that. Also, because their decisions aren't reviewable (in
court), one hopes they'll be able to reach judgments that will
withstand the test of history.''
</P>
<P>
   For many scholars, the opening week of hearings also raised
another question, more fundamental to the Constitution: Does the
committee plan to conduct its own, thorough investigation, or
simply use Kenneth W. Starr's report as the main grist for its
inquiry?
</P>
<P>
   ``Constitutionally speaking, Starr is not the one who is
supposed to be doing the investigation,'' said Tracey Maclin, a
professor of constitutional law at Boston University Law School.
``Here we have Starr laying out most of the charges and the
committee voting up or down. That's not what the framers had in
mind. The committee should do the investigating.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's power derives from the independent counsel law, not the
Constitution, and his role in the impeachment inquiry is unformed;
his report should be the starting point for a probe, not the
wrap-up, Maclin and others said.
</P>
<P>
   During the previous presidential impeachment case, in 1973,
there was no independent counsel law in place. The House Judiciary
Committee met behind closed doors, taking testimony from President
Richard Nixon's aides, and revealed its findings later. A special
prosecutor, appointed by the Justice Department, worked on a
separate track.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been entirely different from what we did,''
complained former representative Robert F. Drinan, a Massachusetts
Democrat who was on the Judiciary Committee during the Nixon probe.
``We went into secret session immediately. We felt we were acting
as a grand jury and didn't want to hurt any innocent people. We
wanted to be fair to the president. I don't see any fairness in
what they're doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's vote to release President Clinton's videotaped
testimony, the House minority leader, Richard A. Gephardt, quickly
blamed the Republicans for pressing ahead with the release of
embarrassing material through votes along strict party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spirit of bipartisanship cannot be `alive and well' as
Chairman Hyde has claimed, when party line votes decide issues of
disagreement between the parties,'' said Gephardt, a Missouri
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's Republican majority, however, suggested that
Democrats were using partisan warfare to deflect attention from
Clinton. In a prepared statement, they declared, ``The process is
working just as our founding fathers intended, and no amount of
partisan sniping will keep us from doing our job in a responsible
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders had a grim view of both parties' performances during
the opening act of this drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're off to a bad start after a lot of talk about
bipartisanship,'' said George Dargo, professor of constitutional
law at New England School of Law, pointing to the largely
party-line votes to release Starr's report before allowing
Clinton's lawyers to review it, and Friday's decision to issue
copies of the tape of Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   David Stewart, managing partner of the Washington office of
Ropes &AMP; Gray who represented Judge Walter Nixon during his
impeachment proceedings in the late '80s, said the partisanship on
the Judiciary Committee suggests that Congress _ and the country _
are a long way from resolving their feelings about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it remains partisan, it indicates that the process
is not nearly complete,'' Stewart said. ``When it becomes
nonpartisan, that's when you reach consensus, and either the
president is cooked, or the president is free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
