<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR HOLYFIELD, LOCATION IS EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ That age-old question _ if a heavyweight title bout is
held with only one fighter's name on the marquee, will anybody
care? _ just might be answered tonight in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   It is being billed as Evander Holyfield's ``Homecoming Party,''
and this undoubtedly was the only way to entice 30,000 fans to pay
good money to watch Holyfield fight That Great Unknown, Vaughn
Bean. Stage the fight in Atlanta, Holyfield's hometown, and the
1,000 fans who might show up otherwise will be multiplied
thirtyfold.
</P>
<P>
   The utmost gravity with which Holyfield, the World Boxing
Association and International Boxing Federation champion, is
approaching this bout is reflected in his fight-day preparations _
the champ Saturday will be watching his sons play football in the
Atlanta area, one a Pee Wee game, the other for older boys. ``Just
another day at the office,'' said Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to fight; I'm here to do a job,'' said Bean (31-1, 25
knockouts against mostly stiffs). ``This will be a September to
remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a good Don King line, from the the ``Thrilla in
Manila'' genre. Holyfield, of course, hasn't fought in 10 months
since finishing off Michael Moorer for the IBF crown with an
eighth-round TKO last November in Las Vegas, a fight in which he
sent Moorer to the canvas five times.
</P>
<P>
   Bean also has fought Moorer, and that might be the only glimmer
of hope for Saturday night's fight. Bean lost a 12-round decision
to Moorer in March 1997 and conceded it wasn't much of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for him to make a move and he was waiting for me
to make a move,'' said Bean. ``So we were just standing there
taking pictures of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean's other glimmer of hope might be that he has Butch Lewis,
Michael and Leon Spinks's promoter, and Joe Frazier in his corner.
Alas, Frazier said he will not be lacing up his own gloves Saturday
night but Bean's.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield weighed in in his usual chiseled form, this time at
217 pounds. Bean, strangely, ballooned to 231 pounds, a whopping
(or Whopper) 19 pounds heavier than he was against Moorer and 8
pounds heavier than he has ever fought at.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too big,'' said Don Turner, Holyfield's wise trainer.
``That means he can't move.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus down here is that Bean's weight gain was caused by
a simple human reaction: ``He knows he can't win,'' said one
veteran observer, ``so he didn't even train.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield was set to fight Henry Akinwande June 6 at Madison
Square Garden, but the fight was canceled because (a) Akinwande was
weak from hepatitis B or (b) ticket sales were weak at the Garden
ticket wickets or (c) King was too busy in court bobbing and
weaving from the latest federal charges against him. Interestingly,
the ever thoughtful King has brought the 12 New York jurors who
cleared him down to Atlanta for Saturday night's 12-round
``Homecoming Party.'' Justice does sometimes pay.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is guaranteed $3.5 million by Showtime for Saturday
night's exercise and stands to make about $6 million with gate
sales _ that is, before King shaves off his share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
