<HEADER>
A3545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK19     09-18 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neagle joins Braves' 15-win club
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Denny Neagle reintroduced himself Thursday night. The
Braves pitching staff responded almost by impulse _ with another
shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta would need it too. The club had one hit reach the
outfield all night.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen drove in the lone run, which was plenty for Neagle
in his first start in two weeks as Atlanta dropped Arizona 1-0. The
shutout was the Braves' 19th of the season and second in three
days. Over their last 37 innings, Atlanta pitchers have given up
three runs (0.73 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a bunt and somehow got a run out of it,'' said manager
Bobby Cox. ``And that was about it. Not much else happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Except that the Braves continued to fatten up on a generous
portion of the schedule. With Neagle now 15-11 after two weeks down
with bursitis in his left shoulder, the Braves became the first
team in 68 years with five pitchers to reach 15 wins. The 1930
Washington Senators last turned the trick with Bump Hadley, General
Crowder, Lloyd Brown, Firpo Marberry and Sad Sam Jones going a
collective 76-44. The Braves five starters are 83-36.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got his 15th, I told (John) Smoltzie, I felt like we
were out on the golf course,'' said Neagle, who allowed four hits
in six innings. ``I had an eight-footer and you had a 15-footer and
you drained it and now the pressure is on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning for the seventh time in eight games, the Braves moved to
99-55, two games over idle Houston for the best record in the
league, while San Diego fell to four games back.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Atlanta beat up Diamondbacks starter Omar Daal. The
Braves' four hits included two bunts and an infield single. Their
only run came about when plate umpire Eric Gregg called a Tony
Graffanino bunt fair in the third when all replays showed it
suspiciously foul when Daal brushed it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a perfect game tonight,'' said Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
