<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS VIEWING GORE IN NEW LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD, CLINTON-BLACKS,
CLINTON-GINGRICH, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-DEFENSE, CLINTON-BOOK.) 
(JT) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Visits to New Hampshire have always been de
rigeur for presidential candidates, and Vice President Al Gore has
made his share. Friday, on his third trip to the state so far this
year, he visited a health-care seminar in Keene and a computer firm
here.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his previous tours through the host state of the
nation's first presidential primary, Gore had never before come
under such extraordinary circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   With leading Republicans, as well as some Democrats, clamoring
for President Clinton's impeachment or resignation over the scandal
involving a former White House intern, Gore appears to many New
Hampshire voters as a President-in-waiting _ even if it remains a
fanciful notion well ahead of events in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think people are paying more attention to him,''
said Dr. Alan Rogers, medical director at a hospital in Manchester
and one of about 200 people who heard Gore and New Hampshire's
governor, Jeanne Shaheen, discuss health-care issues at Keene State
College. ``Everybody assumes he will be the Democratic nominee
anyway. So, yeah, I'd say it has intensified a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mona Anderson, a therapist at the college agreed, saying: ``I
overheard someone misspeak, calling him `President Gore,' when he
meant Vice President Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Here at Teredyne, a company that makes computer modules, Strat
Smith, an operations manager, listened to Gore's 20-minute speech
on job creation and said of the scandal's possible effect on Gore:
``This brings things to the fore. He has to make his case sooner,
which is obviously what he did today.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part during the weeks leading the midterm elections in
November, Gore has steadfastly avoided saying anything that might
fuel such thinking. His oft-stated goal these tumultuous weeks has
been to support President Clinton, administration policies and
Democrats running for election this year.
</P>
<P>
   In speeches, he never mentions the scandal or deliberations in
Congress over impeachment hearings or calls for Clinton's
resignation or the smattering of protesters that have begun
appearing along the route of Gore's motorcade, as they did again
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of interviews with New Hampshire newspapers and a
television station, WMUR _ also de riguer for visiting politicians
_ Gore admitted for the first time that he had not read the report
to Congress by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, that
outlined charges against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel I'm thoroughly familiar with it based upon
briefings and news accounts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he felt most Americans could put the scandal ``in a
larger perspective,'' and predicted that Clinton would finish his
term ``with a distinguished record that will go down in history as
a virtuoso performance.''
</P>
<P>
   In none of the interviews did Gore reveal any personal feelings
about the president's predicament, noting that the president has
already apologized and said it was indefensible. Gore would say
only that Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, ``are good
friends'' and ``I feel badly for them and for their family.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, when Gore began a tour of the plant and a reporter shouted
a question about the House judiciary committee's vote along party
lines to release on Monday the tape of Clinton's grand jury
testimony, Gore said, ``If that's the case, it shouldn't be that
way. They should adopt a more bipartisan approach to this.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of Gore's listeners here and in Keene, frank
discussions about issues affecting the country provided welcome
relief from events roiling Washington. After the 90-minute
health-care discussion, Alan Green, a health-care administrator,
said, ``This is refreshing to me, putting the of scandal aside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
