A3547 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-EVANDER-COX     09-18 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Assured Holyfield awaits Bean
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It is not unusual that he would spend part of a day
watching two sons play football, even hours before defending his
heavyweight title. Evander Holyfield never has been one to
hibernate in a hotel room or lose himself in a three-deep entourage
or punch holes in walls, just in the name of prefight preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that doesn't stop anybody from wondering what in the
heck he is thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win, everybody will say, `Hey, you did a great job
promoting,' and winning would just put icing on the cake,'' said
Holyfield, who has been part promoter and part champion in the days
leading up to his IBF/WBA title defense against Vaughn Bean tonight
at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing ever comes my way that I can't handle. But in this
case, I know if I don't do well, people will say, `See, we know
what the problem is.' But there's no excuse for not doing well. I
train hard; I work hard. If I don't make mistakes, I can't lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's decision to watch his sons' football games is for
personal, not promotional reasons. But it is appropriate
punctuation for the past two weeks, during which the Fairburn
resident has spent as much time hawking tickets as sparring.
Holyfield hit nearly every stop on the Atlanta sports circuit:
Falcons, Braves, Georgia Tech football, Atlanta Motor Speedway. He
kicked off a United Way drive in Birmingham and spoke to several
youths at the World of Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   He staged two open workouts during lunchtime traffic at CNN
Center, threw a barbeque for media members and officials at his
mansion and gave ahandshake-and-photo op with corporate
ticket-buyers along with the usual blur of press interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through this before,'' Holyfield's attorney, Jim
Thomas, said, ``and look what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the rematch with Mike Tyson, Holyfield
launched a clothing line at an elaborate Las Vegas press
conference/stage production, complete with dancers and gospel
singers. No matter. Holyfield appeared well on his way to knocking
out Tyson for a second time when he won by disqualification in the
third round for Tyson's ear-biting.
</P>
<P>
   Before last November's heavyweight title unification against
Michael Moorer, fight-week activities in Las Vegas included a
fitness demonstration and pep talk for kids at a shopping mall, a
news conference with a group of high school journalists, an online
chat and, most memorably, a large religious crusade at a
minor-league baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Then Holyfield dropped Moorer five times en route to a win.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas reiterated his standard Holyfield defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's training, he sleeps 10 hours a day,'' Thomas said.
``If he trains two hours, he's got 12 hours to go. If he stretches
and does sprints, that still leaves 11 hours. What's he going to
do? He's not the kind of guy who's going to sit in his room and try
to get angry enough to beat somebody. It's wasted energy. So he
goes out and speaks to kids, tells them a story, gets energized and
comes home.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Don Turner said the activity would be reason for concern
for most boxers, but not Holyfield. ``This fighter knows how to
keep things in perspective,'' he said. ``Larry Holmes was another
one. So was Ray Leonard, and Marvin Hagler. They know what's
important. Evander is the most focused fighter I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said, ``People say, `What in the world is he doing out
talking to all the people?' But I realize limiting the things I do
limits who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The only difference here from the Tyson and Moorer fights is
that Holyfield has accepted greater responsibility for selling
tickets. This bout is Holyfield's first in Atlanta since 1991, when
the Omni was two-thirds full for a meeting with Bert Cooper, and it
probably will be his last here. The local business community
initially was cool to the fight, and the promotion to fill the
Georgia Dome's 42,000 available seats was harried.
</P>
<P>
   But Holyfield's visibility helped spark strong sales in the past
two weeks. More than 32,000 tickets had been sold as of Friday
afternoon _ more than doubling the 12,996 attendance for the Cooper
fight. Georgia Dome general manager Khalil Johnson said, ``We're
very excited. We're knocking on the door of a sellout. For us, this
is more than a knockout right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on appearances, there is little reason to believe that
tonight's main event won't end in a KO by Holyfield. Bean weighed
in at a puffy 231 pounds and doesn't possess much of a knockout
threat. Holyfield hasn't fought in 10 months but is a fit 217
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield also realizes that if he slips up against Bean, it
smothers his goal of unifying the three heavyweight belts with an
eventual fight against WBC champion Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   If Holyfield defeats Bean, he probably will make a rescheduled
WBA mandatory defense against Henry Akinwande in Las Vegas, New
York or South Africa, assuming Akinwande's blood test is free of
hepatitis B, then meet Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield smiled when he heard that Bean recently had predicted
a knockout win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's how the man feels,'' he said. ``But you know talk
don't mean nothing to me. How many (opponents) always say I'm gonna
lose?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
