<SLUG> BC-FBC-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vols look to snap Gator hex
 &HT;    By Leo Willingham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It doesn't get any bigger in the SEC than Florida
versus Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The second-ranked Gators and sixth-ranked Volunteers are the
winningest teams in the conference this decade and have combined to
win seven of the last eight SEC championships. The rivalry resumes
tonight at 8 in Knoxville, where two years ago an NCAA-record crowd
of 107,608 watched Florida win 35-29.
</P>
<P>
   No. 12 Georgia, awaiting the heart of its conference schedule
next month, plays a non-conference game against Wyoming at Sanford
Satdium (2 p.m.). The 2-0 Bulldogs have won seven straight
non-conference games, since an 11-7 loss to Southern Mississippi in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   After a week off, the Bulldogs will open October on the road
against seventh-ranked LSU, and then face Tennessee on Oct. 10 in
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has won 78 games this decade, but only two against
Florida. The Gators have won the last five games in the series,
including a 33-20 victory last year. This is the first conference
game for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really important for us to get over this hurdle
of Florida,'' Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer said. ``We're in the
same division, and all the consequences puts a special emphasis on
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, however, rebounded from its loss to Florida to win
the SEC East while the Gators lost to LSU and Georgia and missed
the title game for the first time in the event's six-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won our title. They have our ring,'' Florida linebacker
Johnny Rutledge said. ``Now we've got to go out and try to take it
from them.''
</P>
<P>
   In other games:
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 LSU (1-0) travels to Auburn (1-1) in a SEC West contest.
LSU opened the season last week with a 42-6 victory over Arkansas
State while Auburn defeated Mississippi 17-0 its SEC opener.
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Florida State (1-1) looks to rebound from last week's
24-7 loss at North Carolina State when it plays host to Duke (2-0).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
