<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN/FLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volunteers, Gators view game with own agendas
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Both teams are ranked in the Top 10, but No.
2 Florida and No. 6 Tennessee will be seeking very different things
tonight at Neyland Stadium (8 p.m., CBS).
</P>
<P>
   For Tennessee (1-0), which has had a week off since beating
Syracuse on Sept. 5, tonight's game is another attempt at
redemption. The Volunteers are the defending SEC champions but have
spent this week being constantly reminded that they have lost five
straight games to the Gators. Tennessee has won 50 games over the
past five seasons, but the failure to beat Florida in that span is
a demon the Volunteers _ and their fans _ desperately want to
exorcise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last senior class didn't beat them and this one is 0-3
against them,'' Tennessee wide receiver Jeremaine Copeland said.
``If we could just win once _ just to let them know that we beat
them _ that would be a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   An orange-clad crowd of more than107,000 fans will stuff Neyland
Stadium, hoping that what they've read about this group of
Volunteers turns out to be true. Tennessee, which has been known to
come into the game a bit tight, has appeared looser and more
relaxed this week. The Volunteers hope this approach will help them
reverse a significant trend over the past five games.
</P>
<P>
   They have turned the ball over 18 times in their last five
meetings with Florida. Those turnovers usually allowed the Gators
to jump on top early and shake Tennessee's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to play our game, keep cool, and keep moving the
chains,'' said sophomore running back Jamal Lewis, who figures to
play a prominent role in the Tennessee attack. ``We know we can
play with these guys if we don't make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida, 2-0 after lackluster wins over The Citadel and
Northeast Louisiana, is a team searching for an identity. The
Gators committed nine turnovers and a host of other miscues in the
first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Spurrier made no secret of the fact that the first
two games were little more than glorified scrimmages, and he used a
lot of young players. The tempo has picked up considerably this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to play a lot smarter, tighten up and take care
of the ball,'' said Spurrier, in his ninth season at Florida. ``If
we do those things we've got a chance to be pretty good this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier usually trots out something special in big games, and
the expectation is that junior quarterback Doug Johnson will play a
more prominent role.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, still recovering from shoulder surgery on May 8, did
not play against The Citadel and only a few snaps against Northeast
Louisiana. He is close to being 100 percent. Johnson threw for
three touchdowns in last year's 33-20 win over Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Jesse Palmer will start at quarterback, but Spurrier
has not ruled out a shuttle with Johnson, a plan that proved
effective in last year's 32-29 upset of No. 1 Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's possible,'' Spurrier said. ``Of course, that's been
possible all season.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner essentially gets a two-game lead on the other in the
race for the SEC East title.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't end the season or make the season for either
team,'' Spurrier said. ``Last season proved that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
