</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-ADVANCE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donnan: Wyoming best Dogs' foe yet
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It's the type of game that often makes college
football coaches cringe _ a non-conference contest against an
opponent with nothing to lose and everything to gain.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Southern Miss?
</P>
<P>
   You can be assured that Georgia coach Jim Donnan recalls that
debacle, an 11-7 loss to the Golden Eagles in his first game as
coach of the Bulldogs in 1996. That's what Donnan says he sees when
watching film of Wyoming, which 12th-ranked Georgia meets today at
2 p.m. in Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have to do is put the tape on for our players,'' Donnan
said. ``When we showed them the Kent tape (before the Sept. 5
opener), it was hard to convince our players because we definitely
had them outmanned. This team, we don't have them outmanned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a good football tradition out there. The normal
reaction would be, `Oh, well, we're playing Wyoming. Ho hum.' ...
But we're getting tested here. They're the best team we've played
(this year), no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming has more to gain than the $400,000 payday for the
1,500-mile trip south. The Cowboys still are searching for an
identity under second-year coach Dana Dimel after dropping four of
their final six games last season. Wyoming looked sloppy in a 17-9
win over Division I-AA Montana State in last week's opener.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia might have a hard time knowing exactly what it's
going up against. The Cowboys resemble little of the pass-happy
teams of former coach Joe Tiller, now at Purdue. Under Dimel, the
Pokes have gone to a more balanced offensive attack, along with a
blitz-heavy defense.
</P>
<P>
   Before the arrival of Dimel, a former offensive coordinator at
Kansas State, Wyoming had ranked among the top 20 teams in the
nation in passing nine of the last 12 seasons. It was just two
years ago that the Cowboys ranked No. 1 nationally in passing and
No. 3 in total offense. Against the Bobcats, though, Wyoming never
attempted to stretch the field with deep passes and relied on its
running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't show one thing that we're going to do against
Georgia,'' Dimel said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the offensive reputations of both programs, don't expect
a shootout. Wyoming's offensive numbers dropped off considerably
last season, when they averaged 24.8 points and 368.3 yards per
game. In their five losses, the Cowboys scored a combined 44
points. Both offenses struggled last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to score every time we had the ball. We just didn't
finish things off,'' Dimel said. ``I think that was an indication
of the rust we had. We didn't play a bowl game last year, and we
started a week later than most people. We had 10 months between
games, and the rust showed a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
