</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ONDECK19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On deck: Arizona Diamondbacks
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- When: Tonight at 10:05 p.m.; Sunday at 4:05.
</P>
<P>
   -- Where: Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   -- TV/radio: TBS, WSB (750 AM).
</P>
<P>
   -- Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, LHP Tom Glavine (19-6,
2.63; 2-0, 1.29 lifetime vs. Diamondacks) vs. LHP Brian Anderson
(12-12, 4.34; 0-0, 9.00 lifetime vs. Braves). Sunday, LHP Bruce
Chen (1-0, 5.79; first appearance vs. Diamondbacks) vs. RHP Amaury
Telemaco (6-9, 3.92; 1-1, 3.29 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   -- Quickly: If Tom Glavine is to win his second Cy Young award -
and his chances are three times stronger than they were a month ago
- his case must include a 20-win season, which he can accomplish
tonight. His second half has been remarkable. Take away a five-run
beating he took from San Francisco Aug. 19 and Glavine is 7-1 in
his last 12 starts with 17 runs allowed in 81 innings (1.89 ERA).
His season ERA of 2.63, fourth lowest in the NL, is his best since
the 2.55 he posted in his first Cy Young season of 1991. He ranks
third in the league in winning percentage (.760) and is ninth in
both innings pitched (215-1/3) and opponents batting average
(.240). In 14 innings against Arizona this year, he has allowed two
runs on nine hits while striking out 13. After a 1-6 start,
Anderson has turned his year around, ranking second on the D-backs
to Andy Benes in wins and innings (192-2/3). He leads the league in
two catagories, though he could dispense with one. His 1.1 walks
per nine innings is lowest in the NL but he has given up 37 homers
in 30 starts, which is tied with Colorado's Pedro Astacio for the
league lead. Arizona's first selction in the expansion draft,
Anderson faced the Braves April 24 in Atlanta and was ill-treated,
giving up 10 hits and four runs in just innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
