<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sept. 20, will move Saturday in the `a' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-REVIEW _ On Capitol Hill last week, the
Republican-controlled Congress began consideration of a tax cut,
renewed its efforts to limit some late-term abortions, started
wrapping up the spending bills needed to keep the federal
government operating and pushed ahead with an overhaul of the
bankruptcy system. Hobbled though he may be, President Clinton set
in motion an international effort to contain the financial crisis
that began last year in Asia, considered a plea from the Pentagon
for more money, received a report from his advisory commission on
race and directed that the government purchase only recycled paper.
By Richard W. Stevenson. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STRAUSS-SAGE-REVIEW _ Robert Strauss is a former ambassador and
trade representative, who has offered sage advice for former
presidents like Carter, Reagan and Bush. A close friend of Strauss,
Vin Weber, a former Republican congressman from Minnesota, doubts
that President Clinton will seek Strauss' advice in his sex scandal
case. By Francis X. Clines. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEARN-DISABLED-REVIEW _ Over the last decade, learning
disabilities have moved squarely to the foreground of the education
world: more than 5 percent of the nation's students now have
diagnosed learning disabilities. Hundreds of thousands of students
in elementary schools, colleges and graduate schools get special
accommodations like extra time on tests, quiet rooms to work in or
note-takers. By Tamar Lewin. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON-REVIEW _ The Japanese are well versed in the art of
fending off American accusations, including perpetual
hyperventilating over Japan's protectionist trade policies. But
nothing from the past could have prepared the Japanese for the
latest salvo by several prominent American economists. They say
that the Japanese government has been insufficiently reckless. By
running a tight monetary policy, wringing inflation out of the
economy now and for the foreseeable future, the government has
inadvertently contributed to a downward spiral of prices and
production that has cost the Japanese nearly a decade of growth. By
Michael M. Weinstein.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FERRARO-REVIEW _ Perhaps more than any other issue, the 14-year
gap since she had been in elective office _ or run for
vice-president, her claim to fame _ dogged Geraldine A. Ferraro in
her race for the democratic nomination to the United States Senate
from New York. She lost last week and declared her political career
closed, which makes this a good time to reflect on what went wrong.
By Amy Waldman. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEMOCRACY-REVIEW _ Although the world has focused its
attention on the one-sided battle between the Chinese Communist
government and the political dissidents who press for radical
change, there is also a large population of intellectuals, many of
them scholars or former officials, who work openly to nudge the
system in a more democratic direction. By Erik Eckholm. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-REVIEW _ Who's afraid of Afghanistan? Iran, it seems. The
Islamic Republic has positioned as many as 70,000 Revolutionary
Guards and volunteers on its border with Afghanistan. And perhaps
200,000 regular soldiers are on the way. The Taliban of Afghanistan
have only about 40,000 men under arms, so te primary threat to Iran
is not military. It is instead a threat that is deeply political,
and quite humiliating. Instead of showing Iran a little respect,
the four-year-old Sunni Muslim movement, which follows a rigid,
repressive version of Islamic law and now controls most of
Afghanistan, has nothing but contempt for its neighbor to the west.
By Elaine Sciolino. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-PLANS-REVIEW _ The 1985 invasion of Libya would now be
in the lesson plans of every high school history teacher in America
if it had actually taken place. Instead, the stillborn invasion is
a classic example of Washington's propensity to gin up contingency
plans for seemingly otherworldly operations that never get the
green light. Indeed, there is a permanent infrastructure in the
United States national security apparatus that does nothing but
plan for every conceivable crisis, often with little or no hope
that the plans will be taken seriously by senior policy-makers or
the president. By James Risen. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STARR-SPOOF-REVIEW _ A spoof on a supposed manuscript submitted
by Ken Starr for publication. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KING-BABE-REVIEW _ After a long silence, Babe Ruth has emerged
for a rare interview on ``Larry King Live.'' By Richard Sandomir. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
