<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-CREDIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP WARNS ABOUT CAMPUS CREDIT CARD OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a, l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of giving out free T-shirts, chocolates, or mugs to lure
new customers, banks peddling credit cards on campuses ought to be
handing out brochures about responsible debt, officials from a
consumer advocacy group said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group said its
national study of 1,260 undergraduates at 15 campuses found that
students who acquire credit cards from on-campus marketers are more
likely to carry larger balances and acquire more cards than those
who get them through other means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students, especially those who fill out credit card
applications at campus tables in return for trinkets and candy, run
the risk of falling into the campus credit card trap,'' said
Deirdre Cummings, consumer program director for MassPIRG, at a
press conference at the University of Massachusetts at Boston
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Calling for curbs on the use of gifts as enticements, Cummings
said banks zealously market to young adults in hopes of winning
lifetime loyalty through this first-time credit card. Yet college
students, many without jobs, often can't handle the debt.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, ``The Campus Credit Card Trap,''
students responsible for their own cards who obtained them through
an application made on campus had an average unpaid balance of
$1,039. This compares to $854 for those who obtained their cards by
applying another way.
</P>
<P>
   Those who applied on-campus also had an average of 2.6 cards,
compared with 2.1 cards for those who applied outside of school.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings said other studies that have painted a brighter picture
of students' ability to handle debt, such as one recently by the
Institute for Higher Education Policy, fail to distinguish between
students who rely on parents to pay the bills and those who are
responsible for their own cards.
</P>
<P>
   At UMass-Boston, a marketer for Associates National Bank of
Delaware stood inside a student building with free T-shirts,
calling cards, and a thesaurus for anyone who filled out the VISA
application. The card comes with a variable annual percentage rate,
which this month would be about 17.99.
</P>
<P>
   At the bank's headquarters in Irving, Texas, spokesman Joe
Stroop said the bank recruits students hoping they will become
long-term customers when their earning power grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not because we make a ton of money on students, because
we don't,'' he said. ``It's an investment in the future of the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   MassPIRG called on colleges to consider a ban on on-campus card
marketers, and to provide more education about debt. It also called
into question some banks' practice of paying colleges a fee based
on the number of applications completed, giving the schools an
incentive to encourage sign-ups.
</P>
<P>
   College policies vary. Northeastern University bars credit card
marketers from academic buildings and student centers, while Boston
University allows them at some student buildings in return for a
fixed fee, said school officials. UMass-Boston dean of students
Stephanie Janey said it is considering revisions to rules that
currently allow on-campus credit card marketers under a variety of
financial arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   At many colleges, marketers skirt rules by setting up shop on
public sidewalks near the school.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mara, 20, a UMass Boston student, said credit card marketers
are seductive. Wearing a Citibank T-shirt he was given this week
for applying for his third card, he acknowledged he already has two
cards with a total unpaid balance of $3,800. ``These giveaways of
T-shirts and gifts do influence students,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
