<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3565 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-235(2TAKES     09-18 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-235(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE POLITICIANS REACH TENTATIVE PACT ON ECONOMIC PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SHERYL WudUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Ending weeks of bitter deadlock, Japan's governing party
declared Friday night that it had reached agreement with the
political opposition on how to bolster the jittery financial system
and begin reviving the ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute deal appeared to be sketchy, however, glossing
over crucial questions, and it could fall apart. Still, the pact
will give Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi a chance to show off a rough
blueprint to President Clinton when they Tuesday in Tarrytown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have decided that, as the world's second-largest economy,
Japan should not become the source of a global financial
meltdown,'' Obuchi told reporters Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain a deal, however, Obuchi appears to have made
significant concessions, adopting key planks of the opposition,
which controls the upper house of Parliament and has blocked
movement in the legislation for weeks. These include sharply
scaling down the Finance Ministry's power to regulate the country's
financial system, and the ``temporary'' nationalization of the
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, one of the nation's largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi also appears to have agreed to abolish a $100 billion
pool of public funds set up to rescue banks. It is therefore not
clear how much money will be available to write-off the massive bad
debts held by Japanese banks.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the agreement were not available Friday night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The long tussle over the financial legislation reflected a
subtle political joust among the parties. The opposition wanted to
discredit the government and nibble away at its authority so that
general elections might be called _ not immediately, but next year
or so, when the opposition has built up its local organizations.
And Obuchi wanted to show that he can get things done and take
steps toward economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear who won, and it may not be clear for months. The
political consequences may simply depend on whether these measures
restore some vitality to the economy by next year and thus improve
the government's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Key opposition figures were exultant Friday night, declaring
that the government had submitted to their demands, raising the
prospect of difficult battles ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, U.S. officials said they could not assess the
plan because they do not expect to be fully briefed on it until
Monday. They appear particularly focused on whether the plan will
commit Japan to inject billions in public funds to improve the
capital base of banks after they are nationalized.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, who said he had not seen
the plan, said, ``I think we have a strong sense of urgency that
the Japanese government move as quickly as possible to stimulate
its economy, restore growth to deal with its banking problem, open
its markets, to deregulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Movement on the banking legislation has been viewed as crucial
because it would allow Japan to proceed with the task of grappling
with its frail banking system and mountain of bad debts. Only by
tackling those twin challenges, many economists say, can Japan
restore its economic vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has been criticized around the world for dithering in
dealing with its banks and its bad debts, which have been mounting
as the nation's recession deepens. Earlier this week, Standard &AMP;
Poor's said that Japan's bad debts could climb as high as 30
percent of the country's total economic output. The debt has been
an enormous drag on the entire economy for nearly eight years, and
has prevented Japan from acting as an engine of growth for both
Asia and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was released after the close of Tokyo's
long-battered stock market, which now stands at about where it was
12 years ago. Bond yields have plummeted, with the benchmark
10-year bond touching a new record low of 0.64 percent at one point
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The government has begun carrying out a giant fiscal stimulus
package, worth about $126 billion in real spending and loans, along
with big tax cuts. But it has also acknowledged that even with that
program, the economy is expected to contract by more than one
percent during this fiscal year.Some economists say the spending
package focuses too much on dubious public works and will be hard
to implement as swiftly as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials denied that the deal was cemented just so
that Obuchi would not go empty-handed when he meets President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan's policies are not formulated as gifts for the
president,'' said Koji Tsuruoka, a Foreign Ministry official. ``It
could become a turning point in promoting change and reform in the
banking system.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the ruling Liberal Democratic Party appears to have
achieved the deal mainly by acquiescing to the opposition, most of
the opposition parties seemed reasonably satisfied. They can claim
that their own proposal will become the basis for the new financial
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reached an agreement in principle with the government,''
said Naoto Kan, head of the Democratic Party, the main opposition
group, after he emerged from a meeting with Obuchi. ``Now it is
time to put it in place.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the government will have to rewrite its bill for
establishing ``bridge banks,'' the original centerpiece of its
financial legislation now before the Parliament. The idea was to
create a bridge bank to take on the bad debts of failed banks and
collect on those debts or sell them off at cut-rate prices. But the
government resisted using the scheme with the big, frail banks,
while the opposition demanded that a mechanism be designed to deal
with such institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to compromise quite a bit,'' said Yasuhisa Shiozaki, a
member of Parliament and one of the negotiators for the Liberal
Democrats. But he added that the deal was still ``broad'' and the
two sides ``have to work on it to clear up the details.''
</P>
<P>
   The new, rewritten bills are expected to pass the Parliament as
early as mid-October but there is some question over exactly how
firm the pact is. Still, Shiozaki and others said they did not
expect the agreement to fall apart. Still, the wording was vague
enough to allow multiple interpretations, enabling both sides to
claim that they are comfortable with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very broad framework, so the real negotiations will
come,'' said Motohisa Furukawa, a Parliament member for the
Democratic Party and one of the negotiators. He described the deal
as ``chameleon-like'' _ that is, it can be ``read sometimes in two
ways'' or more.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the government is expected to temporarily
nationalize the Long-Term Credit Bank, an ailing institution with
25 trillion yen, or $186 billion, in assets and a capital base so
weak that opposition groups have deemed it insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides still need to thrash out exactly how Long-Term
Credit will be taken over by the state and whether it will be
declared technically bankrupt. The Liberal Democrats have resisted
declaring such a large institution bankrupt, partly out of fear
that doing so would provoke financial instability.
</P>
<P>
   An official at the Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank,
ruled out the possibility of a default by Long-Term Credit if it is
put under state control, according to Japanese media, and he said
the Bank of Japan would provide loans, even without collateral, to
Long-Term Credit to prevent a credit squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   While many economists agree that the Liberal Democrats may have
a point in worrying about instability in the overall system, some
have criticized the emphasis that politicians have put on the
problems of Long-Term Credit, or LTCB, an institution originally
set up after World War II to provide long-term loans to help
finance economic rebuilding . They fear that once a solution to
that bank's crisis is reached, officials may feel that they have
finished their work and relax their resolve to overhaul the
financial system at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world will closely watch LTCB and shift its focus to the
next phase of banking consolidation and restructuring,'' said
Charles Dallara, managing director at the Institute of
International Finance. ``The issue is: Can they pull the entire
banking system through consolidation?''
</P>
<P>
   This issue has been at the heart of the controversy, ever since
the Liberal Democrats first proposed the financial bills during the
spring, in the form of the Total Plan. Even members within the
Liberal Democratic Party were somewhat divided on how to deal with
very large banks that were in danger of collapsing, and everyone
has been concerned about how to save the worthy borrowers of failed
institutions. Many Liberal Democrats members, though, agreed on a
``soft landing'' for the financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the party brokered a rescue merger between the ailing
Long-Term Credit and Sumitomo Trust &AMP; Banking Corp. But after a
stunning defeat of the Liberal Democrats in landmark elections this
summer, then-Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto was forced to resign
and the financial legislation was put in jeopardy. The opposition
groups seized the opportunity to challenge the governing party's
approach and offer a more radical path for stabilizing the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   With the new agreement Friday night, it is unclear what will
happen to those merger plans.
</P>
<P>
   One important question that Friday night's deal does not address
is whether the government will let other weak and insolvent banks
fail or go bankrupt, even if they are among the nation's biggest
ones.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the pact, the Liberal Democrats also agreed to scrap
a 13 trillion yen pool of government funds created in February to
boost capital in the banking system. In March, nearly 2 trillion
yen was used to buy stakes in the nation's largest 19 banks, on the
condition that they were still solvent.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling back that scheme is a humiliation for the Finance
Ministry and its minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, who was instrumental in
designing the government fund, part of an overall 30 trillion yen,
or $225 billion, plan to help bail out the banks. The remainder of
the money will still be used to support depositors.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the biggest concessions, the Liberal Democrats say
they have have agreed to strip the Finance Ministry of some of its
powers in determining financial policy and instead create an
independent panel to determine the fate of troubled financial
institutions. This change, if actually put into effect, could
transform the way financial institutions function in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   To separate out the financial policy-making powers from the
ministry, the politicians agreed to draft new legislation by the
next Parliamentary session in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition will help draw up a new mechanism to deal with
hobbled, weakly capitalized banks under the supervision of a
bankruptcy administrator.
</P>
<P>
   According to Japanese media, these banks will be able to apply
for state control or they may be given the option of conversion
into a bridge bank. The deal also calls for setting up a debt
collection entity, similar to the U.S. Resolution Trust Corp., and
this institution will purchase bad loans from failed banks until
the end of March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of public money to be set aside for the new scheme
has not been decided upon, though Japanese media reports have put
the figure at 10 trillion yen, or $75 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
