</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SALVAGE-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDITION OF CRASH WRECKAGE COMPLICATES WORK OF INVESTIGATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ All those who have seen it fumble with
words that seem inadequate to express the horror of the ocean floor
where the wreckage of Swissair Flight 111 came to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine or describe what's down there, because
it's unbelievable,'' said Petty Officer Josh Boisvert, one of the
Canadian divers who has descended the 180 feet to work at the crash
site five miles off the fishing village of Peggy's Cove.
</P>
<P>
   From the accounts of divers and from videotapes of the wreckage,
it is a hellish scene _ jagged hunks of metal that one Canadian
Navy officer said ``don't resemble an aircraft any more,'' with
cables squirming in the murky currents and shattered bits of human
remains tangled in the debris.
</P>
<P>
   Crews of helmeted divers from Canada and the United States,
wearing weighted boots and vests, have had to pick their way
carefully through the mess, watching for razor-edged shards that
could pierce their protective suits or sever the line to the
surface that allows them to breath a special mixture of helium and
oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Working with caution, respect and quiet efficiency during the 25
to 30 minutes they have on the bottom for each descent, they have
managed to recover most of the easily gathered human remains from
the ocean floor and have started venturing into the pulverized
pieces of the fuselage to find more remains. Altogether, 229
passengers and crew members died instantly when the McDonnell
Douglas jet, flying from Kennedy International Airport in New York
to Geneva, slammed into the North Atlantic two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   From sonar readings taken in the days shortly after the Sept. 2
crash, investigators at first believed that the jumbo jet broke
into several large pieces on impact. But the sonar proved
deceptive. One hunk detected by sonar was actually a big rock, and
the rest were not large pieces, but, said Dana Doiron, a spokesman
for the Transportation Safety Board of Canada, ``large piles of
small pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators now say the main area of debris measures just 200
feet long by 120 feet wide _ less than the dimensions of the MD-11
when it was whole. That suggests that the plane hit the water at a
tremendous rate of speed and at a sharp _ almost perpendicular _
angle. However, Vic Gerden, chief investigator for the
Transportation Safety Board of Canada, said it was too early to
know exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of the wreckage vastly complicates the work of
investigators who are trying to learn what caused the MD-11 to
suddenly plunge into the Atlantic. So far, only about 2 percent of
the wreckage has been brought up from the depths and reassembled,
and it is not at all clear that investigators will be able to bring
up all _ or even most _ of the debris.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials are proceeding cautiously with the recovery
and investigation, but in sharp contrast to the situation two years
ago when Trans World Airlines Flight 800 exploded off off Long
Island, N.Y., they are under no obvious pressure from on shore to
speed up their work.
</P>
<P>
   After the TWA crash, relatives of the victims clamored for
answers, demanding quick retrieval of bodies and recovery of all
the wreckage in hopes of learning what caused that air disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that urgency stemmed from the suspicion that the jet had
been the target of a bomb or missile, a theory that was eventually
discarded by the FBI, but only after every piece of the wreckage
had been examined for even minute traces of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   From almost the very beginning, investigators on the Swissair
crash have said they had no evidence to suggest that a criminal act
was involved. Rather, they know the cockpit filled with smoke
before the crash, and that both flight recorders quit working at
about the same time _ strong indications of a massive electrical
failure. But they do not know what caused the smoke or the
electrical failure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, although many grieving family members made the
sorrowful journey to Halifax and Peggy's Cove to bid farewell,
officials say they expressed no impatience over the course of the
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not once. Not at all,'' said Dr. John Butt, the Nova Scotia
chief medical examiner who has been working almost nonstop to try
to identify the remains of the victims. Only one body was recovered
intact, and Butt's team of pathologists, working out of a temporary
morgue set up inside a hangar at a nearby air base, have been able
to identify the remains of only 10 victims. ``One of the reasons
why there have been no angry phone calls,'' Butt said, ``is that
the situation is such that there are no easy answers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-SALVAGE-2NDTAKE     09-18 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SALVAGE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HALIFAX, Nova Scotia: easy answers.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Butt said he and his team have compiled a computer list of the
medical and personal characteristics of the passengers and crew and
try to find matches with information that comes from collected
remains.
</P>
<P>
   Everything from dental records to DNA and personal jewelry is
cataloged in the computer, Butt said, to make identification
easier.
</P>
<P>
   But the task is enormous and is complicated even further by the
dangerous conditions the divers face as they search through the
debris.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the scene underwater, Boisvert said that in the
central pile of twisted debris, the largest piece seems to be a
section of fuselage about 10 feet long and 5 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had jagged edges, like somebody peeled it off the
aircraft,'' he said. The light on his helmet also illuminated part
of an engine cowling, a wheel of the front landing gear that was
standing upright in the water and what appeared to be some part of
a wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much aircraft parts everywhere, what's left of
human remains is hard to identify sometimes because it almost looks
like cushions,'' Boisvert said.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after his first dive to the wreckage, Master Seaman
Paul Walsh of the Canadian Navy described the eerie sight of jumble
of debris, strangely livened by bright colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are life vests down there with Swissair on it,'' he said
by telephone from one of the Navy ships anchored over the debris
field about five miles off Peggy's Cove. ``You've got the orange
colors of the interior and the white of the airplane skin itself.
And then amongst that you have the flesh tones of human remains
mixed among it.''
</P>
<P>
   The jumble of metal gave evidence of the force of the impact,
but it was the personal items mixed in that most affected the
divers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a woman's purse, a travel purse, not a big one, that was
obviously full of personal effects, and that really put it home for
me,'' said Seaman Walsh, a native of Nova Scotia who remembers his
father, Mickey, also a a Navy diver, sitting alone in the family
kitchen after coming back from a recovery mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's in there, who that purse belonged to and the idea that
that person less than a week and a half ago was on their way home
or on the way from visiting somebody ...'' he paused. ``Everywhere
you look, you say this is definitely a place where people once were
happily on their way going somewhere, and then, kaboom.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point, a specially equipped U.S. salvage ship that
played a key role in the TWA crash investigation, the USS Grapple,
will be used to lift the larger pieces of wreckage to uncover more
remains and to bring parts of the jet to the surface to help
investigators determine what happened.
</P>
<P>
   But although the Grapple has been in place since Monday, said
Lt. John Oliviera of the U.S. Navy, its 300-ton capacity crane
won't be used extensively until the recovery of human remains is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priority of the Navy remains the recovery of human
remains,'' Oliviera said.
</P>
<P>
   There is concern now about deteriorating weather conditions as
winter nears, and about exposing the divers to unacceptable risk.
That issue was raised in the early days of the recovery by a group
of relatives of the victims. Commander Rick Town of HMCS Preserver,
the first Canadian ship to reach the crash site, said that when he
accidentally encountered a group of grieving relatives shortly
after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting there was a group of about 20 grieving relatives. They
quickly surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the people in the group came forward, clearly one of
the families who had suffered the loss of a loved on in this event.
You can see it in their eyes,'' Town said. ``She came up to me and
said, `We understand,' then very quickly she corrected herself and
said `We're trying to understand what it's like for you out there
trying to gather everything on our behalf.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Later,'' he continued, ``they communicated back to my boss and
told him that what they want in very clear and very unequivocal
terms is `Do not endanger yourself to recover the remains for us.'
So is that providing pressure on us? Well, we're human too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
