<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GINGRICH-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN COALITION IS OUTSPOKEN ON CLINTON SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD, CLINTON-BLACKS,
CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-DEFENSE, CLINTON-BOOK.) 
(lb) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the starkest display of contrasting Republican
approaches to capitalizing on the White House scandal, several
speakers at the Christian Coalition's convention here on Friday
expressed outrage at President Clinton while others said only that
he deserved their prayers.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening session of the group's annual meeting, Pat
Robertson, the coalition's founder and chairman, thundered to about
3,000 cheering religious conservatives: ``For nearly nine months we
have been mocked, demeaned, belittled and lied to.'' The applause
grew when he said the office once occupied ``by Washington and
Jefferson and Lincoln'' had become ``the playpen for the sexual
freedom of the poster child of the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, was only the beginning. ``I say to you today,''
he continued, ``we will be silent no longer.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as Robertson, the television evangelist, set the stage
for a weekend of red-meat appeals to the loyal, conservative
Republican base, subsequent speeches by the party's top two leaders
in Congress were decidedly tame.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich and Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican
leader, seemed to go out of their way to resist delivering
sure-fire applause lines. Instead of calling on the president to
resign, they called upon the audience to pray for him.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering offered the most telling display of how
Republicans are seeking to politically make the most of the
president's scandal. By attacking Clinton as immoral, Robertson and
several presidential hopefuls seized the opportunity to emphasize
their religious and conservative credentials to core Republicans
who are crucial in the party's primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Their invective _ Robertson and others said the president should
not resign but be impeached, so he could be punished _ was also
intended to send conservatives to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   But congressional leaders such as Gingrich, who behind the
scenes are orchestrating the effort toward impeaching the president
and are making sure the videotape of his grand jury testimony is
released, are publicly trying to appear above partisanship. The
scandal could backfire on Republicans, their advisers say, if they
appear to relish Clinton's travails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats run the risk of defending a president who has
got a kind of rich man's justice: The laws apply to everybody but
me,'' Randy Tate, the executive director of the Christian
Coalition. said in an interview. The Republicans ``run the risk of
looking like they're too anxious to go through with this.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who did not know better, Gingrich sounded like a
close friend of the president. ``I ask all of you as Americans to
include in your prayers the president,'' he told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than attack Clinton directly, Lott, of Mississippi,
referred to ``the White House attack dogs,'' whom he accused of
being the source for a magazine article this week that disclosed
that Rep. Henry Hyde, chairman of the Judiciary Committee, had an
affair three decades ago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several speakers denounced Clinton while trying not to appear
overtly partisan. Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the majority leader,
did not mention the president directly when he described a
conversation with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the sense that she was speaking for all the women in
America when she started the conversation with `Listen, buster, you
pull a stunt like that on me and you'll be lying in a pool of blood
hearing me ask, `How do I reload this thing?''' Armey said. Turning
to the audience, he added, ``What I'm afraid of is how many of you
guys are going to come out for gun control?''
</P>
<P>
   A comment by Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip,
prompted several listeners to hoot: ``Impeach! Impeach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This president shows such reckless behavior sitting in the
Oval Office _ and I'm being a little indelicate _ being serviced by
a 21-year-old intern while he's on the phone to the chairman of the
Foreign Operations Appropriations Committee, discussing sending
your sons and daughters to Bosnia,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle devoted most of his address to
abortion. Like many other speakers, he ridiculed Democrats for
failing on Friday _ for the second time in two years _ to overturn
Clinton's veto of a ban on a late-term abortion procedure. Senate
leaders delayed the vote so it would coincide with the coalition's
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   But Quayle, who weeks ago called for Clinton's resignation, did
not skip the subject entirely. ``The nation is finally coming to
grips with the consequences of what we have tolerated,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
