<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-GIPSON-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH JAMES H. GIPSON OF THE CLIPPER FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of Clipper Fund is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As stock indexes climbed to record highs during the first half
of the year, many managers of stock mutual funds were throwing most
every dollar they had into the market.
</P>
<P>
   Not James H. Gipson, founder and lead manager of the Clipper
Fund. By mid-July, he had a fat 44 percent of his portfolio in cash
and Treasury bonds, with the balance in just 17 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were not happy, said Gipson, recalling snippy letters
from shareholders. One, he remembered, said something like this:
``If I wanted my money in cash, I would have put it in the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   With the summer selloff in stocks, cash suddenly looked great,
and so did Clipper, which lost far less than the market over all.
And the fund now has a bundle of cash on hand for bargain-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you will find that we did an exceptionally good job of
capital preservation during a difficult period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. From July 17, when the market peaked, through Sept.
11, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slumped by 17.2 percent.
The average large-capitalization value fund lost 17.4 percent over
that period, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher. Gipson's fund, with $960.1 million in assets, lost just
7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in early 1984, Clipper has returned 17
percent annually, on average, just ahead of the S&AMP;P and
substantially better than the 13.5 percent of the average large-cap
value fund.
</P>
<P>
   Gipson founded Clipper's adviser, Pacific Financial Research of
Beverly Hills, Calif., in 1980, to manage institutional portfolios.
Last year, he and four minority partners sold Pacific Financial to
United Asset Management, ``in part for personal reasons but also
for the same reason that we've been selling stocks in the
portfolio,'' he said. ``We found the market was generously valued
and we decided to take some money off the table.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a contract to continue running the firm for seven years,
as do his co-managers, Michael C. Sandler and Bruce Veaco.
</P>
<P>
   Gipson buys a company's stock only when it is priced at least 30
percent below its so-called intrinsic value, the amount a company
is estimated to be worth to a private buyer, and typically sells
when it hits that value. For the last two years or so, the fund
found few stocks that met its standards, and its cash position
grew.
</P>
<P>
   Since the market correction began in July, however, the number
of stocks in Clipper has risen to 23, while cash has fallen to less
than 40 percent. ``We have shifted from being holders of sizable
cash to being patient buyers'' of stocks, Gipson said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the fund's concentration bothers him. Last week, Gipson
rolled out a more concentrated and equity-heavy version of the
fund, UAM Clipper Focus, which invests in the same stocks but holds
no more than 5 percent in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Clipper uses a variety of models in putting a price tag on
companies, a process that helps set Gipson apart from other value
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a large segment of value investors who use a simple
mechanical approach to determining value,'' he said, citing
price-to-earnings ratios, price-to-book ratios and high dividend
yield as examples. He said an advocate of such a strategy could be
considered ``a first-generation value investor, who uses the same
valuation approach for each kind of company.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls his team of seven analyst-managers ``second-generation
value investors,'' because they try to value each company in the
way a private buyer would in bidding for the company, tailoring the
analysis to the nature of the business.
</P>
<P>
   In valuing a media company, for example, relevant benchmarks may
be price to cash flow or price per subscriber, but not book value,
he said. ``On the other hand, book value does have a sizable
element of relevance if you're looking at a bank or an insurance
company or a security broker.''
</P>
<P>
   For giant companies like Coca-Cola or Philip Morris, it may be
more difficult to establish intrinsic value, so he relies heavily
on a model of discounted free cash flow.
</P>
<P>
   He takes his 10-year estimate of a company's free cash flow _
cash after capital and other expenditures _ and discounts it by the
return of a 30-year Treasury bond (now 5.14 percent) and then by a
``risk premium'' that varies with each company (say, 2 percent for
Coca-Cola, a company seen as having little risk, and 4 percent for
Philip Morris).
</P>
<P>
   Gipson then compares the company's intrinsic value with the
price of its stock. ``If we can buy the company at 70 percent or
less of its intrinsic value, then that company would become a good
candidate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make sure that you buy stocks with a margin of
safety,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gipson looks for opportunities company by company, with no
preference for any economic sector or industry. Currently, he said,
``we are finding some reasonable opportunities in specialty
chemical companies.'' But he declined to identify the stocks
because he was still buying them.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the fund has been heavily weighted in the
financial area because of large positions in the Federal National
Mortgage Association, known as Fannie Mae, and the Federal Home
Loan Mortgage Corp., or Freddie Mac, the government-sponsored
mortgage enterprises; each is about 9 percent of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are two very good companies who share a market niche that
is highly profitable and well protected from competition,'' Gipson
said. Fannie Mae closed at $63.375 on Friday; he estimates its
intrinsic value at $82. Freddie Mac trades at $47.125; he puts its
intrinsic value at $60.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest position in Clipper, nearly 12 percent of assets, is
Philip Morris. ``We had a smaller position going into the spring of
this year, when the concern about both litigation and legislation
reached a crescendo,'' he said. He bought more Philip Morris, in
the $36-to-$39 range, in mid-May. ``That was an example of being a
contrarian value investor, buying on bad news,'' he said. The stock
has climbed to $46.25, even as the market has fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime reason it's cheap is concern over litigation and
legislation'' on domestic tobacco, he said. ``But there's more to
Philip Morris than domestic tobacco. They have a very good food
business and a great international tobacco business.''
</P>
<P>
   Gipson estimates the company's intrinsic value at $70 a share,
but he is in no hurry to see it reach that point. ``We're quite
happy to sit and wait, with the 4 percent dividend yield,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And he is not afraid to venture abroad. In recent months,
Clipper added to a small position in De Beers Consolidated Mines,
the South African diamond giant.
</P>
<P>
   He recently paid between $12 and $15 for its American depository
receipts, which have fallen by nearly half from their April high on
concern about plummeting diamond sales in Asia. The ADRs trade at
$14.3125; Gipson puts the intrinsic value at $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
