<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIDS advance: New drug is effective, taken once a day
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The newest AIDS drug approved Friday by the Food and
Drug Administration will set new standards of effectiveness and
convenience in HIV/AIDS treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Sustiva is the first once-a-day HIV medication. In combination
with other anti-HIV drugs, Sustiva, or efavirenz, excels at
reducing the amount of virus in a person's body to undetectable
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Because so few HIV drugs have been approved _ only 13, with
Sustiva _ and because people with AIDS often must switch drugs as
they develop resistance, AIDS patients and their doctors have
anxiously awaited this drug, as they do every addition to their
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Sustiva belongs to a class of drugs called non-nucleoside
reverse transcriptase inhibitors but seems more effective than the
other two drugs in that category. It has the bonus of being
relatively easy to take _ just three capsules, once a day, with no
food restrictions and few side effects.
</P>
<P>
   A drug regimen of Sustiva and Combivir, a twice-daily pill
combining the popular HIV drugs AZT and 3TC, would involve a total
of only five pills, in two doses.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that to other AIDS therapies requiring dozens of pills
daily, some to be taken with every meal, others on an empty
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pills control what you do, how you live,'' said Nicholas
Teti, president of DuPont Pharmaceuticals, which developed Sustiva.
``Sustiva really reverses that. People can have their freedom
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The burden of cumbersome drug regimens is increasingly
problematic in HIV/AIDS treatment. Patients find it tough to adhere
to strict medication schedules, and just a few missed doses of
medication can allow HIV to mutate into a drug-resistant form.
</P>
<P>
   Sustiva answers this concern because the drug remains at
sufficiently high levels in the blood for 40 to 55 hours after
ingestion, said Dr. Laurent Fischer, DuPont's lead virologist.
</P>
<P>
   In clinical trials, drug regimens in combination with Sustiva
have been even more effective than combinations with Crixivan,
which belongs to an extremely potent class of anti-HIV drugs known
as protease inhibitors. Crixivan has been associated with
debilitating and bizarre side effects, such as the redistribution
of body fat to the midsection or back, that have forced many to
abandon the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Sustiva has been generally well tolerated. In some people it
causes dizziness and vivid dreams, but these effects usually
disappear after a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont will price Sustiva in the middle of the range of HIV
drugs; a year's worth will cost around $4,000. Because HIV drugs
usually are taken in combination, annual drug therapy averages
between $10,000 and $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
