<SLUG> BC-BASS-TOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New names catch on at FLW bass tourney
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOLINE, Ill. _ Denny Brauer showed that he was only human, but a
few of the other anglers still in contention in the Wal-Mart FLW
Tour World Bass Fishing Championships were sounding like men of
steel Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Brauer, from Camdenton, Mo., failed to qualify for today's final
round of the top five, ending his string of two straight wins on
the Bass Anglers Sportsman Society circuit and four victories since
the spring. Brauer caught only two fish weighing 4 pounds, 2
ounces, eighth among the 10 qualifying pros who fished the long
stretch of the Mississippi River border between Iowa and Illinois
Friday. All 10 competitors started from scratch, and no weights
will be carried over to today.
</P>
<P>
   Davy Hite of Prosperity, S.C., and Tommy Biffle of Wagoner,
Okla., sharing the same backwater area 50 miles to the north of
Moline, turned in two of the day's heaviest five-fish limits,
propelling both into the favorite's role to win the $250,000 top
prize. Hite caught a 11-12 limit, while Biffle had 11-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there's enough fish in there for both of us,''
Biffle said of the weed-filled shallow area he and Hite agreed to
divide. ``I'm predicting one of us is going to win it. . . . I
don't know what the other five are going to say about that.''
</P>
<P>
   George Cochran of Hot Springs, Ark., who was second to Brauer in
last month's BASS Masters Classic, had the biggest catch of the day
(11-15), using a quarter-ounce buzzbait early in the morning in
shallow water also well north of the launch area. ``Gentleman
George'' made his own polite prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine,'' he said of Biffle's comment. ``I'm confident in
my spot, too. If it's cloudy or rainy or sprinkling tomorrow
morning, I think I can win, too.'' A chance of rain was predicted
for today.
</P>
<P>
   Also advancing to today's final were Gary Klein of Weatherford,
Texas (9-12), and Jerry Williams of Conway, Ark. (9-1). Williams,
the lone angler to go south (he went almost 90 miles down river),
is the comeback story of the tournament. He was shut out the first
day, then took a 13-3 limit Thursday to qualify 10th for the third
round.
</P>
<P>
   In the non-boaters class, which finished up with the top 10
fishing Friday, Stone Mountain's Pat Fisher (two fish, 4-0)
finished second behind Todd Lee of Jasper, Ala. (five, 12-14), who
teamed with Biffle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
