<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bean worthy of our pity, not praise
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Perhaps if they had stayed the course with the
original nickname, we would have trembled at the approach of Vaughn
Bean. ``Vicious'' Vaughn Bean it was when he first broke into the
exciting, glamorous world of professional prizefighting.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it was forced. Didn't really go with such a gentle given
name, sort of like ``Rabid'' Richard Simmons or ``Malicious'' Mr.
Rogers. But at least it was an honest attempt at covering him in
menace.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, however, Vaughn ``Shake-N-Bake'' Bean climbs into the
ring against Evander Holyfield, his nom de fist suggesting a poor
substitute for real fried chicken.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy bringing his lightweight reputation and his
9-to-1 underdog status to Holyfield's home streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do get recognized when people see me walking around in my
turban,'' Bean said, referring to his bright red headwear, symbolic
of his Muslim faith. ``I was walking through Underground and a few
people were saying stuff like, `Holyfield's gonna kill you _ better
get out of town while you can.' I just shook their hands and went
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The setting) just doesn't matter. Everybody's entitled to
their opinion. I would fight Holyfield in any one of his
(mansion's) 32 rooms. I'm going for the gold at the end of the
rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean seems a well-meaning sort. It's not his desire to enter the
Georgia Dome as a walking punchline. In preparation for this night,
he has had some pointed observations.
</P>
<P>
   On his regrets over a low-impact, majority-decision loss to
Michael Moorer, Bean's only opponent of merit: ``Laying around
after that fight, all I could think about was, `If I had only done
a little more, I'd be champion. If I'd only done a little more.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the way to beat Holyfield: ``It's not about finding a
weakness. I have to beat him at every level. Whatever he's good at,
I've got to be better. I've got to be the total package. I've got
to train harder than he does. I've got to believe in God even more
than he does. Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make (Holyfield) change his mind,'' Bean's
trainer, Butch Lewis, said. ``Make him think, `I'm a warrior, but
do I really want to be doing this? This is something I wasn't
expecting. I was looking for Butterbean.''' If they really believe
the solution to Holyfield lies with breaking his will, they have no
idea. They are trying to blow a bank safe with a firecracker.
</P>
<P>
   We should really attempt to take Mr. Bean seriously, because
anyone who risks the ring deserves a portion of respect. Yet, any
informal Bean poll yields the same consensus _ the man is laughably
overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   Belief isn't easy to come by while scanning his 31-1 resume. I
keep re-reading the list of opponents, convinced there must be a
Harpo and a Zeppo in there somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he inspire confidence at Thursday's weigh-in, coming in
at an all-time high 231, with all the muscle definition of an
eggplant. No string-Bean here, he lost the pose-down to Holyfield
in a bloody, first-round knockout.
</P>
<P>
   If tonight somehow became a battle of seconds, then look out.
There in the challenger's corner are Joe Frazier and Michael
Spinks, men of fine standing in the fistic community. But all they
can do tonight is look, not touch.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that nice, young Bean against the world, a prospect
that seems to cause more pity than concern.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
