<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quayle to Clinton: Give it up, get out
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE , Ga. _ President Clinton no longer has the ``moral
authority'' to be president and should resign, former Vice
President Dan Quayle said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In what could easily become the theme in his probable bid for
the Oval Office in 2000, Quayle blasted Clinton for destroying the
credibility of the office.
</P>
<P>
   The former vice president, well known for his criticism of the
family values portrayed in television sitcoms, said Clinton's tryst
with White House intern Monica Lewinsky and the handling of the
scandal has ``stripped away any credibility, any moral authority
that he had to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle swung through Georgia raising money for Republican
gubernatorial candidate Guy Millner at a $1,000-per-couple private
fund-raiser in Gainesville and was to tout other Republican
candidates today. But after the prerequisite glowing words for his
partisans, the attention soon turned to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton ought to do what's best for our country, and that
is for him to step aside,'' Quayle said during an airport news
conference with Millner. ``He could end this today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Republican said ``it is likely'' he will seek the
presidency during the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle is the second potential Republican presidental contender
to endorse Millner's 1998 bid to be Georgia's governor. And he
won't be the last. Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, Sen. Fred
Thompson and publishing magnate Steve Forbes also are on tap in the
next six weeks to raise money for Millner and to build IOUs among
Georgia Republican leaders for their potential bids for the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush raked in more than $500,000 for
Millner at a fund-raiser last month.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle praised Millner as a candidate who shares his values.
``He will be absolutely tireless working for the people of this
great state,'' the former vice president said. ``He's a man of
vision, of good character and good values.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
