<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elliott family patriarch dead at 74
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ George Elliott, patriarch of the Elliott racing
family, died Friday morning at his home in Dawsonville. Cause of
death were complications after the removal of a brain tumor in May.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, 74, is survived by his wife, Joyce, and three children,
Ernie, Dan and Bill. George Elliott's first wife, Mildred, died in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Services for Elliott will be held Sunday at 2 p.m. at Bethel
United Methodist Church in Dawsonville, with burial at McKees's
Chapel United Methodist Cemetery in Dawsonville.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kinseth, a regular on the Busch Grand National circuit will
replace Bill Elliott in the No. 94 McDonald's Ford Taurus for
Sunday's MBNA 400.
</P>
<P>
   Grubb on pole
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Kevin Grubb won his first Busch Grand National pole
Friday qualifying with a BGN track-record speed of 153.498 mph for
today's MBNA 200. Winston Cup regular Bobby Labonte was
second-fastest, 153.055 mph. Atlanta's Buckshot Jones starts
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds to stay
</P>
<P>
   Larry McReynolds has decided to remain with Richard Childress
Racing after briefly considering running his own operation in 1999.
``All of our focus for the remainder of '98 and all of '99 will be
to put Mike Skinner and the Lowe's car in victory lane,''
McReynolds said. ``This decision was getting harder and harder, and
the deeper I got into this deal with the 31 team (Skinner), the
harder it was to think about not being part of this operation. I
want to see this team reach its full potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. for five
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr. reportedly will run five Winston Cup events
in 1999, sponsored by Budweiser. Budweiser and Dale Earnhardt Inc.
are expected to announce Monday a multiyear deal to sponsor
Earnhardt Jr. on the 2000 Winston Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly . . .
</P>
<P>
   Both Richard Petty and Bobby Allison won seven times at the
Monster Mile. . . . Darrell Waltrip, twice a winner at Dover,
hasn't visited the winner's circle anywhere in 187 races.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
