<HEADER>
A3594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-POLE-COX     09-18 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-POLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin sitting on pole _ just barely
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ If Mark Martin is to make a run on Jeff Gordon for
the Winston Cup championship, now could be the starting point. He
won his second pole of the year Friday, qualifying with a track
record speed of 155.966 mph for Sunday's MBNA 400 at Dover Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has little breathing room, however.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace (155.723), Derrike Cope (155.481), Kevin Lepage
(155.420) and Bobby Labonte (155.380) round out the top five. But
that man Gordon is sixth, 0.089 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car was perfect, I never had to change a thing,'' Martin
said of his lap. ``I felt like I got all that was there when I made
my lap, and that had to be good enough. It was lucky for us that it
wound up being on the pole. But, winning this race is really what
we're focused on.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Martin liked what he brought to the mile oval, Gordon was
hoping for more. The sun came out, changing the car and leaving him
with an ill-handling Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car has been driving great,'' Gordon said. ``We just
missed a little bit on what we should have done, based on the sun
coming out. This is the same car we ran at Darlington and I'm
pretty sure it's the same we ran here last time. If it's not, we'd
be crazy to bring something different, unless it gets better fuel
mileage.''
</P>
<P>
   What they may get come Sunday is a dose of Wallace, Cope, Lepage
and Labonte, sprinkled with some John Andretti, Jerry Nadeau and
Dick Trickle, as well as Dale Jarrett, who rounds out the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Each survived hair-raising seconds as the track changed with an
intensive sun beating down, creating loose race cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car made a great lap, but the sun came out about six cars
before me and we dropped in performance,'' Trickle said. ``The day
just got away from us a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It totally escaped some. Jeff Burton is 26th, a week after
winning at Richmond. Jeremy Mayfield is 27th, failing to qualify
for the third straight race. Dale Earnhardt is 41st and said,
``That stinks.'' And Dave Marcis, Wally Dallenbach, Rick Mast, Rick
Bickle and Hut Stricklin are 42nd, 43rd, 44th, 45th and 46th.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Buckshot Jones positioned himself nicely for a second
straight Dover start, qualifying 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
