<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EVIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL TO RELEASE EVIDENCE   IN IMPEACHMENT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warning of a new wave of shocking disclosures, the
Republican-controlled House Judiciary Committee voted Friday to
unseal the videotape and mounds of sexually graphic evidence in
President's Clinton potential impeachment inquiry on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, behind closed doors, followed a second day of furious
_ but fruitless _ protests from the Democratic minority and cleared
the way for images of Clinton's videotaped grand-jury testimony to
begin appearing on the airwaves at 9 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the committee is scheduled to release about
2,800 pages of material the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr,
used to develop 11 possible impeachable allegations against
Clinton. The package includes often crude grand-jury testimony by
former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky, and reams of other
potentially offensive documents.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among other items, according to congressinal sources,
are transcripts of some FBI interviews of Lewinsky, and documents
supporting Starr's allegation that Vernon E. Jordan Jr., a
Washington power broker and Clinton confidant, helped Lewinsky find
her ``dream'' job in New York as part of an effort to cover up
Clinton's illicit affair with her.
</P>
<P>
   Stirring concerns about the committee's ability to conduct a
judicious review of Starr's charges, many members bolted angrily
from the meeting, with Republicans assailing Democrats for acting
like ``criminal defense lawyers'' for Clinton, and Democrats
accusing some GOP members of abusing the president's due-process
rights in their zeal to drive him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from both parties said they expect the committee to
recommend a full impeachment investigation of Clinton to the House
by early October. They are reviewing Starr's allegations that
Clinton committed perjury, witness tampering, obstruction of
justice, and abuse of his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the committee has done is simply turn itself into a
transmission belt for attacks on the president and nothing else,''
said Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat and
senior member of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Henry J. Hyde, an Illinois Republican who is the
committee chairman, said, ``I don't think things are as dismal as
Barney portrayed them ... I would say the spirit of bipartisanship
is alive and flourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Others disagreed. ``This has the makings of a partisan
stampede,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman James Kennedy said: ``This appears
to be a rush to prejudgment and an effort to get out the most
salacious material at the speed of light, not at the proper pace of
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who advocated the material's speedy
release, defended the move in a speech to a group of political
conservatives. ``We won't rush to judgment, and we won't refrain
from judgment'' of the president, Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   The House Democratic leader, Representative Richard A. Gephardt
of Missouri, was unimpressed by the committee's action. ``It is a
truly sad beginning to this investigation,'' he said. ``It is
increasingly clear that the Republicans have absolutely no
intention of conducting this investigation under the bipartisan
principles that the Watergate investigation followed.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes dispute unfolded just a week after the panel
released Starr's original, 445-page report, revulsing many readers
with details of Clinton's illicit affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans generally fearful of a backlash for unleashing
a new barrage of offensive material and Democrats wary of appearing
overly defensive of Clinton's misdeeds, the committee battled
mostly over how much of Lewinsky's provocative grand-jury testimony
to release.
</P>
<P>
   A transcript of Lewinsky's grand-jury appearance contains
voluminous details about her alleged sex acts and sexually explicit
telephone conversations with Clinton. ``If people thought they got
the details in the Starr report, they haven't seen anything yet,''
said Representative Stephen E. Buyer, an Indiana Republican who
serves on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   After days of negotiations, the committee's majority and
minority staffs agreed to propose a list of about 120 sections of
the Lewinsky transcript and other documents to redact, or black
out. Committee aides said they chose material that could
unnecessarily infringe on the privacy of individuals, that was
considered critical to national security, or that was deemed
offensive and irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal touched off a torrent of procedural moves,
including several motions by Democrats to censor more than an
additional 20 references on similar grounds. Each motion was
defeated along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a general view among the Democrats not to reveal
anything, and there was a general view among Republicans to reveal
as much as possible,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's highest-ranking Democrat, Representative John
Conyers Jr. of Michigan, accused committee Republicans of
distributing the material to humiliate Clinton for political gain.
``It is sexually explicit, it is offensive, it is obscene,''
Conyers said. ``And I think it is a politicalization'' of the
process.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the committee voted to make public five sections of
material that both staffs had proposed keeping confidential.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the panel voted, 20-15, to approve a motion to
disclose three graphic passages involving Lewinsky's testimony
about sexual activity with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The motion, by Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican who
was among the first House members to call for Clinton's
impeachment, ignited a pitched confrontation. Only one Republican
joined every Democrat in voting against releasing the passages:
Representative W. Asa Hutchinson, a former US attorney for
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is bipartisanship,'' Frank said after the meeting,
``then the Taliban wins a medal for religious tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said he opposed Barr's motion because he ``did not
want to put anything more out, more graphic in detail, than what
was already in the public record.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the panel voted, 20-15, to approve a motion to
disclose three graphic passages involving Lewinsky's testimony
about sexual activity with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The motion, by Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican who
was among the first House members to call for Clinton's
impeachment, ignited a pitched confrontation. Only one Republican
joined every Democrat in voting against releasing the passages:
Representative W. Asa Hutchinson, a former US attorney for
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is bipartisanship,'' Frank said after the meeting,
``then the Taliban wins a medal for religious tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson said he opposed Barr's motion because he ``did not
want to put anything more out, more graphic in detail, than what
was already in the public record.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, a source said, Buyer proposed disclosing two
sections about sexually explicit telephone conversations between
Clinton and Lewinsky. The motion passed, 22-14, with support from
all the Republicans and one Democrat: Representative William D.
Delahunt of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Delahunt, who has strived to bridge the
committee's partisan gulf, said of the committee's action: ``This
is not about defending the president. This is not about
partisanship. This is about the integrity of the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   But Delahunt also said: ``This is not a process that can be
considered fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In another episode, Representative Bob Inglis, a South Carolina
Republican running for the Senate, sought to publish explanations
of two other redacted sections involving alleged sexual relations
between Clinton and Lewinsky. Inglis asked that the reason for the
redactions to state: ``description of oral-anal sexual contract
between the president and Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in a rare victory for the Democrats, the motion was
defeated, 29-5. Inglis was joined in supporting the measure only by
Republicans: Representatives Ed Bryant of Tennessee, Lindsey O.
Graham of South Carolina, Edward A. Pease of Indiana, James E.
Rogan of California, and Barr.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's GOP majority defeated numerous Democratic
motions aimed at delaying the material's release. One measure would
have required the committee to decide what constitutes an
impeachable offense before it released additional material. Another
would have permitted Clinton to review the documents first.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the committee's final actions, the panel agreed 28-7
to make public the votes it took. Five Republicans who initially
opposed publicizing the votes switched their votes after it
appeared likely to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican leaders came under fire for scheduling the
material's release on Monday, Rosh Hashanah, the Jewish new year.
``It is a time for celebration and reflection, not for dealing with
the videotaped testimony and the inevitable controversy it will
bring,'' said Representative Carolyn McCarthy, a New York Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   She urged House leaders to postpone the release until after the
religious holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
