<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DRUG-MASSACRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN RANCHER TORTURED BEFORE OTHERS WERE SLAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENSENADA, Mexico _ The 38-year-old rancher who was the target of
an apparent drug-related killing here on Thursday was tortured in
his own living room before gunmen put him against a wall and shot
him along with 18 relatives and neighbors, the authorities said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The federal attorney in Baja California state, Gen. Jose Luis
Chavez Garcia, said in a news conference Friday that the cattle
rancher, Fermin Castro, headed a small criminal organization that
specialized in guiding drug planes into desert airstrips and
unloading their cargo onto trucks for shipment across the border
into California.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said men carrying assault rifles and dressed in black,
the color of federal police uniforms, carried out the shootings,
but he said investigators had no idea who they were or what their
motive was.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying of men, women and children from three families in
this Pacific coast settlement 60 miles south of the U.S. border
before dawn on Thursday was the worst incident in the history of
drug-related violence in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Castro survived a gunshot wound in the head and is in a coma in
an Ensenada hospital, said Marco Antonio de la Fuente, the Baja
California attorney general, who appeared with Chavez at the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said a 12-year-old boy and a pregnant
15-year-old who survived the attack have been put under army
protection out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are questioning 10 people in Tecate, a city on the
California border, about Castro's activities and the attack on his
organization. The police seized several rifles and small arms in a
building they searched there.
</P>
<P>
   The weapons are of the same calibers as 80 shells retrieved at
the murder site, and the weapons are being tested for evidence they
may have been used in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez and de la Fuente sought to portray the statements they
had taken in Tecate and the weapons they had confiscated as
important advances, but it was unclear how quickly or methodically
the investigation was advancing. Both men denied reports, repeated
at the news conference by local journalists, about squabbling among
federal and state investigators, who are working together on the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Ensenada, a salty town on the rugged Pacific coast where tuna
boats harbor, attracts hundreds of thousands of American tourists
each year, and the Baja state governor, Hector Teran Teran, said he
feared the violence could harm the area's image.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the state and federal investigators appear to be
feeling pressure to produce quick results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
