<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LABOR-LEADER-650&AMP;A     09-18 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LABOR-LEADER-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR LEADER EXPELLED FOR PLUNDERING UNION'S COFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The long-time president of the local representing
22,000 school cafeteria aides and crossing guards in New York City
has been expelled from the union after an internal judicial panel
concluded that he illegally received $1.75 million from the union,
including $685,000 in fraudulent overtime expenses and $329,000 to
pay his family's credit card bills.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also found said that the official Charles Hughes, had
the union pay a total of $106,000 to 13 people in Georgia who did
not work for the union. Hughes has a luxurious second home in
Georgia, and union officials said many of these payments went to
his personal friends there.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, appointed by the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees, found that over the past two years Hughes
engaged in a vigorous effort to plunder his union's coffers.
</P>
<P>
   The parent union has long refused to release the ruling, which
was issued on June 26. But a union official upset about extensive
corruption at District Council 37, the umbrella group representing
120,000 New York City workers, including Hughes' members, made the
decision available to a reporter this week.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Schmukler, a lawyer for Hughes, criticized the panel's
work, saying the investigation was one-sided. ``All they did was
have some accountant introduce documents that I have no reason to
believe my client was personally acquainted with,'' Schmukler
added. ``The findings are not based on cross-examination.''
</P>
<P>
   But the panel noted that Hughes and his lawyer were present
throughout the hearing and that no evidence was offered to refute
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Several labor experts said the panel's findings documented what
appeared to be one of the worst cases of union embezzlement in
years. It involves a man who was long one of New York's most
visible and powerful union leaders _ someone whom many politicians
courted because of his local's campaign contributions and its phone
banks, which could make thousands of calls an hour on behalf of
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hughes was one of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's closest
labor allies. He appeared in a campaign commercial for Giuliani, he
sponsored a fund-raiser for the mayor at his home, and the two
leaders often hug each other when they meet.
</P>
<P>
   District Council 37 officials said Manhattan District Attorney
Robert Morgenthau, was investigating Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Upset that Hughes' local was $8 million in debt, the
international union put his local into trusteeship last February,
effectively ousting him. Hughes, who ran the local for nearly three
decades, resigned from the union in June, hoping to forestall the
expulsion ruling on the ground that the union no longer had
jurisdiction over him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hughes had decided that he had enough and he retired,''
Schmukler said. ``It was before this decision. There really was no
point.''
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the judicial panel harshly criticized Hughes for
claiming 1,820 hours of overtime _ an average of 35 hours a week _
in 1997 alone. Thus, he was owed more than $300,000 for overtime,
for which he was paid time-and-a-half. His base salary was
$224,000, while most of his local's members earned less than
$15,000 a year from their school jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes also claimed that he had worked 1,820 hours of overtime
in 1993, 1994, 1995 and 1996 and deserved hundreds of thousands of
dollars for those years as well. All told, Hughes received $685,000
for the overtime requests at a time his local and District Council
37, which includes 56 union locals, were facing a deep deficit and
were seeking a 30 percent dues increase from members.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the overtime payments an ``improper and illegal use of
union funds,'' the panel wrote that it ``finds it inherently
impossible that Charlie Hughes, or anyone else for that matter,
worked 35 hours of overtime every week of the year for five years
(or 260 consecutive weeks).''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to the panel, $310,000 of the $329,000 in credit card
payments made by the union went to pay for Hughes' American Express
Gold Card account. ``Most of the charges incurred on the Gold Card
were incurred by his wife, daughter and son,'' the panel wrote.
``The overwhelming majority of the purchases charged to these
accounts were for obviously personal items, such as clothing and
jewelry, with repeated purchases at such retail stores as
Victoria's Secret, Nordstrom, Macy's and Saks Fifth Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel said that Charles Jurgonis, the auditing director for
the international union, found that Hughes received $196,086.24 in
additional cash and checks from the union, although Jurgonis could
find no documentation justifying the payments.
</P>
<P>
   Panel officials also said Hughes wrongly received $512,000 in
retroactive allowances for executive board meetings he attended
from 1991 to 1997. Hughes had requested $979,047.97 for such
allowances, plus interest, saying that in 1971 his local offered
him a $1,000 monthly stipend that he never took.
</P>
<P>
   The panel did not find the request for these payments credible,
asserting that it was unlikely the local's executive board would
have voted Hughes a $1,000 monthly stipend for attending meetings
back in 1971 when his salary was $245 a week.
</P>
<P>
   The panel found that the executive board of Hughes' local had
not approved the overtime payments or many other payments, but it
noted that Robert Myers, treasurer of District Council 37, which
handled much of the local's finances, paid Hughes nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Many union members have faulted Myers and Stanley Hill, the
district council's executive director, for neither stopping nor
sufficiently questioning the payments to Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is outrageous,'' Tom Dawes, a leader of Committee for
Real Change in DC 37, a group seeking financial reforms in the
union. ``It shows the union has no way of holding local presidents
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hill said, ``We cannot comment on this case. It's in the
district attorney's hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
