<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD     09-18 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-MOOD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: ACRIMONY WINS BATTLE AGAINST CIVILITY ON HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to correct slug)  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Mass., Texas, Wis.)   (See also: CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-BLACKS, CLINTON-GINGRICH,
CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-DAY, CLINTON-DEFENSE, CLINTON-BOOK.)  
(js) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much for the dignity attendant to the solemn process of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   This will surely be remembered as a week when the last shred of
civility in Washington's political culture was torn away, and the
day when Republicans found ``bipartisanship'' in party-line votes
and Democrats called them the intolerant equivalent fo
Afghanistan's Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any bipartisan agreement left about Washington, it
was in disgust for this atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Texas, George W. Bush, told the Austin
American-Statesman that the scandal is depressing him and has left
him wondering whether he wants to seek the presidency after all.
``The process in Washington is a sullied process,'' Bush said in an
interview with the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, a veteran who
served in the House during the Watergate impeachment proceedings,
called the atmosphere in Washington ``sick,'' and said that he,
too, was deeply depressed and distressed. ``You have politicians
using the Ten Commandments as spears to skewer each other,'' he
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The overriding issue was the insistence by House Republicans on
prompt publication of President Clinton's testimony to Kenneth
Starr's grand jury _ a torrent of still more salacious and
embarrassing material which they calculate will damage him further
_ even if it risks a backlash against them.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had barely begun to absorb the shock of Starr's lurid
report before new wrangling over releasing the videotape of the
president's testimony inflamed already raw feelings in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Wednesday, another body blow came with the publication
of an article about Rep. Henry J. Hyde's extramarital affair 30
years ago. The article was published in Salon, an online magazine,
which conceded, in a statement explaining why it published a story
that several other publications declined to pursue, that it was
``fighting fire with fire, descending to the gutter tactics of
those we deplore.''
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, Republicans were trying to exploit the sympathy
generated for Hyde, R-Ill., by accusing the White House, with no
evidence at all, of stimulating the story, something several White
House officials, as well as the magazine, strenuously denied.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's tableau, after the House Judiciary Committee met,
showed that partisan acrimony has firmly taken hold. After two days
of rancorous debate over the videotape and 2,800 more pages of
damaging evidence, Republicans prevailed in forcing the release of
the materials.
</P>
<P>
   Going to the microphones outside the committee room to decry the
move, which came in a party-line vote, Rep. Barney Frank of
Massachusetts drew a metaphor that revealed the intensity of the
ill will that pervaded the deliberations. ``If this is
bipartisanship,'' the feisty Democratic liberal said, ``then the
Taliban wins a medal for religious tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, when Hyde, the panel's chairman, attempted to explain the
rationale for the committee's decision, saying he didn't think the
divisions between Republicans and Democrats were so bitter, Frank
stepped back up to the microphone, interrupted Hyde, and lambasted
the Republicans all over again for trying to embarrass the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the emerging bipartisan agreement on the gutter level of
political discourse in Washington these days, it still seems to get
worse with each passing day. But there is a simple explanation, and
one that suggests the end may be in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The November congressional elections are looming and the
shrillest voices in both parties are trying to motivate their voter
base, no matter that the name-calling and salacious subject matter
turns off many other voters in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are Republicans, including Senate Judiciary
Chairman Orrin Hatch of Utah, who have expressed deep concern over
the effect the sordid Lewinsky imbroglio is having on public life,
others see partisan advantage to pushing the scandal to the limit
and further damaging Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show that the public wants Washington to
put the scandal behind it, and even Republican voters expressed
reluctance about releasing the tape of the president's grand jury
testimony, though conservative Republicans favored the release. But
in an off-year election when a low turnout is expected,
congressional Republicans are dependent on these conservative
voters and are thus following their instincts about how hard to
push president Clinton to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising that House Speaker Newt Gingrich of
Georgia, who earlier this month said he would leave the impeachment
process to the judicious Hyde, reversed course this week and
strongly urged his Republican colleagues, in a closed-door meeting,
to vote to release a second wave of more damaging evidence compiled
by Starr. Indeed, Republicans had hoped to resolve the issue
earlier in the week, in time for the Sunday public affairs
television shows.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats like Frank are also looking to November, hoping that
the hard-line Republican rhetoric and Starr's tough tactics will
create a backlash. When Rep. Maxine Waters of California, another
liberal Democratic member of the Judiciary Committee, complained to
news media that the president was being ``railroaded,'' she was
attempting to galvanize an African-American constituency whose
turnout is central to Democratic hopes of escaping an electoral
rout in November and whose support could be one of Clinton's last
lines of defense.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Even within the wings of the two parties, there have been some
jarring contradictions. Rep. Christopher Cox, a California
conservative, took to the airwaves this week to urge the public
release of Starr's case, despite the salaciousness of the
materials. Three years ago, Cox was one of the champions of
Republican legislation to ban indecent material from the Internet.
In a speech on the House floor, he expressed worries about having
his two children find ``offensive material.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington's elders, who have a stake in preserving a culture
where politicians spar by day and dine together by night, expressed
worries that in a media age, such niceties were all but impossible
to preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawyer Leonard Garment, who lived through Watergate
inside the Nixon White House, said the current debate seems more
bitter and hyperbolic because of the ``immense competitive
pressures of this media age. Explanations cannot be given,
distinctions cannot be drawn. We're in the middle of this huge,
emotionally agitating culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Mankiewicz, a veteran of the Robert Kennedy and George
McGovern presidential campaigns, said in an interview: ``I've never
known it to be so bilious or so rancorous. It's as if all the oil
had drained out of the machinery and metal is rubbing on metal
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Another veteran of the Watergate era, former Senate Majority
Leader Robert Dole, who was a Republican of Kansas, expressed hope
that Washington would find its moorings once again. He was
scheduled to meet privately Friday with Clinton, who defeated Dole
for the presidency in 1996, to discuss turmoil in
Bosnia-Herzegovina and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through one of these,'' Dole said in an interview.
``It gets testy and nasty and partisan. And then, hopefully, the
Congress will come together in some bipartisan way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
