<HEADER>
A3622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOSTERCARE-FIASCO-ART     09-18 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTERCARE-FIASCO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TUG-OF-WAR OVER TODDLER, A CRY OF POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It sounds like a typical child welfare dispute: The
foster parents who have reared a 2{-year-old boy almost since birth
want to adopt him. The boy's mother, who lost him because of
addiction but has since stopped using drugs, wants him back.
</P>
<P>
   But when the foster parents are a powerful city alderman and a
prominent judge, accusations of political favoritism are bound to
bubble up. And because the couple are white and the child is black,
the case has also brought a small petition drive and a protest
vigil led by a black minister outside the alderman's office.
</P>
<P>
   The state's effort to terminate the birth mother's parental
rights, which goes to court next month, has already seen its share
of legal skirmishing. With the mother's lawyers arguing that she
could not get a fair hearing in Cook County because both foster
parents held positions of influence here, the state Supreme Court
responded by assigning the case to a judge from another county.
</P>
<P>
   State officials deny any political favoritism and say they are
acting in the best interests of the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``The handling of this case is consistent with the direction
that child welfare systems across the nation are moving in,'' said
Maudlyne Iherjirika, a spokeswoman for the Illinois Department of
Children and Family Services. ``Children cannot be allowed to
linger in foster care while parents are given chance after chance
after chance to get their acts together.''
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in February 1996, when Alderman Edward Burke,
who has been on the City Council for nearly 30 years and is
chairman of its Finance Committee, and his wife, Anne, an Illinois
appellate judge, took in an 8-day-old foster child, whom officials
call Baby T.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother, Tina Olison, 36, had a long pattern of
cocaine, marijuana and PCP use, and her son was born with drugs in
his system. Two other sons had previously been removed from her
care, the first in 1989 after she had disciplined him by putting
two five-pound sacks of sugar on his arms and so pinning him on his
back, the second in 1994 because of her drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those children were placed in foster care with Ms.
Olison's mother, Cecile, who decided not to take Baby T, thinking
that if Ms. Olison was separated from him, she would have incentive
to stop using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic apparently worked. Ms. Olison spent 18 months in drug
rehabilitation programs, and state drug tests, administered to
monitor her progress toward becoming a fit mother, have turned up
no trace of drugs since. She also went to school, became a
certified nursing assistant and now works for an agency that cares
for elderly patients.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olison, who is single, and her lawyer, Anita
Rivkin-Carothers, say her turnaround entitles her to get her son
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I overcame my drug addiction,'' Ms. Olison said in an
interview. ``I have my own apartment. I don't depend on any state
income. I'm a member of a church. I'm reliable and responsible now,
and I'm ready to be a mother to my child.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially the Department of Children and Family Services
intended to reunite Baby T with his mother. But in August 1997, the
agency changed its mind and recommended that the boy be placed for
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say their decision was based on an evaluation of
Ms. Olison by an outside agency, which concluded that ``serious
deficits remain in terms of her ability to safely and adequately
carry the primary responsibilities of parenting.'' The agency said
Ms. Olison had reacted angrily to the evaluators, and Donald
Jonker, a lawyer for the child services department, said the
``report has concluded that the mother's volatile and potentially
dangerous anger would be directed at her children.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olison said she had accused the evaluators of ``being
racist,'' of ``being a part of the conspiracy to keep me away from
my child'' and of ``being bribed by the Burkes.'' She spoke that
way to the evaluators, she said, because she believed that they had
already made up their minds and she was upset at the prospect of
losing her child.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Olison and her supporters say they believe the real reason
for the department's change of heart is that about a month before
the evaluation, the Burkes began expressing interest in adopting
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Burke, reached at home, said that neither she nor her
husband could discuss the case because it was in litigation and
involved issues of confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``What matters here,'' she said, ``is a little boy's life.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the Burkes, both 54, have been dutiful, loving
foster parents, caring for Baby T in the Tudor house on a leafy
street on the Southwest Side of Chicago where they reared four of
their own children, now grown, and briefly cared for another foster
child.
</P>
<P>
   And at a time when Illinois and other states are trying hard to
find permanent homes for foster children, the Burkes, a wealthy,
well-educated couple willing to take a child born with medical
problems, seem to some like a rare find.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ms. Olison says her boy has been well cared for, although
she says that Judge Burke does ``certain things that I wouldn't
do'' and that the judge is unsure of certain ``cultural things,''
like how to care for his hair.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Ms. Olison says, she is being denied a chance to
rear her son, because, she maintains, the state has been unfairly
swayed by the Burkes' credentials.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her job on the bench, which entails ruling on
appeals filed in Cook County, Judge Burke was appointed Gov. Jim
Edgar's special counsel on child welfare in 1994, working for a
year for the Department of Children and Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
