<HEADER>
A3624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOSTERCARE-FIASCO-ART     09-18 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTERCARE-FIASCO-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CHICAGO: Family Services.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her husband, a lawyer and former police officer, has been a
Democratic alderman in the 14th Ward since 1969, occupying a seat
once held by his father. He is a savvy political insider who sits
on the Cook County Democratic committee that selects judicial
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Ms. Olison's supporters say they would consider Burke's
adoption of the child particularly upsetting because he represents
a ward with few African-Americans and was known as a vigorous
opponent of Chicago's first black mayor, Harold Washington. (Burke
has always said that his opposition to Mayor Washington was
motivated not by race but by politics.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Their family has a pattern of not being sensitive to the
African-American community,'' said the Rev. Albert Sampson, a South
Side minister who fasted for 40 days this summer and led a small
protest outside the alderman's office, pushing an empty baby
carriage. Sampson accused the Burkes of trying to ``steal the
child, his legacy and identity, and allow the child to live in one
of the most segregated wards in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enough Irish Catholic children for Burke to adopt
his own,'' Sampson said.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream black political leaders here have not jumped into the
fray. And under state and federal law, race cannot be a factor in
the placement of a foster child.
</P>
<P>
   Cook County Public Guardian Patrick Murphy, who represents the
interests of Baby T, said that although the Burkes might never have
asked for special treatment, he believed that their prominence had
led the state to bend in their favor. The outspoken Murphy has
tangled with state officials before but initially recommended that
Baby T be adopted. Then one of his office's own psychiatric
evaluators concluded that Ms. Olison was a fit mother, and Murphy
has said he now plans to change his stance and support her.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, who is white, said he believed that Ms. Olison's backers
were making a mistake in raising racial issues. But he also said:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that the mom has done everything the agency asked
of her. It's also clear that DCFS has treated this mother
differently from other mothers and that it's clearly for political
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Children and Family Services has tried
unsuccessfully to have Murphy removed from the case, saying he has
undermined his credibility by flip-flopping.
</P>
<P>
   As for his charge of politics, Ms. Iherjirika, the department's
spokeswoman, said they had played no role.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing sinister here,'' she said. ``We gave this
mother a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
