<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DROUGHT-COX     09-18 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DROUGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rains bring relief, but drought's effects remain
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The lawn in front of the Experimental Science
Building at the University of Texas is once again green. Ervin
Lemuel put his gasoline-powered trimmer to work on it Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All summer we were just cuttin' dirt,'' said Lemuel, a
groundskeeper for the university. ``Now it's growing pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs are everywhere: Weeks of on-and-off rains have eased
the drought in Central Texas. Aquifers are rising, creeks are
flowing, and long-dormant lawns are growing. Some officials say the
drought is over in this region, but others caution that it is too
early to make that statement.
</P>
<P>
   There is no debate, however, that severe water shortages remain
in portions of the state, especially in the Lower Rio Grande
Valley, the High Plains and far West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Recent rains spawned by Tropical Storm Frances have brought
considerable relief to Central Texas, East Texas and the Gulf
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is a case in point. Precipitation this month stood at
6.57 inches Friday morning, compared with 1.75 inches at that point
in a normal September, according to the National Weather Service.
Austin has received 20.81 inches of rain this year, compared with
22.65 inches so far in a normal year.
</P>
<P>
   The city's voluntary conservation program, which calls for lawn
watering every five days based on a household's address, runs
through the end of the month. But the urgency has passed as a
result of the rains and a decline in usage to about 110 million
gallons a day this week, said Tony Gregg, the city's
water-conservation chief. Officials get concerned when daily usage
approaches 200 million gallons _ not because of a shortage in the
Colorado River but because of limitations in the system of pumps
and pipes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now, we're in good shape,'' Gregg said. ``We're not
concerned at this point about what day people water on.'' At the
suggestion of city officials, the American-Statesman on Friday
discontinued its watering reminders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the drought is certainly over in Central and South
Central Texas even though we remain a couple of inches below normal
precipitation for the year,'' said John Patton, a hydrologist with
the weather service. Day after day of scattered storms across the
region, with localized accumulations of a half-inch to 6 inches,
``is exactly what the doctor ordered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Texas Water Development Board, the state's
water-planning agency, gave a more cautious assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's safe to say that here in Central Texas we have
returned to near-normal conditions,'' said Bill Hoffman, assistant
director of water resources planning for the board. ``If we
continue with normal rainfall in the future, we basically will have
come through the drought. However, we're still at a point where, if
we were not to get normal rainfall, we may slip back to drought
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barton Springs-Edwards Aquifer Conservation District, which
oversees groundwater supplies for about 45,000 people south and
west of Austin, also stopped short of declaring an end to the
drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in a drought-stage alert, but things are probably
changing with the rains we've had,'' said Nico Hauwert, senior
hydrogeologist for the district. ``On Monday we'll have more
information on how much aquifer levels came up when we check five
monitoring wells.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, which relies on the southern segment of the Edwards
Aquifer, is poised to lift its drought alert. The water level in
the main monitoring well stood at 664.3 feet above sea level
Friday, nicely above the 655-foot drought trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some really good rains, and the aquifer levels have
continued to rise,'' said John Boggess, a spokesman for the San
Antonio Water System. ``Plus, things have cooled off
significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   A problem of definition It's not surprising that experts differ
on whether the drought is over. There is no standard method of
making such a determination. Nor, for that matter, is there a
single, all-purpose way to measure a drought.
</P>
<P>
   The term has scores of definitions, according to the National
Drought Mitigation Center, part of the University of Nebraska at
Lincoln. In simple terms, a drought is a prolonged shortage of
rain. But drought can be measured not only by precipitation but
also by stream flow, spring flow, aquifer levels, farm-pond levels,
temperature, soil moisture, reservoir levels and a combination of
these and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of drought, the Palmer index, shows near-normal
conditions in much of Central and South Texas and a mild drought in
the Valley. The former is true, but the latter is misleading
because, while rain has fallen in the Valley, the upstream
reservoirs are still low, said the development board's Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   Combined U.S. and Mexico water storage in Falcon and Amistad
reservoirs on the Rio Grande is about 29 percent of capacity. That
is up from the 17.5 percent before the August and September rains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley is still in a major hydrological drought,'' Hoffman
said.
</P>
<P>
   For farmers throughout the state, the rains have come too late
to save this year's crops, said Kathleen Phillips, spokeswoman for
Texas A&AMP;M University's agricultural program.
</P>
<P>
   Crop, livestock and other agricultural losses total $2.1 billion
and will cost the state's economy as a whole $5.8 billion, said
Roland Smith, a Texas Agricultural Extension Service economist.
</P>
<P>
   A new report by the Texas Forest Service estimates an additional
loss of $342 million in East Texas timber production from dead pine
seedlings and trees that grew at half their normal rate.
</P>
<P>
   When the losses to processors, haulers, distributors and related
businesses are considered, this works out to a $1.1 billion loss
for the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects have brightened for farmers intending to plant wheat
or hay in coming weeks and months. Leonard Germer, who farms 1,500
acres north of Maxwell in Caldwell County, lost his corn, sorghum
and cotton crops this summer. He's hoping to plant winter wheat in
mid-October. But now he's concerned that his fields might be too
soggy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't put machines in the fields if it's too wet,'' he
said. ``They just choke up and won't work in the mud. If we get
delayed we might have to switch to spring wheat, which we would
plant anytime from December 15th to the first of February.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
