<HEADER>
A3640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PHONY-INSPECTOR-54     09-18 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHONY-INSPECTOR-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONY INSPECTOR COLLECTS RESTAURANTS' `FINES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All-points bulletin to restaurateurs: Beware the
portly, middle-aged fellow in the greenish suit who flashes a
silver badge and photo, identifies himself as an inspector from the
City Health Department and asks to be paid _ on the spot _ for
kitchen violations.
</P>
<P>
   The man is armed: with an official-looking briefcase. And if he
isn't so dangerous, he certainly is persistent: So far he has pried
as much as $15,000 from some 60 restaurants in four boroughs (he
hasn't hit Staten Island yet).
</P>
<P>
   And he is on the loose: The Department of Investigation on
Friday identified the sham inspector as Nathaniel O'Neill, 56, a
veteran of impersonation who has been jailed nine times, including
twice in the past for impersonating a health inspector.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill is accused of three felonies involving forgery and
falsification, punishable by up to seven years in prison, and two
misdemeanors involving criminal impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   The bogus inspector is hardly a fantasizing Walter Mitty, or a
Great Impostor fulfilling long-held dreams of becoming a city
bureaucrat. ``He's in it for the money,'' Edward Kuriansky, the
city's investigation commissioner, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Zagat, publisher of the Zagat restaurant and hotel surveys,
called the deception ``a very smart scam, because a lot of people
in the restaurant industry expect the worst of inspectors, given
the history.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagat referred to the March 1988 undercover investigation that
led initially to charges against 28 health inspectors. They were
accused of extorting hundreds of thousands of dollars from 300
restaurants by threatening to close them or cite them for sanitary
violations. Eventually, nearly 40 inspectors were convicted in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are an awful lot of little restaurant guys out
there who are vulnerable to this kind of approach,'' Zagat said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill is believed to have impersonated a health inspector more
than 50 different times over the last five years, imposing
``fines'' as high as $500. ``Generally he targets restaurants whose
owners may have a limited understanding of English,'' said
Kuriansky.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said the Department of Investigation released
the photograph of O'Neill ``because the defendant has become
increasingly brazen and is striking with greater frequency.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuriansky said that O'Neill had a convincing manner and a
knowledge of Health Department procedures, but had never been an
inspector. At times, the masquerader may have been more akin to the
bumbling Inspector Clouseau of Peter Sellers than some Great
Impostor. Sixty restaurants were known to have been visited by the
impostor, and at 20 of them, people became suspicious and declined
to pay him, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, many restaurateurs were taken in. ``The phony
inspector got $200 from us,'' said Nino Catuogno, the owner of
Bricco Ristorante, the Southern Italian trattoria at 304 West 56th
St. in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in a month ago, checked our inspection records, and
said I had to pay a fine of $200,'' Catuogno said. ``He said that
cash would go through the court more quickly, so I gave him the
money but insisted on a receipt. It's not losing the money so much
that bothers me _ it was that I was taken for a ride.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jennifer Mahabir, who was working behind the counter at the New
Kebab House at 183 Church St. in Manhattan on Friday, said that the
impostor ``is big and fat and looks like he eats a lot,'' recalling
his visit to the restaurant a week ago. ``He said our permit had
expired, and the fine was $250. My boss gave him money and he gave
us a receipt.''
</P>
<P>
   Under no circumstances ``should a member of the public ever give
money to a Department of Health employee outside of a Department of
Health facility,'' said Neal Cohen, the city's health commissioner.
``No Department of Health inspector is authorized to collect money
in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department currently has 90 restaurant inspectors,
called public health sanitarians, who visit the city's 18,000
restaurants. Kuriansky said that the impostor was not asking for
bribes, but rather was cleverly pretending to be carrying out
inspection procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Kuriansky said O'Neill has 13 prior convictions going back to
1962, and has been jailed nine times ``for con scams, larceny and
burglary,'' he said. O'Neill was last released from prison in
August 1997, and has bilked some 15 to 16 restaurants since then.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the authorities released a photograph of O'Neill, but
many restaurateurs already have mug shots posted in their
establishments. ``They have photos of the restaurant critics inside
the kitchen door, on the way out,'' said Zagat. ``Now they'll have
photos of a crook there as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
