<HEADER>
A3646 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-COMMUNE-ART-950     09-18 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COMMUNE-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VILLAGE OF SMALL, FAMILY FARMS MARKS OWN GREAT LEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
(js) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAOGANG, China _ Shooing away clouds of giant dragonflies,
surrounded by lush fields of rice and platoons of clacking ducks,
it is hard to imagine the parched and decrepit conditions of this
little village 20 years ago that forced many of its residents to
become itinerant beggars.
</P>
<P>
   As a few middle-aged villagers tell their practiced story, it is
even harder to imagine that these same people once fearfully defied
Communist Party policy, secretly dividing up the communal farm that
Mao had imposed with disastrous results.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1978, starving and desperate, the 20 families in this
village of Anhui Province in eastern China took matters into their
own hands, risking the wrath of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, as the country learned of the remarkable
gains in Xiaogang and a few other pioneering places, the hated
communal farms broke apart all over China _ the single greatest
step toward the country's vibrant, market-oriented economy of the
1990s. This village in the middle of nowhere earned an important
footnote in the history of the new, post-Mao China.
</P>
<P>
   Historians often focus on leadership struggles in Beijing to
explain such momentous shifts in policy. But the insistent demand
for change from the bottom also played what scholars say is an
often overlooked role in smashing the communes. And similar
grass-roots pressures could, some think, be a driving force of
future convulsions in Chinese politics or economics.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring the family farm, and the wider decontrol of rural
business that followed, ``radically changed the face of China,
altering the relationship between central and local authorities and
perhaps providing China's best single hope of making the transition
to a post-Communist world,'' said Joseph Fewsmith, a China scholar
at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Situated on a fertile plain between the Yangtze and Huai Rivers,
Xiaogang should never have reached the nadir it did.
</P>
<P>
   The disasters began soon after the forced collectivization of
farming here and then the introduction of communes during the Great
Leap Forward of 1958-60. Many Xiaogang residents starved to death
in the catastrophic national famine that resulted from the
disruption of agriculture under the Great Leap Forward.
</P>
<P>
   The bitterness among the area's farmers never dissipated, and
productivity declined. In the decade up to 1978, the village
required large subsidies of grain from the government, recalled Yan
Junchang, 57, who was leader of the communal village ``production
team'' in 1978. Travelers described homes with no doors, with
chairs and tables made only of mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm of the farmers was frustrated,'' was how Yan
described the corrosive effects of communal work in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Local party officials selected Yan along with Yan Hongchang, 48,
who was deputy production leader in 1978, and Yan Jinchang, 55,
another one of the original rebels, to meet a foreign reporter in
Xiaogang, with Yan Junchang, the former team leader, apparently
designated to do the talking. As in many Chinese villages, many
residents are from the same clan and share the same family name.
</P>
<P>
   ``As team leader, no matter how hard I rang the bell or blew the
whistle, I couldn't get anyone to go into the fields,'' Yan
Junchang said. Much of the available land was not even tilled.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, family members would spend months away in towns,
begging for food and coins. Then in 1978 a severe drought made
conditions unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   At an emotional meeting at the end of that year, the family
heads drew up an oath, signed with thumbprints. The parceling of
land to individual households would be kept secret, they agreed. If
any among them were imprisoned, the rest would raise their children
to the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   The change was immediate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people even got up before dawn to go work in the
fields,'' Yan said. The amount of land planted to grain nearly
doubled in one year, and the village began producing a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring villages learned of Xiaogang's move and sought to
emulate it, but angry commune officials tried to squelch the
rebellion, at one point in late 1979 cutting Xiaogang off from its
subsidies of seeds, fertilizers and pesticides, Yan said.
</P>
<P>
   But soon after, the county party secretary visited and called
this a worthy experiment. Then the Communist Party leader of Anhui
Province, Wan Li, visited Xiaogang and gave his blessing _ a bold
decision at a time when the top farm officials in Beijing were
still promoting communal farming, true to the memory of Mao, who
died in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   In that first year, the village produced a large grain surplus,
according to the official history, and output continued to rise. In
1980, as similar wildcat breakups of communes occurred around the
country, Deng Xiaoping _ who was consolidating power as the
national leader _ openly endorsed the change for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1984, the communes had disappeared nationwide,
Zhang Guangyou, a former aide to Wan Li, said in an interview. Wan
himself, a largely unsung hero of China's economic reforms, quickly
moved on to high office in Beijing and is now a retired party
elder.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars like Fewsmith warn against romanticizing the role of
Xiaogang and other villages that defied national policy. Such broad
national changes, he said, resulted from an interaction among
grass-roots pressures, the work of sympathetic local officials and,
at the top in Beijing, the drive of Deng and other reformers to
oust hard-line Maoists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Xiaogang is a legitimate symbol of independent farmer
action,'' said Dali Yang, a Chinese-born political scientist at the
University of Chicago and author of ``Calamity and Reform in
China'' (Stanford University Press, 1996).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even today, 70 percent of Chinese live in the countryside: the
breakup of the communes altered more lives than any subsequent
event. It also, scholars say, was the inspiration for Deng's
much-vaunted urban economic reform in 1985, which allowed the
spread of private enterprise and, in recent years, spectacular
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Injecting market forces into the factories and cities was
easier, Yang observed, because three-fourths of the population
already lived in a virtual market economy, producing not only ample
food but also sought-after consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
   With ``market socialism'' China's new dogma, Xiaogang's onetime
rebels are now heroes of the post-Mao revolution. Today, Xiaogang
has a colorful archway at its entrance and a paved strip of road
down the middle, the better to greet the occasional official
visitor. Many are expected this fall and winter to celebrate the
20th anniversary of that legendary secret oath.
</P>
<P>
   Its borders expanded, the village now is home to 312 people in
75 families. If they are not nearly as prosperous as those in more
advantageous locales, many farmers here have small tractors and
have branched out into production of ducks and pigs and
watermelons, and many homes sport refrigerators and washing
machines.
</P>
<P>
   These days Yan, the onetime production team leader, is careful
with his words. ``What we did was still under the socialist system,
but the pattern was just changed,'' he repeats.
</P>
<P>
   Both Yan and Yan Hongchang, the younger, former deputy team
leader, are now officials in a nearby larger town.The older Yan
said he became a party member in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``The superiority of the Communist Party led me to join,'' he
said, looking over the green fields.
</P>
<P>
   His 27-year-old son is the party secretary of Xiaogang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
