<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3652 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JOKES-COX     09-18 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JOKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President sitting duck, even if not lame one
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Hey, heard the one about the president and the
intern?
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. If you haven't already, you will.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's troubles are no laughing matter _ except of
course for those in the business of mocking the high and mighty
when they seem to be down and out.
</P>
<P>
   The White House scandal has provided a plethora of punchlines
for TV comedians, joke writers and political satirists lured to the
story by an irresistible mix of power, sex and a news media gone
mad.
</P>
<P>
   No big news story in recent memory _ including the O.J. Simpson
murder trial _ has yielded as many zingers as the Clinton-Monica
Lewinsky saga.
</P>
<P>
   And there appears to be no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are either in hog heaven or hog hell on this one,'' said
Madeline Smithberg, supervising producer for Comedy Central's
newsmagazine spoof ``The Daily Show,'' which includes a segment
called ``Countdown to Impeachment '98.'' ``We have so much fodder
that it's beyond anyone's wildest dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Late-night wiseguys David Letterman, Jay Leno and Conan O'Brien
are frequently breaking tradition by devoting their entire opening
monologues to the president's sexual misadventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has three possibilities to consider'' Letterman joked
earlier this week on CBS' ``Late Show.'' ``One, (Clinton) could be
impeached; two he could be censured; three he could be neutered.''
</P>
<P>
   So just how many jokes and one-liners have been told on TV since
the Clinton scandal first broke? Dan Amundson of the Center for
Media &AMP; Public Affairs in Washington has been keeping count.
</P>
<P>
   From Jan. 1 through Sept. 10, there were 1,401 Clinton sex
scandal jokes told on ``Late Show,'' NBC's ``Tonight Show with Jay
Leno,'' NBC's ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien'' and ABC's
``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those, 1,306 involved Clinton, 226 were about Lewinsky and 99
lampooned Kenneth Starr. Also getting jabbed: Paula Jones (66),
Hillary Rodham Clinton (65), Linda Tripp (62), Al Gore (57) and
Janet Reno (34).
</P>
<P>
   The jokes have continued unabated since the Starr Report became
public, and have also become more pointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the jokes are getting bolder because there's so much
more material in the news that's making it harder to define what's
risque,'' Amundson said. ``I don't even think the O.J. jokes were
as blunt as this; they were more elliptical. There is really
nothing to compare this to.''
</P>
<P>
   But while comedians are carpet-bombing just about everyone
anyone associated with the scandal, Chelsea Clinton has been the
only no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't talk about Chelsea in the monologue,'' said Scott
Carter, the executive producer for ABC's ``Politically Incorrect.''
``We do make a distinction about what's fair game and what we won't
touch. She's still a child, not an adult and this is not of her
making.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the story has been a bonanza for television's court
jesters, some are starting to worry the story is growing tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was really exciting and the jokes were writing
themselves,'' said Jeff Stilson, head writer for HBO's ``The Chris
Rock Show.'' ``But after a while you want to write the jokes
yourself. You can't ignore it, but we don't want the show to become
'The Clinton Sex Scandal Show.' And trust me, if we're getting
weary of it, audiences are getting weary of it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Amundson is concerned about another potential effect on the
public.
</P>
<P>
   While skewering politicians is an American tradition dating back
generations, he said he fears the proliferation of jokes on TV
might trivialize the legitimate constitutional issues at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of this is just the way we blow off steam and
we're celebrating the fact that we can do it with such impunity,''
Amundson said. ``But I also think it has done a lot to inoculate
the public, and a majority of people are not shocked by any of
this. It makes the discourse more frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said ``Chris Rock's'' Stillson. ``Jokes are just
jokes,'' he said. ``And we're just comedians.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
