<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TAPES19-COX     09-18 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TAPES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tape, evidence will go public
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans decided Friday to make public President
Clinton's videotaped grand jury testimony and a raft of sexually
explicit material about his adulterous affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of the House Judiciary Committee, which broke along
party lines, means Clinton's four hours' testimony Aug. 17 in the
White House Map Room will be broadcast nationwide as soon as Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Release of the videotape will be accompanied by transcripts of
Clinton's testimony as well as Lewinsky's appearances before the
grand jury convened by independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Some
2,600 pages of documents are expected to lay out in graphic detail
the sexual encounters Starr first described in the report to the
House released last week.
</P>
<P>
   The debate Friday focused not so much on the release of
Clinton's testimony as on what to release from the evidence backing
up Starr's report. In that report, Starr alleged that the president
committed perjury in his testimony about his sexual relationship
with Lewinsky and then obstructed justice in trying to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats fought hard to keep the more lurid details out of the
public domain, arguing that Starr's 445-page report released last
week has already delivered ``enough smut'' to American families via
the Internet, where the report was released and the media. But
Republicans argued that all of the evidence should be made public
if the impeachment process is going to be a fair one.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all of the details in the 2,600 pages of material
will be made public save for 117 exempted passages that members
deleted on the grounds of sexual explicitness, national security or
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   And Georgia Republican Bob Barr is largely responsible for
making public three key passages that were intended to be kept
under seal. Barr won support from most of the committee's
Republicans to include how Clinton used a cigar as a sex prop with
Lewinsky, saying the public needs to know specific evidence of the
president's sexual encounters if it is going to weigh whether he
perjured himself in denying the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes extremely relevant,'' Barr said. ``We're forced to
do this by the president's own words.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Lewinsky's testimony to the grand jury, Monday's
release is also expected to include descriptions of phone sex that
the president and Lewinksy had, explicit details about how the
president undressed her during their sexual encounters and
Lewinsky's description of how the president sexually aroused her.
</P>
<P>
   The White House quickly hammered the committee for releasing
such explicit detail. ``This appears to be a rush to prejudgment
and an effort to get the most salacious material at the speed of
light, not at the proper pace of justice,'' said James Kennedy, a
spokesman for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Following the committee's vote, there was a rush to a gaggle of
microphones awaiting members outside the Judiciary Committee
chambers and there was little attempt to hide the cantankerous
debate that took place inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accomplished a lot,'' said a weary Chairman Henry Hyde,
(R-Ill.). ``We had vigorous, spirited debate, but it was civil. I
would say that the spirit of bipartisanship is alive and
flourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to him, Massachusetts Democrat Barney Frank
quipped that the chairman seemed to hold a ``new concept of
unilateral bipartisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde telephoned Speaker Newt Gingrich earlier in the week and
offered to step down from the investigation after the online
magazine Salon reported that he had had an extramarital affair 30
years ago. Gingrich, however, gave Hyde his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a sign of the depth of Henry Hyde's integrity that he
would offer a resignation for a 30-year-old affair,'' Gingrich
press spokesperson Christina Martin said. ``The speaker did not
entertain the offer because he could think of no person who had
earned more respect or affection than Henry Hyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, members stuck to their party lines. Rep.
Lamar Smith, (R-Texas), defended the decision to release the
evidence, but he said the discussion inside the room would make
``you want to wash your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a good faith effort was made to redact the most
salacious matter, with one or two exceptions,'' Smith said. ``These
exceptions were necessary because they were directly relevant to
allegations in the Starr report.''
</P>
<P>
   That was hardly the view taken by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got rolled,'' said Michigan Democrat John Conyers, the
ranking member of the Judiciary panel. Conyers said that it was
unnecessary to release the details of the cigar episode and other
information in 27 passages that Republicans refused to exclude from
the material.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-page record of votes on various amendments and motions
made it clear that Republicans attempted wherever possible to make
sexual episodes public, yet they refused to make Thursday and
Friday's committee debates open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is sexually explicit, it is offensive, it is obscene,''
said Conyers, attacking the Republicans for allegedly politicizing
the process. Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, (D-Mo.), agreed,
saying the decision was ``a truly sad a beginning to the
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Releasing the material and the video tapes of Clinton's
testimony is akin to pouring ``gasoline on a burning fire,'' said
Sheila Jackson Lee, (D-Texas), questioning how in ``this climate of
hysteria the committee could proceed with fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath all the partisan rhetoric, is a sense that the committee
is paralyzed by partisanship. California Democrat Zoe Lofgren
contrasted the current atmosphere on Capitol Hill with the
bipartisan consensus forged during the Watergate hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a comparison to be made and it's certainly not
favorable to this Congress,'' said Lofgren, who served as a
low-level aide to a member of the Watergate judiciary committee.
``What are we doing here when salacious material is rushed out into
the public arena, but discussion of the Constitution is hidden?''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say that the Democrats are merely trying to turn
this into a partisan fight in order to deflect attention from the
allegations against the president presented in the Starr report.
Arguing that the Democrats used the same strategy during the
campaign fundraising investigations, Barr said it was important not
to let the partisan rancor interfere with the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a step in the direction to resolve these matters today
(by voting to make the materials public) and despite these sort of
shenanigans, we were able to move forward,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   The next step will be for the committee to decide whether to
move forward on an inquiry of impeachment. That would be in the
form of a resolution and could be taken up by the House at any
time.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say that the scope of that inquiry could be expanded
outside the Lewinsky matter and include the campaign fundraising
questions raised by the House Government Reform and Oversight
Committee. The chairman of that committee, Indiana Republican Dan
Burton, said on Thursday that he would refer examples of abusing
executive privilege to the Judiciary Committee for review.
</P>
<P>
   But the first test will be the public's reaction on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Bureau reporter Christi Harlan contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
