<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE PLEASED WITH NEW KINGS DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just 24 hours after saying he didn't know if he'd
be playing in a day, a week or two months, Kings captain Rob Blake
sat before a media gathering Friday afternoon elated that the first
of those possibilities had come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said I wanted to stay here in Los Angeles,''
Blake, 28, said after signing a three-year contract worth $15.8
million. ``But with a contract this size, it takes some time (to
negotiate). Fortunately, it took only five days (of training camp)
and I can get back to business.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who earned $3.15 million last season when he won the
Norris Trophy as the NHL's top defenseman, now will be paid $5.267
million a season, the highest salary for an NHL defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also confirmed the signing of enforcer Matt Johnson to
a three-year deal believed to be worth a total of $2.175 million _
$650,000 this year, $725,000 next year and $800,000 in 2000-01.
Johnson earned $400,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get back as soon as possible and they made it
clear they wanted me back,'' said Johnson, 22, who has four goals,
11 points and 550 penalty minutes in 148 NHL games. ``I didn't know
it would happen this fast, but I was assuming it would be within a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   With Blake and Johnson under contract, both practiced Friday,
but neither is expected to play in weekend exhibition games in Las
Vegas against Colorado. The only unsigned Kings are goalie Jamie
Storr and defenseman Aki Berg, who has returned to his native
Finland.
</P>
<P>
   On finalizing Blake's deal, general manager Dave Taylor said:
``It gives us the opportunity to move forward. Last year, we gained
a lot of respect around the league. With Rob being the captain of
the team, we felt it was important to have him around for the
entire preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   One term of Blake's contract is that he will buy a luxury suite
(at a cost of $217,500 a year) when the Kings move into their new
arena, the Staples Center, next season. The suite will be made
available to charitable organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a leader for this organization as a player and as
a person,'' Blake said. ``To give underprivileged individuals the
opportunity to experience things they may never get a chance to see
is a thrill, and something I really want to make happen.''
</P>
<P>
   By signing Blake for three years, the Kings were able to get
their top player into training camp, but they also ensured that
they will have to deal with him again sooner than if he had
accepted the five-year, $25 million contract he reportedly had been
offered all summer. Blake, who surpassed St. Louis' Al MacInnis ($5
million a year) as the NHL's top-paid defenseman, will be eligible
for unrestricted free agency when he completes his new contract.
It's possible, however, that Taylor will discuss an extension with
Blake's agent, Ron Salcer, before the contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, they're going to be talking to us again,''
Salcer said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Taylor, ``We may try to lock Rob up for longer at some
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson was just happy to have two key contracts
resolved and two key players back on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, our team is much better with Blakey and Matty, and
hopefully Jamie and Bergy will come to their senses, too,''
Robinson said. ``They'll make us a better team. They're all pretty
talented players.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Kings returned seven players to their junior teams
and assigned three others to the IHL's Ice Dogs. Heading back to
junior hockey are defensemen Konrad Brand, Jeff Katcher, Kip
Brennan, Mathieu Biron and Joe Rullier, center Justin Papineau and
goalie Alexey Volkov.... Assigned to the Ice Dogs were defenseman
Jan Nemecek and right wings Justin Martin and Greg Phillips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
