<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3669 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-SERAGEN-STOCKTIP-     09-18 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SERAGEN-STOCKTIP-ART-3TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING A STOCK, NOT WISELY BUT TOO WELL: THE COST OF OBSESSION
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Mass., N.H., Conn., Del., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of Timeline and stock price for Seragen is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
(af) 
By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tip arrived at the rustic New Hampshire farmhouse of George
A. Schrader Jr. in a large manila envelope, postmarked Boston and
stuffed with the prospects of future riches.
</P>
<P>
   The contents told of a promising young drug company called
Seragen Inc., which was developing a new class of drugs that
scientists believed might someday be a ``magic bullet'' in the
fight against cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Seragen had good science, the papers said, and Wall Street
analysts predicted that with Food and Drug Administration approval,
it would quickly become a biotechnology superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader decided to buy about $6,000 in shares of Seragen in
that summer of 1992. A retired professor of philosophy, he did not
know much about biology or the stock market. But he knew the man
who had sent him the envelope _ John R. Silber, then the president
of Boston University, who had been a brilliant student of
Schrader's at Yale 30 years before.
</P>
<P>
   Combative and charismatic, Silber was a true believer in Seragen
and its drugs, and for a decade he was the company's most ardent
salesman. He persuaded scores of associates, friends, and family
members to buy in: his brother, sister-in-law and niece, and
friends on the faculty. His secretary plowed in more than $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   At Silber's behest, the university poured tens of millions into
Seragen, a sum that grew even in the face of a formal rebuke from
state regulators that the stake was too risky for a nonprofit
endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Silber himself sank $1.7 million, close to half his net worth,
into Seragen. To him, Seragen had not just a magic bullet against
disease, but also the cure for Boston University's chronic
financial needs; it was the wonder drug that would propel the
university's modest endowment into Ivy League ranks.
</P>
<P>
   He delved into the company's complex science much as he had
immersed himself in the ethics of Immanuel Kant.
</P>
<P>
   But as with so many infatuations, this one came to an ugly end.
</P>
<P>
   An FDA advisory panel recommended approval of Interleukin-2 this
year _ but not before Seragen, based in Hopkinton, Mass., ran out
of money. The stock collapsed, and the company, flirting with
bankruptcy, was sold in August for a pittance. Boston University's
stake today is worth just $8.4 million. Silber's holdings, which
had grown to $2 million, are valued now at $43,000. Some investors
did better, depending on when they bought in and whether they got
out before the crash. By the time Schrader died in May, his
investment had all but evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the debacle, the finger-pointing has grown
heated. Some shareholders have sued Seragen and Boston University,
among others, contending that in the scramble to keep Seragen
afloat, the university _ which took a controlling interest of the
company in 1987 _ engaged in ``sweetheart deals'' and
``self-dealing'' that benefited the university while whipsawing the
share price and ultimately undermining Seragen's prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse has also served as an opportunity for Silber's
critics to resurrect accusations that he was blind to conflicts of
interest arising from Seragen, including his and the university's
financial dealings with trustees who both oversaw the university's
investments in Seragen and invested in the company themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Silber saw no conflict of interest. ``I advocated that the
trustees invest in Seragen, and I put my poke in Seragen,'' he
said. ``I think it would have been hypocritical if I said, `You
invest, but I won't.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He was, after all, in pursuit of what every investor wants: a
huge score. He just happened to pick one of the toughest ways to
make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biotech is a graveyard,'' said Mark Simon, an analyst at
BancBoston Robertson Stephens. ``This is a very risky area. It's
like wildcatting, oil drilling. But when you hit a well, it can be
very huge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Silber likes to say that he has always been a risk taker.
In 1971, he took a risk on Boston University, a school that he
considered nearly bankrupt, academically and financially, and
transformed it into a bastion of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   He hired what he termed a ``murderer's row'' of top scholars,
bolstered the university's finances and gained notoriety as one of
the nation's highest-paid college presidents, with compensation of
more than $500,000 a year. In 1996, he was named chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   He first became interested in Seragen in 1986, when Dr. John R.
Murphy, a professor at the university, gave a talk about his
discovery of ``fusion toxins,'' genetically re-engineered proteins
that acted as guided missiles, aiming at diseased cells and
injecting them with a protein-destroying chemical. Murphy had
helped found Seragen, with other Boston-area scientists, and his
experimental drug, Interleukin-2, was later licensed to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember him coming up to me after the talk, and he was very
interested in the nature of the science and the potential the
science had,'' Murphy said, recalling his first discussion of
Interleukin-2 with Silber. ``He was very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, when a Norwegian pharmaceutical company decided
to divest itself of its majority interest in Seragen, the
university's trustees, at Silber's urging, bought the stake for $25
million. He was not about to repeat the mistake Boston University
made at the turn of the century, when Alexander Graham Bell
invented the telephone _ while on leave from the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had just 5 percent of what eventually became Bell
Telephone,'' Silber explained recently, ``we would be richer than
Harvard today.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics at the university, however, questioned the Seragen
investment almost immediately. Michael Manove, a professor of
economics, complained that the school was putting ``too many eggs
in one basket.'' The school's total endowment at the time was
valued at $175 million.
</P>
<P>
   More serious questions arose when Silber, a conservative
Democrat, ran for governor of Massachusetts in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   William Weld, his Republican opponent, accused him of personally
profiting from the university's sale of a Seragen unit in 1989.
Silber denied owning stock in the unit, but in 1993, long after
Silber lost the election, the Massachusetts Attorney General's
office _ which regulates nonprofit institutions _ concluded that he
indeed had received $386,700 from the sale.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Silber said he had returned the payment as soon
as he recognized that it was improper. Investigators determined
that Silber had not broken any laws.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into Silber was part of a criminal inquiry,
the attorney general said, which was begun after his office
received ``credible evidence'' that Silber had received a payment
that he had denied receiving in public statements. Meanwhile, a
separate civil inquiry examined the university's governance and its
large stake in Seragen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the university signed an agreement with the attorney
general's office pledging to ``significantly reduce'' its financial
exposure in Seragen. To spread the risk, an initial public offering
was planned.
</P>
<P>
   None of the criticism dampened Silber's enthusiasm for Seragen.
He was enamored with the company and its technology _ in part
because of the story of a Hingham, Mass., man named Bill Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had cutaneous T-cell lymphoma, a form of cancer that
quickly covered his body with lesions. Chemotherapy had failed, and
in January 1990, when he was 60, he was told that he did not have
much time left. Smith was given a dose of Interleukin-2, then in
the early stages of its clinical trials, and soon after, his cancer
went into remission.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me six months to live, and I'm still here,'' Smith
said in a recent interview. ``It's a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   His account, videotaped for Seragen, became a centerpiece in
Silber's personal campaign to spread the word about the company.
Although Silber says he never ``touted'' Seragen's stock, he did
encourage people in his vast circle to invest once the company went
public in April 1992, at $12 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he believed in it, and because he's an intelligent and
persuasive person, I bought it,'' said Walter Lubars, a longtime
professor of public relations at Boston University who bought about
$30,000 worth. ``I was getting ready to retire, and he convinced
me, in '92, '93, '94, that by '97, Seragen would be at $64.''
</P>
<P>
   There was never any doubt about Silber's commitment _ or
compassion. In 1991, he wrote to Roger Shattuck, a longtime friend
who was a professor of modern languages at the university, that
Seragen was developing a molecule that might offer a treatment for
Shattuck's 40-year-old daughter Tari, a teacher, who was suffering
from CML leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Shattuck eventually invested in the company, but Interleukin-2
proved irrelevant to his daughter's disease; she died in April
1993.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Silber arranged for his son David, 41, an actor
infected with HIV, to be treated with the drug. ``Seragen is really
our only hope, because the doctors agree that the other chemo is
only slowing it down but cannot stop it,'' Silber wrote to a
friend. ``David is now in that difficult process for a young person
of coming to terms with the fact that he is very likely to die
within the next few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he died a month later.
</P>
<P>
   Silber's enthusiasm could not disguise the difficulties Seragen
was facing. The company raised $52 million through public stock
sales in 1992 and 1993, but like so many young biotechnology
companies, its cash needs were voracious.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, with FDA approval of Interleukin-2 still just a dream,
Seragen lost $26.3 million, pushing its cumulative losses to $200
million. The stock, which had reached a high of $15 in January
1993, ended 1996 at just over $1 a share. By then, Murphy, the
father of Interleukin-2, had severed his ties to Seragen. Though
his faith in the drug was undiminished, ``it was clear,'' he said,
``that the problems were business problems.''
</P>
<P>
   As tireless as he had been in promoting the public stock
offerings, Silber worked just as hard to bring desperately needed
money into the company when sales of common stock were no longer
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   There was a flurry of deals. In November 1995, Silber
orchestrated a bailout of sorts that brought in $23.8 million
through a loan backed by the university and two affiliated
investors: Leon C. Hirsch, the chairman of the United States
Surgical Corp., who is also a university trustee, and Gerald S.J.
Cassidy, the university's Washington lobbyist. The loans were later
converted into preferred stock.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the university, which had periodically poured new
money into Seragen, invested an additional $5 million through a
private placement of stock, bringing its stake to $84 million. (The
state, which had directed Boston University four years earlier to
reduce its holdings in Seragen, did not object, because with the
overall growth of the school's endowment to $470 million, its
relative exposure to the drug company's stock had diminished, said
Richard C. Allen, head of the public charities division of the
state attorney general's office.)
</P>
<P>
   In December, Seragen's board _ which included Silber, Cassidy
and Kenneth Condon, the university's treasurer _ voted to raise the
number of authorized shares in the company to 70 million from 30
million. It was an act of desperation that would dilute the value
of existing investors' holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a small group of investors began complaining about the
company's issuing what they termed ``exploding puts'': preferred
shares or options with conversion features that could result in
virtually unlimited dilution if the share price fell _ as, indeed,
it did.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle to raise cash continued into 1997, but there were
no more deep pockets for Silber to plumb. In February, Seragen sold
its manufacturing operation to the university for $5 million. The
school leased services back to Seragen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deals like that one, critics said, indicated that Silber and the
university had crossed the lines of propriety in their struggle to
keep Seragen afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors complained that key backers of Seragen had
conflicting allegiances. Silber and Hirsch, for instance, were
trustees of the university, directors of U.S. Surgical and large
shareholders of Seragen.
</P>
<P>
   Among other transactions, U.S. Surgical paid $5 million in July
1997 for the worldwide rights to one of Seragen's drugs, a deal
that also gave U.S. Surgical warrants to buy 500,000 Seragen
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Silber owns 22,000 shares of U.S. Surgical, worth around
$900,000. He has also been designated a director in Cassidy's
lobbying firm, when it goes public.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbed by what they said was the appearance of a conflict of
interest, a group of U.S. Surgical investors called in May of this
year for a vote to remove Silber from the company's compensation
committee, citing an ``inter-locking directorate relationship''
with Hirsch and the men's business ties.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As Seragen collapsed, shareholders outside its inner circle also
began to look askance at the blur of transactions. In August, an
angry group of investors filed a lawsuit in Delaware contending
that the interests of minority shareholders were damaged by Silber,
the university and its associates, including Cassidy and Hirsch.
The suit says they engaged in ``sweetheart deals'' and
``self-dealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy and Hirsch declined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas G. Griffin, a lawyer for the shareholder group, said the
``self-dealing'' included the $23.8 million bailout of Seragen in
1995. The ties between the various parties, he said, obscured lines
of fiduciary duty. ``Boston University and Silber are controlling
Seragen and saying, `You're going to do this deal with BU,' '' he
said. ``So they are both buyer and seller; they have these
arrangements with themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But R. Robert Popeo, a lawyer for the university who earlier
represented Seragen, denied that the university or Silber were
involved in any self-dealing or conflicts of interest. He said that
his office had drawn up strict conflict guidelines that were
closely followed and that Silber and other university officials did
not participate in votes when there were deemed to be conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   At times, though, he said Silber and others _ including himself
_ switched from representing the university to representing
Seragen's interest. ``Dual representation doesn't mean a conflict
of interest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were there ``sweetheart'' deals, he added; rather than
damaging the company, he said, the university saved it from early
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seragen would have been out of business had it not been for
the university, Hirsch and Cassidy,'' Popeo said. ``Pick up a phone
and call Salomon or Lehman and they'll tell you for $23 million
they could have demanded 40 percent of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, of course, conflicts are a matter of perception. ``What
is improper about an officer of the university having business
dealings with trustees?'' Silber asked during an interview last
week. ``Far from being a conflict of interest, it is clearly in the
interest of the university to establish such business dealings.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, Silber's faith in Interleukin-2 has not faltered.
``The fact is, I was right about Seragen's science,'' he said
defiantly in a recent interview. ``For over 10 years, we've had
good results.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, an FDA advisory panel recommended approval for the
use of Interleukin-2 in the treatment of lymphoma. On final
approval, the drug, known commercially as Ontak, may live up to the
promise that Silber imagined for it when he heard Murphy's speech
12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Seragen, and Boston University, will not reap much of the
benefit. Out of money and delisted from the NASDAQ stock market,
Seragen was acquired in August by Ligand Pharmaceuticals Inc., a
San Diego company whose shares promptly tumbled when the deal was
announced. Ligand paid $30 million for Seragen, now a wholly owned
subsidiary, and will pay an additional $37 million if Ontak gets a
final government O.K.
</P>
<P>
   To the university, that represented a loss of 90 percent on its
investment during a time when so many others were soaring. For just
the $50 million that the school had put into Seragen as of 1989, it
could have $175 million today had it instead put the money into a
mutual fund that tracked the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   The cry among critics all along was that Silber just could not
let go. They said the university refused to give up its majority
stake in Seragen, making financing difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Silber says that if the state had not restricted the university
from investing more heavily, Seragen would have flourished.
``Seragen has not fallen and Seragen has not failed,'' Silber said.
``You want to talk about the rise and fall of Seragen's stock?
Fine.'' Regulators say they saved the univeristy from losing
millions more.
</P>
<P>
   Silber's hope, now, is in Ligand, which may eventually bring
Ontak to the market. What remains of his and the university's
Seragen stakes have become Ligand shares.
</P>
<P>
   Silber's friends must hope now, too. Despite their losses, few
have soured on John Silber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry in a way for John, because he wanted to leave as
a legacy a gigantic endowment,'' said Lubars, the retired professor
who bought into Seragen on Silber's tip. ``And I hope people don't
think he's dumped Seragen on us, because he's done so many good
things for the university.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
