<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-18 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINBRENNER DISCUSSES SALE OF YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Yankees have already reached their magic number for
achieving the best record in the American League this year. Now it
appears they are searching for another magic number, one that would
persuade majority owner George Steinbrenner to sell the team to
Cablevision of New York, owned by Chuck Dolan and his family.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe has learned that within the past two weeks,
Steinbrenner had a meeting with his minority owners and asked how
they felt about selling the team. This was the only time
Steinbrenner has broached the subject of selling the team, which he
purchased for $10 million in 1973. According to two sources, he
asked his limited partners, most of them old friends from his days
in Cleveland, if they would prefer to (1) sell all of the team, (2)
sell part of the team, or (3) not sell at all.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, the consensus was that Steinbrenner should agree to
sell all of the club if he feels he is getting what it's worth.
Stories in New York say Steinbrenner has been offered $500 million
by Dolan, also an old friend from Cleveland, in a deal under which
he would be allowed to run the team for at least five more years at
a salary of $5 million annually. That's in addition to his share of
the sale, perhaps almost $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner reportedly owns nearly 60 percent of the team.
Through Cablevision, Dolan has the cable television rights to
Yankees, Mets, Knicks, Rangers, and Devils games. The Yankee deal
is up in two years, but by purchasing the team, Cablevision would
own those rights for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Dolan came up short in his attempt to purchase
the Cleveland Browns NFL expansion team for $500 million. Al Lerner
won the bid with $530 million.
</P>
<P>
   The trend in sports is for major television companies to
purchase teams. Fox recently purchased the Los Angeles Dodgers. It
makes sense for these networks to buy teams because it would cost
less than the TV rights for a decade. Buy the team, then you own
your own rights.
</P>
<P>
   Part II: Could this be the way of the future for the Red Sox?
Reportedly, three major national television companies are
interested in the Sox' TV rights. Reportedly, Cablevision, Fox, and
Disney could be interested. One reportedly has spoken with the Red
Sox about paying $400 million for the rights over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' biggest contract was a few years back when they did a
seven-year deal with Channel 38 that topped out in the area of $16
million.
</P>
<P>
   However, the financial field in sports television has gone crazy
since those days, and the numbers are going out of sight. Last year
the NFL made network TV deals that total $18 billion over eight
years. For that money, that networks could have bought every team
in the league and owned the rights forever.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Rupert Murdoch, the Fox TV mogul, offered $1 billion
to buy Manchester United, the most popular soccer team in Europe.
Again, why pay all that money for the TV rights when you can buy
the team for the same price?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is an up-to-date scouting report on the Tennessee Oilers
from an NFL head coach who has faced them frequently: ``They are
doing more on offense this season than they have since they put
(Steve) McNair at quarterback. They are throwing more and looking
more for the long ball. Last year they played it pretty
conservative and had a reduced offense. They have expanded that.
This is a very tough team physically. They knock you around and
beat you up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, they attack. They come at you and try to make
plays. Jeff (Fisher, the coach) trained under Buddy Ryan, and he
always has gimmicks and tricks that give your offense a lot of
trouble. When they have the ball, they want to pound it down your
throat with Eddie George. But he is not off to the start he's had
in the past. Their offensive line was outplayed by San Diego last
week. The Chargers' front just won that battle clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care who you are, if you are not ready to play this
team or you take them lightly, you're going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There might be NBA games this year ... but maybe not until
Christmas. As the lockout continues, word is that commissioner
David Stern has rallied the owners into a tighter group than he's
ever had. They are ready to play hardball.
</P>
<P>
   How the labor strife plays out will depend upon a ruling by an
arbitrator who has conducted a hearing on whether some players with
guaranteed contracts have to be paid. If he rules no, which the
owners expect, the decision will be easy for them. They'll wait for
the rank-and-file to start missing paychecks and beefing to their
union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   This lockout was triggered by the owners' desire to eliminate
the so-called Larry Bird Exception _ which allows a team to pay
whatever it wants to a free agent already on its roster, regardless
of the salary cap. At present, only 22 players fall into that
category.
</P>
<P>
   As a compromise, look for the owners to offer to grandfather the
Bird Rule players for three or four years. This way, most of them
will be covered for the rest of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Then the owners will try to do a deal without the Bird Rule that
would guarantee more money to the middle class and reserves.
</P>
<P>
   If the arbitrator rules in favor of the players, which means
that the owners would have to pay about half the players in the
league during the lockout (wouldn't that be a crazy scenario?),
then it would be harder for them to hang tough for a long period.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A source in the Bruins' ranks says the surprise of training camp
is comebacking goalie Jim Carey. Carey was dismal in camp and the
exhibition season last year and finally was demoted to Providence,
where he complained and then underwent season-ending shoulder
surgery. Those around the team last year said Carey didn't seem to
care about anything. This year he appears to be back to the form he
showed when he was a standout for the Washington Capitals in his
first two NHL seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newcomers, Jonathan Girard, a defenseman taken in the
second round, seems to have the best chance of sticking with the
big club.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if Glenn Foley does not start for the Jets
Sunday against Indianapolis at Giants Stadium. Foley has sore ribs,
so the Jets are thinking of resting him for two weeks. Like the
rest of the AFC East, the Jets have a bye next week ... You have to
root for Dean Sylvester of Hanson. Sylvester played hockey at BC
High and went to Kent State before it dropped the program. After
finishing at Michigan State, he went to the East Coast Hockey
League, played two seasons with Kansas City of the International
Hockey League, and just signed with the Buffalo Sabres. Most
college players don't have the stomach for spending that many years
chasing a dream ... And speaking of chasing a dream, Stephanie
O'Sullivan of Dorchester is still doing just that. She got plenty
of publicity when she was the last cut by the US women's ice hockey
team before the Olympics. Presently, she is working out with the
all-male Bay State Breakers, a junior team based in Rockland.
However, she first has to get a waiver to be an overage player in
the league, then must make the team. She wants to use this avenue
to launch a comeback toward making the national team and eventually
the 2002 Olympics in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College will honor two members of its 1985 Cotton Bowl
championship team, Doug Flutie and Mike Ruth. The ceremony will
take place at halftime of the nationally televised game against
Virginia Tech Thursday, Oct. 8, at the Heights. Flutie will be
honored for winning the Heisman Trophy. Ruth will be honored for
winning the Outland Trophy as the top lineman in the country.
Flutie will get through practice at about 5 p.m. that day in
Buffalo, then get on a private jet to fly to Boston in time for the
ceremony, then back to Buffalo in time for practice Friday morning
... Tracy Stallard, who served up Roger Maris's 61st home run in
1961, has refused media interviews during Mark McGwire and Sammy
Sosa's successful quest for Maris's record. However, some members
of the Patriots that year remember vividly a train ride back to
Boston from New York the day of Maris's 61st. The Sox ended the
season in Yankee Stadium on a Sunday afternoon, the same day the
Patriots played the Titans (the original Jets) in the Polo Grounds.
By chance, both teams returned on the train, where Stallard
entertained those in the club car by several times announcing, ``I
don't know about you guys ... but I'm going to be in the Hall of
Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
