<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-MANDELA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA GETS RARE DOCTORATE BEFORE 20,000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Nelson Mandela, the legendary South African
leader who has symbolized a commitment to racial justice, stood
before Harvard University Friday, honored by the school as only
George Washington and Winston Churchill had been before him.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of the moment was not lost on Mandela _ nor on more
than 20,000 listeners in Harvard's Tercentenary Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It holds great symbolic significance: to the mind and to the
future memory of this great American institution, the name of an
African is now added to those two illustrious leaders of the
Western world,'' Mandela told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriateness of his words resounded through the crowd,
which responded with a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   With the stage of America's oldest college his, Mandela
challenged the world Friday to close the sweeping disparities
between rich and poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``While in all parts of the world progress is being made in
entrenching democratic forms of governance,'' he said, ``we
constantly need to remind ourselves that the freedoms which
democracy brings will remain empty shells if they are not
accompanied by real and tangible improvements in the material lives
of the millions of ordinary citizens of those countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, 80, looking regal in a dark suit, came to Cambridge to
accept an honorary doctorate, one of only a few given outside of
June commencement. Although Harvard has awarded the degree to
several groups, Mandela, Washington, and Churchill are the only
individuals to receive such an honor.
</P>
<P>
   Contrasting with that stature, Mandela's humility seemed to
strike the audience. At the end of the event, the former African
National Congress leader, the man imprisoned for 27 years during
his struggle for a nation's freedom, made a point to shake hands or
to hug every student in Harvard's two choirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may well be our last official visit to the United States
before retiring from office next year,'' Mandela told the crowd of
Harvard faculty, high school and college students, politicians, and
community leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's second visit to the Boston area marks the start of a
weeklong tour in which he will meet with President Clinton and
address the United Nations next week.
</P>
<P>
   He first visited the United States in 1990, shortly after his
release from South African prison after years of worldwide
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Then, his recently gained freedom made the US appearances seem
almost magical and religious. Accompanied by his then-wife, Winnie
Mandela, he swept the multiracial crowds in Boston as he called for
the continuation of economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   There was similar anticipation for this event; Kevin Bryant,
among others, had been preparing for days. The 43-year-old Harvard
police and Honor Guard officer put in an early request to his
captain to carry Mandela's degree from 17 Quincy St., through the
Yard, and to the stage of the Tercentenary Theater. At exactly 3:53
p.m., he came down the brick path in front of Sever Hall, clutching
the degree with white-gloved hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in awe, I was just amazed,'' Bryant said of the degree
and the moment he will surely tell his grandchildren about. ``It's
an unbelievable feeling I can't even describe. He's like Moses.''
</P>
<P>
   On this visit, Mandela came with new power as president of a
multiracial South Africa. He also came with his new wife, Gracia
Machel, the former wife of Mozambican leader Samora Machel. And he
comes with victories _ fulfilling his principal goal of ending
apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he faces many problems, such as unemployment, poor
housing, an economic morass, and the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission's findings of widespread abuses against blacks during
apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   But, some said, the visit to America, a country that once
thrived from the business of enslaving Africans, symbolized an
eloquent lesson on the perils of a system of racial separatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done something within South Africa that has been
carried over the rest of the world, following the politics of
inclusion, which means that he reached out to people that had been
his enemies, providing a model of leadership everywhere,'' said
Robert Rotberg, development associate at The Harvard Institute and
president of the World Peace foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela emphasized Friday an obligation among the most powerful
countries to share in intellectual and economic wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Professor Henry Louis Gates, meanwhile, announced that
his W.E.B. DuBois Institute of Afro-American Research, is creating
a fellowship program, which will allow visiting African scholars to
study at Harvard as Mandela Fellows.
</P>
<P>
   The project coincides with the Emerging Africa research project,
housed in the Center for International Development.
</P>
<P>
   That project, Mandela said, ``will serve to strengthen and build
African intellectual capacity to take charge of its reconstruction
and regeneration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that it will also strengthen and build our own
understanding of African reality and your capacity to analyze that
reality as part of a shared world.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, Nia Stephens watched from afar _ from the highest
step of Widener Library, more than 100 yards from where Mandela
stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised with the idea of Mandela as a hero,'' said
Stephens, a Tennessee native whose parents both attended Harvard
during the turbulent 1960s. ``I was awakened very early in the
morning by my parents to watch him walk out of prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephens said: ``My heart was really warmed by the optimism of
his speech. To know that people with a history of trying to make a
difference are not cynical, that they can still be committed to a
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Francie Latour of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
