<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAPANESE PARTIES AGREE ON ECONOMIC STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Japan's governing party said that it had reached agreement with
the political opposition on how to bolster the jittery financial
system and begin reviving the ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced by Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi ended
weeks of deadlock that had intensified criticism of Japan for
dithering over how to solve its problems as economic turmoil spread
to financial markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. CONSUMERS ARE STILL UPBEAT
</P>
<P>
   Since the financial troubles in Russia, the tumble in stock
prices in the United States and elsewhere and the release of
Kenneth Starr's report, consumers have turned only slightly more
cautious, according to a major poll of consumer attitudes. The
willingness of consumers to spend is viewed as good news for the
economy and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL BANK FREES RUBLE RESERVES
</P>
<P>
   Russia's central bank said that the country's insolvent banks
could use $1.65 billion in precious ruble reserves to enable them
to make good on customers' bills and debts that are going unpaid.
The government hopes that freeing up the reserves will grease the
wheels of the payment system and get financial activity moving
again.
</P>
<P>
   RIGHT TO SUE HMOS UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   A provision in a new Texas law allowing patients to sue
health-maintenance organizations and other insurers for malpractice
was upheld by a federal judge in Houston, but a second provision
allowing patients to appeal to an independent panel when their
health plan denies coverage for treatment was struck down.
</P>
<P>
   SHAREHOLDERS BACK CHRYSLER MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler shareholders strongly endorsed forming a huge new
international automaker by merging with Daimler-Benz of Germany.
Following their lead, Daimler-Benz's shareholders, meeting well
into the night in Stuttgart, overwhelmingly approved the
combination.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDENT OF UAL STEPS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   John Edwardson, the president and chief operating officer of
UAL, the parent of United Airlines, resigned under pressure from
the company's machinists, pilots and flight attendants unions,
which opposed him as the eventual successor to Gerald Greenwald,
the chief executive, who is expected to retire next year.
</P>
<P>
   BP SETS TARGET FOR EMISSIONS CUT
</P>
<P>
   British Petroleum announced Friday a ``firm overall target'' to
cut emissions by 10 percent of their 1990 levels by 2010, setting a
figure for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   SEC DROPS INSIDER-TRADING CASE
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has dropped a three-year
inquiry into accusations of insider trading by ICN Pharmaceuticals
and its chief executive, Milan Panic. But the SEC will start an
enforcement action against the company and Panic for failing to
disclose adverse information about its viral drug, ribavirin, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   AMP BOLSTERS DEFENSE AGAINST BID
</P>
<P>
   AMP stepped up its defense against Allied Signal's hostile bid
of $44.50 a share by lowering the threshold of its shareholder
rights plan, which makes it prohibitively expensive for Allied to
buy more than 10 percent of AMP's stock.
</P>
<P>
   GUILTY PLEA IN TRADING SCHEME
</P>
<P>
   A brokerage employee who worked on the floor of the New York
Stock Exchange has pleaded guilty to conspiring with exchange floor
brokers to cover up an illegal trading scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ALCATEL TO CONSIDER SHARE BUYBACK
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to contain the damage done by its warning on Thursday
that its profit would not meet forecasts this year, Alcatel said
that it would consider a significant share buyback program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
