<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGE DAY ON THE STREET  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Strange things happened on Wall Street Friday. Prices
of both bonds and stocks rose.
</P>
<P>
   A bond rally pushed the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond
closer to 5 percent, the lowest level for long-term government
yields in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But surprisingly, this flight by investors to the Treasury's
safe harbor did not come at the expense of stock prices, as has
been the case recently. Instead, stocks rallied too, as the Dow
Jones industrial average inched up 21.89 points to recover part of
its 216-point slide Thursday. The broader Nasdaq index jumped 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, it made for one of the calmest days on Wall Street
and in other markets in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The problems for the American stock market _ weak corporate
earnings, a recession in Asia, the threat of one in Latin America
and the spillover into the United States _ all remain.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast of IBES International, which collects analysts'
earnings estimates, for third-quarter earnings of the companies
that make up the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index is now a decline of
1.1 percent, compared with the third quarter a year ago. That would
be the first quarterly drop in earnings since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas Cliggott, the U.S. equity strategist at J.P. Morgan
Securities, sees something positive. Earnings forecasts, which two
months ago were for 8 percent growth in the third quarter, have
come into line with reality, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Given no growth in earnings and the yield on the 30-year bond at
5.25 percent, he said the stock market is now about 9 percent
undervalued. ``That is a very good cushion for an uncertain
world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow finished at 7,895.66, up 0.3 percent for the day and 1.3
percent for the week, while the Nasdaq index jumped 17.52 points,
to 1,663.77, up 1.1 percent for the day and 1.3 percent for the
week. The S&AMP;P 500 rose 1.22 points, or 1.2 percent, to 1,020.09,
putting its gain for the week at 1.1 percent, while the Russell
index of 2,000 smaller-company stocks climbed 7.97 points, or 2.2
percent, to 363.26, finishing the week up 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second consecutive week that all the major indexes
have climbed, and this week's rally came despite the deflating
comments Wednesday from the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board,
Alan Greenspan, who told Congress that ``at the moment there is no
endeavor to coordinate interest rate cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the finance ministers of the Group of Seven,
which comprises the United States, Japan, Germany, France, Britain,
Italy and Canada, and a speech Monday by President Clinton both
raised expectations of an immediate global rate cut to help
stabilize world financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   The rush of worried investors into the Treasury market, which
may have been accelerated by Greenspan's comments, is threatening
to drive the yield on the 30-year bond below 5 percent, to levels
that have not been seen for 30 years. Friday the yield fell to 5.14
percent, from 5.18 percent Thursday, while the price, which moves
in the opposite direction, rose 18/32, to 105 15/32.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, however, are still split over whether the 5 percent
barrier, which has stood for the entire careers of most traders on
Wall Street, will be breached. Kevin Flanagan, a money market
economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said it would take a
deepening of the present global financial crisis to bring yields
below 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan argued that the Fed will not cut its short-term
interest rate target when policy makers meet Sept. 29 because there
is no clear sign yet that the American economy is slowing down
enough. But he is still forecasting a Fed move by the end of the
year, by which time he expects the appearance of clear signals that
the collapse of economies abroad has begun to sap growth here.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 10-year Treasury note, a benchmark for home
mortgage rates, dropped to 4.69 percent, from 4.76 percent,
presaging a continuing decline in mortgage interest rates.
Thirty-year mortgage rates at 6.6 percent are now the lowest they
have been in about 30 years and should help stimulate the housing
market.
</P>
<P>
   But interest rates on mortgages and high-grade corporate debt
have not fallen nearly as much as Treasury yields, and the interest
rates on junk bonds have risen. Because of this, the stimulus to
the economy from lower government rates will be muted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
