<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3687 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATERACE-1STLD-W     09-18 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATERACE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMOST IMMEDIATELY, N.Y. SENATE RACE GETS NASTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add 15 grafs at end)   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To listen to Rep. Charles Schumer in recent days,
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato is a liar: an untrustworthy, out-of-touch,
Republican relic who is soft on crime and a promoter of higher
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   To listen to D'Amato, Schumer is a liar: an ambitious,
out-of-touch, liberal Brooklyn congressman who is soft on crime and
a promoter of higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
   It has been just four days since Schumer began the third attempt
by the Democratic Party to remove D'Amato from the Senate. But
already _ in television advertisements and press conferences, in
speeches and interviews _ the competition between Schumer and
D'Amato has attained a level of invective that usually does not
arrive until a contest's final days.
</P>
<P>
   In an unmistakable signal of how the race is going to be played
during the next six weeks _ rough and on television _ D'Amato
demanded Friday afternoon that Schumer withdraw ``blatantly wrong''
advertisements that end with the memorably harsh tag line:
``D'Amato: too many lies for too long.'' Schumer laughed him off.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Democrats and Republicans familiar with the political
histories of D'Amato and Schumer, and aware of polls showing that
D'Amato's re-election is not assured, had eagerly anticipated this
competition. They expected it to be hard-fought, fast-paced and
engaging.
</P>
<P>
   But few expected it to be this hard-fought and this fast-paced
so soon, even though Schumer had promised that he would ``take it
to'' D'Amato if he won the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of ferocity, I don't think I've seen anything like
this since the 1993 mayoral race in New York,'' said Richard
Schrader, a political analyst. ``Schumer is defining himself as a
stronger candidate than any other candidate D'Amato has faced
before.''
</P>
<P>
   That these two, of all candidates in New York, have engaged so
quickly and intensely is, in many ways, not a surprise to
politicians here. But the fact that the campaign has struck a
negative tone so soon, particularly after a primary that was
noteworthy for its civility, was unexpected by Democrats and
Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   And in an era when voters are known to dislike negative
campaigns _ no matter how effective such tactics prove to be for
some candidates _ there was concern among many Democrats and
Republicans about the risks Schumer and D'Amato were taking in
starting their campaigns at this level.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign so far is a reflection of both the personalities of
the candidates and the constraints of the race. With so little time
between New York's late primary and the general election, it was
essential, Schumer's advisers said, to begin building the case
against D'Amato quickly and harshly. And since he has far less
money than D'Amato, he needed to do it in the light of news
coverage that accompanied his defeat of Geraldine Ferraro and Mark
Green.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer needed to show Democrats that he had, as he promised
during his primary campaign, learned from the mistakes of Robert
Abrams, who waged a relatively anemic challenge to D'Amato in 1992.
So rather than disappearing from public view to raise money,
Schumer began his campaign with a two-day swing across the state,
framing his differences with D'Amato through the issues of
anticrime measures and fiscal moderation, seeking to undercut any
attempt to paint him as left of center.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, 12 hours after D'Amato went on the air attacking
Schumer as liberal _ ``Chuck Schumer's a New York City liberal and
he proves it every day,'' the announcer says, a reprise in tone and
timing of what D'Amato did in 1992 _ Schumer's advertising
consultant, Hank Morris, had pulled the trigger on advertisements
attacking D'Amato's truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   What was surprising, to many Democrats, was the sharp tone of
the advertisements. Typically, a challenger begins a campaign by
presenting his biography and record. The use of the word ``liar''
is explosive, even by the standards of New York politics, and it
gave Schumer's supporters some pause Friday, concerned that he was
risking a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk, in that if this stuff becomes too personal, it
can backfire on you,'' said Bill Lynch, a Democrat, who managed
both mayoral campaigns for David Dinkins. ``I would have gotten
Chuck's voting record first and had him campaign personally in the
upstate areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Kieran Mahoney, a political adviser to D'Amato, asserted that
Schumer would be hurt by the advertisement, which he compared with
attacks Abrams made on the senator in 1992. ``Abrams got out with
half his reputation,'' Mahoney warned. ``Schumer is not going to
have any reputation left. He's been lying about his record while
he's attacking D'Amato for lying.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morris said he had no apologies. ``I don't think this is so
tough,'' he said. ``We always said that the first time
election-year Al D'Amato mentioned congressman Schumer's name, we
were going to react to it. He's just been lying to people too
long.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has been no less aggressive. He has barraged Schumer
during these last three days, issuing a list of votes that Schumer
missed this year in Congress, calling him a ``liberal Brooklyn
congressman'' at every turn. Friday, the campaign described Schumer
as ``a liar'' because he had described D'Amato as ``a liar.''
</P>
<P>
   The early attacks are typical of D'Amato. They are calculated,
one adviser said, to undermine Schumer's attempt to position
himself as a moderate, and to delay him from finding his campaign
footing.
</P>
<P>
   The facts of the assaults by both Schumer and D'Amato are a
matter of dispute.
</P>
<P>
   It is, Democrats acknowledged Friday, debatable that D'Amato's
advertisement, which accuses Schumer of voting for more welfare and
for tax increases and against some crime measures, actually rises
to the level of lying. As is typical in politics, D'Amato has
picked out some of Schumer's votes to try to present him in the
worst possible light.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the notion of Schumer as a liberal, as D'Amato has
taken to describing him, is one that would surely be challenged by
many liberals in New York. Schumer, in anticipation of a statewide
run, has spent much of the last decade establishing himself as
anything but liberal. He has sponsored a number of crime bills,
including a federal death penalty, and voted for legislation
restricting welfare benefits and for a law aimed at restricting
marriages between homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   But senior aides to both candidates said there is little doubt
that the campaign is going to fly at this level for much of the
next six weeks. Anticipating the criticism that no doubt awaits
them, advisers to both Schumer and D'Amato went to some lengths to
deny that they were responsible for the tone the race has taken so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney asserted that Schumer had started it with advertisements
he ran this summer, which, among other things, presented D'Amato as
a Republican partisan who had supported cuts in Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Morris did Mahoney 18 years better. ``D'Amato went negative
first when he unfairly destroyed Jacob Javits,'' responded Morris,
soberly referring to D'Amato's defeat of the longtime senator in
the 1980 Republican primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
