<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-2NDL     09-18 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(SUBS TO ADD QUOTES, DATA, ART NOTE)  
 VOTE ALONG PARTY LINES AFTER TWO DAYS OF WRANGLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Giving a sharp partisan cast to deliberations over
impeachment, the Republican-controlled House Judiciary Committee
voted along party lines Friday to release the videotape of
President Clinton's grand jury testimony, along with 2,800 pages of
documents from the inquiry into his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The materials were set to be made public on Monday, promising to
a nation that would like the scandal to simply go away televised
replays of an angry and legalistic President Clinton jousting with
lawyers over the definition of sexual relations. Several members of
Congress protested the decision to make the material public on the
Jewish New Year.
</P>
<P>
   The party divide over the release of material erupted into the
open minutes after the committee ended its final two hours of
closed-door deliberations Friday morning. Rep. Henry Hyde, the
committee chairman, began to describe the committee's two days of
meetings as ``civil'' sessions in which the ``spirit of
bipartisanship is alive and flourishing.'' But he was quickly
interrupted by Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say that this is a new concept, unfortunately,
of unilateral bipartisanship,'' Frank said. ``Bipartisanship can't
be unilateral.'' He said virtually every vote taken across two days
of deliberations had been along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde retorted, ``I may have a different definition of
bipartisanship. It doesn't include surrender to every single
Democrat's wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the four-hour videotape of Clinton, the documents to be
released add further detail to the report by Kenneth Starr, the
Whitewater independent counsel, who accused the president of 11
acts that might constitute impeachable offenses. The documents
include FBI interviews with Ms. Lewinsky, her own testimony before
the grand jury and her proffer to Starr, outlining what her
testimony would be.
</P>
<P>
   The committee did agree to make about 120 deletions from the
materials on the grounds of sexual explicitness, national security
or privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the two days of debate in the ideologically polarized
committee was taken up with wrangling over things like whether the
committee should be meeting in public and the level of sexual
detail that would be made public. The closed-door deliberations
were followed by dueling news conferences, first by Democrats, then
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings of the House Judiciary Committee are the first
since the Watergate scandal in 1974 at which the House has
considered whether to open an impeachment inquiry into a president.
And the deliberations are taking place in an atmosphere made more
tense by recent news reports on sexual indiscretions on the part of
three Republican members of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials said Hyde telephoned Speaker Newt Gingrich
earlier in the week and offered to relinquish his role in the
investigation after the online magazine Salon reported that he had
had an extramarital affair 30 years ago. Gingrich, however, gave
Hyde his full support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Speaker did not consider the resignation because there is
no person who has earned more respect and affection from the House
than Hyde,'' said Christina Martin, a spokeswoman for Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to ease some of the fears sweeping Congress, Sens. Mitch
McConnell and Bob Kerrey, the chairmen of the Republican and
Democratic Senate campaign committees, respectively, followed the
lead of their House counterparts and pledged in the Senate Friday
not to finance candidates who make personal attacks against
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digging through their record is one thing,'' said McConnell, a
Kentucky Republican. ``Digging through their garbage is quite
another.''
</P>
<P>
   The partisan acrimony over the release of Starr's materials has
grown since last week when Gingrich and Rep. Richard Gephardt, the
House minority leader, pledged to work cooperatively. The House
then voted 363 to 63 to make public Starr's report and backup
materials after scrutiny by the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the panel said Friday that they were carrying out
the will of the full House for maximum public disclosure and that
the documents would make clear whether Starr's report had put the
president's testimony in proper context. They also said that the
panel's Democrats were ideologues who are not representative of
their party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty percent, maybe 70 percent of our colleagues on the
other side had a hard time accepting the mandate of the House,''
said Rep. Lindsey Graham, a South Carolina Republican on the panel.
``Whether that's a partisan fight I don't know. I feel we lived up
to the mandate of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said, ``There was a general view among the Democrats not to
reveal anything and there was a general view among Republicans to
reveal as much as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's Democrats accused the Republicans of trying to keep
up a steady stream of information embarrassing the president,
instead of releasing it at once on the Sept. 28 deadline for the
committee to have reviewed all the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to dribble out information for only one reason:
death by a thousand cuts,'' said Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
