NYT-09-18-98 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980918.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3691 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-2NDL     09-18 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: Wexler, D-Fla.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   His remarks were echoed by the White House. ``This appears to be
a rush to prejudgment and an effort to get out the most salacious
material at the speed of light, not at the proper pace of
justice,'' said James Kennedy, a White House spokesman. ``But in
the end it will have to be the American people who will have to see
if this indeed has been a fair process or a partisan effort to
embarrass the president.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Republicans controlling the Judiciary Committee, the
Democrats had virtually no chance of prevailing on any vote, but
they did create a record across two days of roll call votes to show
the American public which party was voting to release the explicit
details of Clinton's affair with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Schumer, a New York Democrat on the committee who
just won his party's nomination to challenge Sen. Alfonse M.
D'Amato, was absent.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the votes ran along party lines from the moment the
session began on Thursday and the committee voted 21 to 15 against
a motion by Frank to make the meeting open to the public. Friday
the Republicans pushed through the motions for release of the
videotape and of 2,800 pages of transcripts and materials, in two
party line votes of 20 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said some Republicans Friday
morning initially voted against a motion by one of their Republican
colleagues to make the 17 roll call votes public but switched when
it became clear that the majority of the committee favored public
release of the roll calls. In the end seven Republicans continued
to oppose release of the roll calls.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the wrangling concerned sexually explicit materials. The
committee's Republican and Democratic staff members had drawn up a
list of 120 deletions to be made from the released materials.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., succeeded in having three of those
deletions, describing a particular sexual act, restored to the
public record. Rep. Asa Hutchinson, an Arkansas Republican who is a
former federal prosecutor, broke with his party and voted against
Barr.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats tried but failed to win 27 additional deletions,
covering Ms. Lewinsky's description of phone sex with the
president, his manner of undressing her and other explicit sexual
details of their encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, Rep. Bob Inglis of South Carolina, was
defeated 28 to 6 when he tried to amend a public log that will cite
the reasons for deletions. In this one case, he wanted the log to
include a graphic description of the sexual act contained in the
material that was being deleted. Five Republicans voted with him.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Republicans voiced concerns this week that the
release of more sexually explicit materials could boomerang against
their party, the Republicans on the committee Friday said last
week's House vote had carried the presumption of more openness, not
less.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he feared a public backlash, Rep. Stephen Buyer,
R-Ind., said, ``Well, maybe you should ask the question, `Will
there be a backlash against Democrats who seek to act like criminal
defense lawyers.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If someone doesn't want to watch this then don't
watch it. We have the responsibility to move this into the public
domain and give the president of the United States the benefit of
the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
