<SLUG> BC-GLF-SOLHEIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOLHEIM TEAM'S FAST START HAS EUROPE UP THE CREEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ From Friday's first match at the Solheim Cup, the
United States took command and left Europe playing catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   Dottie Pepper and Juli Inkster set the tone by opening play with
a convincing victory. Kelly Robbins made a 5-foot putt on the 18th
hole that gave the United States a 3-1 lead heading into the
afternoon. Pat Hurst, playing like a cup veteran instead of a
rookie, was part of two victories. And Brandie Burton, despite
falling into a creek at No. 11, brushed herself off and went on to
win, making an embarrassing moment part of a satisfying afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Friday's first round had ended, the European team
was in trouble. The United States ended the day with a 5{-2{ lead
at Muirfield Village Golf Club, the largest first-day lead in
Solheim Cup history, and appeared well on the way to successfully
defending the cup. As the defending champion, the United States
needs 14 points to retain the cup, while Europe needs 14{ points to
win.
</P>
<P>
   Europe can take heart from the 1996 cup, when the United States
jumped to a 5-3 lead after the first day, only to see Europe storm
back for a 9-7 lead after Day 2. But the United States ultimately
won in 1996, 17-11, and a 3-point deficit today was not the start
Europe had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got off to a horrible start,'' said Laura Davies, one of
Europe's top players, who managed just half a point in her two
matches. ``We lost by 3 points today, so we have to win by 3 points
tomorrow. That should be our goal. But no matter, it's not over,
but until they get 14 points, we won't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Europe cannot afford to fall further behind before Sunday's
singles matches. The United States has an overwhelming 18-4 record
in singles play during the last two Solheim Cups, making a Sunday
rally by Europe unlikely. That puts extreme pressure on Europe to
play well Saturday, and it will be interesting to see how the team
captain, Pia Nilsson, maneuvers her lineup. Most of what Nilsson
tried Friday did not work as she had hoped, while Judy Rankin, the
American captain, saw her team perform steadily.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning foursome matches, Pepper and Inkster opened with
a convincing 3 and 1 victory over Davies and Trish Johnson. Nilsson
took a chance opening with Johnson, who has been bothered by a neck
injury, and Johnson did not play well. Nilsson may also regret not
playing Liselotte Neumann, one of the world's top players, Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Annika Sorenstam and Catriona Matthew scored the lone morning
point for Europe, defeating Donna Andrews and Tammie Green, 3 and
2. But the most dramatic morning matches both went in the United
States' favor, when Hurst and Robbins defeated Lisa Hackney and
Neumann, 1 up, while Burton and Meg Mallon rallied from a two-hole
deficit through nine holes to defeat Helen Alfredsson and Alison
Nicholas, 3 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon four-ball matches, Betsy King and Chris Johnson
of the United States halved with Charlotta Sorenstam and Davies;
Hurst and Rose Jones dominated Hackney and Sophie Gustafson, 7 and
5; Alfredsson and Maria Laure de Lorenzi defeated Robbins and
Sherri Steinhauer, 2 and 1, and Pepper and Burton defeated Annika
Sorenstam and Catrin Nilsmark, 2 up.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon highlights included de Lorenzi making a bunker
shot from 25 feet on No. 17 to end her match and earn a key point
for Europe. Then there was Burton's tumble into the creek at No.
11. Standing on the bank, Burton lost her balance on her
follow-through and tried to jump over the creek, but her right shoe
became stuck in the mud. Down went Burton, her right leg covered in
mud, and her right shoe came off after it was stuck in the mud.
Fortunately, she was not injured, and afterward her teammates could
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was classic,'' Pepper said. ``I go on record as saying
they should rename that Burton's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's morning foursome matches will feature Annika
Sorenstam and Matthew against Andrews and Steinhauer; Davies and
Charlotta Sorenstam vs. Burton and Mallon; Alfredsson and Laure de
Lorenzi vs. Inkster and Pepper, and Neumann and Nilsmark vs. Hurst
and Robbins.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
