<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS FIND WINNING CURES ALL ILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets' clubhouse doors opened Friday afternoon and
the reporters thundering in were greeted with a loud cheer from the
Mets' players. The cheers weren't for the news media. They were for
Reggie Sanders, whose home run had just given Cincinnati a one-run
lead over the Chicago Cubs in their game at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   The roar subsided and the Mets started to prepare for their game
last evening with the Florida Marlins. But now there was a
clubhouse-wide groan: the Cubs' pitcher, Steve Trachsel, had
singled. Then there was a louder groan as Sanders misplayed a fly
ball that allowed a run to score. Later, Turk Wendell, a Mets'
relief pitcher, spotted another Reds fielding error on television
as he was having an impromptu chat with reporters. That was too
much for Wendell, who suddenly yelled, ``Pick it up with your bare
hand, moron!''
</P>
<P>
   This is what the roller-coaster clubhouse atmosphere of a fight
for the final playoff spot feels like. At certain junctures of the
season, the Mets seemed uncertain where they fit; indeed, whether
they belonged at all with playoff-caliber teams, or were still in
that infernal period of growth.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Mets find themselves running right with the Cubs and
Sammy Sosa in a desperate battle to be the National League
wild-card team. The controversy that dominated the team in
midseason _ the trade for Mike Piazza, the unhappiness of Todd
Hundley _ has been overwhelmed by the chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an open wound and now it's starting to heal,'' said
Lenny Harris, the Mets' right fielder. ``Everybody's starting to
contribute. Nobody's worrying about what's happening here or there;
everybody knows they have a job to do to help this ball club win.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it amazing what winning can do for a relationship? Three
months ago, Hundley felt estranged from his team. Meanwhile,
Piazza, who started the season as a Dodger, then became a Marlin
and then a Met, was being jeered by fans who viewed him as a
mercenary and didn't appreciate all the outs he was making with
runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Tony Phillips, who at 39 had one foot out of
baseball for half the season before suddenly returning and ending
up as the Mets' leadoff hitter. Now, with a little more than a week
to go in the season, Piazza, Hundley and Phillips are catalysts for
a surge that could push the Mets into the playoffs for the first
time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning makes it a lot more fun to come to the ball park,''
Hundley said before last night's game. ``It makes it a lot more
relaxed around the clubhouse when you're winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley has been through a lot this year and has lost a lot. But
a playoff surge turns winning players into good soldiers. Hundley
had surgery in the off season, saw his catching spot filled by
Piazza while he was still rehabilitating, saw a hail of fly balls
in an experiment in left field that ended in ruins. He has watched
the Mets prosper and has seen himself reduced to a backup at
catcher and a pinch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get this close you don't want to mess it up,'' he
said. ``You don't want anybody to mess it up. So you've got to take
on a different mentality, a different attitude. Team is everything
and your personal stuff doesn't matter: sacrifice, get the guy
over, get the guy in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning answers a lot of questions and stops a lot of
questions,'' Hundley added. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, who began his major league career 17 years ago, said
that a transformation has taken place in the Mets' clubhouse that
went beyond winning or losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can win and still have a screwed-up clubhouse,'' said
Phillips. ``The Yankees won for a lot of years, had great teams,
but they didn't have a good clubhouse so they didn't win back in
the 80's. This is a special clubhouse. I hadn't been in a clubhouse
like this since I left Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of caring here. Everybody's calling each other
out, keeping each other in check . . . that type of thing. The club
is policing itself without a lot of animosity. Everybody in this
clubhouse is on the same level from Mike Piazza, who is in a league
by himself, to the lowest guy on the totem pole.''
</P>
<P>
   So each Met is talking team. In a climate of free agency, with
uncertainty and little loyalty, pragmatism ultimately takes over.
But not now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wintertime is when this business turns into a $2
billion-a-year industry,''' Hundley said. ``That's when you got to
think about business. Right now, it's baseball. Play baseball, win,
get to the finish line. That's the bottom line. There have been
guys playing 20 years that don't get this close. When you're having
this kind of year, you don't want to mess it up, you want to treat
it like a diamond, like a baby. You want to take care of it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
