r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     09-18 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING BACK, '98 LOOKS SPECIAL INDEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the year 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire has retired to a house on a golf course he
designed, complete with a 360-yard par 3 and Andro Shots at the
19th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Cute little Matt McGwire has grown up, died his hair blue,
pierced a nostril and become spokesman for the anti-logging
movement, rejecting his father's achievements as ``lumber abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa has been elected president of the Dominican Republic
and overthrown by Jose Offerman, but shrugs it off in typical Sosa
good humor, saying, ``When it comes to being overthrown by
Offerman, Eric Karros is still The Man.''
</P>
<P>
   And the battle over Sosa home-run ball No. 62 is going to the
U.S. Supreme Court, where the swing vote is to be cast by Chief
Justice Fehr, an appointee of President Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   It's 10 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   When baseball's legion of historians look back at the 1998
season, how will they view it? As a quaint, innocent summer, to be
sure, one feel-good hit after another.
</P>
<P>
   As the greatest baseball season of them all? Oh, yeah, that too.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, considering it has produced only one close
division race _ and that American League West race might be (begin
ital)lost(end ital) by the Angels rather than (begin ital)won(end
ital) by the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, considering that in a year of further
expansion, under the most objective examination, the actual quality
of the average major-league ballplayer might be the lowest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe, considering it began with the sport's
executives still fretting over the effects of the 1994 World Series
cancellation and embarrassed by the sell-off of the 1997 World
Series champion Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe we should revise our standards.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as this might be to appreciate in Los Angeles, this
season has made more people across the country happy than any I can
remember. McGwire and Sosa have only been part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees will fall short of the 1906 Chicago Cubs'
116 victories, but by posting the major leagues' highest winning
percentage in 44 years with a team pleasantly devoid of superstars,
even the Yankees have been hard to hate.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the Cubs and the Boston Red Sox _ insert
``long-suffering'' in this sentence wherever you wish _ expect to
see both teams in postseason play for the first time since Boston's
Carl Mays outdueled Chicago's Lefty Tyler in game 6 of the 1918
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual continuity is demonstrated in the club standings, with
all six divisions led by 1996 or '97 division winners, and in the
individual leaderboard, where the right people are in front _ Ken
Griffey Jr., Juan Gonzalez, Alex Rodriguez, Roger Clemens, Larry
Walker, Tom Glavine, Kevin Brown, Greg Maddux, Curt Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention... the Randy Johnson resurrection... the Dennis
Eckersley farewell tour... the unanticipated fan-friendliness of
players who finally seem to (begin ital)get it(end ital)... and the
Dodgers' tumult, which has inspired greater mirth around the
country than L.A. fans will ever understand.
</P>
<P>
   And Cal Ripken Jr. is still going. Remember when he was the
single point of light in the baseball darkness?
</P>
<P>
   Now the darkness envelops the NFL, belted off its accustomed
place at the top of the sports pages on the first two Mondays of
the football season, and the NBA, should it still exist.
</P>
<P>
   You can compare one year to the next in baseball. The biggest
reason is that you can (begin ital)distinguish(end ital) one year
from the next.
</P>
<P>
   Try it in basketball: I say ``1979.'' Do you think of the year
of Dennis Johnson and the Seattle SuperSonics or the year of Magic
Johnson and the bearhug he threw around a stunned Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar on opening night? Same year, different seasons. Try it
in football: I say ``Heidi.'' That was 1968. I say ``Joe Namath.''
That was the 1969 _ Super Bowl III. Same season, different years.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fans don't need Roman numerals. I say, ``1968,'' you
think, ``pitching.'' I say, ``1978,'' you think, ``Bob Welch and
Reggie Jackson.'' I say, ``1988,'' you think, ``shoe polish and
Kirk Gibson.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward a decade.
</P>
<P>
   I say, ``1998.'' You say, ``Still the greatest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
