<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTAVERDE KNEW THIS MIGHT HAPPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ For months, Vinny Testaverde has believed that
at some point this season he would become the Jets' starting
quarterback _ either because of his ability or because of the real
possibility that Glenn Foley would be injured. After all, almost a
third of the National Football League's 30 starting quarterbacks
have already missed some playing time.
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to be a step closer to reality Friday as signs
continued to point to Testaverde's making his Jets debut at
quarterback against the Colts on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Foley has also practiced this week despite having painful torn
rib cartilage, but his effectiveness concerns Coach Bill Parcells.
Asked Friday about the lingering question of Foley's durability (he
had season-ending injuries in 1995 and last year), Parcells said:
``This isn't a test for Glenn Foley. His reputation has no effect
on me. Look, he doesn't want to be in this situation. I don't want
him to be in this situation. But he's in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who helped bring back the 1994 and 1996 New England
teams from an 0-2 start into the playoffs, must also make his
decision based on a league rule that is strict in limiting the play
of the third quarterback. Teams are permitted to dress two
quarterbacks and designate a third as an emergency. But if the
third quarterback comes in at any point before the fourth quarter,
then neither of the first two quarterbacks may return to the game
in any capacity. This rule is designed to allow a team to add an
extra man to the 46-man roster _ but only as the third quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is compounded for the Jets this week because
Parcells wants to use the Jets' third-string quarterback, Ray
Lucas, in his more prominent role as a fine special-teams
performer. Thus, Lucas has been listed as the No. 2 quarterback,
which has permitted him to play on the specials.
</P>
<P>
   But if Foley starts, then Parcells has said he would have to
list Testaverde as the second quarterback _ essentially taking
Lucas out of the game. In any event, Parcells said he would dress
all three quarterbacks on Sunday. But at this point it appears that
Foley will be the designated third quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Parcells admits that this has been an awful week for
him, after starting the season 0-2. ``You don't know whether you'll
ever win a game,'' he said. ``You stay at home. You go in the back
door of a restaurant so people don't see you.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity on Board for Colts
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Manning, the Colts' $48 million rookie quarterback, has
become such a larger-than-life figure in Indianapolis that the
team's president, Bill Polian, clears all of his speaking
engagements. The club's public relations department has been in
touch with the Broncos and Dolphins to determine how they handle
their celebrity quarterbacks, John Elway and Dan Marino. Some other
elements that make Manning, this year's overall No. 1 draft pick,
unusual:
</P>
<P>
   _ He is the Colts' 17th starting quarterback since they drafted
Elway in 1983 but were unsuccessful in signing him. Elway forced a
trade to the Broncos. Since the Broncos got Elway, only five other
quarterbacks have started for Denver.
</P>
<P>
   _ Manning attracted many fans who made the six-hour drive from
his college town of Knoxville, Tenn., to see his debut in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   _ Manning has the most interceptions in the NFL, six, after
having been the least-intercepted quarterback in Division I
history. He is being picked off once every 12 passes, compared to
once every 42 attempts at the University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Byars Starts at Fullback
</P>
<P>
   Keith Byars will return as the Jets' starting fullback for two
reasons: Jerald Sowell has been ineffective blocking for running
back Curtis Martin, and the team needs Sowell on kicking coverage.
It is part of the domino effect created by the loss of linebackers
Marvin Jones (for the season) and James Farrior (for at least two
games).
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major issues a lot of people don't understand is
that their loss has made us a little slower,'' Bill Parcells said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
