<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIEFS ON THE RICH AND BUSINESS MAGNATES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILLIONAIRE'S BASH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where Kennedys Once Played &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The oil billionaire DAVIDKOCH took the wraps off his newly
redecorated Fifth Avenue apartment, formerly owned by JACKIE
ONASSIS. And, the guest of honor was _ GEORGE BUSH. In rooms where
CAROLINE and JOHN JR. once played, Wall Streeters and former
Republican officials sipped Chateau Margaux and dined Friday on
gold-leaf china to honor one of Bush's favorite charities, the M.D.
Anderson Cancer Center in Houston. Tanned and fit, Bush asked:
``What do you do when you used to be president with the rest of
your life?'' His answer: ``Plug my causes,'' including charities
where ``I'm a big deal now.'' JOHN HENNESSY, chairman of CS First
Boston, and LIZ TILBERIS, editor of Harper's Bazaar, attended the
event as did BOB MOSBACHER, a former Commerce secretary; WALTER
CURLEY, a former ambassador to France, and JOSEPH ZAPPALA, a former
ambassador to Spain. Koch, who paid $9.5 million for the apartment
and spent three years redecorating it, quipped: ``If I knew what
Jackie's possessions would fetch at Sotheby's, I would have taken
the place furnished.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Wayne &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COSTLY GOOF? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Computing an Options Grant &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES B. WANG, the chief executive of Computer Associates, has
been under fire since May, when he and two aides were paid 20.25
million shares of the company, based in Islandia, N.Y. The stock
was worth $1.1 billion, but the price fell 30 percent a few days
later. Now the three executives and four company directors face a
novel accusation in Delaware Chancery Court.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Sanders, a shareholder, says the plan that shareholders
approved in 1995 authorizing up to six million shares for Wang and
the executives SANJAY KUMAR and RUSSELL M. ARTZT had no provision
to adjust for stock splits. The suit reasons that awards made after
1995 must be on presplit terms, and demands 9.5 million shares
back.
</P>
<P>
   So did Wang make a costly goof that will force him to give back
nearly half of his 12.15 million shares? Not according to Bob
Gordon, Wang's spokesman; he says the lawsuit by the Tenzer
Greenblatt firm in Manhattan lacks merit. David Cay Johnston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NANTUCKET WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Invasion of the Land Snatchers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The transmutation of Nantucket from quaint redoubt of East Coast
Wasps to summer playroom of the famously rich continues apace with
a new round of eyebrow-elevating real estate transactions.
</P>
<P>
   H. WAYNE HUIZENGA, the billionaire financier and owner of the
Florida Marlins, paid $7.5 million last month for a six-bedroom
house on the water. ROGER PENSKE, transportation magnate and auto
racing team owner, plans to build a 9,300-square-foot home on two
dozen acres he bought for $6.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   FRANK and KATHY LEE GIFFORD spent a comparatively modest $1.44
million for a 250-year-old house. Less recent arrivals include
TOMMY HILFIGER, who paid $4.6 million two years ago for a house not
far from one owned by RICHARD MELLON SCAIFE, the Mellon banking
fortune heir and bankroller of conservative causes.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that BILL GATES is shopping around appear to have no
foundation. But as one town official said: ``As soon as someone is
seen on the island, there is a whole lot of speculation about what
he's doing here: Is he here just to play golf or to buy half the
island?''
</P>
<P>
   Janny Scott &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BITS AND PIECES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of Prints, Propriety and Property &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAVE WILLIAMS, chairman of Alliance Capital, and his wife, REBA,
are adding 18th century work by the Peale family of Philadelphia to
their 6,000-piece collection of early American prints. The couple
paid just under $50,000 for a Charles Wilson Peale museum ticket
and the plate from which it was made. ... RICHARD BRANSON, the
billionaire owner of the Virgin business empire, is now marketing a
stripped-down version of himself. In the past, he has appeared in
outlandish costumes, including a wedding dress, to peddle his
products. Now, he is appearing in ads in British newspapers in the
buff, except for a strategically placed newspaper, to promote
``Losing My Virginity _ the Autobiography.'' ... MOSSIMO GIANNULLI,
the California designer whose net worth has declined by a
half-billion dollars or so as his company's stock price nose-dived,
has been unloading property in California, including his
curved-concrete Laguna Beach bluff home to a New Jersey trust last
month for close to $3.5 million and an undeveloped five-acre site
near Newport Beach for nearly $12 million, a local real estate
agent said. ... RUPERT MURDOCH, the News Corp. chairman who is
divorcing his wife ANNA, has put his Beverly Hills estate on the
block for $19.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
