<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BREEDERS-COUNTDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTDOWN TO BREEDERS' CUP PITS HORSES IN BIG RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty of the best race horses in the country will
gather at Belmont Park on Saturday for three races _ the Woodward
Stakes, the Ruffian and the Jerome _ in a countdown to the
Breeders' Cup that will match contenders against champions. And, in
a sequel Sunday, 11 star 2-year-olds will meet in two Grade I
stakes _ the Matron and the Futurity _ that will cast long shadows
into next year's Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's stakes are dominated by the small but
distinguished cast entered in the 45th running of the Woodward, a
Grade I event billed as ``the race of the year'' with a purse of
$500,000 and a field of five running one mile and an eighth. The
favorite is Skip Away, the gray champion who has earned $9.2
million and who enters the race with a winning streak of eight. He
has not lost in a year since Formal Gold outran him in the 44th
Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   But Skip Away will be racing for the 36th time in a career that
has run nonstop for four years, and the experts keep looking for
signs of wear. In his last start, he ran with damaged front feet in
the Iselin Handicap at Monmouth Park last month and won by a nose
in a race that he was expected to dominate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went through all of that and still kept winning,'' said
Sonny Hine, who trains Skip Away for his wife, Carolyn. ``That's
how tough a horse he is.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Woodward, Skip Away will have to withstand a dream field
of Free House, who ran in the money in all three races in last
year's Triple Crown; Gentlemen, who has won $3 million, and
Coronado's Quest, the 3-year-old son of Forty Niner, who has won
his last five starts, including the Wood, Haskell and Travers. The
fifth starter is the English 4-year-old Running Stag, described by
his trainer, Frank Mitchell, as ``the best dirt horse in the United
Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ruffian Handicap, the race that precedes the Woodward, has a
field of nine fillies racing a mile and a sixteenth for a purse of
$250,000. It also comes with a superstar: Sharp Cat, the 4-year-old
daughter of Storm Cat, who won the Acorn at Belmont last year and
has won three straight this year since running second in the
Breeders' Cup Distaff.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp Cat's chief rivals figure to be Stop Traffic, who won the
Ballerina at Saratoga last month, and Colonial Minstrel, who got
roughed up in the starting gate and finished fifth, although she
won five in a row earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of horses that may go with her,'' said
Wally Dollase, Sharp Cat's trainer. ``But that will just push her
on and make her more competitive. She's thriving here. I've never
seen her eat so well. Her coat looks nice, she loves Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   The day's third stakes race, the 130th running of the Jerome
Handicap, will take six 3-year-old colts one mile, most of which
may be spent trying to catch Secret Firm, who will be running for
his seventh straight victory. But his tactical speed will be
challenged by Scatmandu, Dice Dancer and Grand Slam, who won the
Futurity, Champagne and Peter Pan over the Belmont track.
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the dispute over in-home betting seemed to be in a
stare-down. The New York Racing Association, which stopped sending
television pictures of its races to the homes of Off-Track Betting
clients in New York City on July 22, was waiting for the next move
by the city OTB, which on Thursday won permission to bring in races
from out of state. But, there has been no action from the NYRA,
which could also pull the plug on OTB offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
