<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-GOV-RACE-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR CANDIDATE STRUGGLES TO EXPLAIN HER SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ U.S. Rep. Barbara Kennelly held a solidarity
lunch Friday to call attention to the novel presence of four women
on the Democrats' statewide ticket, but wound up trying to explain
her campaign's steep slide despite an ever-more-aggressive style.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly, the Democratic candidate for governor of
Connecticut, joked that in ``the year of El Nino,'' even the most
predictable phenomena are subject to drastic change. Nevertheless,
she acknowledged that her race against Gov. John Rowland has become
even more uphill than she had realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very strange year,'' Mrs. Kennelly said, referring
to the turmoil in Washington and to Connecticut voters' apparent
satisfaction with the status quo. ``It's a very strange time. It
has not been a fun time for me. But I know I ran for the right
reasons, and I know I would be an excellent governor.''
</P>
<P>
   The reflective reference to her campaign was a sign of the speed
and decisiveness of the reversal in her political fortunes. When
Mrs. Kennelly (pronounced ken-NELL-lee) entered the race a year
ago, polls showed her in a dead heat with Rowland, who at 41 is the
United States' youngest governor.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the University of Connecticut released a poll showing
that Rowland was leading by 37 percentage points. If every
undecided voter in the poll switched to Mrs. Kennelly, she would
still lose by 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly's quest now becomes a test of whether a political
campaign can be salvaged in the final weeks when voters are paying
the most attention. Pointing to this week's Democratic Senate
primary in New York as an example that political perception is not
always borne out, she said: ``If you've seen my friend Geraldine
Ferraro, she was way up there. Guess what? She didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly, 62, whose Hartford-area seat is one of the most
reliably Democratic in Congress, is the widow of a lion of state
Democratic politics, James Kennelly, who was speaker of the state
House of Representatives, and the daughter of a former chairman of
the Democratic National Committee, John Bailey. Her decision to run
was greeted with euphoria by Connecticut Democrats who thought she
had the stature to undermine Rowland's formidable position.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Kennelly emerged from a diner Friday with the other
three women on the ticket, she was peppered again and again with
variations of one question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Mrs. Kennelly said. ``I don't know. I have
worked so hard all my life _ all my public life _ to absolutely
promote education for all young people. I ran for governor because
I thought every child in Connecticut should be protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly said she planned to begin television advertising
next week. Rowland has spent $1 million to broadcast six
advertisements over the last year characterizing his stewardship in
images of warmth and success. Mrs. Kennelly's aides admit that they
expect to be outspent 4-to-1 on television, but contend that voters
will move toward her after they hear her story. ``We have not yet
begun to fight,'' said her campaign manager, Jonathan Pelto.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who served four years in Congress with Mrs. Kennelly,
discusses her respectfully but increasingly dismissively. Asked
Friday about complaints by Mrs. Kennelly's aides that he had an
``obscene'' lead in fund raising, Rowland said: ``I understand
their frustration, but I didn't tell her to get in the race. It was
her idea. Let the chips fall where they may.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Just two hours before what Mrs. Kennelly's campaign had billed
as a ``historic'' strategy session among the most women ever to run
together on a state slate, one of her running mates indicated that
with such a bleak outlook at the top of the ticket, it was going to
be every candidate for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Wyman, who is seeking re-election as the state
comptroller, refused to criticize Rowland when asked to during the
taping of ``CT '98,'' a political talk show to be broadcast Sunday
on WFSB-TV, Channel 3, the CBS affiliate in Hartford. ``My message
is what I have accomplished and what I have done,'' she said. Ms.
Wyman also said, ``Barbara Kennelly has not gotten the message out
_ yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two women on her ticket _ Denise Nappier, the
Democratic nominee for state treasurer, and state Rep. Susan
Bysiewicz, who is running for secretary of the state _ promised
Friday to use their energetic styles to help Mrs. Kennelly.
</P>
<P>
   Seeming to gain grit by having the three three female running
mates at her side, Mrs. Kennelly discussed her plight in feisty but
bald terms. ``I hate the poll today,'' she said. ``But I'm going on
television, and I am going to fight right to the day of election.
And it is not over. It is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   The importance of television advertising was underscored in the
fine print of the poll released Friday by the University of
Connecticut, which showed that fewer people claimed to know Mrs.
Kennelly than did so the last time the poll was taken, in June.
That can be seen as an opportunity for Mrs. Kennelly, since 50
percent of people said they did not know enough to rate her, while
just 14 percent made that claim about Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   Those polled said they preferred Rowland to Mrs. Kennelly by 60
percent to 23 percent, with 17 percent undecided. The telephone
poll of 505 Connecticut residents was conducted Saturday through
Wednesday and had a margin of error of plus or minus five
percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
