<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-COLISEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES AGAINST ISLANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York state judge Friday denied a request by the
New York Islanders to secure dates for home games at arenas other
than Nassau Coliseum. Supreme Court Justice Burton Joseph directed
the team to follow his ruling on Thursday that ordered the
Islanders to play their exhibition and home games at the Coliseum,
which is in Uniondale.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Islanders and SMG, the company that maintains the
Coliseum, were ordered by Joseph to appear in court next Wednesday
for a hearing on a preliminary injunction.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a lawsuit filed by the Islanders alleging unsafe
conditions at the 26-year-old building. The Islanders moved out of
the Coliseum a week ago, citing uninhabitable conditions and
alleging in the lawsuit that the hoist which holds up the 21-ton
scoreboard and speaker system is in danger of falling. The $10
million lawsuit also alleges that SMG knew of the unsafe status of
the hoist for several months without notifying the Islanders or
Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going on the assumption that the Islanders will be
playing at the Coliseum next Friday,'' said SMG president Wes
Westley, who added that the hoist is scheduled to be replaced.
</P>
</TEXT>
