<HEADER>
A3729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BIG-APPLE-CIRCUS-A     09-18 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BIG-APPLE-CIRCUS-ART-470(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CIRCUS THAT CAME TO TOWN, AND STAYED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(js) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALDEN, N.Y. _ ``Here's the town the circus came to, when it
came to town,'' said Darren Hernandez, the village manager of this
postage stamp-size community straddling the Wallkill River in the
Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled with satisfaction. ``And then it decided to stay,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 12586, the Walden ZIP code, is the first permanent address
of the Big Apple Circus, a 21-year-old icon of street-smart
entertainment that is celebrated for pitching its one-ring tent in
the urban wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The circus' new home is far from Gotham _ nearly 70 miles to the
north, actually _ in a former wire-extruding factory on 30 woodsy
acres. In a cavernous, 50,000-square-foot industrial space, the
circus has created a place to mount its new shows.
</P>
<P>
   So this all-American Orange County village, trumpeted as ``the
Sheffield of America'' for its knife manufacturing before the
factories closed, has been learning to live with an exotic,
extravagantly international invasion of more than 100 circus
tummlers, tumblers and big-top eccentrics, not to mention three
elephants, 27 dogs, eight horses and eight parakeets.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, a few residents who have made it known
that they think Big Apple should be contributing more to Walden's
diminished local tax base. Economic development aside, though, few
people would disagree that the arrival of the circus has done
wonders for Walden's self-esteem, which suffered mightily not long
ago when a radio shock jock from the other side of the Hudson
decided to make the village the butt of a bizarre guerrilla war of
the airwaves. The circus people might be a bit odd, but any
discomfort along those lines tends to pale against being known in
radioland as New York's version of Dogpatch.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, village residents say they have grown
accustomed to the sight of a dozen Chinese acrobats carrying off
35-pound bags of rice from the supermarket, to encounters with
juggling troupes in the laundermat and to glimpses of elephants and
horses taking their exercise.
</P>
<P>
   But grocery schleppers in the Thruway Shopping Center, near the
circus headquarters, still do a double take when they catch sight
of Bello Nock, the Big Apple's star clown, with his four-inch-high,
er, platform of stiffly sprayed reddish-blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he said, ``they ask to touch it.'' He lets them.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we were concerned that they'd be carnival types, who
are pretty tough,'' said June DeBates, a waitress at the Walden
Diner. ``But we learned that circus people are really the salt of
the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hecht, a Walden tow-truck operator who has come to the aid
of Big Apple vehicles, put it this way: ``You know how some people
have dogs in their backyards? Well, these people have elephants.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of other stuff, too. While the clowny red-and-white
tent on Edmunds Lane is visible to any of the 6,500 townsfolk who
drive by, hidden away on the property is a tiny circus village of
40 house trailers and dozens of vehicles, including cars, trucks,
generator vans and the communal dining trailer that serves more
than 300 meals a day. Behind the old factory, the performers have
arrayed their mobile homes in a tidy grid of brand-new streets.
</P>
<P>
   This is the troupe's first season in the fully renovated $4
million building, although Big Apple first began leasing space in
Walden in 1995 before buying the factory last year.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades ``we'd been creating the show under primitive
conditions,'' said Paul Binder, Big Apple's 55-year-old founder and
artistic director. The first performances of the fledgling circus
in 1977 were mounted in the tiny Synod House at the Cathedral of
St. John the Divine in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Big Apple shuffled off to makeshift rehearsal spaces in
Manhattan and Floyd Bennett Field in Brooklyn, ``where helicopters
took off in the middle of the night and the Concorde swooped over
us twice a day,'' said Katja Schumann, the show's star equestrian.
``Now that was noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by high city prices, and guided by a circus friend of
Binder who trains bears and lives in nearby Middletown, Big Apple
found Walden, where lower-priced properties were available.
</P>
<P>
   The compound has five indoor practice spaces and workshops to
restore the show's equipment, which takes a beating when the show
is on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever we traveled, we were always at home in the ring
surrounded by the family of the circus,'' said Michael Christensen,
creative director. ``But now, for the first time, we can feel at
home in a place.''
</P>
<P>
   Around Walden, the feeling is mostly mutual. ``They've been good
neighbors, and Big Apple has been a good thing for Walden,'' said
Carl Aiello, editor and publisher of the local weekly, The Wallkill
Valley Times.
</P>
<P>
   For several years now, Big Apple has lent its performers to the
annual Walden Day celebration. And it has welcomed as many as 1,500
of its neighbors to its annual open house. When new shows are
ready, the circus also holds a dress rehearsal for 500 guests, many
of them suppliers and area residents.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Walden's redemption from that nasty business
with the disk jockey, Bob Wohlfeld, a.k.a. ``the Wolf,'' who made
the village the target of several years' worth of jokes on his
radio show. Despite complaints to the radio station, WPDH in
Poughkeepsie, and threats against Wohlfeld, the assault on Walden's
reputation subsided only a year ago, when Wohlfeld left for an
Albany station.
</P>
<P>
   If Walden's reputation is on the rebound, its economy had
already been doing a bit better when the circus settled in. It is a
hub for the region's dairy and apple farmers and has a mix of
manufacturing, retail and service businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a vocal minority is resentful that the circus, which
enjoys nonprofit status because of its children's educational
programs, is likely to remove a building that once represented the
village's sixth-largest source of property tax income from the
local, county and school district tax rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not opposed to circuses _ why, I even went to the circus
in Moscow a few years ago,'' said David Lustig Jr., 76, the owner
of Lustig Realty on Main Street and a longtime member of the
village Planning Board. ``But that building could have accommodated
another industrial plant.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Big Apple is still paying $45,000 in annual real estate
taxes to the Town of Montgomery, Binder said, although the circus
has challenged the payment under its tax-exempt status. Besides, he
said, ``the factory had been closed for years,'' adding, ``There
was little hope of reviving the site.''
</P>
<P>
   Lustig is hardly the only circus critic in Walden. ``Given their
tax-exempt status, the least they could do for the town is to put
on a show for us,'' said Frank Ciliberto, owner of a plumbing and
heating business. ``Big Apple travels all over the country, but
their hometown never gets to see the show.''
</P>
<P>
   The invitation-only dress rehearsal is limited to 500 because
Big Apple does not have parking spaces for enough guests to fill
the 1,980-seat tent, Binder said. But beyond this, the circus
people say, the point is that they aren't in Walden to entertain;
they are there to build new shows.
</P>
<P>
   And so, in one of the rehearsal spaces on a recent afternoon,
under the harsh factory lights, Todd Robbins, the comedic soloist
with the seven-member circus band, was giving a virtuoso
performance on washboard, cowbell, klaxon, duck call and, at one
point, the Knall 9-millimeter starter pistol. Robbins explained
that he is capable ``of the full range from high hokum to the
lowest form of hokum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
