u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-SCHOOLBUS-CRASH-NY     09-18 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SCHOOLBUS-CRASH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL BUS COLLIDES WITH TRUCK, INJURING 7 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa.)   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLMDEL, N.J. _ A school bus and a three-ton dump truck loaded
with topsoil collided at a busy intersection here this morning,
critically injuring the driver of the bus and one of the six
students aboard, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   With horn blaring and brakes squealing, the truck slammed into
the left front end of the bus about 7:20 a.m. as the bus was about
to turn from eastbound Route 520 onto northbound Route 34. During
the turn, the bus driver, Deirdre Pietrowski, 26, of Old Bridge,
N.J., was facing the rising sun, and the police are exploring
whether she was momentarily blinded by the glare and went through a
red light at the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may have been a contributing factor,'' Sgt. Donald Hughes
of the Holmdel police said of the possibility that Ms. Pietrowski
was unable to see the light or the truck bearing down on the bus
from her left.
</P>
<P>
   The crash occurred moments after Al Taylor, an auto mechanic,
arrived for work at Holmdel Auto Body, which is at the
intersection. He said he heard the truck's brakes screeching, a
blow from its horn, and then the crash. He ran toward the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids were screaming and hollering to get out,'' Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pietrowski was driving the six students, 7 to 16 years old,
from their homes in nearby Colts Neck to St. John Vianney High
School and an adjacent elementary school, St. Benedict's. Her trip
this morning was only her third over the route, said David Armitt,
a regional general manager of Laidlaw Transit, the owner of the
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they believed that one or more of the
children were helping to direct her to the schools, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw Transit hired Ms. Pietrowski as a part-time driver last
Tuesday, Armitt said. Previously, he said, Ms. Pietrowski had
worked as a bus driver from 1992 to 1997 for the Pocono Mountain
School District in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Usually, about 30 children, most of them students at St. John
Vianney, ride the bus each morning, said the school principal,
Joseph Deroba. Hughes said the previous bus driver usually arrived
at least 15 minutes late each morning. He said Ms. Pietrowski was
on schedule Friday and at least 24 students missed the bus.
</P>
<P>
   The critically injured student, Kyle DeRespinis, 7, was flown
from the crash site on a medical evacuation helicopter to Robert
Wood Johnson Hospital in New Brunswick. He had severe head and neck
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The other injured students were identified as Kyle's sister,
Kristen, 13; Ashley Merrigan, 16; Rebecca Stuart, 15; Emily Hodges,
no age available; and Sal Foran, 13, who suffered a broken
collarbone. Kristen DeRespinis was in satisfactory condition at the
Jersey Shore Medical Center in Neptune. All the other students were
treated at hospitals and released.
</P>
<P>
   The driver's compartment was crushed on impact and Ms.
Pietrowski suffered severe head injuries. She was taken to Jersey
Shore Medical Center, and the police had been unable to question
her as of late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, Michael Cherence, 22, of Cliffwood, N.J., was
not injured, even though the truck flipped over after hitting the
bus. Police said he had told them he had a green light as he
approached the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Police questioned several motorists who witnessed the crash but
declined to say if they had confirmed Cherence's account. Hughes
said investigators were looking into the possibility that Cherence
was speeding as he came down an incline of about 170 yards toward
the bus.
</P>
<P>
   The posted speed limit on that stretch of Route 34, a busy
north-south thoroughfare, is 50 miles an hour. But Hughes said
loaded construction vehicles, like Cherence's, are limited to 35
miles an hour on that stretch of road.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, Cherence was given three summonses for
speeding or reckless driving in New Jersey, Hughes said. Ms.
Pietrowski has one moving violation in the last eight years, he
said. Neither driver was given a summons Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said accidents are fairly common at the intersection.
``We're used to hearing beeping and screeching,'' he said. ``It's a
bad intersection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
