</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AMERICORPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PUNISHING AMERICORPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Sept. 19:
</P>
<P>
   Americorps is one of President Clinton's pet projects and thus a
tempting target for congressional Republicans looking for ways to
humiliate Clinton and gain a bargaining chip in budget negotiations
with the weakened White House. But GOP lawmakers risk looking
shabby if they persist in playing politics with the future of this
worthy, four-year-old volunteer program.
</P>
<P>
   Americorps members perform a host of needed tasks to help
strengthen communities, providing tutoring and mentoring for
thousands of at-risk children, for example, and working with local
nonprofit groups to restore blighted neighborhoods and clean up the
environment. The program will field some 40,000 members this year,
making it five times the size of the Peace Corps. Members receive a
modest stipend of about $8,000 and a $4,725 voucher to help pay
education costs in exchange for one year of full-time service.
</P>
<P>
   Much as Clinton promised, Americorps is a good deal for the
nation and for its workers. But while the Senate has approved
continuing the program's current $425.5-million funding level in
the next fiscal year, the House eliminates all funding. That leaves
resolution of the issue to a conference committee and the vagaries
of political horse-trading.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton should remain ready to wield his veto pen, if necessary,
to preserve his program. Americorps can show tangible
accomplishments in all 50 states and has earned renewal without a
messy and demoralizing fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
