<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-18 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HMO-MALPRACTICE     09-18 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HMO-MALPRACTICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIXED VERDICT ON TEXAS HMO LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A provision in a new Texas law allowing patients to sue
health maintenance organizations and other insurers for malpractice
was upheld Friday by a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   But a second provision, allowing patients to appeal to an
independent panel when their employee health plan decides treatment
is unnecessary, was struck down.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, from Judge Vanessa Gilmore of U.S. District Court in
Houston, came in a lawsuit filed last year against the Texas
Department of Insurance by Aetna Life Insurance Co. and its Texas
subsidiaries. The suit challenged a state law that was passed that
May and took effect last September. It was the first law in the
nation that expressly gave patients the right to sue insurers over
quality-of-care decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides hailed Friday's decision as at least a partial
victory and said they had not decided whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for patients and it upholds in the main the
Texas statute,'' said David Mattax, an assistant Texas attorney
general.
</P>
<P>
   But Elton Bomer, the state's insurance commissioner, said he was
not pleased that the ruling eliminated the appeals provision for
most Texas patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are the losers, because they will be denied access
to the independent review process, which has been working very well
in Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bomer said he hoped the attorney general would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, in a written statement, also said it was ``very pleased''
with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   How much national significance the ruling will have is unclear.
Congress is considering federal legislation that could open
insurers to more suits or require independent reviews of decisions
denying coverage for treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
