<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WORKFARE-NYT &LR;      09-18 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WORKFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BACKS GIULIANI'S WAY OF ASSIGNING HOURS FOR WORKFARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state appeals court has upheld the way New York
City calculates the number of hours that welfare recipients must
work in its workfare program to receive benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The state Appellate Division in Manhattan, in a ruling released
on Thursday, overturned a lower court decision that said the city's
method of calculation, which is based on the minimum wage, was
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Giuliani administration created its version of
workfare in 1995, city officials have been calculating
participants' hours so that their benefits are roughly equal to the
minimum wage, $5.15 an hour. A welfare recipient who receives the
equivalent of $100 a week in benefits, for example, must work about
20 hours a week in workfare.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for several workfare participants challenged the city's
approach in court. In May 1997, Justice Jane Solomon of state
Supreme Court ruled that the city must base its calculations on
what it pays regular city workers for similar tasks, as much as $8
to $10 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   More than 32,000 New Yorkers are enrolled in workfare, known
formally as the Work Experience Program. Most of them sweep city
streets, clean parks or perform clerical tasks in return for their
welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for workfare participants had praised Ms. Solomon's
ruling as a breakthrough that might mean workfare participants
would be treated more like other workers. They also said that if
the ruling was upheld the city would either have to reduce sharply
the number of hours workfare participants put in each week or
increase welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But in its unanimous decision, the Appellate Division noted that
state law specifically authorizes paying the minimum wage to
workfare participants. ``Moreover, there is a historical
recognition that public-assistance recipients performing tasks in
exchange for benefits are not public employees,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Levine, the deputy mayor for economic development, praised
the decision Friday. ``It's a very sound ruling, a common-sense
ruling, because it recognizes what the mayor has been saying for a
long time: Welfare is a temporary situation, unionization is a
permanent situation,'' Levine said.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Cohan, the lawyer for the workfare participants, could not
be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In another court ruling on workfare, a state judge has
temporarily blocked the city's Human Resources Administration,
which oversees welfare, from changing its rules determining which
welfare recipients enrolled in college can be ordered into
workfare.
</P>
<P>
   The city agency recently decided that welfare recipients
enrolled in college work-study programs _ some of whom had been
exempt from workfare _ would now have to participate. Lawyers for
welfare recipients challenged the new rule, and on Wednesday,
Justice Richard Braun of state Supreme Court issued a preliminary
injunction against the city. Braun said the city must individually
assess students' skills and work history before assigning them to
workfare.
</P>
<P>
   The city will appeal the decision, said Debra Sproles, a
spokeswoman for the city agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
