<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAVERS EYE UPSET OF TROJANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC coach Paul Hackett walked around the practice
field the other day with a piece of paper in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Always an excellent monitor of Internet information, Hackett
finally pulled out the article, which picked Oregon State as an
``upset special'' selection over the Trojans tonight at the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett's good-natured reaction to the prediction indicated that
it was nothing more than a well-timed source of motivational
material for his team.
</P>
<P>
   But considering how USC has fared in recent Pacific-10
Conference openers, anything that can be used to inspire his
players should be utilized.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are just 4-4 in Pac-10 openers in the 1990s, and few
teams with Rose Bowl aspirations can afford to lose their first
conference game to an outmanned opponent.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a caveat. Only one of those opening games was
against Oregon State, which has become an institution of ineptitude
when playing the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   USC has not lost to the Beavers since 1967, a span of 24 games.
In fact, Oregon State has rarely beaten anybody recently. The
Beavers last had a winning season in 1970, and are 60-233-6 in the
previous 27 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure none of this information was relayed to the
Trojans by Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter who we're playing, and by that I'm
not being disrespectful at all,'' Hackett said. ``Our first issue
is that we have to be efficient and take care of our business.
Oregon State is a confident team, they're pumped up, but we can't
worry about history.''
</P>
<P>
   The simple truth is that this game is the finale of a three-game
stretch where Hackett tries to smooth out all the problems before
taking USC to Florida State next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hackett admitted that he still hasn't been around the
Trojans long enough to gauge his team's mood heading into a game,
just in case he has to guard against a letdown or looking past an
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's too early right now,'' Hackett said. ``I think
we've got to have more adversity before I know how we'll respond.''
</P>
<P>
   That should come next week.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Hackett is reminding USC that a loss to Oregon
State tonight is probably more devastating than a loss to Florida
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more important to beat Oregon State because it's in the
conference,'' Hackett said. ``It's more important than the other
two games (Purdue, San Diego State) because the goal is the Rose
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   That means eliminating penalties, avoiding missed tackles and
missed pass plays, according to Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   It also means that the Trojans will continue their
two-quarterback rotation, with freshman Carson Palmer possibly
getting a series or two in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans also need to try to stay healthy. Five starters
(Chad Morton, Antoine Harris, Lawrence Larry, Grant Pearsall, Mark
Cusano) are nursing minor injuries and will not be in the opening
lineup. The team's top two centers (Matt McShane, Eric Denmon) are
out and left guard Jason Grain will start in their place. David
Pratchard of Canyon High School will start at left guard for Grain.
</P>
<P>
   Although second-year Beavers coach Mike Riley, a former USC
assistant, has begun rebuilding the Oregon State program, victories
over Nevada and Baylor probably don't warrant consideration for
pulling off an upset.
</P>
<P>
   Even Riley has tried to downplay the Beavers' best start in 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a couple good games, not great, but solid,'' Riley
said. ``We're not a juggernaut on offense, but we haven't made
mistakes and only taken a couple of sacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense is a totally revamped group from the one USC shut
out 23-0 last year in Corvallis. The newest additions are
quarterback Terrance Bryant, a junior-college All-American, who has
passed for more than 200 yards in each of the first two games.
There is also a new tailback, redshirt freshman Ken Simonton, who
has rushed for more than 100 yards in each game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing less-than-imposing competition, it's still worth
something when the Beavers can boast such stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our offense had a terrible running game last year. In
order to get better, we had to turn that around,'' Riley said.
``We've been efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Strong safety Grant Pearsall (strained knee) and
linebacker Mark Cusano (sprained ankle) expect to play sparingly
against Oregon State and fully return for the Florida State game.
``It's not worse, it's definitely better,'' Cusano said regarding
his ankle. ``I'm playing tentative on it now, not at full
speed.''... Freshman quarterback Jason Thomas has undergone surgery
to remove scar tissue around his ankle and has begun
rehabilitation.... Defensive end Lawrence Larry tweaked his
sprained ankle and is listed as possible. Freshman Lonnie Ford will
start at tight end, with starter Antoine Harris limited by a
sprained ankle.... A crowd of about 50,000 is expected for
tonight's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
