<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CUBS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA AND THE CUBS LACK PUNCH IN A LOSS TO THE REDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When Sammy Sosa and the Chicago Cubs left Wrigley
Field last weekend for the West Coast, Sosa had just tied Mark
McGwire in their home-run race by belting four in the three-game
series against Milwaukee, and the Cubs had staged two dramatic
come-from-behind victories.
</P>
<P>
   In their return home on Friday, Sosa and the Cubs lacked last
weekend's flair. Sosa went 0-for-4 in a 6-4 loss to the Cincinnati
Reds, and the Cubs managed just six hits, without a home run, let
alone any late-inning heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's performance, in front of more than 40 family members whom
the Cubs had flown in from the Dominican Republic as a surprise,
left him one behind Mark McGwire, who has 64 after homering in the
fourth inning Friday night against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa never hit the ball out of the infield even as 40,105 fans,
on their feet, chanted ``Sammy, Sammy'' and ``MVP'' during each of
his at-bats. He did reach base and scored a run in the first inning
after hitting a checked-swing grounder that second baseman Bret
Boone booted. Sosa then grounded out to third in the second inning,
struck out in the fifth inning after battling to a full count, and
popped out to Boone in the seventh. He was left in the on-deck
circle when the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   It was Reds shortstop Barry Larkin and left fielder Dmitri Young
who stole the show. Young was 4-for-4 with two RBIs, and his diving
catch on Micky Morandini's sinking line drive in the sixth inning
kept the Cubs from tying the score. It also ended the inning and
prevented Sosa from coming to the plate with two runners on. Young
then led off the seventh with a single and scored a run, putting
the Cubs away for good. Larkin was 4-for-5 with a double and a home
run, and he scored two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The loss drops the Cubs' lead over the Mets in the wild-card
race to just a half-game, with the Mets playing Friday night. The
two teams, whose play and dramatic games have mirrored each other
the last couple of weeks, have not been separated by more than one
game in the standings since Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Though fruitless on Friday, hundreds of ticketless fans again
flocked to Waveland Avenue, just past Wrigley's left-field wall, in
anticipation of a potentially lucrative home-run ball. Following
Sosa's two-homer game last Sunday, during which a fan claimed he
had possession of home-run ball No. 62 but lost it after being
bitten and mauled during the scramble for it, the Chicago police
have added officers and erected barricades for this series,
corralling the fans onto one sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's game, a collector who paid a fan $10,000 for
home-run ball No. 61 returned the ball to Sosa in exchange for some
of Sosa's autographed equipment. Sosa said after the game he
intended to donate the ball to the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   And despite recent criticism that major-league baseball was not
giving Sosa the same attention that McGwire receives, Sosa said he
felt plenty of support from fans everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are what motivate me every day,'' he said after the
game. ``The support here in Chicago and all over the country has
been wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   He then gave a parting word of encouragement to McGwire, his
friend and fellow slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't hit one every day,'' Sosa said before heading home to
celebrate his son's sixth birthday. ``I'm just going to go home and
relax with my family and watch Mark. I hope he hits one tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
