<HEADER>
A3766 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN     09-18 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON'S FATE ON ROPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson will learn today whether he's been
forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada State Athletic Commission will decide after a hearing
whether to restore the fighter's boxing license 15 months after he
bit off a portion of Evander Holyfield's ear.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe his chances aren't good, particularly after he was
accused of punching one man and kicking another after a traffic
accident last month in Gaithersburg, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the hearing took place before the incident, I would have
said he had a good chance. Now, I don't think so,'' said promoter
Bob Arum, who lives in Las Vegas and is familiar with the
five-member commission that will decide Tyson's fate.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson's application is rejected, he could reapply next
September.
</P>
<P>
   However, it appears he wouldn't wait that long. Shelly Finkel,
Tyson's adviser, said he will explore other options _ including
numerous offers from outside the country _ if he can't fight in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets his license, Finkel said, Tyson will fight before the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he isn't licensed, he has to earn a living and depending
what it is, of course, we'd consider other options,'' Finkel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only concern now is Saturday. Hopefully, Saturday, it's a
fair hearing, it's a tough hearing, Mike stands up to what it is
and they do something that's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, 32, was eligible to reapply for a license in June, a year
after his fight with Holyfield. However, his advisers apparently
believed he would have a better chance to be granted a license in
New Jersey and applied with that commission. That angered Nevada
officials and could work against him today.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing there, he lost his composure _ which raised further
questions about his ability to control his temper. Political
pressure began to build against him to a point where it seemed he
would be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   So he and his team returned to the scene of the crime and
applied there.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Nevada commission allowed him to reapply for his
license after a year to give him a chance to prove he could be a
good citizen.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, he saw a therapist regularly and generally behaved
himself. However, the incident in Maryland could haunt him: If it
happened as Tyson's alleged victims say it did, it seems to
indicate the troubled fighter hasn't progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson denies that he attacked the two men. And Finkel said it
should have no bearing on the case, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say they don't license him as a result of that and he
fights it all the way. And he's cleared in two years, it's proved
he's innocent. Do you think he should be denied the right to make a
living for two years?'' Finkel said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's mission isn't complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The former champion refused to comment at a luncheon to honor
one of the commissioners on Thursday but will testify today. He and
his handlers will attempt to demonstrate he is remorseful over the
ear-biting incident and that it will never happen again.
</P>
<P>
   They'll also try to use financial hardship as leverage: He has
limited liquid assets and the IRS has several liens against
property he owns, Finkel said.
</P>
<P>
   Finkel said emphatically that his client is stable and deserves
another chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``He would rather die than have that
happen again in the ring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-18-98 2258EDT &QL; 
