<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, Sept. 18 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Friday failed to overturn a presidential veto of
the partial-birth abortion ban. The vote, 64-36, fell three votes
short of the two-thirds necessary to overturn a veto. The House
successfully voted to override the presidential action earlier this
year. Supporters of the override said that the procedure was
inhumane and did not belong in civilized society. Opponents said
that there were not sufficient protections for the health of the
mother. A ``yes'' vote supported the override.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: JUVENILES
</P>
<P>
   The House Tuesday approved, 280-126, a bill designed to toughen
the penalties on young offenders. The measure would allow the
government to spend a total of $500 million each year on states
that try anyone over 15 as an adult and adopt mandatory penalties
to ensure that no juvenile offender goes unpunished. The vote also
approved a measure combining several prevention programs into block
grants. Supporters said that there was a need for a policy that
holds juveniles accountable for their actions. Opponents said
emphasis should remain on the less costly and more effective
prevention efforts, not with punitive measures. A ``yes'' vote
favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: DRUGS1
</P>
<P>
   The House Wednesday voted, 384-39, to expand and improve efforts
to stop the flow of drugs into the United States, spending $2.6
billion over three years. Supporters said that the spending was
necessary to improve upon the existing drug policy. They said the
existing policy favors education and prevention over enforcement.
Opponents said the bill was unnecessary and motivated by
election-year politics. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: DRUGS2
</P>
<P>
   The House Wednesday voted, 396-9, to create programs aimed at
reducing illegal drug use in the United States. The measure would
include a program to use medication to treat addictions and an
anti-drug media campaign. Supporters said more is needed to fight
domestic drug abuse. At least one member opposed the bill because
questions about it could not be answered since no hearings were
held and it wasn't clear how the bill would help. A ``yes'' vote
favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: IMF
</P>
<P>
   The House Thursday approved, 255-161, a bill that finances
foreign operations and would give $3.4 billion to the International
Monetary Fund, $14.5 billion less than what the Senate passed
earlier this year and what President Clinton had requested. The
bill also places restrictions on U.S. aid to foreign groups that
perform abortions. Supporters of the bill said they wanted the IMF
to undergo lending reforms, but said they may be willing to
compromise when the bill goes to the House-Senate conference
committee. Opponents said the IMF needs the full $18 billion to
prevent the global ``economic chaos'' from spreading. A ``yes''
vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
