<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN FATHER ARRESTED AFTER GIRL, 9, DROWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The father of a 9-year-old Brooklyn girl was arrested
Friday on suspicion that he drowned his daughter late Thursday
night because she was taking too long washing herself in the
bathtub, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Smith, a paroled robber who was once arrested but not
convicted in the scalding of one of his sons, called the police to
his Crown Heights home at 11:10 p.m., telling the operator that his
daughter had stopped breathing, the police said. When officers and
emergency medical technicians entered the apartment at 1226 Lincoln
Place, the police said, they found Antoinette Smith's nude body
resting in a tub of water, where the young girl appeared to have
drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to revive Miss Smith failed. She was pronounced dead at
St. Mary's Hospital 20 minutes after the 911 call was received, the
police said. Smith, 35, was then taken into custody. He faces a
charge of second degree murder, which carries a sentence of 25
years to life in prison upon conviction, said Patrick Clark, a
spokesman for the Brooklyn district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said that no charges were expected against Smith's wife,
Angela, saying it appeared she was not involved.
</P>
<P>
   According to one of the officials, Mrs. Smith, 35, had left four
of her children, ranging in age from 5 to 11, at home that night
when she went to visit a relative.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Smith started arguing with Antoinette shortly after
she got home from school, and his anger erupted when she spent too
long in the bathroom, the official said. As the other children sat
in the apartment's living area, the police said, Smith drowned his
young daughter and then called 911.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became unhappy with the length of time it was taking her to
shampoo her hair,'' the officer said. ``So he held her head under
water and drowned her.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's killing came after a decade of reported abuse and
neglect in the family, according to Nicholas Scoppetta,
commissioner of the Administration for Children's Services. Five of
Mrs. Smith's children spent time in foster care from 1988 to 1995
due to her inadequate guardianship and drug use, he said, noting
that it did not appear that Smith was in the home during those
years. For most of that time, he was incarcerated on a robbery
charge, the police said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Smith gained custody of all of her children following the
completion of a drug treatment program in 1995. When Smith returned
to the family in 1996, the couple took classes in parenting skills
and received drug treatment and family counseling from
Graham-Windham, a social services agency that contracts with the
city, Scoppetta said. But reports of abuse continued to filter out
of the home.
</P>
<P>
   Scoppetta said that Smith was accused of inadequately caring for
and excessively punishing one of his sons in June 1996. In February
of the following year, he was accused of scalding the same son, who
the police say was 8 at the time. Both reports of abuse were
substantiated by the agency, Scoppetta said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was arrested after the scalding incident, according to
Clark of the district attorney's office. But he added that the case
was not criminally prosecuted because ``the evidence was legally
insufficient to sustain the filing of a criminal charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith remained in the home, as did the children. City officials
said that they were now conducting an investigation into
Antoinette's death that they hoped, among other things, would
explain why the children had not been removed from the home after
the 1997 scalding incident.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who is awaiting arraignment in Brooklyn Criminal Court,
has a lengthy record of convictions dating back to 1992 for
criminal sale of marijuana, grand larceny, fraud and robbery,
according to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Grant, a spokesman for the state Division of Parole, said
that Smith was currently on parole until May 24, 2000, for a 1990
robbery conviction. He said Smith had served six years of a 5-to-10
year sentence for the robbery _ his second in eight years _ and was
paroled in May 1996. If he had been convicted under the current,
stricter, sentencing guidelines, Smith would not have been eligible
for parole until the middle of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd still be in jail,'' Grant said.
</P>
</TEXT>
