<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, Sept. 18 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Friday failed to overturn a presidential veto of
the partial-birth abortion ban. The vote, 64-36, fell three votes
short of the two-thirds necessary to overturn a veto. The House
successfully voted to override the presidential action earlier this
year. Supporters of the override said that the procedure was
inhumane and did not belong in civilized society. Opponents said
that there were not sufficient protections for the health of the
mother. A ``yes'' vote supported the override.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: JUVENILES
</P>
<P>
   The House Tuesday approved, 280-126, a bill designed to toughen
the penalties on young offenders. The measure would allow the
government to spend a total of $500 million each year on states
that try anyone over 15 as an adult and adopt mandatory penalties
to ensure that no juvenile offender goes unpunished. The vote also
