<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE BLASTS BACK INTO THE LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)  (js) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ For the most part, the Milwaukee Brewers had been
smart this season when facing Mark McGwire. They had pitched him
low, high, inside, outside, whatever was necessary to avoid being
bashed.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy had been as successful as any against McGwire, the
St. Louis Cardinals' barrel-armed slugger, allowing him only two
home runs in eight games. But Friday night, rookie Rafael Roque
scrapped his team's plan and challenged McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a blast into the left-center-field bleachers,
estimated at 417 feet, that drove the crowd of 48,194 at Milwaukee
County Stadium into a frenzy, even though the two-run shot tied the
score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Amid flashing cameras and screaming fans, Roque's fastball
rocketed off McGwire's bat, driving in Ray Lankford and increasing
McGwire's record-breaking season home run total to 64. It also
broke the deadlock that Chicago's Sammy Sosa had forged with his
63rd home run, a grand slam, on Wednesday night in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It was McGwire's 451st career home run, and it moved him within
one of Carl Yastrzemski for 20th place on the career list.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who of late had been the hotter half of the
record-breaking duo, went 0-for-4 Friday at Wrigley Field in the
Cubs' 6-4 loss to Cincinnati and remained at 63.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, McGwire had not homered in 18 at-bats since he
had surpassed Roger Maris' record of 61 on Sept. 8. Now, two homers
in four games have given him back the lead in a race in which he
trailed only once this season, and then for less than a game.
</P>
<P>
   While all of America, and much of the world, is keeping tabs on
the race between McGwire and Sosa, McGwire insisted before the game
that it meant little to him _ and that it would not bother him if
Sosa had more homers when the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it really matters,'' McGwire said at a news
conference. ``What he and I have been doing is fantastic. What
we've done nobody in the game has done for 37 years. I'm pretty
happy with the way things have been going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers were pretty happy until the fourth inning. Roque, a
left-hander, walked McGwire on six pitches in the first inning and
appeared to be heading that way in the fourth. But with the count
at 3-1, he threw a fastball down the center of the plate, and
McGwire got all of it.
</P>
<P>
   Once the ball and bat made contact, there was no doubt about
where it would land. Jason King, a 23-year-old Madison, Wis.,
native, was the lucky fan who retrieved McGwire's 64th home run
ball of the season. Diving from the stands into the exit well, he
tracked down the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, salivating at McGwire's every stroke of the bat,
almost got another treat in the fifth inning when, after throwing
two balls high, reliever David Weathers put one in McGwire's power
zone. With one of his mighty cuts, McGwire drove the ball high and
into the upper deck, just 15 feet to the left of the left-field
foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Weathers' next pitch looked like No. 65 as well,
but McGwire's drive to right center field was caught by right
fielder Jeromy Burnitz at the front of the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire walked in the first inning and fouled out to the catcher
in the eighth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McGwire will have two more games to thrill Milwaukee's fans,
facing the Brewers on Saturday and Sunday. And then it will be
Sosa's turn. The Cubs play the Brewers on Tuesday and Wednesday,
and it's a safe bet that Sosa will put one, two or three balls over
the fences. In his 10 games this season against the Brewers, he has
homered 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   While some believe Sosa's success against Milwaukee could enable
him to pull ahead of McGwire in the final week of the season,
McGwire pays it no heed. The genuine respect and admiration that he
and Sosa share for one another might be one reason for McGwire's
professed couldn't-care-less attitude toward the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respect each other tremendously,'' McGwire said. ``Here's
two guys from two different countries who have great sportsmanship,
really admire each other and really pull for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, McGwire said he would love it if he and Sosa
finished the race in a dead heat, and Friday he implied that Sosa
had received less attention from the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up to you,'' McGwire said to reporters. ``I would give
him as much publicity as I've gotten, and I encourage you to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
