<HEADER>
A3908 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      09-18 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Bright Prospects Illuminate Dim Offices at Juniper Networks   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Walking into the Mountain View office of Juniper Networks, the
first thing I noticed was that it was nearly as dark as a movie
theater.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being a startup, I wondered if Juniper was strapped for cash and
behind in its light bill.
</P>
<P>
   No, said chief executive Scott Kriens. Juniper has $35 million
in venture funding in the bank. Its engineers simply prefer working
in subdued light.
</P>
<P>
   And after listening to their story, I couldn't argue with their
quirks. Over the past two years, Juniper's 45-person engineering
team invented five microprocessors that were collectively far more
complex that a Pentium II chip.
</P>
<P>
   These special-purpose processors form the core of a new router
that Juniper announced last week. This router is designed to break
one of the Internet's bottlenecks _ the backup that occurs when the
data from slow copper wires must be translated into the speedy
light pulses that travel over fiber optic lines.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Juniper announced the commercial availability of its
new router and said it can perform about 10 times faster than the
fastest box from market-leader Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juniper is the most credible threat to Cisco in the high-end
router space,'' said Aman Kapoor, an analyst with RHK, a
telecommunications market research firm in South San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that bullish assessment goes back to those chips,
designed by a team led by Juniper founder Pradeep Sindhu and
colleague Bjorn Liencres.
</P>
<P>
   As Kriens explained it, today's routers _ the hardware boxes
that direct electronic traffic on the Internet _ are based on the
same microprocessors found in computers. When faced with the
compute-intensive task of translating digital bits into optical
pulses, they slow down.
</P>
<P>
   Juniper's chips were designed to expedite this
digital-to-optical conversion. Who would want such a
special-purpose router? Internet service providers, for instance,
who collect signals from copper phone lines and ship them
cross-country on fiber optic backbones.
</P>
<P>
   Several large ISPs, such as UUNET, have been testing Juniper's
$100,000 boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Kriens downplays Juniper as some sort of Cisco-killer. ``Some
day maybe we'll have to take money from Cisco to eat,'' he said.
But for the near term, he'd be content to pick at the crumbs in the
growing Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco declined comment on Juniper, much as Godzilla might ignore
a newt scampering at its feet.
</P>
<P>
   But Lin DeNoia, an analyst with Strategic Networks in
Massachusetts, said Juniper had the allies to help it get big,
fast. IBM is making its chips. Contract manufacturing giant
Solectron is assembling its routers. Juniper's investors, including
Lucent, Nortel, AT&AMP;T and WorldCom, can help it gain entree to key
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The real decision facing network startups in these days of
consolidation is whether to stay independent and go public, or sell
out to a larger firm.
</P>
<P>
   I put this question to Kriens, who co-founded StrataCom, another
network firm that Cisco acquired two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll stay independent,'' Kriens said. ``Not for the ego of
it, but because we can build more value than anyone would be
willing to pay for us now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Failing grade?  &LR; A recent column about a possible tech-backed
initiative to do a ``hostile takeover'' of public education sparked
an avalanche of comments.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was TechNet President Reed Hastings' critique that
the column painted all Silicon Valley execs as being of one mind on
education reform.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, there are at least three schools of thought
among Valley execs on public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Some execs favor strong doses of privatization and competition,
perhaps through vouchers, to shake up public educators.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like TechNet and the American Electronics Association,
are lobbying for reforms in Sacramento, like letting parents choose
which public schools their kids attend, or ending automatic grade
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   A third strain, exemplified by Joint Venture: Silicon Valley,
eschews lobbying in favor of direct action _ putting volunteers and
money into selected schools to train teachers, wire classrooms, and
enrich reading and science programs.
</P>
<P>
   Into this complicated landscape I lobbed my literary grenade. As
punishment, I'll write 100 times: ``I will not oversimplify.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
