<HEADLINE>
MEGA-MANSION IN HAMPTONS IS MERELY A HOME, LAWYERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. _ A man's home may be his castle, but lawyers
and the public spent hours Friday night debating whether the
castle-size complex being built by Ira Rennert really is his home _
as defined by local zoning law _ or is actually a hotel, conference
center or religious school in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking publicly about the project for the first time,
Rennert's lawyers argued that the sprawling limestone mansion,
occupying about 100,000 square feet on 63 oceanfront acres, is a
single-family home and legally qualifies as such. They opposed
litigation seeking to halt its construction.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the angry neighbors contended that in its
entirety _ with 25 bedrooms, 39 bathrooms, a 1,100-square-foot
theater, a restaurant-size kitchen, an 80-foot-long pool, beach and
garden pavilions, bowling alleys, exercise and game rooms and
courts for basketball, squash and tennis _ the project adds up to
something far beyond a single-family home.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its legal status, experts say that the Rennert complex
_ called Fair Field _ would be the largest in the nation, exceeding
such grand residences as the White House, the Hearst castle in San
Simeon, Calif., and Bill Gates' mansion in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders on both sides of the issue faced off here at the third
and final hearing held by the Southampton Zoning Board of Appeals.
After overflow crowds of hundreds of opponents at the earlier
sessions, Friday night's meeting drew closer to 100.
</P>
<P>
   The board is considering the opponents' demand that it rescind
the building permits issued for the project. In the meantime, work
on the project continues apace.
</P>
<P>
   The official who granted the permits, Paul Houlihan, the town's
chief building inspector, defended his decision. ``This appeal is
based on the fact that the homeowners association feels the house
is too big, and that is the only issue before us,'' he testified.
``If a dwelling meets our definition of a single-family dwelling,
there is nothing in the town code to limit the size of the dwelling
or the number of bedrooms.'' He added that ``the Rennert dwelling
fully complies with those regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the zoning board is awaiting the lawyers' final briefs, and
no vote is expected before November. Whichever way the board rules,
both Rennert and his critics are prepared to file suit immediately
in state Supreme Court to overturn the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rennert, an investor said to be worth $500 million, runs the
Renco Group, a holding company with estimated annual gross revenues
of $2.5 billion. He paid $11 million for the Fair Field site, and
construction costs are estimated at several times that.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rennert's lawyers argued that the board must uphold the building
permits. ``The people are frustrated; the people want to stop the
work,'' conceded one lawyer, Anthony Tohill. But he said, ``There
is no basis on which you could grant the relief requested.'' The
critics are engaging in ``fantasy'' when they say the project is
really a hotel, conference center or school, he said, and the
courts bar premature enforcement against ``possible future illegal
uses.'' Instead, he said, ``the key is the actual use'' of the
property.
</P>
<P>
   His co-counsel, Martin Gilmartin, said: `` Rennert has been
viciously attacked. The level of hostility is almost palpable. He
has said in simple terms that this is to be his residence.''
Although ``no one knows what is in Rennert's mind, we think Rennert
has designed this mansion as his residence,'' he said. ``We believe
his stated intention.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition was led by the Sagaponack Homeowners Association,
which was formed to fight the project. That group's lawyer, John
Shea, told the board: ``If this is a one-family residence, then we
are headed for years of chaos in land development. This is, from
the ground up, commercial in nature. The complex cannot by any
stretch of the imagination be considered a single-family
residence.''
</P>
<P>
   One critic, David Worby, said the large, institutional nature of
Fair Field raised a legitimate question on its real use, ``and we
shouldn't be afraid of addressing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
