<HEADLINE>
FOR GIANTS, SUCCESS IS OFTEN SHORT ON THIRD DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ After two games, the 1-1 New York Giants
are last in the National Football League in one statistical
category: third-down efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   That's a bad one to claim as your own.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have converted 3-of-26 third-down opportunities, an
11.5 percent success ratio in a league in which the average team's
third-down efficiency this season has been 36.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What has been going wrong for the Giants? Everything. Even luck
has not been on their side. But the biggest problem on third down
is the same one that has negatively affected every facet of the
Giants' offense: an anemic running game.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Giants have averaged only 2.9 yards a carry this
season, they have faced unusually long second- and third-down
plays. On average, the Giants on third down have needed 8.6 yards
to pick up the first down. Twelve of their 26 third-down plays have
been third-and-9 or longer. The Giants have had two third-and-24s,
a third-and-18 and two third-and-13s.
</P>
<P>
   That's the story on the bad play. Here's the lowdown on the bad
luck:
</P>
<P>
   Four times on third down, the Giants have fallen 1 yard short of
the first down, getting 14 yards when they needed 15, 10 yards when
they needed 11, 3 yards when they needed 4 and 1 yard when they
needed 2.
</P>
<P>
   Short-yardage situations have been no better. The Giants have
had two third-and-1's and one third-and-2. No first downs in any of
those attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third down hasn't been good because of first down,'' Giants
Coach Jim Fassel said. ``It hasn't been good because of penalties,
too, and a lack of execution. We had this trouble last year early,
and we corrected it by running the football better on first and
second down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made the third-down situations more manageable. We picked
up a few first downs and the confidence rose and we started to play
better. There's a momentum effect. The numbers improved
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants finished last year with a third-down efficiency
percentage of 31.2.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery for Sehorn
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Jason Sehorn underwent surgery Friday to reconstruct
his anterior cruciate ligament, which was torn in a preseason game
Aug. 20. The surgical procedure, which calls for pieces of the
patellar tendon in the knee to be used to re-create the anterior
cruciate ligament, was performed by the team physician Russell
Warren at the Hospital for Special Surgery/Cornell Medical Center
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn's medial collateral ligament, also torn Aug. 20, has been
healing with rest and rehabilitation and was not a part of Friday's
surgery, the team said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Warren told us the surgery was successful,'' Jim Fassel
said. ``There were no complications.''
</P>
<P>
   Galyon Listed as Doubtful
</P>
<P>
   Nickel linebacker Scott Galyon was downgraded to doubtful for
Monday night's game against the Dallas Cowboys at Giants Stadium.
Galyon, who has a sore Achilles' tendon and a calf muscle pull in
his right leg, has not practiced this week. Galyon, a key defender
in passing situations, had 12 tackles against the Cowboys in two
games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Marcus Buckley and left guard Greg Bishop also did
not practice Friday, but coach Jim Fassel said he expected each to
play Monday. Bishop has started every Giants game the last four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone Wheatley continued to get plenty of work with the
first-string offense. It is very likely that he will be activated
for Monday's game, for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   All-Pro linebacker Jessie Armstead sprained his right ankle in
the season-opening game against Washington and has only four
unassisted tackles in the first two games. Armstead's ankle has
improved, and he is promising a strong performance against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to lead the team in tackles,'' said Armstead, who
grew up in the Dallas area. In 16 games last year, Armstead made
101 unassisted tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of Jessie's game is seeing and reacting,'' Fassel
said. ``He goes by instinct and he goes at 100 miles an hour. You
take that edge off with an injury, and he can become a regular
guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
