<HEADLINE>
`LOS SUPER SEVEN': OF MEXICO, LAUGHTER AND TEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe it's a fond backward glance as the end of the
century approaches. Maybe it's a symbolic resistance to cultural
homogenization. Maybe it's the graying of a generation of rockers.
And maybe it's only a matter of musicians seizing a chance to
record songs they love.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, a confederation of Mexican-American
musicians _ including Freddy Fender, three members of Los Lobos,
country singer Rick Trevino and a longtime Tejano singer, Ruben
Ramos _ along with the Texan songwriter Joe Ely got together to
record an album of old songs as Los Super Seven, and they regrouped
to perform on Thursday night at the Bowery Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The only missing member was Flaco Jimenez, the great Tex-Mex
accordionist, who mysteriously chose to make a rare New York
appearance on Wednesday night at the Rodeo Bar instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Super Seven'' (RCA) is a glimpse into the past like
``Buena Vista Social Club,'' the collection of vintage Cuban songs.
But where the Cubans perform songs from their own generation, ``Los
Super Seven'' pays tribute to songs the musicians grew up hearing.
And while the album has some of the nostalgia that suffuses ``Buena
Vista Social Club,'' most of ``Los Super Seven'' is filled with
rambunctious affection that turned even more ebullient onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Tex-Mex or norteno songs balance laughter and tears. The singers
often pine for what they've lost: women, mostly, but also places
and times left behind. Their voices are filled with drama verging
on the maudlin, with aching vibrato and sobbing flourishes. But the
music doesn't let the singers wallow too much. Bouncy,
accordion-topped Mexican polkas, clip-clopping cumbias, sprightly
waltzes and propulsive, flamenco-tinged sones jarochos insist that
despair won't interfere with dancing.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bowery Ballroom, Los Super Seven actually numbered 11
musicians, including two invaluable members of the Austin band Los
Aztex: Max Baca on bajo sexto (acoustic bass guitar) or drums and
Joel Guzman on button accordion, whose solos darted and tootled and
raced. David Hidalgo, from Los Lobos, variously handled drums,
guitar, fiddle and requinto, a small guitar used for staccato
syncopations.
</P>
<P>
   With his pure, tender voice, Hidalgo also took his turn among
the lead singers, each conveying his own kind of ardency: Trevino
with a supple croon, Ramos with grainy authority, Cesar Rosas (of
Los Lobos) with a touch of a growl. Ely recharged folk-rock's
Mexican connections, singing Woody Guthrie's ``Deportee'' and Tom
Russell's ``Gallo de Cielo,'' a song about cockfighting.
</P>
<P>
   Fender sang a bolero from the 1930s, ``Piensa en Mi,'' in a
gently archaic style. Even Guzman took a lead vocal in ``La
Pajarilla,'' jumping and twirling with his accordion as Hidalgo's
drums kicked the music into an irresistible oompah.
</P>
<P>
   For encores, the time line moved forward, as Fender sang his
norteno-flavored mid-1970s hits ``Before the Next Teardrop Falls''
and ``Wasted Days and Wasted Nights'' and the whole group charged
into Sam the Sham's 1965 blockbuster, ``Woolly Bully.'' The songs
were reminders that rock has been hospitable to a Mexican tinge,
and could be again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
