<SLUG> BC-NY-TAX-EXEMPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH GROUP ESCAPES TAX IN AREA ZONED FOR BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.M.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT PLEASANT, N.Y. _ An order of Roman Catholic priests is
entitled to a religious tax exemption on its 265-acre conference
and training center here despite town leaders' insistence that the
property was ineligible because it was zoned for business only, a
state judge has ruled in a decision announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Denis Donovan, of state Supreme Court in White Plains,
sided with the church group, the Legion of Christ, which bought the
sprawling property two years ago from IBM for about $35 million.
The order had sued the town for tax relief, and the town
countersued, asserting that the property, which is now a seminary
and religious conference center, was violating the zoning law and
depriving the town of tax money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to appeal,'' said Robert Meehan, supervisor of
Mount Pleasant, a town of 40,000 in central Westchester County.
``IBM took that property, and they turned it on its ear. Up until
that point, they were good neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the property was sold, IBM paid about $1.4 million a year
in local taxes, and provided 2 percent of municipal tax revenues
and 5 percent of the school tax base, Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Judges have long held that towns cannot withhold religious tax
exemptions because of residential zoning, but this case may have
been the first test in New York state that concerned commercial
zoning, legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Church-owned property is exempt in residential districts,''
said Jerome Kurtz, a professor of tax law at New York University
Law School. ``My impression is that if you have a church in a
business district, you still can't tax the church. I'm not
surprised at the ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Marwell, the lawyer for the Legion of Christ, said the
town's lawsuit failed on the zoning issue because the religious
group uses the campus in precisely the same manner that IBM did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When IBM used this as a conference center, men and women in
business suits came and stayed,'' Marwell said. ``They studied
marketing, computer science and what have you. Now you have men who
wear black suits and different kinds of collars, and they study
theology and philosophy. The actual use of the property has not
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The legion is one of the fastest-growing Catholic orders in the
world, said Jay Dunlap, its communications director and a lay
follower. Founded in 1941 in Mexico City, it is a missionary order
that now has 400 ordained priests and 2,500 members.
</P>
<P>
   The order, which still draws most of its members from Mexico,
has two smaller schools, a high school seminary in New Hampshire
and a two-year novitiate in Connecticut. The campus here, called
the Thornwood Conference Center, has a gym, auditorium, classrooms
and 225 hotel-like rooms. It also has 163 acres of undeveloped
land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
