</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS IMPROVES RECORD, BUT PETTITTE'S A PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ David Wells was manager Joe Torre's conundrum a year
ago. With moods and habits Torre could not understand, Wells
dropped to the back of Torre's rotation in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wells is the anchor of the staff. His record is 18-4 after
the Yankees beat Baltimore Friday night, 15-5, and Torre is
watching comfortably from the Yankees' dugout. Wells is almost
certain to start the Yankees' first game in the American League
playoffs, which begin Sept. 29, and Torre's puzzler this year is
what to do with Andy Pettitte, Orlando Hernandez and Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   Torre prefers postseason experience, and he remembers Pettitte
contributing a sensational performance against Atlanta to help the
Yankees win the 1996 World Series. But lately, Pettitte has been
the least effective of the five starters, and Torre acknowledged
Friday that he might not be part of the playoff rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a chance,'' said Torre. ``There's always a chance. It
comes down to the information you have and what you want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells and David Cone are virtually assured of starts in the
playoffs, with Pettitte, Irabu and Hernandez vying for the other
two spots. Pettitte would probably be part of the Yankees' playoff
rotation if the postseason started Friday. But the playoffs are
still 10 days away, and Torre said he could not ignore what he had
been seeing and what he would see in the last days of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Torre has been seeing:
</P>
<P>
   _ On Monday, Hernandez pitched a three-hit shutout against
Boston, a potential playoff opponent, allowing no walks and
striking out nine. Hernandez, a rookie, is 10-4 with a 3.25 earned
run average, and he has demonstrated the ability to stifle lineups
thick with right-handed hitters, like the Texas Rangers, whom the
Yankees could face in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Thursday, Irabu pitched eight scoreless innings against
Tampa Bay, surrendering just two hits and two walks while striking
out five. The Devil Rays have the league's worst offensive team,
but Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, said Irabu's
pitching was so good that he could have beaten any team, with any
set of hitters. Going into that start, Irabu had allowed 30 runs in
his last 201/3 innings, but all the while Stottlemyre was saying
Irabu was making solid adjustments in his bullpen workouts and was
capable of breaking out of his slump at any time. He did against
the Devil Rays. Irabu (12-9, 4.19 era) has no postseason
experience, and his performance Thursday could have been an
aberration. But Irabu may have two more starts to show he is for
real. His next outing is next week against Cleveland, another
possible playoff opponent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pettitte allowed six runs in six innings Wednesday against
Tampa Bay, the latest in a series of poor outings that began Aug.
9. Pettitte seems to be healthy, reflected in the velocity of his
fastball on Wednesday: 90 to 93 miles an hour. But he is pressing,
and as a result he is making crucial mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   He is 16-10 with a 4.27 era, and opponents are batting .274
against him, as opposed to .234 versus Irabu and .223 versus
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte has the experience Torre loves, and he has shown he can
get better when he needs to get better. Pettitte seems to have
allowed his anxiousness to overcome his ability, but both Irabu and
Hernandez have had moments when they have permitted frustration and
inexperience to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Torre has another week to think about the decision and consult
with the coaches, considering any number of options.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte could start Game 2 of a series against Texas at Yankee
Stadium, but Torre must consider the possibility of resting his
hopes on Pettitte even after losing Game 1; Pettitte could start
Game 3 or 4 in Texas, but he has pitched terribly at Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Torre also could use Hernandez in Game 2 and Cone in Game 3, and
perhaps, Irabu in Game 4 if Pettitte does not improve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
