<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOOD-SAM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIFTH-GRADER RETURNS POUCH WITH $300
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Merlyn Melendez found $300 in a money pouch
next to a soda machine, she thought of all the things she might
buy. After all, the 10-year-old doesn't get an allowance.
</P>
<P>
   But then Merlyn remembered what she had learned in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it's just not right to keep someone else's money,''
said Merlyn, a perky fifth-grader at St. Genevieve's Elementary
School.
</P>
<P>
   So she gave back the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother's friend said, Why didn't you keep it? But I knew
that was wrong,'' she said. ``You take it, and it comes back
because they'll find out who stole it _ and the Coca-Cola man would
have to pay for it if no one turned it in.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, administrators at St. Genevieve's held a special
assembly to honor Merlyn in front of all her classmates for her
good deed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's an example of what it means to live out our Christian
values, and that's what I told the students,'' said Sister Francina
Vivier, principal of the Catholic elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   With some 500 fellow students looking on, Merlyn was rewarded
with a certificate of appreciation, two tickets to Disneyland and
20 cases of Fruitopia juice drink to share with her classmates.
</P>
<P>
   All that was courtesy of the Coca-Cola distribution plant in
Sylmar because a driver inadvertently left the money pouch Tuesday
atop a pay phone next to vending machines at St. Genevieve's.
</P>
<P>
   Among those most proudest of Merlyn was her older brother, Mario
Melendez Jr., 17, a senior at the high school next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a little kid to see that much money, what a temptation,''
he said. ``If it was my situation, I don't know what I'd do or what
other high schoolers would do. I think she'll grow up to be
righteous, big-time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mario was in the middle of football practice when his sister
showed him the small blue bag, labeled ``No. 10'' and bulging with
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I didn't think it was anything, like $5 or $10,''
Mario said. ``I saw the stack of bills when my principal showed it
to me and I was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Greiner, cold-drink manager at a nearby Coca-Cola plant,
said Merlyn certainly deserved to be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We truly appreciate her honesty _ and getting the money
back,'' Greiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Merlyn's find came when she was standing near the gym after her
volleyball practice was canceled. She said she spied the money bag
on top of the pay phone and grabbed it with a quick hop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was the school's to buy books or for ice cream,
because they're always selling ice cream here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And Merlyn said she did not think twice about giving the money
to one of the school's coaches for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Merlyn got the soda she had wanted that afternoon
but could not afford or bring herself to buy with the money she had
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked one of our volleyball coaches what she should do
because she wanted $1 to buy a soda, so the coach gave her a dollar
of his own because he was so proud of her for turning in a big bag
of money,'' said the school's athletic director, Thom Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
